(13, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Council', 'Natural Resources Management Division', 'Project', 'Coordinated Project on Arsenic in Soil-Water-Plant System', 'Arsenic affected  areas of Faridpur, Jessore, Brahmanbaria, Narayangonj, Manikganj and  Satkharia districts', '', '', '', '01-04-2010', '31-12-2012', '01-04-2010', '', '1.To study the impact of arsenic contaminated soil and water in crops\r\n2.To find out arsenic tolerant species/varieties of different crops\r\n3.To study the effect of different soil amendments for arsenic mitigation\r\n4.To find out suitable management practices for reducing Arsenic toxicity in crops and soils\r\n5.To find out suitable mitigation technology of arsenic calamity through different soil amendments in drinking water\r\n6.To find out remediation measures to reduce the entry of arsenic in soil-water-plant systems\r\n', '', '', 'Arsenic , Soil-Water-Plant,  Arsenic mitigation', 'SPGR', 17271030, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(14, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Council', 'Livestock Division', 'Project', 'A coordinated project onto the surveillance of important infectious, Zoonotic and Emerging Diseases of Livestock and poultry in Bangladesh', 'Dhaka, Netrokona, Tangail, Sylhet, Borguna, Kurigram, Comilla, Chandpur, Banderban, Rangamati, Khagrachori, Rangpur, Potuakhali, B. Baria', '', '', '', '01-01-2010', '31-12-2012', '28-04-2010', '', '1.Designing a data-based active surveillance protocol comprising Case definition, Target population, Sampling frame (Random, stratified, purposive, etc.), Sampling frequency, Confidence level (expected prevalence, confidence limit), Type of samples (questionnaire, clinical observation, laboratory samples) available, Analysis of laboratory samples for confirmatory diagnosis, Data flow, Computer based data entry and analysis etc. \r\n2.Use/ adaptation of classical and molecular test protocols like ELISA, PCR, RT-PCR, Immunohistochemistry etc. towards confirmative diagnosis of the infectious etiology. \r\n3.Developing Geographic Information System (GIS) map on livestock diseases targeting available etiology, distribution pattern, seasonal variation, animal(s) affected etc.\r\n4.Formulation of possible steps/ resolutions towards controlling/ preventing outbreak of specific disease (by reducing exposure to the risk factors, or altering the determinants of the diseases processes) and make it available in the net. \r\n5.To generate periodic, more in-depth data on selected zoonotic and emerging diseases of livestock and poultry in Bangladesh. This would assume to enable us to predict disease patterns, economic analysis of diseases progresses, and risk evaluation of disease factors.\r\n', '', '', 'Surveillance , infectious, Zoonotic, Emerging, ELISA, PCR, RT-PCR, Immunohistochemistry, Zoonotic and emerging diseases ', 'SPGR', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(15, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Biotechnology Laboratory', 'Project', 'Genetic Enhancement of Sugarcane for Sustainable Productivity through Tissue Culture and Molecular marker Techniques ', 'Mill zones of PBSM, NBSM, FSM, RJSM etc. and some other selected areas all over Bangladesh where sugarcane is grown under stress conditions', '', '', '', '01-02-2010', '31-12-2012', '25-02-2010', '', '1.To develop improved varieties and enhanced germplasms with desirable traits against disease pests adapted to the major agro-ecological conditions using tissue culture and molecular marker tools.\r\n2.To develop sugarcane varieties against water-logging, drought and salinity stress through cell and tissue culture techniques\r\n3.To produce large scale high quality seeds/setts (HQS) through micropropagation for enhanced productivity of sugarcane.\r\n4.To characterize for identification and documentation of sugarcane varieties and germplasms through DNA fingerprinting using molecular markers.\r\n5.Tagged molecular markers with desirable traits for Linkage Mapping, Quantitative Trait Loci (QTL) and Marker Assisted Selection (MAS) of sugarcane. \r\n', '', '', 'Genetic Enhancement, Tissue Culture, Molecular marker Techniques ', 'SPGR', 6842280, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(16, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Plant Pathology Division', 'Project', 'Surveillance  of seedling diseases of some important fruit species in Bangladesh with molecular characterization of pathogens and eco- friendly model development for their management ', '18 districts covering all the Agro-ecological zones of Bangladesh (such as Mymensingh, Dhaka, Rajshahi, Dinajpur, Bogra etc.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-02-2010', '31-12-2012', '25-02-2010', '02-28-2013', '1.To know the status of seedling trade of fruit trees in Bangladesh. \r\n2.To know the quality and health of seedlings of selected fruits species in Bangladesh.\r\n3.To study the epidemiology of nursery diseases of selected fruits species in Bangladesh.\r\n4.Molecular characterization of pathogens of seedling diseases.\r\n5.To develop a model of environment friendly management practices of seedling diseases \r\n', 'A.	Selection of locations as well as fruit species\r\nB.	Survey on incidence and severity of different diseases of seedlings of major fruits in Bangladesh\r\nC. Monitoring disease-environmental relation in epidemiological aspects\r\nD.  Assessment of disease incidence and severity \r\nE. Isolation, identification and preservation of disease causal organisms\r\nF.	Management of seedling diseases following sustainable and eco-friendly components in order to develop an environment friendly durable model of seedling disease management in the nurseries of Bangladesh\r\nPreparation of nursery soil for pot experiment \r\n', 'Nursery diseases of seven different fruit species viz. Jujube, Litchi, Guava, Jackfruit, Lemon, Mango and Coconut were investigated in five different locations viz. Dhaka, , Gazipur Khagrachari, Sarupkathi and Faridpur. The nurseries of the fruit species were selected considering specific growing area of the specific fruit species.  Under the present study, altogether 20 nurseries were surveyed and prevalence of nursery diseases of fruit species were recorded. In case of mango 5 different diseases viz. anthracnose, red rust, powdery mildew, malformation and die-back; in litchi 4 diseases viz. leaf spot, leaf blight, die-back and red rust; in jujube 5 diseases viz. leaf spot, powdery mildew, sooty mold and rust; in jackfruit 2 diseases viz. leaf spot and leaf blight; In guava 5 diseases viz. leaf spot, leaf blight, red rust, anthracnose and sooty mould; in lemon 4 diseases viz leaf spot, die-back, scab and canker, in coconut 2 diseases viz. leaf spot and bud rot were recorded. Among the 27 recorded diseases of the nurseries of fruit species, a new disease namely bacterial leaf blight was recorded in case of litchi which is first time record in Bangladesh and is caused by Pseudomonas. The bacterial leaf blight of litchi has been identified by challenge test and further study is going on for species identification. Altogater around 525 diseased samples of different fruit species were collected from different surveyed locations. Isolation of pathogens are in progress as well as preservation of disease causal organism are going on. By this time 43 different isolates of pathogens were collected and preserved for further study. The weather data of different locations were collected and further data collection on this issue is progressing. Pot experiment is going on for development of eco-friendly management model of nursery diseases. ', 'Seedling diseases, Molecular characterization, Pathogens and eco- friendly model, Epidemiology of nursery', 'SPGR', 592580, 592180, 400, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(17, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Genetics and Plant Breeding Department', 'Project', 'Generation of short duration high oil content high yielding doubled haploid (DH) rape seed through microspore embryogenesis', 'Farm and laboratory of SAU and in the farmers field of Manikgong', '', '', '', '01-02-2010', '31-12-2012', '24-02-2010', '', '1.To develop short duration higher yieldings rapeseed genotypes which can fit well into Aman  Rapeseed  Boro cropping pattern.\r\n2.To develop yellow seed materials which will give 3  4% more oil then the usual brown seeded ones.\r\n', '', '', 'Doubled haploid (DH) rape seed, Microspore embryogenesis, Rapeseed genotypes', 'SPGR', 3706150, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
