(27, 'Bangladesh Forest Research Institute', 'Mangrove Silviculture Division', 'Project', 'Enrichment and Conservation of Mangrove Ecosystem ', 'The Sundarban and its adjacent areas', '', '', '', '01-02-2010', '01-01-2013', '24-02-2010', '', '1.To enrich mangrove ecosystem and determine better silvicultural techniques for major mangrove species. \r\n2.To conserve a wider range of mangrove forest gene resources for future generations.\r\n3.To develop the appropriate management strategies for sustainable yield and protective services from mangrove ecosystems.\r\n', '', '', 'Enrichment, Mangrove Ecosystem, Sundarban, silvicultural  ', 'SPGR', 4799750, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(28, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Fisheries Biology and Genetics Department', 'Project', 'Gene banking of improved broodstocks of Indian Major Carps (catla, rohu and mrigal) and development of breeding technique of three threatened species (mohashol, bagair and baim)', 'Mymensingh (Research work will be done in the Fisheries Faculty of BAU, but the innovated technology will be disseminated to the hatchery owners through workshop, training, exhibition, demonstration etc. who are the direct beneficiary of the research output).', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-03-2010', '31-12-2012', '24-03-2010', '31-12-2012', 'The project purposes are divided into two main headings:  short and long term\r\nShort term\r\n1.1. Indian major carps (IMCs)\r\nIdentification of genetically superior fish stocks of the species\r\nSelective breeding of the identified superior stocks\r\nComparison of growth performances between seeds obtained by selective breeding and from hatcheries\r\nCryopreservation of sperm of superior/improved stocks\r\n\r\n1.2. Threatened species\r\nDomestication of the species\r\nDevelopment of induced breeding technique\r\nStockable sized seed production\r\nCryopreservation of sperm \r\n2. Long term\r\n2.1. Indian Major Carps (IMCs)\r\nBroodstock development through selective breeding\r\nConservation of superior/improved stocks through live and cryogenic gene banking\r\n2.2 Threatened species\r\nBreeding technique development/standardization\r\nLarge scale seed production\r\nConservation of broodstock through cryopreservation\r\n', '', 'In order to know the comparative growth performance of three Indian major carps (catla, rohu  and mrigal) spawns were collected from three different vivers viz. the Halda (P1), the Jamuna (P2) and the Padma (P3) as well as from six hatcheries of three different regins i.e., Brahmaputra (P4) and Rahim fish hatchery (P5), Mymensingh; Rupali-J (P6) and Ma-fatema (P7) fish hatchery, Jessore; Bismillah (P8) and Rupali-C (P9)  fish hatchery, Comilla. The seeds were stocked in 9 separate experimental ponds of 2 decimal each. 75 individual of each of the three species of 45 days old were stocked in the pond and reared for 6 months. Among the hatchery produced seeds catla of Rupali-J hatchery of Jessore and roju and mrigal of Ma Fatema hatchery of Jessore showed the highest drowth performance. However, hatchery populations of all the three IMCs showed inferior performance when compared with natural populations.\r\n\r\nFor allozyme electrophoresis, muscle samples of 540 individuals of three species from above mentioned nine sources were used for four enzymes (LDH, MDH, PGM and GPI) in CA 6.1 buffer system. Swven presumptive loci were screened and four loci (Mha-1*, Pgm*, Gpi-1* and Gpi-2* were found to be polymorphic in rohu populations and three (Mdh-1*, Mdh-2* and Gpi-1*) wre found to be polymorphic in case of mrigal populations. No polymorphic locus was found in catla populations. The highest mean proportion of polymorphic loci in rohu was 57.14% which was found in P3, P4, P6 and P7 populations and in mrigal it was 28.57 which was found in P4, P7, P8 and P9 Populations. Based on Neis (1972) UPGMA dendrogram, 18 populations on rohu, and mrigal were divided into two major clusters by the genetic distance of D = 1.541. Cluster-1 for rohu nad cluster-II for mrigal. In cluster-I three riverine and six hatchery populations make separate two subclusters by the genetic distance of D = 0.117 and in cluster-II three riverine mrigal and  six hatchery mrigal populations made same sub-clusters separated by the genetic distance of D = 0.017.\r\n\r\nFor domestication and induced breeding of three threatened species (TS) (Tor tor-Mohashol, Bagarias bagarias-Bagair and Mastacembelus armatus-Baim) fishes were collected from their natural habitats (the Shomeshshori River at Shushang Durgapur in Netrokona district, the Old Brahmaputra river in Mymensingh district and haor region in Kishoreganj district respectively).  Mohashol were being released in ponds and other two species w ere in raceway and cisterns. Mega feed is being given as supplementary feed twice a day at a rate of 5% body weight for Mohashol and poultry viscera for bagair and baim every alternate day. Within two to three months bagair and baim have been habituated to accept the feed in raceway and cisterns. From the histological observation perinucleolar and yolk vesicle stage of oocytes in the ovaries of mohashol are found in the months of July. In case of bagair and baim spent phases in the ovaries are observed in the month of October. \r\n', 'Gene banking, Broodstocks, Threatened species', 'SPGR', 11637550, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(29, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Freshwater Station', 'Project', 'Investigation into fish diseases and economic losses due to disease incidence', 'Mymensingh, Sylhet and Rajshahi', '', '', '', '01-02-2010', '31-12-2012', '25-02-2010', '', '1.Investigation into the impact and occurrence of disease outbreaks \r\n2.Causes of diseases outbreak \r\n3.Characterization of pathogens involved in the outbreak of diseases \r\n4.To develop strategies for improved health management \r\n\r\n', '', '', 'Fish diseases, Economic losses, Diseases outbreak, Pathogens ', 'SPGR', 3211920, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(30, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Animal Production Research Division', 'Project', 'Study on milk urea nitrogen (MUN) for improvement of dietary nutrition of dairy cows in Bangladesh ', 'Pabna/Sirajgonj, Rangpur, Noakhali and Jessore plus BLRI Dairy Farm and CCBS &amp; DF, Savar', '', '', '', '01-02-2010', '31-12-2012', '25-02-2010', '', '1.Conduct a bench mark survey on the feed availability, feed composition, milk composition, feeding system prevailing in different regions and production systems.\r\n2.To evaluate MUN of cows considering variations in dietary nutrition, seasons, genetic quality and lactation yield, and to determine on-farm factors that affect MUN content.\r\n3.To determine optimum feeding levels of rumen degradable protein (RDP) and readily degradable (RDC) carbohydrate to optimize MUN content.\r\n4.To develop practical feeding guidelines for dairy cows considering MUN contents.\r\n', '', '', 'Milk urea nitrogen (MUN) , Rumen degradable protein (RDP), Readily degradable (RDC), Carbohydrate ', 'SPGR', 7912130, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(31, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Poultry Science Department', 'Project', 'Approaches to develop broiler sire and dam line from available genetic resources ', 'BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-03-2010', '31-12-2012', '31-03-2012', '', '1.To produce day-old table /broiler chicks suitable for rural &amp;   commercial farmers.\r\n2.To produce colored feather table bird/ broiler &amp; to evaluate their performance for sustainable market.\r\n3.To know the health status of the strains.', '', ' The experiment was set up with 1800 one-day-old chicks of synthetic, White Plymouth Rock (W. P. R) and Aseel (AS) x R. I. R chickens to evaluate their performance as a male &amp; female line parents for broiler production. The birds were brooded with electric brooder for 5 wks of age. They were reared on litter floor up to 18 wks of age. They were then transferred to individual laying cages. The experiment was continued up to 35 weeks of age. The synthetic (male line) males were selected on the basis of 5th week body weight, while female lines, WPR &amp; As x RIR were selected for moderate growth at 6 weeks of age. Finally 25% female of female were selected on the basis of index value calculated on the basis of 6 wk body weight, 35 week egg production &amp; 32 week egg weight for the production of next generation.\r\n\r\nThe highest growth was observed in synthetic male line than female lines during both the growing periods. Among the female lines As x RIR Crossbred had better growth than White Plymouth Rock. The shank length increase with the advances of age of birds in all strains. The synthetic bird had 100% whitest shank, white feather &amp;single comb. While the As x RIR crossbred, the highest proportion (86.16%) had yellow shank and brown feather (68.75%). While each of 33% population had single, rose &amp; pea comb respectively. The WPR and 100% yellow s hank, white feather &amp; single comb.\r\nThe female line As x RIR came to sexual maturity earliest, 20 week followed by WPR, 21 week. The synthetic male line came to sexual maturity at 25 week. The peak egg production was 92, 85 and 53% in AS x RIR, W. P. R. and synthetic respectively. The egg production up 35 weeks of age was 57, 60 and 43% respectively. The egg size was the best in synthetic, followed by WPR and As x RIR at sexual maturity and at 32 week of age. The body weight was the highest in synthetic, while female lines had almost similar body weight at sexual maturity &amp; at peak production. The liveability and dressing meat yield was the best in As x RIR than other strains.\r\n\r\nBoth the strain/hybrid obtained from crossbreeding of selected male &amp; female lines perform equally i. e. 1078 and 1110 g at 6 weeks of age. While F. C. R was better in synthetic x WPR strain (1.77) as against 2.07 for synthetic x As  RIR strain. The livability and dressing meat yield (99 and 75.48%) was the best for synthetic x As-RIR strain. \r\n', 'Broiler sire, Dam line, Day-old table, Broiler chicks, Table bird/ broiler', 'SPGR', 5555900, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Poultry', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(32, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Soils and Nutrition Division', 'Project', 'Development of Nitrogenous Bio-Fertilizer for Sugarcane with Free-Living and Associative Bacteria Using Biological Nitrogen Fixation (BNF) Technology ', 'Sugarcane growing area at Ishurdi, Pabna', '', '', '', '01-04-2010', '31-12-2012', '01-04-2010', '', '1.To identify / screen out suitable sugarcane genotypes favored with biological N2-fixing system under N-stressed field condition. \r\n2.Development of nitrogenous bio-fertilizer using free living and associative bacteria with biological nitrogen fixation ability (BNF) to supplement nitrogenous fertilizer for sugarcane.\r\n3.Create laboratory facilities and upgrade technical skill of scientific manpower for conducting researches in the field of biological nitrogen fixation (BNF) and developing appropriate microbial cultures to be used in bio-fertilizer preparation.\r\n4.Investigate site specific more efficient appropriate strains of free living and associative bacteria for fixing atmospheric nitrogen in sugarcane genotypes of Bangladesh.\r\n', '', '', 'Nitrogenous Bio-Fertilizer,Free-Living,  Associative Bacteria, Biological Nitrogen Fixation (BNF) Technology ', 'SPGR', 9026070, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(33, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Animal Breeding and Genetics Department', 'Project', 'Studies on the Quantitative Trait Loci (QTL) of economic traits in Black Bengal Goat ', 'Gurudaspur, Baraigram, Ishurdi, Bandarban Upazila', '', '', '', '01-04-2010', '31-11-2012', '01-04-2010', '', '1.Production of pure Black Bengal bucks and back cross does &lt;br /&gt;\r\n2.Identifying the Quantitative Traits Loci (QTL) in Black Bengal goat  for meat quantity and quality and other economic traits&lt;br /&gt;\r\n3.Enhancing the institutional capacity for education and research &lt;br /&gt;\r\n', '', '', 'Quantitative Trait Loci (QTL), Black Bengal Goat ', 'SPGR', 12769720, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(34, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Animal Breeding &amp; Genetics Department', 'Project', 'Production of HYV vis-a-vis Indigenous Seed Bulls to Support Smallholder dairying in Bangladesh ', 'AIC of BAU, Mymensingh and its surrounding peri urban and rural cattle breeding and AI service areas', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-03-2010', '31-12-2012', '31-03-2010', '31-12-2012', '1.To develop a science-led farmer participatory system for seed bull production and \r\n2.To ensure supply of meritorious and clean seed bull to the dairy industry of the country.\r\n', '', 'Research on the production of HYV vis-avis indigenous seed bulls to support smallholder is being undertaken since 1 April, 2010 through World Bank and Government support. The main goal of the project is to develop a science-led farmer participatory system to produce seed bulls so that supply of meritorious and clean breeding material to the dairy industry of the country is ensured.\r\n\r\nA socio-economic and technical benchmark survey was conducted at 61 villages of the said cattle. For this assessment, an interview schedule to collect the required baseline data form households was prepared, tested and then finalized after necessary correction, modification and adjustments. More than fifty percent farmers (52.45%) prefer Deshi while 41.26% prefer crossbred preference (35.66%) was higher milk production. Milk sale and consumption (85.31%) was found as main objective behind cattle rearing. In addition, rearing all types of cattle together (71.33%) is preferred than that of separately (6.29%). Average milk yield of Deshi and crossbred genotype were found as 2.05 and 6.65 liter per day respectively. Whereas lactation period and dry period were found respectively as 240.89 and 75.16 days for crossbred, 229.24 and 92.5 days for Deshi. Artificial insemination (A1) was preferred (61.06%) over natural service (38.94%). For Al, semen of Holstein Friesian (43.07%) was preferred. Farmers were found to be unsatisfied with the production performance of available crossbred genotypes. Most of the farmers are not happy with the present milk price. Among different problems identified by the respondents-seed of unknown genotype. \r\n', 'Bull production, Meritorious, HYV vis-a-vis Indigenous, Peri urban,  Rural cattle  ', 'SPGR', 9582000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Animals', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(35, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Agricultural Extension &amp; Information System Department', 'Project', 'Assessment of Post-harvest Losses and Improvement of Post-harvest Practices of Major Fruits and Vegetables of Bangladesh', 'Chapainawabgonj, Rajshahi, Dinajpur, Gazipur, Mymensingh, Narsingdi, Jessore and Bogra  districts', '', '', '', '01-04-2010', '01-03-2013', '28-06-2010', '', '1.To identify the existing post-harvest practices and assess the losses of major fruits and vegetables. \r\n2.To improve the post-harvest practices of major fruits and vegetables\r\n3.To determine the nutritional composition of stored and improved products with their economic benefit\r\n4.To suggest remedies for minimizing the post-harvest losses of major fruits and vegetables\r\n', '', '', 'Post-harvest, Fruits, Vegetables', 'SPGR', 4000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(36, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'CASR', 'Project', 'Development and validation of USG applicator and rice transplanter', 'Six districts (Rajshahi, Rangpur, Kushtia, Comilla, Habigonj and Netrakona) of the country will be selected on the basis of cropping intensity and location and two upazila of each district will be selected to implement the project activities', '', '', '', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2013', '28-06-2010', '', '1.To design and development of user friendly manually operated USG applicator \r\n2.To modify and improvement of rice transplanter\r\n3.To validate and adoption of the developed technology to the end users\r\n4.To increase labor efficiency and reduce human drudgery\r\n5.To reduce turn-around time and increase the cropping intensity \r\n', '', '', 'USG Applicator, Rice transplanter', 'SPGR', 11467830, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(37, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Pest Management Division', 'Project', 'Development of threshold level (seed health standard) of Colletotrichum corchori in jute seed', 'The research activities will be conducted at the nine regional/ sub station of BJRI viz., Central station, Dhaka; JAES, Manikganj; Rangpur Regional Station; Comilla Regional Station;  Kishoreganj Regional Station; Faridpur Regional Station; Jessore sub station and Dinajpur sub station.', '', '', '', '15-06-2010', '15-05-2013', '', '', '1.To undertake research in order to develop the threshold level or seed standard for one of the major seed- borne fungal pathogen, Colletotrichum corchori in capsularis (Corchorus capsularis) jute seeds.\r\n2.To recommend the seed standard or threshold value for seed- borne C. corchori in jute to NSB.\r\n3.To recommend procedure for undertaking routine seed health test for C. corchori in jute.\r\n4.To suggest further research activities of relevance to seed health and seed borne disease of jute.', '', '', 'Threshold level, Colletotrichum corchori, Corchorus capsularis, Seed- borne C. corchori', 'SPGR', 6015240, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
