(105, 'Bangladesh Institute of Nuclear Agriculture', 'Soil Science Division ', 'Program', 'Soil Water and Nitrogen Management for Sustainable Crop Production Using Tracer Technique in Drought Prone Areas of Bangladesh ', '', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To improve the nitrogen use efficiency in wheat based cropping systems with a view to minimum water use.  \r\n2.To recommend economic and environment friendly nitrogen management approaches for wheat based cropping pattern.\r\n', '', '', 'Soil, Water, Nitrogen, Sustainable, Tracer Technique,  Drought Prone ', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(106, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Genetics and Plant Breeding Department', 'Project', 'Development of short duration high yielding rice varieties ', 'Mymensingh sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat Upa-Zilla of Mymensingh districts', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', 'To select and develop short duration high yielding rice varieties for the Boro, Aus and T. Aman  seasons to fit into the existing cropping pattern', '', '', 'high yielding,rice varieties ', 'BARC', 950000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(107, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Crop Botany Department', 'Project', 'Production of Somaclone In vitro for Drought Stress Tolerant                ', '', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To establish a protocol on callus induction, proliferation and for high frequency plantlet regeneration through somatic embryogenesis.\r\n2.To development a system for selection of somaclones in vitro under salinity and drought stress.\r\n3.Isolation and development of salinity and drought tolerant strain for farmer use.\r\n4.Capacity building and manpower development on in vitro somaclone production in potato.\r\n5.Creation of knowledge on morpho physiological features and production potential of in vitro grown potato.\r\n', '', '', ' Somaclone, vitro, Drought Stress Tolerant,  proliferation,  physiological, potato', 'BARC', 900000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(108, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'IPM Lab', 'Project', 'An Integrated Approach for the Management of Wilts and Foot Rot/Collar Rot of Important Vegetables', 'IPM Lab,Department of Plant Pathology,Bangladesh Agricultural University,Mymensingh 2202, Bangladesh\r\n', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To study the efficacy of Trichoderma harzianum as bio-control agent against Ralstonia solanacearum, Fusrium oxysporum, Meloidogyne javanica and Scleortium rolfsii causing wilts and foot of vegetables.\r\n2.To formulate Trichoderma as bio-control agent for controlling wilts and foot /collar rot of vegetables\r\n3.To develop cost-effective, commercially viable mass production technology of Trichoderma\r\n', '', '', ' Wilts, Foot Rot/Collar, Rot, Vegetables', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(109, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Organic amendments for mitigating soil salinity in rice-maize cropping system\r\n', '', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To investigate the protective effect of proline on the growth and yield of rice and maize against salt stress.\r\n2.To examine the effect of proline on K/Na ratio, chlorophyll content and proline accumulation by rice and maize under salt stress.\r\n3.To examine the effect of proline on ascorbate and glutathione contents and the activity of ROS-scavenging antioxidant enzymes under salt stress.\r\n4.To investigate the effect of organic manures on the growth and yield of rice and maize under salt stress.\r\n5.To examine the effect of organic manures on K/Na ratio, chlorophyll content and nutrient uptake by rice and maize under salt stress.\r\n6.To investigate the changes in physico-chemical properties of soils including electrical conductivity (EC), pH, exchangeable sodium percentage (ESP), organic matter status, etc.\r\n7.To suggest an approach for the improvement of crop production under salinity.\r\n', '1.Pot culture experimentation: Pot experiments with proline and organic manures under salt stress in rice and maize crops.\r\n2.Field experimentation: Field experiments with proline and organic manures in coastal areas of Bangladesh in rice and maize crops.\r\n3.Laboratory experimentation: Physiological and biochemical characteristics of plants affected by proline and organic compounds under salt stress.\r\n4.Development of the technology for rice-maize cropping systems in coastal areas of Bangladesh. \r\n5.Organizing workshop: Arrangement of workshop at the end of project to evaluate the performance on expert level.\r\n6.Policy development and dissemination: During field experiment trials and at the end of project, the innovated technologies will be disseminated to the scientists and extension workers as well as to the farmers through workshop, training, exhibition, demonstration etc who are the direct beneficiary from the research output. \r\n', '', 'Organic, Amendments, Soil salinity, Rice-maize, Cropping, Proline ', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(110, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Crop Botany Department', 'Project', 'Biological Nitrification Inhibition is a novel approach for enhancing nitrogen use efficiency in cereal production ', '', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1. To reduce the vast loss of applied urea (67%) through emission and leaching    which in turn will reduce the cereal production cost.\r\n2. To enhance the farmers income for improving their livelihood\r\n3. Finally it will contribute towards the development of low-nitrifying and low-N2O emitting cereal production systems that use nitrogen fertilizers more rationally and responsibly in cereal cultivation.\r\n', '', '', 'Biological Nitrification Inhibition, Nitrogen, low-nitrifying, low-N2O ', 'BARC', 1140000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(111, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Farm Power and Machinery Department', 'Project', 'Remote Controlled Guti Urea Applicator', 'Research Station: Department of Farm Power and Machinery,Bangladesh Agricultural University,Mymensingh  \r\nField trials in farmers field : In Mymensingh, Gazipur, and Sherpur districts\r\n', '', '', 'New', '01-09-2011', '30-08-2014', '', '', 'Development of a remote controlled guti urea applicator, characterized by increased operational comfort, low cost and precise placement.', '1.The design of different push type guti urea applicators currently available will be studied thoroughly. Four different design of the applicators are available in the work station of this project proposer.  \r\n2.The available remote control mechanism currently being used in various toys will be studied in details.\r\n3.A compact (mini version) having same working principles of BARI/BRRI USG applicator will be designed and fabricated in the workshop of the department of Farm Power and Machinery, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh. The required power to roll the device between the rows of the rice plants through uneven (wet and dry) soil condition will be determined.\r\n4.Based on the power estimation to operate the device, rechargeable batteries of required capacity will be installed into the device along with necessary electronic circuit and antenna.\r\n5.A remote controlled hand operated device will be selected to operate the machine from a boundary of the rice field.\r\n6.The performance evaluation of the machine will be conducted in farmers field, if necessary modification will be done accordingly.\r\n7.The necessary field data will be collected to determine the field capacity, placement efficiency, rice yield, benefit-cost ratio etc.\r\n8.Operational activities of the machine will be captured in to a video. A series of demonstration will be conducted in the farmers field in Mymensingh, Gazipur and Sherpur. Mass motivation through TV, radio and newspapers would help promote the machine among the farmers.\r\n9.The technology will be handed over to the interested manufacturers in the country for mass production\r\n', '', 'Remote, Guti Urea,  Applicator', 'BARC', 1287500, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(112, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Crop Botany Department', 'Project', 'Collection of some targeted threatened plant species of Sylhet forests for sustainable management and curation', 'Lawachara forest of Maulabhibazar,Rema-Kalenga, Madhabkunda Eco-park,Botanical Garden of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh\r\n', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To develop the Botanical Garden as a resource centre for biodiversity education, research and information;\r\n2.Capacity building of the Botanic Garden for collection, propagation and conservation of plants ; and \r\n3.Enrichment of plant diversity,  particularly the diversity of threatened plant species \r\n', '', '', 'targeted, threatened plant, species, forests, sustainable, management, curation, biodiversity, Enrichment  ', 'BARC', 1196000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(113, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Microbiology and Hygiene Department', 'Project', 'Epidemiological Investigation of Anthrax and Determination of Efficacy of Local Anthrax Vaccine in Bangladesh ', 'Sirajganj and other anthrax-prone areas where outbreak occur in Bangladesh. ', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To determine the environmental factors (soil type, pH, geographical location, environmental temperature, humidity, season etc.) responsible for the outbreak of anthrax.\r\n2.To determine the host factors (age, sex, breed, nutritional status, immune status) associated with the outbreak of anthrax.\r\n3. To determine the role of managerial (feeding, bedding, watering, prevention and control measures etc.) and vector system in transmitting the disease.\r\n4.To isolate and characterize B. anthracis from the suspected sources.\r\n5.To determine the efficacy of local anthrax vaccine produced by LRI, Mohakhali, Dhaka.\r\n', ' ', '', 'Epidemiological,  Anthrax, Determination, Efficacy, Anthrax Vaccine ', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(114, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Aquaculture Department', 'Project', 'Study on Fish Disease and Health Management in Rural Aquaculture', 'Locations of data collection will be Bogra and Pabna districts. Laboratory analysis will be performed at the Fish Disease Laboratory, Department of Aquaculture, BAU, Mymensingh. ', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To assess the level of farmers knowledge on fish health and disease  and find out existing fish health management problems in rural aquaculture \r\n2.To identify and characterize pathogens involved in fish disease\r\n3.To develop fish health management protocol and provide training to farmers\r\n', '', '', 'Fish Disease, Health Management, Rural ', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(115, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Fisheries Management Department', 'Project', 'Study of reproductive endocrinology of mud eel Monopterus cuchia for artificial propagation\r\n', 'Haor area of Netrokona district, Fisheries Field Laboratory of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh and Laboratory of Conservation Biology at Department of Fisheries Management, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh.', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', 'Controlled reproduction and production of quality seeds in captivity are the key prerequisites for domestication and sustainable aquaculture of any new species under consideration. Again, fry production in captivity and introduction to aquaculture are useful tools for conservation of any threatened fish species like M. cuchia. On the other hand, an induced breeding and fry production trial without understanding the reproductive biology and neuroendocrine mechanism in any fish might often subject to failure. Therefore, the specific objectives of the proposed project are  \r\n1.To understand different aspects of reproductive biology of M. cuchia through study of GSI and gonadal maturity stages\r\n2.To identify the location of GnRH and GtH genes in the brain and pituitary by immunohistochemistry and\r\n3.To trial advanced maturation and spawning using specific GnRH-analog (GnRH-a).\r\n', '', '', 'Reproductive, Endocrinology, Mud eel Monopterus cuchia, artificial propagation ', 'BARC', 1188000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(116, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Fisheries Biology &amp; Genetics Department', 'Project', 'Production of genetically male tilapia by identification of YY supermales using microsatellite DNA markers', 'The Mini Fish Hatchery complex, Faculty of fisheries, Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '1.To produce neofemale (genetically male but phenotypically female) by hormonal sex-reversal\r\n2.To identify true YY supermales from XY males using sex-linked microsatellite DNA markers in Nile tilapia\r\n3.To develop a stock of YY supermales to produce mass scale genetically all male tilapia populations\r\n', '', 'Monosex (male) Nile tilapia Oreochromis niloticus is highly preferable for commercial production system to control unwanted reproduction by females and to obtain higher growth of even sized male tilapia leading to good profit. The technique of producing all male using androgen hormone (particularly 17-&amp;#945;-methyl-testostorone) is  being widely used in Bangladesh. However, the use of hormone in the direct food chain is prohibited in many countries of the world because of the adverse physiological effects. Very recently, sex-linked markers have been identified for Nile tilapia which can assist selection of YY males in tilapia. The current study aims at the production of genetically male Nile tilapia using such markers. Initially hormonal sex reversal of mixed sex has been performed. Estrogen hormone treatment has been conducted to convert sex of XY males to XY females (neofemales). The swim up fry have been fed with the hormone mixed diet from the very first day of weaning (immediately after absorption of yolk sac) for a period of four weeks. The trial was conducted in the Mini Fish Hatchery complex, Faculty of fisheries, Bangladesh Agricultural University. Fry with yolk-sac were collected from the tilapia hatchery (Agro3). Three hormonal doses were used for the feminization of tilapia, i.e., Treatment 1 (DES hormone 100mg/kg feed), treatment 2 (DES hormone 200mmg/kg feed), treatment 3 (DES hormone 300mg/kg feed) and control U*no hormonal feed). There were three replication for each of these three treatments. 300 fry were released in each aquarium. The fry were fed 4 times a day. The hormonal treatment was conducted for a period of 1 month. The fry were released in cisterns after the completion of the hormonal trial. Normal feed I(Starter 2, Saudi Bangla Fish Feed Ltd) is being provided now to grow them up to sexual maturity. Part of them will be gonad squashed to observe the sex reversal to carry out further experiments.  ', 'Tilapia,  YY supermales, Microsatellite DNA, Marker', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Protein products', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(117, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Fisheries Biology and Genetics Department', 'Project', 'Development of breeding and fry rearing techniques of endangered Tengra, Mystus vittatus and Gulsha, Mystus cavasius', 'The experiments will be conducted in the Fish Genetics Laboratory, Wet Laboratory under the Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics, and Fisheries Faculty Field Laboratory Complex under the Faculty of Fisheries, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh-2202. The equipment and other facilities available at the Department, Field Laboratory and Faculty will also be used whenever required.', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To develop a captive broodstock from different wild sources.\r\n2.To develop breeding protocol using different inducing agents and their dose optimization.\r\n3.To establish fry rearing techniques.\r\n', '', '', 'Breeding, Fry rearing techniques, Endangered Tengra, Mystus vittatus,Gulsha, Mystus cavasius', 'BARC', 1180000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(118, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Genetics and Plant Breeding Department', 'Project', 'Evaluation of New Plant Type (NPT) advanced lines of rice for Amon season as high yielding varieties ', '', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.Evaluation of NPT advanced lines for release as new variety(s) \r\n2.Quality characterization of the selected NPT advanced lines for better acceptance by the consumers\r\n', '', '', 'New Plant Type (NPT),   Amon, Quality ', 'BARC', 900000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(119, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Soil Science Department', 'Project', 'Influence of fertilizer, manure and water management on soil fertility, nutrient availability and productivity under Rice-Rice cropping system. ', 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University ', 'High', 'Applied', 'on going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '1.Integrated use of fertilizer and manure with different water management on the yield and quality of Boro and T. Aman rice.\r\n2.Judicial use of fertilizer and manures with proper water management for improving soil fertility, nutrient availability and productivity.\r\n3.Fate of applied N, P, K, S fertilizer and manures in irrigated rice soil with different water management.\r\n4.To know the organic matter accumulation at various depths of paddy soil resulting from the addition of different level of manure and fertilizer with different levels of irrigation practices.\r\n5.To know the effect of intensive fertilization and water management on the change of physico-chemical properties of soil.\r\n', '', 'The two experiments were conducted in the farm of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University, Dhaka, Bangladesh during the period from July 2012 to June 2013 to study the effect of various organic manure and inorganic fertilizer with different water management on the growth, yield of rice and nutrient availability in paddy soil during rice growing periods. BRRI dhan32 and BRRI dhan29 were used as the test crop for boro and T. aman season. The two rice-rice cropping experiments are being conducted in the same 48 (8 fertilizer X 2 irrigation X 3 replications and 72 (8 fertilizer X 3 irrigation X 3 replications) plots. The yield parameters, yields and nutrient concentrations of grain, straw were significantly affected by fertilizer and manure. The yield and yield parameters were not significantly influenced by different irrigation treatments. In the second crop T. aman rice and 3rd crop boro rice, the higher grain and straw yields were found in T7 (70% NPKSZn + 2.1 ton poultry manure/ha) treatment in both experiments and the interaction effects of fertilizer and irrigation were not significantly influenced the yield and yield parameters. The pore water nutrient availability was also affected by fertilizer and irrigation treatments. The higher grain yield and grain N, P, K and S concentrations were found in the fertilizer and irrigation treatments. The higher grain yield and grain N, P, K, and S concentrations were found in the fertilizer treatments where the pore water nutrient concentrations were higher.', 'Fertilizer, Manure and,  Nutrient, Rice-Rice cropping ', 'BARC', 1200000, 1200000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fertilizer and Water Management', 'Rice', 'The effect of residual and renewal added of fertilizer and manure influenced the yield and yield parameter of T. aman rice. In the first and 2nd experiments, the highest grain yield of T. aman rice (BRRI dhan32) was found in the T7 fertilizer treatment where 70% NPKSZn + 2.1 ton poultry manure/ha was added during first boro rice (first crop) growing period and renewal fertilizer was added during second crop T. aman growing season. The growth and yield of 3rd crop boro rice were not significantly affected by irrigation but significantly affected by fertilizer treatments. The different fertilizer treatment affected the yield parameters and yield of BRRI dhan29. Different levels of fertilizer and manure were used with two or three irrigation levels in two field experiment and better performance was found in the combined application of manure plus fertilizer. The poultry manure performed better compared to compost and cowdung, the highest yield of BRRI dhan29 was found where 70% NPKS plus 2.1 ton poultry manure/ha was applied.\r\nThe pore water samples were collected from the soils of boro rice field experiment one. The N, P, K and S concentrations were studied in the pore water and the concentration of available N, P, K and S in the pore water varied with irrigation, fertilizer treatment, cropped and without cropped area and time. The higher levels of pore water K concentrations were found in the continuous flooded condition than the pore water of saturated condition. The higher concentrations of N, P and K were found in the pore water of T6 and T7 treatments where poultry manure plus inorganic fertilizers were used. The higher levels of pore water N were found in the treatments where chemical fertilizer was used in combination with manure. There was good correlation between yield vs. pore water nutrient concentration and pore water nutrient concentration vs. grain nutrient accumulation.', 'Fertilizer, manure and water management increase soil fertility, nutrient availability as well as crop productivity.', ''),
(120, 'Soil Resources Development Institute', 'Upazila Nirdeshika Cell', 'Project', 'Organic amendments for upland crops under light textured soils in Char land under Active Ganges Floodplain', 'Charharirampur  union in Charbhadrason Upazila Under Faridpur District', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1.To determine the performance of organic manure application on Mustard- B. aus and Mustard  Jute cropping patterns in light textured char land soils.\r\n2.To determine the influence of Mustard - B. aus and Mustard  Jute cropping patterns on soil fertility and soil organic matter contents in different treatment combinations.\r\n', '', '', 'Organic, Amendments, Textured soils,  Active Ganges Floodplain', 'BARC', 1075000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(121, 'Soil Resources Development Institute', 'Soil Conservation and Watershed Management Centre', 'Project', 'Effect of Different Hedge Species on Soil Erosion and Crop Yield at Different Hill Slopes of Chittagong Hill Tract. ', 'The project will implement at the Research farm of Soil Conservation and Watershed Management Centre (SCWMC), SRDI, Bandarban', '', '', 'New', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1. To identify different hedge species and assess alley width in controlling soil erosion.\r\n2. To estimate soil loss under different hedge species and alley width at different slopes.\r\n3. To examine the effect of different hedge species and their alley width on crop yield at different slopes.  \r\n', '', '', 'Hedge Species, Soil Erosion,  Crop Yield, Hill Slopes, Hill Tract. ', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(122, 'Sylhet Agricultural University', 'Fisheries Biology and Genetics Department', 'Project', 'Development of artificial breeding techniques of Sperata aor ', 'Faculty of Fisheries, Sylhet Agricultural University, Sylhet', '', '', '', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', 'The overall goal of this project is to carry out a detailed and in-depth scientific study in order to establish artificial breeding techniques of S. aor while the objectives are: \r\n1.To understand the breeding biology of S. aor\r\n2.To assess their reproductive potential in captive condition\r\n3.To develop artificial breeding techniques \r\n', '', '', 'Artificial, Breeding, Techniques, Sperata aor ', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
