(1331, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Project', 'Searching cost effective rice production technology for stress prone environments in Bangladesh: Targeting replacement of Bolan by Sub 1 Rice varieties.', 'Rajarhat and Kurigram Sadar Upazila', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2011', '30-06-2011', '', '30-06-2011', 'a. Know the possibility of replacing bolan practice or double transplanting systems with submerged tolerant rice varieties.\r\nb. Determine the cost effectiveness of these two rice production practices.\r\nc. Assess the impact of replacing double transplanting of existing varieties with single transplanting of submerged tolerant varieties on cropping pattern, cropping intensity, and productivity as well and\r\nd. Understand the farmer&amp;#39;s attitudes and perceptions on the newly developed rice varieties.\r\n', 'Area and sample selection: A sample survey of about 120 farmers from 12 villages under Rajarhat and Kurigram Sadar Upazila was conducted. These Upazilas are characterized by submerged prone areas of Kurigram district where DAE Personal.\r\nCost-Effectiveness and / or Profitability Analysis using an Empirical Analytical Tool: Cost-return analysis is the most common practice of examining the cost effectiveness and/or profitability of an enterprise and farm activities. Profit is defined as the difference between the total revenue and total cost. The following conventional profit model was applied to examine the profitability level of the HYVs and hybrid rice production.', 'The Study was carried out to know the possibility of replacing bolan practice or double transplanting systems with submerged tolerant rice varieties; determine the cost effectiveness of these two rice production practices; assess the impact of replacing double transplanting of existing varieties with single transplanting of submerged tolerant varieties on cropping and perceptions on the newly developed rice varieties. Instead of discarding the system, rice researchers must work on refining the system through developing appropriate varieties and other crop management practices for the system.', 'Rice, Cost effective, rice stress prone environments, Bolan, Sub1 rice varieties, Production technology, environment', 'BARC', 200000, 150000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Socio-Economics and Policy Program area', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1129, 'University of Chittagong', 'Forestry', 'Project', 'Biodiversity in arbuseular Micorhiza fungi of forest soils and their conservation.', '', '', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-05-2000', '20-05-2001', '21-05-2000', '', '1. To assess the mycorrhizal status of commonly available forest plants in different forest areas of Bangladesh.\r\n2. To study the biodiversity of AM spore population in different forest soil types.\r\n3. To study the mycorrhizal development in root systems of different forest  plant species.\r\nd. To develop mycorrhizal inoculum in trap crop methods to confirm identification of available AM fungi in forest soils of Bangladesh.\r\n4. To develop a germplasm bank of AM fungi for future use of mycorrhizologist.\r\n5. To develop AM inoculum for nursery inoculation of different forest plant species.\r\n6. To develop a biotechnology unit for supply of pure inoculum of AM fungi as biofertilizer.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Biodiversity', '', '', '', ''),
