(1119, 'Hortex Foundation', 'Crops', 'Project', 'Effect of hydrocooling on the shelf life and quality of some summer vegetables of Bangladesh.', '', '', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-04-2000', '30-09-2000', '17-04-2000', '', '1. To study the effect of lowering down the field temperature of some just harvested summer vegetables through the method of hydro-cooling at different  temperature levels on the shelf life of these vegetables without deteriorating their qualities.\r\n2. To try to find out if possible, a temperature range, which may be best suited for a particular vegetable in increasing its shelf life and also quality retention.\r\n3. To study whether hydro-cooling as a method of lowering down temperature is suitable or not for vegetable crops taken under this project.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Post Harvest', 'Vegetable', '', '', ''),
(1326, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Food Technology and Rural Industries', 'Project', 'Processing of indigenous fruits and vegetables to improve livelihood of rural poor in Madaripur region.', 'BAU, Mymensingh and Modhupur Upazila of Tangail District', '', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '1) To asses the current production status, post-harvest processing and preservation practices for indigenous fruits and vegetables.\r\n2) To develop new technologies and/or modify the indigenous methods to suit to the needs of rural poor for processing value added products.\r\n3) To improve knowledge and skills of rural poor, including women, in post harvest management and to prepare a manual on post harvest processing and preservation of indigenous fruits and vegetables.\r\n4) To evaluate the acceptability of the processed fruits and vegetables.\r\n', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 0, 1782426, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '1.	Eighty rural unemployed poor have been trained on processing and preservation of indigenous fruits and vegetables. The trainees got motivated and adopted the technologies. Some trainees have already started preparation of processed products to earn livelihood.\r\n2.	There are potential markets for the processed products viz: street side small market places, school premises, grocery shops, bakeries and other food outlets in the locality.\r\n3.	Technologies have been developed through modifications of indigenous methods to suit the need of rural poor. These developed technologies and the processed products would help the locals improve their livelihood.\r\n4.	A manual on post-harvest processing and preservation of indigenous fruits and vegetable has been prepared. \r\n', '1.	The technologies developed for processing value added products would help the rural poor to generate income and improve livelihood.\r\n2.	Distribution of 500 copies of the training manual (in Bengali) would help the rural poor improve their capacity to manufacture and sale of value added products and earn more cash money.\r\n', ''),
(1327, 'International Development Enterprises (IDE)', 'International Development Enterprises (IDE)', 'Project', 'Promotion of agricultural Marketing in Hills', 'Bandarban District', '', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	1) To identify the constraints in the value chains of high value crops.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	2) To develop/strengthen value chains of at least five high value crops in 3-5 Unions of sadar Upazila of Bandarban District.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	3) To develop a sustainable methodology for agricultural market promotion in the project area.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n', '', '', 'value chains of high value crops, five high value crops', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1547919, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Marketing network development', 'Crops in hill areas', '1) Five crops (Vegetable and fruits) have been selected and their constraints and opportunities in supply/value chains market actor have been identified.\r\n2) Twenty input sellers were identified and trained. Four input supplying companies have been linked with the local input sellers.\r\n3) Target farmers were trained on improved production practices and linked with trained input sellers and output market actors for quality inputs and better agricultural market promotion in the project area.\r\n4) Agri product collection point and collection point management committee have been established.\r\n ', '1) The production technologies introduced by the project are likely to be continued with higher productivity and income.\r\n2) The bargaining power of the farmers for good quality inputs and good price for their produces will be increased through the linkage development.', ''),
(1328, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Project', 'Capacity building of the farmers through exporting comparative advantaged horticultural products.', 'Narshingdi, Jessore, Comilla and Bogra', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '1) To determine comparative advantages of exporting horticultural products.\r\n2) To explore capacity building ability of the farmers who have the potentiality of exporting horticultural products.\r\n3) To provide some policy directions on capacity building of the farmers.', '', '', 'exporting horticultural products, capacity building, policy directions', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1475671, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Farmers capacity building', 'Export horticultural products', '1) Production of tomato has highest comparative advantage followed by onion, brinjal and potato.\r\n2) The capacity building ability of the farmers who produce exportable horticultural crops is higher.\r\n3) Farmers in the exportable horticultural crop producing areas improved their individual capacities by effectively using their technical, social, human, natural and financial capital.', 'Improvements in capacity building of the farmers will help to reduce the inefficiency in farming and actual return can be obtained up to maximum level with the existing level of input use.', ''),
(1329, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Genetic Research Centre', 'Project', 'Expansion of Rice gene bank facilities and strengthening existing conservation program. ', 'BRRI Head Quarter', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-04-2003', '31-03-2007', '', '31-03-2007', 'a. Collection, preservation and evaluation of local rice genetic resources of Bangladesh to ensure proper use of desirable traits for developing new rice varieties.\r\nb. Collection and conservation (ex-situ and on-farm) of different important rice genetic resources from exotic gene pool to strengthen national rice research programme.\r\nc. To characterize the important traits of rice genetic resources through national and international collaboration.\r\nd. To take step for exchanging information on different traits and characteristics of rice germplasm with different national and international agencies, NGOs, Universities and research institute.\r\ne. To facilitate in conserving genetic resource of other crop research institutes to avoid any other risk evolved due to disaster in future.', '', '', 'Rice, Gene Bank', '', 77800000, 77800000, 0, 'Report, Booklet', 'Training, Workshops, Field days', 0, 'Rice Gene Bank', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1319, 'Gana Bishwabiddalaya', 'Microbiology', 'Project', 'Study of herd health management practices for Ruminants in Bangladesh', 'Manikganj, Jamalpur and Sirajganj Districts', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '1) To develop an effective model for viable herd health management practices for the farmers.\r\n2) To improve knowledge and skill of the farmers on herd health management practices.', '', '', 'Herd health, Ruminants, Improve knowledge', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1426704, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Health management', 'Ruminant animal', '1) Almost all ruminants in 3 villages were vaccinated against Foot &amp; Mouth Disease, Anthrax, Hemorrhagic septicemia, Black Quarter and Peste des petis ruminants (PPR) which prevented the disease incidence to a large extent.\r\n2) Potential farmers were trained on different aspects of herd health management to act as local service providers.\r\n3) Leaflets developed on disease and feed management and fodder cultivation were distributed among the farmers of 3 villages.', 'The developed herd health management model when adopted by a large number of farmers will prevent diseases, improve health and nutrition of ruminants and contribute to the economy of the farming community.', ''),
(1320, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Surgery and obstetrics, Faculty of Veterinary Science', 'Project', 'Improving livelihood through Herd Health Management and milk market access to poor farmers living in the nothern Bangladesh.', 'Sariakhandi, Islampur and Belkuchi Upazilas of Bogra, Jamalpur and Sirajganj disgtricts', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-04-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-04-2011', 'a. Clinical nutrition and forage based cattle feeding\r\nb. Upgrading of desi cattle through cross breeding using A1 tool with frozen semen\r\nc. Improvement of cattle fetility through clinical intervention.\r\nd. Control of dairy cattle diseases through vaccination. e. Development of dairy farmers cooperative cociety/community. f. Analysis of economic impact of the project.', 'Selection of villages and participants,Clinical package intervention for herd health management,Formation of co-operative/society/community,Production records and economic evaluation,food security evaluation,market access to the milk producers,impact of future contracting\r\n', 'The rural poverty rate is about 41% of which 32% are ultra-poor people living particularly in the char areas of northern Bangladesh. The objective of the study was to improve livelihood and food security of extremely poor people of different char areas through herd health management with the development to milk marketing channels to increase the productivity of the animals and to reduce the poverty experienced by the farmers. A total of 600 dairy households having at least one cow and 300 non-dairy households in 12 villages of island char areas from Sariakhandi, Islampur and Belkuchi Upazilas of Bogra, Jamalpur and Sirajganj districts, respectively were randomly selected. Various components were assessed through direct interviewing the farmers on family size, land ownership, livestock composition, sanitation and source of drinking water and other household items using pre-tested questionnaire. The bench mark scenarios of 600 dairy and 300 non-dairy char households from 12 villages of three Upazilas were recorded. It was revealed that about 50% of the people were involved in dairying and both men (47%) and women (53%) were associated in cattle rearing. Ownership of 5 (202m2) and 10 (405m2) decimals homestead area of dairy group were 61%, 14%; 62%, 10% and 60%, 13%;and cultivable land of 10 and 20 decimals were 44.5%, 13.5%; 43.5%, 12% and 38%, 5% in Sariakandi, Islampur and Belkuchi upazilas, respectively. About 70% and 74% dairy households had the drinking water and sanitation facilities, respectively, while 49% and 44% non-dairy households had such facilities. The livestock population in three upazilas of 300 dairy households was 3065 of which 946 were cattle; while 1915 were of non-dairy households including 17 cattle. Average daily income of each dairy and non-dairy household was 129/- and 109/- Taka, respectively. Further, many of the dairy household group had a bicycle (n=54), radio (n-59) and cell phone (n211), but few in the non-dairy had a bicycle (n=8) and cell phone (n=43). On average, 97.2% of the cattle in these three areas were indigenous and only 2.8% were crossbreed cattle. About 24% of the cows were affected with various reproductive problems such as longer calving intervals (&gt; 430 days; 20.1%), repeat breeding (3.7%), abortion (5.1%), dystocia (6.7%) and retention of placenta (4.6%). A package of veterinary services comprising deworming, vaccination against important diseases, oestrus synchronization of sub-fertile cows, artificial insemination (A1) and management of repeat breeding cows was delivered for 1466 animals of the selected dairy households. Cattle health was improved by gaining body weight (80g/day/cow) and the average milk yield increased from 1.4 to 2.2 liters/day/cow after three months of veterinary services. A total of 268 sub-fertile cows were synchronized using PGF2&amp;#945; analogue and 67.5% of the treated cows showed oestrus after an average of 68-70 hrs and pregnancy was confirmed in 54.1% cows. The pregnancy rate of cows was 50% following AI of 115 cows using frozen semen. Eighty eight repeat breeding wows treated with gonadotrophin releasing hormone (GnRH) immediately after natural service had 29.5% pregnancy. All the dairy farmers were organized into 24 groups through motivation. An informal contractual arrangement for milk marketing was developed between the milk producing groups and Gowalas (Middleman) through series of discussion. Both parties were benefited in terms of a better milk price after developing this market channel. Package delivery of  productive veterinary health care services improved the general health, production  and fertility status of the dairy cows. Improved milk marketing channel with farmers good bargaining power facilitate to gate better economic return. Dairying implies substantial contribution to ensure the livelihood and food security of char dwellers. ', 'Livelihood, Herd health management, Milk market, Poor farmers', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 2000000, 2000000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Herd health management &amp; marketing', 'Livestock', '1) As a result of package delivery of veterinary services and milk market development, the cattle health, fertility, pregnancy rate and milk price increased.\r\n2) The artificial insemination improved the local stock.\r\n3) Organized group formation improved the bargaining power of the local livestock keepers for better milk price.\r\n4) The productivity of livestock and profitability of livestock keepers have been increased.', 'Two interventions viz. a) package delivery of improved veterinary services and b) Milk market development when expand to all over the char areas. Then there would be a revolutionery change in improving the herd health generating more income ensuring better food security and improving livelihood of charlanders.', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(1321, 'SEDA', 'SEDA, Rebeca cottage, Mashkanda, Mymensingh', 'Project', 'Assessment of effectiveness of IPM practices for pest management in Brinjal', 'Gafargaon upazila under Mymensingh district and Islampur upazila under Jamalpur district ', '', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '1.	To improve the effectiveness of IPM technologies in terms of productivity (t/ha) and profitability (%) in brinjal.\r\n2.	To evaluate the economics and profitability (%) of growing brinjal using IPM techn0ologies.\r\n3.	To adapt and up-scaling of rice-duck farming system in some specific ecological conditions.\r\n', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1844208, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '1.	The highest yield of 52 t/ha and BCR benefited the farmers in brinjal production.\r\n2.	The introduction of IPM practices and its contribution to high return would encourage many farmers for adoption.\r\n3.	The use of IPM practices minimized pesticide uses and saved huge amount of foreign currency.\r\n', 'The IPM practices would provide: (1) Long term strategy for minimizing crop loses,\r\n(2) Safeguard the environment from pesticide-pollution, \r\n(3) Minimize/cut down the uses of pesticides and save considerable amount of foreign currency, (4) Minimize/reduce the risks of health hazards and above all \r\n(5) Established the strong base for production of organic high value commodities (HVCs) for export earnings.\r\n', ''),
(1322, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Pomology Division, Horticulture Research Centre', 'Project', 'Standardization of production practices and technology transfer of BARI Strawberry-1', '', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-11-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-11-2011', '1) To find out appropriate planting time and plant spacing for BARI Strawbery-1 to maximize yield and quality.\r\n2) To determine suitable mulch materials for BARI Strawbery-1.\r\n3) To find out the proper pot size and soil media for urban roof top culture of BARI Strawbery-1.\r\n4) To disseminate production technology and adoption of BARI Strawbery-1 among the enthusiastic farmers.', '', '', 'BARI Strawbery-1, Mulch, Roof top', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 0, 1350000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fruit production technology development', 'Strawberry', 'Several experiments on time of planting and plant spacing, effect of different mulch materials and plant spacing, effect of different soil amendments, nutrient management, weed management and roof top pot experiments on pot size and potting media were conducted. Planting of BARI Strawberry-1 on 01 October and 40 cm. plant to plant distance with straw mulch was most suitable. Tricho-compost @ 3 t/ha + 0.5 of recommended chemical fertilizer + 0.6% leacet in combination of N120P70K120S40 (kg/ha) was most suitable for soil amendments and nutrient management of BARI Strawberry-1. For weed management combination of herbicide + black polythene was most effective. For pot cultivation combination of 12 inches pot with 50% soil + 50% poultry refuse was most suitable. ', 'To developed appropriate planting time, plant spacing, weed, soil and nutrient management for BARI Strawberry-1 to maximize yield and quality.', ''),
(1323, 'Agrarian Research Foundation', 'Agrarian Research Foundation', 'Project', 'Global market analysis for production and export potentials of high valued crops.', 'Dhaka and Gazipur', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-10-2010', '01-05-2009', '30-10-2010', '1) To identify high value crops that are grown or can potentially be grown for export markets.\r\n2) To identify potential export markets for high value crops from Bangladesh.', '', '', 'Global Market, Export, High value crops', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1884609, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Global market for export', 'High value products/crops', '1) The project has identified several crops, especially some new potential crops such as strawberry, cashew nut, sesame, barley, fresh fruits and vegetables.\r\n2) The farmers would benefit from growing the high value commodities due to their export potential.\r\n3) Potential export markets for high value crops have been identified.', '1) The cultivation and export market potentials of some identified high value crops would encourage diversification and growth of agriculture.\r\n2) Prospect of growing some of these crops in the vulnerable hilly areas of Chittagong, Sylhet and coastal areas in the southern districts would help utilization of all these vulnerable areas, which remain mostly fallow during winter/dry season, for production of high value crops.\r\n3) A potential source of foreign currency earning.', ''),
(1324, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Hill Agricultural Research Station, Khagrachari', 'Project', 'Validation of Improved agricultural technologies at farmer''s field in hill farming system.', 'Khagrachari sadar, Dighinala and Panchari Upazila of Khagrachari District.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '1) To screen out modern crop varieties suitable for production in Khagrachari.\r\n2) To standardize and adopt home-garden model in Khagrachari.\r\n3) To improve knowledge and skill of farmers for growing improved varieties in the hilly areas.', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1899198, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '1.	Vegetables and quick growing fruit suitable for hill farming have been identified which produced higher economic benefit for the farmers.\r\n2.	A home garden model has been standardized which can produce and supply vegetable sufficient for a family of 5 members round the year.\r\n', '1.	A year round homestead vegetable production model would bring high economic return for the hill farmers.\r\n2.	Increased vegetable production and consumption provided more nutrition to hill farmers. \r\n', ''),
(1325, 'AID-Comilla', 'AID-COMILLA, Comilla sadar, Comilla', 'Project', 'Ecological determinants of Bamboo flowering and rodent population outbreaks in the Chittagang Hill Tracts.', 'Ruma Upazila of Bandarban District', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '1) To understand the ecological consequences of gregarious bamboo flowering, simultaneous rat-outbreaks, heavy crop damages and consequent livelihood of CHT- indigenous people.\r\n2) To establish evidences of relationship between gregarious flowering and rat brakes/rat floods.', '', '', 'Bamboo flowering, Rate brakes, Rodent Population', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 2000000, 2000000, 0, '', '', 0, '', 'Bamboos', '1.	A close relationship exists between rat population build-up and bamboo-flowering bamboo seed-falling on the ground.\r\n2.	The high population pressure resulted in migration of rats from forest habitats to nearby jhum crop fields and household food storages.\r\n3.	Trap barrier system (TBS) is more effective in controlling rates of jhum fields than  bamboo fence.\r\n', 'An understanding about the behavioral phenomena between rat population and bamboo flowering would help the locals to make early predictions and undertake precautionary measures to protect their jhum crops from possible rat damage.', ''),
