(1082, 'Bangladesh Tea Research Institute', 'Soil', 'Project', 'Improvement of soil health in tea garden for sustainable productivity.', '', '', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-1998', '30-04-2001', '01-05-1998', '', 'i)  Characterization of experimental sites.\r\nii)  To study the uptake of both major and minor elements under fertilizer management programme at different locations.\r\niii)  To study the efficiency of urea on the yield of tea and residual effect of applied fertilizers on soil health in tea gardens\r\niv)  To evaluate the yield response with different tratments used in the study.\r\nv)  To make a comprehensive fertilizer recommendation package to the growers.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1046000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fertility Management', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
(1277, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Postharvest Technology Division', 'Project', 'Study on the effect of ripening chemicals on postharvest quality of major fruits and vegetables ', 'Mango- Chapai Nawabgonj, Meherpur\r\nBanana- Tangail (Modhupur),Bogra\r\nTomato- Chapai Nowabgonj and Panchagar districts\r\n', 'High', 'Strategic, Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2003', '30-06-2006', '01-07-2003', '30-06-2006', '	To assess the various chemicals and their doses used to accelerate/retard the ripening   \r\n    time for 	fruits like mango, banana, pineapple, papaya and vegetables like tomato.\r\n	To evaluated the effect of ripening chemicals on the quality of fruits and vegetables. \r\n	To study the residual effect of various ripening chemicals. \r\n	To standardize the doses of chemicals for ripening experimental fruits and vegetables.\r\n', 'Four different types of fruits viz. mango, banana, pineapple, papaya and one vegetables viz. tomato will be selected for the study. Both the fresh and chemically treated fruits/vegetables will be collected from the major growing areas. The chemically treated fruits/vegetables will be analyzed for determination of their nutrient content quality and residual effect of chemicals. The laboratory experiment will be conducted with fresh fruits and vegetables. Ripening chemicals viz. Ethophane, Harvest, Tomtom, Eden, Eipen-15, Promote, Profit, Gold plus etc. will be used in the study. Various doses of ripening chemicals including the farmers/traders practices will be used for treating the fruits/vegetables. The samples will be stored at ambient temperature. Various physico-chemicals parameters nutritional attributes of fruits and vegetables and the residual effect of chemicals will be studied during the experimental/storage period. ', 'In Bangladesh some of the fruits and vegetables growers and traders are using various chemicals to accelerate ripening of fruits and vegetables. The fruits and vegetables treated with chemicals are mango, banana, pineapple, papaya and tomato. The farmers or traders do not follow any standard doses. They use higher doses of chemicals to accelerate ripening process. Even they apply the chemicals in immature fruits and vegetables those are nutritionally poor. As a result, the eating quality of chemically treated fruits and vegetables available in the market is not good and are not acceptable by the consumers. Considering the above situation assessment of artificial ripening practices by chemicals on quality of tomato, banana, mango, papaya and pineapple was undertaken. Assessment of artificial ripening practices in mango was carried out in Rajshahi, Chapai Nowabgonj Kustia and Meherpur, for banana Bogra, Joypurhat, Modhupur and Kustia, for tomatoes Rajshahi, Chapai Nowabgonj, Jessore and Kustia, for papaya Modhupur and Gazipur and for pineapple Modhupur. It was observed that farmers and traders of Rajshahi and Chapai Nowabgonj area used ethephon and ethrel for ripening tomato. They used 100cc ethrel/5-7lit water for 15-20 mond tomatoes. Tomatoes are ripened within 6-8 days. Tomtom, Profit and Ripen-15 are used also Jessore and Kustia area in the same way. In winter season, farmers and traders are used high doses of ripening chemicals. Ripen-15 is used in Bogra and Joypurhat region for banana. In Kustia region Profit, Promote and calcium carbide are used to ripe the bananas. They used Profit 10ml/lit water and calcium carbide 75-100g for 4-5 bunches of banana. The farmers/traders of Modhupur are also used same doses of ripening chemicals for bananas. In case of mango the farmers/traders of Kustia and Meherpur region use calcium carbide 75-100gm/40kg of mango. In Rajshahi and Chapai Nowabgonj region, ethrel are used. In case of papaya Promote, Tomtom, Profit, Harvest, etc are used in Modhupur and Gazipur region. Farmers and traders of Modhupur region used 20ml/10lit water for 700-800 pineapples. ', 'Mango, Banana, Tomato, Ripening chemicals, Postharvest quality, Major fruit, Vegetables.', 'BARC', 575000, 575000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1311, 'Bangladesh Centre for Advanced Studies', 'Bangladesh Centre for advanced studies', 'Project', 'Assessing the longterm impacts of climatic vulnerabilities on crop production and evaluation of adaptation practices in the vulnerable areas of Bangladesh.', 'Drought prone area in Rajshahi. Five districts in flood prone area. Five districts in Coastal area and three districts in hilly area.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '1) To assess the impacts of climate change hazards on crop production in the vulnerable areas (droughts, floods, salinity/tidal surges and erosion prone hills) of Bangladesh.\r\n2) To evaluate the severity and extent of extreme conditions affecting crop production in vulnerable areas.\r\n3) To screen, identify and suggest some innovative farming practices to improve crop production and mitigate sufferings.\r\n', '', '', 'climate change hazards,droughts, floods, salinity/tidal surges and erosion prone hills ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1527618, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Climate change', 'Adaptation technology', '1) Some adaptation options with production packages for different climate vulnerable areas were identified.\r\n2) Innovative practices like use of seed priming, mulching, zero tillage and dry land farming increased yield by 9-34% in different climatically vulnerable areas.', 'The innovative options for different vulnerable areas, if adopted and up-scaled, would help the farmers to cope/live with the adverse situation, improve productivity, food security and livelihood.', ''),
(1312, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'On-Farm Research Division', 'Project', 'Adaptation of suitable crops in saline soils of Noakhali.', 'Four Upazilas of Noakhali district', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '1) To select suitable crops/varieties for specific level of soil salinity.\r\n2) To evaluate the performance of selected crops/varieties at different level of soil salinity.\r\n3) To utilize the fallow land of coastal saline areas for cultivation of crops.\r\n', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1719398, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', 'a.	Suitable crops for cultivation at varying degrees of soil salinity have been identified.\r\nb.	Critical soil salinity level of soybean groundnut, sweet potato, mungbean, cowpea, sunflower, chilly wheat, barley, kaon, sugar beet, really kheshari and lined have been determined. \r\nc.	Adaptability of soybean, cowpea, sweet potato and grasspea was assessed for upscaling in 4  upazilla of Noakhali district. \r\n', 'a.	Crops identified for different levels of soil salinity can be cultivated during winter / dry season when a vast area of land remain fallow due to high level of soil salinity.\r\nb.	Cropping intensity and land productivity can be improved in the selected 4 upazilas. \r\n', ''),
(1313, 'Khulna University', 'Fisheries and Marine Resources Technology Discipline', 'Project', 'GIS and Remote Sensing Database for Spatial decision support system for sustainable shrimp culture in south-west coastal region of Bangladesh.', 'Pikegacha of Khulna, Shamnagar of Satkhira and Rampal of Bagerhat districts.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2010', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2010', 'To develop GIS and remote sensing database to identify potential site for shrimp production.', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1998201, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', 'a.	Suitable areas for shrimp production have been identified in 3 upazilas based on 16 parameters.\r\nb.	Upazila maps showing the suitable areas for shrimp culture are produced.\r\n', 'a.	Proper zoning of shrimp culture can be made in all coastal districts of Bangladesh using the same techniques for profitable shrimp culture.\r\nb.	Shrimp farmers will be able to select appropriate sites for shrimp culture.\r\n', ''),
(1314, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pathology', 'Project', 'Molecular Characterization of poultry salmonellae and production of formalin killed pullorum disease vaccine using local isolate in Bangladesh.', 'BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '13-05-2009', '12-05-2011', '13-05-2009', '12-05-2011', '1) Molecular characterization of the salmonella vaccine developed in Bangladesh that can be used for the patenting of the vaccine.\r\n2) Phytogenetic relationship of the vaccine bacteria with the field isolates will be known.\r\n', '', 'Salmonella Pullorum causes pullorum disease resulting severe systematic disease of poultry and that cause economic losses through mortality, morbidity and reducing in egg production. The mortality of pullorum disease confined mainly to the first 2-3 weeks of age chicks and mortality varies from 35 to 100%. The disease also affects layer birds and cocks. For prevention and control of the pullorum disease in chicks potent vaccine is the most important and effective tool to vaccinate layer birds. Salmonella Pullorum bacteria were isolated through different laboratory approaches and the methods were culture in different media, morphological study by Grams stain, carbohydrate fermentation test, biochemical test, motility test. One of the isolated bacteria was used as master seed for production of Pullorum disease vaccine. Efficacy of prepared vaccine and molecular characterization of vaccine bacteria are under progress.', 'Molecular characterization, salmonella vaccine, Phytogenetic relationship ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 2000000, 2000000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Livestock Development', 'Poultry disease', '1) Vaccine from local isolate of Salmonella pullorum has been developed.\r\n2) Molecular method and Polymerase chair reaction (PCR) for diagnosis of Salmonella has been standardized.', 'Avian Salmonellosis of poultry in Bangladesh can be effectively controled/prevented by the vaccine produced from the local isolate.', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
