(512, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Modification of physical and chemical characteristics of jute fibre fibre to improve', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'Jute fibre is basically coarse, stiff, brittle and  thus unsuitable for fine spinning due to the presence of lignin and other non-fibrous materials which are about 40% of the weight of the fibre. so this is not used  in textile purposes. This fibre mayhowever be soft and flexible or modified through partial removal of lignin and other non-fibrous materials by suitable chemical means in order to obtain better spinnable fibres. Treatment of jute by sulphonation process to remove the non fibrous constituents to some extent has already been reported. Moreover sulphonation adds some more properties to the fibres inducing better fibrils arrangement within the intrinsic fibre without causing significant loss of strength. It has also been reported that the blending of chemically modified jute staples with  cotton and natural and synthetic fibres produces more regular yarn. But no study has so far been made on the modified fibre blended with silk, wool &amp; silk wool fibres. It is expected hat jute-silk and wool blends may develop some novel properties in modified yarn and fabrics. The present programme has been undertaken to study the physico-chemical properties of jute fibre modified by different chemical means with special reference to sulphonation and to determine the properties of textile processing of the modified jute staples blended with wool, silk fibres and also to assess the development of the physico-mechanical properties of the blended yarns and fabrics.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
