(519, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To develop dyes, pigments, thickener and finishing agents for jute and jute products.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '01-12-2001', '', '', 'The dyeing and Printing Division has been able to utilize the indigenous raw materials for the preparation of thickeners which could be successfully used for both jute and blended fabrics, This project is on  going project to study the indigenous and natural materials on printing technology. High price, scarcity of natural thickeners and increase demand of thickeners stimulate the search of locally available natural materials to be used as textile thickeners. The starches which the field of textile printing  will be studied further.were already examined and tried to use as mixed and single thickeners in', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(520, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'a) Development of laboratory processes for preparing emulsions by using different vegetables oils.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1997', '', '', '', 'The jute fibres are naturally stiff , brittle and less extensible. The fibres do not  possess much  spinning properties. A hairy yarn with much waste is produced if the jute fibre is carded and spun in its natural state. Hence to spin the jute fibre smoothly the fibre stiffness is needed to be reduced that is, the fibre is required to be softened before spinning. It is known that oil acts as lubricants. During jute processing oil lubricates the fibre to help their free movement. Water gives the required flexibility of fibres. It is also known that emulsions give better results than separate application of water and oil due to easy control process, easy spreading and deposition of oil conventionally to prepared jute batching emulsion. In recent years, the use of this mineral oil (which contains carcinogenic hydrocarbon) in processing of jute has become a matter of great concern as various questions have been raised by the developed countries to the fact that batching oil containing objectionable hydrocarbons residue migrate and contaminate the food grains packed in the jute bags. As a result, the business prospect of jute goods in the exporting countries is being affected. It is therefore, necessary to replace the mineral oil by a vegetable oil for preparing the emulsion that could be used for jute processing in view of this state circumstances, the project has been undertaken to develop cost effective methods of preparing jute batching emulsions by using cheaply available vegetable oils.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(521, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Pilot scale production and development of jute products.', '', '', '', '', '01-04-1997', '31-03-1999', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(522, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To find out a process for manufacturing of synthetic dyes by means of reaction with various chemicals and to apply them ', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1997', '31-12-2000', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(523, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To develop some textile properties of jute materials for diversified end uses.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'Jute had once world wide market for quite a long time because of its unique properties like high strength, rough handling advantage, silky lustre, low extensibility, environment friendly, easily degradable, considerable heat and fire resistance properties. However, jute products also possess certain drawbacks namely, harsh feel, high rigidity, high fibreshedding,  short fibre length and susecptability to deterioration by moisture. These defects make the traditional jute products rough, dusty and poor handiling. Moreover, its uses are being reduced due to tough competition with allied and synthetic fibres. The conventional uses of this commodity as sacking, hessian and carpet backing cloth being reduced. So non-conventional products are sougt in wider textile fields at present. Such atrtempts need improvements of inherent drawbacks of the  jute fibre, yarn and fabric. From the literature it is expected that the above demerits of jute may substantially removed by chemical modification. The work has therefore been taken to modify jute fibre/yarn/fabric by cross-linking reaction. The results may increase the serviceability of the jute fibre/yarn/fabrics. Consequently it may also be possible to increase the elastic properties of jute carpet which is now facing complaints for possessing poor resistance. Such process is also expected to reduce the hygroscopicity of the carpets, which in turn may provide lesser susceptibility to fungal growth. This low susceptibility of bacterial/fungal growth will enable to increase the durability of jute carpet in the long run. In view of this the work to modify jute with new resins like DMEU/epoxy resin has been proposed here in continuation of our previous work on cross linking in BJRI. Jute and jute carpets will be studied for improvement in the proposed project work.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(524, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Development of enzymatic biopulping and biobleaching process from green jute/kenaf (whole plant).', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'Wood and bamboo are the only source for pulp and paper industry and these two items are in acute shortage to meet up our growing demand. To mitigate this situation it is urgently needed to find out an alternate source of wood and bamboo for pulping. Considering the growing demand of pulp and paper and also increasing conscious for preserving\r\nforest, jute being an annual crop, can be used as renewable source of raw materials for pulping. BCIC has already started chemical pulping from whole jute plant.\r\nThe chemical pulping processes are health hazardous and also pollute the environment. In this situation it is necessary to find out viable and novel method to minimize the pollution of present chemical pulping processes.\r\nIt is reported by various workers about the possible use of microbial pretreatment prior to chemical pulping and enzymatic bleaching have profound effect about the chemical requirement during chemical pulping. Microbial and enzymatic processes are environment friendly and they do not pollute the environment. Development of biopulping and biobleaching processes will have tremendous impact on the environmental pollution problem created by chemical pulping. This will facilitate  newer uses jute plant instead of tedious retting process.\r\nSo attempts are now being undertaken to develop biopulping and enzymatic biobleaching processes in making pulp and paper from green jute/kenaf (whole plant)', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(525, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Development of bleaching process for the diversified uses of jute.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '31-12-2002', '', '', 'For the diversified use of jute, chemicals are used for bleaching of jute products. During bleaching process some organic halides are discharged which pollute the enviornment\r\nIn view of the above various Laboratories of world are trying to use ligninase enzymes. Attempts  will be made to isolate proper microorganisms for the secretion of ligninase i.e. lignin peroxidase, Mn peroxidase and laccase. These crude enzyme will be used in various sequences of  chemical bleaching to reduce chemicals now being used in the present bleaching process.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(526, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To study the physical properties of all-jute and blended union furnishing fabrics.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1998', '01-01-2002', '', '', 'Furnishing fabrics are generally made with cotton and man-made fibres. Jute yarns may be used instead of synthetic yarn. Thus the use of jute yarn may be  increased', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
