(531, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To obtain ways of removing arsenic (As) from water using jute as filtering media.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh is a plain land formed by bengal delta, moreover 200 rivers have criss crossed it like a net work. One third of its land are being inundated with seasonal monsoon water. But since last few years deterioration of atmosphere, descending of ground water, deterioration changes of quality in internal water etc are appearing due to continuous deforestation, draught, flood, agroecological practices &amp; many other environmental degrading reasons. For agricultural development shallow &amp; deep tube well are utilizes as major input for irrigation purpose in the major areas of the country.\r\nThus &amp; for other reasons our internal and as well as the normal water are getting surfaces which involve heavy metal appearance. This is seriously harmful for health &amp; overall environment of the country and has become a national problem now. As such chemists, Environmentalist, public health people are trying to evolve a cost effective proper technique for removing heavy metal like arsenic(As) particularly from drinking water immediately.\r\nJute is lignocellulosic meshy structural compound having cellulose, hemicellulose &amp; lignin as major component. It is hydrophilic, anionic &amp; composite in nature. The various characteristic properties of jute e.g. physical &amp; chemical properties and tendency to form hydrogen bond seems to be suitable for chelation with arsenic (As) in water in optimim condition.\r\n The present programme has been undertaken to exploit this property of jute fibre to develop a technology by utilizing its chelate  forming character in revoving arsenic (As) founds in the water using natural &amp; modified fibre ,yarn, fabrics of jute as necessary.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(532, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To obtain ways of fine spinning of jute fibres having improved physico-chemical properties.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1994', '', '', '', 'For fine spinning jute fibres having lesser non-cellulosic i.e. non fibres constituents are desirable early harvest may serve such purpose. Attempts are therefore necessary to determine the optimum harvesting time of the jute plant. In view of this the project has been undertaken', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(533, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', '141', 'Project', 'Utilization of biologically decomposed jute materials and wastes as fertilizer', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'Jute has been used in various purposes throughout the world. a huge quantity of jute bags, sacks and other packing materials are being rejected and disposed every year after one or several time uses. Usually these materials are either burnt or kept in heaps making environment hazardous. Burning of these rejected or old jute goods and wastes cause environmental pollution. The burnt debris has no potential use of economic value. The present project has been undertaken for making the environment pollution-free from those hazardous materials. Moreover, through microbial or enzymatic degradation of these rejected jute and jute products. It will be possible to get bio-fertilizers.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(534, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Improvement of jute fibre quality by the application of xylanase,', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'In microbiology Laboratory of BJRI (Tech.) a number of mesophilic land thermophilic fungi have been isolated and identified. Experiments were carried out with those organism to assess their suitability. Their efficiency in upgrading jute cuttings and low grade jute and in sacharification purposes are not very much satisfactory. So the continual search for a suitable microbes is a basic routine work for upgrading jute cuttings and low grade jute. These organisms may also be used in various other purposes of the divisional research projects.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(535, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Improvement and cost reduction of traditional jute products.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'From literature survey it has been revealed that the most of the white-rot fungi have the ability to degrade lignin of various lignocellulosic materials. For the improvement of the quality of jute fibre, it is very much essential to remove lignin from jute fibre. In view of that we are trying to isolate some white-rot fungi from various sources. From these isolated organism, enzyme will be produced for the degradation of lignin of jute fibre and thereby to reduce chemical in the bleaching process. Enzymes are environmental pollution created by the discharge of wastes during the chemical process. So attempt should be taken to adopt enzymatic process for the development of new jute product.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(536, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Development of pectinolytic xylanolytic enzymes for the improvement of the quality of fibre.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '31-12-2000', '', '', 'A number of fungi are now being used for production of crude enzyme preparation through exploitation of their cultural  parameters. Thus the enzyme production can be increased to certain limited extent. But in order to make the different projects of the division more effective and viable, the enzyme productivity of the extensively used fungal strains need to be increased further through developments of hyper enzymes producing mutants.\r\nthe enzyme productivity of potential strains can be increased by changing their genosome through mutation either by Gamma radiation or chemical mutagents. Therefore, this projects is under taken to improve the enzyme productivity by producing hyper enzyme producing mutants through mutation.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(537, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To improve the physical and chemical characteristics of low grade jute and fabrics for its diversified use.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'A number of fungi are now being used for production of crude enzyme preparation through exploitation of their cultural  parameters. Thus the enzyme production can be increased to certain limited extent. But in order to make the different projects of the division more effective and viable, the enzyme productivity of the extensively used fungal strains need to be increased further through developments of hyper enzymes producing mutants. the enzyme productivity of potential strains can be increased by changing their genosome through mutation either by Gamma radiation or chemical mutagents. Therefore, this projects is under taken to improve the enzyme productivity by producing hyper enzyme producing mutants through mutation.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(538, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To fix suitable balanced twists for conventional jute yarns of lower counts.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1997', '01-01-2002', '', '', 'Conventional jute yarns manufactured in industries are not of less than 138 Tex (4 lbs/spy). The yarns are usually spin by flyer spinning  frames and the twist factors and optimum  twists are known to the technologists,. As twist is important , the  amount of its insertion needs to be carefully selected. There is no internationally acceptable value for the insertion of number of twists for the yarns of count lower than 138 Tex. The project aims at determining the optimum twists for the non-conventional yarns of count lower than 138 Tex (4 lbs/spy)', '', '\r\n', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(539, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To study the effect of change of draft, doubling and type of the drawing  machinery on yarn quality.', '', '', '', '', '01-06-1999', '01-06-2002', '', '', 'Drawing stages are very vital for jute processing. Thus drawing machinery/frames play an important role on physical properties of yarn. Sliver as received from the finisher card is only moderately uniform and the fibres in the sliver are not parallel. So the sliver require further treatment in order to make it as uniform as possible and to straighten the fibres in the sliver. All these conditions are fulfilled in the process known as &quot;Drawing and Doubling&quot;.There are several types of drawing ;frames, all alike in regard to the arrangement of essentials. The difference in faller bar mechanism gives them different names of which push bar and spiral drawing frames are in common use. Push bar drawing again is of two types. One is orthodox and another is High speed  type.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(540, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Improvement of productivity and quality of traditional jute yarns.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '01-01-2002', '', '', 'Presently, the hessian spinning frame of different jute mills are producing 7-12 count yarn. in some cases 5-6 count yarn can be produced by reducing the flyer speed of the machine which  leads to lower production.As a result production cost of this yarn is higher. Accepting this higher production cost some mills of the country are producing this type of yarn in limited scale .this type of yarns are slidely used in fine fabrics, shopping bags, handicrafts etc. Light weight and cost effective shopping bags are most essential to replace polythene bags from the market . It may be possible to produce 5-6 count yarn by the existing hessian spinning frame with higher production rate within acceptable cost. If a system can be developed for this type of yarn the mills will be  immensely benefited by producing this yarn.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(541, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Performance of emulsion with different vegetable oil on jute processing.', '', '', '', '', '01-06-1999', '01-06-2002', '', '', 'Jute is a hard fibre and it does not posses much  spinning  properties.. airy yarn with much waste is produced if jute fibre is carded and spin in its natural  stage. Hence to spin jute fibre smoothly the stiffness of the fibre  is needed. That is the fibre is required to be soft end before spinning. It is known that water and oil act as lubricants. During jute processing oil fibres and helps their free movement. Water gives the required flexibility. It is also known that emulsion gives better result than separate application of water and oil due to easy control of process, easy spreading and deposition of oil conventionally to prepare jute batching emulsion.\r\nIn recent years, the use of this mineral oil(which contains hydrocarbon) in processing of jute has become a matter of great concern as various questions have been raised by the developed countries to the fact that batching oil containing objectionable hydrocarbons residue migrate and contaminate the food grins packed in the jut e bags. As a result the business prospects of jute goods in the exporting countries is being affected .It is therefore, necessary to replace the mineral oil by a vegetable oil for preparing the emulsion that could be used for jute processing. In view of this state of circumstances efforts are being made to develop cost effective methods of preparing jute batching emulsion by using cheaply available vegetable oils.With the aim of studying performance of the emulsions prepared from different vegetable oils by trial processing and also to optimize the concentrations of oils in emulsion for desirable processing performance this project has been undertaken.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
