(544, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'A study  on structural Compatibility of jute with man-made fibres used in blends.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1995', '01-01-2001', '', '', 'Blending an up-to-date technique of material science for obtaining desired properties in the end-products has been proved to be immensely beneficial in textile field as well. This techniques has also been applied in jute to diversify its its end-uses. to select proper component fibres for blending with jute, fibre characteristics along with these fibres are complementary to jute in blends are required to be known. To meet these requirements,compatibility of different textile fibres with jute is to be studied,which is responsible for the ultimate physico-mechanical properties and performance characteristics of the blended products.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(545, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'To fix up suitable balanced twists for jute yarns blended with other  textile fibres.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1997', '01-01-2002', '', '', 'Conventionally the yarns are spun  by flyer spinning  frames. The twist  factors and optimum twists are known to the technologists. As twist is important, the  amount of its insertion needs to be carefully selected. There is no internationally  accepted value or number of twists for inserting in blended jute yarns.\r\nSince yarns of jute blended with various man-made or natural fibres are getting importance for its better prospect in jute diversification. And as there has not been  much study to obtain an d fix suitable process parameters like number of twist on yarns of jute study to obtain and fix suitable process parameters like number of twist on yarn of jute blended with different component fibres eg. acrylic/polyester/rayon etc. this project has been undertaken.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(546, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Use of Rotor spinning technology in makiing fine yarns with jute and jute in blending with other fibres.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1998', '01-01-2003', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(547, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Development of enzymatic biobleaching process for jute fabrics and jute pulp.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'For the diversification of jute fabrics and also for bleaching of paper chemicals like chlorine. hypochlorite  and Clo2, H2O2 etc are used as bleaching agents.\r\nIn bleaching  process through which the brightness of the fabric/pulp is increased by removal or modification of some of the constituents of the unbleached pulp and chlorine, hypochlorite and Clo2, H2O2 etc are used as bleaching agents. The chemical effluent as waste water containing organo-halides pollute the enviornment seriously. Considering the growing awarness about enviornmental pollution attempts are now being under taken in various countries to use enzyme prior to bleaching. In this project enzyme will be developed to use in various sequence of bleaching.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(548, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Studies on the photostability of jute and jute products by using different antioxidants and chemical means.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '01-12-2001', '', '', 'Jute is a lignocellulosic bast fibre obtained from the stalks of the plant. Jute both natural and processed when exposed to sunlight and heat, certain deterioration of its properties takes  place particularly change of colour which technologically called yellowing. It is not only cause of yellowing of natural and bleached jute fabrics, but also associated fading of dyed fabrics. Yellowing of jute is a great hindrance for any sophisticated textile use of jute. When jute exposed to light and air then the major component undergo degradation and exposed materials are acidic and contain reducing substances than unexposed one.\r\nMany workers were given conclusion about the processes and causes of yellowing of bleached jute and colour fading of dyed jute product. One of the cause of yellowing and fading is the oxidation of lignin of jute fibre. It is observed that lignin acts as a sensitizer and H2O2 is evolved on irradiation of jute. Photostability of dyed jute products with all classes of dyes very important for diversified and sophisticated textile uses of jute fibre yarn and fabric. The project was undertaken to develop the photostability of dyed jute products by use of antioxidants and chemical means.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(549, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Studies on the vegetable dyes for jute fibre  products.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '01-12-2001', '', '', 'The bast fibre jute for commercial uses is extracted from the annually renewable jute plant (Corchorus Olitorius-Tossa jute and Corchorus Capsularis-white jute) after a process of retting. Chemically ,jute fibre consists of alpha cellulose (59-63%), hemicellulose(20-24%), lignin(12-14%),as major integral constituents and trace amounts of fats,waxes, minerals and minor constituents. The fibres are bio-degradable and eco-friendly. Because of these characteristics, the jute fibres have greater demands then synthetic fibres which are non-biodegradable and environmentally health hazard. For this reason the use of synthetic fibres are posing to decline ,while the use of natural fibres are increasing to maintain ecological balance. It is therefore essential that the physico-chemical modification of jute products by natural dyes should be accomplished in commensurate with environmental friendliness. In the above context, it is necessary to mention that one of the main attributes of jute for many textile application is that jute can be dyed with all classes of dyes due to the presence of cellulosic and non-cellulosic fibre components (i.e. lignin and hemicellulose). For this natural advantage ,jute fibre/fibre products are extensively bleached, dyed for the manufacture of finished products which have wide demand in the domestic and export markets. At present synthetic dyes are used for the production of the above jute based products/made ups. It is true that synthetic dyes give brilliant/bright shades and they are also less expensive. But these dyes do not give adequate fastness to light according to market demands. Furthermore, synthetic dyes which are reported or suspected  to generate/release harmful amines are allergic, carcinogenic or poisonous in nature. In recent years globally the use of dyes and dyeing processes have been increasingly influenced by ecological and toxilogical standards/rules. For example, according to German legislation, textile materials which come in contact with human body must not be dyed with azo dyestuffs. Such regulations may be enforced in other countries of the world. This will invariably affect the export market of jute products. Hence it is essential to avoid the synthetic dyes for dyeing the jute products. There are however, scopes for avoiding these synthetic dyes through the use of natural dyes. Bangladesh is naturally blessed with ever green beauty and flora from which ample vegetable dyes/pigments may be obtained for this purpose. Hence a research study is essential to find out non-toxic vegetable sources from our surroundings in order to obtain natural dyes for dyeing the jute products.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(550, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Physico-chemical aspects of dyeing of jute and jute products', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '01-12-2001', '', '', 'Jute is a ligno-cellulosic bast fibre composed of cellulose, hemicellulose ,lignin as its major components. Technical jute fibre consists of strands,i.e. ,bast bundle fibres assemble in a parallel manner with ends overlapping to produce continuous filaments throughout the length of the stalk.The individual fibres are held together by noncellulosic materials,such as lignin ,hemicellulose and pectin,etc.  to form a fibrous meshy net work. Jute fibre also contains different minute substances,such as oils,waxes,fats,proteinous materials, dirt and colouring materials.\r\nThe traditional uses of jute materials,such as,ropes cords, hessain,sacking and carpet backing clothes are gradually decreasing owing to keen competition from synthetic fibres.However,jute can be used as sophisticated jute products as decoratives,table clothes, wall covers, up-holstery,apparels,etc. For such uses,jute requires wet processes, such as scouring, bleaching, dyeing,printing,finishing and washing. But, it is also observed that in most cases coloured jute materials are not so fast to different agencies like light,water, weather,etc. It must be improved.The present work is undertaken to find out different causes of this problem and effective method for their solution.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(551, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Studies on the spray bleaching techniques on jute and jute products.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '01-12-2001', '', '', 'Dying and Printing Division has developed an economic bleaching methods on jute fibres, jute ribbon and jute products with different types of bleaching reagents (oxidizing and reducing). The previous works have been undertaken   for optimization of low cost economic bleaching and softening methods in the experimental mill of BJRI, Dhaka. But due to some problem it could not be optimized in 1998. So it will be continued in 1999.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(552, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Development of textile finishing/proofing process for jute products by chemical means.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'Jute is highly flammable, the versatile use of this fibre is handicapped to some extent, particularly in some specific purposes where jute products with flame resistance finished are demanded. Considering this disadvantage, a research project was undertaken a few years back to make this fibre flameproof and therefore safer in specialized textile uses.\r\nAttempts were taken to develop suitable processes to impart fire proof finished jute fabrics and yarns. In case of making jute fabrics fire resistant by using some bromine phosphorus based and urea ammonium phosphate based fire retarding chemicals some laboratory processes had been developed. The treatments carried out in this respect were found to impart good fire resistance property to the fabrics causing loss of fabrics strength beyond a reasonable limit. Present work has been undertaken to develop suitable process for imparting desirable flameproof finished to jute fabrics without causing undesirable loss of strength and also to perform some works to improve the processes so far been developed for producing fire-resistant jute products with necessary desirable properties.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
(553, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'TRB', 'Project', 'Irradiation of jute hessian cloth by UV radiation for improvement of its quality.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2000', '', '', '', 'Jute is the potential resource of Bangladesh. Conventionally Jute is used for making bags, carpets, mats and other covering materials. These jute products should be improved in qualities so that it can survive in the world market. The conventional jute products have got some demerits and defects. There are some references of work to improve the property and quality of jute products by using resin materials. It has been reported that this resin treatmet developed a composite characteristics in jute products with improved tensile strength and low water absorbing capacity. This project has been undertaken to improve jute products by application of oligomers and different monomers, filer, photo initiator, through radiation with un light and sun ray etc. It is expected that this uv treatments will give comparatively better results to improve the quality diverified uses of jute.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Agronomy', '', '', '', ''),
