(624, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Gender Issues', '', '', '', '', '01-03-1998', '31-08-1999', '01-07-1998', '30-06-2000', '1. To determine the contribution of women in animal husbandry\r\n2. To analysis the livestock processing activities carried out by women;\r\n3. To determine the insentive that motivate the family members to participate in livestock raising and processing activities;\r\n4. To determine the contribution the women in family income through livestock raising;\r\n5. To ascertain the magnitude of consumption of livestock products from owns source;\r\n6. To suggest suitable policy measures for encouraging women''s participation in livestock rearing and processing.', '', '', '', 'IDA', 692119, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Livestock', '', 'Red investigation showed that the average size of landholding sper farm was 1.96 acreas. It was 9.70 acres, 2.98 acres, 1.11 acres and 0.16 acres for large, medium, small and landless farms, respectively. Aveage size of familly per household was 6.16. The average size of family varied from 5.07 to 8.56. A positive relationship was found with the size of family and landholdings.\r\n\r\nThe major litestock reared by the farms in all areas were cattle, goat, chicken, duck and pigeon. The number of buffalo, sheep, pig and goose were found very insignificant. The average number of catttle, buffalo, goat, sheep, pig, chicken, duck, goose and pigeon per farm for all categories of farms were 2.79, 0.04, 1.22, 0.15, 0.05, 12.46, 2.52, 0.17, and 1.55, respectively.\r\n\r\nThe differeent management practices carried out for livestock production were identified as cleaning of shed, feeding/tending animals/collection of grasss, taking care of pregnant animals, collection of milk and eggs, sale of milk and eggs, purchasing of animals, nursing of animals and taking animals into/out of the shed etc, On average, for all activities men spent 78.31 man-days and women spent 70.74 man-days pr ==er year. Participation of men in different activities were 66.66%&gt; 55.52%, and 44.20% for large, mieium, small and landless farms, respectively, Participation of women for those activities were 37.34%, 44.48%, 46.70% and 55.80% for large, medium, small and landless farms, respectively. Results showed that participation of men in livestock raising activities inxcrease with the increase in farm sixe but of women increases with the decrease in farm size.\r\n\r\nCost and return from livestock raising were analysed. It was found that 86.35% per cent of the total cost was accounted for variable cost. The net return per farm was Tk. 561227. Benefit cost ratio (on total cost) was acconted for 1.66:1.\r\n\r\nThe share of vairable cost to total cost for male and female headed households were 85.98% and 91.72%, respectively. Net return was found higher for male headed household.\r\n\r\nThe share of livestock income to total household income was 30.82 per cent of which the contribution of male and female members were 52.54% and 47.46%  , respectively. The wage rate was found significantly lower for women labourers. \r\n\r\nIn decision making process for raising livestock, the magnitude of participation of men and women were 45% and 53.40%, respectively. The participation of women in decision making process was found higher for smalll  animals and poultry.\r\n\r\nThe factors that mativate the women members in participating livestock rearing activities were identified as increasing personal and family income, increasin the status of women, utilization of idle women labour, supplying animal protein for family nutrition etc. Of these factors, the highest opinions were for increasing family income (77.45%), followed by increasing the status of female members (52.72%)\r\n\r\nThe consumption of livestock products from own suouces was found higher (egg 3.68) nons. Milk 3.39 lit,) than those purchased from the market (egg 0.60) no, milk  0.60 lit,) with the exception of duck and beef.\r\n\r\nAn analysis on the utilization pattern of income from livestock sources showed that a significant portion of income (23.91%) was spent for purchasing food, followed by investment in agricualture (15.37%) and investment in business (11.19%).', '', ''),
(899, 'Bangladesh Tea Research Institute', 'Crops', 'Project', 'Varietal Improvement and Multiplication of Tea Through Tissue Culture Techniques.', '', '', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '01-11-1997', '', 'i)  Rapid multiplication of the superior tea plants which have high yielding characteristics as well as better cup quality.\r\nii)  Selection of desirable plants through screening by exploiting somaclonal variation.\r\niii)  Development of homozygous diploid plants derived through anther culturre', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 729000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Tissue Culture', 'Tea', '', '', ''),
(900, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Crops', 'Project', 'Studies on the protocol development for tissue culture techniques of fruits and ornamentals at Agricultural Research Station, Pahartali, Chittagong.', '', '', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-06-1998', '31-05-2001', '01-06-1998', '', 'a)	To establish tissue culture laboratory (pilot production unit) at Pahartali for the development of mass propagation protocol of fruits and ornamentals crops.\r\n\r\nb)	To produce disease free sapling of fruits and ornamentals plants.\r\n\r\nc)	To popularise the tissue culture technology through demonstration.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 2000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Tissue Culture', 'Fruits', '', '', ''),
(626, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Impact of Smallholder Livestock Development Project in Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '', '', '01-06-1997', '31-08-1997', '1. To Estimate the number of poultry reared by each beneficiary farm by breed and calculate the mortality rate.\r\n2. To determine the level of household income from SLDP and from other sources.\r\n3. To analyse the pattern of consumption of beneficiary households with special reference to animal protein.\r\n4. To determine the socio-economic impact of the project on beneficiary farms.', '', '', '', 'DANIDA', 344511, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Chicken', 'Poultry', 'This study was conducted in 5 districts of Bangladesh with 3 NGO''s covering 1000 farm households to evaluate the impact of interventions made by SLDP on socio-economic conditions of rural poor women. Results showed that the SLDP has made substantial positive impact on poultry population, adoption of HYVs, disease control and mortality, employment, income and empowerment of women in rural areas. The larger beneficiaries of the project are poor men and women. Ghe average size of loan received per beneficiary was Tk. 2587 which varied from Tk. 1,000 to Tk. 10,000, depending on the type of beneficiary farms. The repayment rate of loans was 99 per cent. The recovery system of SLDP credit varied among NGOs depending on the nature of their own credit administration. BRAC and Swanirvar, for example, collect repayment instalment on a weekly basis while Proshika collects it on a monthly/seasonal basis.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe contribution of SLDP to generate income and to reduce poverty of the rural poor is significat. Further extension of the programme in other areas of the country is desirable. It is also desirable to intensify the programme integrating goat and cattle enterprises with poultry. This will increase the level of income of beneficiaries and help alleviate their poverty.', '', ''),
(627, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Economics of poultry farms in Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1994', '31-12-1995', '01-05-1994', '31-03-1996', '1. To determine the productivity; cost and return aspects of different types of poultry farms under different managements\r\n2;To determine the employment opportunities created in these farms ; and\r\n3.To calculate the marketing cost and margin for eggs  poultry.', '', '', '', 'IDA', 259976, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(628, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Economics of Milk Production in Dhaka District    --  A Case for Savar Thana.', '', '', '', '', '01-12-1991', '30-06-1992', '01-12-1991', '30-06-1992', '1. To compare the cost of rearing native and cross--bred cows by farm size;\r\n2To calculate the cost and return of milk production of native and cross-bredcows; and \r\n3To examine the bu', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Milk', 'Cattle, Dairy', 'This study was conducted to compare the cost of rearing native and cross-bred dairy cows and returns received from them. For this purpose, 144 cows of 132 households from 24 villages were randomly selected. Of them, 96 were nativ cows and 48 were corss-bred cows. The study revealed that among the structure of cost components, labour charge occupied the major share in the total cost of milk production per litre. The total cost of rearing native and cross-bred cows was Tk. 14.155 and Tk. 19,854 per annum, respectively. The average net cost of milk production per litre was Tk. 14.12 for native ocws and Tk. 10.41 for cross-bred cows . Returns over cost of milk per litre for native cows were tk. 0.52 and for cross-bred cows were Taka 3.40. The befifit-cost ratio of milk per litre was higher (1:1.33) in cross-bred cows than native ones (1:1.04). The study further showed that in comparing with bulk line cost, the price of milk per litre received by the farmers was higher in cross-bred cows than native cows . Therefore, the study recommends dairying with cross-bred cows as encouraging and viable commercial enterprise in Bangladesh.', '', ''),
(629, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Economics of Mini Dairy farms in selected Areas of bangladesh.', '', '', '', '', '01-12-1991', '30-06-1992', '01-12-1991', '30-06-1992', '1.To determine the cost of mini dairy farms To calculate the the returns to mini dairy farms\r\n3.To analyse the profitability of those farms\r\n4. To understand the pattern of labour utilization in those farms.', '', '', '', 'PL-480', 700, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Dairy Farm', 'Milk', 'In this study an attempt was made to evaluate the economics of dairy farming in selected areas of banglaedesh. Data from 20 randomly selected farms were collected by survey method. Results show thatcross-bred cows were more in number (2.55) in those farms than that of local cows (0.65). The number of cross-bred cows increased as the farm sizes increased. The production of milk per cross-bred cow was higher (5.66) litres) than the loal ones (2.23) liters . Highest (5.74 liters) milk yield per cross-bred cow was recorded in large faarms. The average lactation period for cross-bred cows was higher (304 days) than the local xows (210 days). In production cost of farms, concentrates tood the highest share (35.19%) followed by labour charges (23.64%). The production cost and gross returns for mini dairy farms were higher in large farms(Tk. 183,005 and tk. 187.544, respectively), compared to medium and small farms. The befefit cost ratio of all farms was 1:1.03, indicating that mini dairy farming is economically profitable. In addition, each farm created an annual employment opportunity of 649.70 man-days which was met by both male and female labourers. The small farms employed more female family labourers while the large farms depended more on hired labourers. \r\n\r\nThe expansion of dairy farming with cross-bred cows is suggested for accelerating income and employment opportunities in rural Bangladesh.', '', ''),
(630, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Socio-economic Impact of Artificial Insemination Programme in Bangladesh.', '', '', '', '', '01-03-1990', '28-02-1992', '01-03-1990', '28-02-1992', '1. To determine the proportion of cross-bred cattle population in the A.I. Areas.\r\n2. To assess the economic benefit devived from A.I. Programme.\r\n3. To examine the social attitude towards the adoption of artificial insemination technique.\r\n4. To determine the cost of semen in the study areas.\r\n5. To assess the number of technical personnel and staff and their related training.\r\n6. To find out the available infra-structure, laboratory facilities and A.I. Equipments.\r\n7. To determine the level of Veterinary Services and medicare facilities, fodder production,institutional credit, insurance policies in the A.I. Areas.\r\n8. To suggest suitable implications for policy and research.', '', '', '', 'IDA', 895943, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'A I', 'Cattle', 'The study was undertaken to evaluate the socio-economic aspects of artificial insemination program in Bangladesh. For this purpose a total of 640 adoption and 320 nonadopting households from 64 villages covering 8 centres, 16 sub-centres and 32 points were investigated. The proportion of cross-bred cattle population in the study areas was 11.69 per cent which varied among urbnan, semi-urban, and rural areas and also among regions. The rate of adoption was high near the A.I. Points and the process of adoption was more intensive in areas where NGOs have intervened. The study recommends for establishment of more A.I. Points in rural areas and involvement of NGOs in A.I. Activities to promote the rate of adoption in future. The analysis of productive and reproductive performances of both local and cross-bred cows interms of milk yield; lactation period;dry period; the period from calving to first breeding and calving interval showed that the cross-bred cows have better productive and reproductive performances over the local cows.\r\n\r\nEvidence showed that an Insemination covered 26 villages and 4375 households which suggests that the number of Inseminatiors be increased significantly for intersive supervision and smooth operation of the A I program at the A I sub centres and points suffered set back due to lack of laboratory facilities and A I equipment. This study revealed that the available veterinary services and medicare facilities were key to the success of the A.I. Program. Evidence showed that 72 per cent of the adopting farmers had the access to veterinary services. This access was found high in urban areas (95.83%) than in semi-urban and rural areas. For the success of A.I. Programs establishment of more A.I. Points and creation of A.I. Facilities in the rural areas have been suggested.', '', ''),
(631, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Fodder Production at Savar Dairy Farm! An Economic Analysis', '', '', '', '', '01-06-1989', '31-03-1991', '01-06-1989', '31-03-1991', '1. To compare the yiel of different fooders grown on the Savar Dairy Farm (SDF).\r\n2. To calculate the per hectare cost of production of fodders, and\r\n3. To calculate the per kilogram cost of preparation of silage from fodder crops.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fodder', 'Fodder', 'In this study an attempt was made to determine the cost of producing fodders at Savar Dairy Farm (SDF). For this purpose, all seasonal fodders, such as Maize, Jowar, Cowpea and Oat and all perennial fodders. Such as Para and Napier were studied. The highest acreage of land was allocated to high-land Para (33.8%) and the lowest average (2.7%) was devoted to Cowpea. Jowar attained the highest yield (74.2 tons) per hectare and Maize attained the lowest yield (25.8 tons/h). The highest cost per hectare was attributed to Jowar (TK. 20944.18) while the lowest cost was attributed to low land para (TK. 10349.86). The cost of production of fodder per kilogram was the highest (Tk. 0.66) for Maize and the lowest for Oat (Tk. 0.24). The cost of production of low-land Para was much lower than that of high land Para. The per kilogram cost of silage production was the highest (Tk. 0.71) for Maize and the lowest (Tk. 0.31) was for Napier. The gross return analysis further showed that the highest net margin and B:C ratio were observed for Napier followed by low-land Para, Jowar, Oat, Cowpea, High-land Para and Maize. Therefore, those fodders whose B:C ratios and yield/ha were higher should be allocated more area of land to stimulate increased returns to SDF in the future is suggested.', '', ''),
(632, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'The Draft Power Shortage in Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '01-06-1986', '31-07-1987', '01-06-1986', '31-07-1987', '1. To determine the availbility and requirements of draft animals in Bangladesh.\r\n2. To analyse the nature and magnitude of the current draft power shortage in the country.\r\n3. To suggest policy implication for reducing the draft power shortage in Bangladesh.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Animal Power', 'Cattle', 'The relative density of cattle population in Bangladesh is well above the average for many other countries of the world. Despite the high density of cattle population the country has been suffering from an acute shortage of draught power. The magnitude of draught power shortage was estimated to be 7.3 per cent in terms of number of draught cattle heads, but the proportion increased from 27.8 to 40.9 per cent when the estimate was made on the basis of power units. This is because of a decline in animal health. The power output of each work animal has declined from 0.25 Hp in the seventies to 0.17 Hp in the eighties.', '', ''),
(633, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Single Animal Ploughing in Bangladesh : A Bench Mark Survey', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1988', '31-12-1990', '01-03-1988', '30-06-1990', '1. To identify the locations where single animal ploughing (SAP) is in practice.\r\n2. To find out the causes for localization of the SAP system.\r\n3. To detect the socio-economic constrainsts responsible for hindering the development of the system.\r\n4.To indicate the policy measures to introduce this system of single animal ploughing in Bangladesh.', '', '', '', 'IDA', 528755, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Cattle', 'Cattle', 'In this study attempts were mde to identify the areas of single animal ploughing (SAP) in Bangladesh, causes of its localization and the socio-economic constraints hindering the expansion of the system. To determine the areas of single animal ploughing, 123 upazilas of 15 districts were surveyed. Of them, 16 upazilas were found heavily engaged with this system. A detailed investigation of 469 SAP and 439 double animal ploughing (DAP) farmers revealed that there was significant difference between the two systems in respect of cost of production and yield per unit of land. The benefit/cost (B/C) ratio was higher in SAP system. However, no significant difference was observed in respect of time required for ploughing, intensity of cropping, cost of implements, and cost of repairing implements (except yole).The study recommends for expansion of SAP system in areas where buffaloes are concentrated. For this purpose, logistic and institutional supports need to be made available.', '', ''),
(634, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Economics of Straw  Based Ration for Dairy Cows', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1990', '30-06-1991', '01-07-1990', '30-06-1991', '1 Economic Analysis of Straw based ration Developed for Dairy cows.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Effect of supplemented feed', 'Straw', 'A study on the development of straw-based ration for dairy cows with the objective of determining the effect of feeding urea treated rice-straw supplemented with diferent levels of fish-meal on milk yield and growth rate was carried out. A total of nine lactating cows were used in the digestion trials with three rations. Nine animals were divided into three groups and were supplied with ad-libitum 5% urea treated rice straw, 2kg green grass, 1.5kg wheat bran and 1 kg salt per day. In addition, each group of animals (A,B &amp; C) was supplied with 100 gm, 200 gm and 300 gm of fishmeal per day, respectively. It is evident that the average milk yield per cow reduced significantly in each trial indicating that the straw-based ration does not have any positive effect on milk yield. In the case of body weight, however, there was some positive gain in the trials of B and C rations. On average, each animal gained a marginal weight of 0.35 kg in 52 days. The overall effect of straw based ration on total income was negative because it reduced milk yield. However a positive impact of straw-based ration on growth of animals was encouraging.\r\n\r\n\r\nTherefore, straw-based ration can be supplied to milking cows in a crisis period. However, the replacement of green grasses by straw-based ration would be uneconomic in a normal situation. There is a positive impact of straw-based ration on growing animals.', '', ''),
(635, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Livestock Research in Banglaesh ! Present Status and Future Potential', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1994', '31-12-1994', '01-01-1994', '31-12-1994', '1. To determine the present status and future potential of livestock resources in Bangladesh.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Livestock', 'Livestock', 'This study was undertaken to determine the present status and future potential of livestock resources in Bangladesh. For this purpose, data was collected from various secondary sources.\r\n\r\nIt was observed that cattle population in Bangladesh increased marginally over the last three decasdes. Among others, low birth rate, high mortality, slaughtering of large number of young cattle on Did-ul-Azha and unplanned slaughtering of cattle for meat throughout the year are mainly responsible for slow growth rate of cattle population in Bangladesh.\r\n\r\nThe major constraints to livestock production are feeding, breeding, diseases and management. An estimate of supply and demand for animals and poultry feed based on 1984 data showed that there is a shortage of 39% dry matter (DM), 38% total digestible nutrients (TDN) and 43% digestible crude protein (DCP). The shortage of feed can be reduced using unutilized or underutilized wastelands for fodder cultivation, introducing short duration high yielding fodders and utilizing unconventional feed resources.\r\n\r\nThe loss of livestock due to diseases is tremendous in Bangladesh. The supply of vaccine and sera against major diseases are less than 20% of the national demand. In order to reduce the incidence of diseases, farmers should be trained-up on proper feeding sanitation, first aid and early diagnosis of diseases. An effectrve vaccination and control programmes have to be developed to combat the livestock diseases.\r\n\r\nThe traditional system of livestock management is a major constraints to livestock development. So, an effective mechanism for supply of improved breeds, prepared fed, vaccines, medicines and other inputs have to be developed.\r\n\r\nBangladesh has a high density of livestock population. But the country suffers from an acute shortage of livestock production like milk, meat and eggs. The shortage of milk, meat, egg and draft power is accounted for 86.42%, 89.50%, 77.22% and 41% respectively. The shortage of livestock product is attibuted to prevalence of diseases, feed shortage, poor quality of livestock species, poor management and their low productivity.', '', ''),
(636, 'Bangladesh Livestock Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Recent Trends in Livestock Population and Products in Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '01-03-1999', '30-06-1999', '', '', '1. To estimate the growth rate of livestock population;\r\n2. To determine the growth rate of livestock products; and\r\n3. To suggest suitable policy implications to solve the problem.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Livestock and Livestock products', 'Livestock', 'The bovine population of Bangladesh registered a slow annual growth rate of 0.19 per cen between 1983-84 and 1996. Sheep and goat population is increased only by 0.2 per cent. However, chicken population showed a significant increased over that period with an, annual compound growth rate of 4.16 per cent. Although the livestock population has increased marginally in recent years, the number of households having large and small animals has declined over time. The decline has been marked specially for households possessing cattle and buffaloes due to an increase in landlessness accompanied by an increase in the shortage of feeds and fodders. The current production of milk, meat and eggs meets only 14%, 12% and 29% ;respectively of our minimum national requirements .The annual growth rates of those products have been low during the 1990s; 2.36 for milk; 3.59  for meat and 5.52  for eggs .The value of imported milk at constant 1984-85=100 prices was Taka 233.5 million in 1988-89 which declined to Taka 101.0 million in (1993-94) very recently; import duty on powdered milk has significantly reduced which has promoted import of milk. The value of leather exports showed a threefold increase from Taka 162.2 million in 1985-86 to Taka 486.9 million in 1995-96. An increase in the supply of cattle from India through cross border informal trade has contributed significantly to expor of leather from Bangladesh. The value of leather export has, however, declined in 1996-97 due to a weakening of global demand for Bangladesh products and a continuing decline in the supply of high grade hides from Bangladesh.', '', ''),
