(724, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Induced Maturation, Artificial Breeding and Culture of Mud Crab, Scylla serrata.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '', '30-06-2000', ' i) To study maturation, breeding and seed production technique of mud crab.\r\nii) To develop culture technology of mud crab.', '', '', '', '', 1530000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Brood maturatio, Breeding and culture', 'Crabs', '1. Stocking density of 6000/ ha. of mud crab, Scylla serrata, has been  found as optimum density for controlled culture. \r\n2. The survival rates of male crabs were more or less independent with the increasing densities but that of females showed inverse relationship.\r\n3. Maturation and breeding of crab are under progress.', '', ''),
(725, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Studies on improved production, transportation and marketting infrastructure and their cost bebifit at farm level', '', '', '', '', '01-04-1998', '31-03-2001', '', '31-12-2000', '1.To study the existing different culture management practices of shrimp farm in the coastal region of Bangladesh.', '', '', '', 'BARC', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Shrimp handling, transportation and processings', 'Shrimps', 'The farm run by proper management practice showed better production performance than that of traditional farms with improper management practice and production were recorded as 398.5 kg/ha and 170.80ha, respectively. Due to improper management practices in the traditional farms of Bangladesh, shrimp production sufferings from both quantitative and qualitative loss.', '', ''),
(726, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Identification, Characterization and Control of Shrimp and Prawn Diseases', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-1999', '', '', '1. To assess the commonly occurring shrimps and prawn disease in Bangladesh.\r\n2. To monitor environmental and ecological parameters and management aspects of disease affected and unaffected shrimp and prawn farms to find out relationship to those parameters with disease.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n3. To formulate effective water quality management process and sustainable shrimps and prawns farming system to produce healthy and cost effective crops.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n4. Transmission of the research findings to the target group of people.', '', '', '', 'BARC', 1200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Coastal region of Bangladesh', 'Shrimps', 'With a view to fulfill the first two objectives of the project, a total of fifteen shrimp and prawn ghers from the different locations of greater Khulna district namely, Paikgacha, Shyamnagar and Bagerhat were selected. On the other hand, manpower recruitment and purchase of chemicals are under process, rather than those, necessary preliminary preparations are performed. To assess the commonly occurring shrimp and prawn disease in Bangladesh and to monitor environmental and ecological parameters and management aspects of disease affected and unaffected shrimp and prawn farms to find out relationship to those parameters with disease. For P. monodon, two farms from each of the existing farming systems i.e. traditional and improved traditional type from all the three locations were selected. Study reveals that compare to M. rosenbergii, P. monodon is more susceptible to disease occurrence. Though there was no significant variation in water quality parameters between the affected and unaffected shrimp farms, but the major cause of disease was identified as environmental stress, malnutrition and improper culture management that ultimately invites microbs, parasites and fungus to become active. The disease identified in the P. monodon farms during study were red coloration of shrimp body because of presence of Vibrio spp., soft shelling because of dilution of calcium and magnesium bicarbonates appendages and shell lesions because of nutritional problems, acid sulphate soil and environmental degradation etc. Shrimp fouling disease where the Barnacles were observed, Zoothamnium sp. were found in the gills of juveniles and sub-adults of shrimp and shrimp cotton disease was reported for many ghers caused by the presence of Agmasoma sp., other than those, Aeromonas and Pseudomonas spp. were isolated from the environmental water but the concentration was minimum to produce infection. Barnacles and Zoothamnium parasites were also isolated from the gill of M. rosenbergii body and gill. Gas bubble disease was noticed from the gill of M. rosenbergii, which was due to the super saturation of nitrogen/oxygen gas.\r\nIn the later part of shrimp culture in some of the selected shrimp ghers and other ghers of those area found to affect with some more common diseases. But the degree of incidence was not much alarming.\r\nAs a set out objective, to minimize and to control the disease incidence of shrimp/prawn in the farms through management improvement the selected farmers were oriented with process of farm preparation, water management, seed stocking, health management and feed and fertilizer utilization etc. Water quality records and the shrimp/prawn behavior and observation on presence of disease symptoms (if any) and its degree has been monitored weekly basis. With a view to transmit research findings to the target group of people farmers training &amp; extension booklet preparation has already been performed.', '', ''),
(727, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Development of sustainable culture technique for mud crab Scylla serrata', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1994', '30-06-1997', '', '30-06-1997', '1. To study of different stocking density on growth and survival of crab.\r\n2. To study the effect of organic manure and water quality on growth and survival of mud crab.\r\n3. To study the effect of different feed on fattening / gonadal development of mud crab.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\n4. To develop a package of appropriate technology for mud crab farming.', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Paikgacha, Khulna', 'Crabs', 'Stocking density of 10000/ha performed better production than other (5000/ha, 15000/ha)  and the effects of cow dung', '', ''),
(728, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Polyculture of Shrimps with Commercially Important Brackishwater Fin Fishes', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '', '30-06-2000', 'a)  To develop a package of fish-shrimp polyculture system in brackishwater    environment.\r\nb) To demonstrate, educate and popularize improved polyculture technology. \r\nc) To increase production per unit area of culture through optimum utilization of  water  body.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(729, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Studies on the Impact of Shrimp Farming on Mangrove and Estuarine Environment.Sub .', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1999', '01-01-1999', '', '', 'Objectives:\r\ni) To study the environmental changes of mangrove ecology (in term of mangrove destruction, soil erosion, water quality etc.) of the Sundarban coast caused by shrimp farming.\r\nii) To assess the environmental effects on major penaied shrimp nursery ground in the Sundarban area.\r\niii) To enlist the available shrimp and fin fish fauna in project area.\r\niv) To identify the specific cause and extent of erosion of biodiversity of mangrove species of southeast regions of the country.', '', '', '', '', 480000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Impact of shrimp farming', 'Mangrove', 'Progress up to June, 1999:\r\n1. Site selection:Three ghers has been selected which are situated at the middle position of the Dacop, Paikgacha and the Koira thana of Khulna district. The ghers are 18.0 km., 13.5 km. and 0.1 km. far from the Sundarban and having an area of 67.0, 100.0 and 13.0 ha. respectively. Besides the ghers, three spots has been also selected in the corresponding river basin of mangrove area where the major effluent of the ghers are discharged. For study of erosion, siltation and mangrove destruction three area of the Sundarban namely Hudda, Nalian and Koira has been selected.\r\n2. Procurement of necessary chemicals consumables\r\nAs preliminary preparation, some chemicals, consumables and other necessary materials were purchased.\r\n3.  Preparation of laboratory	For the laboratory analysis of samples, the laboratory has been prepared and equipped with different testing kits and chemicals of different strengths were made up.\r\nPROGRESS IN 1999-2000:\r\n4. Objective (s):  Part of the objective No. (i) and (iii)\r\n9. Progress/achievement:\r\nI. Technical achievement:\r\n? Sampling of the ghers and river spots are done fortnightly at new moon and full moon. Results on water &amp; soil quality are presented in Table-(1-3).\r\n? Twenty seven species of fin fish, 6 species of shrimp and 3 types of crab are enlisted so far from the study area Table-4 (a, b and c respectively) .\r\n? Nine genera of phytoplankton and 8 genera of zooplankton are so far identified from the study area Table- 4 (d and e respectively). Seven type of unknown fin fishes are preserved for further identification.\r\n? Soil samples from gher and Sundarban has been collected for analysis.\r\n? Silt samples from ghers has been collected for analysis.\r\n? Seven types of unknown fin fishes has been preserved for further analysis.', '', ''),
(730, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Breeding plans and genetic studies: Stock improvement of commercially important carps, catfish and tilapias.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', '', '30-12-2001', 'i) Stock improvement of silver barb, Puntius gonionotus, through selective breeding techniques.\r\nii) Stock improvement of rohu, Lebeo rohita (selected from different land races), through selective breeding techniques.\r\niii) Production of monosex female population in catfish, shing, Heteropneustes fossilis, through genetic manipulation techniques.\r\niv) Mass seed production and dissemination of genetically upgraded fish stocks to farmers hatcheries and evaluation of them.\r\nv) Formulation and establishment of policy guidelines for effective national breeding plans and programmes.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1780000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'FS, Mymensingh', 'Tilapia', '1. Genetically improved stocks of silver barb, Barbodes gonionotus, up to 4th generation have been developed.\r\n2. Genetic clones in rohu, Labeo rohita, has been developed.\r\n3. Production of monosex male population of GIFT strain is made and is being given to farmers for large scale adoption.\r\n4. Stock improvement of rohu and catla through individual selection is under progress', '', ''),
(731, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Development of breeding and culture technology of endangered fish species.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i)  To develop induced breeding and fry rearing technique of shoal.\r\nii)    To investigate aquaculture profitability of gonia and masheer in farmers ponds.\r\niii)   Mass seed production of mahseer.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1470000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'F, Mymensingh', 'Fish', '1. Controlled breeding technique of mahseer, Tor tor, has been developed.\r\n2. Controlled breeding techniques of koi, (Anabas testudeneous); gonia (Labeo gonius); bata (Labeo bata) and reba (Cirrhinus reba) have been developed.\r\n3. Further research works are in progress', '', ''),
(732, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Genetic selection and dissemination of genetically improved farm tilapia (GIFT) in Bangladesh.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1998', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i)   Genetic up-gradation of GIFT strain   through selection programme.\r\nii)  Production of mono sex male fry of GIFT through hormone administration.\r\niii) Evaluative of growth performances between MT-treated fry and non-treated fry of GIFT in hapa condition.\r\niv) Introduction and popularizing GIFT village set up, demonstration and motivation.', '', '', '', 'Strengthening Project', 900000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'FS, Mymensingh', 'Fish', '1.GIFT strain of tilapia has been genetically improved and seeds have been distributed for wide adoption.\r\n2. Production of mono sex male fish is under progress.', '', ''),
(733, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Breeding and culture of local catfish: (a)  shing  mass seed production  (b) and magur on culture trial', '', '', '', '', '01-06-2000', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i)  To evolve nursing techniques for shing (H. fossilis) fry and fingerling for mass seed production.\r\nii)  To evolve grow-out trial for shing (H. fossilis) and local magur (C. batrachus) in on-station and on-farm conditions\r\n', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(734, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Breeding and culture of local catfish shing (H. fossilis) and magur (C. batrachus).', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '', '30-06-2000', 'I)  To develop techniques for induced breeding of shing fryfor mass production\r\nii) To develop nursing techniques for shing fry for mass production\r\niii) To develop culture techniqus for shing (H. fossilis) and local magur (C.batrachus) in differing farming conditions through the determination of optimum stocking densities and different feeding condition\r\niv) Dissemination of information of the evolved technologies nation wide through a series of traing , symposia and national workshop.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'FS, Mymensingh', 'Catfish', '1. Technique for induced breeding of shingi has been perfected.\r\n2. Studies on the growth and survival of magur fry are under progress.\r\n3. Effect of different live feeds on the growth and survival of shingi larvae is  in progress.', '', ''),
(735, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Improvement of seed production and culture methods of freshswater prawn M. rosenbergii.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '31-12-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i) To improve and develop appropriate design and management system for  M. rosenbergii seed production in backyard operation\r\nii) To standardize and adopt for  M. rosenbergii backyard hatchery technology through farmers participation\r\niii) To develop in-door and out door M. rosenbergii nursery systems\r\niv) To develop fish-prawn polyculture system', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 13712000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'FS, Mymensingh', 'Fish', '1 Stocking density prawn postlarvae has been standardized in out-door and in-door nursery system.\r\n2 Prawn nursery feed and feeding schedule have been developed.\r\n3 Stocking density of juvenile in fish-prawn polyculture has been stanadrdized.\r\n4 Experiment on  species combination in fish-prawn polyculture is in progress.', '', ''),
(736, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Development of pearl culture technique in Bangladesh.\r\n(January 1997-December 2001)', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1998', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i) To develop appropriate technique freshwater  pearl culture.\r\nii) To study growth and survival of spat and post-operated mussel.\r\niii) To study the commercial aspects of pearl production in respect to time, size and shape of pearls.', '', '', '', 'Strengthening Project', 1038400, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(737, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'FS', 'Project', 'Optimization of stocking density of GIFT strain in net cages.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', ' i)     To optimize the stocking density of GIFT strain in cage\r\n ii)    To assess the economic viability of GIFT aquaculture in cages.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', '', '', '', ''),
(738, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'FS', 'Project', 'Culture of pabda (Ompok pabda) and gulsha (Mystus cavasius) with carp in polyculture system.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i)    To assess effects of introducing pabda and gulsha on fish production under carp polyculture system.\r\nii)  To develop suitable polyculture method of pabda and gulsha with Indian and Chinese carp.\r\niii)   To evaluate the economic benefit of introduction of pabda and gulsha in polyculture system.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 199300, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', '', '', '', ''),
(739, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'FS', 'Project', 'Polyculture of carp using over-wintered fingerling', '', '', '', '', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i)   To determine the appropriate stocking density of over-wintered fingerlings in carp polyculture.\r\nii)   To evolve a polyculture management system for a maximum production with maximum individual weight.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 250000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', '', '', '', ''),
(740, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'FS', 'Project', 'Development of technique for optimizing the production of 4-5 stockable size fingerlings of carps.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-1999', '', '30-06-1999', 'I. Production of 4-5 Inch. Fingerlinhs in nursery system.\r\nII. Comparative study of performance of BFRI and private hatchery bred seed .\r\nIII. Study of constrains by the private nursery owners and in nurseey operation', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 400000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', 'Carp', 'Optimized technique to produce 4-5 inch. fingerlings of carps and assisted different hatchery operators.', '', ''),
(741, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Research', 'Project', 'Status of broodstock management, hatchery and nursery operation in Jessore region.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1998', '31-12-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i) To survey the current brood management aspects and hatchery and nursery operation practices in Jossore area\r\nii) To study different parameters related to fish breeding in selected hatchery.\r\niii) To study the problems in brood stock management, hatchery and nursery operations and suggest future studies/mitigating measure', '', '', '', '', 600000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', 'Carp', '1. Survey on 23 hatcheries and 67 nurseries following prepared questionnaire was completed\r\n2. Information collection is continuing.', '', ''),
(742, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'FS', 'Project', 'Feed and Nutrition: Development of cost-effective feeds for brood stock management of carps and prawn.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '', '30-06-2000', 'i) Formulation of balanced feeds for broodstock of carp and Freshwater prawn using locally available ingredients.\r\nii) To increase /improve the breeding performance (maturity, fertilization, ovulation, fecundity, hatching rate) of carp using quality feeds.\r\niii) Testing of feeds of prawn in ponds (on-station).\r\niv)  Testing the efficiency of brood stock feeds of carp in farmers pond.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 543675, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', 'Fish', '1. Five different feed formulations having various levels of protein concentrations for carp brood stock are being tested.\r\n2. Prawn feeds are being formulated and tested in experimental cistern and pond conditions.', '', ''),
(743, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'FS', 'Project', 'Development of cost-effective feeds for brood stock of carps and catfish.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i) Formulation of balanced feeds for broodstock of carp and catfish feed using locally available ingredients.\r\nii) To increase the growth rate of catfish using formulated feeds, which ultimately increase catfish production.\r\n(iii) Testing the efficiency of broodstock feeds of carps in farmers pond condition.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 400000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', '', '', '', ''),
(744, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'FS', 'Project', 'Freshwater fish health  management: Studies on disease of carp and catfish.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '', '30-06-2001', 'i) Study with relationship between Epizootic Ulcerative Syndrome (EUS) with pond ecology\r\na) Physio-chemical water quality study\r\nii) Study on commonly occurring disease of carp and catfish\r\niii) Determination of median lethal concentration (LC50) of common drugs and chemicals used in ponds fish culture system of Bangladesh\r\niv) Determination of workout treatment concentration of drugs and chemicals against diseases\r\nv) Establishment the laboratory facilities\r\nvi) Advisory services to the farmer''s problams', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 365000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', 'Fish', 'a) Epizootic Ulcerative Syndrome (EUS) affected Channa sriatus was examined, the bacterium Areomonas sp. was identified from gill and lesion of the diseased fish and the identified parasites were Trichodina sp. and Dactylogyrus sp.\r\nb) The 24h median lethal concentration (LC50) of formalin, KMnO4 and CuSO4 were determined on fingerlings of rohu (Labeo rohita) and mrigal (Cirrhinus mrigala). Sub-lethal concentration of formalin for 8.3 to 10.0 cm labeo rohita fingerlings in 24h was confirmed as 86.6. Whereas (LC50)   )   of KMnO4 was determined as 1.34 for Labeo rohita fingerlings of 5.7 7.9cm. (LC50)    ) of CuSO4 was 1.32 for Cirrhinus mrigala of 7.2- 8.5 cm fingerlings.\r\nc) Pathogen identified from disease affected Labeo rohita and Cirrhinus mrigala. Parasite Trichodina sp and bacteria Areomonas sp .were identified from the disease affected fish.\r\nd) Disease affected African magur, hybrid magur and Pungas were studied for their suspected pathogen. The identified bacteria were Areomonas sp., Pseudomonas sp. and Enterobacteria sp. \r\ne) Treatment measures with different chemicals:\r\ni)Epizootic Ulcerative Syndrome (EUS) affected Cirrhinus mrigala and Barbodes gonionotus fingerlings were treated with 1.0- 1.5 ppm KMnO4 and 0.5-1.0 ppm  NaCl  in several trials. But all the infected fish were died after treatment.\r\nii)Herbal drug at the rate of 4L/acre was applied to disease affected Heteropneustes fossilis. The rate of recovery was 10%.The herbal drug was supplied by a farmer.', '', ''),
(745, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'FS', 'Project', 'Freshwaterfish diseases management: Diagnosis and trial control of some common fish and shrimp disease', '', '', '', '', '01-06-2000', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i) Determination of workout treatment of drugs and chemicals against diseases of fish shrimp.(P. monodon) in pond condition.\r\nii) Investigation of  Brainchiomyces in cultured fishes of Bangladesh.\r\niii) To develop suitable drugs for EUS of fish and shrimp.\r\niv) Advisory services to the farmers problems', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 160000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', '', '', '', ''),
(746, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'HQ', 'Project', 'Study and documentation of the status of freshwater fish genetic resources in Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i) To establish baseline data base on freshwater fish species in the three principal river systems and catchment of Bangladesh\r\nii) To assess the genetical profile to endangered freshwater fish species\r\niii) To evaluate the potential effects of environmental degradation, flood control projects on fish biodiversirty\r\niv) To list and document the species that are already extinct, if any and to identify the reasons for extinction', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fisheries Production', 'Fish', 'Collection, identification, morphometric and merestic studies of freshwater fish species from different ecological conditions are in progress. So far about 45 endemic species have been found to be threatened, demanding their conservation.', '', ''),
(747, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'HQ', 'Project', 'Demonstration of aquaculture technologies and feed-back research through Department of Fisheries (DOF).', '', '', '', '', '01-06-1998', '31-12-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i) To establish baseline data base on freshwater fish species in the three principal river systems and catchment of Bangladesh \r\nii) To assess the genetical profile to endangered freshwater fish species\r\niii) To evaluate the potential effects of environmental degradation, flood control projects on fish biodiversirty\r\niv) To list and document the species that are already extinct, if any and to identify the reasons for extinction\r\ni) Demonstration of BFRI evolved aquaculture technologies at different farming conditions in different parts of the country through DoF\r\nii) Standardization and/or adjustment of technology, if any, in varying conditions off environment, culture practice and farmers resources availability\r\niii) Training of field level fisheries extension workers and progressive fish farmers on various improved fish culture practices\r\niv) Feed-back field problems to research for solution', '', '', '', 'Strengthening Project', 2432000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fishery Biology', 'Fish', ' Nine rural aquaculture technologies are being  tested in farmers field at  26  Thanas in different districts at different different parts of the country.', '', '');
INSERT INTO `research_info` (`research_id`, `org_name`, `ddcr_name`, `ppe_type`, `r_title`, `r_location`, `r_priority`, `r_type`, `r_status`, `plan_sd`, `plan_ed`, `actual_sd`, `actual_ed`, `r_objective`, `r_method`, `r_abstruct`, `r_keywords`, `fund_source`, `total_budget`, `total_expenditure`, `total_refund`, `d_technology`, `p_organize`, `p_trained`, `r_programarea`, `commodity`, `outcome`, `impact`, `reference`) VALUES
(748, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Development of an environment friendly semi-intensive shrimp farming in Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '01-04-1995', '01-07-1997', '', '01-07-1997', '1) To develop an environment friendly culture penaeid shrimps.\r\n2) To find out survival and growth performance of imported and locally avaiable post larvae of shrimps at controlled condition and under semi-intensive culture.\r\n3) Upgradation of present practice of semi-intensive shrimp culture particularly  Penaeus monodon at the initial stage of the project in relation to environment and demonstartion to farmers of any positive findings.\r\n4) Establishment of a sustainable shrimp culture method through biological manipulation.', '', '', '', '', 2615113, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Culture', 'Shrimps', 'From the study, it was observed that stony hard soil, sandy soil, old mangrove forested  non acid sulphate soils are suitable for closed shrimp culture syatem and acid sulphate soil is unsuitable for this type of culture. Further, crop rotation or polyculture of black tiger shrimp with  detrivorous or planktivorous fishes may provide an opportunity for disease free shrimp cultivation. Locally harvested natural seeds or locally produced hatchery seeds yeilded better growth and survival compared those with imported ones. Soft and hard shell of shrimps appeared to be related with lunar cycle and nutrition.  Gradual declines in salinity helps post larvae to cope with the the situation but stress and sudden drop in salinity may cause high rate of mortality. Limited number of carnivore fish released in shrimp farm helps to remove diseased and week shrimps.', '', ''),
(749, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Development of improve methods for the culture of some important marine and hyposaline organisms', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1994', '30-06-1997', '', '30-06-1997', '1) Mass cultivation  of live food organisms for plankton feeders and carnivore fishes.\r\n2) Ecological adaptation of marine organism to hyposaline or fresh water condition.\r\n3)  Test for salt resistance for important fishes to be used in coastal aquaculture.\r\n4) development of culture methodology  of some marine   and hyposaline species', '', '', '', '', 1070258, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Culture Method', 'Meat', 'Mixed raising of planktonic food in fertilized mini-ponds were developed using underground hyposaline water. Survival rate of post larvae of tiger shrimp was 69% when salinity was generally dropped to 0 ppt within 10 day and raising continued for 28 days. Seed production of freshwater gaint shrimp Macrobrachium rosenbergii was successful in hyposaline ponds with a salinity range of  2-9 ppt. Commercial culture of tiger shrimp in almost freshwater condition appeared bright. Polyculture of tiger shrimp and Indian major carps or silver barb appeared possible at a lower salinity. Improvement of dietary conditions enhance maturity of M. rosenbergii. Brood development of penaeid shrimps in pond with a lower salinity was not successful. Mixed culture of euryhaline species ( sea bass &amp; tilapia ) in coastal ponds showed promising prospect. Silver barb,Thai catfish and some other so-called freshwater species showed relatively higher degree of salinity tolerance. Some fish (silver barb &amp; mirror carp ) naturally produced seeds in mild saline ponds (0-2 ppt ).', '', ''),
(750, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Studies on the water quality management in shrimp farms and its relationship with disease.', '', '', '', '', '07-01-1994', '30-07-1997', '', '30-06-1997', '1) To monitor water quality management in shrimp pond by analysing physicochemical parameters.\r\n2) To sudy biological parameters such as primary productivity, types of phytoplankton, algae and zooplankton in shrimp ponds.\r\n3) To assess the condition of pond soil for suitability of shrimpo culture.\r\n4) To assess the effect of pond discharge water on the surrounding water body and other shrimp farms.\r\n5) To monitor bacterial and other microbial loads and its composition in shrimp pond water and soil.\r\n6) To identify causative agents/factors responsible for shrimp disease.\r\n7) To assess water quality and its possible relationship with disease and take necessary measures for prevenation and control.', '', '', '', '', 1868249, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Water quality/disease', 'Fish', 'Water quality parameters viz., salinity pH, transparency, dissolved oxygen, alkalinity and ammonia and bacterial load of water and soil of shrimp culture ponds of four farms situated in two different areas were studied in five consecutive culture seasons. The shrimps in all the farms and all the culture seasons were fed with commercial artificial feed. Water quality parameters all the farms were congenial for shrimp culture. Even than, shrimps of three farms in Coxs Bazar area were attacked with viral disease in the 1st  and 2nd crop of 1995. The other farm in Teknaff area some how escaped from the disease. In the 1st crop of 1996, water quality was almost similar with that of 1995. In this season, shrimps of two farms of Coxs Bazar area were attacked with disease and one farm in Coxs Bazar area and Teknaff farm were escaped from the disease. In the 2nd crop of 1996, disease incidence was observed in no farms. But in the 1st crop of 1997, viral disease attacked shrimps of all the farms. However, no relationship of water quality with disease incidence was observed.', '', ''),
(751, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Development of environment friendly semi-intensive shrimp/fish  farming and water quality management via-a-vis disease', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', '1) To find out an environment friendly approach in shrimp farming by changing culture physiology for shrimps and fishes on crop rotation basis.\r\n2) Routine observation on physico-chemical and biological parameters and management aspects of disease affected and unaffected shrimp farms to find out relationship to those parameters.\r\n3) Development of an effective water quality management process and  sustainable semi-intensive farming to produce healthy shrimp.\r\n4) Studies on pond microcosom, biological control of planktonic biomass and health status of raised shrimp.\r\n5) Transmission of research findings to target group of people.i) To find out an environment friendly approach in shrimp farming by changing culture physiology for shrimps and fishes on crop rotation basis.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1217000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Culture/Disease', 'Shrimps', 'It has been observed from the findings achieved till date that water quality showed no relationship with the incidence of viral disease occurance.  It will not be wise to culture two successive crops of  shrimp  in the same pond which deteriorates environmental conditions and increases chance of contamination.  Culture of shrimp in the modified closed culture system in first crop in rotaion with the culture of planktovorous or detrivorous fin fishes in the second crop would be able to decrease the probability of disease incidence of shrimp.\r\nOrganic deposits created by shrimp farming can be naturally mineralized to produce planktonic food which will intern consumed by planktivorous fishes. Successive cropping of shrimp and fin fishes creates an environment friendly culture procedure. Raising of fin fishes in coastal farm with artificial feeding showed no noted incidence of disease but excessive feeding deteriorates water quality condition. Polyculture of salt tolerant fin fishes in abundant  shrimp  farm appears promising.', '', ''),
(752, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Development of pearl culture technique in Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '07-01-1998', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', '1) To develop appropriate techniques for freshwater and marine pearl culture.\r\n2) To optimize growth and survival of post operated mussel bearing pearl materials.\r\n3) To study the commercial aspects of pearl production in respect to time, size and shape of pearls and economic value.', '', '', '', 'Strengthening Project', 129150, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Culture', 'Pearls', 'A few pearl oyster bed exit in Bangladesh specially on coral stones in St. Martins Island and some isolated areas of Moshukhali island specially in mangroves.\r\nNatural pearl oysters being harvested in Coxs Bazar region are  tiny by shell structure and flattened internal muscle and gonads. Several attempts were made as trial and error to open shells but resulted 100% mortality of oyster.\r\nIt was found that separation of settled spat of oyster from the soft substratum when they attain a diameter of 2-3 cm is possible. But it will require rearing of spat for a considerable period to attained a size of 10-12 cm when experimental implantation of foreign particles may be undertaken. To learn methodology of implementation of foreign particles in shell fishes some attemt has been taken with fresh water mussel, results of which yet to be known.', '', ''),
(753, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Brood development and culture of seabass, mullets and milkfish', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '', '30-06-2000', '1)  To develop brood of  sea bass.\r\n2)  To develop brood of  mullets.\r\n3)  To develop brood of  milkfish.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1576000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Brood Development', 'Dairy Cattle', '1. Sea bass raised with live tilapia in mixed culture attained 6.5kg in average within 3 and half years.\r\n2. Milk fish raised in salt or hyposaline water showed slightly better growth compared to those raised in freshwater\r\n3.  Average weight of milk fish in 2 years period is 1.85kg under culture.\r\n4. Sea bass raised in captive condition for 3.5 years did not show maturity in freshwater.\r\n5.  Mullet, Liza. Sp attained brood stage within 18 months rearing.\r\n6.  Raising of sea bass fingerlings with artificial feed was not promising.', '', ''),
(754, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Studies on the biology, fishery, breeding and cultural suitability of gang magur (Plotosus canius)', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1999', '30-06-2002', '', '', '1) To determine the abundance, distribution of gang magur in Bangladesh and know its habitat condition.\r\n2) To stydy its food and feeding habit.\r\n3) To study its facundity, age and maturity and spawning frequency.\r\n4) Adaptation in pond condition and development of brood fishes for induced breeding.\r\n5) Study its cutural suitability in pond condition.', '', '', '', '', 1521000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Biology', 'Catfish', 'Catfish eel collected from wild showed good prospect of their domestication. However, high sized fish harvested with hooks needs antibiotic treatment for their survival.  Their distribution and feeding habit studies showes these are available in a small number in mangroove forested area, they mostly lives on crustacea and small fishes.', '', ''),
(755, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Utilization of fisheries resources through processing preservation and product development', '', '', '', '', '07-01-1994', '30-06-1997', '', '30-06-1997', '1) To study self life of some commercially important marine fish species under different storage conditions.\r\n2) To study gel forming ability of underutilized fish species for processing of surimi based products.\r\n3) To evaluate quality of traditionally dried fishery products prepared from various  species in Coxs Bazar and Teknaf area. \r\n4)  Studies to evolve improved method for preparation of dried and salted marine fish products. \r\n5) Studies to evolve improved method for preparation of quality fish meal from underutilized marine fish species of Bangladesh.', '', '', '', '', 1235000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Processing', 'Fish', 'Study reveal that the quality and degree of insulation of container has a direct effect on the self life of fish species.  Container types did not affect the proximate composition of the fish species.  Self life was longer in lab. ice box and metal sheet-cork box than wooden box. \r\nGelforming ability of 17 underutilized marine species was studied. The species were grouped according to the elasticity of gel.  Catfish, ribbon fish, flat fish and  pomfret were extremely elastic.  Bombay duck, croaker, eels, and spotted croaker were medium elastic.\r\nNo remarkable variation was observed in proximate composition and pH value between raw fish and surimi pruduct. Most of the species lost lipid in surimi when compared those with the raw.\r\nDifferent types of triditionally prepared fisheries products are available in Coxs Bazar area. The main products are dry fish.  It was found that most of that dry fish production does not use a standard hygenic procedure.  It was also found that fishermem use DDT or Nogos duruing drying process.  An improved drying method  was developed using solar panel.  In this  drying method the drying time was short and  quality of products was improved. Furthermore, an improved method was developed for preparation of quality grade fish meal from cheap trash fish.', '', ''),
(756, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Utilization of fisheries resources through processing preservation and product development (2nd phase)', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', '1)  Shelf lifecondition of some commercially important marine fish.\r\n2)   Evaluation of present status of the traditionally processed dried and salted fish products and to study effect of different additives used in the preparation of dried fish.\r\n3)  To evolve improve method for the preparation of dried and salted marine fish product and quality fish meal from under utilized marine fish.\r\n4)  To study gel forming ability of under utilized fish species for processing of surimi based products.\r\n5)  To evaluate quality aspects of traditionally dried fishery products prepared from various species in Coxs Bazar and Teknaf area.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 976000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Processing', 'Protein products', '1. Dry fish produced by solar dryer reduce bacterial load significantly compared to those produced by traditional methods.\r\n2. Time required to produce dry fish by solar dryer is less compared to traditional methods.\r\n3. Quality fish meal produced through improved methods yielded better nutritive value compared to traditional commercial fish meal available in Bangladesh.\r\n4. Survey on traditional dry fish production in Cox`s Bazar area showed disturbing incidence of using substances considered detrimental to human health.', '', ''),
(757, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Monitoring and assessment of marine fisherry resources of Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1994', '30-06-1997', '', '30-06-1997', '1) To initiate  a system for for rountinely monitoring the marine fish catches of Cox''s Bazar and Teknaf region.\r\n2) to monitor  composition and seasonal variation of species at landing sites.\r\n3) To monitor crafts and gears used in the area.\r\n4) Studies on length weight relationship of selected marine species.', '', '', '', '', 1868249, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Stock assesment', 'Adhesives', 'Thirty to thirty five marine fishes comprises more than 90% of sea landings in Bangladesh. October to March is the peak season of marine landings. Artisanal fishing and trawl fishing shows marked differences in catch compositions, where the former is dominated by hilsa (Indian shad ) and later is dominated by catfish and croaker. For the last few years though fishing intensity increased significantly, but catch per unit effort gradually declined. Though shrimp constitutes marginal amount in marine landings but its economic significance is high. The crafts and gears used in Bangladesh marine fishing is outdated and out-maned. Hilsa as a single species dominates by volume and price. Marine set bag net though harvest a significant volume of marine catch but this fishing  device is most detrimental in marine resource management. Biological analysis showed some species are under the threat of over exploitation.', '', ''),
(758, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'MFTS', 'Project', 'Monitoring and  assessment of marine fisheries resources of Bangladesh(2nd phase)', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', '', '', '1)  Monitoring and assessment of marine fish catch by gears used for artisanal and industrial fishing in Coxs Bazar and Chittagong region.\r\n2) Studies on some biological information such as sex, size, fecundity, length-weight relationship of some commercially important marine fishes of the Bay of Bengal such as catfish, pomfrets, mackerel, clupeids, ribbon fish, crokers, etc.\r\n3)  To develop a data base for marine fisheries resources.\r\n4)  Studies on socio-economic condition of marine fisherfolk.', '', '', '', '', 1036000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Monitoring/Assesment', 'Molasses', '1. CPUE of different gears are declining year by year.\r\n2. Recruitment pattern indicates spawning season deviated from normal course during last few years.\r\n3. Dominance of hilsa, catfish, mackeral and shark are evident compared to other marine species.\r\n4.Compared to landings of 10 years back so called less expensive fish collectively occupies larger share.\r\n5. Recruitment of commercially important fishes shows irregular trend.\r\n6. Length of gill nets for pelagic fish increasing year by year, and boats are fishing more deeper waters in successive years.', '', ''),
(759, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Sylhet-Mymensingh basin fish stock assessment', '', '', '', '', '07-01-1997', '30-06-2001', '07-01-1997', '30-06-2001', 'i)Collection of more baseline information of  the beels of Sylhet-Mymensingh basin.\r\nii) Study the limnological and biological     productivity (primary production and status of phytoplankton, zooplankton) of some sample beels and formulate the criteria to classify the beels based on productivity status.\r\niii) Study the abundance, species composition and catch statistics of the commercially important fish species of the beels.\r\niv) Investigate the fishing effort being exerted in the beels and study the efficiency of different fishing gears and their effort.\r\nv) Collection of length-frequency data of major commercial fishes of the beels for the estimation of growth, mortality, recruitment, etc. and hence to estimate maximum sustainable yield (MSY) of carps and catfish.\r\nvi) Formulate a sustainable management plan and publish research papers based on the data for dissemination of the present status of the beel fishery. In addition, reports and popular brochures will be prepared to augment mass awareness', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1160900, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Sylhet-Mymensingh, Fish Stock Assesment', 'Fin-Fish, Habitat', '1. Benchline information on the location, area and status of different beels and haors of the Sylhet-Mymensingh basin have been compiled.\r\n2. Collection of data on the fish species composition, fishing season and patterns, gears and catch per unit effort, fishing intensity, etc. are continuing.\r\n3. Productivity management study is under progress.', '', ''),
(760, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Hilsa Fisheries Resaerch in Bangladesh', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1996', '30-12-1998', '01-01-1997', '30-12-2000', '1. Development of catch monitoring system of hilsa\r\n2. Assessment of impact of environmental parameters and water quality on the catch, abundance and distribution of hilsa\r\n3. Assessment and confirmation of races/sub-populations that may exist in Bangladesh;\r\n4. More precisely identification of spawning and nursery grounds of hilsa, estimation and enumeration of juvenile hilsa (jatka) that are caught by different gear in different habitat of Bangladesh;\r\n5. Development of ageing technique of hilsa;\r\n6. Assessment of age of reproduction and spawning frequencies of hilsa from different habitat of Bangladesh.\r\n7. Assessment of socio-economic status of Hilsa fisher-folk in order to assess the human impacts of different management options.\r\n8. Training of BFRI scientists in relevant stock assessment, electrophoretic technique, bio-chemical genetics and computing both at home and abroad to develop a capable hilsa research team both at Riverine Station, Chandpur and MFTS, Cox''s bazar and training of hilsa traders and fishers to create awareness about fishery.', '', '', '', 'ACIAR (Australia)', 181, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fish Stock Assesment', 'Hilsa', 'Significant achievements made during the project period were\r\n\r\n1.Hilsa population is presently overexploited (Present Exploitation level E = 0.66, Optimum E = 0.50). Total mean catch was recorded as 33.00 kg/ boat/ day during the peak-harvesting season. \r\n2. The effect of water flow and rainfall on hilsa production was found noticeable.\r\n3. Found only one stock/race of hilsa in Bangladesh water.\r\n4. Confirmed two nursery and 5 spawning grounds.\r\n5. Ageing technique has been developed by counting daily rings from otolith.\r\n6.About 400 fisher-folks data were collected and analyzed for socio-economics study of hilsa fisher-folk.\r\n7. Two BFRI Scientists were trained on Genetics, Electrophoresis and Population dynamics at CSIRO, Marine Laboratory, Cleveland, Australia. About 500 fishermen and fish traders were trained.\r\n8. Hilsa Fisheries Management Action Plan (HFMAP) has been prepared and submitted in National Workshop and it has been approved with some improvement.', '', ''),
(761, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Studies on the production potentiality and management of fisheries of  Kaptai lake', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1997', '30-07-2001', '01-01-1997', '30-07-2001', 'i) Production efficiency, which is related to different limno-biological status of the water body and&lt;\r\nii)  Present status of fish and fisheries and different biological parameters such as growth, fish density, mortality and recruitment pattern, etc. of fishes and fishing effort most be known', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1069950, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Riverine Substation, Rangamati, Captai Lake', 'Labeo rohita', '1. Growth performances of the major carps, their spawning intensity, hatching pattern, natural recruitment, extent of supplemental stocking, and its performances, food and feeding habit, species diversity, catch statistics, CPUE and catch composition of commercially important species have been studied. \r\n2. Impact of artificial stocking of fish fingerlings in the creeks of the lake is being investigated.\r\n3. Physico-chemical and biological parameters of the lake water and soil are being monitored routinely.', '', ''),
(762, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Development of pen and cage culture techniques in different environment', '', '', '', '', '01-01-1997', '30-06-2001', '01-01-1997', '30-06-2001', 'The general objectives of the project are -\r\na.Development and further refinement of polyculture techniques of carps and other species in pens\r\nb.Assessment of biological productivity and supplemental feed for pen fish farming\r\nc. Development of cage culture techniques\r\nThe specific objectives are as follows:\r\ni.Study the effects of organo-mineral fertilizers and supplemental feed on the production of pen fish farming\r\nii.Assess the of production potential (physico-chemical and biological productivity) and optimization of stocking density by biotic balance (energy balance) of pen ecosystem\r\niii.Study the selection of suitable fish species for cage culture\r\niv.Determine the optimum stocking density for cage culture\r\nv.Select the suitable food for raising fish in cages	vi.Develop nursery rearing techniques of carps spawn in pen; and \r\nvii.Prepare field guide/ extension materials.', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 1681200, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fish Production', 'Fin-fish', '1. Polyculture of carps in pen in borrow pit canals in different irrigation project areas yielded 1-2 t/ha/crop of 6 months with low cost supplemental feeding.\r\n2. Cage culture of silver barb, common carp and prawn produced 7-11ton/ha/8 months, 8-13ton/ha/8 months and 300-400kg/ha/3 months, respectively.\r\n3. Raising of Thai pangas and freshwater prawn in floating and fixed net cages in the Kaptai lake is in progress. Thai pangas exhibiting good performance in terms of growth, adoption and survival.\r\n4. Polyculture of Indian major and Chinese carps has been undertaken in three suitable locations of the Kaptai lake.', '', ''),
(763, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Develoment of Macrobrachium backyard hatchery', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', 'i. Development of brood rearing technique of M. rosenbergii\r\nii. Development of Macrobrachium backyard hatchery operation technique.\r\niii. Development and further refinement of Macrobrachium backyard hatchery operation technique.\r\niv. Development of nursery rearing technique of M. rogenbergii post larva', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 270000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Disease Management', 'Shrimps', '1. Prawn seed production in backyard hatchery has been developed. \r\n2. Experiment on prawn brood development is in progress. A stocking density @ 5,000 juvenile/ha produced higher percentage (60%) of berried females in only three months period.', '', ''),
(764, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Fish seed rearing and culture using pen in Kaptai Lake Creeks', '', '', '', '', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', 'i) Development of nursery rearing techniques of major carp spawn in floating fine meshed cages setting in pen environment of Hilly coves.\r\nii) Development of rearing techniques of major carp fries in the Hilly coves.\r\niii) Development of polyculture technique through construction of demonstration pen in Hilly Coves', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 516164, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(765, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Improved fish seed production, demonstration and promotion of BFRI developed aquaculture technologies.', '', '', '', '', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', '01-07-2000', '30-07-2000', ' On-Farm:\r\ni) Demonstration of pen and cage fish culture.\r\nii) Demonstration of rice-cum-fish/shrimp culture.\r\niii) Demonstration of  polyculture  of pangas fish\r\nOn-Station:\r\ni) Development of brood bank of pangas, carp, shrimp and other species.\r\nii) Seed production and nursery rearing of carp, pangas and shrimp', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(766, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Studies on the effect of commonly used agrochemicals on aquatic biota', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2001', 'i)  Laboratory and field trial / identification of suitable pesticides which are not hazardous for fish.\r\nii) Evaluate the residual effects of pesticides in fish tissue and aquatic environment.\r\niii) Preparation of final report, booklet and leaflet', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 600300, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Effect of pesticides on fish and aquatic organisms', 'Fishes and Pesticides', '1. Heptachlor, Dieldrin, Basudin, Sumicidin, Ripcord, Cymbush, Decis, Pounce, Basmid, Danitol, Fastac, Karate, pesticides have been found highly toxic to fish.\r\n2. Among the organophosphorus Lethal 20EC, Rugby 10G, Lorbsan 15G, Darbsan 20EC, Basudin 10G, Zolone 35EC, Sungor 40EC have been found toxic to fish/shrimp but Regent 50EC has been found safe to fish.\r\n3. Sumithion 50EC, Malathion 57EC, Marshal 6G, Polyram-combi, Chemophate 75EC, Folicar 250EC, Furadan 5G, Carbofuran 3G, etc have been found safe to fish at their recommended doses.\r\n4. Further work is under progress on the extent of use of pesticides in fish drying.', '', ''),
(767, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Studies on water pollution of the Buriganga and Shitolakh rivers.', '', '', '', '', '01-01-2001', '31-12-2001', '01-01-2001', '31-12-2001', 'i) Review of research work conducted on water pollution of the river Buriganga and Shitalakh rivers.\r\nii) Identify and assess the resources of pollution of the rivers.\r\niii) Determine the nature and kinds of pollution of the rivers\r\niv) Determine the impact of pollution on the biological production particularly, fish fauna of the rivers and \r\nv) Recommend probable remedial measures', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(768, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Studies on the Reproductive Biology and Development of Breeding Techniques of Riverine Catfishes', '', '', '', '', '01-07-1997', '30-06-1999', '01-07-1997', '30-06-1999', 'The main objective of this project was to develop breeding and rearing techniques of riverine catfishes based on the studies on their reproductive biology. Within this main objective, the specific objectives were as follows:\r\ni. Study the reproductive biology of Pangasius pangasius, P. sutchi, Rita rita, Mystus aor and Silonia silondia and develop their breeding techniques.\r\nii. Develop nursing/ rearing techniques for newly hatched fry of these species.\r\niii. Prepare final report, field guides, extension material', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 815500, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fish Production', 'Catfish, Habitate', '1. Fingerlings of Pangas, Aier and Rita are collected from the river system, domesticated in the pond system and broods have been developed. \r\n2 Artificial breeding and culture technology of native Pangas and Aier fish are being developed.  \r\n3. Controlled breeding and fingerling production of exotic pangas (P. sutchi) have been evolved. \r\n4.Further studies are made to improve survival rate of larvae and pangas fingerling.', '', ''),
(769, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'RS', 'Project', 'Studies on the reproductive biology and development of breeding techniques of Pangasius pangasius)', '', '', '', '', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2001', 'i) Identify and confirm the natural spawning, breeding and nursery grounds.\r\nii) Domestication from very early stages of spawn/fry of P. pangasius for broodstock development.\r\niii) Development of breeding and rearing techniques (hatchery management) of P. pangasius', '', '', '', 'ARMP', 484000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
