(1285, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Genetic Resources and Seed Division', 'Project', 'Coordinated sub project on Characterization of important plant genetic resources: BRRI component', 'GRSD and Biotechnology Division, BRRI, Gazipur', 'High', 'Basic', 'On-going', '01-10-2010', '30-09-2013', '01-02-2011', '30-09-2013', 'a. To analyze the genetic deversity and population structure of Bangladesh germplasm in comparison to global rice varieties.\r\nb. To characterize important local germplasm both Phenotypically and at molecular level.\r\nc. To evaluate the potential usefulness of Bangladeshi germplasm for association mapping.\r\nd. To protect our important local germplasm from any biopiracy.\r\n', 'a. Plant material: About 300 local land races of rice and BRRI released rice varieties in Bangladesh.\r\nb. Phenotyping: Phenotypic evaluation will be done in RCBD with three replications. Standard management will be given up maturity. Important traits required for DUS will be recorded.\r\nc. Trait evaluation\r\nd. Genotyping\r\ne. Data Analysis\r\n', 'The project aimed at to analyze the genetic diversity and population structure of Bangladeshi germplasm in comparison to global rice varieties, to characterize important local germplasm both Phenotypically and at molecular level and to protect our important local germplasm from any biopiracy. Morphological characterization of twenty GL rice, Fifty Aus landracesand 100 Aman landraces has been completed.', 'Plant Genetic Resources, Rice', 'NATP-SPGR', 9733000, 752897, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Plant Genetic Resources', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1169, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Biotechnology Division', 'Program', 'Genetic Enhancement of Sugarcane for sustainable productivity through Tissue Culture and Molecular Marker Techniques.', 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-01-2010', '31-12-2012', '01-02-2010', '', '1. To Screen improved varieties and enhance germplasm with desirable traits against disease pests adapted to the major agro-ecological conditions using tissue culture and molecular marker tools.\r\n2. To screen sugarcane against water-logging, drought and salinity stress through cell and tissue culture techniques.\r\n3. To produce large scale high quality seeds/setts (HQS) through micropropagation for enhanced rpoductivity of sugarcane.\r\n4. Tagge4d molecular markers with desirable traits for Lindage Mapping, Quantitative Trait Loci (QTL) and Marker Assisted Selection (MAS) of Sugarcane.', '1.	Tissue culture for variety improvement and germplasms enhancement-  Murashige and Skoog (MS) basal medium supplemented with 2, 4-D (4, 6 and 8 mg/l) + coconut water (10%) will be used for callus initiation. For root initiation regenerated shoots will be sub-cultured in the medium, MS+NAA (5 mg/l) supplemented with partially purified toxins of red rot fungus ranging from 0.05-0.5%.\r\n2.	Water-logging tolerant sugarcane development through tissue culture technique- BSRI bred varieties and germplasm prone to water-logging stress will be used as experimental materials. For callus initiation explants will be inoculated on MS + 2, 4-D (4, 6 and 8 mg/l)+coconut water (10%) and  Liquid medium MS + NAA (5 mg/l) with and without submerged conditions.\r\n3.	Drought tolerant sugarcane development through tissue culture technique- Semisolid MS media containing Hydroxy proline (0.5, 1.0, 1.5, 2.0 and 2.5 mM) and Polyethylene glycol (5.0, 7.5, 10.0, 12.5 and 15.0%)\r\n4.	Salt tolerant sugarcane development through tissue culture technique-inoculated on MS + 2, 4-D (4,6 and 8 mg) + coconut water )10%). Callus will be sub-culture on semisolid MS media containing NaCl salt (50, 100, 150, 200 and 250 mM) to in vitro salinity stress conditions.\r\na.	Micropropagation for High Quality Seeds (HQS) production of sugarcane, Experimental designs, Data collection, Data analysis.\r\nb.	Modecular markers based DNA fingerprinting for identification, documentation, protection of varieties and germplasms; linkage mapping QTLs and MAS. Band Scoring and Data Analysis. \r\n', 'Cell, tissue and organ culture, molecular marker techniques such as DNA Fingerprinting Linkage Mapping for Quantitative Trait Loci (QTL) and Marker Assisted Selection (MAS) are modern field of research offering great promise for genetic enhancement and varietal development with desired traits for sustainable productivities of sugarcane. The proposed project will be helpful to attain Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) and SAARC Development Goals (SDGs) sharing the success of Poverty Reduction Strategies (PRS) of Bangladesh through increase sugarcane and sugar production for Employment generation, consumption for nutrition towards realizing goals (employment, nutrition, quality education, maternal health, local governance, criminal justice, sanitation and safe water, monitoring) MDGs.\r\nIn view of the fact it is the most important and urgent need of sugarcane improvement using advance technologies such as tissue culture and molecular marker techniques which claim the proposed research attention.\r\n', 'Genetic Enhancement, Tissue Culture, Molecular Marker', 'BARC', 6842280, 3690467, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Biotechnology', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1170, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Agronomy and Farming Systems Division', 'Project', 'Coordinated sub-project on Farming system Research and Development for Farmers''Livelihoods Improvement: BSRI Component', 'Muladuli, Ishurdi, Pabna.', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'On-going', '01-02-2012', '31-10-2013', '', '31-10-2013', '1.	 To develop location-specific system-based technologies.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n2.	To modify/fine tune on-station technologies generated by NARS institutes at different Agro-ecological Zones (AEZs).&lt;br /&gt;\r\n3.	To integrate component technologies (crops, livestock, fisheries and agro-forestry and homestead, etc.) for improving farm practices &amp; establish linkage with different stakeholders.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n4.	To improve family income and livelihoods.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n', 'The broad methodology followed in FSRD is a 5- step problem- solving approach in which existing farming systems are described or diagnosed, farmers problems are prioritized, and improvements are designed, tested, evaluated and extended within similar agro ecological zones. Diagnostic aspects include socioeconomic parameters of farm families and farms described by an interdisplinary team of researchers, occasionally with the help of extension personnel. Technologies are designed by multidisplinary teams, sometimes with the assistance of experiment station researchers. Field testing is done usually by biological scientists. Researchers conduct multilocation testing and pilot production of promising technologies with the assistance of extension agents. The first step in FSRD process involves selection of target area and the client group of farmers. The target area is also frequently referred   to as the extrapolation area or the recommendations domain. Research is conducted in rather a small part of this target area called FSR site. The basic methodological framework is a- 5-step iterative process which involves descriptation of existing farming systems, designing alternatives packages/technologies based on identified problems, testing the alternatives, evaluating them, and disseminating the potential technology to the target group of farmers in the extrapolation area', 'This project aimed at developing Farming system technologies to maximize farm productivity and efficient use of resources by developing location specific system based technologies; by integrating component technologies (crops, livestock, fisheries and agro-forestry and homestead, etc.) for improving farm practices &amp; establish linkage with different stakeholders; by modifying/fine tuning on-station technologies generated by NARS institutes at different Agro-ecological Zones (AEZs);  by improving family income and livelihoods. For fulfilling those objectives we are establishing 17 experiments for crops, livestock, fisheries and homestead vegetables gardening. Already we have established 10 experiments.', 'Coordinated approach of Crops, Livestock, Fisheries, Homestead vegetables, Agroforestry, Sugarcane, Onion, Mustard, Carrot, Cabbage, Cauliflower', 'GOB', 3994800, 833523, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 0, 'Livestock, Fisheries, Homestead vegetables, Agroforestry', 'Livestock, Fisheries, Homestead vegetables, Agro forestry.', '', '', ''),
(1141, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'RPRS, Madaripur', 'Project', 'Identification of year round Mungbean variety for sustaining the changing climate of Southern belt and eco-friendly management of MYMV, Pod borer and Thrips.', 'RPRS, BARI, Madaripur', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '', '30-06-2011', 'To find out optimum sowing time for higher yield.\r\nTo study the impact of sowing time on incidence and severity of diseases of mungbean.\r\nTo manage the pod borer and thrips of mungbean\r\n', 'The experiment entitled &quot;Effect of different dates of sowing time of selected mungbean lines&quot; was carried out at the Regional Pulses Research Station, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Madaripur during the period from January 2011 to April 2011 in order to study the effect of dates of sowing on the incidence and severity of diseases of Mungbean.&lt;br /&gt;\r\nThe seeds of the four lines and two varieties of mungbean viz. BMXK2-030011-1, BMXK2 0300011-4, BMXK2 03000, BMXK2 03005-4 including BARImung-5 and BARImung-6 were collected from Pulses Research Centre, BARI, Ishurdi, pabna. The experiment was layout in the split plot design with two replications. The collected data were analyzed statistically by using MSTAT program.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n', 'Mungbean Yellow Mosaic Virus (MYMV) is one of the major constant of mungbean production in Bangladesh. Under the present study four advance line and two released varieties of mungbean were evaluated from January to April 2011 at 15 days interval of Regional Pulses Research Station, BARI, Madaripur in order to study the effect of dates of sowing on the incidence and severity of diseases and yield of Mungbean. The mean effect of sowing time all the parameters showed statistically differ except pod length and March 01, 2011 sowing gave the highest yield (1854 kg/ha) followed by February 15, 2011 sowing (1295 kg/ha). The mean effect of variety, all yield and yield contributing characters showed higher in BMXK2 03005-4 during kharif-1 season. The interaction effect of sowing time and lines/varieties all the parameters showed statistically differ from one to another. The yield performance ranged from 681.3 kg/ha to 2131kg/ha while the highest (2131 kg/ha) yield was found in i.e. March 01, 2011 sowing with BMXK2-030005-4 followed by   (1919 kg/ha) i.e. March 01, 2011 sowing with BARI mung-6. The less (681.3 kg/ha) yield was found in  i.e. April 01, 2011 sowing with BMXK2-03000 line. The increase of incidence of MYMV (%), yield of mungbean decreased. Among the five insecticides Fiter showed lowest (8.21%) insect infestation and highest yield (1522 kg/ha). The highest (22.12%) insect infestation and lowest yield (832 kg/ha) was observed in control plot. Among the five treatments Emitaf showed lowest (2.12) number of thrips per flower and highest yield (1875 kg/ha). The highest number of thrips (12) per flower and yield (1042 kg/ha) was observed in control plot.\r\n', 'Mungbean Yellow Mosaic Virus ', '', 200000, 200000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Pulse Crop', 'Mungbean', '', '', ''),
(1171, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', '', 'Project', 'Stadies on Date palm,Palmyra palm trees in Bangladesh', 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute, Ishurdi, Pabna', 'Medium', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-11-1997', '30-10-2000', '', '31-03-2001', '1. To find out appropriate agronomic management practices of Date palm and Palmyra palm trees to enhance juice secretion, degee Brix of juice and gur recovery.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n2. To find out effective size of cut/type of cut to enhance juice secretion, and gur recovery.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n3. To find out low cost appropriate preservation technique of Date palm and Palmyra palm gur.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n4. Plantation of noble Date palm (Phoenix dectylifera)along with wild Date palm (Phoenix sylvestris).', '', '', 'Date palm, Palmyra palm trees, Ancillary sugarcane.', 'BARC', 1490400, 1340425, 149975, 'Report', 'Field days', 0, 'Ancillary Sugarcane', 'Date Palm and Palmyra Palm', '', '', ''),
(1142, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'PRSS, BARI, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Quality improvement of farmer''s stored seeds of Mungbean, lentil and chickpea and its relation to disease development in Bangladesh.', 'Gazipur, Chapainawbgonj, Pabna, Magura, Jhenaidha  and Barisal ', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-06-2009', '31-05-2011', '', '15-08-2012', 'To determine the quality status of farmer stored mungbean, lentil and chickpea seeds.\r\nTo improve the quality of  farmers stored seeds of mungbean ,lentil  and chickpea.\r\nTo determine the seed health quality as affected by infection of the major pathogens.\r\nTo develop sustainable technology for production and preservation of quality pulses seed  through farmers participatory action research.\r\n', 'Experiments were conducted in the farmer''s field at different location of Bangladesh. The laboratory experiments were conducted at Pulse research sub-station (PRSS), BARI, Gazipur. Twenty (20) batches of farmers and 9 batches of DAE staffs training were conducted before sowing of pulses. Baseline survey and farmers selection, seed collection from different location, seed quality analysis, seed health test were done for the experiment.', 'Seed samples of lentil, chickpea and mungbean were collected from individual farmer''s stored house for seed quality analysis. Ninety (90) seed samples were collected from farmer''s stored house of mentioned pulse growing area. Out of 90 samples each pulse crop consists of 30 seed samples for seed quality analysis. Most of them had high moisture, varied from 11.8% to 13.5% in lentil, while it was 13.4 to 13.9 for chickpea and 11.8 to 13.8 for mungbean. The highest percentage of germination was found 75.60%, 78% and 75% respectively for lentil, chickpea and mungbean. The highest percentage of healthy seeds of lentil, chickpea and mungbean was found with an average of in Ishurdi, Chapai and Barishal region respectively. Nine fungi species were detected from lentil seeds and seven from chickpea seeds and 8 from mungbean seeds through blotter incubation method. The fungi Aspergillus and Penicillium were dominated in lentil, chickpea and mungbean seeds. 21 batches of farmers and 9 batches of DAE staff training were conducted to increased farmer''s knowledge as well as transfer the technology for quality pulses seed production. The percent insect infestation was recorded highest in Motka and lowest in plastic drum with neem leaves additives. The lowest percent motality and disease severity was recorded for seed treated with provex-200 and healthy seed as well as highest seed yield (1750 kg/ha) in lentil at Magura and the highest yield (1560 kg/ha) for chickpea at Chapai region.\r\n', 'Aspergillus and Penicillium, Lentil, Chickpea, Mungbean, Plastic drum. ', '', 1800000, 1800000, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 0, 'Pulse Crop', 'Mungbean, Lentil, Chickpea', '', '', '');
