(1172, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Agricultural Engineering Division', 'Project', 'Utilization and Management of sugar mills effluent water for irrigation purposes to increase crop production', 'North Bengal Sugar Mill and Faridpur Sugar Mill area.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-02-2010', '30-04-2013', '', '', 'To study the physico-chemical properties of effluent water&gt;\r\nTo evaluate the effect of effluent water on soil physicochemical properties\r\nTo determine the transport properties of pollutants in effluent water through soils\r\nTo study the effects of treated effluent water on growth and yield of sugarcane and other crops\r\nTo investigate groundwater quality due to irrigation with effluent water\r\nTo investigate possibility of treating the effluent by low-cost simple technique(s), and\r\nTo design and develop a low-cost effluent treatment plant.\r\n', 'Upgrading laboratory: The laboratory of the Agricultural Engineering Division of Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute (BSRI) is currently poorly equipped. The laboratory will be equipped and upgraded by the fund of this project\r\nField survey: Preliminary and detailed survey on the production of effluent water by some selected sugar mills will be done by interviewing local people through pre-test questionnaire. Analyses of these data will generate information on the quantity of mill effluent water, its impact on local environment, human and animal health, peoples perception of the effluent water, and potential scope of using this water.\r\nIn-hand training and demonstration on equipment use: A number of training and demonstration programs will be arranged for the persons involved in the project in which use of the equipments will be familiarized.\r\nSoil and water physico-chemical measurements: Sample of effluent water and affected soil will be analyzed at the beginning of project period to know their initial basic conditions. Soil properties will be required at the beginning, during and at the end of each crop experiments with effluent water to know the degree of accumulation of pollutants in the soil. Such data will also be required for reclamation experiments with polluted soils. Both soil and water properties will be evaluation parameters of ant water treatment experiments.\r\nLaboratory experiments on pollutant transport: The transport parameters of the major solutes of the sugar mill effluent will be determined for different textured soils by high-tech Time-Domain Reflectometry (TDR) method under controlled conditions.\r\n Wastewater treatment: Controlled laboratory experiments will be conducted to reduce pollutant loads by using different locally available low-cost materials such as saw dust, coal, soil materials, etc. Having done this a low-cost treatment plant will be established.\r\n Field experiments with wastewater: Experiments will be carried out to evaluate the effect of both treated and untreated effluent water on growth and yield parameters of sugarcane and other crops along with their yield quality.\r\nTraining and demonstration: A number of training and demonstration programs will be arranged for the stake holders of the project that will include local farmers, agricultural engineers and supporting staff involved in irrigation and drainage management, and other people who are directly and / or indirectly related to the management of effluent water.\r\nWorkshop and seminar: A number of seminar and workshop will be organized, preferably at institutional, inter-institutional and national levels, to disseminate the generated information on the treatment, use and management of sugar mills effluent water.\r\n', 'The project started in May2010.  Then Project Bank Account was opened in line with the directives of PIU-BARC, NATP: Phase-1. An Account Assistant (part time) was recruited. Procurement plan was prepared and submitted to PIU-BARC, NATP: Phase-1.  Questionnaire for benchmark survey in Sugar mills area was developed jointly by BAU and BSRI.  Benchmark survey was completed by interviewing 100 (hundred)  local people through pre-test questionnaire on the basis of sex, age, education and profession in North Bengal Sugar Mills area. The Co-PI of BAU component collected soil samples from North Bengal Sugar Mill waste water affected and non affected area.  Preparation was made to set up field experiments for laboratory column experiment. All respondents mentioned that the sugar mill is the source of waste water and that waste water is available during crushing period of the mill. Eighty (80%) respondents stated that they utilize this water to a limited scale to irrigate some crops in the land near the canal of waste water. Due to poor quality of the waste water, the farmers only occasionally used it for irrigation. High temperature of the waste water was a major problem to the farmers since it completely damaged the crops when used for irrigation. Major irrigated (by effluent water) crops were sugarcane (37%), wheat (40%), rice (25%), lentil (18%) and other crops (20%).  The respondents also informed that initially the waste water appeared clean, but turned black and started emitting a foul odour after stagnation for some time. Initial temperature of the effluent water was high, and this is harmful for aquatic life. 78% respondent stated that soil became brownish black after long term use of effluent water although 22% did not agree with that. In case of change in fertilizer and insecticide rate, 45% respondent thought it is responsive, but 27% did not think so. Farmers realized that the organic solids, oil and grease in the untreated waste water clogged the soil pores. The waste water degraded ground water quality. Waste water creates hazards to human and animal health by polluting the local environment. They also complained of skin infection and often injury to hands and legs due to working in the fields irrigated with the waste water.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\nField experiment was set up at Bijoypur (west Para), Gopalpur municipal area, Gopalpur, near North Bengal Sugar Mill area and   Vatikandi mothurapur, Union: Gazna, P.O: Modhukhali, Upozilla: Modukhali, Dist: Faridpur near Faridpur Sugar Mill area.   \r\n Wheat, Mustard was sown and pre-germinated sugar cane setts were planted in the farmers field on 24th November 2010 in NBSM area. In FSM area wheat and mustard were sown and sugarcane was planted in the farmers field on 12th November 2010. The experiments were set up in split plot design, with three replications, Irrigation treatments are: (a) Fresh water (FW) b) 50% fresh water + 50% waste water (c) Waste water (WW).  Fertilizer treatments are: a) Recommended Full dose fertilizer (FDF) (b) Half dose of recommended fertilizer (HDF) and (c) No fertilizer (NOF).  Mustard (Variety-BARI-15) of Faridpur sugar mill area was harvested on 26/2/11 and that of NBSM area was harvested on 28/2/11. Incase of wheat in FSM area the yield obtained in 50%Waste water + 50% Fresh water + Full dose of fertilizer treatment was 2.02 t/ha  and the lowest yield was obtained in 50%Waste water + 50% Fresh water  + NoF fertilizer treatment.   The highest yield of mustard at (Variety-BARI-15)  in North Bengal Sugar Mill area was obtained in 50%Waste water + 50% Fresh water + Full dose of fertilizer treatment (1.92 t/ha) and the lowest yield (0.57 t/ha) was obtained in Fresh water with no fertilizer treatment.  \r\nSamples of effluent water and fresh water were collected and analyzed at Water Quality Lab., IWM Dept. of BAU Mymensingh. Of the various quality parameters of the North Bengal Sugar Mills wastewater, nitrate nitrogen (NO3-N) and manganese (Mn) exceeded the limits given by FAO (1999) for irrigation, some parameters however remained below their limiting values. The measured quality parameters of the sugar mills wastewater indicated that this water was problematic one. The results of soil analysis showed good contrast in the properties of the wastewater-affected and unaffected soils. Among the measured chemical properties of the soil, such as pH, EC, Tot-N, P, K, S, Na, and organic carbon only the pH and sodium content of the soil decreased due to the impact of sugar mills wastewater. All other parameters increased in the wastewater-affected soils. The saturated hydraulic conductivity of the soil increased due to the effect of wastewater.\r\n', 'Effluent water, Sugarcane, Irrigation, Sugar mill.', 'BARC', 9200000, 0, 0, 'Publication', 'Training', 0, 'Effluent water management', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1143, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Pulses Research Sub-Station', 'Project', 'Development of sustainable production of mungbean and improvement of soil fertility &amp; soil environment through mungbean cultivation under Rice-Wheat-Mungbean cropping System.', 'Pulses Research Sub-Station, Gazipur and Regional Agricultural Research Station, Ishurdi, Pabna.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '12-06-2012', '01-07-2011', '12-06-2012', 'To develop short duration, late potential and synchronous maturing variety(s) of mungbean for cultivation after wheat as well as other Rabi crops. To improve soil fertility and to develop soil environment through biomass ploughing done and increase nutrient use efficiency. Finally, development and establishment of new variety of mungbean and new cropping pattern for maximum economic benefit and soil fertility improvement.', 'Collection and screening of short duration mungbean germplasm  in  Kharif-II season. Screening of mungbean germplasm for short duration, late potential and synchronous maturing in kharif-I season at research station in Joydebpur, Gazipur and Ishurd, Pabna. Participatory Variety Selection (PVS) was done within the location in farmers field. Finally seven mungbean lines were selected for short duration, late potential and synchronous maturing in kharif-I season under Rice Wheat-Mungbean cropping systems.', 'Seven short duration genotypes have identified which is now under trial at research station and farmers field. Through the development of short duration mungbean variety remaining fallow lands of wheat could be brought under mungbean cultivation which will be increased pulses cultivation. It will be ensured food security and also be help to increase farmers net return. Soil health to be improved', 'Mungbean, Screening, Germplasm, Genotypes', '', 150000, 150000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Pulse Crop', 'Mungbean', '', '', ''),
(1144, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Pulses Reseach Sub-Station, BARI, Gazipur', 'Project', 'DNA finger printing of BARI Released Pulses Varieties and available germplasm by using molecular markers.', 'Pulses Research Sub-Station, Gazipur.', 'High', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '13.	Objective(s) of research: To characterize available germplasm and relsed varieties of pulse crop for future breeding purpose.It was done also to avoid duplication of germplasm.', 'Bulk DNA isolation\r\nEight to ten days after emergence, the first leaves from five young seedlings from each of the  varieties were sampled and subjected to DNA extraction. Total genomic DNA was isolated from bulked leaf tissue using the protocol of Doyle and Doyle ( 1990) with minor modification. The extract DNA concentration and purity was determined by spectrophotometry and the concentration   was adjusted to 5 ng/&amp;#956;L.\r\n PCR procedure\r\nPCR reaction was performed in volume of 10 &amp;#956;L containing 2 &amp;#956;L    extracted genomic DNA, 1 &amp;#956;L 10x PCR buffer ( 100 mM Tris-Cl buffer, 500 mM KCl, 20 mM MgCl2, Gelatin 0.01%), 1 &amp;#956;L 1 mM dNTPs ( Promega, USA), 1 &amp;#956;L 2 mM primer, 0.2 &amp;#956;L ( 1 unit/ &amp;#956;L) Taq DNA polymerase (Promega) and 4.8 &amp;#956;L sterile water. Each tube was added with 30 &amp;#956;L of sterile mineral oil to seal the reaction mixture and to prevent evaporation. The PCR was carried out in a DNA Thermal Cycler (Bio Oven &amp;#1064;) programmed to the following temperature profile: 1 cycle of 1 min at 94&amp;#730;C, 44 cycles of 1 min at 91&amp;#730;C for denaturation; 1 min at 36&amp;#730;C for annealing, 2 min at 72&amp;#730;C for extension, 1 cycle of 7 min at 72&amp;#730;C as the final extension.\r\n Electrophoresis\r\nPCR products were size-separated by electrophoresis in 1.6 % agarose gel containing 0.6 mL 50x TAE buffer and 1 &amp;#956;L ethidium bromide ( 10 mg/mL). Three &amp;#956;L of BFF ( 1.2 mg/mL bromophenol, 125 mg/mL Ficoll) was mixed with 10 &amp;#956;L of PCR products and the whole mixture was applied in each well of the gel. DNA molecular weight markers were added to each gel. The gels were run in 1x TAE buffer with 2 &amp;#956;L ethidium bromide at a current of 100 mA until the front maker of BFF had reached 1 cm from the end of the gel. The gels were further stained with ethidium bromide solution ( 0.08 mg/ mL) for 5 min and then visualized by UV light transmitting Transilluminator and recorded with Bioprint- version 96.07 system and also photographed by Polaroid film 667. Polymorphisms at all loci were confirmed by three repeating tests at different times.\r\nPrimers Identification\r\n A set of seven random primers were selected to estimate the potential of these marker for variety identification. Finally four primers were selected based on their performances for RAPD analysis in lentil varieties.\r\n', 'The Institutionally ( BARI) developed more than 27 varieties of 7 different pulses crop species ( Annual report,2008)and available germplasms which have some identified characters.  But those are not adequate and well characterized and documented in the form that can support effective implementation of the Plant Variety and Farmers Right Protection Act (PVFRPA) of the country. The germplasms biopiracy by the commercial seed industry is another threat to protect native/indigenous variety, so standard and internationally accepted DNA profiling/molecular characterization would be a strong document to protect and clam genetic resources for national and farmers interest. The suitability of the RAPD technique in identifying DNA polymorphisms among the lentil genotypes, 7 oligonucleotide primers were used against 13 cultivars. Among seven primers four primers are found polymorphic .A total number of 33 score able bands were obtained through the RAPD analysis, which ranged in size from approximately 480 to 2300 bp. Of these amplified bands, 21 bands were reproducible polymorphic and thus regarded as informative RAPD markers for cultivar identification and 11 of bands detected as monomorphic across the genotypes examined. These informative polymorphic markers were able to differentiate all cultivars. Amplified 12 bands were unstable i.e. non-reproducible when the amplifications were repeated at different times, and thus were excluded from further study. The total number of reproducible bands produced with each primer varied from 6 to 10. Depending on the primer, the percentage of polymorphic bands observed among cultivars ranged from 100% to 50%.', 'Germplasms, DNA Polymorphisms, Lenntil Genotypes, RAPD, Polymorphic.', '', 400000, 400000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Pulse Crop', 'DNA fingure printing', '', '', ''),
(1145, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Pulses Research Sub-Station, BARI, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Action Plan for Increasing 15% Pulses production.', 'Patuakhali, Borguna, Jhalokhati, Barishal, Vola, Jessore, Jenaidhah, Magura, Cuadanga, Nator, Kustia, Pabna, Faridpur, Rajbari, Madaripur, Shariatpur, Rajshahi, Chittagong, Feni, Noakhali, Pirojpor, Panchagar, Tahkurgaon, Dinajpur, Nilphamari, Lalmonirhat, Kurigram, Chapinawganj, Naogaon, and Bogura. ', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2010', 'To increase production in traditional pulse growing area through improved variety and production technology.\r\nRetain the pulse growing area by encouraging farmer through block demonstration and field day.\r\nSearching new niches for traditional and nontraditional pulse production\r\n', ': Its  a coordinated national project. Program was run through two different ways. Firstly seed production both breeder and truthfully level seed. Seed production was done on station and seed village under the close supervision of pulse scientist.  Secondly technology transfer activities were done through block demonstration, farmers training, staff training, workshop and field days. Each year all the work was done on four pulse crop lentil, mungbean, chickpea and cowpea.', 'The accelerated increasing on population has triggered the production of food crops particularly rice. But for nutritional security of the growing population, production of food legumes special pulses is a prime need. Considering the facts govt. has taken up crush program to increase the production of rice and side by side pulses, under the program of 15% increase of rice and pulses during three years starting from 2007-08. In increasing pulses production program, different organizations are engaged BARI as the largest multicrop research institute of the country is also engaged in this program.', 'Nutritional Security, Growing population. Legumes', '', 1424900, 1424900, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 0, 'Pulse Crop', 'Lentil, Mugnbean, Chickpea, Cowpea', '', '', ''),
(1146, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Plant Breeding Division, BARI,', 'Project', 'Adaptation and popularization of salt tolerant hull-less barley for saline/coastal area.\r\n', 'Patuakhali, Satkhira &amp;   \r\n    Noakhali\r\n', 'Medium', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-09-2006', '30-06-2007', '01-09-2006', '30-06-2007', 'The major objectives of this project was to popularize Barley varieties among the farmers and provide training on barley production and its uses for DAE personals, Farmers, SSA and NGOs.\r\n&amp;#9679;To select salt tolerant genotypes for Saline area of Bangladesh\r\n&amp;#9679;To popularize and adaptation of hull-less barley cultivation among the farmers at selected areas.\r\n', 'A. Farmers selection: Selection of farmers at different saline area of Bangladesh 	\r\nB. Demonstration: The area of this project was different locations (Saline area) of the country e.g Rahmatpur, Barisal, Kalapara, Patuakhali, Khulna&quot; Banerpota, Satkhira, Sonagazi, Noakhali, Pahartoli, Chittagang and Cox''s Bazar. Field demonstration of BARI released barley varieties (BAR! Barley-3, 4 &amp; 6). These three varieties were demonstrated at the different location of BARI as well as farmers fields.\r\nC. Breeder seed production: Breeder seed was produced at different location e.g. Joydebpur, Ishurdi, Rahmatpur, Patuakhali, and Jessore during Rabi season\r\nD. Training: Training was conducted at each of the above locations about the production Technology and seed production technology at each location. Training program at each location comprising of DAE, OFRD, NGOs personnel and farmers.\r\n', 'According to the objectives of the project breeder seed of the selected barley varieties (BARI Barley-3, BARI Barley-4 and BARI Barley-6) were produced at Joydebpur, Ishurdi, Rahmatpur, Patuakhali and Jessore and field days were also held at those locations. Besides, training of 280 farmers and 90 SAAO/SSA/SA was also held to popularize the hull-less and salt tolerant barley varieties. After training program seeds of selected barley varieties were distributed to the trained farmers so that they can cultivate the hull-less BARI released barley varieties.', 'BARI Barley-3, BARI Barley-4, BARI Barley-6', 'BARC', 852000, 852000, 0, 'Booklet', 'Training', 370, 'Adaptation of salinity tolerent crop', 'Barely', '', '', ''),
(1147, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Plant Breeding Division, BARI,  Joydebpur, Gazipur-1701', 'Project', 'Varietal development of barley.', 'Joydebpur, Gazipur.', 'Medium', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-04-1998', '31-03-2001', '01-04-1998', '31-03-2001', 'a)  Collection, evaluation and characterization of barley genotypes specially for early, hull- \r\n     less and salt-tolerance.\r\nb) Selection of barley germplasm to develop early and hull-less varieties.\r\nc) Screening of barley germplasms against salinity to develop salt-tolerant varieties.\r\n', 'The project was conducted under two sub-project including the following  \r\n                               experiment.\r\nSub-project A- \r\na) Collection, evaluation and characterization of germplasm\r\nb) Hybridization of barley\r\nc) Study of F1 generation of barley\r\nd) Study of F2 generation of barley\r\ne) Study of F3 generation of barley\r\nf) Observation trial of barley\r\ng) Preliminary yield trial of barley\r\n\r\nSub-project B-\r\na) Screening of barley genotypes against (Nacl)\r\nb) Screening of barley genotypes with sea water\r\nc) Screening of barley genotypes in potted saline soil \r\nd) Maintenance of collected germplasm\r\n', 'Collected barley germplasms were characterized and evaluated. Crossing was done among the selected barley genotypes. The performance of F1, F2 and F3 generation was evaluated to develop hull-less early barley variety. To develop salt tolerant barley variety screening of barley germplasm was done in laboratory condition. Finally two barley variety were developed one of which was hull-less barley variety (BARI Barley -3) and the other was salt tolerant barley variety (BARI Barley -4).', '', 'BARC', 700000, 700000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Varietal Development', 'Barely', '', '', ''),
(1148, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Project', 'Marketing  and Price Behaviour of Brinjal in Some Selected Areas of Bangladesh', 'Chittagong, Comilla, Jamalpur, Jessore and Rangpur district', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2007', '', '30-06-2007', 'i.	To estimate the growth rates, instabilities and fluctuations of price, area, production and yield of brinjal\r\n\r\nii.	To analyse the price behavior (i.e. trend, seasonal and irregular) and the existence of brinjal price cycles in Bangladesh;\r\niii.	To analysis the factors responsible for determining the acreage under brinjal cultivation;\r\niv.	To determine the price flexibility and see the role   of supply of output in influence current prices of brinjal; \r\nv.	Examine the economic efficiency of various brinjal-marketing channels through Selected indicators and;\r\nvi.	To determine the constraints and suggest guidelines for improving the marketing systems.\r\n', 'Following steps were done\r\n1) Selection of study area:\r\nFive major brinjal growing districts of Bangladesh, namely Chittagong, Comilla, Jamalpur, Jessore and Rangpur, were selected  for this study. These five districts contributed more than forty percent towards the countrys brinjal production. (BBS, 2004)\r\n\r\n2) Sources of data and period of Study\r\nBoth primary and secondary data used for this study.\r\n3) Selection of Samples and Sampling Technique:\r\nA total sample of 100 growers were chosen randomly taking 20 farmers from each district.\r\n4) Analytical Framework\r\nDifferent methods of analysis were employed in accordance with the objectives set for the study.\r\na) Estimation of growth rates\r\nb) Instability estimation \r\nc) Fluctuations in price, area, production and yield \r\nd) Decomposition of Time Series Data\r\ne) Supply Response of Brinjal\r\nf) Price flexibility coefficient\r\n', 'The present study is an attempt to analyse the marketing and price behaviour of brinjal in selected areas viz., Chittagong, Comilla, Jamalpur, Jessore, Rangpur and as well as whole of Bangladesh in terms of growth, instability, annual fluctuation of prices, and decomposition of time series components. Both primary and secondary data were used for the study. Six performance indicators were used for measuring marketing efficiency of brinjal. Time series data for the period 1989/90-2003/04 and primary data from July/06 to June/ 07 were employed for this study. Growth rates of real prices in Chittagong and Jessore were found to increase over the period due to high demand of brinjal. Area instability of brinjal in Rangpur was the highest followed by Comilla, Chittagong, Jamalpur and Jessore during in terms of instability index. It was observed that annual real prices of brinjal in selected areas fluctuated to a great extent and it was highest in Comilla, followed byJamalpur, Chittagonj, Rangpur . The upward trend of real price was found for Chittagong and Jessore. The length of cycle in real prices was found 3 - 6 years on an average in the selected areas. The extent of fluctuation in irregular component was the highest for Comilla Chittagong and Jamalpur during the study period. It is evident from the seasonal indices that wide seasonal fluctuation occurred in brinjal prices in all the selected markets. The price flexibility was estimated to be 0.2134 in Rangpur. For the country as a whole the last year area played a dominant role in determining current year area allocation under brinjal. The district result showed that last year real price was an important for determining variable in area response function, particularly for Jamalpur district.  The farmers did not take into consideration the yield and price risk in the preceding two years for making a decision about the allocation of area under brinjal. The performance indicators revealed that the channel IV was the most efficient channel in the selected areas.', 'Brinjal Marketing, Price behavior, Gross margin', '', 100000, 100000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Marketing', 'Brinjal', '', '', ''),
(1188, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Entomology Division', 'Project', 'Integrated Pest Management in Sugarcane', 'NRS farm, Thakurgaon and Peerganj, Thakurganj; Vomradaha and Voulerhat, Thakurgaon.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-07-1998', '31-12-2000', '', '31-12-2000', 'i)On farm trial of recommended technologies for the control of major sugarcane pests through IPM.\r\nii)Training/Demonstration/adoption of PIM for sugarcane extension personnel/farmers.\r\niii)To study the economics of IPM in sugarcane.\r\n', 'For executing biological control measure in the field egg parasitoid Trichogramma chilonis Ishii was reared in the biological control laboratory on eggs of laboratory host (alternate host), rice meal moth (Corcyra cephalonica Stain ton). Corcyra was reared on ground wheat (food for larvae( in wooden trays. Optimum temperatures (25 &amp;#730;-30 C&amp;#730;) and % RH (70% and above) were maintained in the laboratory with the aid of air coolers, room heaters, humidifiers, mist sprayers etc. The bio-con lab was also equipped with thermometers, max-min thermometers, dry bulb-wet bulb thermometers, thermo hygrographs etc. Reading of daily temperatures and % RH were recorded in registers. Production of both host and parasitoid were recorded regularly.\r\nFor pest management in full package and in IPM plots Schedule of sugarcane insect pest management practices by BSRI. \r\n', 'Contract research project Integrated pest management in sugarcane of cost tk 20.00 lakh was initiated from  July 1998 and completed in December, 2000. The project was controlled from BSRI, Ishurdi, Pabna. The experimental site was Thakurgaon where most of the major sugarcane pests attack the cop every year. The project was conducted by 1 PI, 1 C0-PI and 2 SOs. Both the SOs were posted at North Regional Station (NRS), Madarganj. Thakurgaon to execute the regular programme of the research.\r\nThough yields were similar in full package and IPM but generally IPM gave more return/yield in control plots were much lower. Both class room training and field demonstrations increased the knowledge of all categories of trainees.\r\nThe results revealed that adoption of IPM in sugarcane was the best among the three treatments in respect to pest control and economics. The study recommends adoption and extension of IPM strategy in sugarcane for better environment and benefit.\r\n', 'Pest Management, Sugarcane', 'BARC', 2000000, 1272941, 152059, 'Report', 'Field days', 0, 'Pest Management', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1189, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Pathology Division', 'Project', 'Control of White Leaf Disease of Sugarcane', 'Sreepur Thana, Gazipur District', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '15-02-1998', '24-02-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'i.To find out appropriate control measures of white leaf disease of sugarcane\r\nii.To find out the effective time temperature combination of moist hot air therapy for controlling white disease.\r\niii.To find out the efficacy of heat therapy in controlling white leaf disease in plant cane and its subsequent generations.\r\niv.To find out the effect of heat therapy on cane yield and sugar/gur recovery.\r\nv.To suggest the cane growers to adopt specific technologies for controlling white leaf disease.', 'The experiments were set up at Sreepur Thana under Gazipur district for consecutive 4 cropping years i.e. in 1998, 1998-99, 1999-2000 and in 2000-2001.\r\n1.The experiments were set up in four farmers plot. Three lots of seed material were treated by moist Hot Air at 54 C for 2, 3 and 4 hours respectively and the remaining lot was used as check. Treated and untreated setts were placed in the seed bed and regular watering was done.\r\n2.T0 = Check (without treatment), T1 = Seed treatemtn by MHAT at 54 &amp;#730; C for 2 hours with above 99% R.H. T2 = Seed treatment by MHAT at 54 &amp;#730; C for 3 hours with above 99% R.H. T3 = Seed treatment by MHAT at 54 &amp;#730; C for 4 hours with above 99% R.H. After 45 days of treatment the germinated settlings were transplanted in the main fields (plot size 12x8 spq. M.) at a distance of 0.33 m having 8 rows of sugarcane 1 m apart with RCB design. Three replication were maintained for each category.\r\n3.To investigate the effect of MHAT of sugarcane seed on control of white leaf disease in the 3rd generation crop of treated seed another experiment was set up in another 4 farmers plot.\r\n', 'Experiment conducted to determine the effect of moist hot air treatment (MHAT) of sugarcane seed on control of which leaf disease (WLD) in the 1st, 2nd,  3rd and 4th generation and 1st ratoon crop of treated seed.  Sugar yield in teh treated plot were many folds compared to their check plots. In the check plots the average yield of sugar was 3.62 Mt. Ha -1 while int eh treated ;olts of MHAT at 54 0 C for 2, 3 and 4 hours the yield of sugar were respectively 7.59, 9.41 and 9.68 Mt. Ha -1', 'Sugarcane, White leaf diseases, Control measure', 'BARC', 600000, 569800, 0, 'Publication', 'Field days', 30, 'Sugarcane Diseases Management ', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1190, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Horticulture Center', 'Project', 'Adaptive trial and mass demonstration of pheromone trapping for pesticide free vegetable production', 'Bogra, Comilla, Chittagong, Gazipur and Norshigdhi.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-07-2012', '30-06-2015', '', '30-06-2013', 'The objectives of the adaptive research are\r\ni)	to educate, adopt and popularize poly-bag as a simple, low-cost and environmental friendly technique effectively control banana leaf and fruit beetle\r\nii)	to produce safe and pesticide free banana for consumers,\r\niii)	to reduce pest management costs and increase income of poor marginal and small banana farmers of the country', 'i)	Selection of farmers\r\nTruly poor marginal and small banana farmers will be selected on the basis of orchard size. Farmers having orchard at least 200 banana plants are to be selected. During selection necessary cooperation from Department of Agricultural Extension (DAE) of the respective Upazila will seek. At best two Upazila of each district will be select for educate, demonstration and popularization of the technology. \r\n\r\n\r\nii)	Farmers Training\r\nThe activities under this project are fully up-scaling of the technology through result demonstration and motivational training of poor marginal and small banana farmers on poly-bag use for controlling leaf and fruit beetle at the selected locations. Day-long training on safe banana production will be conducted at the farmers field near their banana orchards. Each batch contained 30 trainees. Among them 25 poor marginal and small banana farmers and 5 DAE field staffs. A total of eight (08) training programs will be conducted during the project period in four selected locations. Pest management expert, crop production specialists from leading research organization (BARI) and DAE personnel will also participate in the training and motivational camps as resource speakers and facilitators. \r\n\r\niii)	Publication of illustrated booklet\r\nAn illustrated booklet on use poly-bagging technique, its effectiveness and economics for safe banana production will be published and distributed among the target banana growers of the selected locations\r\n\r\niv)	Organize farmers field-day\r\nFarmers field-day will be organized at the end of the project period tentatively in the month of March to April 2013. Four field days will be arranged at four district locations. Approximately 110 participants will expect to gather in each field-day. In addition to that local leaders, public administration, DAE personnel, NGO representatives, production and plant protection experts are expected to join in the gathering. Booklets will be distributed among the presence at that day/occasion.', 'After being completion of the above planned activities a full-length project compilation report on the proposed title will be submitted to the funding authority with due facts of project implementation, financial statement, results, achievements, short-fall and future recommendations.', 'Vegetable, Pesticide, Pheromone Trapping', '', 200000, 50000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Environmental Science', 'Pesticide', '', '', ''),
(1191, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Horticulture Research Centre', 'Project', 'UP-Scaling of poly Bagging Technique for pesticide-free Banana production', 'Palashbari, Gobindaganj (Gaibanda District), Shibganj, Sonatala (Bogra district), Sokhipur, Modhupur (Tangail District), Monohordi, Panchdonr (Narsingdhi district). ', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-09-2012', '30-04-2013', '', '30-04-2013', 'i)Enrich farmers understanding, knowledge, views and attitudes through result demonstration, training, exchange visit and motivational campaigning/tours.\r\nii)To compare efficacy of IPM package over existing farmers practice.\r\niii)To reduce pesticide use in vegetables.\r\niv)To promote adoption process.\r\n', 'i.  Rate of technology use, change of attitude\r\nii. Yield and yield contributing characters, cost of treatment', 'Enrich farmers understanding, knowledge, views and attitudes through result demonstration, training, exchange visit and motivational campaigning/tours from this project.', 'Banana, Insect, Bittle', 'DANIDA', 1198144, 520590, 0, '', 'Training', 150, 'Banana Insect', 'Banana', '', '', ''),
(1192, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Horticulture Research Centre', 'Project', 'Risk assessment and Development of Management Packages against Citrus Leafminer and Fruitfly', 'Gazipur, Khagrachari and Norshingdi', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '', '15-11-2011', '1.	To identify leaf miner and fruit fly free areas and or orchards. \r\n2.	To find out severity of leaf miner and fruit fly in different citrus growing areas.\r\n3.	To develop effective control measures against leaf miner and fruit fly.\r\n4.	To create awareness of growers and exporters about citrus production and insect pests management.\r\n', 'Survey on Leaf miner and Fruit fly incidence and their pest status at different citrus orchard\r\n1.to identify leaf miner and fruit fly attack free areas/orchard/cultivars\r\n2. to know the pest status and severity of leaf miner and fruit fly\r\n2.to collect resistant cultivars/germplasm against leaf miner and fruit fly\r\nCrop	:	4. Lemon, Satkara, Jara lebu\r\nLocation	:	3.  Gazipur, Khagrachari and Norshingdi\r\nDate of initiation	:	From project starting\r\nDevelopment of management package (s) against leafminer and fruit fly\r\nObjective(s): \r\n1.	To evaluate effectiveness of different combinations of control methods formulated based on earlier experiments\r\n2.	To identify the best combination  of management practice based on benefit-cost ration and minimum of applications for the management of citrus leafminer and fruit fly\r\n', '16.	Abstract/ Executive Summary (Max. 200 words, Please underline the keywords)\r\nCitrus is the group of several fruits belonging to family rutaceae. It is an important fruit crops which are cultivated almost every where in Bangladesh but it is grown commercially in greater Sylhet, Chittagong and Norsingdi districts. Now days farmers of Bangladesh are facing problems to produce citrus fruits due to severe attack of citrus leaf miner and fruitfly for exporting citrus fruits to middle east and UK. Leaf miner (Phyllocnistis citrella) is a serious quarantine pest of citrus crops especially in lemon, limes and oranges that causes great damage (Behlau et al. 2007). Leaf miner infestation favors the canker disease (Haque et al., 2006).  Leaf miner larvae causes curl and distorted leaves which hampers photosynthesis process (Grafton-Carwell et al, 2008).  Fruit fly (Bactrocera dorsalis) causes economic losses of citrus fruits throughout the world in Bangladesh, and recognized as a major threat to the citrus industry. It damages 15-21% of production every year (Morse, 2009).\r\nKeeping all these in consideration, detailed survey was done to investigate the pest status and incidence of leafminer and fruit fly in different citrus orchard at three different locations of Gazipur, Norshindi and Khagrachari. and some efforts have been given under this project to find out the suitable management option for the control of citrus leaf miner and fruit fly which would be useful for Farmers, Nurserymen and Private Entrepreneurs. The survey was conducted at three locations of Gazipur, Norshindi and Khagrachari on pest status and abundance of citrus leaf miner and fruit fly during 2010-11 cropping season. From the results it was found that 23.70% lemon, 19.12% lime and 17.53% mandarin leaves were infested with leaf miner. Minimum leaf miner infestation was observed at Norshingdi. Fruit fly infestation was upto 34.38% and its infestation started in July and reached at the peak in October. No fruit fly incidence was found in lemon and lime during study period in three locations. To develop a suitable management approach against the destructive citurs leaf miner, Phyllocnistis citrella stainton (Lepidoptera: Gracillariidae), several management options were evaluated  on sweet orange (malta) during 2010-11 at Fruit farm of Horticulture Research Center, BARI, Gazipur. There were six treatments in the experiment. Among all the treatments, 2 spray of Roxion 40EC @ 1.5ml/l of water starting from flash at 15 days interval performed best to reduce leaf miner infestation followed by 2 spray of Actara 25WG @ 1.0g/l of water starting from flash at 10 days interval. Another field experiment was conducted at Hill Tract Agriculture Research Station, Ramgorh, Khagrachari during July to November 2010 to find out effective control measures against citrus fruit fly, Bactrocera dorsalis. There were six treatments used in the experiment. The results indicated that the bagging of fruit with perforated polybag showed best performance in reducing fruit fly infestation.\r\n', 'Canker disease, Leaf miner, Fruit fly', 'GOB', 200000, 200000, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Plant Protection', 'Citrus leaf miner and fruit fly', '', '', ''),
(1193, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Horticulture Research Centre', 'Project', 'Risk assessment and Development of Management Packages against thrips (Thrips palmi) in exportable brinjal and bittergourd', 'Gazipur, Norshingdi, Jessore and Chittagong', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2012', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', '1.To identify thrips tolerant varieties/cultivars and thrips free areas of brinjal and bittergourd for export.\r\n2.To find out severity of thrips in different brinjal and bittergourd growing areas.\r\n3.To develop effective pre and post harvest control measures against thrips.\r\n4.To create awareness of growers and exporters about brinjal and bittergourd production and thrips management.', '1.Survey of different exportable brinjal and bittergourd growing areas to know pest status and their severity.\r\n2.Screening of genetic resources of brinjal and bittergourd for selecting promising lines* tolerance against thrips. \r\n3. Evaluation of different management practices against thrips in brinjal and bittergourd \r\n4.Development of management package against thrips\r\n5.Field demonstration in selected sites with package technologies.\r\nSurvey on Thrips incidence and their pest status at different exportable brinjal and bittergourd growing areas\r\nScreening of brinjal and bittergourd germplasm  resistant/tolerant against thrips', '1.Survey on Thrips incidence and their pest status at different exportable brinjal and bittergourd growing area.\r\n2. Screening of brinjal and bittergourd germplasm  resistant/tolerant against thrips.\r\n3. Evaluation of different management practices against thrips in brinjal and bittergourd.\r\n4. Development of management package (s) against thrips.\r\n5. Farmers field demonstration in selected sites with package technologies.\r\n', 'Brinjal, Bittergourd, Pest control, ', 'GOB', 300000, 300000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Pest Control', 'Brinjal and Bittergourd', '', '', ''),
(1149, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Project', 'Technical Efficiency of Maize Growers in Some Selected Areas of Bangladesh', 'Chuadanga, Dinajpur, Bogra and Lalmonirhat district', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2007', '', '30-06-2007', 'i.To know the socio-economic profile of maize growers\r\nii.To estimate cost, return and profitability of maize production\r\niii.To quantify the technical efficiency of maize growers\r\niv.To know the impact of technical efficiency on production; and\r\nv.To suggest some policy implications for maize production in Bangladesh.\r\n', 'The study was conducted in four major maize growing districts Chuadanga, Dinajpur, Bogra, and Lalmonirhat according to intensity of maize area as well as maize area index. The selected four districts covered 61 per cent of total maize areas of the country. A list of maize growers was collected from each area and a total of 200 samples taking 50 from each area were selected by random sampling technique for the study. Data were collected by survey method with the help of pre-designed and pre-tested interview schedules during the year 2006-07. The collected data were analyzed by tabular and statistical method.', 'The study was carried out in four major maize growing areas namely Chuadanga, Dinajpur, Bogra and Lalmonirhat during 2006-2007 to estimate technical efficiency of maize growers. Maize production was found to be profitable. Findings of impact of different inputs use on maize yield revealed that farmers in the study areas did not use inputs judiciously. But the average technical efficiency of maize growers was reasonable in all areas. Lack of capital and high price of TSP were the main constraints to its production.', 'Technical Efficiency, Maize Production, Profitability', '', 80000, 80000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Farmers Technical Efficiency', 'Maize', '', '', ''),
(1186, 'Dhaka University ', 'Soil, Water and Environment Department', 'Project', 'Potassium Studies in Soils and Crops in Bangladesh', 'Soils of the Ganges, Brahmaputra and Meghna Floodplains.', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-06-1986', '30-06-1988', '01-06-1986', '01-07-1988', 'The main thrust was to determine the quality of different forms of potassium (readily available difficultly available and unavailable) in the agricultural soils formed on the floodplains of Bangladesh and the need for potash fertilizer application.', 'Some selected soil samples from the floodplains of the Ganges, the Brahmaputra and the Meghan river s were collected from two depths-surface soils (0.15 cm depth and subsoil 15-30 cm depth). Various forms of potassium 8in soils were determined by following the standard methods. ', 'The total contents of potassium in the soils were high as there were abundant mica minerals in all the size fractions.  But the availability of potassium to plants was not high in all soils. The value of 0.2 me/100 gms of soil of exchangeable Kt was taken as the threshold value of exchangeable potassium to meet the plant needs. Variation of exchangeable potassium was quite wide. There was need for application of muriate of potassium some soils for luxuriant plant growth. There was suggestion for more research on potassium in these soils. ', 'Threashold values, Potassium bearing Minerals, Exchangeable  Potassium.', 'BARC', 60000, 60000, 0, 'Publication', 'Workshops', 0, 'Soil Potassium', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
(1187, 'Dhaka University ', 'Soil, Water and Environment Department', 'Project', 'Land Quality Assessment and Utilization for Sustainable Agriculture in Bangladesh. ', 'Eight Upazilas of Bangladesh: Bahubal, Delduar, Fultala, Kalai, Melandaha, Mirpur, Muktagachha and Ramgati.', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies', 'Completed', '01-06-2001', '30-06-2005', '01-06-2001', '30-06-2005', '-The major objective of this project was to assess the present aland quality in Bangladesh and to find out if the soil health has deteriorated ever time as consequent of overuse of land through multiple cropping which was triggered by demographic pressure. \r\n-With the money of this project of first class GIS  laboratory was established in the Soil, Water and Environment, Department of the University of Dhaka ', 'In determining soil quality the concept of minimum data set (MDS) was applied. Some soils quality indicators were selected. These were organic carbon and of soil. The present soil organic carbon and pH of eight selected upazilas in Bangladesh were determined and were concept with some past reference base of those indicators. Soils were pH were determined. For the post reference base of organic carbon and pH values the results of corresponding upazilas as presented in the RSS (Reconnainance Soil Survey) and upazila Nirdeshika of SRDI were used.', 'The results obtained through the above methods showed that the mean organic carbon contents and the mean pH value of the present die not differ appreciably from the results of the past reference base. This was thoroughly to be due to the fact that although multiple cropping cause more decompositions of organic carbon in soil, it also helped in adding more organic residues to the soil from every crop.\r\nOur conclusion was that there was not much deterioration of soil quality in the last few decades. If was suggested that more such researches should be undertaken in future as soil is the only basic resource of Bangladesh be regularly monitored for maintain its productivity. \r\n', 'Soil health, multiple cropping, minimum data set, organic carbon, past reference base, soil quality indicators, soil quality monitoring , soil productivity, beregalarly mointored', 'USDA', 10000000, 10000000, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 0, 'Soil Quality', 'Soils', '', '', '');
