ts will be in excess of foreign costs or savings indicating that the i crop should not be produced domestically and should be imported instead. \r\n\r\nFinally, the livelihood development due to cultivating improved oilseed varieties will be measured by analyzing data and information regarding livelihood improved indicators under the with improved variety and without improved variety .\r\n\r\nEx-post evaluation of oil crops research investment: The third objective of the present study is to estimate the returns to investment in oilseeds research and development in Bangladesh.  An ex-post evaluation with the help of economic surplus model will be adopted in this study to estimate the benefit-cost ratio (BCR), internal rate of return (IRR) and net present value (NPV) of the investment on oil crop variety research and development in Bangladesh. The analysis will be done under closed economy situation. The theoretical and empirical discussions of economic surplus model are given below.\r\n\r\nThe theoretical model: The concept of economic surplus has been used to measure economic welfare and the changes in economic welfare from policy and other interventions (Alston et al., 1995 and Currie et al., 1971). The social benefits to the research and extension of improved technology in Bangladesh are measured in terms of producers and consumers surpluses resulting from a shift in the supply curve, caused by an increase in productivity. This outward shift in the supply function results from an upward shift in the aggregate production function resulting from the adoption of improved technologies. This relation is shown in Figure-1 in which D1 and So represent the actual market demand and pre-research supply curve, whereas Sn represents the post-research supply curve that would have existed due to the adoption of improved technology.\r\n\r\n\r\nFigure 1. Closed-economy Economic Surplus Model\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n         \r\n\r\n\r\n  Quantity (Q)\r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\nDistribution of Economic Benefits:\r\nChange in consumer surplus/benefit 	=	Area ABC + Area PoBAPn\r\nChange in Producer surplus/benefit	=	Area AOC - Area PoBAPn\r\nChange in total economic surplus/benefit 	=	Area ABC + Area AOC\r\n\r\nAssuming market equilibrium and closed-economy commodity market, the shift in the supply curve from So to Sn would increase consumers surplus by Area ABC+Area PoBAPn, the producers surplus by Area AOC-Area PoBAPn, and the total social benefit or economic surplus by Area ABC + Area AOC (Fig 1). The shift in the supply curve has decreased the price that made consumers better off. The change in consumers surplus (benefits) can be measured as a monetary value. Besides, area AOC represents the benefits to the farmers from adopting improved technology and can also be measured and quantified in monetary terms. Farmers will be benefited from the adoption of improved technology intervention if Area AOC is greater than Area PoBAPn. In the present case, the Area AOC is less than the Area PoBAPn. The size of the two areas depends on the elasticities of the supply and demand curves and the size of the supply curve shift. The total social benefit from the adoption of improved technology is the summation of the change in consumers surplus plus the change in producers surplus for adopting the technology. \r\nEmpirical model: The Akino and Hayami (1975) approximation formula for calculating changes to producer and consumer economic surplus will be used in the proposed study. The approximation formula for calculating the change in economic surplus for a closed-economy situation (Fig 1) is as follows:\r\nArea ABC = ((&frac12; PnQn) ((k ( ))2 /( ))) ------------------------------------------------------   (11)\r\nArea AOC = (kPnQn)  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  (12)\r\nArea PoBAPn = ((PnQnk( ))/( ))x((1- (&frac12; k (( ) ))/( )) - (&frac12; k  ( ))) ---------- (13)\r\n\r\nWhere,\r\nPo =  Output price that would exist in absence of research\r\nQo =  Quantity of output (ton) produced that would exist in absence of research\r\nPn =  Actual output price (existing market price)\r\nQn =  Actual quantity of output (existing production)\r\n   k =  Horizontal supply shifter \r\n   =  Price elasticity of output supply\r\n   =  Absolute price elasticity of the demand for the output. \r\n        (For a closed-economy model, the estimated   is used in the above formulas. For a small \r\n        open-economy model where the   is perfectly elastic, use a sufficiently large no. for .)\r\n\r\nThe overall yield advantage of improved technology over the traditional varieties weighted by the proportion of the total production saved due to improved technology adoption is called the supply shifter (k). In estimating yield advantage, the yield of selected crops (both improved and traditional variety) will be collected through HH survey. The supply shifter k is calculated as follows: \r\nWhere,\r\n          Yit = Yield of improved variety in year t\r\n           Yt =  Yield of traditional variety in year t\r\n          Ait =  Proportion of the total production saved due to improved variety adoption in year t\r\n  	n =  Number of farms (Sample respondent).\r\nThe following primary and secondary data and information will be needed to run the model. Type of primary and secondary data and their sources are presented in the following boxes.\r\n\r\nData type	Sources of data\r\nYear-wise district level area, production and yield	BBS, DAM and DAE\r\nLocal level area, production and yield	Questionnaire survey\r\nAdoption profile of oilseed varieties	ORC and DAE \r\nRetail prices of oilseeds	DAM\r\nRetail prices of oilseeds in rural markets	Questionnaire survey\r\nSupply and demand elasticities	Research report\r\nResearch costs	BARI, DAE, BARC\r\nYear-wise quantity and price of imported oilseed/oil 	BBS, Bangladesh bank\r\nFOB price of oilseeds/oil	Bangladesh bank\r\n21.	Environmental impact, social safeguard and gender matter (One para statement on each of these issues. If negative impacts, add mitigation plan. Environmental matrix to be filled and attached, check the website of BARC)\r\nThe quality of soil is deteriorating day by day due to repeated crop cultivation, practicing injudicious cropping patterns, use of excessive chemical fertilizers &amp; pesticides, and unable to keep land fallow for a certain period. All these activities are appeared to be threatening to the environment and whole agricultural system. The proposed project is related to oilseed production which will not be harmful to the environment.\r\n', 'The 2-year survey based project titled Assessment of socio-economic impacts of oilseeds research and development in Bangladesh is being implemented by the Agricultural Economics Division, BARI during July, 2011- June, 2013. It will evaluate the public investment on research and extension of oilseeds technologies in terms of variety development, area coverage by improved technology, factors of adoption, comparative advantage of production, returns to investment, foreign exchange savings due to adoption, and farmers perception toward developed technologies. The budget for the project is Tk.36,66,480/=. \r\nTotal 2160 oilseed farmers spread over 10 selected districts namely Manikgonj, Faridpur, Tangail, Rajshahi, Pabna, Dinajpur, Noakhali, Comilla, Luxmipur, and Jessore were interviewed for collecting farm level data. Various econometric models such as Probit, Cobb-Douglas, economic surplus, and DRC will be used along with different statistical tools for analyzing the collected data.\r\nIn the last 1.5 year, the major outputs of the project were collection of related literature, staff recruitment, procurement of goods, vehicle hire, conducting workshop on inception report, and collection of both primary (2160 nos.) and secondary data. Secondary data were mostly analyzed in this period. The works to be done in the next half year are data analysis and report preparation.  \r\n', 'Field level Data, Oilseed, Socio-Economic Fectro, Respondent Farmers.', 'BARC', 3666480, 1428354, 0, 'Publication', 'Workshops', 7, 'Socio economic impact', 'Pulses', '', '', ''),
(1158, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Oil Seed Research Centre', 'Project', 'Seed Production, Storage and Utilization of Groundnut Through Farmers Participation', 'Noakhali, Laxmipur, Jamalpur, Kaliakoir, Kapasia, Debigonj', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', 'Production and distribution of quality seeds of groundnut to farmers to   \r\n  popularize HYV.\r\n\r\n   ii) Validation of mature technologies by conducting research based block \r\n        demonstration at farmers field for minimizing yield gap.\r\n', 'Seed production and storage techniques of HYV groundnut varieties was conducted at the different locations of the country during two consecutive years of 2008-09 and 2009-10 under the financial support of Agricultural Technology Transfer Project, BARC, Farm Gate , Dhaka, Bangladesh. Twelve block demonstrations of about 12 hectares (Table 1.) HYV groundnut varieties namely BARI Chinabadam-6, BARI Chinabadam-7 and BARI Chinabadam-8 with the local check Dhaka-1 were set up during Last week of December to 1st  week of January in each years of 2008-09 and 2009-2010 in Jamalpur, Kaliaqur, Kapasia, Noakhali, Laxmipur and Debigonj to disseminate the improve varieties. Twenty (20) farmers were selected from each block demonstration area. The farmers were trained up on modern production technologies, qualities seed production and storage technique of HYV groundnut varieties in block demonstrated areas. Fertilizers and other intercultural operations were done following Mondal and Wahhab (2001). The crop was harvested on last week of May in each year. Date of maturity, harvesting time and shelling (%) and yield (Kg/ha) were also recorded in different varieties and locations.', 'Seed production blocks of about 9.00 hectares HYV groundnut varieties BARI Chinabadam-6, BARI Chinabadam-7 &amp; BARI Chinabadam-8 with the local variety Dhaka-1 were set up during two consecutive years of 2008-2010 in Jamalpur, Kaliaqur, Kapasia, Noakhali, Laxmipur and Debigonj to disseminate the improve varieties to the farmers. About 400 farmers and extension personnel (10 batches) were trained up on improved production technologies and storage of groundnut. About 10.0 (ten) tones of quality seeds of HYV groundnut were produced in those block demonstration areas. The highest yield (2.50 t/ha) was obtained from BARI Chinabadam-8 followed by Chinabadam-6 and BARI Chinabadam-7 (2.4-2.45 t/ha). Dhaka-1 produced the lowest yield (1.7 t/ha) but matured early (140-145 days). The farmers of those areas were pleased and impressed. Demonstrated modern technologies are helpful to the farmers improving knowledge on quality seed production as well as good storage techniques. Productivity, cropping intensity, income generation and employment opportunity has also been increased.', 'Groundnut, Seed production, Storage', 'BARC', 600000, 600000, 0, 'Publication', 'Training', 400, 'Seed Production', 'Groundnut', '', '', ''),
(1159, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Regional Spice Research Station, BARI, Gazipur.', 'Project', 'Increasing Productivity of Bilatidhonia through Seed Treatment and Quality Seed Production.', 'RSRC, BARI, Joydebpur and RSRC, BARI, Magura.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2012', '30-06-2013', '01-08-2012', '30-06-2013', 'The main objectives of the project are:\r\n1. Standardization of improved Bilatidhonia leaf and production techniques in respect to hormone dose and soaking time with shade system and agronomic practices.\r\n2. To reduce cost of Bilatidhonia production cost about 40% of the total thus increased farmer''s profitibility.\r\n3. To increase Bilatidhonia seed production and germination using growth regulator thus increase cultivated area and production to meet the local and export demand.\r\n4. To help in improving the socio-economic condition of the growers by using the improved technology in Bilatidhonia production.', 'The method will be followed to fulfill the objectives of the proposed project is described below:\r\ni) Selection of experimental plot: The experiment will be conducted at two stations such as\r\n1) Regional Spice Research Station, BARI, Gazipur (AEZ-12).\r\n2) Spice Research Station, Magura (AEZ-28)\r\nii) Collection of experimental inputs: Different inputs for conduction the experiment such as seeds, fertilizers, growth regulators etc. will be collected in proper time for setting up the experiment in time.\r\niii) Implementation of research activities: \r\nTreatments\r\nFactor A: Shade\r\n 1) Black mosquito net (2 mm loop) shade\r\n2) Cucurbit Trellis\r\n3) Control (No shade)\r\nFactor B: Sowing and Thinning:\r\ni) 10 cm line sowing with no thinning.\r\nii) Line sowing with 10x10 cm plant spacing.\r\niii) Broadcasting without thinning.\r\niv) Broadcasting with thinning\r\nCommon treatment: 72 hours soaking (8 hours soak and 4 hours drying for 6 times) with growth regulator (GA3 500 ppm + Kinetin 50 ppm) treatment.\r\nTreatment: 8 (2 shade x 4 sowing &amp; thinning)\r\nLocation: (2): RSRS, Gazipur and SRC, Magura\r\nVariety: The selected Bilatidhonia line (EF003)\r\nDesign: Split plot design (Shade in main plot, sowing and thinning in the unit plots).\r\nReplication: 3\r\nPlot size: 3 m x 3 m (2 beds in each plot).\r\nDate of sowing: November, 2012', '', 'Bilatidhonia, Seed treatment, Seed production', '', 300000, 300000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Spices', 'Bilatidhonia', '', '', '');
