(1160, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Oilseed Research Centre', 'Project', 'Adoption of Short Duration HYV Mustard in Between T. Aman and Boro Rice', 'Gazipur (Kapasia), Tangail (Birsingh, Ghatail, Elenga, Dhonbari, Kalihati), Nilphamari (Domar), Brahmanbaria, Comilla (Lakhsam, Homna and Daudkandi), Jamalpur (Baruamari, Mothergonj, Ramnanor), Manikgonj, Sherpur (Nalitabari).', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2010', '', '30-06-2010', 'i) To fit short duration HYV mustard varieties in between T. Aman and Boro Rice. \r\nii) To demonstrate whole package production technologies of mustard in the farmers field.\r\n', 'Adoption of Short Duration HYV mustard in between  T. Aman and Boro Rice was conducted at the different locations of the country during three consecutive years of 2007-08, 2008-09, and 2009-10 under the financial support of Agricultural Technology Transfer Project (ATTP), BARC, Farmgate , Dhaka, Bangladesh. Nineteen block demonstrations of about 38 hectares land of HYV mustard varieties namely BARI Sarisha-9, BARI Sarisha-14 and  BARI Sarisha-15 with the local check Tori-7 were set up during Last week of October to 2nd week of  in each years of 2008, 2009 and 2010 in Dhonbari, Ghatail, Tangail, Nalitabari, Sherpur, Kapasia, Daudkandi, Comilla, Baruamari, Mothergonj, Jamalpur to disseminate the improve varieties. Twenty (20) farmers were selected from each block demonstration area. The farmers were trained up on modern production technologies, qualities seed production and storage technique of HYV mustard varieties in block demonstrated areas. Fertilizers and other intercultural operations like weeding, thinning, application of insecticides and fungicides were applied during proper time in different locations following Mondall and Wahhab (2001). The crop was harvested on last week of January to first week of February in each year. Date of maturity, harvesting time and yield (Kg/ha) were also recorded in different varieties and locations.', 'Adoption of short duration HYV mustard in between T. aman and boro rice was conducted at the different locations of the country during 2007-08, 2008-09, and 2009-10 under the financial support of ATTP, BARC, Dhaka, Bangladesh. A total of nineteen block demonstrations of about 38 hectares land of HYV short mustard varieties namely BARI Sarisha-9, BARI Sarisha-14 and BARI Sarisha-15 were set up nineteen locations of the country. About 900 farmers including SAAO have been trained up on modern production technologies of short duration mustard varieties. About 900 farmers with DAE officers and SAAO were participated in field days occasion.  The results revealed that BARI Sarisha-9 took 78-81 days, BARI Sarisha -14 took 80-82 days while BARI Sarisha-15 took 84-85 days  to mature. The highest yield (1655 kg/ha) was obtained from BARI Sarisha-15 at Dhonbari, Tangail followed by BARI sarisha-14 (1345-1532 kg/ha) and BARI Sarisha-9 (1200-1450 kg/ha). Farmers showed positive reaction to grow short duration mustard varieties in between T.aman &amp; Boro rice. Because they got about 40 to 45% higher yield than local variety Tori -7 in those areas. Farmers of these project areas benefited about more than 22000 Taka/ha for growing short duration HYV mustard varieties in this cropping pattern.', 'Short duration HYV Mustard T. Aman and Boro rice', 'BARC', 1200000, 1200000, 0, 'Publication', 'Workshops', 900, 'Cropping pattern Development', ' Mustard', '', '', ''),
(1161, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Oilseed Research Centre', 'Project', '     Study on Yield Loss Assessment of Soybean and Sesame', 'BARI, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-06-2005', '31-07-2007', '', '31-07-2007', 'i.To identify the reasons of soybean and sesame yield gap \r\nii.To evaluate the actual management practice for soybean and sesame cultivation\r\n', 'A study was carried out at the experimental farm of Oilseed Research Centre, BARI, Gazipur during Robi season of 2005-06. The 11 treatment were T1= Recommended package (RP):Timely sowing (by mid December) + Recommended fertilizer @ 25-35-55-18-1.5-1.8 kg ha-1 of NPKSZnB+ Weeding cum thinning+ Irrigation (two)+ Insect control + Disease control; T2= RP except timely sowing (delayed sowing); T3= RP except fertilizer; T4 = RP except half fertilizer; T5= RP except weeding cum thinning; T6 = RP with one irrigation; T7 = RP except irrigation; T8 = RP except insect control and T9= RP except disease control. The experimental design was RCBD with three replications. The unit plot size was 4 m x 3 m with the spacing of 30 cm x 5 cm. The seed rate of soybean (BARI Soybean-5) 70 kg ha-1 was sown on 14th December 2005. From seedling to harvesting management practices were done as per treatments. Data on grain and stover yields were calculated from the whole plot but all the yield components like plant height, primary branches per plant, number of pods per plant, number of seeds per pod and 100 seed weight were collected from ten plants selected randomly from each unit plot. Collected data were analyzed statistically separately (Steel and Torrie, 1960). Land equivalent ratio (LER) was computed from the yield data according to Shaner et al. (1982). The economic analysis of benefit cost ratio (BCR) was analyzed on the basis of total expenditure of the respective treatment along with the total return from that particular treatment. Treatment wise management cost was calculated by adding the cost incurred for labours and inputs for each treatment. The yield was utilized to calculate the gross return. This was estimated by multiplying the total yield by the unit price of soybean at that time. Net return was calculated by subtracting management cost from gross return.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n b) Methodology of sesame&lt;br /&gt;\r\nAn experiment was conducted at the experimental farm of Oilseed Research Centre, BARI, Gazipur during Kharif season of 2005-06. The 11 treatment were T1= Recommended package (RP):Timely sowing (by 1st week of February) + Recommended fertilizer @ 80, 65, 60, 20, 3 and 1 kg ha-1 of N, P2O5, K2O, S, Zn and B respectively + Weeding cum thinning+ Irrigation (one)+ Insect control + Disease control; T2= RP except timely sowing (delayed sowing); T3= RP except fertilizer; T4 = RP except half fertilizer; T5= RP except weeding cum thinning; T6 = RP with one irrigation; T7 = RP except irrigation; T8 = RP except insect control and T9= RP except disease control. The experiment was laid out in a RCBD with three replications having plot size 4 m x 3 m with the spacing of 40 cm x 5 cm. The seed rate of sesame (BARI Til-3) 08 kg ha-1 was sown on 4th February 2006. From seedling to harvesting management practices were done as per treatments. Data on grain and stover yields were calculated from the whole plot but all the yield components like plant population, days to maturity, plant height, branches per plant, number of capsule per plant, number of seeds per capsule and 1000 seed weight were collected from ten plants selected randomly from each unit plot. Collected data were analyzed statistically separately (Steel and Torrie, 1960). Land equivalent ratio (LER) was computed from the yield data according to Shaner et al. (1982). The economic analysis has been analyzed.   ', 'a) Executive summary of soybean\r\nSoybean (Glycine max L.) has high potential both as a pulse and oil crop for Bangladesh (Anon. 1985). Soybean seed contains over 40% protein and it can play a vital role in balancing the protein deficiency of our diet. Soybean plant with the help of Rhizobium bacteria in its roots nodules is capable of utilizing atmospheric nitrogen for its growth, higher yield and finally enriching the nitrogen fertility of the soil (Biswas et al. 1991).  \r\nIn farmers field the average per hectare yield of soybean is about 1000 kg ha-1 although the yield potential of modern soybean varieties is more than 1500-2000 kg ha-1. There are many reasons which caused the yield gap. An experiment was conducted at Oilseed Research Centre under Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Gazipur to calculate the proportionate yield and economic loss of soybean through identifying different management factors of yield gap of soybean. The management factors were T1= Recommended package (RP); T2= RP except timely sowing; T3= RP except fertilizer; T4 = RP except half fertilizer; T5= RP except weeding cum thinning; T6 = RP with one irrigation; T7 = RP except irrigation; T8 = RP except insect control and T9= RP except disease control. The results showed that the highest soybean yield 2000 kg ha-1 was obtained from recommended package. The maximum yield reduction 62.20% was recorded from the plot delayed sowing with compared to recommend packaged. Results also showed that soybean seed yield were reduced by 57.75, 33.65, 28.75, 22.85. 15.75, 13.25, and 9.45% were obtained from the treatments without weeding cum thinning, without insect control, without fertilizer, without disease control, without irrigation, without half fertilizer and with single irrigation respectively. The highest economic loss Tk. 15074 ha-1 was achieved from the treatment delayed sowing. \r\nb) Executive summary of sesame\r\nSesame (Sesamum indicum L.) is one of the edible oil in Bangladesh (Kaul and Das 1986). It is cultivated both in Kharif-I and autumn season but two third sesame is produced in Kharif-I season. Per hectare yield of sesame is only 640 kg ha-1 (BBS, 2003) which is very low yield compared to ORC, BARI released varieties of sesame. The yield potential ranging from 1200-1500 kg ha-1 depending on variety. The yield performance of these varieties in the research station is very good but in the farmers field it was not satisfactory. There are many reasons of yield gap of sesame such as delayed sowing, imbalance fertilizer, lack of irrigation, lack of insect and disease control etc. \r\nAn experiment was conducted at Oilseed Research Centre under Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Gazipur to calculate the proportionate yield and economic loss of sesame through identifying different management factors of yield gap of sesame. The management factors were T1= Recommended package (RP); T2= RP except timely sowing; T3= RP except fertilizer; T4 = RP except half fertilizer; T5= RP except weeding cum thinning; T6 = RP with one irrigation; T7 = RP except irrigation; T8 = RP except insect control and T9= RP except disease control. The results showed that the highest net returns Tk. 17816 ha-1 was obtained from recommended package.The highest economic loss Tk. 12455 ha-1 was achieved from the treatment no fertilizer and second highest loss Tk. 10942 ha-1 was obtained from the treatment no weeding cum thinning. To minimize the yield gap and economic loss of sesame, full package of management practices should be applied which will help to reduce the yield gap between research and farmers field.\r\nd) Funding Information\r\n', 'Soybean and Sesame, Seed production, Storage', '', 150000, 150000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Seed Production', 'Soybean and Sesame', '', '', ''),
(1162, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Regional Pulses Research Station, Madaripur', 'Project', 'Upgrading of Pulses Research Sub-Station Madaripur to Regional Pulses Research Station', 'Madaripur', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-01-2010', '30-06-2014', '', '30-06-2014', 'i)Collection, identification, characterization and evaluation of germplasm of pulses of the southern region of Bangladesh\r\nii)Development of high yielding varieties with resistant to biotic and abiotic stresses\r\niii)Conduction of research based demonstration in block and training of farmers, NGO and extension personnel\r\niv)Production and distribution of breeders seed and truthfully labeled seeds of improved varieties of pulses\r\nV) Upgrading of Pulses Research Sub-station (PRSS) to Regional Pulses Research Station (RPRS) with increasing skill manpower, land area and infrastructure\r\n', 'Increase area and production of pulses.\r\nTo make available HYV pulses to the growers.\r\nImprove soil health by biological nitrogen fixation.\r\nMotivate farmers in using modern technologies.\r\nImprove nutritional status of poor people.\r\nIncrease employment opportunities for rural women and unemployed youths.\r\n', 'Pulses cover 4% area of 9.10 million ha of cultivable land in Bangladesh. Area under pulses is about 0.66 million ha producing 0.67 million tons of dry grain to feed the 150 million people of Bangladesh (Source: Krishi Dairy, 2010). It is necessary to produce 2 million tons of pulses to meet up 45 g per capita consumption of pulses per day. Local production meets only 25% of the demand and the remaining 75% are imported at the cost of valuable foreign currency.\r\nMadaripur, Gopalgonj, Jessore, Jhenaidah, Magura, Shariatpur, Faridpur, Rajbari, Khulna and Barisal districts are traditionally pulses growing area. But farmers are growing the old local varieties of pulses using the primitive practices of cultivation. More over, farmers are facing several constraints in cultivating pulses. Disease and insect pests are the major constraint. Similarly, soil and environmental factors are important for growing pulses. To increase pulses production, location specific backup researches as well as development activities directly handled by the scientists are essential. There is however no station for location specific researches and transfer of the generated modern technologies. For carrying out research and development activities already existing research farms of BARI were being used which was found insufficient and could not be used for the specific purpose of pulses R. &amp; D. activities because the organization has so many other mandate crops to handle with. So, to put sufficient effort to a crop or a group of crops separate research stations for pulses research is essential. Depending on same reason BARI established location wise research sub-stations for spices under Spices Research Centre. Pulses Research sub-station, Madaripur was established in 2002 to address the problems of pulses cultivation and to expand pulses varieties and technologies in Southern part of the country under Lentil Blackgram and Mungbean Development Pilot Project (LBMDPP) with an area of 15 acres although the administrative approved was for 30 acres. \r\nPresently research work on development of major pulses variety like lentil, Khashari, Chickpea, field pea, mungbean and cowpea suitable for southern part of the country are being conducted. Out of the research, collection of germplasm of the above mention crops are being collected from inside the country and from aboard and are being evaluated in this station. This station is continuing research activities with man power recruited under development project.\r\nAlthough research on pulses was initiated in 1970S but initial research work concentrated in collection of local germplasm of different pulses. Only few varieties of pulses was development in 1980S,. Mean while research on crop management and crop protection of pulses was started with the financial support from externally funded crop diversification programme, funded by Canadian International development Agency (CIDA). Similar research work was simultaneously carried out at BINA. By 2006, BARI developed altogether 27 varieties of pulses and BINA developed 16 varieties. There was no manpower provision in the initially established station. One senior scientist has been deputed from BARIs main body to run the station. But over the last four years the manpower and research and development activities of the sub-station was found quite insufficient compared to the demand of the region. Therefore, strengthening of pulses research sub-station at Madaripur was felt necessary. In this project the sub-station has been proposed to be upgraded to a Regional Pulses Research Station (RPRS) which will play a significant role in research and development of pulses in the southern region covering districts of Madaripur, Gopalganj, Shariatput, Faridpur, Rajbari, Patuakhali, Bhola, Barisal, Jalakhati, Pirojpur, Khulna and Bagerhat.\r\n', 'Upgrading, Crop protection, Crop diversification', '', 181600000, 73716000, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 11500, 'Pulse variety development', 'Pulses', '', '', ''),
(1163, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Pulses Research Centre', 'Project', 'Validation and Up-Scaling of Mungbean and Lentil Technology in the rice based Cropping Systems in Bangladesh.', 'Jessore, Jhenaidah, Gopalganj, Rangpur, Kurigram and Gaibandha', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '31-05-2014', '01-10-2011', '31-05-2014', '1) To verify the yield potentiality of promising short duration Lentil lines and Mungbean varieties in the farmer''s field.\r\n2) To adopt Lentil relay cropping in the rice field.\r\n3) To established the short duration Mungbean variety with a cropping system of Lentil/Mustard/Wheat/Potato/Maize-Mungbean-T. aman rice.', 'To established short duration Lentil and Mungbean variety to a new cropping niche different combination will be required from among the following agronomic elements: 1. Validation of short duration Lentil lines with yield potentiality and diseases resistance 2. Relay cropping especially broadcasting prior to before harvest T. aman rice. Short duration Mungbean Cultivar is available.\r\nOn-Station research to identify short duration Lentil and Mungbean lines with yield potentiality and diseases resistance will be conducted in Years 1 and 2.\r\nLentil relay cropping into rice will be done as a no-toll system using results from on station research, which suggest the use of seed rates of 40-50 kg/ha. 2% urea as a foliar spray on to 1.5 month-old palnts, and cultting the rice to retain stubble 25cm tall. On-farm adaptive research will focus firstly on the comparison of cultivar Barimasur-4 with the short duration lentil line and secondly on the optimization of the timming of broadcasting in relation to residual soil moisture rather than the current recommendation loam soils (avoiding the heavy clays) in Jessore, Jhenaidah and Gopalgonj district.\r\nMajor diseases of lentil are foot and root rot and Stemplylium blight. Mungbean is the short duration grain legume which fits well in various cropping systems in Bangladesh. Day by day farmers are being intersted to cultivate this valuable crop after harvesting rabi crops due to its short life span. But insect pests from seedling to pod maturing stage and cause significant ield loss. Among these pests, Stemfly, flea beetle, hairy caterpillar etc. attacks in seedling to vegetative stage. Thrips and pod borers are the major cause of yield loss at flowering and pod developing stages. Therefore the experiment has undertaken to find out effective and economic management package(s) against insect pest''s complex of mungbean as well disease of lentil and mungbean.', 'With the vision to verify the package of production technologies the farmer''s cooperators will be selected one trail in each to two Upazilas of ten selected district for lentil and mungbean (Gopalgonj, Jessore, Jhenaidah, Kurigram, Gaibandha, Rangpur and Kurigram). The technologieswill be adaptively-tested and demonstrated in large-blocks (30 per season) each comprising at least 10 farmers in a compact block. Each farmer demonstrated 1 bigha of land for lentil and mungbean. One thousand square meter of each plot will be harvested and yield will be calculated for kh/ha. Proportionately the modern short duration varieties seeds and limited inputs will be disgtributed among neighboring farmers during the tenure of the project for up scaling the modern varieties.', 'validation, Lentil, Mungbean, Up-scaling.', '', 13000000, 0, 0, 'Booklet', 'Training', 1200, 'Pulse Crop', 'Mungbean, Lentil', '', '', ''),
(1164, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Workshop Machinery and Maintenance Division', 'Project', 'Design, Development, Modification and Introduction of self-propelled reaper and mini-power tiller to augment crop production', 'BRRI, Gazipur, Rangpur, Rajshahi.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-01-2010', '31-12-2012', '10-06-2010', '09-06-2013', '1. Enhancement of self-propelled reaper through introduction of field test at different locations in Bangladesh.\r\n2. Ensure timeless of harvesting to increase cropping intensity through the developed self-propelled reaper.\r\n3. Minimize human drudgery and post harvest losses as well as harvesting cost.', 'Workshop machinery and maintenance Division of BRRI has developed a self-propelled reaper for harvesting rice and wheat. The complete design of self-propelled reaper has been done with the help of AutoCAD tools. In this machine for easy power transmission, a gearbox with mechanism of two forward and a backward speed have been introduced. Fabrication of the reaper has been going on in full swing at BRRI Research Workshop by the direct supervision of the Principal Investigator (PI) and Co-Principal investigators. On the other hand, using the AutoCAD tool, the design of a mini-power tiller has been completed which will be operated by the same power unit of reaper. Simultaneously, fabrication of mini power tiller is also going on at BRRI research workshop. ', 'Design, development, modification and introduction of self-propelled reaper and mini power tiller to augment crop production, a sponsored public goods research project, received by the Workshop Machinery and Maintenance Division of Bangladesh Rice Research Institute. The main objectives of the project were to ensure timelines of farm operation, increase cropping intensity and minimize human drudgery as well as post harvest losses by demonstration of newly developed users friendly self-propelled reaper and mini power tiller. The imported self-propelled reaper and existing BRRI developed self-propelled reaper were tested in BRRI regional station, Rajshahi in Boro 2011-12 and T. aman 2010-11 seasons. During the field operation of the reaper with 1.2 m head, average field capacity of the imported reaper and the existing BRRI developed self-propelled reaper were found 0.236 ha/hr (58.29 decimal/hr) and 0.278 ha/hr (68.66 decimal/hr) respectively in Boro season. On the other hand, in 2010-11 T. aman season the average field capacity of the imported reaper and the existing BRRI developed self-propelled reaper with the same head were found 0.232 ha/hr (57.24 decimal/hr) and 0.267 ha/hr (65.84 decimal/hr) respectively. The average fuel consumption of imported reaper and BRRI reaper were 0.827 l/hr and 0.765 l/hr respectively. The purchase price of the imported reaper is almost double of BRRI reaper. But the existing reaper need some modification due to its various limitation such as turning mechanism, forward speed, chasis difficulties etc. Therefore modifications have been carried out step by step at BRRI research workshop to fulfill the objectives of the proposed research project.', 'BRRI developed self-propelled reaper, Imported reaper, modification', 'BARC', 10370480, 4775116, 0, '', '', 0, 'Farm Machinery', 'Reaper, Mini Power Tiller', '', '', ''),
(1165, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Co-ordinated project on Soil Fertility and Fertilizer Management for crops and cropping patterns.', 'BRRI Component, Rajshahi, Rangpur, Hobiganj, Sonagazi, Feni, Barisal.', 'High', 'Basic', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '01-07-2013', '', '', 'To determine fertilizer requirement for adaptive rice and rice based croping pattern in ecologically unfavorable areas (coasts, submergene. drought-prone and haors)\r\nTo assess the changes in soil fertility under by rice based cropping pattrns and soil fertility management practices.', 'Approach and methodoloty: Both laboratory and field studies will be conducted for the project. However, the following approaches and methodologies will be used to achieve the objectives of the proposed research project.\r\nThe following approaches and methodologies will be adopted to fulfill the objectives of the proposed research project.\r\nField Experimentation: Five field experiments (Sites mentioned above) will be conducted under different unfavorable conditions with Rice-Fallow-Rice or rice-based cropping pattern.\r\nLocations: Fertilizer management for haor areas: Hobiganj\r\nVarieties: HYV or  promising lines\r\nFertilizer management for saline soils: Sonagazi\r\nVarieties: Salinity tolerant rice varieties or promising lines.\r\nFertilizer Management for submergence ecosystem.\r\na) Rangpur\r\nb) Barisal\r\nVarieties: Submergence tolerant rice varieties or promising lines\r\nFertilizer Management for drought-promising lines\r\nExperiment: To determine the optimum and economic fertilizer dose for Rice-Fallow-Rice-based cropping patterns in unfavorable conditions.\r\nJojectives: 1. To assess soil fertility of rice growing areas in unfavorabole conditions;\r\n2. To determine the optimum and economic fertilizer dose for crop/cropping patterns under unfavorable conditions trial.\r\nMaterials and Methods: Field experiments will be conducted with the following treatments for each location: \r\nT1=100% NPKSZn (STB)\r\nT2=T1+25%N\r\nT3=T1+25% NP\r\nt4=T1+25%NK\r\nT5=T1+25%PK\r\nT6=t1+25%NPK\r\nT7=75% of T1\r\nT8= Sontrol ', 'Coordinated project on soil fertility and Fertilizer Management for crops and cropping patterns: BRRI component, a sponsored public goods research project, received funding from the NATP of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Council. The Coordinated project on soil fertility and fertilizer management for crops and cropping patterns: BRRI component has officially launched on 15 June 2011 through the signing of letter of agreement. The project received an approval of budget Tk. 46,20,653/= for a period of two years two months. Aiming to formulate and update of fertilizer recommendation for rice and rice-based cropping systems under different unfavourable ecosystem the project has a provision of one Scientific Officer, one Field Assistant and one Lab Technician. The objectives will be achieved through survey, laboratory analysis work and field experiments. Site selections and initial soil samples collection of 5 unfavourable ecosystems (Coasts and char, submergence, drought prone, tidal and haors) will be started in 1st week of July, 2011. Laboratory analysis work and field experiments will be started immediately after personnel recruitment. The recruitment process will be started very soon. Procurement plan of the project including goods, work and services are included in this inception report.', 'BRRI component, Crops and Cropping Patterns, Soil fertility, fertilizer management', 'BARC', 4620653, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Soil Science', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1174, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Experiment', 'Economics of Fertilizer use in Sugarcane Production and its Impact on Sugar Yield in Some Selected Areas of Mills Zone in Bangladesh.', 'Pabna, Joypurhat and Carew &amp; Co. sugarmills zone.', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-06-2003', '30-06-2006', '', '30-06-2006', '1)To find out the returns to fertilizer use for sugarcane production.\r\n2)The impact of fertilizer use on per hectare sugarcane production and sugar yield.\r\n3)To compare per hectare sugar yield of farmers field and sugar mills with BSRI varietals potentiality.\r\n4)To find out the causes of sugar yield variation from research station to sugar mills.\r\n', 'A preliminary survey had been conducted randomly 90 sugarcane sample farmers taking 30 from each location in Pabna, Joypurhat and Carew &amp; Co. sugarmills zone area. Data on actual fertilizer dose applied (N, P, K), cost &amp; return of the sugarcane production, pesticides and irrigation use, cane yield was collected by interviewing cane farmers of the respective mills area and sugar yield data have been collected through chemical analysis from BSRI Physiology and Sugar Chemistry division before cane supply to the sugar mills. Data on fertilizer uses had been collected from individual mills /BSFIC. Descriptive statistics was employed to analyze the data of the project. Fertilizer returns have been calculated by applying partial budgeting method. After maturity of the sugarcane crop and before harvesting the pole % of sugarcane was collected directly from the farmers plot.', 'The study was conducted during the period of 2005-2006 to evaluate the effect of recommended and non recommended doses of fertilizer use. Ninety sugarcane farmers had been selected randomly this purpose in Pabna, Joypurhat and Carew &amp; Co. sugarmills zone location. Descriptive statistics was used in this study. It is observed from the study that in the mill zone area out of 90 farmers 32(35%) farmers used recommended doses of fertilizers (N,P,K) and 58 (65%) farmers did not used recommended doses. Higher sugarcane yield 67.93 ton/ha as well as net return Tk. 37,270/ha was obtained by the farmers who used recommended doses of fertilizer. On the other hand, the farmers achieved 41.33 ton/ha average yield and net return Tk.15,332/ha who did not used the recommended doses of fertilizers. The farmers, who used recommended doses of fertilizer, achieved 26.60 ton/ha more sugarcane yield than the farmers who did not used as recommended doses. Use of recommended fertilizer had a positive impact on sugar yield also. Average sugar production was achieved 4.88 ton per hectare by the recommended doses of fertilizer user. On the other hand, the farmers achieved 2.91 ton/ha sugar who did not used. So, sugar yield difference between with and without recommended doses of fertilizer user was 1.91 ton/ha.', 'Sugarcane, Sugar, Yield, Recommended doses and Fertilizer ', 'BARC', 100000, 16000, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'TOT and Socio-Economic', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1175, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Agriculgtural Economics Division', 'Experiment', 'An Economic Analysis of Sugarcane Intercropping with Special Emphasis on High Value Intercrops in Some Selected Areas of Bangladesh. ', 'Mills and non-mills zone area of Bangladesh ', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-06-2005', '30-06-2007', '', '30-06-2007', 'To find out existing adoption rate of intercropping with sugarcane.\r\nTo find out constraints to intercropping practice with sugarcane\r\nTo find out the impact of intercropping with sugarcane production.\r\nTo determine benefits obtained from different experimental, demonstration and farmers practice with intercropping to sugarcane with special reference to high value intercrops.\r\n', 'Criteria for selection of the study area was based on where the sugarcane crop competes with the other crops intensively. Both mills and non-mills zones of Bangladesh has been undertaken for the study. Thirty sugarcane growing sample farms have been selected randomly from each of selected mills (Joypurhat, Rajshahi Sugar mills zone), and non-mills zone (Chapai Nawabganj) areas. Data was collected from the farmers who cultivated sugarcane with intercrops through tested questionnaire. ', 'The study was conducted for the cropping year 2005-07 both in mills and non-mills zone areas where sugarcane compete with other crops intensively to study the economic impact of intercrop with sugarcane. Thirty sugarcane sample farms have been selected randomly from each of the selected mills (Joypurhat, Rajshahi Sugar mills zone), and non-mills zone (Chapai Nawabganj) areas.. The major intercrop pattern in the study area were sugarcane + potato, sugarcane + onion, sugarcane + garlic, sugarcane + lentil. It was found that yield of potato; onion, garlic and lentil as an intercrop were 8, 5, 3.5 and 0.60 ton respectively. It was also observed that the major competing crops grown in that areas were Onion + Mustard + Garlic, Mustard + Gram + Garlic + Paddy and Carrot + Wheat + Okra.', 'Sugarcane, Intercrop, Economic Analysis', 'GOB', 30000, 30000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'TOT and Socio-Economic', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1176, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Experiment', 'A Socio-Economic Analysis of Date Palm and Palmyra Palm Cultivation in Some Selected Areas of Bangladesh.', 'Madaripur (Rajoir), Faridpur, (Bhanga), Jessore (Monirumpur), Satkhira (Sadar), Patuakhali (Sadar) &amp;  Natore (Bagatipara) District.', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2009', '', '30-06-2009', 'Farmers practice of cultivating date palm and palmyra palm in selected areas of Bangladesh\r\nProfitability analysis of date palm and palmyra palm cultivation in selected areas of Bangladesh\r\nTo determine the present marketing systems of date palm and palmyra palm production, its product (gur), and by-product in the country\r\nConstraints to production of date palm and palmyra palm in selected areas of Bangladesh.\r\n', 'Data was collected by 3-4 interviews through tested questionnaire during 2006/07. Data from 30 samples on date palm and palmyra palm will be collected from each location. In total 360 samples farms will be selected for data collection on date palm and palmyra palm cultivation in Bangladesh. Necessary information on cost and return of date palm and palmyra palm will be collected. Besides these, data on socio-economic factors, gur preparation of date palm and palmyra palm, its marketing (including sale of date palm and palmyra palm) and utilization of labours, and constraints to cultivation will be collected. Cost and return analysis of date palm and palmyra palm production will be estimated. Financial analysis of date palm and palmyra palm was employed to estimate discounted benefit-cost ratio (BCR), net present value (NVP) and internal rate of return (IRR). The research project was continued for three years (2006/07-2008/09).', 'The study was conducted on date palm and palmyra palm cultivation from 36 locations with a view to estimated returns from date palm and palmyra palm cultivation and its marketing in Bangladesh. Data were collected by 3-4 interviews through tested prescribed questionnaire from 36 locations of 1080 randomly selected sample farms during the study period (2006/07-2008/09). Cost and return analysis of date palm and palmyra palm production were also estimated. The study found that on an average, the farmers were benefited per date palm tree through 21.12 kg of gur, 140 liter of juice production for 2006-07 season, 22.00 kg of gur, 142 liter of juice production for 2007-08 season and 22.50 kg of gur, 155 liter of juice for 2008-09 season, respectively. On the other hand the farmers were benefited from per palmyra palm tree through 34.58kg of gur, 250 liter of juice, 450 nos green fruits production for 2006-07 season, 35.00 kg of gur, 262 liter of juice, 520 nos green fruits production for 2007-08 season respectively. Farmers earned more net income from per palmyra palm than date palm tree both of gur and juice production. However, farmers got more net return from juice production than gur and fruit production. The farmers usually sold their product in the local market and that is almost consumed in the local area. There is a lack of methodical cultivation of date palm and palmyra palm tree, fertilizer application, technical know-how of the farmers, extension services from DAE about gur preparation, gur processing and preservation.', 'Date palm, Palmyra palm, Socio-Economic Analysis', 'GOB', 432000, 432000, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'TOT and Socio-Economic', 'Date Palm and Palmyra Palm', '', '', ''),
(1177, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Soils and Nutrition Division', 'Project', 'Development of Nitrogenous Bio-Fertilizer for Sugarcane with Free-Living and Associative Bacteria Using Biological Nitrogen Fixation (BNF) Technology.', 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute, Ishurdi, Pabna', 'Low', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-12-2008', '30-11-2011', '', '31-03-2013', 'In view of high energy crisis, scarcity and escalating high prices of chemical fertilizer, low purchasing power of the most farmers and environmental pollution due to imbalanced and injudicious use of chemical fertilizer, the objectives of the project have been set up as follows:\r\n1.Development of nitrogenous bio-fertilizer (viz., Acetobacter diazotrophicus, Azospirillum spp, Azotobacter spp, Agrobacterium diazotrophicus, Herbaspirillum seropedica, Bacillus spp, Derxia spp, etc.) to supplement urea fertilizer for sugarcane.\r\n2.Establish laboratory facilities and upgrade technical skill of scientific manpower for conducting researches in the field of biological nitrogen fixation (BNF) and developing appropriate microbial cultures to be used in bio-fertilizer preparation.\r\n3.Development of site specific more efficient appropriate strains of free living and associative bacteria for fixing atmospheric nitrogen in sugarcane.\r\n4.Improvement of soil health through integrated use of bio-fertilizer, chemical fertilizer and organic manure for sustainable sugarcane production.\r\n', '1st year:\r\ni) Benchmark survey\r\nii) Procurement of equipment and furniture\r\niii) Employment of contractual staff\r\niv) Phenotypic selection of promising genotypes suspected for BNF ability\r\nv) Set up of the experiment in field: A field experiment has been conducted under N-stressed field condition (without N-fertilizer) at BSRI farm, Ishurdi. It was laid out in RCBD with four replications. A ten number of selected promising sugarcane genotypes suspected for BNF was planted for evaluation and screening. Traditional three-budded cutting of sugarcane was used. Data on percent germination, tiller at 120, 150 and 180 DAP, mill able cane, yield of cane and sugar at harvest has been scheduled to be recorded. Initial and post harvest soil nutrient status, total N at 0, 120, 150, 180 and 270 DAP is also scheduled for the record and analyses. Rhizosphere soils and cane stalk would be collected for laboratory investigation.\r\nvi) Intercultural operation in field experiment\r\nvii) Analyses of soil and plant tissue in laboratory\r\n2nd year:\r\ni) Culture, isolation and characterization of the diazotrophs sampled from the stem/root of sugarcane genotypes and rhizosphere soils of the field experiment (By using appropriate selective growing media) in laboratory.\r\nii) Count of bacterial cells per plant/ per gram of rhizosphere soil by using plate count Technique.\r\niii) Identification of the favorable N2-fixing sugarcane genotypes and bacterial organism by using biolog and gas chromatography.\r\niv) N-balance method will also be followed to calculate the relative input of N from BNF in sugarcane genotypes.\r\n3rd year: i) Selections of appropriate carrier material and conditions for survival of that diazotrophs to be used as bio-fertilizer.\r\nii) Finally nitrogenous bio-fertilizer for sugarcane will be developed with those appropriate bacteria.\r\niii) That developed bio-fertilizer will be evaluated both in laboratory and in sugarcane fields under different Agro-ecological zones of Bangladesh. \r\niv) Leaflet/booklet on the technology will be prepared and final report of the project will be published.\r\n', 'A field experiment was conducted at Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute farm, Ishurdi during 2009-10 and 2010-11 to identify and screen out sugarcane clones endowed with bio-logical nitrogen fixation (BNF) in absence of nitrogenous fertilizer. In 2009-10 ten promising sugarcane genotypes viz., B 34-104, Isd 28, Isd 32, Isd 35, Isd 37, CO 846, I 95-01, I 112-01, I 53-94 and I 486-99 were used as treatments but in 2010-11 six promising sugarcane genotypes viz., viz., B 34-104, CO 846, Isd 37, Isd 32, Isd 28, and I 486-99 were used as treatments in the study. Results revealed that all the growth parameters Results revealed that all the growth parameters were influenced significantly in different genotypes grown without N-fertilizer.  In respect of yield, they followed the trend: Clone CO 846&gt; B 34-104&gt; Isd 37&gt; Isd 32&gt;  I 486-99&gt; Isd 28 .Among the genotypes, Clone CO 846, B 34-104 and  Isd 37 showed higher yield of 101.20, 88.77 and 81.05  tha-1 in 2009-10cropping season, but in 2010-11  they followed the trend: Clone B 34-104&gt; CO 846&gt; Isd 32&gt; Isd 37&gt; Isd 28&gt; I 486-99.Among the genotypes, Clone B 34-104 showed higher yield of 127.9 tha-1 having no urea fertilizer, which might have the ability to fix atmospheric nitrogen through BNF with the found gram negative bacteria. However, further comprehensive microbiological studies are required to identify those bacteria and results.\r\nResults on the yield and yield contributing parameters are presented. The highest germination was recorded in Isd 37 50.89%, 43.87% in 2009-10 and 2010-11 respectively and the lowest was recorded in Isd 28 (32.98%) in 2009-10 but in 2010-11 from CO 846 (23.73%)  at 90 days of plantation. The highest millable cane 138.4 tha-1 and 166&times;103 tha-1  in 2009-10, 2010-11 respectively were found from CO 846 and B 34-104 which was statistically significant with other sugarcane genotypes. The significantly higher cane yield 101.2 tha-1   and 127.9 t ha-1 in 2009-10, 2010-11 respectively were found from CO 846, B 34-104 respectively and the second highest cane yield 88.77 tha-1,  117.5 t ha-1 in 2009-10, 2010-11 respectively were found from B 34-104, CO 846 respectively. However the lowest cane yield 46.85 t ha-1, 75.19 t ha-1 in 2009-10, 2010-11 respectively were found from Isd 28.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\nThe clones B 34-104 and CO 846 showed better performances in producing cane yield and other yield attributes in 2009-10 and 2010-11 cropping season under N-stressed condition in field where no nitrogenous fertilizer was applied', 'Sugarcane, Biological Nitrogen Fixation, Treatments, Genotypes', 'World Bank', 9026070, 6513583, 1692830, '', 'Workshops', 0, 'Soil Microbiology', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
(1178, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Soils and Nutrition Division', 'Program', 'Coordinated Project on Soil Fertility and Fertilizer Management for Crops and Cropping Pattern (BSRI Component)\r\n', 'Ishurdi, Jamalpur, Joypurhat, Chapainawabjong (Shibjong).', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', 'i) To find out optimum and economic doses of fertilizers for sugarcane and intercrops (potato, onion and garlic).\r\nii) To verify and update the national fertilizer recommendation guide\r\n', 'Treatments: Eight different treatments included in the study for sugarcane and intercrops at each experiment. These are as follows:\r\nT1 = STB 100% NPKSZn\r\nT2 = T1 + 25% N\r\nT3 = T1 + 25% NP\r\nT4 = T1 + 25% NK\r\nT5 = T1 + 25% PK\r\nT6 = T1 + 25% NPK\r\nT7 = 75% of T1\r\nT8 = Control\r\nTable 1. Effect of fertilizer treatments on the yield of potato intercropped with sugarcane\r\nTreatments Tuber yield of potato (t/ha)\r\nJamalpur-1	Jamalpur-2	Joypurhat	Ishurdi\r\nT1 = STB 100% NPKSZn	11.47 abc	7.16 c	15.61 a	8.60 ab\r\nT2 = T1 + 25% N	11.24 bc	9.49 b	14.49 a	8.40 ab\r\nT3 = T1 + 25% NP	11.64 abc	7.02 c	16.66 a	7.76 abc\r\nT4 = T1 + 25% NK	12.09 ab	7.53 c	16.84 a	8.64 ab\r\nT5 = T1 + 25% PK	12.85 ab	9.02 b	15.75 a	8.96 ab\r\nT6 = T1 + 25% NPK	13.95 a	10.76 a	16.94 a	9.28 a\r\nT7 = 75% of T1	9.71 c	7.00 c	15.16 a	7.16 bc\r\nT8 = Control	6.56 d	5.21 d	11.10 b	6.24 c\r\nLSD(5%)	2.12	1.00	2.51	1.81\r\nT1= N 180P38 K170 S20 Zn5.6 (sugarcane) and N73 P11 K65 S4 Zn2  (potato) at Jamalpur-1\r\nT1= N183 P18 K170 S20 Zn4.5 (sugarcane) and N75 P5 K65 S3.5 Zn1.8 (potato) at Jamalpur-2\r\nT1= N171 P25 K127 S16 Zn3.5 (sugarcane) and N85 P7 K48 S3 Zn1.7 (potato) at Joypurhat \r\nT1= N177 P55 K107 S15 Zn3.7 (sugarcane) and N57 P23 K32 S5 Zn1.7 (potato) at Ishurdi\r\nCrop: Sugarcane; variety : Isd 39 and Potato; variety : Cardinal\r\nSalient findings: The highest intercrop (potato) yield (13.95,10.76,16.94&amp; 9.28) was recorded from T6 treatment where 100% NPKSZn  and additional 25% NPK was applied on the basis of soil test value which was statistically significant over control at all the locations.  The lowest yield data was recorded in control plot ', ' Intercropping in sugarcane with potato, garlic, onion and vegetable is a common practice in cane growing countries. Intercropping has been recognized as a potential system for augmenting the productivity over space and time in subsistence farming situations. Sugarcane is a long duration and widely spaced crop and up to 120 days the canopy does not cover the vacant space in between the rows, as such there is ample scope to grow short- duration intercrops. Due to complementary effect of different crops when grown together, making better use of resources ultimately helps in productivity of sugarcane. Hence, under the project we conducted three experiments at four locations. In these experiments we cultivate potato, onion and garlic as intercrop with sugarcane. Potato, onion and garlic were harvested and data was recorded properly. From the intercrop data we observed positive impact of fertilizer management on basis of soil test value. Incase of sugarcane we recorded only germination and tiller data, because sugarcane is a long duration crop, it needs 12-14 months from planting to harvesting. Data of other parameters  ie. millable cane stalks, cane height, cane girth, yield of sugarcane and recoverable sucrose of cane will be collected   at harvest and determination of N, P, K, S,  Zn contents of cane leaves will be analyzed   at 240 -280 days after plantation. The crop condition is satisfactory.', 'Sugarcane, Potato, Onion, Garlic, Parameters.', 'World Bank', 6748000, 1692830, 0, '', 'Training', 160, 'Soil Fertility', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
(1179, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Pathology Division', 'Program', 'Effect of Compost Tea Supplemented with bio-agent Trichoderma spp. in Controlling Soil-borne Diseases of Sugarcane and Enhancement of its Productivity', 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute (BSRI), Ishurdi, Pabna ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '', '30-06-2012', '1.To control sett and root rot diseases of sugarcane.\r\n2.To improve rhizosphere of sugarcane with soluble nutrients and beneficial microbes and improvement of root growth.\r\n3.To increase the yield of cane and sugar.\r\n4.To make sustainable sugarcane cultivation.\r\n5.To make country sufficient in sugar production.', 'Trichoderma harzianum was collected from soil, isolated, cultured and maintained in the artificial media since October 11. Compost tea was prepared with farm yard manures, leafy grasses &amp; molasses. All three components are mixed together and are kept in the jute sac (used and old) and finally emerged in the water in large barrel.  Every 2 days interval the sacs were stirred for mixing the extract with water. This extract is called Compost tea. After 5 days, Trichoderma harzianum were mixed in the compost tea for its mass production as well as to brew the extract. After 10 days, the compost tea supplement with Trichoderma harzianum is ready to use. Compost tea and other treatments have been applied every 1 month interval. The following treatments are maintained to compare the effectiveness of compost tea supplemented with Trichoderma harzianum:T0   Control (seeds treatment in 0.1% solution of Bavistin 50WP before plantation). T1   Seed treatment and soil drenching with Trichoderma harzianum suspension. T2   Seed treatment and soil drenching with Compost tea.T3   Seed treatment and soil drenching with compost tea supplemented with Trichoderma harzianum. Sugarcane variety Isd 40 has been employed to carry out the experiment. After 60 days of planting, germination of sugarcane setts has been recorded on 15 January, 2012. Data on germination, no. of millable cane and yield were taken.', 'Times New Roman', 'Compost Tea, Trichoderma harzianum, Sugarcane.', '', 300000, 300000, 0, '', 'Field days', 0, 'Pathology', 'Sugarcane', '', '', '');
