(1180, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Dreeding Division', 'Program', 'Implementation Programme of Action Plans on Pulses, Oilseeds and Spices ', 'BSRI Head Quarter, Ishurdi, Pabna.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-06-2005', '30-06-2008', '', '30-06-2008', 'To increase oil seed production as intercrop with sugarcane ', 'Sl. No.	Line Items	Locations	Proposed Work Plan\r\n1. Field       Demonstration	Pabna, Kushtia, Chuadanga, Rajshahi, Jamalpur, Gazipur, Jaypurhat &amp;  Thakurgaon.	Eighteen demonstrations of oilseeds ( Mustard &amp; Sesame) as intercrop with sugarcane. \r\n2.Farmers Training	Pabna, Chuadanga, Rajshahi, Jamalpur, Gazipur &amp;  Thakurgaon.	 6 Batch ( 30 No per  batch)\r\n3.Field days Pabna, Kushtia, Rajshahi, Jamalpur, Gazipur &amp; Jaypurhat.6 Batch ( 50 No per batch)\r\n4.Co-ordinatin, Monitoring, Evaluation, Operating, Publication etc	Pabna, Kushtia, Chuadanga, Rajshahi, Jamalpur, Gazipur, Jaypurhat &amp;  Thakurgaon.\r\n', 'Sl.No.	Line Items	Locations	Achievement\r\niField Demonstration	Pabna, Kushtia, Chuadanga, Rajshahi, Jamalpur, Gazipur, Jaypurhat &amp;  Thakurgaon.	Eighteen demonstrations of oilseeds ( Mustard &amp; Sesame) as intercrop with sugarcane have been performed .\r\nii.	Farmers Training	Pabna, Rajshahi, Jamalpur, Gazipur  &amp;  Thakurgaon.	 Training of 5 Batch ( 30 No per  batch) have been done.\r\niv.	Field days	 Kushtia, Jamalpur &amp; Jaypurhat 	Field days of 3 Batch ( 50 No per batch)  have been done.\r\nv.Co-ordinatin, Monitoring, Evaluation, Operating, Publication etc	Pabna, Kushtia, Chuadanga, Rajshahi, Jamalpur, Gazipur, Jaypurhat &amp;  Thakurgaon.	 Monitoring &amp; evaluations have been done in all locations.\r\n', 'Oil seeds, Sugarcane, Demonstration, Intercrops.', 'BARC', 461000, 461000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 480, 'Varietal Improvement', 'Oil Seed', '', '', ''),
(1181, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Breeding Division', 'Program', 'Development of Sugarcane Varieties Through Somatic Hybridization', 'BSRI Head Quarter, Ishurdi, Pabna.', 'High', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-06-2005', '30-06-2006', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2006', '. Determination of most suitable explants for isolation of protoplast culture. \r\n         2. Optimization of protoplast culture condition \r\n            3. Fusion of protoplast \r\n        4. Regeneration of hybrid plants\r\n       5  Selection of somatic hybrid plants.\r\n', 'PLANT TISSUE SOURCE\r\n 	      \r\n		Young leaf tissue viz. mesophyll tissue, root tip and two to three months old calli of sugarcane varieties will be used as plant materials. \r\n\r\nISOLATION OF PROTOPLAST FROM LEAF/ROOT TIP\r\n         Explants (leaf pieces and young root tips) will be surface sterilized by immersing in 10% Nahypocloride for 20 minutes. After three times washing with distill water, leaf pieces will be peeled and pretreated with enzyme mixture (macerozyme 0.5%, potassium dextram sulphate 0.3% in 13% mannitol at pH 5.8). The explants will be cut into different sizes and incubated in different enzyme combinations and concentrations at 90 rpm shaking rates at 37oC temperature. After incubation, materials will be passed through a mesh sieve and transferred to centrifuge tube. The protoplast pellet will be washed out for several times and finally resuspended with mannitol. \r\n\r\nISOLATION OF PROTOPLAST FROM CALLUS\r\na) Initiation of Callus : For callus initiation leaf sheath of the said varieties will be culture in MMS agar medium with 2,4-D and NAA. The culture will be maintained at 25&plusmn;10C for 12hrs. under mild room light condition. Three to four weeks old callus will be subcultured on fresh agar medium.\r\n\r\nb) Rapidly growing callus will be suspended in enzyme solution and shaken. The mixture (protoplast + enzyme) will be passed through nylon mesh to remove undigested cells. The filtrate will be transferred in tube and centrifuged for pelleted protoplasts. After centrifugation, protoplast will be washed twice in mannitol solution.\r\n\r\nFUSION OF PROTOPLAST\r\n		Parental protoplast will be adjusted at 1X105/ml CPW 13M solution, and will be mixed in different ratios. After settle, few drops protoplast will be mixed with  300-450&micro;l PEG solution. PEG and protoplast solution will be connected by making a line with micropipette tip, and incubated for 20-25 mins. at 18oC. The fused material will be washed in washing solution, resuspended and centrifuged for 3 minutes. Then the fused protoplast will be dispensed into the centre of two petridishes and solidified in agar solution medium. Finally, the material will be embedded in MSP liquid medium and sealed with parafilm.   \r\n\r\nTREATMENTS:\r\n\r\n1)  Macerozyme + Cellulase\r\n2) Cellulase + Pectinaze \r\n3) NaNO3 / NaCO3 solution\r\n4) MS + Auxin + Cytokinin.\r\n\r\nDATA TO BE COLLECTED:\r\n\r\n1) Days to callus initiation from protoplast\r\n2) Days to shoot initiation\r\n3) No. of shoot / culture\r\n4) No. of root per shoot\r\n\r\n\r\nWORK ELEMENTS :\r\n\r\n1. Parent selection and tissue collection\r\n2. Separation of single cell using different enzyme \r\n3. Nacket protoplast development\r\n4. Culture of protoplast for callus formation\r\n5. Fusion of protoplast\r\n6. Development of hybrid protoplast\r\n7. Callus and plant development.\r\n', 'Young leaf tissue and root tips of sugarcane have been treated with Macerozyme for protoplast isolation. At the same time cell suspension of fragil callus was centrifuged and decant was treated with enzyme solution (0.5% cellulase + 0.5% macerozyme + 0.35 mM KH2PO4+ 3mM CaCl2). After treatment tissue maceration was occurred but cell wall was not dissolved which hampered the protoplast fusion.  ', ', Callus, Cell wall, Protoplast, Somatic hybridization ', 'BARC', 30000, 30000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Varietal Improvement', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1182, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Breeding Division', 'Program', 'Development of Somaclonal Plant Using Inflorescence/Somatic Tissue of Sugarcane', 'BSRI Head Quarter, Ishurdi, Pabna.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-06-2005', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', 'To develop somaclonal variant plant for higher cane and sugar yield, and red rot resistant flowering variety. \r\n         2. To select and standardize media composition, growth regulator and other chemical \r\n             and physical factors for callus formation, shoot proliferation, rooting responses and \r\n             growth.    \r\n            3. To acclimatize regenerated plant in the soil. \r\n        4. To compare the in vitro field grown plants with donor plants.\r\n', 'The experiment was carried out in the in vitro germplasm laboratory    of BSRI, Ishurdi, Pabna. Different aged of inflorescence/ somatic tissues as explants were collected from field grown plants at different times. General aseptic techniques concerning in vitro culture of plant tissue and organ culture was followed. The explants were disinfected using 0.1% HgCl2 or NaHCl2. Later on, the materials were washed with distill water and the inflorescence was taken out through opening of flag leaf. Mercuric chloride or Hypochlorite was used to disinfect the somatic tissues after collecting from the field. MS (Murashige and Skoog, 1962) medium and its modification was used for somatic tissue and inflorescence culture supplemented with auxin in different concentrations for callus formation. After callus formation from the explant, the culture was kept for shoot initiation and elongation. Then it was transferred in shoot multiplication media and finally in rooting media. Normally, culture was grown on medium having carbon source (1-3%), 0.6% gelling agent (agar) and pH was set at 5.7 with 0.1N NaOH or 0.1N HCl. Later on, plantlets were potted in glasshouse prior to acclimatize in natural conditions. Finally, newly developed plantlets were transplanted in the field. For red rot disease rating the somaclones  were inoculated against red rot isolates. Germination , tiller, millable cane, cane yield and sugar yield, pol % cane , field brix were recorded for comparison with the donor plant.  \r\nTreatments:\r\n 1) MS/Modified MS+ Auxin (2,4-D)\r\n 2) MS+ Auxin (IBA, IAA and NAA)+ Cytokinin (BA and Kn)\r\n 3)  MS+ Auxin (IBA and NAA)\r\n\r\nData  collected:\r\n1) Days of callus initiation\r\n2) Regeneration of shoot\r\n3) Number of shoot initiation per explant\r\n4) Days of shoot initiation\r\n5) Number of root per shoot\r\n         6) Recording of comparative morphological variation of regenerated plant with donor \r\n              plants. \r\n', 'To produce somatic variant plant for desire characters such as disease resistant, high cane and sugar yield, the somatic tissues of the varieties K 84-200, Sl 92-83, Sl 17-03, Sl 88-116, VMC 84-224,  VMC 84-524 and VMC 354 were cultured in vitro in 2,4-D supplemented modified MS medium for callus initiation. The callus was cultured for shoot formation in shooting medium and then rooted in rooting medium. Among different concentration of hormone used in shooting medium, only BA 1.0 mg/l + NAA o.5 mg/l supplemented MS medium showed the better responses. After satisfactory multiplication, the in vitro micros hoots showed better rooting in MS medium supplemented with 5.0 mg/l NAA. After hardening in vitro derived somatic plantlets were planted in the field for variant selection. Besides this, under R1 generation higher germination was recorded for somatic lines of Isd 17 (72%), Isd 18 (69%), BS 96 (64%) and Co 1158 (78%).  After 120 days of plantation better tiller/ha10-3 were155, 180, 125 and 188 for the lines of Isd 17, Isd 18, BS 96 and Co 1158, respectively. The varieties LJ-C, Isd 18, Co 1158 and Ni 8 are high yielding and high in sucrose content. Sometime the varieties   Isd 18, Co1158 and Ni 8 are found susceptible to red rot disease. Another variety Isd 32 is high yielder but medium in low in sucrose content. To produce somatic variant plant for desire characters, somatic tissues of these varieties were cultured in 2,4-D supplemented modified MS medium for callus initiation. Besides, for desired variation the somatic tissues of BS 96, PR 1000 and Isd 17 were also cultured in high conc.of 2,4-D supplemented medium. After callusing, these were transferred in different hormone supplemented MS medium for shoot formation, multiplication and finally in rooting medium. Under Ro, R2, R3, R4, R5 and R6.generations 879, 21, 8, 5, 8, and 4 regenerated lines are being maintained in the field for observation and   screening for diseases. The germination of 58 regenerated lines of K 84-200, Sl 92-83, Sl 17-03, Sl 88-116, VMC 84-224, VMC 84-524 and VMC 88-354 were recorded for evaluation. In R4 generation one regenerated line R4(1) of non-flowering variety Isd 18 was found to flower; whereas one regenerated line R4 (2) of flowering variety Isd 16 did not  flower.', 'Sugarcane, Somitic tissue, Somaclone, Variant', 'BARC', 330000, 330000, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Varietal Improvement', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1183, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Pathology Division', 'Project', 'Evaluation of Chweing of varieties of Sugarcane and clean seed production.', 'BSRI farm, Ishurdi. Noorbug farm, Joydebpur, Gazipur.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '1. To find out and collect the chewing type sugarcane varieties being cultivated in different regions of the country.\r\n2. Screening of preliminary recommended suitable chewing varieties region wise against pest and diseases under natural condition and chewing quality.\r\n3. To produce and multiply disease free clean seed cane of chewing varieties\r\n4. Distribution of clean seed among the cane growers for rapid spread of the chewing cane to meet up the country''s demand.\r\n5. To acquaint advance sugarcane growers with modern technique of sugarcane cultivation through demonstration and training.\r\n', 'a.Natural resistance for major disease like red rot, wilt, smut, white leaf, leaf scald and top rot were recorded in ta schedule format. Besides, artificial inoculation by Collectotrichum falcatum, the red rot organism were made at BSRI farm Ishurdi and Noorbag Farm, Joydebpur, Gazipur.\r\nb.Chewing quality as regards sweetness of cane ( brix % by hand refractometer),  rind hardness nodal hardness, fibre softness, external appearance, length and breadth of cane and finally assessment on market demand was made.\r\nc.Treatment of seedcane of selected chewing varieties was done by MHAT at 54 C for 2 hours with above 95% relative humidity or hot water treatment at 50 C for 30 minutes followed by Bavistin/Knowing treatment at 0.1% solution for 30 minutes.\r\nd.For BSRI part, the experiments were set up at 2 locations with 11 varieties ( 16 with duplication) in RCB design with 3 replications having plot size of 48 (8x6) m2. For each variety 330 settlings were required including extra 7% for gap filling and total 350 settlings per variety ere distributed for each of two location. \r\n', 'Two experiments were set up at BSRI farm, Ishurdi and Noorbag horticultural farm, Joydebpur, Gazipur. Out of 22, 11 varieties, namely Amrita, Bonpara Gandary, Co. 208, Co. 419, Co. 527 Gazipur. Gandary, Isd 24, Kazla, Khoai, Misrimala and Turg Gandary which are commonly reported to have good chewing quality were planted at both the farms in RCB design with 3 replications by spaced transplanting (STP) method during the crop season 1999-2000.\r\nAfter transplanting, the clump establishment was found most satisfactory in all the chewing varieties. However, the lower clump establishment of 81.70% and 87.85% was observed in the  important chewing varieties Co 208 and Bonpara Gandary respectively. However, the varieties Amrita, Kazla and Misrimala produced higher yield like other varieties due to robust cane and Co. 527 due to its high population of millable cane. In 5 demonstration plots of different regions, the varieties Amrita, Bonpara G., Co 208, Co 527 and Misrimala showed the yield ranging from 110.15 to 184.47 20.64 to 127.39, 36.60 to 113.77 87.19 to 189.00 and 97.80 to 113.29 metric tones respectively. \r\nBased on 8 important criteria for selection of chewing quality cane, the varieties Co. 208, Bonpara, G. And Amrita, ranked the 1st, 2nd 3rd polistion. The varieties Co 527 and misrimala jointly the 4th polotion and Kazla 5th position. On the basis of the rank order, the varietyes Co. 208, Bonpara G., Amrita, Co. 527,m Misrimala and Kazla resulted 10.36,m 8.31, 9.25, 10.18, 9.29 and 9.12% recovery respectively in the month of October and considered as early maturing variety. Other than the varieties suitable for chewing, the rest of 16 collected varieties are mostly used to cultivate for juice making and gur production.\r\n', 'Sugarcane, seed production, Chweing varieties', 'BARC', 875000, 925114, -50114, 'Report', '', 0, 'Pathology', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1185, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Entomology', 'Project', 'On farm trial of Biological control for Sugarcane Borers', 'NRS, RSRS Madarganj, Thakurgaon and BSRI, Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute, Ishurdi, Pabna.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '31-12-1998', '30-11-2000', '01-01-1999', '31-12-2000', '1.	To finalize recommended dose/time the dose  rate/frequency of application of egg parasitoid trichogrmma chilonis in controlling early shoot borer (ESB), Rootstock borer (RSB) and Stem borer (SB) of sugarcane.\r\n2.	To study the feasibility of glass rearing Coroyara or commercial production schemes in future.\r\n3.	To find out better diet for the laboratory host Coroyra.\r\n4.	To arrange training/demonstration field day on NGO personnel and farmers on modern sugarcane cultivation with special emphasis on insect pest  control (Biological control) \r\n', 'The recommended control measures were as : Mechanical control (removal of infested plants through cutting), Cultural practices i.e. earthing up were followed, Application of Lorsban 15 G (at planting, March and July), Biological control i.e. release of parasitoid @ 50,000/ha/wk was carried out in Ishurdi site from mid February till September 2000 and at Thakurgaon from mid April to September 2000.\r\nFertilizer such as Urea, TSP, MP Gypsum, MgSo4, and ZnSo4 were applied according to the AEZ as per fertilizer recommendation guide published by BARC.\r\nData on pest infestation was taken from time to time from both the location to compare the performance of Trichogramma as bio-control agent over other treatment. \r\n', 'Biological control unit at both Ishurdi and Thakurgaon were modified to rear Coroyra and Trichogramma. To fulfil the objectives one laboratory experiment was carried out at Ishurdi with different food medium in 1999 and two field trials were set up in 1999-2000 cropping season for releasing Trichogramma in the experimental plot both at Ishurdi and Thakurgaon. Data on Germination percentage was higher in completed package plot (CPP) and Trichgramma release plot (TRP) than Check plot (CKP) at both the locations. Result showed that Trichogramma release plot and complete package plot were almost similar in lowering the pest infestation over check.\r\nYield record showed that (CPP) produced higher tonnage at both Ishurdi and Thakurgaon than TRP but CPP gave more return.\r\n', 'On firm trial, Biological control, Borers, Sugarcane', 'BARC', 1976000, 1976000, 0, 'Publication', 'Workshops', 30, 'Biotechnology', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1184, 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute', 'Pathology Division', 'Project', 'Screening Sugarcane Germplasms for Resistance to Red Rot wilt and Red Rot-wilt complex.', 'Bangladesh Sugarcane Research Institute, Ishurdi, Pabna', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-1989', '31-12-2000', '17-07-1998', '30-04-2001', '1.	To identify and select sugarcane germplasms having superior resistance against red rot to use as parent materials for hybridization purposes in breeding programme.\r\n2.	To identify and select sugarcane germplasms having resistance against, wilt disease to use as parent material for hybridization purpose in breeding programme.\r\n3.	To indentify and select sugarcane germplasm having combined resistance against red rot and wilt complex. \r\n4.	To collect, maintain and to evaluate the resistance of exotic and indigenous sugarcane germplasm against red rot, wilt and their combined complex to broaden the scope of hybridization for developing future hereditary resistant varieties to the aforesaid diseases. The sorted out resistant clones can be mutually exchange among the SAARC countries. \r\n', '1.	Disease resistance for red rot, wilt and red rot wilt complex were evaluated by taking data of inoculated canes on a) nodal transgression, b) lesion width, c) white spot present or absent, d) nodal infection and e) condition of cane tops.\r\n2.	One hundred and fifty flowering germsplasms were inoculated separately with mixed isolate of red rot, wilt and red rot wilt composite isolates in 3 separate plots.\r\n3.	Procedure: Random sampling design,   fifteen canes were inoculated, 3 separate side by side plots for red rot, wilt and both red rot-wilt complex were planted, area-0.73 ha, 12.5 meter plot for each clone and each diseases, plot limit- 12.5 x 150 sq. m for each disease,  Settling to settling 50 cm and row to row 1 m. 5 metric tons of seed rate/hectare, 4 border lines were planted with the resistant sugarcane clones along the side of the experimental plots, Total Experiment- 0.80 ha including border line.\r\n4.	Mechanised cultivation was made followed by one ploughing, 2 harrowing, labelling and trenching, Mechanised/chemical pest control measures were under taken.\r\n5.	Collection, planting and set up of the experiment of flowering germsplasms, collection of red rot and wilt affected cane samples, isolation preservation maintenance and inoculation of the pathogen. \r\n', 'The separate experiments were set up for secreeing 150 flowering germplasms against red rot, wilt and red rot-wilt complex at BSRI farm during the year 1998-1999 and 1999-2000. Seed materials of all the clones were treatment in hot water at 500 C for 30 minutes followed by chemical treatment in Bavistin solution (0.1%) for 30 minutes before planting in polybags for raising settling. The settling of all the clones were transplanted in the main field at the end of 4th week of January in both the years 1999 and 2000. In case of red rot, 12, 41, 39, 28 and 30 clones were found resistant (R), moderately resistant (MR), moderately susceptible (MS), susceptible (S) and highly susceptible (HS), respectively during 1998-1999, while during 1999-2000 crop season, 16, 18, 34, 57 and 25 clones were found R, MR, MS, S and HS respectively.', 'Screening, Germplasm, Red Rot, Rot-wilt, Resistance', 'BARC', 773200, 74731727, 25889, 'Report, Booklet', '', 0, 'Plant Production', 'Sugarcane', '', '', ''),
(1194, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Floricullture Division (HRC)', 'Project', 'Improvement of gladiolus quality and its adaptation', 'Gazipur; Burrirhat (Rangpur), Sonatola (Bogra) and Gadkhali (Jessore)', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '30-06-2014', 'i.	To improve quality and disseminate BARI released gladiolus varieties.\r\nii.	To increase the cultivation of gladiolus varieties and available to consumers.\r\niii.	To increase yield per unit area and farmers income.\r\n', 'Three experiments on On- Station Trial and one experiment on On-Farm Trial are going on at the Floriculture Division, Horticulture Research Centre (HRC), Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (HRC), Joydebpur, Gazipur; Burrirhat (Rangpur), Sonatola (Bogra) and Gadkhali (Jessore) to produce quality flower as well as quick dissemination and popularization of BARI released gladiolus variety.', 'This project is on going. So, abstract will be drawn after completion of the project.\r\n', 'Gladiolus, Growth Regulators, Promising line(s), Boron, Quality flower, Adaptive trial', 'BARC', 884000, 0, 0, 'Publication', 'Training', 60, 'Gladious', 'Flower', '', '', ''),
(1195, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Floriculture Division (HRC)', 'Program', 'Variability Association, Regulation of Flowering and Improvement of Gerbera Through Tissue Culture', ': HRC, BARI, Gazipur', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2010', '', '30-06-2010', 'i.To determine the morphological variability available in germplasm\r\nii.To enhance quality of flower \r\niii.To increase vase life of flower\r\n', 'Five experiments were carried out at the Floriculture Division, Horticulture Research Centre (HRC), Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (HRC), Joydebpur, Gazipur during Rabi season 2009-2010. \r\nTwenty eight genotypes of gerbera were included to study variabilities and identify morphological characteristics of gerbera genotypes.\r\nOne month age of tissue cultured BARI Gerbera-2 variety was included in this study with two protective structures (poly tunnel and polyhouse) including control (open field) for quality flower production. \r\nInfluence of different mulches (water hyacinth, rice bran, black polythene, cocodust, sawdust and control) on tissue cultured plantlet of BARI Gerbera-1 variety was studied.\r\nTissue cultured BARI Gerbera-1 plantlets were sprayed with aqueous solution of gibberellic acid @ 100, 150, 200 ppm; cycocel @ 300, 400, 500 ppm and maleic hydrazide @ 250, 500, 750 ppm. Thus, three growth regulators and three concentrations each of the regulators along with control formed 10 treatments variables. The growth regulators were sprayed on plant in the morning started after one month of planting at monthly interval for quality flower production. \r\nTen different concentration of vase solutions including sucrose, AgNO3 and citric acid on gerbera    (GJ-020) spikes were studied to increase vase life.\r\n', 'There was a great deal of variation observed among the genotypes in respect of plant height, flower number, stalk length, sucker number, vase life, flower colour , leaf colour etc. Considering cut flower production and quality aspects, BARI Gerbera-1, BARI Gerbera-2, GJ-013, GJ-022, GJ-023, GJ-024 and GJ-028 were recommended for commercial cultivation at Gazipur. \r\nThe plants grown under poly house attained best performance in respect of flower production and vase life of gerbera\r\nThe black polythene and cocodust were observed to be equally effective in producing maximum growth and quality flower production gerbera.\r\nThe GA3 @ 100 ppm performed better than other concentrations, where as, CCC at all concentrations had some adverse effect on plant and flower performances of gerbera.\r\nGerbera (GJ-020) spike treated with a mixture of 4% sucrose with 200 ppm AgNO3  and 25 ppm citric acid preserved the sticks in fresh form without excessive loss in quality as these treatment recorded the maximum vase life by increasing the water uptake and maintaining  higher fresh weight of flower.\r\n', 'Gerbera, Evaluation, Growth Regulators, Protective cultivation, Quality flower, Vase life', 'GOB', 400000, 400000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Gladious', 'Flower', '', '', ''),
(1196, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Plant Genetic Resources Centre', 'Project', 'Strengthening of Plant Genetic Resources Centre', 'BARI Head quarter : Joydebpur, Gazipur\r\nRegional station     : Jessore, Ishurdi, Jamalpur, Khagrachhari and Burirhat (Rangpur)   \r\nClonal Genebank  : Rajshahi, Jamalpur, Rahmatpur  (Barisal)  and  Jaintapur (Sylhet) \r\n', 'High', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-07-2004', '30-06-2008', '', '30-06-2009', 'To survey and prepare an inventory of Plant Genetic Resources (PGR) of cultivated plants and their wild relatives and medicinal plant also\r\nTo carryout and co-ordinate exploration and collection of plant genetic resources of diverse germplasm of cultivated plants and their wild relatives and naturally occurring species of economics Important in Bangladesh and abroad;\r\nTo develop ex-situ conservation (active and base collection) of PGR at genebank and in-situ conservation facilities at different Agro-Ecological zone of the country;\r\nTo characterize and evaluate for identification of accessions, gene transformation and enhancement of PGR;\r\nTo give due attention for improvement popularization and research and development of under utilized plants;\r\nTo carryout and co-ordinate exchange and utilization of PGR in home and abroad;\r\nTo develop In-vitro and cryopreservation respository of PGR;\r\nTo maintain and co-ordinate maintenance of PGR of economics plants in the form of propagating material other than seed e.g. annual and perennial planting in the filed genebank;\r\nTo carryout and co-ordinate research on improvement of certain industrial plants like medicinal and aromatic plants;\r\nTo develop human resources for Scientific backup to the PGR conservation and management;\r\nTo document available information of PGRC for users;\r\nTo maintain liaison with national and international organization in relation to PGR;\r\nTo create awareness about the importance of PGR and to promote its traditional and diverse use VIS a vis protection of environments;\r\nTo establish right on PGR and to protect PGR from biopiracy;', 'To conserve the collected PGR and to maintain a supply chain of PGR to the stakeholders for sustainable utilization to develop high yielding modern crop varieties, Exploration and collection, Characterization and evaluation, Conservation, and Documentation were done. The broad research programme under the project is envisaged below: \r\n\r\n          A. Exploration and collection\r\ni)	Cereals, Pulses, Oil seeds,Vegetables, Fruits, Spices\r\nAromatic, ornamental and medicinal plants, Economic wild species and Indigenous knowledge;\r\nCharacterization and evaluation\r\nMorphological characterization, Molecular characterization, Genetic fingerprinting and Regeneration Conservation\r\n\r\nEx situ conservation, In situ conservation, In vitro/cryopreservation, Field genebank and Monitoring of the conserved accessions\r\nDocumentation: Passport information, characterization and evaluation information, conservation information, PGR exchange and distribution information\r\n', 'Plant Genetic Resources. (PGR) are the valuable resources of a country. PGR are the basic raw materials to meet up the present and future need of crop improvement programme. But these are being depleted rapidly from the country through high population pressure, massive deforestation, habitat loss, natural calamities, etc. which will adversely affect the well being of the people. Due to implementation of the Project titled Strengthening of Plant Genetic Resources Centre a modern infra-structure for plant genetic resources management has been created and a momentum has also been created to save valuable and essential PGR from extinction. A survey was conducted to know the distribution and availability of PGR. Fortysix exploration and collection mission were carried out in different parts of Bangladesh by PGR scientists to collect PGR of cultivated crops and their wild relatives. Ex situ conservation mid term (4-60C) and long term (-200C) conservation facilities has been developed; two lakhs samples will be conserved. For effective utilization of the present infra-structure and facilities as well as to save plant genetic resources future project are to be developed and executed.', 'PGR exploration, Collection, Characterization, Conservation, Utilization and Documentation and Pulses and Oilseeds, Cereals, Vegetable, Fruit', 'GOB', 2499, 2342, 0, 'Publication', 'Workshops', 1182, 'PGR exploration, Collection, Characterization, Conservation, Utilization and Documentation', 'Pulses and Oil seeds, Cereals, Vegetable, Fruits', '', '', ''),
(1197, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Plant Genetic Resources Centre', 'Project', 'Collection and Conservation of Indigenous Vegetable Germplasm', 'Chittagong Hill Tracts and Rajshahi Region', 'High', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-11-2009', '31-10-2011', '', '31-10-2011', 'To collect indigenous vegetable germplasm in Rajshahi division and CHT\r\nTo document the indigenous knowledge of the IVS utilization and cultivation\r\nTo establish community genebank among end users and providing training to them\r\n', 'Prior to make survey and collection programs three training programs were conducted for both officers and farmers under Rangamati, Bandarban and Chapainawabganj districts. Later on, germplasm collection expedition teams went to various selected upazilas of each of the above mentioned districts. Each germplasm expedition team made survey program during germplasm collection period. At last many rare indigenous vegetable germplasm were collected from vegetable growing farmers.', 'After the inception of the project progressive farmers from both project sites (CHT &amp; Rajshahi regions) were made contact priory for their cooperation regarding survey as well as collection for rare indigenous vegetable germplasm from those regions. Survey was conducted by interviewing selected farmers. Interviewing was completed following a questionnaire prescribed by Plant Genetic Resources Centre (PGRC), BARI. During project operation period six training programs both for officers and farmers regarding vegetable cultivation practices, their harvesting and preservation were successfully completed at Khagrachari, Bandarban and Rangamati hill districts and Rajshahi and Chapainawabganj districts. Later on, germplasm expedition teams with their full preparation went at all six aforesaid districts. They made survey regarding indigenous vegetable germplasm in various upazillas of all six districts by interviewing enthusiastic farmers in respect of cultivation practices of vegetable growing. The teams finally succeeded to collect rare indigenous vegetable germplasm from several upazillas of all the six districts mentioned above. Of All the collected materials most of them were orthodox seeds. Some of the collected materials were under live plants. Some of the collected materials as seeds were regenerated in micro plots of PGRC, BARI.  Afterwards, regenerated seeds were conserved in conservation unit of PGRC, BARI for future research activity. In the conservation unit all the collected seed materials have been conserved in medium term cool room for future reference.', 'PGR exploration, collection, characterization, conservation, utilization documentation andIndigenous Vegetable, ', '', 20, 10, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 330, 'PGR exploration, Collection, Characterization, Conservation, Utilization and Documentation', 'Indigenous Vegetable', '', '', ''),
(1198, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Plant Genetic Resources Centre', 'Project', 'Characterization of Important Plant Genetic Resources: BARI component', 'Gazipur, Kishorganj, Norshindi, Barisal, Sylhet, Rajshahi, Dinajpur, Tagorgaon, Ishurdi, Jessore ', 'High', 'Basic', 'On-going', '01-10-2011', '30-09-2013', '', '30-09-2013', 'Identification of the degree of morphological and genetic variation of crops within cultivars \r\nEstablishment of permanent database for documentation of crops\r\nEstablishment of Intellectual Property Rights (IPR)', 'Work program (WP) 1:  Recruitment of manpower and input collection\r\nWork program (WP) 2:  Collection of original seed/leaf of GIs crops and germplasm\r\nWork program (WP) 3:Optimization of protocol for morphological and molecular characterizations, and development of working manual and data book for individual crop. \r\nMorphological characterization of GI crops varieties (Mango, bel, litchi, banana, lemon and satkara, Burmese grape, betel leaf, golden apple, and mung bean). \r\nMolecular characterization of BARI mandated GIs crops with released varieties [(Mango (9) and Mung Bean (19)] will be done. Molecular characterization of other GI crops, which will be characterized morphologically, will also be done if possible.\r\nWork program (WP) 4: Statistical analysis and documentation by computer database\r\nWork program (WP) 5: Arrangement of Workshop/Seminar and Project completion report\r\n', 'Morphological characterization of assigned crop has been initiated. Passport information and plant and leaf characteristics of most of the crop have been recorded. Technical progress achieved so far is presented below.Four GIs (viz. Kadmi Lichu, Mongalbari Lichu, Rajshahi Local and Bedana Lichu) and four released varieties (viz. BARI Lichu-1, 2, 3 &amp; 4) have been included in this programme. Rajshahi Local and Bedana Lichu have been released as BARI Lichu-1 and BARI Lichu-4, respectively. So, total number of genotypes to be characterized stands at six. One GI of burmese grape (local cultivar from Narsingdi) and one released variety (viz. BARI Lotkan-1) have been included in this programme. Eight GIs of mango (viz. Fazli, Langra, Gopalbhog, Khirsapat, Ashwina, Himsagar, Laxmanbhog and Surjapuri), nine released varieties (viz. BARI Aam-1to 9) and two parental lines (viz. Ashwina and M-3896) have been included in this programme. Laxmanbhog has been released as BARI Aam-2 and Ashwina is female parent of BARI Aam-4. So, total number of genotypes to be characterized stands at seventeen. Two GIs of golden apple (viz. Swarupkathi and  Kuriana) two released varieties (viz. BARI amra-1 and BARI amra-2) have been included in this programme', 'Resources and Biodiversity, Fruits, Pulses, Betelleaf', '', 100, 11, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 60, 'Genetic Resources and Biodiversity', 'Fruits, Pulses, Betelleaf', '', '', ''),
(1199, 'Soil Resources Development Institute', 'Correlation Section', 'Project', 'Minimizing Rice Yield Gap', '75 Upazilas (25 district).', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'On-going', '01-01-2011', '31-12-2013', '', '31-12-2013', 'To maintain soil health/fertilizer through soil test based fertilizer use', 'Soil analysis and recommend fertilizer dozes', 'Rice is the main crops, about 80% agricultural land occupies to grow rice. Upshi Rice average grows per hector 7.00 ton but in the farmer level it less than 80 ton per hector. It is proved that on the basis of SRDIs Upazila Nirdeshika to follow Fertilizer Recommendation after soil test, it is possible to increase rice crop production 15-25% and its depend on appropriate time and quantity of fertilizer uses (SRDIs field research, B-Kha block, SRMAF project). An Information from BARI, Gazipur field research that it is possible to increase product per hector 1.5-2.0 by using modern technology. Alsoif it is possible to export our rice after our country demand if we increase our rice crop production. On the other hand we can grow pulses, oil seed, vegetable, fruit and pieces to proper land utilization.', 'Soil, Rice, Yield, Fertilizer.', 'GOB', 9300000, 7000000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fertilizer Recommemdation', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
(1200, 'Soil Resources Development Institute', 'Soil Testing Division', 'Project', 'Soil Fertility and Fertilizer Management for Crops and Cropping Pattern', 'Fultala, Metro, Rupsha, Dumuria and Batiaghata upazilla of Khulna  (AEZ 11,12,13 &amp;14).', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', 'To determine the nutrient status of the saline soil and water in the study areas.\r\nExpt.1: Response of crops to fertilizer application in the Very Slightly Saline Soil of Fultala upazilla. \r\n- Soil samples will be collected based on land type from saline soils of Metro Thana,  Fultala and  Degholia upagilla of Khulna.\r\n- Site of soil sample &amp; water sample collection will be selected on the basis of Thana Nirdeshika.\r\n- A total of 500 soil  &amp;  water  samples will be collected from Metro, Fultala and Degholia upazilla of  Khulna.\r\n- Soil samples will be analyzed for nutrient content (pH, OM, EC, N, P, K, S Ca, Mg,  Cu, Fe,  Mn, Zn).\r\nExpt. 2: Response of crops to fertilizer application in  the  Metro Thana of Khulna Soils. \r\nLocations : Metro Thana of Khulna, AEZ-13.\r\nSites : Taligati, Metro Thana.\r\nCropping pattern: Boro Rice (BRRI dhan 28)-Fellow-T. Aman  (Bina dhan 7).\r\nDesign:Randomized Complete Block Design (RCBD)\r\n', 'Soil pH will be measured by glass electrode pH meter (McLean, 1982), organic carbon by wet oxidation method (Nelson and Sommers, 1982), total N by micro-Kjeldahl method (Bremner and Mulvaney, 1982), available P by Olsen method (Olsen and Sommers, 1982), exchangeable K &amp; Mg by IN NH4OAc, pH 7.0 extraction (Barker and Surh, 1982), available S by 0.15% CaCl2 extraction (Page et al., 1982), available Zn, Fe, Mn &amp; Cu by DTPA extraction (Lindsay and Norvell, 1978) and available B by MCP extraction followed by determination by azomethine-H  (Page et al., 1982). \r\nThe collected main produce (grain, tuber, curd) and by-product (straw, stover, residues)  from each plot will be dried in an oven at 65 0C for about 24 hours after which they will be ground by a grinding mill. Later the ground samples will be sieved through a 20-mesh sieve. The prepared samples will then be chemically analyzed for N, P, K, S and micronutrients following di acid digestion procedure (Jones and Case, 1990; Watson and Issac, 1990).\r\n', 'Bangladesh is one of the densely populated countries of the world. To meet the food grain \r\nrequirement for a growing population with limited land resources, an increasing pressure on the land is taking place without adequate compensation of the plant nutrient taken up from the soil. To increase yield per unit area the soil resources of Bangladesh have been exploited intensively without proper care. We are increasingly forced to meet up growing food needs from increases in yield from existing or even from shrinking land areas. In this process we are moving away from the traditional soil dependent agricultural to dynamic fertilizer dependant agriculture. In order to derive the maximum benefit, fertilizer should be applied in a judicious way. Coordinated Project on Soil Fertility and  Fertilizer  Management for Crops and   Cropping Patterns will be  helpful to find out optimum and economic fertilizer dose for different crops and cropping pattern at different AEZs of Bangladesh and also helpful to update the existing the FRG.\r\nSoil Resource Development Institute (SRDI) conducted survey in 1975, 2000 and 2009 to prepare maps delineating soil and water salinity in the coastal area and reports to support planning and implementation of agriculture. Some adaptive research has been conducted on farm pond technology, raise bed technology and conservation of soil moisture in dry period at Salinity Monitoring and Research Center (SMRC) of SRDI, Khulna. SRDI  have lab facilities for analysis of soil, water, plant and fertilizer. Coordinated Project on Soil Fertility and  Fertilizer  Management for Crops and   Cropping Patterns has given an opportunity to utilize its lab experience and  field experience to find out the actual requirement of fertilizer for different crop growing in the saline  areas.   \r\nSeven experiments were conducted in five upazilla of Khulna district which are Mosiali of Fultala Upazilla, Teligati of Metro Thana, Gobindakhati and Kapalidanga of Dumuria Upazilla, Jabusha of Rupsha Upazilla and Ghagramari of Batiaghata Upazilla. Seedlings of Boro (BRRI dhan28 &amp; BRRI dhan47) were transplanted at the first and second week of January and harvested at third and fourth week of April. Except rice Sesame were grown in Kapalidanga of Dumuria and Ladys Finger and Sweet Gourd were grown in Ghagramari of Dumuria Upazilla. Experimental plot prepared with 8 treatments and 3 replications. Crop of the all experimental areas were harvested. Statatistical analysis was done. After harvest soil samples were collected. Straw, grain and soil samples were sent to laboratory for analysis\r\n', 'Soil Fertility, Fertilizer, Fertilizer Management', 'GOB', 7882130, 6000000, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 0, 'Soil Fertility and Fertilizer Management', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
(1201, 'Soil Resources Development Institute', 'Central Laboratory', 'Project', 'Coordinated Project on Arsenic in soil-water plant system', 'Chandina under Comilla district, Kochua under Chandpur, Veramara under Kustia district', 'High', 'Basic', 'On-going', '01-04-2010', '31-03-2013', '', '31-03-2013', 'To asses the Arsenic status different source of irrigation water.To asses the Arsenic status in paddy soils.\r\nTo asses the Arsenic content in rice grain. To develop database on As contamination in soils and water of study area.To prepare Map on Arsenic status of Chandina, Kochua and Veramara Upazila', 'At the beginning of the project, the research team and project staffs finalized sample selection site of 3 upazillas  likeVeramara of Khustia, Kachua of Chandpur &amp; Chandina of Comilla.  The research team and project staffs have selected study sites (Villages) on the basis of benchmark survey findings and GIS.\r\nB.Benchmark survey:\r\nA benchmark survey in the project area (Veramara of Khustia, Kachua of Chandpur &amp; Chandina of Comilla) has been conducted on water and soil quality in respect of As contamination through analysis of water of tube wells and soil samples. Arsenocosis patients will also be identified in the project areas. Both year of installation and depth of tube wells have been considered during the selection of the tube wells. Rice grain samples have been collected from the command area of the study tube wells. The upazila wise soil arsenic maps have been prepared with benchmark survey data and it will be included with the benchmark survey report.\r\nC. Water, Soil and plant samples collection and analysis\r\nat the beginning of the project, 10 irrigation sources like STW and DTW of each union have been selected for water sample collection. Soil and rice grain (Boro &amp; T. Aman) samples were collected from the same spot. The samples of soil, water and grain have been analyzed by ICP flowing world wide standard method.\r\n', 'There is a potential danger that undesirable amount of As could be accumulated in the rice grain, the staple food grain in Bangladesh, due to irrigation of rice field with As contaminated water. However, the extent of contamination level varies from area to area. Unfortunately, little is known about the impact of As contaminated irrigated water on rice yield and grain quality and ultimately on the health of the millions of the rice consumers in Bangladesh. The database information regarding soil As status, As content at different depths of ground water and its mitigation ways are lacking. So, a survey and field study carried out to find out the level of As in different depth of As contaminated groundwater level and analyses of rice plant (root, straw and grain). Information on arsenic contamination in soil, plant and water are very limited in Bangladesh. No systematic research work has yet been done on the assessment of arsenic contamination in the soil-water-plant system and its impact on crop production in the country. With a view to generate information on Arsenic status in soils and irrigation water of different locations of Bangladesh, the coordinated project on Arsenic in Soil-Water- Plant System was formulated. The information might be useful and can play a great role to minimize hazardous effect of this toxic element on crop productions, crop quality and human health of the country. To achieve the goal of the project Soil Resource Development Institute has collected 240 soil , 240 water samples as well as 300 rice grain samples from Chandina, Kochua and Veramara. Rice samples have been collected in both Boro and Aman season. The samples of soil, water and grain have been analyzed by ICP flowing world wide standard method. The findings of the study show that most of the soils of project area contain less than 20 ppm arsenic. The highest concentration of arsenic (25.96 ppm) has been found in Boro Koraia union of Kochua Upazila under Chandpur District. The water sample s from different locationsof the study area contain 0 to25.96 pmm arsenic. Findings og the study that irrigation water of STW contains more arsenic than irrigation water of DTW. The concentration of arsenic in rice grain of the study area varies from 0 to 1.77 pmm. It is to mention that local varieties of rice absorb more arsenic than HYV rice', 'There is a potential danger that undesirable amount of As could be accumulated in the rice grain, the staple food grain in Bangladesh, due to irrigation of rice field with As contaminated water. However, the extent of contamination level varies from area to area. Unfortunately, little is known about the impact of As contaminated irrigated water on rice yield and grain quality and ultimately on the health of the millions of the rice consumers in Bangladesh. The database information regarding soil As status, As content at different depths of ground water and its mitigation ways are lacking. So, a survey and field study carried out to find out the level of As in different depth of As contaminated groundwater level and analyses of rice plant (root, straw and grain). Information on arsenic contamination in soil, plant and water are very limited in Bangladesh. No systematic research work has yet been done on the assessment of arsenic contamination in the soil-water-plant system and its impact on crop production in the country. With a view to generate information on Arsenic status in soils and irrigation water of different locations of Bangladesh, the coordinated project on Arsenic in Soil-Water- Plant System was formulated. The information might be useful and can play a great role to minimize hazardous effect of this toxic element on crop productions, crop quality and human health of the country. To achieve the goal of the project Soil Resource Development Institute has collected 240 soil , 240 water samples as well as 300 rice grain samples from Chandina, Kochua and Veramara. Rice samples have been collected in both Boro and Aman season. The samples of soil, water and grain have been analyzed by ICP flowing world wide standard method. The findings of the study show that most of the soils of project area contain less than 20 ppm arsenic. The highest concentration of arsenic (25.96 ppm) has been found in Boro Koraia union of Kochua Upazila under Chandpur District. The water sample s from different locationsof the study area contain 0 to25.96 pmm arsenic. Findings og the study that irrigation water of STW contains more arsenic than irrigation water of DTW. The concentration of arsenic in rice grain of the study area varies from 0 to 1.77 pmm. It is to mention that local varieties of rice absorb more arsenic than HYV rice', 'BARC', 2484650, 2087868, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Soil, Water and Plant', 'Arsenic', '', '', '');
