(1202, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Plant Breeding Division', 'Project', 'Pyramiding salinity and submergence tolerance genes in to BRRI dhan49 through marker-assisted selection', 'BRRI Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '05-12-2011', '04-12-2013', '', '31-12-2013', '1. Introgression of SUB1 and SALTOL QTL into the genetic background of BRRI dhan49 through marker-assisted backcrossing\r\n2. Training of young scientists and strengthening capacity of newly established marker-assisted selection laboratory of plant breeding division of Bangladesh Rice Research Institute\r\n', 'a. Standard protocol for MABC will be followed\r\nb. Hybridization will be done for the cross combinations BRRI dhan49/BRRI dhan52 and BRRI dhan49/FL478 to obtain F1 seeds\r\nc. F1s will be backcrossed with recurrent parent to obtain around 200 BC1F1 seeds\r\nd. MABC activities will be going on in parallel for two population to introgress SUB1 and SALTOL into BRRI dhan49\r\ne. For each population, in BC1F1 generation, foreground, recombinant and background selection will be carried out using standard methodology followed for converting BR11 and best plant having maximum genetic background will be backcrossed to produce BC2F1 population (around 500 plants)\r\nf. Foreground and recombinant selection will further be carried out in BC2F1 population to find the best plant with maximum recipient alleles and heterozygous target QTLs (SUB1and SALTOL).\r\ng. The best plant of BC2F1 generation will be self-pollinated to produce BC2F2 population and BRRI dhan49-Sub1 and BRRI dhan49-Saltol will be identified in two of populations.\r\n', 'A project funded by NATP: Phase 1 of PIU, BARC has been undertaken with the objective to pyramid salinity and submergence tolerance genes into BRRI dhan49. The major purpose of this project is to introgression of SUB1 and Saltol QTL into the genetic background of BRRI dhan49 through marker-assisted backcrossing and training of young scientists and strengthening capacity of newly established marker-assisted selection laboratory of plant breeding division of Bangladesh Rice Research Institute. Total approved cost was Tk. 50,89,560/- (Taka Fifty lakh, eighty nine thousand five hundred and sixty only). For pyramiding salinity and submergence tolerance genes, FL478 and BRRI dhan52 (BR11-Sub1) were used as donors and BRRI dhan49 was used as recipient parent. Marker-Assisted Backcrossing technique was followed to Saltol along with Sub1 in the genetic background of BRRI dhan49 and the approach will be completed by BC2F2 generation. Fifty background markers were identified to check recovery of recurrent parent (BRRI dhan49) genome through background selection. Selection for target gene (Sub1-foreground selection) was carried out by using gene-based marker RM8300 for submergence tolerance in BRRI dhan49*4/ BRRI dhan52. A training program on Theoretical and Applied Molecular Breeding funded by NATP Saltol-Sub1 Project was held at Plant Breeding Division, BRRI on 24-29 September 2012. A total of 23 participants from NARS Institutes (BRRI, BARI, BINA, BSRI and BJRI) took part training program and successfully completed after final evaluation.', 'Rice, Saltol, Sub1, salinity, submergence and marker-assisted backcrossing', 'World Bank', 5089560, 0, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 23, 'Plant Breeding', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1203, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division', 'Project', 'Upscalling and adoption of hybrid dryer for quality grain seed production', 'Gazipur, Dinajpur, Rajshahi and Jessore', 'High', 'Strategic', 'Completed', '18-05-2009', '17-05-2011', '', '17-05-2011', 'i.To make modification of the existing hybrid dryer suitable for grain seeds drying\r\nii.To evaluate the technical performance of the dryer and test the seed quality\r\niii.To test and demonstrate the dryers in the farmers field \r\niv.To disseminate the dryer among the seed growers and traders through training and  workshop\r\n', 'This project was combinely carried out by Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division and Seed Technology Division of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute, Joydebpur, Gazipur-1701. Farm Machinery Postharvest Process Engineering Division was the leading organization and Seed Technology Division was the collaborative organization. The duration of the project was two years. First year was R&amp;D phase and second year was the dissemination phase. Engineering aspects of the dryer i.e. design, drawing, fabrication and performance tests were carried out in Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Divisional workshop and seed quality was evaluated in Seed Technology Division. \r\nThe hybrid dryer was fabricated at Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI) using the workshop and technical manpower facilities during 2009-10. This dryer also was tested in the laboratory using the laboratory facilities. Seed quality was tested in the Seed Technology laboratory using the laboratory facilities of Seed Technology Division of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute. Field level tests on grain seeds drying were conducted during 2010-2011. Three seed dryers were fabricated and installed in Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jessore, Regional Wheat Research Centre, Rajshahi and Wheat Research Centre, Dinajpur. The seed dryers were demonstrated to the farmers and small seed traders. During the field level tests, local Department of Agricultural Extension, BADC and Seed Testing Agency were included. \r\nThis project was combinely carried out by Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division and Seed Technology Division of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute, Joydebpur, Gazipur-1701.\r\nThe hybrid dryer was fabricated at Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI) using the workshop and technical manpower facilities during 2009-10. This dryer also was tested in the laboratory using the laboratory facilities. Seed quality was tested in the Seed Technology laboratory using the laboratory facilities of Seed Technology Division of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute. Field level tests on grain seeds drying were conducted during 2010-2011. Three seed dryers were fabricated and installed in Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jessore, Regional Wheat Research Centre, Rajshahi and Wheat Research Centre, Dinajpur. The seed dryers were demonstrated to the farmers and small seed traders. During the field level tests, local Department of Agricultural Extension, BADC and Seed Testing Agency were included.', 'A hybrid seed dryer (combination of solar energy and electric energy) was designed and constructed at Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Gazipur. The technical performance of the dryer was tested for drying of grain seeds and seed quality was evaluated during the period of 2010-2011. The reflected solar radiation was 53% of global solar radiation. The thermal efficiency of the collector was 28.73%. The dryer was tested for drying of paddy, wheat, maize and groundnut. Time required for drying of 250-300 kg of paddy, 250 kg of wheat, 350 kg of maize and 200 kg groundnut were found to be 17, 12, 16 and 20 hours, respectively. There were no significant differences in drying rates between top and bottom layers (12 cm depth) of paddy seeds. The dryer was tested and its field performance was evaluated in Jessore, Rajshshi and Dinajpur during the period of 2010-2011. Three dryers were fabricated and installed at Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jessore; Regional Wheat Research Centre, Rajshshi and Wheat Research Centre, Dinajpur. In all the locations, paddy seeds were dried. The field performance of the dryer was found satisfactory in terms of drying rate and seed quality. The benefit cost ratios (BCR) for drying of paddy seeds on variable and total cost basis were 1.47 and 1.40, respectively. The pay back period of the dryer was 0.44 year. Major portion of energy used in  hybrid dryer was solar energy and it is environment friendly.', 'Hybrid seed dryer, Solar energy, Performance, Solar radiation', '', 1800821, 1800821, 0, 'Publication, Report, Booklet', 'Training, Workshop', 140, 'Hybrid dryer', 'Quality Grain Seed Production', '', '', ''),
(1204, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division', 'Project', 'Design and adaptation of solar pump irrigation systems for ecofriendly environment', 'Gazipur, Jamalpur, Magura and Barisal', 'High', 'Strategic', 'On-going', '01-06-2010', '31-05-2013', '', '31-05-2013', '(i)Select the suitable solar pumps for different irrigation systems based on the results of base line survey.\r\n(ii) Test and evaluate of the technical performance of selected solar pumps for surface and ground water lifting.\r\n(iii) Install and test the appropriate solar pumps in the selected areas for different types of irrigations for rice and non-rice crops.\r\n(iv) Make economic analysis and socio-economic impacts study of solar pump irrigation in the selected areas of the project.\r\n', 'Five different types of solar pump were tested at different times, suction and delivery heads. The specifications of the selected solar pumps are given in Table 1. Among five solar pumps, two were locally designed and three were made by developed countries (USA, Australia and China). BARI designed solar pump was made with 800 W dc motor coupled with 0.5 hp locally made centrifugal pump. Dhaka University (DU) designed solar pump was made with ac motor, 0.5 hp centrifugal pump, inverter (1000 W), charge controller and battery (24 V, 200 AH). The USA made solar pump was 0.5 hp suitable for surface water lifting and Australia made submersible solar pump was same capacity but suitable for surface and ground water lifting. The China made pump was 2.2 hp motor capacities suitable for both surface and groundwater lifting. BARI, USA and Australia made solar pumps were operated by 600 W solar panels. On the other hand, DU and China made solar pumps were operated by 1000 W solar panels. During testing of solar pumps, solar radiation, panel voltage, current, power, suction head, delivery head and discharge were measured.\r\nThe solar pump was used for drip irrigation and furrow irrigation for tomato cultivation in the experimental field of FMPE division during rabi 2011-12. The soil type was clay loam. The plot size was 40 m &times; 13 m (520 m2). Six beds of tomato were irrigated by the drip method having three water tanks each of 500 liter water holding capacity. The drip sets were made with plastic pipes, water tank, capillary tubes, pegs etc. The tomato variety was BARI Tomato-14.Two rows of tomato were planted in each bed on 4 December, 2011. The age of seedlings was 31 days. Row to row and plant to plant distances were 60 cm and 40 cm, respectively. Cowdung 10.0 t/ha, urea 600 kg/ha, TSP 500 kg/ha, MP 200 kg/ha, zinc 10 kg/ha and boron 8 kg/ha were applied in tomato field. Total dose of cowdung, TSP, MP, zinc, boron and one third of urea (200 kg/ha) were applied as basal dose before final ploughing. Rest of urea (20 kg/ha) was applied after 20 days and 45 days after the date of planting. Tomato was harvested during the period of February to April 2012. Irrigation was applied when the soil moisture content became below the field capacity (FC=20% MC).\r\n', 'Five different types of solar pump were tested at different times, suction and delivery heads. Among five solar pumps, two were locally designed and three were made by USA, Australia and China. BARI, USA and Australia made solar pumps were operated by 600 W solar panels. On the other hand, DU and China made solar pumps were operated by 1000 W solar panels. The average discharges of BARI, DU, USA, Australia and China made solar pumps were 60, 34, 100, 90 and 120 l/min, respectively. Yield of drip irrigated tomato (63.0 t/ha) was significantly higher than that of furrow irrigated tomato (53.5 t/ha). The yield of furrow irrigated brinjal (27.3 t/ha) was slightly higher than drip irrigated brijal (25.8 t/ha) but there was no significant difference between them. Water required for tomato cultivation in drip and furrow irrigations during the season were 254 and 590 mm and those for brinjal cultivation were 228 and 453 mm, respectively. Water savings by drip irrigation method over furrow irrigation for tomato and brinjal were 57% and 50% respectively. Total water applied during the boro season by solar pump in the rice field in Magura was 1024 mm. Water required during boro season for rice cultivation in Magura was 1481 mm', 'Solar panels, Drip irrigated, Furrow irrigations, Brinjal, Tomato, Solar pump', 'BARC', 9788000, 9788000, 0, 'Publication, Booklet', 'Training', 120, 'Solar Pump Irrigation Systems', 'Ecofriendly Environment', '', '', ''),
(1205, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Farm Machinery and Postharvest  Process Engineering Division', 'Project', 'Design and Development of a power weeder', 'Gazipur', 'Medium', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '12-10-2009', '23-12-2010', '', '23-12-2010', 'a) To design and develop a power weeder for row crops \r\nb) To test the performance of the weeder for weeding maize and other row crops \r\n', 'The weeder was designed for upland crops. Three dimensional drawing of the power weeder was done by AutoCAD 2004. It was fabricated at workshop of FMP Engineering Division, BARI, Gazipur in 2009-10. It weighed about 145 kg with rotary blade attachment. \r\nGround wheel: The weeder was supported on two ground wheels made of 50 mm flat bar. The wheel diameter was 457 mm. Lugs, made of 40x40x5 mm MS angle bar of 12 mm height, were 55 mm apart to provide grip on soil. The wheel to wheel distance was adjustable between 560 mm and 610 mm which allowed operating between 30, 40, 70, cm rows. \r\nLaboratory test: To ascertain various design parameter of the weeder, laboratory test was carried out to determine the engine speed, rotary speed and fuel consumption. Fuel consumption was determined by operating the power weeder at field speed in tilled soil and measuring the time and volume of fuel required. \r\nThe experiment was conducted at the research farm of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur during rabi season of 2009-2010. The soil was clay loam. The experimental plots were well pulverized with a tractor and levelled with a bullock drawn ladder. Soil moisture was recorded before each treatment was imposed. Weeds species wise density of all weeds was recorded before and just after the treatments imposed. The weed sampling was done randomly in middle three rows in 50x75 cm quadrants. Three steel frames (50x75 cm) were placed in the middle of the row positioning 75 cm sides along the row.\r\n', 'A power weeder was designed and developed in FMP Engineering divisional workshop, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Gazipur in 2009-10. The drawing was drawn by AutoCAD 2004 software. Then the weeder was fabricated according to design with locally available materials and spare parts. A gearbox was incorporated to get the facility of forward and backward motion of the weeder. A hand clutch connected with a dog clutch was also added to get the turning facilities. The weeder was tested with its rotary blade attachment for weeding maize, soybean and groundnut in 2009-10. The treatments were T1 Weedy (control), T2Hand weeding and T3Weeding by power weeder.  Among the treatments, T2 and T3 produced statistically similar yields, but significantly higher than that of T1. Mechanical weeding by the power weeder saved significant weeding cost and associated labour requirement. T3 produced the highest benefit and the lowest weeding cost. ', 'Design, Development, Power Weeded, Instroment development', '', 100000, 100000, 0, 'Publication, Report', '', 0, 'Design and Development', 'Power Weeder', '', '', ''),
(1206, 'Soil Resources Development Institute', 'Head Quarter', 'Project', 'Soil Resources Management &amp; Analytical Services Project', 'All over Bangladesh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2003', '', '30-06-2003', 'The main objective of this project is over all sustainable agricultural development by strengthening the advisory services to the farmers including increasing crop production and sustaining productivity. ', '', '', 'Soil Management, Soil Analytical Services, SRDI, Soil Resources.', '', 200000000, 200000000, 0, 'Report, Booklet, Leaflet', 'Training, Workshop, Field days', 200, 'Soil Management and Analytical Services', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
(1207, 'Soil Resources Development Institute', 'Head Quarter', 'Project', 'Soil Testing, Management and Development of SRDI''s ', 'All over Bangladesh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-1992', '30-06-2000', '', '30-06-2000', '', '', '', 'Soil, Soil management, Soil test, Soil development, SRDI.', '', 580000000, 580000000, 0, 'Report, Booklet, Leaflet', 'Training Workshop, Field days', 1000, 'Soil test, Management and Development', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
(1208, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'Mechanical Processing Division', '', 'A Study on the Effect of  Processing Parameters of  the Spinning Machine of Fine Jute Yarn.', 'Dhaka, BJRI.', 'Low', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-06-2008', '30-06-2011', '', '30-06-2011', 'To produce yarn and clothe from jute in blends with cotton, rayon, polyester etc. by the application of developed technology evolved with the help of existing machinery and equipment and to  strengthen the research activities for this purpose. \r\nTo create entrepreneurship and transfer the innovated technology for the purpose of commercial   production of the newly evolved fine jute yarn and fabric and other textile products and to promote  marketing of the new jute based products. \r\nTo develop industrialization of the jute based textile technology through the exchange of scientific and technological expertise/knowledge with or in association with textile, jute and garment industries and to make an extension of the technologies to the level of handloom and cottage industries.\r\nTo modify and improve the country made machinery and technologies in case of necessity to make a viable commercial production of jute based fine yarns and various commodities produced experimental in the laboratory.\r\nThe findings will have a direct impact on the jute industry and be able to produce better quality jute fine yarns by adopting the method suggested.\r\nConsequently the use of jute fibre will be increased, which is bio-degrading and therefore environment friendly.\r\nValuable foreign currency can be saved by encouraging the use of jute yarn in place of synthetic yarn.\r\n', 'The following process will be applied/followed for producing the fine jute yarns.\r\n(A)Study the connected literature.\r\n(B)Assortment of  raw materials\r\nCollection of Raw materials (Fibre: Jute, Polyester, Acrylic etc.)\r\nDetermination of fibre Properties ( Strength, Elongation%, Modulus, Fineness, Maturity, Structure, Linear Density etc.)\r\n(C) Blending of Jute with other natural &amp; synthetic fibres.\r\n(D)Selection of  Processing Parameters (Design of the process).\r\n(E)Run the trial (Experimental Blended Yarn Production)\r\n(F)Spinning and production of fine yarn\r\n(G)Determination of physical properties of the yarns.\r\n(H)Study the Yarn Performance.\r\n(I)Production of Home Textiles by the Produced Yarn.\r\n(J)Submission of the Report.\r\n', 'Abstract/ Executive Summary (Max. 200 words, Please underline the keywords):\r\nAn experimental investigation for the production of jute yarn of 138 and 172 tex has been conducted. In this investigation, a laboratory type Apron Draft Spinning machine of 10 	spindles has been used for the study. Bangla White B (BWB) grade jute fibre and synthetic fibres were used as raw material for the production of jute yarn. The input sliver 	of the experimental machine was controlled from the very beginning of the back process.	Numbers of experiments were carried out in order to find the optimum machine parameters, such as spindle speed, twist and draft of the spinning machine for the 	production of desired quality yarn. The processing parameters were also optimized in accordance with the back process machinery. The physical properties of the produced yarns such as load at break, strain percentage, tenacity at break, textile modulus, and quality ratio were tested. The Optimum parameter of processing machinery for making 	yarns are Breaker cards delivery speed of cylinder: 2335 inch/min, Finisher cards delivery speed of cylinder: 1830 inch/min, Draft of 1st, 2nd and 3rd Drawing frame: 4.0, 6.3 and 5.4. In this experiment, effect of draft variation on yarn along with its different sliver weight was studied. From this study, it was noted that with the changes of drafts,	cv% varied. The yarn spun at 8000 rpm with actual twist level of 6.8 tpi relatively nearer to the quality yarn. This is the better result of yarn in comparison to others. Therefore, applied draft 22 at 8000-rpm spindle speeds of yarn offers better quality ratio.The Optimum parameter of processing machinery for making yarns are Breaker cards 	delivery speed of cylinder: 2335 inch/min, Finisher cards delivery speed of cylinder: 1830 inch/min, Draft of 1st, 2nd and 3rd Drawing frame: 4.0, 6.3 and 5.4.For 138 tex jute yarn, Draft: 22, Spindle speed: 8000 rpm, Twist: 6.8 tpi (turns per inch) and for 172 tex 	jute yarn: Draft: 22, Spindle speed: 8000 rpm, Twist: 6.8 tpi (turns per inch) are suitable for producing quality yarn in Apron draft spinning frame.', 'Fine jute yarn, Processing Parameters, Spining Machine', 'BARC', 300000, 300000, 0, 'Publication', 'Workshops', 0, 'Fine Jute Yarn', 'Jute', '', '', ''),
(1210, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Freshwater Station, Mymensingh', 'Project', 'Investivation into the fish diseases and Economic losses due to disease incidence', 'Rajshahi, Sylhet', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-03-2010', '30-06-2013', '01-03-2010', '30-06-2013', 'Investigation into the impact and occurrence of disease outbreaks\r\nCouses of disease outbreaks\r\nCharacterization of pathogens involved in the outbreak of disease\r\nTo develop control strategies for improved health management', 'Field observation and collection of diseases fish\r\ninformation of fish diseases collected through questionnaire\r\nPossible recommendations given to fram owners on the spot \r\nMoribund diseased fish were transported to the laboratory for necessary study                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  ', 'Now-a-days, disease is the important issue for fish culture. Under the present research sub project in molecular laboratory has been developed at the disease division in Bangladesh fisheries Research Institute, Mymensingh\r\nBut it is essential part of the laboratory to equip with other necessary equipments like centrifuge, shaker, water sterilizing plant, cooled incubator, inoculating chamber, PCR machine for successful running of molecular laboratory.\r\nFor disease incidence and analysis of economic loss, only three districts survey are not enough to make a report. Thus study should be extended to other districts of Bangladesh for getting more data for preparing a good report.', 'Fish, Fish diseases, Economic losses', 'BARC', 3211920, 2410741, 0, 'Report', '', 30, 'Fish Diseases', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(1209, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', '', 'Project', 'Coordinated project on improvement of agro-forestry practices for better livelihood and environment (BJRI component)', 'Rangpur, Faridpur and Dinajpur', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', 'July, 2011', 'June, 2013', '', 'June, 2013', 'To introduce the BJRI developed late jute seed production technology in farmers homestead, farmland and orchard based agroforestry systems to be self-sufficient in jute seed production.', '', 'Late jute seed production technique was applied to the farmers (i) Homestead areas and (ii) early stages of orchard plantation. Both white (cv. CVL-1) and tossa (cvs. O-9897 and O-72) varieties were used with established cultivation practice (balanced fertilizer and intercultural operations). Few farmers intercropped jute seed crop with vegetables in their kitchen garden also. In farmers homestead areas 2 to 2.5 kg of jute seed per decimal and 2.5 to 3.5 kg of jute seed at early plantation of orchard areas were produced. Economically farmers were benefitted with late jute seed production in both homestead and early stages of orchard plantation, but late jute seed production in early stages of orchard plantation were more profitable.', 'Late jute seed, Late sowing, Agroforestry, Homestead, Orchard, Farmland', 'GOB', 8343270, 4554568, 0, 'Booklet', 'Field days', 350, 'Agroforestry', 'Urea', '', '', ''),
(1211, 'Bangladesh Forest Research Institute', 'Khepupara Sub-station', 'Project', 'Coordinated Sub-project on Addressing Climate Change on Fisheries Sector Through Community Based Technology Identification and Adoption in the Fragile Aqua Ecosystem of Bangladesh, BFRI, Component.', 'Saiedpur, Nilphamari and Kalapara, Patuakhali', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', '1. Provide technical supports to the on farm experiments.\r\n2. Conduct on-station trails for the similar identified technologies\r\n3. Develop training manuals on community based fisheries/aquaculture technologies in context to changing climatic conditions.\r\n4. Build capacities of training facilitators and community.\r\n        ', 'Riverine sub-station Khepupara on BFRI was conducted on-station technology trails of coastal region, whereas freshwater sub-station Syhedpur was conducted on-station technology trails of drought and river bank erosion region.&lt;br /&gt;\r\nRiverine sub-station Khepupara on BFRI was monitored water quality parameters of on farm trails of coastal region, whereas freshwater sub-station Syhedpur was monitored the water quality parameter of drought and river bank erosion region.\r\n', 'Results:\r\n	Khepupara Sub-station\r\n1.	Cage culture of GIFT\r\n2.	Hapa breeding of GIFT\r\n3.	Overwintering of carp fingerling\r\nSayedpur Sub-station:\r\n1.	Monoculture of GIFT\r\n2.	Monoculture of Local GIFT\r\n', 'Fish, Climate change, Aqua Eco-System', 'BARC', 10147640, 1000000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 50, 'Climate Change', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(1212, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Freshwater Station, Mymensingh', 'Project', 'Nutrient contents of indigenous small fish of Bangladesh and their products', 'BFRI, Mymensingh Head Quarter', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '', '30-06-2011', 'Determine the proximate, macro and micro-nutrient composition of available small indigenous fish species (SIS) and fish products from SIS in Bangladesh.\r\nEstablish a Fish and Fish Product Nutrients table for the sustainable management in relation to resource conservation and food security.', 'Chemicals analysis:\r\nBoth fresh and cooked fish and fish products will be used for nutritional composition study. Proximate composition will be determined according to the Association of Official Analytical Chemists (AOAC 1995) procedures. Macro and micro nutrient composition will be determined using an atomic absorption spectrophotometer (AAS) following modified method of Cresser and Parson (1979). Vitamin compounds will be determined by high performance liquid chromatography (HPLDC) following method of Leth and Jacobsen (1993).&lt;br /&gt;\r\nEstablishing Nutrient Table:&lt;br /&gt;\r\nThe fish and fish products will be classified according to their nutrient value as nutrient (protein, calcium, zinc, iron etc.) and vitamin supplements.', '	Complete scenario of nutritive value of small indigenous fish species and fish products.\r\n	Provide knowledge on importance of SIS in our aquaculture system.\r\n	Establish a Fish Nutrients Table to develop a guideline for food security and combating malnutrition among rural poor in Bangladesh, which will help in policy making.\r\n', 'Nutrients, Small fish', 'BARC', 324000, 315000, 9000, 'Report', '', 0, 'Freshwater Aquaculture/Nutrition', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(1213, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Mymenshigh Head Quarter', 'Project', 'Coordinated project on contaminants and adulterants in food chain and their mitigation, BFRI component. ', 'Mymensingh, Dhaka, Khulna, Chittagong, Cox''s Bazar', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', '1.To investigate potential hazards for fish &amp; fish products.\r\n2.To investigate the pathway of adulteration of fish &amp; fish products through biochemical and microbial analysis.\r\n3.To monitoring fish feed &amp; water quality and their relevance to food safety.\r\n', 'Sample collection and analysis:\r\nFish samples of representative group from different fish markets/production centers of Dhaka, Chittagong, Coxs Bazar, Khulna &amp; Mymensingh.\r\nAlso samples from specific dried fish production areas like Kisorgonj, Sirajgonj, Patuakhali etc.\r\nAnalytical procedure:\r\nProximate &amp; mineral composition\r\nTotal Volatile Base Nitrogen (TVB-N)\r\nPeroxide Value (POV\r\nBacterial count &amp; identification\r\nHeavy metals\r\nAntibiotic &amp; pesticide residues\r\nFormalin \r\n', 'Questionnaire survey:\r\nConsumer perception (Dhaka, Chittagong, Khulna Cities); Fish traders (Dhaka, Chittagong, Coxs Bazar); Fish farmers (Trisal, Muktagacha, Bhaluka, Savar)\r\nQuestionnaire survey has been planned to perform at beginning and end of study\r\nField survey on fish farms at Trisal &amp; Bhaluka\r\nField observation on fish drying activities in Khulna, Patuakhali &amp; Coxs Bazar\r\nField monitoring on fish farming in industrial zone (Bhaluka &amp; Savar areas)\r\nAssess the fish feeds and feed industries\r\n', 'Fish, Consumers, Farmers, Traders, Aqua-buniness, Food safty, Quality, Hazardous and Risk, ', 'BARC', 5729000, 3100000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Food and Nutrition', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(1214, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Biotechnology Division', 'Project', 'Coordinated sub-project on characterization of important Plant Genetic Resources', 'All over Bangladesh', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-10-2011', '30-09-2013', '', '30-09-2013', '1.Morphological characterization of crop varieties and germplasm\r\n2.To characterize crop varieties and germplasm at molecular level using molecular markers (SSR, RAPD, STS, SNP and other markers)\r\n3.Document of characterized crop varieties and germplasm', 'a)Morpho-physiological data will be collected from the field or pot during the growing stage of the crops.\r\nb)Collection of leaf sample for DNA extraction; genomic DNA extraction using cetyltrimethyl ammonium bromide (CTAB) method; confirmation and quantification of DNA; Preparation of working solution (25ng/&micro;l) of DNA samples; polymerase chain reaction (PCR); electrophoresis, Agarose gel electrophoresis, polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (PAGE); visualization of DNA samples; Scoring of bands  and Molecular data analysis.', 'Molecular markers consist of specific DNA nucleotides sequences, which show easily detectable diferences among different strains of a species or among different species.', 'Genitic Resources, Characterization of Plant Genetic Resources, Crops, Jute, Seasame, Lentil, Soyabean', 'BARC', 1891700, 200000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Characterization of Plant Genetic Resources', 'Rice, Mustard, Sesame, Soyabeen, Groundnut, Mungbean, Chickpea, Lentil, Blackgram, Graspea, Tomato, ', '', '', ''),
(1215, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Entomology division', 'Project', ' Varietal resistance in rice to brown planthopper, nilaparvate lugens stal. ', 'BINA Head Quarter', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-04-2000', '30-06-2001', '', '30-06-2001', 'The objective of this study is to identify and develop high yielding rice varieties resistance to brown plant hopper.', 'Nineteen mutants/varieties of rice were tested along with a resistant check, t2tA and suscepti ble check, TNI on the feeding, oviposition and settling responses of brown planthopper (plate 1) . Feeding responses to BPH was studied in tow ways i.e. , honeydew test by parafilm sachet technique and percent weight change of the brachypterous females.\r\nThe experiment was set up in a completely randomized design having six replications. Data on orientation and settling of nuymphs were collected at 4, 24, 48 72 h after release. Data were analyzed statistically.\r\n', 'Significant differences were observed in the quantity of honeydew excreted by individual females over 24 h of feeding on the rice mutants/varieties (Table 1, 2 and 3). The excretion of honeydew was significantly less on the resistant variety, t27a and the mutants Atomita, Cilosari, Y1281 (Q31-02-2) and gtheir mother variety Cisadane, Q31 Acc. 9338, the mutants BINA 250-24 and Binadhan6. Binasail, Binadhan 5 and the mutants 250-83 and IR5 had also significantly lower honeydew excretion as a result of feeding compared to susceptible TN1. On the other hand, the mutants Kashmir Basmati and DM25 and their mother variety Basmati 370 were at par with t he susceptible TN1.', 'Entomology, Varital resistance, Brown palnthopper', 'Science and Technology (S&amp;T)', 200000, 200000, 0, 'Publication, Report', '', 0, 'Insect resistance variety', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(1279, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Project', 'Rice production situations in different agricultural regions of BD.', 'Dinajpur, Gaibandha, Rajshahi, Satkira, Pirojpur, Bandarban, Sylhet, B. Baria and Sunamganj', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-05-2006', '30-06-2008', '01-05-2006', '30-06-2008', 'a. To estimate the total rice demand, supply and demand supply balance in different rice production environments of the country.\r\nb. To determine the present storing capacity and quantity of paddy stored and storage time at the farm level.\r\nc. To find out the reasons for storing paddy and the benefits derived by the farmers for storing paddy at the farm level; and\r\nd. To suggest necessary policy guidelines for future production, domestic marketing, import and export strategy of Bangladesh.', '', '', 'Storing capacity, Surplus production, Buffer stock, ', 'BARC', 200000, 200000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'More Production Technology', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1216, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Entomology division', 'Project', 'Varietal resistance in rice to the brown planthopper, Nilaparvatta lugens Stal. And the rice hispa, Dicladispa armigera Oliv.', 'BINA Head Quarter', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2004', '30-06-2005', '', '30-06-2005', 'To identify and develop high yielding rice varieties resistant to brown planthopper and rice hispa.', 'Follwong are the main methodology:\r\n1. Resistance of rice mutants/varieties for their reaction to Brown Planthopper\r\n2. Feeding responses of the brown planthopper, Nilaparvata lugens Stal. on rice mutants/varieties\r\n3. Oviposition behavour of rice hispa dicladispa armigera on rice mutants/varieties\r\n4. Effect of plant age and varieties on the feeding responses of brown planthopper\r\n5. Evaluatin of rice mutants/varieties for resistance against rice hispa, dicladispa armigera', 'The mutants/varieties Tainan-3, IR-22M-1, Y-128 and atomita-4 were found to be resistant to N. Lugens with a rating of 1 (Table 1). Basmati-370, Sigadis Milagrasa, PR-26763, THDB, Cilosari, IR-25''86 ....... -2, RD-2586, IR-64, RD-25, MR-219, TNDB-100, DM-25, and 3027 were domerately resistant while kashmir Basmati, PNR-381, Q-31 Acc. 9338, PNR-519, R-3027, Q-50, PNR-166, IR-5, PR-26305-M-32, IR-8 were moderately susceptible. The mutant/rariety tep Hanh and Tai Nguyen were found to be susceptible.', 'Varietal Resistance, Entomology, Brown planthpper', 'Science and Technology (S&amp;T)', 200000, 200000, 0, 'Report, Publication', '', 0, 'Varietal Resistance', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(1217, 'Bangladesh Institute of Nuclear Agriculture', 'Biotechnology Division', 'Project', 'Sustainable Rice Seed Production and Delivery Systems for Southern Bangladesh', 'Bagerhat, Barguna, Barisal, Bhola, Chuadanga, Faridpur, Gopalganj, Jalokati, Jessore, Jhenaidaha, Khulna, Madaripur, Magura, Meharpur, Narail, Patuakhali, Pirojpur, Rajbari, Satkhira and Shariatpur.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-07-2012', '31-03-2013', '', '31-03-2013', '1.	The results of the collaborative research will be jointly published in the public interest as mutually agreed upon.\r\n2.	All outcomes of the joint activities, including all intellectual property rights (IPR) shall be jointly owned by contributing collaborators. As such they shall remain publicly accessible and shall be available to the partners of collaborating institutions and end-users following the rules and regulations of exchange of materials as set by Govt. of India.\r\n3.	All research materials used in the collaboration will be transferred using Standard Material Transfer agreements (SMTA). Further, the transfer of biological materials, including breeding materials and germphasm, will be subject to pertinent biosafety and bioprospecting laws, rules, and regulations.\r\n4.	Funds shall be used exclusively for the purpose of implementing the project activity and any unspent funds at the end of the project shall be returned to IRRI.', 'The project will be contribute to improve food security by enhanced and sustained rice productivity through the promotion of high yielding stress tolerant rice varieties, Major activities of the project are simultaneous promotion of seed multiplication and awareness generation to ensure seed demand and supply; strengthen the capacity of local institutions involved in the production and distribution of high quality seeds including farmers and extension personnel. The project will be implemented in the Southern 20 districts of Bangladesh.', '', 'Seed production, Seed Delivery System, Rice, Southern Bangladesh', 'USAID, IRRI', 2427116, 1500000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Seed Production', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1218, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Plant Breeding Division', 'Project', 'Development of Salt Tolerant Rice Variety Through Intregression of Salt Tolerant Genes into Popular Early Rice Variety Binadhan-7.', 'Coastal Saline Areas of Bangladesh', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-06-2012', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', 'a.To intr4ogresss salt tolerant loci from selected salt tolerant IRRI line FL478 into salt susceptible Bondman-7 through marker assisted backcrossing.\r\nb.To screen derived backcross lines under salinized condition at the seedling and reproductive states.\r\nc.To evaluate agronomic performances of the developed backcross lines (BC2F1 or BC2F2).\r\nd.	To genotype backcross lines (BC2F2 or BC2F2) using SSR markers.\r\ne.To map QTLs for salinity tolerance at seedling and reproductive states; and compare the QTLs that confers tolerance in both stages.\r\nf.To develop salt tolerant version of Binadhan-7 for cultivation in the coastal saline areas of Bangladesh to increase production.\r\n', '', '', 'Salt tolerant variety, Early rice, Binadhan-7, Salt tolerant genes.', '', 200000, 30000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Development of Salt Tolerant Rice Variety', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1219, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Evaluation of Soil Fertility Indices for Assessment of Land Degradation Situation of Bangladesh.', 'Rangpur, Dinajpur, Lalmonirhat, Thakurgaon, Panchagar, Gaibandha, Nilphamari and Kurigram districts', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '', '30-06-2009', 'a.To monitor the changes of some physical and chemical characters of soils from different agro-ecological regions of Bangladesh during the period between 1966 and 2009.\r\nb.To evaluate the fertility indices/properties of the soils in terms of potentiality for improved land use.\r\nc.To survey and indentify the constraints related to soil and environment of the locations/AEZs under study.\r\nd.To train the officers and staffs of BINA and DAE about land degradation and soil fertility conservation practices.\r\n', '', 'A study was initiated to evaluate the changes in soil characters over time for the assessment of land degradation situation in Bangladesh. The sampled soil series covered four AEZs as mentioned before. Based on the local landscape characteristic and hydrological condition, soil samples falls under medium highland to highland (above normal flood level) group. The collected soil samples have been analysed in the laboratory in order to evaluate the changes in soil physical and chemical characters e.g. particle size distribution (sand, silt and clay contents), soil pH, organic matter, total N and exchangeable caution (Ca++, K+ and Na+) contents for the assessment of land degradation situation during the period between 1996 and 2009.', 'Soil Fertility, Soil degradation, Soil fertility indices.', 'Science and Communication Technology', 600000, 600000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Soil Chemistry and Soil Fertility', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
