(1229, 'Bangladesh Institute of Nuclear Agriculture', 'Plant Pathology Division', 'Project', 'Development of biofungicides uning natural antagonists', 'BINA lab. NINA farm, Ishurdi and Mugura', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2011', '', '30-06-2011', '\r\na.	To collect and identify bio-control micro-organisms mainly Trichoderma sp. Against target pathogen(s) such as Fusarium solani, F. oxysporum f. sp. Ciceris and Sclerotium rolfsii causing foot and root rot/wilt and collar rot of lentil, respectively in soils.\r\nb.	To develop cost effective and environment friendly Biofungicidesusing highly antago nist species of fungi for the management of the target pathogens(s).\r\nc.	Mass production of Biofungicide\r\nd.	Formulation and evaluation of different methods of application and storage of Biofungicide.\r\n', '', '', 'Biological control, Antagonist fungus, Soil borne pathogen ', 'BARC', 450000, 450000, 0, 'Publication, Report', '', 0, 'Biological control of plant pathogen', 'Lentil', '', '', ''),
(1230, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Freshwater Station, Mymensingh', 'Project', 'Stock improvement of Tilapia and Climbing Perch Koi through Genetic selection', 'Freshwater Station, Mymensingh.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2015', '30-06-2015', '30-06-2015', 'a.	To continue the stock improvement of BFRI-GIFT strain using family selection protocol\r\nb.	To improve  the stock of Thai Koi using brood stock replacement technique\r\nc.	To evaluate the growth performance of improved BFRI GIFT and THAI Koi', 'Expt. I: Family Selection Program of BFRI-GIFT strain (F-6 generation)\r\nOn the basis of family wise highest breeding values of F-5 generation (tagged fish), the selected best 70 males will be crossed with 70 females for production of F-6 generation. Then 70 breeding hapas (1m3) will be set up in a pond. A pair of female and male breeders (1:1) will be stocked in each breeding hapa. After 15 days, it is necessary to check the hapa for collecting the swim up fry. Then 300 fry from each progeny family will be transferred to separate series of nursery hapas in a pond. From 300 fry, 100-150 fry will be transferred to the rearing hapa until the attainment of 8-10g. From each progeny group at least 20 male and 20 female fish will be tagged using Passive Integrated Transponder (PIT) tags. From each progeny group at least 40-50 tagged fingerlings (25 male and 25 female) will be transferred in a pond for 5 months for communal rearing. After five months rearing, fish will be harvested and tag number, weight, sex, body depth will be recorded. Then breeding\r\nvalue will be determined by the following formula: ebv =	) X h2 [ h2 = VA I Vp\r\nExpt. II: Evaluation of F-6 Generation with founder population of GIFT strain\r\nThe aim of this study will be the evaluation of growth performance of the BFRI GIFT strain after three generation of selection. This trial will be carried out for a period of five months in a pond having an area1000m2. There will be two treatment groups, where offspring of founder population will be treated as treatment-1 and offspring of F-6 Generation, which produced from 70 families will be considered as treatment-2. In each treatment group 700 fingerling will be stocked in a pond for communal rearing. Fingerlings of treatment-1 will be marked through cauterization of pelvic fin. During rearing, fish will be fed with supplementary feed contained 25% crude protein at the rate of 5-8% of estimated body weight. Harvesting will be done after five months rearing. After harvesting,\r\nindividual weight of all fishes in both treatments will be recorded. Data analysis will be done through SAAS statistical programme.\r\nExpt. III: Stock improvement and mass seed production of newly introduced pure line of Koi (A. testudineus) through Brood stock replacement techniques\r\nThe largest and heaviest individuals of F2 generation of each sex will be selected and stocked in a breeding pond for the production of F3 generation. For the production of F-3 generation, the following protocols will be followed:\r\n	Before induced breeding at least 60 breeding hapas (size 2 x 2 x 1 m) need to be set in a tank of hatchery.\r\n	The fishes will be mated in 05 pair cross in a single hapa to ensure equal numbers of male and female fish\r\n	This activities to be completed in six batch induced breeding\r\n	After breeding, about 20 gm of hatchlings from each hapa will be mixed together and reared in a single nursery pond for 4 weeks.\r\n	As such six nursery pond will be maintained where each nursery pond will contain 200g larvae (from 10 hapas out of a total of 60 hapas)\r\n	After nursing, 1000 fry randomly selected from each batch (each nursery pond) and put into the brood stock replacement pond in which 300 pairs of brood fish contribute fingerlings in this desired stock.\r\nExpt. IV: Comparative growth performances between improved koi (F3) and founder stock of koi at on station management\r\nFor evaluating the growth performance of F3 generation of Thai Koi (A. testudineus), an experiments will be carried out for a period of four months in the on-station condition. There will be two treatments with three replications. Designs of experiments are as follows:\r\nT-1:	F-3 generation of Thai Koi; and\r\nT-2:	Founder stock of Thai koi (A. testudineus)\r\nStocking density will be maintained for each species at 75,000 ha-t. After stocking, fish will be fed with supplementary feed contained 35% crude protein. Sampling of fish will be done at fortnightly interval to determine their growth rate. Water quality parameters such as will be monitored at weekly interval. After completion of the experiment, growth and production will be analyzed through statistical analysis.\r\nExpt. V: Evaluation of growth performances of cross bred koi (A. testudineus) at on-farm management\r\nEvaluation of growth performances of cross bred koi (A. testudineus) will be under taken at on farm management for the period of four months during April to June, 2012. Six farmers ponds having area of 800 m2 each will be selected in Muktagacha/Fulpur upazilla, Mymensingh. There will be two treatments with three replications. Here, species of koi will be considered as treatment. The design of experiment is as follows:\r\nTreatment	Species	Stocking\r\ndensity/ha\r\nT-1	Cross bred koi	75,000\r\nT-2	Thai Koi	75,000\r\nAfter stocking, supplementary feed containing 35% crude protein will be supplied for the fishes of different treatments. Water quality parameters will be monitored at weekly interval. Fish will be sampled at fortnightly intervals to know the growth as well as feed adjustment. After completion of the experiment, data will be analyzed through statistical package\r\nV. Distribution of improved BFRI-GIFT strain and Thai Koi\r\nGermplasm of improved BFRI-GIFT strain and Thai Koi will be distributed in four sub-stations of BFRI and brood bank of DoF. Germplasm will also be distributed in selected private tilapia seed producing hatcheries for their dissemination. The guidelines of seed production of technique as well as culture technique of improved BFRI GIFT strain will be given to the hatchery operators.\r\n', '', 'Stock Improvment of Telapia fishes, Telapia fishes, climbing perch Koi, Genetic selection.', 'BARC', 7000000, 5200000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Genetic Selection', 'Fishes', '1) Improved BFRI-GIFT tilapia and Thai Koi are available for small and large-scale aquaculture.\r\n2) Pond fish production increased through improved GIFT and Thai Koi culture.', 'Fish production especially GIFT tilapia and Thai Koi will be increased which ultimately will help to ensure family nutrition security in the country.\r\n', ''),
(1231, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'Jute Textile Product Development Centre (JTPDC)', 'Project', 'Production and development of jute based blended fabrics in cotton processing system of textile uses.', 'BJRI Head Office', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', '1)	To produce different types of blended yarn &amp; fabrics.\r\n2)	To determine the properties of blended yarn &amp; fabrics\r\n3)	To compare the properties of blended yarn &amp; fabrics with the 100% respective cotton yarn and fabrics.\r\n4)	To use jute as textile fibre in place of cotton', '', '', 'Blended Fabrics, Jute, Cotton, Textile fibre, Cotton yarn, ', 'BARC', 9334000, 8020728, 0, 'Booklet', 'Workshops', 0, 'Blending Fabrics Development', 'Jute, Cotton', '', '', ''),
(1232, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Popularization of the involved technologies on soil and fertilizer management for quality jute seed production. ', 'Manikganj, Kinajpur, Faridpur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-10-2005', '30-09-2006', '', '30-09-2006', 'a. To popularize the evolved technologies among the farmers and related personnel&amp;rsquo;s on soil and fertilizer management for the production of quality jute seed byBangladesh Jute Research Institute.\r\nb. To build up a linkage between research and extension people as well as NGO&amp;rsquo;s.\r\nc. Documentation of the developed technologies for the use of research, extension personnel&amp;rsquo;s NGO&amp;rsquo;s and policy makers.', 'a. Result demonstration of the developed technologies for quality jute seed production in different AEZs of Bangladesh.\r\nb. Three field days sowing higher performance of the evolved technologies at three different locations.\r\nc. A booklet/Leaflet on matured technologies developed by BJRI Soil Science Department of quality jute seed production.\r\nd. Purchasing some essential printing materials for documentation and presentation of the modern technologies of jute seed production.', '', 'Soil and Fertilizer Management, Quality Jute Seed Production.', 'BARC', 100000, 100000, 0, 'Report, Leaflet', 'Training, Field days', 300, 'Jute Seed Production', 'Jute', '', '', ''),
(1233, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Farming System Research Development Division', 'Project', 'Coordinate sub project Farming system research and Development of Livelihoods improvement of Farmers: BJRI component', 'Manikganj, Kishorgonj', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-05-2012', '31-10-2013', '', '31-10-2013', 'a. To introduction location-specific jute farming system-based technologies.\r\nb. To validate developed BJRI and other NARS institutes technologies at different Agro ecological zones (AEZs) of Bangladesh.\r\nc. To integrate component technologies (crops, homestead and agro-forestry, livestock and fisheries etc.) for improving farming practices and market linkages.\r\nd. To improve family income and farmers&amp;rsquo; livelihood.', '', '', 'Farming System Research, Agro-Ecological Zones, Year round vegetables production, farmers livelihood', 'BARC', 5412700, 900000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 210, 'Farming Systems Development', 'Jute, Vegetables, Fish, Livestock, Rice', '', '', ''),
(1234, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', '', 'Project', 'Improvemental Jute Based Cropping Pattern and Jute Seed Production Technologies in Southern Area of Bangladesh.', 'Kalapara, Dhumki and Amtoli Upazila of Potuakhali', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', 'July, 2011', 'June, 2014', 'July 2011', 'June 2014', '1) To identify suitable variety of Jute (Capsularies) and Kenaf for fibre production at farm level in the Southern area.\r\n2) To identify suitable winter vegetable as inter crop with Jute seed production.\r\n3) To identify cost effectiveness of Jute cultivation in Southern areas of Bangladesh.', '', 'The study has been undertaken to assess agro-economic performance of existing cropping patterns followed by farmers in the coastal salinity area of Kalapara &amp; Dhumki under Potuakhali district and Amtoli under Barguna district. A total of 60 farmers (taking 20 from each Upazila) were selected by adopting simple random sampling method under bench mark survey. Data were collected through survey method by using structured questionnaire. There are seven major cropping patterns, which are generally practiced by the farmers in the study area. Among the cropping patterns, majority of the farmers practiced Fallow-T. aman-Fallow pattern (76%) followed by T. Aus-T. aman-Fallow (74%), T. aus-T. aman-Pulses (64%), Fallow-T. aman-Pulses (55%), Fallow-T. aman-vegetables (48%), B. Aus/T. Aus-Fallow-Chilli (29%) and Vegetables-T. aman-vegetables (25%). Under the experiment &quot;Performance of Jute Seed Production with winter vegetables in southern areas of Bangladesh&quot;. Four cropping pattern were studied in this experiment like Jute seed as a sole crop (T1), Jute seed + Lalshak + Radish (Broadcast method)(T2), Jute seed + Lalshak + Tomato (line sowing with three pair method) (T3), Jute seed + Tomato + Brinjal + Palongshak (Line sowing with three pair method) (T4). Among the four cropping patterns the maximum yield of jute seed was observed from jute seed as a sole crop 543 kg/ha and 532 kg/ha in Kalapara and Amtoli respectively. The benefit cost ration (BCR) on full cost basis ranges from 1.06 to 1.65. Other experiments are in the field. As a result, the data collection of the experiments not yet has been completed. There were four farmers training programme conducted at Kalapara, Amtoli and Dumki with participation of 200 farmers and three field days were conducted at Kalapara and Dumki with participation of 133 farmers and SAAO at jute fibre maturity stage in the year 2011-12.', 'Cropping Patterns, Maximum yield of Jute seed, Bench mark survey, Jute fibre maturity stage.', 'BARC', 1000000, 650000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 200, 'Seed Production', 'Jute', '', '', ''),
