(1241, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Agronomy Division, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Selection of drought and excess mointure tolerant maize genotypes for sustainable productivity in stress prone environment.', 'BARI, Gazipur', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '23-05-2012', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', 'a. To identify drought and excess soil moisture stress tolerant maize genotypes for sustainable production in stress prone environment.\r\nb. To increase maize productivity and economic return of the farmers of stress prone environment\r\nc. Varieties/genotypes in each species different from each other in their responses to water stress conditions. So, there is some scope to find out moisture stress (deficit/excess soil moisture) tolerant maize genotypes.\r\n', 'Drought tolerance maize genotypes identification through physiological trait and yield.\r\nHalf on N and all other fertilizer will be applied as basal. Rest N will be topdressed in two equal splits at 35 and 65 DAS.', 'Data to be recorded- Soil moisture monitoring, relative leaf water content, photosynthesis, leaf chlorophyll, yield and yield contributing characters.', 'climate change, Water logging', 'BARC', 200000, 50000, 0, '', '', 0, 'Climate Change', 'Water Logging', '', '', ''),
(1242, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'Kenaf Mesta Department, Breeding Division', 'Project', 'Identification, Evaluation and Development of parental materials of Kenaf and Mesta variety.', 'Dhaka, Manikganj, Faridpur and Potuakhali', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', 'March 2009', 'June 2011', 'March 2009', 'June 2011', '1) To select Kenaf and Mesta germplasm containing higher yield and year round cultivation.\r\n2) To select water logging tolerent, short day tolerant and salinity tolerant variety of Kenaf and Mesta. ', '', 'Kenaf and Mesta are fibre yielding plants like jute. Seeds of 100 germplasms of Kenaf (Hibiscus canabinus) and 100 Mesta (Hibiscus sabdariiffa) of both indigenous and exotic origin containing desirable traits and three recommended variety and Mesta (HC-2, HC-95) were used in the study to identify and select superior parents to develop high yielding Kenaf and Mesta variety containing disease and pest resistant characters, water logging tolerant, saline tolerant, early maturing high biomass, prickles free and good fibre quality. The studied germplasms showed wide range of variability in their phenotypic and genotypic characters. The Kenaf accession number 9, 12, 24, 37 and 42 showed rapid growth and gave higher plant height, base diameter, fibre weight and stick weight than the other germplasms at Manikganj. The Kenaf accession number 18, 23 and 37 showed early maturing characters, which also showed prickle free stem and leaf at Faridpur. The Kenaf accession 22, 34 and 45 showed slightly tolerance to salinity. The selection accession showed resistant characters to disease and insects.\r\nIn case of Mesta, the accession number 780 and 1003 showed leafy characters which can be used as a delicious vegetable. The accession number 715 showed freshly, edible calyces in their fruits. 812 which can be used for cooking purpose and preparation of jam and jelly, tea and confectionery materials. The Mesta accession number 1025, 1228, 1887 and 2048 showed prickle free smooth stem and the highest plant height and base diameter. ', 'Kenaf, Mesta, Identification, germplasm, new variety', 'BARC', 300000, 295000, 5000, 'Report', 'Training', 100, '', 'Jute', '', '', ''),
(1243, 'Bangladesh Jute Research Institute', 'Soil Science Department, Agronomy Division', 'Project', 'Coordinated Project on Soil Fertility and Fertilizer Management for Jute and Jute based Cropping Pattern: BJRI Component', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', 'May 2011', '30 June 2013', 'August 2011', '30 June 2013', '1) To develop balanced fertilization practices for improving jute growth, fibre yield and soil properties.\r\n2) To recommend fertilizer dose for the production of jute seed crop.\r\n3) To find out the method/procedure, time of application of fertilizer for improving fibre quality, soil properties.', '', '', 'Fibre yield, Jute seed crop, Fibre Quality, Balanced Fertilization', 'BARC', 6379912, 3246089, 0, '', '', 0, 'Soil Fertility and Fertilizer Management', 'Jute', '', '', ''),
(1244, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, BARI, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Upscalling and adoption of hybrid dryer for quality grain seed production', 'Gazipur, Dinajpur, Rajshahi and Jessore', 'High', 'Strategic', 'Completed', '18-05-2009', '17-05-2011', '', '17-05-2011', 'i. To make modification of the existing hybrid dryer suitable for grain seeds drying\r\nii. To evaluate the technical performance of the dryer and test the seed quality\r\niii. To test and demonstrate the dryers in the farmers&amp;rsquo; field\r\niv. To disseminate the dryer among the seed growers and traders through training and workshop.', 'This project was combinely carried out by Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division and Seed Technology Division of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute, Joydebpur, Gazipur-1701. Farm Machinery Postharvest Process Engineering Division was the leading organization and Seed Technology Division was the collaborative organization. The duration of the project was two years. First year was R&amp;amp;D phase and second year was the dissemination phase. Engineering aspects of the dryer i.e. design, drawing, fabrication and performance tests were carried out in Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Divisional workshop and seed quality was evaluated in Seed Technology Division.\r\nThe hybrid dryer was fabricated at Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI) using the workshop and technical manpower facilities during 2009-10. This dryer also was tested in the laboratory using the laboratory facilities. Seed quality was tested in the Seed Technology laboratory using the laboratory facilities of Seed Technology Division of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute. Field level tests on grain seeds drying were conducted during 2010-2011. Three seed dryers were fabricated and installed in Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jessore, Regional Wheat Research Centre, Rajshahi and Wheat Research Centre, Dinajpur. The seed dryers were demonstrated to the farmers and small seed traders. During the field level tests, local Department of Agricultural Extension, BADC and Seed Testing Agency were included.\r\nThis project was combinely carried out by Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division and Seed Technology Division of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute, Joydebpur, Gazipur-1701.\r\nThe hybrid dryer was fabricated at Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI) using the workshop and technical manpower facilities during 2009-10. This dryer also was tested in the laboratory using the laboratory facilities. Seed quality was tested in the Seed Technology laboratory using the laboratory facilities of Seed Technology Division of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute. Field level tests on grain seeds drying were conducted during 2010-2011. Three seed dryers were fabricated and installed in Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jessore, Regional Wheat Research Centre, Rajshahi and Wheat Research Centre, Dinajpur. The seed dryers were demonstrated to the farmers and small seed traders. During the field level tests, local Department of Agricultural Extension, BADC and Seed Testing Agency were included.', 'A hybrid seed dryer (combination of solar energy and electric energy) was designed and constructed at Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Gazipur. The technical performance of the dryer was tested for drying of grain seeds and seed quality was evaluated during the period of 2010-2011. The reflected solar radiation was 53% of global solar radiation. The thermal efficiency of the collector was 28.73%. The dryer was tested for drying of paddy, wheat, maize and groundnut. Time required for drying of 250-300 kg of paddy, 250 kg of wheat, 350 kg of maize and 200 kg groundnut were found to be 17, 12, 16 and 20 hours, respectively. There were no significant differences in drying rates between top and bottom layers (12 cm depth) of paddy seeds. The dryer was tested and its field performance was evaluated in Jessore, Rajshshi and Dinajpur during the period of 2010-2011. Three dryers were fabricated and installed at Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jessore; Regional Wheat Research Centre, Rajshshi and Wheat Research Centre, Dinajpur. In all the locations, paddy seeds were dried. The field performance of the dryer was found satisfactory in terms of drying rate and seed quality. The benefit cost ratios (BCR) for drying of paddy seeds on variable and total cost basis were 1.47 and 1.40, respectively. The pay back period of the dryer was 0.44 year. Major portion of energy used in hybrid dryer was solar energy and it is environment friendly.', 'Hybride Seed Dryer, Solar Energy, Performance, Solar radiation', 'GoB and World Bank', 1800821, 1800821, 0, 'Report, Publication, Booklet', 'Training, Workshop', 140, 'Quality Grain Seed Production', 'Hybrid Dryer', '', '', ''),
(1245, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, BARI, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Design and adaptation of solar pump irrigation systems for ecofriendly environment ', ': Gazipur, Jamalpur, Magura and Barisal', 'High', 'Strategic', 'On-going', '01-06-2010', '31-05-2013', '', '31-05-2013', '(i) Select the suitable solar pumps for different irrigation systems based on the results of base line survey\r\n(ii) Test and evaluate of the technical performance of selected solar pumps for surface and ground water lifting\r\n(iii) Install and test the appropriate solar pumps in the selected areas for different types of irrigations for rice and non-rice crops\r\n(iv) Make economic analysis and socio-economic impacts study of solar pump irrigation in the selected areas of the project.', 'Five different types of solar pump were tested at different times, suction and delivery heads. The specifications of the selected solar pumps are given in Table 1. Among five solar pumps, two were locally designed and three were made by developed countries (USA, Australia and China). BARI designed solar pump was made with 800 W dc motor coupled with 0.5 hp locally made centrifugal pump. Dhaka University (DU) designed solar pump was made with ac motor, 0.5 hp centrifugal pump, inverter (1000 W), charge controller and battery (24 V, 200 AH). The USA made solar pump was 0.5 hp suitable for surface water lifting and Australia made submersible solar pump was same capacity but suitable for surface and ground water lifting. The China made pump was 2.2 hp motor capacities suitable for both surface and groundwater lifting. BARI, USA and Australia made solar pumps were operated by 600 W solar panels. On the other hand, DU and China made solar pumps were operated by 1000 W solar panels. During testing of solar pumps, solar radiation, panel voltage, current, power, suction head, delivery head and discharge were measured.\r\nThe solar pump was used for drip irrigation and furrow irrigation for tomato cultivation in the experimental field of FMPE division during rabi 2011-12. The soil type was clay loam. The plot size was 40 m &amp;times; 13 m (520 m2). Six beds of tomato were irrigated by the drip method having three water tanks each of 500 liter water holding capacity. The drip sets were made with plastic pipes, water tank, capillary tubes, pegs etc. The tomato variety was BARI Tomato-14.Two rows of tomato were planted in each bed on 4 December, 2011. The age of seedlings was 31 days. Row to row and plant to plant distances were 60 cm and 40 cm, respectively. Cowdung 10.0 t/ha, urea 600 kg/ha, TSP 500 kg/ha, MP 200 kg/ha, zinc 10 kg/ha and boron 8 kg/ha were applied in tomato field. Total dose of cowdung, TSP, MP, zinc, boron and one third of urea (200 kg/ha) were applied as basal dose before final ploughing. Rest of urea (20 kg/ha) was applied after 20 days and 45 days after the date of planting. Tomato was harvested during the period of February to April 2012. Irrigation was applied when the soil moisture content became below the field capacity (FC=20% MC).', 'Five different types of solar pump were tested at different times, suction and delivery heads. Among five solar pumps, two were locally designed and three were made by USA, Australia and China. BARI, USA and Australia made solar pumps were operated by 600 W solar panels. On the other hand, DU and China made solar pumps were operated by 1000 W solar panels. The average discharges of BARI, DU, USA, Australia and China made solar pumps were 60, 34, 100, 90 and 120 l/min, respectively. Yield of drip irrigated tomato (63.0 t/ha) was significantly higher than that of furrow irrigated tomato (53.5 t/ha). The yield of furrow irrigated brinjal (27.3 t/ha) was slightly higher than drip irrigated brijal (25.8 t/ha) but there was no significant difference between them. Water required for tomato cultivation in drip and furrow irrigations during the season were 254 and 590 mm and those for brinjal cultivation were 228 and 453 mm, respectively. Water savings by drip irrigation method over furrow irrigation for tomato and brinjal were 57% and 50% respectively. Total water applied during the boro season by solar pump in the rice field in Magura was 1024 mm. Water required during boro season for rice cultivation in Magura was 1481 mm.', 'Solar panels. drip irrigated, furrow irrigationstomato, Solar pump and brinjal.', 'GoB and World Bank', 9788000, 9788000, 0, 'Publication, Report', 'Training', 120, 'Solar Pump Irrigation Systems', 'Eco-Friendly Environment', '', '', ''),
(1246, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Farm Machinery and Postharvest Process Engineering Division, BARI, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Design and Development of a power weeder ', 'Gazipur', 'Medium', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '12-10-2009', '23-12-2010', '', '23-12-2010', 'a) To design and develop a power weeder for row crops\r\nb) To test the performance of the weeder for weeding maize and other row crops', 'The weeder was designed for upland crops. Three dimensional drawing of the power weeder was done by AutoCAD 2004. It was fabricated at workshop of FMP Engineering Division, BARI, Gazipur in 2009-10. It weighed about 145 kg with rotary blade attachment.\r\nGround wheel: The weeder was supported on two ground wheels made of 50 mm flat bar. The wheel diameter was 457 mm. Lugs, made of 40x40x5 mm MS angle bar of 12 mm height, were 55 mm apart to provide grip on soil. The wheel to wheel distance was adjustable between 560 mm and 610 mm which allowed operating between 30, 40, 70, cm rows.\r\nLaboratory test: To ascertain various design parameter of the weeder, laboratory test was carried out to determine the engine speed, rotary speed and fuel consumption. Fuel consumption was determined by operating the power weeder at field speed in tilled soil and measuring the time and volume of fuel required.\r\nThe experiment was conducted at the research farm of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur during rabi season of 2009-2010. The soil was clay loam. The experimental plots were well pulverized with a tractor and levelled with a bullock drawn ladder. Soil moisture was recorded before each treatment was imposed. Weeds species wise density of all weeds was recorded before and just after the treatments imposed. The weed sampling was done randomly in middle three rows in 50x75 cm quadrants. Three steel frames (50x75 cm) were placed in the middle of the row positioning 75 cm sides along the row.\r\n', 'A power weeder was designed and developed in FMP Engineering divisional workshop, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Gazipur in 2009-10. The drawing was drawn by AutoCAD 2004 software. Then the weeder was fabricated according to design with locally available materials and spare parts. A gearbox was incorporated to get the facility of forward and backward motion of the weeder. A hand clutch connected with a dog clutch was also added to get the turning facilities. The weeder was tested with its rotary blade attachment for weeding maize, soybean and groundnut in 2009-10. The treatments were T1&amp;ndash; Weedy (control), T2&amp;ndash;Hand weeding and T3&amp;ndash;Weeding by power weeder. Among the treatments, T2 and T3 produced statistically similar yields, but significantly higher than that of T1. Mechanical weeding by the power weeder saved significant weeding cost and associated labour requirement. T3 produced the highest benefit and the lowest weeding cost.', 'Design and Development, Power Weeder, Weeding maize', 'GOB', 1000000, 1000000, 0, 'Publication, Report', '', 0, 'Design and Development', 'Power Weeder', '', '', ''),
(1247, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'On Farm Research Division (OFRD)', 'Project', 'Coordinated Project on Assessment of Land Productivity and its Enhancement through Utilization of Surface Water in Coastal Area: BARI OFRD Component.', 'Noakhali and Khulna', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '20 July 2010', '19 July 2013', '20 July 2010', '19 July 2013', '1) Screening and adaptation trial of saline prone varieties and technologies (BARI)', '', '', 'Nutrient Management, Intercropping, Rain water harvest, Soil salinity', 'ADB', 4500000, 2125000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 240, '', '', '', '', ''),
