(1255, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Response of hybrid maize to boron and lime ', 'Hatibandha, Lalmonirhat, Patgram', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2009', '', '30-06-2009', 'a. To find out the effect of lime and boron on hybrid maize production.\r\nb. To find out the optimum and economic dose of boron for hybrid maize.', 'Two experiments were conducted in a farmers&amp;rsquo; field that represents the Non Calcareous Floodplain Soils under Tista Meander Floodplain (AEZ- 3) at Lalmonirhat and Hatibandha during the rabi season during 2006-2007 and at Lalmonirhat and Patgram during 2007-2008 and 2008-2009. The tested crop was hybrid maize (cv. BARI hybrid bhutta-5). The initial soil samples at a depth of 0-15 cm from the experimental fields were collected and analyzed following standard methods.\r\nThere were 8 treatment combinations comprising 4 levels of B (0, 1, 2 and 3 kg ha-1) and 2 levels of lime (0 and 2 t ha-1) during 2006-2007. During 2007-2008, sixteen treatment combinatios were used at Patgram according to the opinion of the expert members where 4 levels of B (0, 1, 2 and 3 kg ha-1) and 4 levels of lime (0, 1, 2 and 3 t ha-1) comprised the treatments. During 2008-2009 as farmers refused with sixteen treatments, eight treatments were used for Patgram. Besides, a blanket dose of N300P50K125S40Zn2 kg ha-1 and cowdung 5 t ha-1 was used for each of the locations under study. The experiments were laid out in a randomized complete block design with three replications. The unit plot size was 4 m X 5 m. Seeds were sown with a spacing of row to row 75 cm and seed to seed 25 cm and the seed rate was 25 kg ha-1. The seeds were sown at Hatibandha on 9th December and that of at Lalmonirhat on 15th December, 2006. During 2007-2008, 9th and 15th December and 2008-2009, 23rd and 11th December seeds were sown in Patgram and Lalmonirhat, respectively. Urea, TSP, MP, Gypsum, Zinc oxide and Boric acid were used as the source of N, P, K, S, Zn and B, respectively. All P, K, S, Zn, B and cowdung and 1/3rd N were applied at the time of final land preparation and the remaining 2/3rd N was applied in two equal installments each at 30 and 60 days after sowing. Lime (Dolomite) was applied 1 month before final land preparation during 2006-2007 at Hatibandha and Lalmonirhat and during 2007-2008 at Patgram. No lime was applied in the following year of lime application. Irrigation, insect, pest control and other intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. Data on yield and yield contributing characters at harvest were recorded and analyzed statistically following MSTAT package while the mean separation was done by Duncan&amp;rsquo;s Multiple Range Test. Post harvest soil and plant samples were also collected at harvest for analysis.', 'Field trials on hybrid maize (cv. BARI hybrid bhutta-5) was conducted in the farmers&amp;rsquo; field that represents the Non-Calcareous Floodplain Soils under Tista Meander Floodplain (AEZ- 3) at Hatibandha, Lalmonirhat and Patgram during the rabi season of 2006-2008. The objectives were to find out the response of lime and boron on maize yield and to find out the optimum level of B for hybrid maize production. At Lalmonirhat, the experiment was conducted in three consecutive years (2006-2007, 2007-2008 and 2008-2009) to see the residual effect of lime (applied in previous year) along with applied boron. The experiments were also conducted during 2006-2007 at Hatibandha and 2007-2008 and 2008-2009 at Patgram. Treatments comprising four levels of boron (0, 1, 2 and 3 kg ha-1 from boric acid) and 2 levels of lime (0 and 2 t ha-1 from dolomite) along with a blanket dose of N300P50K125S40Zn2 kg ha-1 and cowdung 5 t ha-1 were used but no lime was used at Lalmonirhat during 2007-2008 and Patgram during 2008-2009 to see the residual effect of lime. Lime played major role in augmenting the yield of maize. Maize was also found responsive to both boron and lime in the study areas. Soil of Rangpur region should be amended with lime @ 2 t ha-1 at least one month before cultivation. Boron @ 2.0 kg ha-1 along with the said dose of lime and a blanket dose of N300P50K125S40Zn2 kg ha-1 and cowdung 5 t ha-1 appeared to be the best-suited dose which may be recommended for maximizing the yield of hybrid maize at Hatibandha, Patgram and Lalmonirhat, respectively in the greater Rangpur region (AEZ-3).', '', 'BARC', 150000, 150000, 0, 'Report, Booklet', 'Training, Field days', 60, 'Response Boron and Lime on Maize Production', 'Maize', '', '', ''),
(1256, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Maximizing crop production through potassium management', 'Kustia, Rangpur (Burirhat), Ishurdi, Joydebpur', 'High', '', 'On-going', '01-10-2009', '30-10-2010', '', '30-.10-2010', 'i. To maximize of yield potential with the application of optimum potassium\r\nii. To estimate the uptake of potassium and make a balance sheet for the nutrients; and\r\niii. To monitor soil health after crop cultivation.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Methodology: Two field trials were conducted one at Gazipur (AEZ 28) and another at Multi Location Trial (MLT) site of Kushtia Sadar (AEZ 11) during the Rabi (winter) season of 2009-2010 at the farmers&amp;rsquo; fields. The objectives were to ascertain the yield potential of hybrid maize through K management. There were five treatments. T1: Native fertility, T2: High Yield Goal (HYG) Full dose of Fertilizer Recommendation Guide (FRG) dose of K (K100) + (N250P50S30Mg10B1.5 kg/ha), T3: HYG STB K (K80) + (N200P35S20Mg7B1.2 kg/ha), T4: HYG STB K (K80) + (N200P35S20Mg7B1.2 kg/ha) + 5 t/ha CD (Cow dung), T5: HYG STB K (K80) + (N200P35S20Mg7B1.2 kg/ha) + 3 t/ha PM (Poultry Manure). The experiments were laid out in Randomized Complete Block (RCB) design with three replications.\r\nField experiments on wheat were also carried out at the High Ganges River Floodplain Soils (AEZ-11) of Regional Agricultural Research Station (RARS), Ishurdi, Pabna and Agricultural Research Station, Burirhat, Rangpur of the Non-Calcareous Grey Floodplain Soil under Tista Meander Floodplain (AEZ-3) during the Rabi season of 2009- 2010. The objectives were to estimate potassium requirement for sustainable yield of wheat at both the locations where it is extensively cultivated. The variety used in the experiment was Shatabdi. There were five treatments viz. T1: Native fertility, T2: HYG FRG K (K75) + (N120P35S20Zn5B1.5 kg/ha), T3: HYG STB K (K65) + (N110P30S15 Zn4B1.5 kg/ha), T4: HYG STB K (K65) + (N110P30S15 Zn4B1.5kg/ha) + 5 t/ha CD, T5: HYG STB K (K65) + (N110P30S15 Zn4B1.5 kg/ha) + 3 t/ha PM. The experiments were laid out in RCB design with three replications.\r\n', 'During November 2009 &amp;ndash;October 2010 four experiments- two on maize and two on wheat were carried out at different agro ecological regions of the country (AEZ-3, 11 and 28) to find out the optimum doses of potash and other fertilizers for sustaining the crop productivity as well as for improving quality in the produces. Maize experiments were carried out at Gazipur (AEZ 28) and at Multi Location Trial (MLT) site of Kushtia Sadar (AEZ 11) and wheat experiments were at the High Ganges River Floodplain Soils (AEZ-11) of Regional Agricultural Research Station (RARS), Ishurdi, Pabna and Agricultural Research Station, Burirhat, Rangpur of the Non-Calcareous Grey Floodplain Soil under Tista Meander Floodplain (AEZ-3). BARI Hybrid Maize-5 and Shatabdi were used as the test variety for maize and wheat, respectively. Treatment (T5) package consisting of 3 t PM ha-1 with HYG (STB) chemical fertilizers (N200P35K80S20Mg7B1.2 kg/ha) appeared as the best suited combination for maximizing the yield of maize (8.54 and 8.51 t ha-1in Gazipur and Kushtia). Between the two organic fertilizers poultry manure proved superior.\r\nIncase of wheat, it can be concluded that the treatment package consisting of 3 t PM ha-1 with HYG (STB) chemical fertilizers (N110P30K65S15Zn4B1.5 kg/ha) appeared best combination for maximizing yield of wheat in the study areas (AEZ-11 and AEZ-3).', 'Maize, Wheat, Agro ecological regions, Potash, Organic fertilizers poultry manure', 'International Potash Institute (IPI)', 525000, 525000, 0, 'Report', 'Training, Field days', 60, 'Potassium Management', 'Crops', '', '', ''),
(1257, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Effect of poultry manure applied in combination with fertilizers on the yield and nutrient uptake of groundnut', 'Lalmonirhat, Burirhat and Dinajpur', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-06-2007', '30-06-2008', '', '30-06-2008', 'i. To investigate the yield potentiality of groundnut\r\nii. To study the influence on dry matter production and\r\niii. To determine the nutrient uptake as influenced by poultry manure in combination with chemical fertilizers\r\n', 'The experiment was carried out in the farmer&amp;rsquo;s field of Lalmonirhat and Dinajpur and at the Agricultural Research Station (ARS) farm, Burirhat (AEZ-3). The design of the experiments was RCBD . BARI Chinabadam-6 was sown on December 2, 3 and 6, 2007 in Dinajpur, Burirhat and Lalmonirhat respectively. Unit plot size was 3m X 2.4m. Seeds were sown with a spacing of 30 cm between rows and 15 cm within a row. Two to three seeds were sown per hill and plants were thinned out to one plant per hill after establishment. Hand weeding was done twice during the growing season. There were six treatments replicated three times. The initial soil samples were collected from the respective fields and were analyzed in the Soil Science Laboratory, BARI. Accordingly, the fertilizer doses and treatments were re-adjusted and based on theses, treatments were as follows: T1- N20P30 kg ha-1 + PM0 t ha-1\r\nT2- N20P30 kg ha-1 + PM2 t ha-1\r\nT3- N20P30 kg ha-1 + PM4 t ha-1\r\nT4- N60P30 kg ha-1 + PM4 t ha-1\r\nT5- N20P45 kg ha-1 + PM4 t ha-1\r\nT6- Absolute control\r\nNitrogen and phosphorus were used in the form of urea and TSP. All the treatments except the control, also received 20 kg sulphur (S), 50 kg K, 2 kg zinc (Zn) and 1 kg boron (B) ha-1, in the form of gypsum, muriate of potash, zinc sulphate and boric acid, respectively. All the fertilizers were incorporated in the soil during the final land preparation. A general application of lime (Dolomite) was applied @ 2 t ha-1 one month before final land preparation in Burirhat and Lalmonirhat to raise the soil pH for the availability of major plant nutrients.\r\nData collected on plant height, number of plants m-2, number of branches plant-1, number of pods plant-1, number of kernels pod-1, 100 pod and kernel weight and pod yield were done. Collected data were statistically analyzed and means of treatments were compared by DMRT. Ten randomly plants were carefully uprooted from each plot at harvest. The plants were first air dried, then oven dried at 70&amp;ordm; C for nutrient analysis.', 'Field experiments were conducted to study the changes in dry matter production and to determine the total nutrient uptake of groundnut as influenced by poultry manure in combination with chemical fertilizers. BARI Chinabadam-6 was sown on December 2-6, 2007 in Lalmonirhat, Burirhat and Dinajpur farmers&amp;rsquo; field. Six treatment combinations comprising two levels of each of N (20 and 60 kg ha-1), P ( 30 and 45 kg ha-1) and three levels of poultry manure (0, 2 and 4 t ha-1) along with one control treatment were tested in a randomized complete block design with three replications. A blanket dose of 20 kg S, 50 kg K, 2 kg Zn and 1 kg B ha-1 was used in each treatment and also to develop these practices in the farmer&amp;rsquo;s field of Burirhat, Lalmonirhat and Dinajpur. Poultry manure along with chemical fertilizers had significant influence on pod yield of groundnut in the study areas. Significantly higher pod yield Burirhat 2.94 t ha-1, Lalmonirhat 2.79 t ha-1 and Dinajpur 2.91 t ha-1 was produced with 4 t ha-1 poultry manure along with 45 kg P and 20 kg N ha-1. Therefore, 4 t PM ha-1 in combination of N20P45 kg ha-1 along with the blanket dose S20K50Zn2B1 kg ha-1 would be most suitable for the cultivation of groundnut in Northern region of Bangladesh (AEZ-3).\r\n', 'Groundnut, Poultry Manure, Chemical Fertilizers', '', 150000, 150000, 0, 'Report, Booklet', 'Training, Field days', 60, 'Fertilizer Recommemdation', 'Soils', '', '', ''),
