(1261, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Plant Pathology Division', 'Project', 'Development of Integrated Disease Management Technologies for soil borne Pathogens.', 'Head quarter, BARI, Gazipur-1701', 'High', 'Basic', 'On-going', '01 April 2010', '31 March 2013', '01 April 2010', '31 March 2013', '1) To collect and identify the soil borne plant pathogens associated with major crops from different parts of the country with conventional and advance molecular techniques.\r\n2) To design, implement and assess control measures of soil borne plant pathogens involving cultural, physical, organic soil amendments and chemical approaches and their integration.', '', '', 'Soil-borne pathogens, Advance molecular technique, Wilt disease', 'World Bank', 9205400, 7235433, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 450, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1262, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Postharvest Technology Division', 'Project', 'Coordinated Project on Contaminants and Adulterants in Food Chain and Their Mitigation: BARI Components', 'Chapai Nawabganj, Bogra, Jessore, Jamalpur, Tangail, Norsindi, Comilla and Gazipur.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01 May 2011', '30 June 2013', '20 July 2011', '30 June 2013', '1) To assess the various chemicals/pesticides and their dosages used to accelerate the ripening process of selected fruits (Mango, banana, Pineapple, Papaya) and vegetables (Tomato, Brinjal, Country Bean, Bitter Gourd).\r\n2) To Standardize the proper application method and dosages of safe ripening chemicals to artificially ripe of selected fruits and vegetables.\r\n3) To evaluate the effect of ripening chemicals/pesticides on the nutritional quality of selected fruits and vegetables and to determine their residual effect in the produces;\r\n4) To disseminate information among the growers, traders, interested agency personnel, extension and NGO personnel for the improvement of postharvest management of fruits and vegetables.', '', '', 'Chemicals, Pesticides, Safe ripening, Fruits and vegetables', 'BARC', 13189000, 1054000, 0, 'Booklet', 'Training', 90, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1263, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Agricultural Statistics and Information &amp; Communication Technology (ASICT)', 'Project', 'Strengthening of Information &amp; Comminication Technology (ICT) and Biometrical Facilities at BARI.', 'BARI Head Quater, Gazipur, Wheat Research Center, Dinajpur, Spices Research Center, Bogra, RARS, Jamalpur, RARS, Ishordi, RARS, Akbarpur, RARS, Jessore, RARS, Rahamotpur and RARS, Hathhazari.', 'Internet, Network, VPN and Office automation', 'Internet, Network, VPN and Office automation', 'On-going', 'July 2009', 'June 2013', 'July 2009', 'June 2013', '1) To strengthen capacity of Information &amp; Communication Technology (ICT) and Biometrical Facilities of BARI.\r\n2) To develop internal, national, regional and global linkages to improve research and information sharing.\r\n3) To facilitate creation of environment for the establishment of e-governance at the institute.\r\n4) To develop state-of-the art MIS, Web and Biometrical laboratory facilities.\r\n5) To develop human resources in the field of ICT and improve ICT services of the institute and to establish a division at BARI.', '', '', 'ICT, Biometrical facilities, Global Linkage, e-governance', 'GOB', 80000000, 32000000, 0, 'Website, e-mail, Office information', 'Training', 200, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1264, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Plant Breeding Division', 'Project', 'Breeding for Arsenic tolerant rice', 'Gazipur and Bhanga', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '2009', 'June 2013', '2010', 'June 2013', '1) Development of rice varieties tolerant to arsenic toxicity and reduced uptake.', 'Field and screening house trial, screening and development of breeding population through conventional and Marker assisted backcross breeding.', 'BRRI dhan47, IR44595, JEFERSON and HUA 564 have been found to have potential to give stable performance in highly arsenic contaminated soils. JEFERSON and TIE 90-1 along with previously reported BRRI dhan47 showed tolerance to 60 ppm soil arsenic. On the other hand, BRRI dhan29, HUA 564 and HUA 565 were found as most susceptible genotypes to increased level of arsenic in soil. Three mapping populations have been developed for QTL mapping through SSR genotyping. Around 500 SSRs have already been surveyed among the donor and recipient parent to find out polymorphic markers.', 'Arsenic, Toxicity, Soil arsenic, QTL, Tolerant variety', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
