(1270, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Training Division', 'Project', 'Development and Utilization of Bangladesh Rice Knowledge Bank (BRKB)', 'All over the country', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-04-2010', '31-03-2013', '', '31-03-2013', 'a. Generation of updated research-based rice information and develop technology package\r\nb. Providence of technical knowledge to enable the extension community, GO, NGOs and the private sectors\r\nc. Web based and electronic system for quick and effective response to the farming community.', '', '', 'Development and Utilization of Bangladesh, Rice Knowledge Bank, Rice', 'SPGR', 6070341, 4061137, 0, 'Report, Booklet', 'Training, Workshop', 330, 'Rice Knowledge Bank', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1271, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Plant Breeding Division, BRRI, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Develop rice varieties and hybrids for conservation agriculture systems in South Asia: Rice for mechanized direct seeding and water-saving irrigation.', 'Gazipur, Lalpur, Natore', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-06-2009', '30-06-2013', '', '30-06-2013', 'To evaluate exotic and locally developed hybrids under direct seeded conditions.\r\nTo assess the socio-economic aspects of direct seeding\r\n', 'The experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with three replications at the experimental farm of Bangladesh Rice Research Institute, Gazipur. In this method, sprouted seeds were sown on well prepared puddle land. Direct seeding was be done by using Drum Seeder. Unit plot size was 8 m. Thinning was done at proper time. Data was collected on plant height (cm), No. of effective tillers, No. of tellers/m2, Flag leaf length, days to 50% flowering, spikelet fertility (%), Panicle length (cm), TGW, Plot yield (kg) and Grain yield (t/ha). Fertilizers were applied @ 150: 100: 70: 60: 10kg/ha Urea, TSP, MP, Gypsum and ZnSO4 respectively. Basal: &amp;frac14; Urea, Full dose of TSP, Gypsum, Zn So4, 2/3 MP; Top dressing: &amp;frac14; Urea (15-20 DAT), &amp;frac14; Urea (35-40 DAT), &amp;frac14; Urea (booting Stage) and 1/3 MP at 2nd top dress of urea. Water management, Weeding and Insects and pest control were done when it is required.', 'Among the tested entries, two exotic hybrids and one locally developed hybrid performed well in late Boro transplanting condition. Exotic hybrid Tea and Riser out yielded both the check variety with more than 20% yield advantage. Locally developed hybrid BRRI hybrid dhan2 showed similar yield advantage over both the check variety. From this experiment it is clearly evident that BRRI hybrid dhan2 can easily be recommended for Aus season transplanting favorable variety and can be harvested within 100 days after sowing in direct seeded condition.', 'Direct seeding of rice, conservation agriculture systems', 'BARC', 900000, 900000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 10, 'Rice Varietal Development', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1272, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Plant Breeding Division', 'Project', 'Development and Dissemination of high yielding rice varieties for increasing productivity in salt affected tidal areas of Bangladesh.', 'BRRI, Gazipur and Moralganj, Bagerhat', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', 'July 2010', 'September 2013', 'October 2010', 'September 2013', '1) To develop and disseminate rice varieties incorporating genes for increased tolerance to salinity and high nutrition uptake efficiency under salinity stress, together with management practices with the potential to 4.5 t/ha yield over no yield under stress condition during dry season.\r\n2) To provide farmers with intermediate tall type improved varieties, combing tolerance to submergence and salinity and to disseminate new varieties in coastal areas for doubling yield of poor farmers during wet season.\r\n3) To involve farmers and local NGOs of target areas in participatory varietal selection approach for selection and dissemination of rice varieties. ', '', '', 'Tidal submergence and salinity tolerance rice varieties, Molecular tools, Salinity stress', '', 4000000, 3520000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 25, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1273, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Plant Breeding Division, BRRI, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Development of Hybrid Rice and Production of Parental Lines', 'Gazipur, Fenchujanj, Sylhet', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-01-2012', '30-09-2013', '01-05-2012', '31-08-2013', 'a.To develop high yielding hybrids having non-sticky cooked rice, good adaptability, tolerance to a biotic stresses suitable for Boro and T. aman season.\r\nb.To develop cost effective quality seed production of hybrid rice.\r\nc.To enhance capacity of public and private sectors on quality seed production of hybrid rice.\r\nd.To scaling up of yield maximizing technologies of BRRI developed hybrid rice varieties through farmers participation in different AEZ  of Bangladesh.\r\n', '', '', 'Hybrids having non-sticky cooded rice, Marker assisgted selection.', 'SPGR', 4171890, 1895000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 30, 'Rice Varietal Development', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1274, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Biotechnology Division,  Gazipur-1701', 'Project', 'Strengthening of Molecular Genetics and Genetic Engineering Research at BARI', 'Biotechnology Division, BARI, Gazipur and ARS, Pahartali, Chittagong', 'High', 'Basic, Adaptive, Applied', 'Completed', '01-06-2006', '30-06-2009', '', '30-06-2009', ' To identify disease and pest resistance genes from various wild relatives or landraces and cloning, sequencing and expression of those genes.\r\n To identify plant genes and genomes at molecular level, to characterize plants, diagnose plant disease and pests, assay of biologically active components and gene mapping.\r\n To develop transgenic plants using the identified beneficial genes through genetic transformation of the cultivated varieties\r\n To develop new genotypes of different crops through somatic hybridization and gene pyramiding.\r\n To introduce transgenics or somatic hybrids from abroad.\r\n To create facility for trial of transgenic crops and risk assessments and field release for commercial cultivations.\r\n To develop facilities for tissue culture, micropropagation and multiplication of high value fruit, vegetable and ornamental crops\r\n', 'A modern biotechnology laboratory for molecular genetics and genetic engineering research at BARI, Gazipur and improvisation of tissue culture micropropagation laboratory at Pahartali, Chittagong has been set up.', 'The project was scheduled to be completed by 30 June, 2009. To bring consistency in one item expenditure and project proposal provision, the project has been revised without increasing the cost and keeping the same implementation period. A decision was taken at the project review committee meeting held on 15-09-2008 in the Ministry of Agriculture suggesting DPP revision. The main cause of DPP revision was that the cost of construction material has increased substantially since the approval of the DPP. Hence, it was not possible to build four greenhouses with the fund allocated in the DPP. Besides, according to the recently gazetted Biosafety Guidelines Bangladesh as well as international convention, genetically engineered crops must be grown under confinement before release. Considering the above factors, construction of two phytotron greenhouse (250 m2) instead of four (two phytotron and two fan-pad ) greenhouses was proposed in this revision.', 'Strengthening of Molecular Genetics and Genetic Engineering, RFLP, DNA, RAPD, SSR, AFLP, PR', 'GOB', 154487000, 154487000, 0, 'Report', 'Training, Workshop, Field days', 0, 'Transgenic Crop Development', 'Brinjal, Potato, Papaya, Tomato, Food grain and Banana', '', '', ''),
(1275, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Biotechnology Divsion', 'Project', 'Standardization of protocol, in vitro production of BARI Kola-3 &amp; BARI Kola-4 plantlets and their validation in hilly areas', 'Agricultural Research Station, Ramgarh, Khagrachari, Raikhali, Chandragona, Rangamati Hill District\r\nPlant Tissue Culture Lab\r\nOodaleah Tea Estate, Mustafa Agro Products Ltd., Mustafa Group of Industries, Nagirhat, Chittagong\r\n', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-06-2011', '31-05-2014', '', '31-05-2014', 'i. To standardize protocol for in vitro production of BARI Kala-3 and BARI Kala-4\r\nii. To validate performance of tissue culture banana plantlets in hilly areas\r\niii. To improve capacity of public and private organization on tissue cultured banana plantlets production technologies\r\niv. To improve knowledge and skill of farmers and popularize scale up tissue cultured banana cultivation in hill areas\r\n', 'This project is designed as collaborative program. In vitro works are to be conducted at Biotech Lab of Biotechnology Division, BARI for standardization of existing protocol and mass production of quality banana plantlets (BARI Kola-3 and BARI Kola-4). Validation trail of plantlets will be established at Khagrachari Sadar, Ramgarh, Matiranga and Manikchari of Khaghrachari Hill District and Rangamati Sadar, Kawkhali, Kaptai and Rajasthali of Rangamati Hill District by Hill Agricultural Research Station, Ramgarh, Khaghrachari and Hill Agricultural Research Station, Raikhali, Rangamati Hill District, respectively. Plant Tissue Culture Lab, Mustafa Group of Industries, Mustafa Agro Products Ltd, Oodaleah Tea Estate, Nagirhat, Chittagong will be the counter part for disease free quality plantlets production and continuation of activities after completion of the project. Baseline survey for farmers&amp;rsquo; selection along with their land selection have been done with the help of upazila Agriculture Officer along with Sub-assistant Agriculture of respective areas.\r\ni. Optimization of protocol\r\nii. Mass production of plantlets\r\niii. Conducting validation trial\r\niv. Data recording, analysis and report preparation\r\nv. Organizing field days and\r\nvi. Leaflet/booklet preparation\r\n', 'The project was designed as a collaborative one involving Biotechnology Division of BARI; Hill Agricultural Research Station, Ramgarh, Khagrachari Hill District; Hill Agricultural Research Station, Raikhali, Rangamati Hill District and Plant Tissue Culture Lab, Oodaleah Tea Estate, Mustafa Agro Products Ltd, Mustafa Group of Industries, Nagirhat, Chittagong. Area and production of banana has been reduced in the Hill Tracts Regions due to its quality planting materials, pest, disease etc. To solve these problems, in vitro production packages for plantlets production has been optimize. More than 6000 plantlets have been produced and their validation trials have been established in eight upazillas of khagrachari and Rangamati Hill Districts. Two persons from each trial have been trained up for better management of the field. Also, sixteen Sub-Assistant Agriculture Officers from eight upazillas were trained up to help the farmers.\r\nMoreover, two Scientific Assistants (SA) were recruited for 36 months following BARI recruitment rules last year. One accountant and a store keeper have been working as part-time basis as per project proposal to maintain accounts and store from the beginning of the project. A two week hands on training on Basic Biotechnology and Tissue Culture for newly recruited SAs was organized. Four inception workshops have also been organized at four locations of the project activity. Necessary chemicals and capital items were purchased with the prior permission of the authority following PPR, 2008. To achieve the objectives, sword suckers of BARI Kola-3 and BARI Kola-4 from disease-free plant crop were collected from ARS, Raikhali, Rangamati and cultured in MS medium supplemented with different concentrations of BAP since 26th November, 2011 to optimize existing protocol for in vitro production of plantlets. A well developed protocol for in vitro plantlet production has been established. A total of Tk. 98.0 lakh was approved for the entire project period (36 months) where Tk. 45,33,625/- have been spent within 18 months. Cumulative financial progress is 95.66%.\r\n', 'Banana, in vitro propagation, tissue culture, BARI kola-3, BARI kola-4, validation trail', 'GOB', 9800000, 4533625, 0, 'Report', 'Training, Workshop, Field days', 78, 'Biotechnology', 'Crops', '', '', ''),
(1276, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Postharvest Technology Division', 'Project', 'Development of packages for fruits (mango, banana) and vegetables (yard long bean, pointed gourd, okra)', 'Chapai Nawabgonj, Bogra, Jessore, Tangail, Norsindi, Comilla, Chittagong, Rangamati and Gazipur.', 'High', 'Strategic, Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '30-06-2014', 'To standardize the packages of selected fruits (mango, banana) and vegetables (yard long bean, pointed gourd, okra) at farmers, traders and retailers level.\r\nQuality evaluation of fruits and vegetables in the packages', 'Baseline survey\r\nDifferent activities of the project will be done at 09 (nine) locations of the country, viz. Chapai Nawabgonj, Bogra, Jessore, Tangail, Norsindi, Comilla, Chittagong, Rangamati and Gazipur. A detail survey will be conducted by a selected questionnaire for each of crop in the project areas within the first four months. First, we have to select particular location from each selected district\r\nInput collection\r\nAvailability of sufficient inputs such as different types of packaging material and packages viz. HDPE, LDPE, foam net, plastic crates, plastic film, CFB carton, etc. will be collected from the packaging industries and local market as per our design and requirements. Chemicals, glass wares and other consumables will also be collected from local market.\r\nCollection of fresh fruits and vegetables\r\nSelected fresh fruits and vegetables will be collected from farmer&amp;rsquo;s field of the mentioned locations for conducting a series of experiment as per design from farmers&amp;rsquo; field to laboratory in order to find out different types of postharvest losses. After that, collected samples will be sorted, graded as per their size and analyzed for their physico-chemical parameters and nutritional quality, i.e., colour, texture, firmness, rotting loss/physiological weight loss, TSS, acidity, vitamin A &amp;amp; C, minerals, sugars, etc.\r\nConducting experiments\r\nA series of experiment will be conducted in Postharvest Technology Division, BARI for each of crops in particular sessions. Different types of packaging materials and packages as per thickness and design will be used for determining the storage life and keeping qualities.\r\nExperimental data recording, compilation and analysis\r\n', 'The storage life and keeping quality of the samples viz. freshness, color, firmness, pest and disease infestation, texture, marketability, physiological weight loss, decay/rotting, etc. will be recorded and analyzed with the untreated samples. The nutritional quality (vitmins, mineral, TSS, acidity, starch, sugar, etc) of the samples will also be analyzed.\r\nStandardization of packages and packaging materials&lt;\r\nAfter conducting the experiments and analyzing the data the standardized packages and packaging materials (e.g. size and thickness as per capacity) of the selected fruits and vegetables will be supplied to the supply chain.\r\nPublication of booklets/leaflets\r\nAfter completing the experiments booklets/leaflets, folder, etc will be published to generate information on appropriate packages and packaging materials of selected fruits and vegetables among the beneficiaries.\r\nStatistical analysis of collected data and final report preparation\r\nCollected data will be summarized and analyzed through tabular methods using descriptive statistics. Spreadsheet tool like MS Excel will be used for data entry and will analyze in computer using appropriate statistical method like MSTAT software. Periodical financial report will be submitted quarterly and technical report at half-yearly. Annual technical and financial report will be submitted at each year ending and the final technical and financial report will be submitted during project end.\r\n', 'Mango, Banana, Bean, Pointed gourd, Okra, Fruits, Vegetables', 'BARC', 1187000, 0, 0, 'Report Publication, Booklet', '', 0, 'Development of Packages ', 'Fruit and Vegetables', '', '', ''),
(1332, 'Social Upliftment Society', 'Social Upliftment Society', 'Project', 'Linking small farmers with supermarkets through promotion of per-urban agriculture ', 'Savar, Dhaka and Rangamati sadar', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	1) To form producers organizations with the farmers participating in production and marketing of high value crops.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	2) To Provide training to the farmers and managers of producers organization to improve their knowledge and skill on production, post-harvest handling and marketing of high value crops.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	3) To establish a market chain linking producer organizations with the supermarkets.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', '', 'market chain linking producer, marketing of high value crops', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1967000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'farmers linkage promotion with supermarkets', 'Peri urban agriculture', '1) Two producers group involving 100 small farmers each in two peri-urban areas have been formed.\r\n2) Farmers of both locations were trained and motivated to grow and sell four high value crops.\r\n3) Producers group have been linked with 3 supermarkets at Dhaka and one at Chittagong.\r\n4) Two hundred farmers of the two producers group were trained on production, post harvest handling and marketing of high value crops.', '1) Supply of high value quality vegetables and fruits to the supermarkets in the large cities will be ensured.\r\n2) Income and livelihood of large number of peri-urban farmers will be improved.\r\n3) Production and supply of high value crops in hill tarcts districts will increase and thereby small farmers in the hills will be benefited greatly.', ''),
(1333, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'FMP Engineering Division', 'Project', 'Up-scaling and adoption of hybrid dryer for quality grain seed production.', 'Gazipur, Jessore, Rajshahi and Dinajpur', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '1) To modify BARI developed hybrid drier for grain seed drying.\r\n2) To motivate farmers and small seed traders for adoption of the technology.', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1800821, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '1.	A hybrid dryer suitable for drying of paddy, wheat, maize and groundnut has been developed for farmers as well as for small seed traders.\r\n2.	This dryer may also be used for drying of fruits, vegetables and spices in normal sunny days as well as in cloudy or rainy days.\r\n3.	Many solar energy is used for operation of the dryer and it is environmentally friendly.\r\n4.	Good quality seed can be produced by using hybrid dryer.\r\n', '1.	Good quality grain seeds for good crop can be produced using this dryer.\r\n2.	The farmers and small seed traders will be economically benefited by reducing postharvest loss and good price of seeds.\r\n3.	Mainly solar energy is used for operation of the dryer and no carbon emission occurs from this dryer which is environmental friendly. \r\n', ''),
(1334, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Tuber crops Research Sub centre, Munshiganj', 'Project', 'Increasing storability of potato in natural storage and income generation through small scale processing of potato.', 'Munshiganj', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '1) To minimize post-harvest losses in potato.&lt;\r\n2) To increase storability of potato in natural storage condition.\r\n3) To engage female labourers in income generation activities by adopting Tuber Crops Research Centre (TCRC) developed processing technology.', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1492119, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '1.	Improved method of natural storage of potato can reduce about 155 loss and increase storability by about one month compared to farmers method.\r\n2.	Potato varieties viz Asterix, Cardinal, Course, Diamant, Esprit, Granola and Lady Rosetta are good for storing under natural condition.\r\n3.	Skill of female and male farmers on natural storage and processing of potato was developed.\r\n4.	Dried chips can be stored in plastic container and 12 months without quality deterioration. \r\n', '1.	Reducing storage loss of potato will increase farmers income.\r\n2.	Longer storability will ensure higher price and higher income to the farmers.\r\n3.	Chief making by the female members will can some additional income.\r\n4.	Availability and consumption of potato will be increased.\r\n', ''),
(1335, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Pulses Research Sub Station', 'Project', 'Quality improvement of farmers stored seeds of Mungbean, Lentil, Chickpea and its relation to diseases development in Bangladesh.', 'Gazipur, Pabna, Magura, Jhenidah, Chapainawabganj and Barishal', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05- 2009', '31-05-2011', '01-052009', '31-05-2011', '1) To asses the quality of the pulse seeds in the existing farmer''s storages.\r\n2) To asses disease and insect incidences in farmers storages.\r\n3) To find out the appropriate storage system to maintain seed quality in farmer''s storages.', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 0, 1878005, 0, '', '', 0, 'Pulse Crop', 'Mungbean, Lentil, Chickpea', '1.	Quality status of farmers storage seeds of lentil, chickpeas have been documented.\r\n2.	Pulse seeds (lentil, chickpeas mungbeans) performed better when stored in plastic drums.\r\n3.	Improved storage technology contribute to more seed germination (15%) and less seed uses (25%).\r\n4.	Integrated seed management technology has been developed for improving seed quality.\r\n', '1.	Storage-technologies developed would help the farmers maintain seed quality, reduce pest-incidences, induce more germination (15%) and less seed uses (25%) and more pulse production (about 30-40%)', ''),
(1336, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Spices Research Centre', 'Project', 'Seed production of Summer Onion: Determining appropriate method and Agro-ecological conditions for optimal production.', 'Gazipur, Bogra, Magura, Faridpur, Rajshahi and Thakurgaon', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '1) To determine the appropriate method(s) of summer onion seed production\r\nand\r\n2) To identify the potential seed production area under different agro-ecological conditions.', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1669403, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '1.	Appropriate method of seed production has been determined and areas of seed production have also been delineated to produce as high as 400 to 600 kg/ha seed yield.\r\n2.	Highest seed yield was obtained in Rajshahi region. \r\n', 'a.	Farmers, small seed traders and NGOs are getting interest of summer onion bulb and seed production.\r\nb.	Increased summer onion production in the country will reduce import and save foreign exchange. \r\n', ''),
(1337, 'Khulna University', 'Vice Chancellor', 'Project', 'Socio-economics and livelihood development of aqua-products trader in urban and periurban areas of Khulna Metropolis.', '', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1338, 'Research and Development Foundation for the poor', '', 'Project', 'Factors affecting shifting from food insecurity to food security, A study of selected Monga prone areas.', 'Rangpur Division and Kurigram District', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '1) To identify the factors/methods/practices that enabled many food insecure households of monga-prone districts of greater Rangpur region to become food secure households over the last 5-10 years period.\r\n2) To disseminate these identified factors/methods/practics among the similar monga-affected food insecure households through GOs and NGOs/POs engaged in improving the food security of the food insecure households.', '', '', 'factors/methods/practices that enabled many food insecure households', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1170960, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Food Security', 'Factors affect food insecurity', '1) The factors/methods/pratice that facilitated the monga affected or food insecure households to gradually move from food insecurity to food security have been identified and documented.\r\n2) Dissemination of these identified factors/methods/practices among the monga affected household benefit the monga affected households.\r\n3) Increase of cultivated land by food insecure household in any form contributed greatly towards food security.', 'Dissemination of the relevant information among the potential users and capacity building of the monga affected household members for adoption of the identified factors, would contribute greatly to overcome gradually the sufferings of monga and attain food security.', '');
