(1339, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Project', 'Hybrid rice technology and its sustainablity at the farm level: A study on food grain security in Bangladesh', 'Satkhira, Rangpur, Kurigram, Sherpur and Rajshahi', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2011', '30-06-2012', '01-01-2011', '30-06-2012', 'i) To examine adoption of hybrid rice at the farm level in the selected areas.\r\nii) To identify the factors responsible for shifting land to hybrid rice from inbred rice.\r\niii) To analyses the profitability of hybrid rice production at the farm level; and\r\niv) To To assess the level of consumer&amp;#39;s consumption preference and identify constraints towards hybrid the farmers&amp;#39; attitudes and perceptions on the newly developed rice varieties.\r\n', 'Site Selection: Farm household survey will be carried-out for this study. During Boro season (2010-11) a nation-wise survey under five major rice production environments. Rice Ecosystem: Favorable, Flood prone, Drought prone, Saline and Tidal submergence environmental areas.\r\nEmpirical analytical tool: Profitability Analysis: Cost and return analysis is the most common method of determining and comparing the profitability of different farm household or technologies. Profit is defined as the difference between the total revenue and total cost.\r\n', 'The Present study was undertaken in order to examine adoption rate of hybrid rice at the farm level, area shifting to hybrid rice from MVs, comparative profitability of hybrid rice to HYVs, document consumer&amp;#39;s preferences and constraints towards adoption of hybrid rice. Data were collected by conducting farm level survey survey in Favorable (Rangpur), Folld prone (Sherpur) drought pronmne (Rajshahi), Saline (Khulna) and Tidal submergence (Barisal) etc.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Hybrid rice, Adoption and profitability, Sustainability', 'BARC', 300000, 300000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Socio-Economics and Policy Program area', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1340, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Agro-forestry and Environment', 'Project', 'Assessment of techno-Socioeconomic resources and development of strategies for promoting food and economic securities of ethnic communities in Bangladesh', 'Ghoraghat, Dinajpur, Modhupur, Tangail and Durgapur, Netrokona', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-05-2011', '1) To document the traditional agro-technologies and livelihood status of the ethnic groups.\r\n2) To asses the contribution of traditional technologies to food security and livelihood.\r\n3) To develop policy for introduction and up-scaling', '', '', 'ethnic groups, traditional agro-technologies, food security ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1817240, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Food security', 'Ethnic Communities', '1) The ethnic communities were economically benefited from the higher yield of bottle gourd, country bean, tomato, cauliflower, boro and aman rice.\r\n2) Indigenous farmers were benefited from training gained skill on vegetable production.\r\n3) Production technologies of high yielding rice and vegetable varieties produced higher yield and economic benefit for livelihood improvement of ethnic communities.', 'Large scale adoption of the production technologies for high yielding vegetables and rice varieties will generate more income and improve the livelihood of ethnic communities.', ''),
(1341, 'Bangladesh Unnayan Parishad', 'Land Loss and Food Security', 'Project', 'Agricultural Land Loss and Food security: An Assessment', '24 villages from 6 divisions', '', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', 'May 2009', 'April 2010', 'May 2009', 'April 2010', '1) Estimate annual loss of aricultural land.\r\n2) Investigate into the present pattern of non. agricultural uses of the converted land.\r\n3) To determine the factors responsible for conservation of land.', '', '', 'Land loss, agricultural land', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1500000, 1442732, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', 'a.	An assessment on annual agricultural land loss has been made (0.64%) based on 600 farm families under 6 divisions.\r\nb.	Patterns of non-agricultural land use of converted agricultural land have been identified.\r\nc.	Factors responsible for conversion of agricultural land have been identified.\r\n', 'a.	Project outcomes can be used in the formulation of land use policy.\r\nb.	Projection on Agricultural land availability can be made.\r\nc.	Public awareness may be created to reduce rate of land loss.\r\n', ''),
(1342, 'Center for Agriresearch and Sustainable Environment and Entrepreneurship Development', 'Problematic Acidic Soils', 'Project', 'Maximizing yield of tea in some selected problematic acidic soils through improved management practices.', 'Brindaban T.E., Putijuri, Habigonj', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-05-2011', '1. To improve the physico-chemical properties of old tea soil by reducing acidity through liming (dolomite) to increase tea yield.\r\n2. To develop an appropriate method of fertilizer applications for tilla tea soil to increase fertilizer use efficiency.\r\n3. To evaluate an interaction effect of liming and pruning to bring young tea into brearing before 1st plucking for making good frame structure and increase in yield of tea in the long run.\r\n', '', '', 'Tea, Acidic soils, ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1930860, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '1.	Degraded old tea soil was improved substantially by application of dolomite which produced about 29% more tea yield in old tea soil than without dolomite in Brindaborn Tea Estate. pH of soil increased up to a desired level of 4.5  4.8. \r\n2.	Fertilizer use efficiency in tilla tea soil was improved through half-moon method of  application.\r\n3.	Quick growth and good configuration of young clonal plant was achieved by pruning (De-centering) including liming (Dolomite@200gm/plant).\r\n', '1.	Overall tea production in the country will be increased.\r\n2.	The tea industry will earn more foreign currency by exporting additional amount of tea after meeting domestic demand.\r\n', ''),
(1343, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Horticulture', 'Project', 'Collection, Conservation characterization and varietal development of Garlic and Onion through selection and molecular techniques', 'BAU, Mymensingh', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '1) To collect, characterize (morphological and molecular) and conserve local and exotic germplasms of garlic and onion crops for developing variety/varieties.\r\n2) To assess the yield potentials of garlic and onion germplasms; and\r\n3) To develop appropriate practices for the production of onion seeds.', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1980000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '1.	A few promising garlic and onion germplasm have been identified with yield potential of 2-3 times more than the present national average yield (2.86 t/ha).\r\n2.	One garlic germplasm (G-49) with yield potential of 9.4  t/ha has been registered and released by the National seed Board as BAU garlic-3 variety.\r\n3.	Onion seeds of the promising genotypes can be made available to the farmers for increasing yield, production and bet income. \r\n', 'a.	The highest yielding BAU garlic-3 (9.46 t/ha) would bring a dramatic improvement in garlic production through adoption and up scaling. The higher production would reduce import and save foreign currency.\r\nb.	Further evaluation and testing of 6 promising onion germplasm may result in high yielding onion varieties for large scale cultivation.\r\nc.	The conservation of 25 germplasm of garlic and 11 germplasm of onion enriched the B\r\nBAU plant genetic resources.\r\n', ''),
(1344, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Genetic Resources and Seed Division', 'Project', 'Rice germplasm collection and conservation from hilly, coastal, haor and other areas of Bangladesh', 'BRRI Head Quarter, Gazipur', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-05-2009', '30-11-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-11-2011', '1) To collect cultivated and wild rice germplasm from unexplored areas especially from hilly, coastal, haor and other areas of Bangladesh.\r\n2) To document the collected rice germplasm for different uses.', '', '', 'rice germplasm, collect cultivated and wild rice germplasm', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1936716, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Germplsm conservation', 'Rice', '1) About 100 percent of the targeted areas in aus season, 90 percent in aman season and 80 percent in boro season was explored during the reporting period.\r\n2) Out of 1078 collected samples 667 were identified as new collection at preliminary stage after duplicate sorting on the basis of same name and seed morphology.\r\n3) The passport data of the new collections were documented on the basis of the origin, habitat characteristics and photograph of the grain.\r\n4) 162 samples were rejuvendated, characterized morphologically and seed increased for further storage.\r\n5) About 400 samples are expected to be new germplasm after cross check with the BRRI gene bank collections after growing and characterization. ', 'BRRI gene bank enriched with the diversified new rice germplasm collections. The information generated from the characterization of jhum (Aus) and some aman and boro germplasm is ready for using by the end users especially by plant breeders. The novel collections might have potential gene sources against different stresses like drought, salinity, and submergence. The collection records through passport data will help in establishment of the identity and sovereignty on Bangladeshi rice germplasm. Any sample of rice germplasm collection from any corner of the country has no negative impact on the environment.', ''),
(1345, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Agricultural Economics Division', 'Project', 'Tracking in Adoption of Improved Rice Varieties in Different Production Environments / Ecosystems of Bangladesh ', 'Faridpur, Tangail, Sylhet, Mymensingh, Khulna and Patuakhali for Aus; Jessore, Kustia, Habiganj, Kishoreganj, Satkhira and Barisal for Aman and Dinajpur, Rajshahi, Rangpur, Jamalpur, Noakhali and Feni districts for Boro season.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2011', '31-12-2011', '01-01-2011', '31-12-2011', 'To conduct nation-wide survey at the community and household level to look into the adoption level of modern rice varieties and their constraints to adoption at the field level for giving feedback to the breeders for further refinement of the varieties for wider adoption at all levels and in all environments.', 'The study locations are given in the following table developed on the basis of rice area coverage and intensity of rice production in respective season and the information was collected from year Book of Agricultural Statistics, 2008.\r\nStudy location with different season: Faridpur, Tangail, Sylhet, Mymensingh, Khulna and Patuakhali for Aus; Jessore, Kustia, Habiganj, Kishoreganj, Satkhira and Barisal for Aman and Dinajpur, Rajshahi, Rangpur, Jamalpur, Noakhali and Feni districts for Boro season\r\n', '', 'Adoption, Feeback and domern vice varieties,', 'IRRI', 450000, 150000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Socio-Economics and Policy Program area', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1346, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'On-Farm Research Division', 'Project', 'Productivity enhancement through improved management practices, tools and techniques', 'Dhamrai Upazila of Dhaka and Singair Upazila of Manikganj district.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To increase crop productivity through improved management practices.\r\n2) To facilitate adoption of appropriate technology in the project area for minimizing yield gap of selected crops.', '', '', 'minimizing yield gap, crop productivity,  ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 4496000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Crop productivity enhancement', 'Rice, Mustard, Wheat, Jute', '1) Yield of individual crop like rice, mustard, wheat, maize and jute will be increased at least 20-30% over existing yield level through adoption of modern and recommended production technologies.\r\n2) Cost of production of each crop can be minimized through appropriate machine operations by trained farmers.', '', ''),
(1347, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Maximization of crop yield in T. aman-Mustard-Boro cropping pattern by agronomic manipulation', 'Dhanbari and Kalihati Upazila of Tangail district.', '', 'Adaptive', '', 'September 2011', 'August 2014', 'September 2011', 'August 2014', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	1) To adapt, adjust and refine the agronomic best practices (varietal selection, tillage options, water management) for T. aman-Mustard-Boro cropping pattern.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	2) To increase system productivity and net income of farmers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	3) To improve knowledge and skill of the farmers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', '', 'T. aman, Mustard, Fallow land, Productivity', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 2700000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1348, 'Bangladesh Institute of Nuclear Agriculture', 'TC and P Division', 'Project', 'Yield maximization of mustard and sesame through improved package of production practices in some selection areas of the country.', 'Jessore, Narail, Jhenaidah, Faridpur, Kushtia and Chuadanga Districts.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To identify and up-scaling suitable mustard and sesame varieties for specific location towards maximizing yields.\r\n2) To validate appropriate and location specific high yielding package of production practices of the selected mustard and sesame varieties for increased production and maximizing farm income.\r\n3) To improve knowledge and skill of the farmers about improved production technologies of mustard for increased production and cropping intensity.\r\n4) To increase system productivity and farm income through inclusion of improved mustard and sesame production technology in the cropping pattern.', '', '', 'Mustard and sesame, Yield maximization of mustard and sesame', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 4000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Oil seed crop production', 'Mustard and Sesame', '1) Identified suitable high yielding mustard and sesame varieties for all the locations studied.\r\n2) Improved knowledge and understanding of farmers and extension personnel on the improved technologies related to mustard and sesame to the door steps of farmers in working areas.\r\n3) Established profitable cropping pattern including oil seeds cultivation.\r\n4) Increased awareness among farmers about the benefit modern mustard and sesame cultivation.\r\n5) The practices identified and tested are environmental friendly and sustainable.\r\n6) Trained 240 farmers and extension workers and 60 extension personnel.\r\n7) BINA scientists and NGO personnel made direct contact with 2400 farmers and exchanged views regarding performance of BINA varieties.', '', ''),
(1349, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Regional Agricultural Research Station (RARS), Jamalpur', 'Project', 'Integrated management of major diseases of brinjal and tomato in Jamalpur &amp; Sherpur Districts.', 'Jamalpur and Sherpur districts.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To develop effective technology for controlling major diseases of brinjal and tomato and thereby increase yield.\r\n2) To evaluate and up-scaling the technology with the vegetable growers of Jamalpur and Sherpur districts.\r\n3) To increase the knowledge and skill of the target beneficiaries.', '', '', 'major diseases of brinjal and tomato, vegetable growers of Jamalpur and Sherpur', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1797000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Vegetable production and Disease management', 'Brinjal and Tomato', '1) Identification of NARS promising technologies and dissemination to the vegetables growers.\r\n2) Verification of NARS proven technology.\r\n3) Capacity developed through training of the improve technology.', '', ''),
(1350, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of poultry Science', 'Project', 'Formulation of cost effective poultry feed using parboiled rice polish', 'Poultry Farm and poultry Science Laboratory, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', '', 'Adaptive', '', '15-09-2011', '15-09-2014', '15-09-2011', '15-09-2014', '1) To assess the effects of different levels of dietary PRP and phytase in mass or pellet on the meat and egg production of chicken and duck.\r\n2) To recommend a cost effective and cheaper diet(s) for chicken, ducks, and quails for increasing productivity and profitability.\r\n', '', '', 'cost effective poultry feed, meat and egg production', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 4000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Poultry sector development', 'Poultry feed', '1) It is expected that technology adoption for better utilization of PRP would reduce the feed cost by 10-12% in chicken and ducks.\r\n2) Reduced feed cost in PRP based diets also expected to decrease production cost and might increase the profitability of poultry farming.\r\n3) Appropriate diet combination and their better use in correct form should increase meat and egg production by about 15%.', '', ''),
(1351, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Technology', 'Project', 'Adaptation of high valued fish species shing (Heterponeustes fossilis) culture technology for maximizing prediction in three Agro-Ecological zones of Bangladesh.', 'Narsingdi, Habiganj and Sirajganj districts.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To select the best stocking densities from the available shing culture technologies.\r\n2) To identify the best production of shing culture technologies in relation to different agro-ecological zones.\r\n3) To assess the economic viability of shing culture technology in different agro-ecological zones.\r\n4) To develop the skill &amp; knowledge of the farmers on shing culture.', '', '', 'shing (Heterponeustes fossilis), agro-ecological zones.', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 7989000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fish production', 'Shing (Heterponeustes fossilis)', '1) Refined production packages of shing (H. fossilis) culture technology will be available.\r\n2) The production of high valued fish shing (H. fossilis) will be increased.\r\n3) High valued fish shing (H. fossilis) culture technology suitable in three different agro-ecological zones will be available.\r\n4) Farmers skill &amp; knowledge will be increased.', '', ''),
(1352, 'Rural Development Academy', 'Project planning and Monitoring, Rural Development Academy', 'Project', 'Improvement of appropriate rice based cropping systems in Barind areas', '3 Upazilas of Bogra district, Sherpur, Shajahanpur and shibganj Upazila and on station trial of RDA demonstration farm at sherpur Upazila, Bogra.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1. Selection and validation of improve methods and technology packages for increasing yields for rice, maize, potato in major rice based, and\r\n2. Increasing system productive of major rice-based cropping systems in 3 upazila of Bogra district.', '', '', 'major rice-based cropping systems, increasing yields for rice, maize, potato', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 7000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Crop production', 'Rice', '1) The proposed cropping pattern may be found suitable for Barind highlands after the completion of the trials on the basis of rice yield gap minimization, farmers profitability and soil improvement. The selected farmers will be provided training on higher yield concerned. So, they are able to overcome yield gap. Increased production in fact, to ensure their additional income, food security and sustainability. The knowledge of the farmers on the use of balanced inputs including organic matter is likely to contribute to reduce production cost and improving soil fertility. ', '', ''),
(1353, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'On-Farm Research Division', 'Project', 'Maximizing yield gaps in rice based cropping systems in three nothern districts', 'Rangpur, Kurigram and Bogra districts.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) Selection and validation of improved methods and technology packages for increasing yields of rice, potato and mustard in major rice based\r\n2) Increasing system productivity of major rice based cropping systems in three Upazilas of Bogra, Rangpur and Kurigram districts.', '', '', 'Maximizing yield gaps, system productivity, rice based ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 6600000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Yield Gap Minimization', 'Rice', '1) Existing farming technology and use of inputs by the farmers will be known.\r\n2) Improved production package of major rice based patterns will be identified.\r\n3) Yields of rice, potato and mustard will be increased by minimizing yield gap\r\n4) Farmers knowledge about balance use of inputs including OM for maintaining soil fertility will be raised.\r\n5) Income as well as livelihood of the farmers will be increased.', '', ''),
(1354, 'Bangladesh Cotton Development Board', 'Cotton Development Board, Farmgate, Dhaka-1215', 'Project', 'Testing, Validation and Up-scaling of cotton-rice intercropping in Chittagong Hill districts', 'Bandarban, Rangamati and Khagrachari district', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-09-2011', '30-10-2014', '01-09-2011', '30-10-2014', '1.to develop improved crop production practices incorporating hill cotton and rice substituting traditional jhum system.\r\n2. to improve system productivity and \r\n3. to reduce soil erosion. ', '', '', 'jhum system, soil erosion, improved crop production practices incorporating hill cotton', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 3441000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Cropping pattern development', 'Cotton-Rice', '1) Improved production technologies of growing cotton and rice in intercropping system developed, tested and standardized for large scale adoption in the uplands of Chittagong hill districts.\r\n2) Traditional jhum cultivation substitute by cotton-rice inter cropping system\r\n3) Yields of cotton and rice increased by at least 50% and 20% respectively.', '', ''),
(1355, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'On-Farm Research Division (OFRD)', 'Project', 'Crop Intensification through incorporating quick growing fruits and vegetables into existing cropping systems in Jhalokathi and Potuakhali districts.', 'Dumki and Potuakhali sadar of Potuakhali and Jhalokathi sadar of Jhalokathi district.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To improve cropping systems incorporating quick growing high value fruits and vegetable crops into existing cropping systems in tidal floodplain of Patuakhali and Jhalokathi districts.\r\n2) To increase farm income through production and marketing of fruits and vegetables\r\n3) To develop farmers organization for growing and marketing high value crops.', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 4625000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Crop intensification', 'Fruit and vegetables', '1) Constrainsts to upland crop production during post monsoon dry season identified and documented.\r\n2) New management practices and technologies evolved that lead to improved cropping system, more efficient use of inputs, higher yields, or other atributes that increase profit.\r\n3) Crop production models and predictability of the incidence of tides developed in order for avoiding crop damage.\r\n4) Increased cropping intensity\r\n5) Increased capacity of communities to grow vegetables and fruits\r\n6) Market chains developed for targeted fruits and vegetables.', '', ''),
(1356, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Polmology Division, Horticulture Research Centre', 'Project', 'Validation and Up-scaling of year round pineapple production technology in hilly areas', 'Maulavibazar, Rangamati and khagrachari district.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To evaluate the validity of the year round pineapple production technology in selected hilly areas.\r\n2) To increase farmers income by producing and marketing of pineapple round the year\r\n3) Up scaling the year round pineapple production technology in selected hilly areas.', '', '', 'year round pineapple production, Hilly areas ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Year round fruit production', 'Pine Apple', '1) Four hundreds farmers will be trained on improved production techniques of pineapple round the year. After having the training on propagation and production of pineapple by using the technology the trained 400 farmers will be awarded about importance of the technology. Four hundreds farmers will be interested to adopt the technology after observing the technology through field day.\r\n2) Adaptive trial plots will be established at the 15 farmers field for disseminating the proven technology. By using the technology 15 progressive farmers will be directly benefited by increasing yield and marketing their produce obtaining the pineapple fruit at their expected time according to their need.\r\n3) As the technology will help them for obtaining the fruit round the year and at lean period as well. Hence, pineapple production an income of 15 progressive farmers at the project area will be increased. ', '', ''),
(1357, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Director (Research)', 'Project', 'Development of integrated crop-fish production system using ditch-and-dyke method in low lying areas of Jhalokathi and Bogra region.', 'Jhalokathi sadar and Rajapur Upazila of Jhalokathi and Gabtoli Upazila of Bogra districts.', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To increase the system productivity in low lying areas convert low land (beel) into ditch and dyke for simultaneous crop production and fish culture.\r\n2) To increase farm income', '', '', 'Ditch and dyke method for growing crops, Low lands converted into ditch, vegetable crops in the dykes', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 4976000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Integrated crop production', 'Crop cum fish', '1) Low lands converted into ditch and dyke system by 10 farmers in 3 Upazilas and 3 districts.\r\n2) Ditch and dyke method for growing crops and raising fish tested, validated and adopted by farmers.\r\n3) Vegetable crops/varieties and quick growing fruit species validated and adopted by farmers.\r\n4) Screening of fish species suitable for raising in ditches are screened.\r\n5) Production technologies are validated and suitable planting time for growing vegetable crops in the dykes determined.\r\n6) Production technologies and suitable rearing time for raising fishes in the dykes identified.\r\n7) System productivity of participating farmers in low lying areas increased.', '', ''),
(1358, 'AS and N', 'Department of As&amp; N, CVASU, Khulshi, Chittagong', 'Project', 'Least cost feed formulation for poultry through the production of fermented yeast product from locally available feed resources.', 'Chittagong Veterinary and Animal Science University, Khulshi, Chittagong', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1359, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pathology, Faculty of Veterinary Science', 'Project', 'Calf mortality in large and small holder cross bred dairy cattle: Epidemiological and Pathological investigation and mitigation.', 'Muktagacha, Mymensingh and Sahjadpur, Sirajganj', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '', '', '1) To identify epidemiological factors that influence calf morbidity and mortality.\r\n2) To isolate and characterize the etio-pathological agents associated with calf.\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	3) Development of methods &amp;amp; their application to prevent morbidity and mortality of calves.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '', '', '', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 6000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Livestock production', 'Calf', '1) Risk factors that directly or indirectly influence the morbidity and mortality of calves will be identified.\r\n2) Methods will be available for rapid diagnosis and characterization of the ecological agents.\r\n3) Based on the identified pathology and causes of calf morbidity and mortality, better management strategies of the diseases of calves will be formulated.\r\n4) One hundred fifty trained farmers on dairy farming will be available in the project area.', '', ''),
(1360, 'Khulna University', 'Agotechnology discipline', 'Project', 'Development of management package for powdery mildew of BAU kul and apple kul', 'Satkhira, Jessore, Natore', '', 'Adaptive', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To identify the disease occurrence and severity of powdery mildew from the study area.\r\n2) To characterize the pathogen of powdery mildew of jujube.\r\n3) To find out the appropriate control measures of the disease.', '', '', 'powdery mildew, BAU and Apple Kool, Jujube', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 4500000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Management package for BAU and Apple Kool', 'Powdery Mildew', '1) Epidemiological pattern of the disease will be identified.\r\n2) The morphological characterization and variability of the pathogen Oidium species causing powdery mildew diseases of jujube of different regions of Bangladesh will be available.\r\n3) The pathogenic capacity of different isolates will be identified.\r\n4) Molecular characterization and genetic grouping of the isolates of Oidium causing powdery mildew diseases of jujube of different regions of Bangladesh will be done which will help marker based identification of new strain and races of the pathogen for set up control measures.\r\n5) Appropriate chemical control measures for the million of the farmers and fruit traders will be prescribed for controlling in the field.\r\n6) Ultimately production and shelf life of jujube will be increased. ', '', ''),
(1361, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Bio-technology Division', 'Project', 'Standardization of protocol, and in virto production of BARI Kala-3 &amp; BARI kala-4 plantlets and their validation trial at hilly areas.', 'BARI (Gazipur), Nazirhat (Chittagong), Hill Agriculture Research Station, Ramgarth (Khagrachari)', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', 'To standardize protocol for in vitro production of BARI and Kala-3 and BARI Kala-4.\r\nTo validate performance of tissue culture banana plantlets in hilly areas.\r\nTo improve the capacity of farmers on tissue cultured banana plantlets production.\r\n', '', '', 'BARI Kala-3, BARI Kala-4, Hilly areas', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 9789000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fruit production', 'Banana', '1) A simple and reliable protocol for in vitro production of BARI Kala-3 and BARI Kala-4.\r\n2) 30,000 quality banana plantlets.\r\n3) Well trained 4 SA/LT at Biotech lab BARI and Plant tissue culture lab. Mustafa Agro product Ltd. Oodaleah Tea Estate, Nagirhat, Chittagong.\r\n4) Well trained 100 farm members from 50 banana growing families and 40 SAAO/SA.\r\n5) 50 tissue culture banana orchard at khagrachari and Rangamati Hill districts.', '', ''),
(1362, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Extension and Rural Development', 'Project', 'Rice production in Drought Prone Areas of Bangladesh', 'Dinajpur, Rangpur, Rajshahi, Bogra, Joypurhat and Naogoan districts', '', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. To identify factors responsible for lower yield of rice in the study areas\r\n2. To adapt rice varieties suitable for drought prone areas\r\n3. To improve soil fertility level for sustainable rice production; and\r\n4. To increase adaption capacity of rice farmers under changing climate.', '', '', 'drought prone areas, improve soil fertility, changing climate.', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 9789000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Crop production in drought prone area', 'Rice', '1) Rice production increased by 10-15%.\r\n2) Drought tolerant rice varieties selected.\r\n3) Soil fertility improved.\r\n4) farmers awareness on rice production under climatic stress condition and adaptive capacity increased up to 10%.', '', ''),
(1363, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Crop intensification in nothern region of Bangladesh through up-scaling the production of short duration rice and mungbean.', 'Rangpur, Gaibandha, Nilphamari, Lalmonirhat, Kurigram, Dinajpur, Thakurgaon and Panchagarth', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. To increase cropping intensity and system productivity by at least 15-20% in upland ecosystem of northern Bangladesh and\r\n2. To minimize ground water use in rice cultivation by 20 %.', '', '', 'increase cropping intensity, northern Bangladesh, ground water use', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 9800000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Crop Intensification', 'Rice', '1) At least 2000 farmers in 8 nothern districts adopt alternative cropping system.\r\n2) Cropping intensity increased by at least 25% through incorporation of mungbean in the system.\r\n3) System productivity enhanced by growing an additional crop (mungbean) and high yielding variety of aus and aman rice.\r\n4) Irrigation water saved to the extent of 20%.\r\n5) Additional employment opportunity generated.\r\n6) Seasonal food insecurity alleviated through advancing aman rice harvesting time by one month (October).', '', ''),
(1364, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetics and Plant Breeding', 'Project', 'Intensification of rice based cropping system incorporating short duration oilseed mustard varieties.', 'Haluaghat, Muktagacha and Mymensingh sadar of Mymensingh and Bagha of Rajshahi, Ishurdi and Pabna sadar of Pabna districts.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. Increase cropping intensity in the proposed regions of Bangladesh by at least 20 percentage points and\r\n2. Increase total productivity in rice based cropping patterns by at least 15%.', '', '', 'Increase cropping intensity, Incorporating, Rice, Mustard.', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 8286000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Cropping System Deveopment', 'Rice and Mustard', '1) Prevailing T. aman-Boro cropping system replaced by a more intensive T. aman-Mustard-Boro cropping system;\r\n2) High yielding, short duration mustard varieties selected and disseminated in project areas;\r\n3) Mustard yield increased by 60% and\r\n4) 800 farmers in 6 Upazilas trained on improved production practices.', '', ''),
(1365, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Plant Breeding Division', 'Project', 'Yield gap reduction through short duration rapeseed mustard and Sesame varieties under existing cropping system', 'Sirajganj sadar &amp; Shahjadpur of Sirajganj; Sherpur sadar, Nakla and Nalitabari of Sherpur and Shibganj &amp; Gomostapur of Chapai Nawabganj Districts.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. To verify the yield potential of modern varieties of short duration rapeseed mustard and sesame in the farmers field for replacing their traditional cultivars.\r\n2. Application of improved production technologies for increase yield.\r\n3. Up scaling of selected varieties acceptable to the farmers in the vicinity.', '', '', 'Rapeseed, Yield gap, sesame.', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 3958000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Yield gap reduction', 'Repeseed; Mustard', '1) Income generation of the local contractual farmers. Capacity building among the contract farmers which will help to disseminate technology in oil crop growing areas quickly towards replacement of the traditional varieties and practices. Awareness building among the oil crop growers for modern varieties. Established the technologies as sustainable in the dominant cropping pattern where oil crops included as component crop.', '', ''),
(1366, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Pulses Research Centre, Gazipur', 'Project', 'Validation and Up-scaling of mungbean and lentil technologies in the rice based cropping system in Bangladesh.', 'Gopalganj, Jessore, Jhenaidah, Gaibandha, Rangpur and Kurigram', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. To verify the yield potentiality&nbsp; of promising short duration lentil lines and mungbean varieties in the farmers field.\r\n2. To adopt lentil relay cropping in the rice field.\r\n3. To established the short-duration mungbean in variety within a cropping system of lentil/mustard wheat/Potato/Maize, Mungbean-T.Aman rice.\r\n', '', '', 'Validation and Up-scaling, Mungbean, Lentil, Rice based cropping system', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 13000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Validation of Technology', 'Mungbean, Lentil', '1) Short duration mungbean cultivation expanded.\r\n2) Super early Lentil production expanded.\r\n3) Improved production practices of lentil and mungbean adopted incorporating in intensive cropping systems.\r\n4) Knowledge, skill and capacity of farmers in growing pulse crops increased.', '', ''),
(1367, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Plant Pathology Division', 'Project', 'Rhizome rot disease of Ginger and its management', 'Rangpur, Bogra, Tangail, Mymensingh, Bandarban, Chittagong, Khagrachari, Rangamati, Pabna and Gazipur', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', 'To identify the microorganisms associated with rhizome rot.\r\nTo develop appropriate management technologies for controlling rhizome rot disease in Bangladesh\r\nValidation of developed technologies to the farmers.', '', '', 'Ginger, Microorganism, Rhizome Rot, ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 4500000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Disease and pest management', 'Ginger', '1) Disease free ginger will be produced.\r\n2) Ginger production will be increased.', '', ''),
(1368, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Entomology Division', 'Project', 'Selection and application of BPH management technologies in Sirajganj', 'Tarash Upazila of Sirajganj', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', 'Validation and selection of suitable technologies for management of BPH.\r\nImproved management practices for controlling BPH by the farmers in Sirajgonj (Tarash).\r\nTo improve knowledge and skill of participating farmers.', '', '', 'Technologies Management, Controlling BPH', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 4150000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Pest management', 'Rice', '1) BPH management technologies will be validated and selected for up-scaling.\r\n2) About 250 farmers in Tarash Upazila are adopting improved management practices for controlling BPH.\r\n3) Rice yield loss due to BPH will be reduced.', '', ''),
(1369, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'OFRD, BARI, Barind Station', 'Project', 'Validation of drought management techniques for sustainable crop production in the high barind tract', 'Nahole of Chapai Nawabganj, Godagari of Rajshahi and Shapahar of Naogaon Districts.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '&lt;ol&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		To increase cropping intensity under rainfed condition.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		To increase crop yield though appropriate drought management techniques&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		To increase knowledge and skill of the farmers on drought management techniques and also to increase farm level income.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n', '', '', 'High Barind Tract, Sustainable crop production, Rainfed condition.', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 3992000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Drought management', 'Crops', '1) Suitable drought management practices/options in HBT developed.\r\n2) Yield gap through adoption of modern/appropriate technology.\r\n3) Cropping intensity increased by 20%.\r\n4) Farmers income increased by 10%.', '', ''),
(1370, 'Patuakhali Science and Technology University', 'Agronomy Department', 'Project', 'Development of Intensive Cropping system in two coastal districts for increasing production', 'Jhalokathi sadar and Rajapur of Jhalokathi and Dumki and Mirzaganj of Potuakhali districts.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. To improvement yield and production of rice through testing validating and delivery of improved management practices suitable for aman rice under tidal flood condition\r\n2. To generate and identify best management practices for growing upland crops (maize, sesame, and chickpea) during rabi (dry) season; and\r\n3. to increase knowledge and skill of participating farmers in growing upland crops and aman rice.', '', '', 'Intensive cropping system, Coastal district, rice, ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 9780000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Cropping System Deveopment', 'Rice, Chickpea, Maize and Sesame', '1) Management practices appropriate for obtaining higher yield of transplanted aman rice in tidal flood condition are developed, validated and adopted.\r\n2) A large number of farmers adopted improved varieties and production practices.\r\n3) Farmers are getting higher yield in aman.\r\n4) A set of experiments and on farm trials conducted and improved practices for growing upland crops after aman rice developed and standardized.\r\n5) Over 150 farmers in 2 districts adopted improved cropping systems involving transplanted aman and upland crops (Chickpea, maize and sesame).', '', ''),
(1371, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Regional Agricultural Research Station (RARS), Rahamotpur, Barishal', 'Project', 'Validation and Up-scaling of improved pulse production technologies for crop intensification', 'Madaripur, Khulna, Kayra, Barishal, Jhalokathi, Tangail and Mymensingh', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. Technology validation for adapting mungbean lentil, blackgram and chickpea in Madaripur, Barisal, Jhalakati, Tangail and Mymensingh districts identified.\r\n2. Screening of germplasm for resistance to Fusarium/Sclerotium blight of lentil and YUMV and CLS of mungbean and\r\n3. Increase production through intensive cultivation of mungbean, lentil, blackgram and chickpea in Madaripur, Khulna, Barisal, Jhalakati, Tangail, and Mymensingh districts.', '', '', 'Validation, Pulse production, Lentil, Chickpea, Mungbean', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 13388000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Validation of Technology', 'Pulses', '1) Bio-physical factors containing pulse production in the southern districts identified and documented.\r\n2) Improved varieties of lentil, mungbean, blackgram and chickpea suitable for specific locations in Tangail, Mymensingh, Madaripur, Barishal and Jhlokathi districts identified.\r\n3) Production technologies including pest management strategies developed, validated and disseminated through location specific on farm trials.\r\n4) 500 farmers of three southern districts and two central districts trained on improved pulse production technologies pulses.\r\n5) 500 farmers use improved varieties and component technologies covering 150 ha in Barishal, Jhalokathi, Madaripur, Khulna, Tangail, Mymensingh districts.', '', ''),
(1372, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Irrigation water management Division', 'Project', 'Testing, Validation and Up-scaling of water saving technology in rice production', 'Naogaon', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '&lt;ol&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Harvesting and ponding of rainwater for utilization in mitigating drought affected rice;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Minimizing conveyance loss and increasing water use efficiency in rice production;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Increase irrigated area coverage by adopting water saving technologies; and&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Avoiding repeated priming in STW.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n', '', '', 'Irrigation, Water management, DTW, water use efficiency', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 3995000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Irrigation and Water Management', 'Rice', '1) Fifteen to twenty percentof irrigation coverage in DTW increased.\r\n2) Water use efficiency in rice production increased by 10 to 15%.\r\n3) Drought in rice mitigated as well as yield increased by 25% to 20%.\r\n4) STW priming avoided\r\n5) Knowledge and skill of at least 200 farmers increased.', '', ''),
(1373, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Regional Agricultural Research Station (RARS), Hathazari, Chittagong', 'Project', 'Development of an integrated rice-fish production system in lower Meghna river floodplain of Noakhali and Lakshmipur districts.', 'Sonaimuri, Begumganj, Noakhali sadar, Subarnachar (Noakhali) and Ramgati (Lakshmipur)', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1) Improving the system productivity through incorporation of modern varieties of rice and fish in lower Meghna flood plain area.\r\n2) Improvement of traditional cropping pattern through adoption of short duration and long stature transplanted aman rice varieties in water logged areas.\r\n3) Increasing cropping intensity in boro rice-fallow system by incorporating fish culture.\r\n4) Increasing farm family income through community mobilization.', '', '', 'Increasing cropping intensity, Increasing farm family income', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 7500000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Integrated Crop Management', 'Rice-fish', '1) Improved cropping systems evolved through incorporation of modern varieties of rice and up lands crop in Meghna river floodplain of Noakhali and Lakshmipur;\r\n2) Adoption of short duration and long stature transplanted aman rice varieties adopted in water logged areas;\r\n3) Cropping intensity increased and production increased by 20% utilizing fallow land;\r\n4) Fish production and economic return increased and\r\n5) Technology for rearing quick growing fish in rice-fish culture system generated.', '', '');
INSERT INTO `research_info` (`research_id`, `org_name`, `ddcr_name`, `ppe_type`, `r_title`, `r_location`, `r_priority`, `r_type`, `r_status`, `plan_sd`, `plan_ed`, `actual_sd`, `actual_ed`, `r_objective`, `r_method`, `r_abstruct`, `r_keywords`, `fund_source`, `total_budget`, `total_expenditure`, `total_refund`, `d_technology`, `p_organize`, `p_trained`, `r_programarea`, `commodity`, `outcome`, `impact`, `reference`) VALUES
(1374, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Science', 'Project', 'Development of cost effective complete feed formula for the productive and reproductive performances of buffaloes.', 'Mymensingh, Pabna, Rajshahi, Sylhet and Noakhali', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', 'a. To identify the availability of feeds and fodder, existing feeding and management system and current productivity of milk and meat of buffaloes in Mymensingh, Sylhet, Noakhali, Pabna and Rajshahi areas of Bangladesh.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	b. To develop a low cost feed formula for increasing productive performances (milk and meat) of buffaloes under semi-intensive management system in the selected areas of Bangladesh.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	c. To develop a low cost feed formula for improving reproductive performance of buffaloes under semi-intensive management system in the selected areas of Bangladesh.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	d. To improve knowledge and skill of rural small and marginal buffalo farmers on buffalo rearing for productive and reproductive performances.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	A. The proposed project will be executed in Bangladesh Agricultural University (BAU) under the supervision of Bangladesh Agricultural University Research System (BAURES). The research will be collaborative between the department of Animal Science, Animal Nutrition and Animal Breeding and Genetics, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh along with NGO named Bittohin Chasi Somaj Kallyan Sangstha (BCSKS), School Para, Airport Road, Ishwardi, Pabna.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	B. Site of the Experiment: On-farm experiments will be conducted at Mymensingh, Sylhet, Noakhali, Pabna and Rajshahi areas of Bangladesh.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	c. Baseline information, Selection of farmers and experimental buffaloes, Management practices.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	d. Chemical analysis, Diet and methods of feeding trial, Parameters to be considered, Productive parameters.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	e. Reproductive parameters, Economic benefit, Statistical Analysis.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	The buffaloes in Bangladesh will continue to remain as the useful animal for the small holders in the foreseeable future, playing an important role in the livelihoods of resource-poor farming families,. Harnessing the full potential of buffaloes as milk and meat producing animals will benefit the majority of the rural farmers.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n', 'Livestock production, Livestock, Animal, Rural farmers, Meat production, Buffaloes, Milk.', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 7500000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Livestock development', 'Livestock feed', '1) Available feeds and fodders, existing feeding system and management practices, current production of milk and meat and reproductive status of buffaloes in Mymensingh, Sylhet, Noakhali, Pabna and Rajshahi areas identified.\r\n2) Cost effective feeds formula developed for buffaloes using locally available feedstuffs.\r\n3) Productive and reproductive potentialities of buffaloes improved.', '', ''),
(1375, 'Chittagong Veterinary and Animal Sciences University', 'CVASU, Khulshi, Chittagong', 'Project', 'Investigation on calf diseases and Development of mitigation measures.', 'Belkuchi and Shahjadpur (Sirajganj); Ramgati and Komol Nagar (Luxmipur); and Char Fassion and Lalmohon (Bhola)', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1) To reduce calf mortality (Cattle &amp; Buffalo) by adopting mitigation measures.\r\n2) To improve knowledge and develop skill of the farmers about calf disease management.', '', '', 'Calf disease, mortality, calf disease management', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 9953000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Livestock Development', 'Calf disease', '1) Causes of calf mortality e.g. diseases (bacterial, viral, parasitic) poor feeding/malnutrition, health care management practices and poor skill of farmers will be identified.\r\n2) Diseases and serious diseases in chronological order causing deaths of calves will be determined.\r\n3) Percentage of death before intervention will be assessed and economic benefit of technology intervention will be determined.\r\n4) Appropriate technologies for reducing deaths of calves will be identified.\r\n5) Farmers skill in application of improved calf rearing technology will be improved.\r\n6) Calf mortality will be reduced about 50% to 60% thus increasing the replacement stock of cattle and buffaloes in the project areas.', '', ''),
(1376, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pathology, Faculty of Veterinary Science', 'Project', 'Clinicopathological and serological surveillance of Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD) and Peste des Petits Ruminants (PPR) and adopt preventive measures against them at Shakhipur and Madhupur Upazila of Tangail.', 'Shakhipur and Madhupur Upazila of Tangail', '', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1) Perform sero-surveillance of FMD and PPR in ruminants and evaluate immune response against FMD and PPR vaccines and viral sero/subtypes.\r\n2) To adopt accurate diagnostic system of FMD and PPR viral subtypes.\r\n3) Develop appropriate vaccination schedule and doses intervals to prevention the occurrence of these diseases.', '', '', 'FMD and PPR, sero-surveillance, ruminants', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 8849000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Livestock development', 'FMD and PPR diseases', '1) Cost effective surveillance techniques would be made available for rapid and confirmatory diagnosis of clinical and sub clinical infection with FMD and PPR.\r\n2) Adopt techniques for the rapid and accurate evaluation of immune response following natural infection and vaccination.\r\n3) Apply techniques for the diagnosis and typifying viral strains in the study areas.\r\n4) Improve milk, meat and leather quality of farm animals and enable us for sustainable cattle, buffaloes, sheep and goat production in Bangladesh.\r\n5) Strategies and recommendations will be made available in the state government and therefore to the NGOs workers for the formulation of National policy and prevention strategy of FMD and PPR outbreak in Bangladesh.', '', ''),
(1377, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Diversification of carp polyculture Integrating Snail (Viviparus sp.) shing, (Heteropneustes sp.) culture in Cage in ponds of Adivashi households.', 'BAU component, Mymensingh and Nalitabari, Sherpur districts.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', 'a. To increase production of crops in poly culture pond.\r\nb. To increase production of shing in case system.\r\nc. To increase income as well as increase knowledge and skill of the farmers of shing culture.', 'The farmers will be given full inputs for 2 years by the KGF grants. However, in the Year III, the farmers will be supplemented for initial stocking of fish and feeding and the remaining work would be done by the farmers themselves with the local support of BISHAL. Project Location: BAU component and Nalitabari, Sherpur (8 villages). Participatory and beneficiary farmers- 80 (individual pond 16 farmers + Multi owner pond 64 farmers (4 farmers per pond), number of ponds - 32. size of ponds- 30 decimal,&amp;nbsp; Cage per pond- 2, size of cage- 1 m&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;, Fingerling cage- 100, carps fingerling/decimal - 80, substrate area for snail production- 1-2m&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;/decimal of pond, Bamboo/decimal-3.', 'Aquaculture production in Bangladesh has got a considerable momentum in terms of fish production, nutritional supplement and livelihood improvement of a wide range of people. However, the people of poor socio-economic classes in remote places in the country are not getting the potential benefits of aquaculture. This is partly due to monotonous pond based fish culture that undermines optimum pond productivity and diversification of other non-piscine based aquaculture practices. Therefore, a farmer participatory research project (2011-2014) funded by KGF (Krishi Gobeshona Foundation), at its initial stage, assessed the potential to diversity carp polyculture in Adivasi households ponds. A number of participatory community appraisal (PCA) tools such as focus group discussion, well-being ranking, seasonality analysis and food consumption matrix were used to analyze the agrarian context of Adivasi households in a community namely, andharupara in Nalitabair, Sherpur. Adivasi people are traditionally poor and disadvantaged due to their cultural practices, who mainly depend on wild food collections however, because of the scarcity of wild food sources they started adopting agricultural practices. Among different agricultural activities, some of Adivasi households adopted small-scale pond farming in the recent years. In the studied community, out of 68 Adivasi households, 95% were poor without any richer households. However, about 20% of households were characterized by having small and medium ponds (mostly perennial) with some formal experience in pond aquaculture. Seasonally during the rainy season (April-August), Adivasi households do not have the intensity of farm or non-farm activities. In this time, the availability of vegetables in their won farm (mainly homestead) and market become less available. In terms of access to food fish, except Pangasius, other fishes were reported high priced and less available. Particularly indigenous catfish such as shing (heteropneustes fossilis) and magur (Clarias batrachus) were high priced and least available. Meat items from own farm and market origin were reported highly expensive. On the other hand, the wild meat animals were reported least available which are gradationally highly tasty to them. The vegetables in market became expensive and less available in the recent years. Now-a-days, the wild vegetables became least available. Considering this context, the follwon research is focusing to develop aquaculture diversification in Adivasi households ponds combining carp polyculture, shing in cage, snail in pond to feed shing, and aquaponic vegetables to produce various food items using limited aquatic resources. ', 'Fish, Crop diversification, aquaculture practices ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 3995000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Crop diversification of acquaculture practices', 'Fishes', '1) Productivity of existing pond based aquaculture will be manifold using this technology.\r\n2) Diversified production of carps, snail, and shing would be found.\r\n3) Cash flow in the poor adivashi households will be increased considerably as shing is high valued fish in the existing market demand.\r\n4) Dependency on the natural resources collection will be reduced considerably. ', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(1378, 'Bangladesh Rice Research Institute', 'Adaptive Research Division', 'Project', 'Yield Gap minimization in rice using integrated crop and resource management (ICRM) practices at selected locations in Bangladesh', 'Madarganj (Jamalpur), Sherpur sadar, Nalitabari and Nokla (Sherpur), Kapasia (Gazipur), Pakundia and Kotiadi (Kishorganj, Monohordi and Palash (Narshingdi)', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. To minimize yield gap in rice increasing yield by 0.5-1.0 t/ha using integrated crop and resource management (ICRM) practices.\r\n2. To enhance skill and knowledge of participating farmers.', '', '', 'integrated crop and resource management (ICRM), minimize yield gap', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 8700000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Yield gap minimization', 'Rice', '1) Rice yield increased by 0.5-1.0 t/ha minimizing yield gap by 10-22%.\r\n2) Input (seed, nutrient, water) use efficiency increased by 5-30%.\r\n3) Farmers net income increased by Tk. 10,000-15,000/ha.', '', ''),
(1379, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'On-Farm Research Division (OFRD)', 'Project', 'Validation and Up-scaling of maize after T. aman rice in two southern districts.', 'Khulna sadar and Rupsha (Khulna), and Kolaroa and Satkhira sadar (Satkhira)', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. To increase cropping intensity and system productivity through adoption of hybrid maize in fallow-rice cropping system in Satkhira and Khulna districts\r\n2. To increase yield of T. Aman rice introducing high yielding varieties.\r\n3. To increase knowledge and skill of the farmers on the production practices of improved cropping system.', '', '', 'Up -scaling of maize, Southern districts, T. aman rice, ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 9072000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Up-scaling of maize production', 'Rice and Maize', '1) Best performing high yielding varieties of T. aman rice and hybrid maize identified.\r\n2) High yielding varieties of T. aman rice and hybrid maize adopted in the cropping system in 4 Upazilas of Khulna and Satkhira districts.\r\n3) Knowledge and skill of the farmers increased.', '', ''),
(1380, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'On-Farm Research Division (OFRD), Jessore', 'Project', 'Variety selection and integrated crop management for yield gap minimization in mustard and sesame in the high Ganges river floodplains.', 'Monirampur and Jhikargacha (Jessore); Kaliganj (Jhenaidah); Narail sadar (Narail); Modhukhali (Faridpur); and Kushtia sadar (Kushtia)', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '1. To identify the&nbsp; suitable high yielding varieties of mustard and sesame to be fitted in the specific cropping pattern.\r\n2. Adaption of integrated crop management (ICM) in mustard and sesame production compared to farmers'' practice to reduce the yield gap\r\n3. To increase the knowledge and skill of farmers in mustard and sesame production technology.\r\n', '', '', 'Variety Selection, Integrated crop management, Yield gap,  ', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 6500000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Variety Selection and Integraged Crop Management', 'Mustard and Sesame', '1) Suitable mustard and sesame varieties will be identified to be fitted in the major cropping pattern.\r\n2) Suitable HYV mustard and sesame with their production practices will be adapted by the farmers by at least 20-25%.\r\n3) Skill on mustard and sesame production technique and income of the farmers will be increased by at least 15%.', '', ''),
(1381, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Horticulture Research Station', 'Project', 'Management of Coconut mite', 'RARS, BARI, Jessore', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2014', 'To determine the best management practices for controlling coconut mite.\r\nTo enhance the technical skills and knowledge of the participating farmers.', '', '', 'Coconut, Technical Knowledge, Coconut mite', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 3140000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Pest management', 'Coconut mite', '1) An effective package of management practices for controlling mite on coconut is developed, validated and adapted by at least 1200 households in Jessore.\r\n2) One thousand two hundred farmers in Jessore trained and skilled in controlling coconut mite.', '', ''),
(1382, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Reproductive physiology and genetics', 'Project', 'Genetic Studies and stock improvement of commercially important carps.', 'Freshwater Station, Mymensingh-2201', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2015', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2015', '1. To continue genetic stock improvement of Rohu (Labeo rolita) through family selection protocol.\r\n2. To continue genetic stock improvement of silver barb  through family selection protocol\r\n3. Distribution and on-farm trails of improved germplasm of carps.', 'I. Stock improvement of rohu (Labeo rohita) through family selection\r\nIn view of breeding and genetic stock improvement program of rohu, L. rohita, land races collected from different river systems of the country viz., Brahmaputra and Jamuna, were reared separately in ponds. The two wild stocks, Jamuna and Brahmaputra, along with the domesticated existing BFRI hatchery stocks were mated to produce three crossbred lines through a 3X3 diallellic design of cross breeding programme. The two crossbred lines thus produced, BFRI Hatchery X Jamuna and Jamuna X Brahmaputra were involved in the planned breeding. These crossbred lines were the base population from which the F1 base generation was produced through Mass Selection. The Family Selection program were initiated involving the F1 rohu according to the designed protocol (Fig. 1).\r\nFifty families of progeny group were produced (and selected) through a series of nested mating design between selected pair of female and male brood fish (2:1). Equal volume of fertilized eggs of about 100 ml from each pair were incubated and maintained as separate families. Individual progeny families were nursed separately in primary, secondary and tertiary hapas in pond for 2, 4 and 6 months, respectively. About 25 g of grown fingerlings of each of forty families were PIT tagged and recorded. Then, a total of 600 tagged fish (#15 from 40 families) were being reared communally in earthen pond. After communal rearing of one and a half year, the fish will be sampled for sexing and growth achievements. Family wise data will be analyzed using BLUP. To prepare mating design, the breeding value of individual fish will be estimated as: e_bv = (x  x) X h2 [h2 = VA / Vp]. The following improved generation will be produced through a series of mating between selected pair of female and male according to the plan of mating design list.\r\nObservation on variations in male and female sex in rohu\r\nGenerally, female fish grow faster than their male sibs especially in carps. Therefore, an observation will be made in sib groups of a typical carp, rohu, in terms of growth of male and female sex. In that case, sexual dimorphism will be performed in rohu.\r\nII. Stock improvement of silver barb, Barbodes gonionotus, through family selection\r\nThe genetic stock improvement program of silver barb was initiated with three different stocks of fish from Indonesia, Thailand along with existing in Bangladesh and the follow up mass selection protocol was continued up to the seventh generation. The improved generation of silver barb showed 32% faster growth rate for body weight in comparison to the existing strain of Bangladesh. As the rate of genetic gain in weight of fish was decreased gradually,the genetic improvement strategy was re-designed under the 2'' phase of Carp Genetic Improvement Project and was implemented in 2004-2006. During 2004-05, breeding program was conducted involving 7th generation of silver barb descended from mass selection experiment of the first phase of the project. A total of developed 50 progeny families were tested for growth evaluation through PIT tagging and communal rearing. The data of growth after five-month rearing were analyzed to estimate the breeding values of all the progeny by the BULP method. According to the breeding value, two mating lists (selection line and control line) were prepared. Also, the component of on-farm evaluation of improved stock showed significantly (P&lt;0.05) higher growth performance (30-35%) over the local stocks. In 2006, a total of 50 full sib groups of progeny family for selection line and 20 full sib groups for control line were developed and maintained for further selection program as 2'' breeding cycle. After PIT tagging and communal rearing of one year, the fish were harvested and sampled for Tag number, sex and growth. Family wise data were analyzed using BLUP. The follow up Family Selection program were implemented in 2009 with the F2 silver barb stock produced through the 3rd breeding cycle using mating plan list according the designed protocol. After PIT tagging and communal rearing of 3 months, the F3 silver barb were harvested and sampled for Tag number, sex and growth (40 families from selection line and 10 families from control line). Family wise data were analyzed using BLUP. Thus a mating plan list was developed for F3 generation. The follow up Family Selection program will be implemented with the 4th breeding cycle to produce F4 silver barb stock. A 50 families of progeny group for selection line along with 20 families of control group will be produced through a series of single pair mating design between individuals of selected and listed pair of female and male brood. Equal volume of fertilized eggs of about 20-30 ml from each of the\r\npair mating of selected brood will be incubated and maintained as separate family. Individual progeny families will be nursed separately in primary, secondary and tertiary hapas for 2, 3 and 4 months, respectively. About #20 grown fingerlings of 20 g of each of fifty families will be PIT tagged and recorded. Then, a total of #1000&lt; tagged fish (#20&lt; from selected 50 families) will be reared communally in earthen pond. In grow out trial of brood, stocking densities for the experimental fish will be 1.0-1.5 fish/m3. After communal rearing of 5-6 months, the fish will be sampled for sexing and growth achievements. Family wise data will be analyzed using BLUP. To establish mating design, the breeding value of individual fish will be estimated as: ebv = (x  x) X h2 [ h2 = VA I Vp]. According to that, the following improved generations (from F5) will be produced through a series of mating between individuals of selected pair of female and male according to the mating list and design. In each generation, evaluation of growth performance will be carried out through communal rearing of selected and non-selected groups in controlled conditions. The design of breeding cycle protocol is the same as in rohu (Figure 1) except single pair mating for silver barb\r\ninstead of nested mating.\r\nIlL Distribution and on-farm trials of improved germplasm of carp\r\nImproved germplasm of carp will be distributed in Satellite Stations of BFRI and selected public hatcheries through DoF. The Satellite Stations will establish brood bank and will distribute the germplasm to private hatchery operators and fish farmers. The dissemination program will be implemented through designed mechanisms involving Research Institute, DoF and private hatchery operators. Performance data will be collected from the hatcheries for fine\r\ntuning of the technology. The trials will be carried out for a period of six months at Mymensingh region. There will be 6 perennial ponds with a range of area of 800-1000 m2. The two treatments will be designed with rohu, catla, mrigal and silver barb. Upgraded stocks of rohu and silver barb will be stocked in Treatment-I while, locally available existing stocks of rohu and silver barb will be stocked in Treatment-II (Table 1). After stocking, commonly available supplementary feed will be applied in all the ponds. Fish will be sampled at monthly interval to assess growth performances and to adjust feeding ration. After six months of rearing, the fish will be harvested and data will be analyzed\r\nthrough ANOVA.\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 'Fish, Genetic stock improvement, commercially important carps.', 'GOB', 700000, 250000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Genetics and Plant  Breeding', 'Fishes', '1) Genetically improved stocks of fish developed to support public/private broodbank center.\r\n2) Improved breeds and quality seeds ensured for enhancing aquaculture production.\r\n3) Present deteriorating and inbreeding problems of hatchery populations will mostly be mitigated.', 'Genetically improved stocks of fish will produce quality seeds which  will enhance fish production and will eradicate inbreeding problems in our hatchery.', ''),
(1383, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Rerpoductive Physiology and Genetics', 'Project', 'Rotational Breeding Programme of GIFT strain at the satellite breeding center of BRFI ', 'Freshwater station, Mymensingh-2201', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '31-12-2012', '01-07-2009', '31-12-2012', 'Production of quality mass seed of GIFT strain in different satellite breeding centres of BFRI\r\nEvaluation of grouth performance of GIFT strain producted from rotational breeding program and\r\nDistribution of quality BFRI seed among public and hatchery/nursery operations.', 'Project area\r\nFor the production of quality mass seed production through rotational breeding technique of BFRI GIFT strain, the project activities are being carried out at Freshwater Station, Mymensingh, Freshwater Sub-stations (Jessore, Sayedpur and Santaher) and Riverine Sub \r\nstation (Khepupara) during July 2011 to June 2012.  Rotational breeding program for GIFT strain\r\nThe third generation of selection (and every odd generation)\r\n1.	When the fish reach sexual maturity (fish produced from even generation), selection and mating will be conducted.\r\n2.	In each hapa, select the best 200 males and 200 females in terms of size (ie. good body shape and weight) as parents of the second generation.\r\n3.	Follow the rotational mating program as shown in Diagram 2. The males from hapa-1 will move to mate with females of hapa-2, while males of hapa-2 will go to hapa-3 and so on.\r\n4.	After producing enough progeny, take out the breeders and put in other hapas. These parents can be used to produce fingerlings for farmers.\r\n', '', 'Rotational Breeding, GIFT Strain, Satellite Breeding Centres', 'GOB', 1800000, 1200000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Rotational Breeding', 'Fishes', '1) BFRI-GIFT strain will be available for small and large-scale aquaculture; and\r\n2) Pond fish production will be increased through BFRI-GIFT tilapia culture.', 'BFRI-GIFT tilapia production will be increased in farm level due to available of its strain', ''),
(1384, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Genetics &amp; Fish Breeding', 'Project', 'Reproductive physiology study of Rohu (Labeo Rohita)', 'Freshwater station, Mymensingh-2201', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-06-2010', '30-06-2013', '01-06-2010', '30-06-2013', 'To study of effect of seasonal change in gonad development of Rohu\r\nTo study the gonad histology of Rohu\r\nTo identify the suitable levels of feed management, environment aspects imrpovement &amp;amp; hormone induction for pre maturation of Rohu.', 'Fingerling Rearing, On-growing &amp; Growth Estimation:\r\nFingerlings of Rohu more or less same age (3 months) and size (10-12 cm) were stocked under carp polyculture design and reared in BFRI, FS pond complex. Feeding, fertilization &amp; water management were monitored properly. Growth parameters were estimates monthly. The experimental design and management protocol are shown in the following layout:\r\nTreatment : T1 Normal management (feeding 20% protein, @ 1-2 % body weight, No water change or\r\nA flash, no pre-maturation hormone doges)\r\nT2 Improve management (feeding 30% protein @ 3-5% body weight, 4-5 days water flashing in a week, pre-maturation hormone doges)\r\n: Three replications for each treatment;\r\nPond Selection\r\nPond Area	: 30-40 decimal\r\nNo. of Ponds	: 6 ponds\r\nCulture Period : 36 months\r\nPond preparation (for both treatments) Cleaning of weeds, drying and dyke repairing, liming @ 250 kg/ha &amp; maturing (Cow dung) @ 3000 kg/ha, Urea @ 25 kg/ha, TSP @ 25\r\nkg/ha\r\nStocking rates and ratio\r\nRate	: 5000 fingerlings/ha\r\nBreeds	: BFRI improved breeds\r\nSize	: 13-14 cm\r\nRatio	: Rohu 100%\r\nFeed\r\nT1 : Commercial peleted feeds 20% protein\r\nT2 : Commercial peleted feeds 30% protein\r\nFeeding rate\r\nTi : @ 1-2% body weight/day\r\nT2: @ 3-5 % bw/day\r\nFertilization\r\nCow dung @ 2000 kg/ha/month and Inorganic fertilizers 50 kg/ha/month. Both fertilizers will be used in every alternate week.\r\nWater management\r\nDepth of water will be maintained within 4-5 feet in both the treatments and any unwanted leakage or loss of water will be\r\nrecovered everyday.\r\nIn T2 water will be flashed 4-5 days in a week throughout the experimental period.\r\nSexual Maturation &amp; Reproduction\r\n Monthly estimates of standard length &amp; weight for growth determination and gonad weight for Gonado Somatic Index (GSI) study were recorded. Gonad Histology\r\n	Ovarian &amp; Testicular samples will be collected every month (from 8 months of age).\r\n	Gonad histology was studied using recognized methods.\r\n	Data were recorded properly and presented using appropriate Statistical Methods.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 'Fish, Rohu, Reproductive physiology, Labeo rohita', 'GOB', 1940000, 498921, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Physiology Study', 'Fishes', '1) Detail knowledge of reproductive physiology of Rohu will help to find out the way for  early breeding of this species.\r\n2) As a result fish farmers will be able to get fingerlings earlier which ultimately increase culture period for the increase fish production as a whole.', 'Early breeding of Rohu will increase the culture period and as a result total production of the species will increase', ''),
(1385, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Dept. of Genetics and Plant Breeding, BAU', 'Project', 'Application of microsatellite markers for screening and identification of iron rich rice genotypes.', 'BAU', 'High', 'Basic', 'On-going', '01-08-2012', '31-07-2013', '01-08-2012', '31-07-2013', 'a. to determine the iron content of rice germplasm from the grain.\r\nb. to observe the phenotypic performance of rice germplasm for enhanced iron.\r\nc. to identify the iron rich rice germplasm using microsatellite markers.\r\nd. To screen rice varieties including wild relatives viz. Sada Binni, Kalo Binni and Lal Binni for identifying the iron-rich rice varieties through the application of mocrosatellite markers.', 'Seed of important local (viz. Sada Binni, , Kalo Binni and Lal Binni and exotic popular varieties of indica rice along with wild relatives will be collected\r\nPreparation and maintenance of stock solution\r\nPhenotyping for iron contend: Screening of iron content at the seedling stage\r\nDetermination of Iron content from rice grain\r\nGenotyping of iron rich rice germplasm using SSR markers\r\nConfirmation and quantification of DNA\r\nConfirmation of DNA using gel electrophoresis\r\nDNA sample preparation and electrophoresis\r\nDocumentation of DNA samples\r\nPCR analysis for SSR markers\r\nParental survey and primer selection\r\nPreparation of reaction mixture to perform polymerase chain Reaction (PCR).\r\nAmplification of SSR Markers by polymerase chain reaction (PCR)\r\nNutrient status for bio-available iron will be assessed by different biochemical analysis\r\nQuantification of the iron content in seed of the identified iron rich rice genotypes\r\nDocumentation and Reporting\r\n', 'Rice (oryza sativa L.) is one of the most important cereal crops in Bangladesh and it is the main staple food for the people. Iron deficiency in the staple food is the most common nutritional disorder tin the globe affecting between 2 to 5 billion people. Molecular breeding gives us a unique opportunity to incorporate iron-rich genes in cereals to improve their nutritional value. In this crop improvement program 100 rice varieties (local landarecs-78, Mega varieties-9, advance line-13) were collected. The germinated seeds of collected rice varieties were sown in pot for collecting the leaf sample. Now the determination of iron content of the rest rice genotypes is ongoing. For the procurement process we called for the quotation from different enterprise against the chemicals and consumables. One of the enterprises who quoted the lowest price was selected for supplying the chemicals and consumables. Then the chemicals&amp;nbsp; and&amp;nbsp; consumables were procured completely.\r\n', 'Iron rich rice, Microsatellite markers, Landraces', '', 1330550, 727000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Genetic Resources and Biodiversity', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1386, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Dept of Food Technology and Rural Industries', 'Project', 'Small scale processing of functional fruit juices applying enzyme technology', 'BAU-Mymensingh, Modhupur-Tangail', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '05-11-2009', '31-11-2011', '05-11-2009', '30-11-2011', '', '', '', 'Fruits, Juice, Post harvest of High Value crops', '', 1903000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Post harvest Processing of high value crops', 'Fruits', '', '', ''),
(1387, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetics and plant breeding', 'Project', 'Production and Dissemination of short duration Boro and Aman Rice Seed to Increase Cropping Intensity and Address Food Security Issues in Bangladesh.', 'Mymensingh sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat Upazila of Mymensingh District.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', 'October 2012', 'July 2013', 'October, 2012', 'July 2013', '1) Multiplication of short duration HYV of T. aman and Boro rice seed by the farmer&amp;#39;s of the selected area with special emphasis on those suitable for high input and high output in agriculture.\r\n2) Distribution of such seed to the selected farmer&amp;#39;s level for higher production and yield.\r\n3) To promote farmer&amp;#39;s acceptance and use of improved varieties of seeds.\r\n4) To promote, through education, training and financial supports, balanced development of public and private sector seed enterprise.\r\n5) Increase cropping intensity in the proposed regions of Bangladesh by incorporation a third crop between these two short duration rice cultivation.\r\n6) Increase total productivity in rice based cropping pattern.', 'In Mymensingh district the proposed project work will be located at three Upazilas Viz. Mymensingh sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat. In the present proposal we will select 100 farmers in each Upazila, therefore, the total number of farmers in sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat Upazilas will be 300. Under the proposed project each farmer will get 5.00 kg of seed of BRRI dhan28/BINA8/BRRI dhan55 and BRRI dhan33/BRRI dhan52/BRRI dhan57/BINA7/Bashmoti/other suitable varieties for aman and boro season according to cropping season for one bigha of land. We will also monitor all the activities related to quality rice seed production. We will also select required number of farmers covering all these three Upazilas for selected Breeder seed multiplication. For this purpose we will hire farmers plot. In those plots seed multiplication will be done for further distribution and all activities related to seed production will be monitored by our expert team regularly. Field days will be conducted in every Upazila in every growing season.', 'Primary constraints to achieving food security are the low yield per unit area and negligible scope for expansion of the area of land for cultivation. Hence, increase in intensity of cultivation and in yields per unit area are the only available options to meet future food needs to feed an ever increasing population. In Bangladesh, most of the farmers are growing local landraces of T. aman and boro rice annually in many regions of Bangladesh. Those landraces required long growth duration. Due to the lacking in the availability of short duration HYV of T. aman and Boro rice farmers are reluctant to grow any third crop in between T. aman and Boro rice. To address this problem we proposed crop intensification with short duration HYV of T. aman and Boro rice. In Bangladesh most of the farmers are growing more than one crop on the same land during one year of production system. Within this concept there are many possible cropping patterns. With the availability of short duration HYV of T. aman and Boro rice farmers will be able to grow any third crop between T. aman and Boro rice. The main research objective is to multiplication of short duration HYV of T. aman and Boro rice seed by the farmer&amp;#39;s and distributing of those quality seed free to selected farmer&amp;#39;s of the Upazilas of Mymensingh district Viz. sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat.', 'Food security, Dissemination, Cropping intensity', '', 300000, 150000, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 300, '', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1392, 'Sylhet Agricultural University', 'Dept. of Horticulture, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'Project', 'Collection, Conservation, Characterization and Varietal development of Garlic and Onion through selection and molecular techniques.', 'All over Bangladesh', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', '01-05-2009', '30-04-2011', '01-05-2009', '31-10-2013', '1. To collect, preserve, characterize and varietal development of garlic and onion\r\n2. To fingerprint different germplasm of onion and garlic\r\n3. To develop suitable production system fro onion seed and garlic production.\r\n4. To register promising varieties through national seed board.', 'Short day tropical cultivates of onion and garlic will be collected and the nature of these cultivars will be tested trough on farm research, Bulb productivity trials will be evaluated for both crops, and seed production potential measures for onion.\r\nBased on preliminary results at BAU, a more local germplasm will be collected and planted in the horticulture farm as well as GPC (GermplasmCenter) of Horticultural Crop improvement project.\r\nMore trails of short day tropical garlic will be initiated to better selected for clones with higher yield potential, long shelf life, and higher allicin content.\r\nTraining of famers, homestead owners, rural youth and women in respect of crop production crop management, nutrition, income generation &amp; marketing.\r\nTraining of the trainers (TOT): Research supervisors of various GO, NGO personnel will be conducted.\r\nLiaison between NGO like CAR, VFFP, CARITAS, WVB (World vison Bangladesh), PROSHIKA, RDRS will be made.\r\nMolecular characterizatin of the collected onion and garlic varieties using DNA based marker techniques.', 'PI of this project will be responsible for planning, designing and executing all the experiments. Moreover he will prepare and present the report and will also be responsible for the financial expenditures of this project.', 'NGO, Onion, Garlic, Farm research, farmers training, Rural youth and women, marketing techniques, Varietal development.', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1980000, 0, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 0, 'Molecular Techniques', 'Garlic and Onion', '', '', ''),
(1388, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Dept. of Food Technology and Rural Industries', 'Project', 'Processing of indigenous fruits and vegetables to improved livelihood of rural poor in Modhupur regions', 'Dodhupur (Tangail district)', 'High', 'Adaptive', '', '01-05-2009', '30-04-2011', '01-05-2009', '30-04-2011', 'a. To develop new formulation for selected indigenous fruits and vegetables products with mineral fortification and existing processing method will be improved.\r\nb. To develop a year round production model.\r\nc. To evaluate acceptability of processed products.\r\nd. To assess the self life of processed product.\r\ne. To trained up and increase the food processing and preservation knowledge and skill of the rural peoples especially of rural woman.\r\nf. To increase income of the rural poor people.\r\n', 'A. PRA survey: A survey will be conducted to assess acreage, production, gender issues, mode of consumption, processing and marketing present status of the existing small-scale food processing industries in the locality and market feasibility of the processed fruit and vegetables products.\r\nB. Research on products developments, Quality control of selected products, Documentation of final results and findings, Evaluation of shelf-life and packaging requirement for the products.\r\nC. Equipment like regenerator, freezer, blender etc. will be procured from the market.\r\nD. Organize seminar/workshop to share the experience acquired. Organize visits for entrepreneurs to other industries and institutions to make them aware of other processed food products.\r\nE. Information dissemination: Documentation of the findings in reports, Sharing of findings with other stakeholders, Production of communication and display materials, Publication of the research findings and the achievements.', 'The economy of Bangladesh with large and rapidly growing population and low per capita income reveals a condition of abject poverty for majority of the people. Agriculture contribute about one-third of its gross domestic product and about 80% of people still live in rural areas. The standard of rural poor is precariously low and very simple. Though agriculture is the major source of employment in rural areas, the prospect of absorption&amp;nbsp; of increasing number of labour force in agriculture does not appear to be bright. opinion prevails that even the most optimistic estimate of growth in the crop production can absorb only a quarter or half of the increasing number of labour force. So, utmost effort must be made for expansion of non-crop sections like fishery, livestock, poultry and food processing.\r\nBangladesh produces many metric tons of fruit and vegetable annually. These are more or less seasonal in production and therefore, often form glut in the market in their harvesting season. The price paid to the growers during peak period is low and not conducive to their investment.', 'Fruit, Vegetables, Food, Rural Woman.', 'Krishi Gobeshona Foundation (KGF)', 1998700, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Priority Research Area of Socio-Economics, Marketing and Sypply', 'Fruits', '', '', ''),
(1389, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetics and plant Breeding', 'Project', 'Development of short duration high yielding rice varieties', 'Genetics and plant breeding field lab, BAU, Mymensingh sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat Upazila of Mymensingh district.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', 'November 2011', 'October 2014', 'November 2011', 'October 2014', '1) To select and develop short duration high yielding rice varieties for the Boro, Aus and T. aman seasons to fit into the existing cropping pattern.', 'Breeding line SL-9 and ADT (R)47 selected as donor (male) parent and BRRI dhan52, BRRI dhan53, BRRI dhan57 as recipient (female) parent for aman season and crosses were made among the selected parents. For Boro season, crosses were made in BRRI dhan28 X IR 77734-93-2-3-2, BRRI dhan29 X ADT(R)47 and BRRI dhan55 X IR 77734-93-2-3-2. Crosses will be done in BRRI dhan48 X Parija, BRRI dhan55 X Parija, BRRI dhan48 X NERICA 2, BRRI dhan55 X NERICA 2, BRRI dhan48 X NERICA 4, BRRI dhan55 X NERICA 4 to obtain short duration high yielding Aus rice. The most promising ones will be selected from the hybridized generations following the modified pedigree method. Three Upazilas of Mymensingh district viz. sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat will be considered for the experiment. On-farm variety trial will be conducted. During the first year there will be hybridization and selection of rice varieties. In the second year, selection of the superior line of short duration rice varieties will be done. In the third year, trial of selected superior line of short duration, stable and high yielding rice varieties will be conducted.', 'Rice, the staple food crop of Bangladesh, covered about 10.58 million ha of cropped area and total production in the FY 2010-11 was 33.52 million metric tones, in which the contribution of Aus, Aman and Boro were 2.13 mmt, 12.79 mmt and 18.60 mmt respectively. The national cropping intensity was 181% during the period 2010-11. More than 94% of the population derives 76% of its daily calories and 66% of its protein needs from rice. Primary constraints to achieving food security are the low yield per unit area and negligible scope for expansion of the area of land for cultivation. Hence, increase in intensity of cultivation and in yields per unit area are the only available options to meet future food needs to feed an ever increasing population. In Bangladesh, most of the farmers are growing Aus, T. aman and Boro rice annually in many regions of Bangladesh. But the existing field problem of rice cultivation in Bangladesh is lacking in short duration high yielding rice varieties for all seasons. The area of aus cultivation decreased by about 50% from the year 1990 to 2006 due to lacking in short duration modern varieties. Farmers are reluctant to grow the poor yielding Aus varieties. To address this problem the present study will help to develop high yielding varieties of accestable grain quality, preferably short growth duration to increase land productivity to 3 crops in a year. The main goal of this research is to develop short duration, stable and high yielding rice varieties for Aus, Aman and Boro to fit into the existing cropping patterns.\r\n', 'Short duration, High yielding, PVS', 'BARC', 1194000, 461580, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(1390, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetics and Plant Breeding', 'Project', 'Crop Intensification with short duration mustard cultivation in between Aman and Boro rice.', 'Mymensingh sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat Upazila of Mymensingh, Bagha of Rajshahi, Ishurdi and Pabna sadar of Pabna district.', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'On-going', 'June 2011', 'May 2014', 'June 2011', 'May 2014', '1) To increase cropping intensity in the proposed regions of Bangladesh.\r\n2) To increase total productivity in rice based cropping pattern.\r\n', 'High yielding short duration oil seed Brassica varieties/advanced lines namely BARI Sarisha 14 &amp;amp; BARI Sarisha 15, BINA Sarisha 4 &amp;amp; BINA Sarisha 7 and Unnata Tori-7 were collected from BARI, BINA, BAU and BADC. Three Upazilas of Mymensingh district viz. sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat, Bagha Upazila of Rajshahi, Isurdi Upazila of Pabna and Lalpur Upazila of Natore were considered for the experiment. On-farm variety trial will be conducted. During the first year there will be screening of varieties involving 300 farmers. In second year, adaptation trial will be conducted involving 400 farmers. In third year, scaling up of the materials will be conducted and 500 farmers will be selected. For the selection of the farmers, the data base of the Directorate of Agriculture Extension will be given to CIG (Common Interest Group) farmers.\r\n', 'An attempt was taken to change the cropping pattern Aman-Fallow-Boro into Aman-Mustard-Boro by growing short duration but high yielding mustard varieties with a view to increasing cropping intensity and edible oil production of the country as well as net income of the farmers. With this view point as a test case three Upazilas of Mymensingh district viz. sadar, Muktagacha and Haluaghat and three Upazilas namely Ishurdi of Pabna, Lalpur of Natore and Bagha of Rajshahi districts were chosen. Fifty CIG farmers from each of the six Upazilas (300) were selected during the first year and screening of the varieties has been completed successfully. In the present year i.e. second year adaptation trial involving 400 farmers is in progress. All the farmers were supplied with one kg seeds of the mustard variety BARI Sarisha 14/BARI Sarisha 15/BINA Sarisha 4/BINA Sarisha 7/Unnata Tori-7. Inddition a standard rate of N, P, K, and Zn fertilizers incentives for applying insecticides and fungicides were supplied to all the 400 farmers.', 'Crop intensification, Short duration, Mustard, Food security', '', 8286000, 5258373, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 300, '', '', '', '', '');
