(1395, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Dept. of Fisheries Management', 'Project', 'Induced breeding of great snakehead (gajar, channa, marulius) using Molecular Technology', 'Faculty of fisheries, BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '3006-2012', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '1. To know the location of GnRH genes in the brain and pituitary by immunohistochmistry (IHC).\r\n2. to do the advancement of maturation and spawning using specific GnRH peptides.\r\n3 To know the fry hearing and culture techniques of giant snakhead murred', '', '', 'Fish, Genes', '', 120000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Fish Breeding', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(1393, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Fish Nutrition and Feed Technology', 'Project', 'Development and optimization of feed with probiotics and feeding strategies for commercially important fish farming', 'Freshwater Station, BFRI, Mymensing', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2014', 'To evaluate the potential of using selected probiotics in the formulated diets for Anabas Testudineus (koi), Heteropneustes fossilis (shing) and Pangasius.\r\nTo develop and optimize feeds and feeding strategies and techniques in fish forming.\r\nTo assess and refine satiation feeding techniques in these species in pond conditions.\r\nTo investigate the suitability of utilizing restricted and mixed feeding schedule for increased production with a view to minimizing feed wastage and feed costs.', 'The study will be conducted to evaluate the potentiality of selected probiotics by improving the growth, digestibility, efficiency of feed &amp; nutrient utilization with a view to develop cost-effective quality feeds for important fish species. The feeding trail will be carried out a series of cylindrical fibre glass tanks (70-L each) for 8 weeks at Freshwater Station, BFRI. The same aged uniform size fingerlings of Anabas testudineus (koi) will be randomly distributed into groups of 50 fish (averaging 3.00-5.00 &plusmn; 0.05 g in weight) per 70-L fiberglass tank and three replicate tanks used for each test diet. Artificial aeration used to maintain an adequate level of dissolve oxygen in each test tank. The fish was individually weighed at the start and end of the experiment by weekly. Weekly sampling of fish will be done to adjust the daily feed ration for the following week. Water quality parameter such as temperature, pH, dissolve oxygen and total ammonia will be monitored through weekly sampling At the beginning of the experiment 15-20 fish will be randomly sacrificed and kept for analysis of initial whole body composition. At the end of the feeding trial all fish will be weighed and survival will be determined. Five to seven fish will be taken out from each tank for determination of whole body carcass composition.\r\nExperimental diets and feeding\r\nSix experimental diets (iso-nitrogenous and iso-energetic) will be formulated containing optimized protein to energy ratio (P/E ratio) and lipid to CHO ratio and to meet determined requirements for maximum growth of the fish species. Feed will be prepared using locally available fish feed ingredients such as fish meal/protein concentrate, meat &amp; bone meal, mustard oil cake, maize meal, rice bran and wheat flour (Atta) in different combinations. Fish meal/ protein concentrate meat and bone meal and mustard oil cake will be used as protein sources. Maize meal and rice bran/wheat bran will be used as carbohydrate sources and wheat flour (Atta) will be used as binder. Soybean oil will be used as lipid source and 0.5% chromium (III) oxide an inert indicator for digestibility studies. Vitamin and mineral premix will be added following the recommended dose by the manufacturers. The selected five types of probiotics Lactobacillus; Bacillus (2); Saccharomyces; Actinomycetes and Nitrobacteria will be added the diets following the recommended dose by the manufacturers. A control diet will be prepared with same feed ingredients without mixing probiotic in each study. Experimental diets will be prepared by locally made semi-auto pellet mill using 2-4 mm die depending on fish size. The fish will be offered the experimental and control diets, 2-3 times daily at the rate of 5-10% of their body weight and sub-divided into 2-3 equal feeds at 9.00, 13.30 and 18.00 h. Feeding rate will be adjusted based on weekly and fortnightly sampling (fish weighing) of fish.\r\nAnalytical methods and statistical analysis\r\nProximate composition of diet ingredients, experimental diets, initial fish carcasses and whole body fish will be analyzed following AOAC (1990) methods. Nitrogen-free extract (NFE) will be calculated by difference. Gross energy will be calculated according to Jauncey (1998). All samples will be analyzed in triplicate. Economic analysis of experimental diets and production of fish will be done in standard procedure. Specific growth rate (SGR), %weights gain, food conversion efficiency (FCR), protein efficiency ratio (PER) and apparent net protein utilisation (ANPU) will be calculated as follows:\r\nSGR (% / day) = [(Ln. Final body weight  Ln. Initial body weight) / days x 1001\r\n% Weight gain = (Final body weight  Initial body weight / Initial body weight) x 100\r\nFCR = Food fed (g dry weight)/ Live weight gain (g)\r\nPER = Live weight gain (g) / Crude protein fed (g dry weight)\r\n	ANPU (%) = (Final carcass protein  Initial carcass protein) / Total dry protein consumed x 100\r\nThe growth performance, feed utilization, and whole body composition data will be analyzed using one way ANOVA. A significance level of P&lt;0.05 will be used. Standard deviation (&plusmn; SD) will be calculated to identify the range of means. Wherever a significant F resulted from the analysis of variance the Tuky''s test will be applied to locate difference among treatments and the means will be ranked using a computer program (SPSS 10,0 for Windows). Differences will be regarded significant when P &lt; 0.05.\r\n', '', 'Fish, commercial fish farming, Pangasius, Anabas Testudineus (koi)', 'GOB', 800000, 800000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Commersicl fish farming', 'Fishes', '1) Suitability of the selected probiotics in formulated diets and appropriate feeding regimes for A. testudineus (Thai Koi), H. fossilis (Shing) and Pangasius will be known.\r\n2) Cost-effective quality seeds and appropriate feeding regimes for the above fish species will be developed.\r\n3) Aquaculture production will be increased by ensuring the quality feeds and appropriate feeding regimes.\r\n4) Protocol of satiation feeding in the above fishes will be known.\r\n5) The waste (nitrogen and phosphorus loading) production of the culture system will considerably be reduced. ', 'Cost effective quality feeds and feeding regimes will increase the production of A. testudineus (Thai Koi), H. fossilis (Shing) and Pangasius in the ponds by reducing wastes production.', ''),
(1394, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Reproductive physiology and Genetic', 'Project', 'Development of seed production and grow-out technique for endangered fish (Notopterus chitala, Glossogobius giurus, Eutropiichthys vacha and Monopterus sp.) in Bangladesh.', 'Freshwater Station, BFRI, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2013', 'Development of induced breeding techniques of Chital (N. Chital) and Gobi (G. Giuris).\r\nStudy on the reproductive biology of vacha (E. vacha).\r\nGrowth performance evaluation of native eel (M. cuchia) and chinese eel (M. albus)\r\n', 'Expt. I: Development of induced breeding technique of N. chitala Collection\r\nAbout 40 broods of chital fish having weight range of 1500-2000g and age over two years will be collected from the different farmers'' ponds at Mymensingh area during November-December 2011. Collected fish will be stocked in a pond (1000 m2) for a period of 5 months.\r\nRearing\r\nCollected brood chital will be fed regularly with live feed such as small fish and small prawn regularly as supplementary feed.\r\nInduced breeding\r\nInduced breeding trials will be performed during May to June with given different doses of inducing agent (PG and HCG). After administration the hormone dose male and female fishes will be kept in the breeding arena. After hormone administration, breeding activities will be monitored intensively. After successful breeding, hormone dose will be optimized later on.\r\nExpt. II: Development of induced breeding technique of G. giurus\r\nFor the development of induced breeding technique, 400-500 hundred fish having weight range of 40-60g will be collected from river Brhamputra during November-December. After collection, the fish will be stocked in a rearing pond (400 m2). Brood gobi will be fed with supplementary feed (30% protein). Induced breeding trials will be initiated during April to May with given different doses of inducing agent (PG and Ovaprim). After administration of inducing agent, mature male and female fishes will be kept in hapa which placed in cistern. After hormone injection, breeding data such as spawning time, fertilization, hatching\r\npercentage, hatching time will be recorded properly and all the activities will be monitored intensively.\r\nExpt. III: Study on the reproductive biology of E. vacha\r\nAbout 300-400 live adult E. vacha having weight range 50-100g will be collected from the Brhamputra River during October- November 2011. After collection, live fishes will be stocked in well prepared rearing pond. Then the fish will be fed with supplementary feed\r\ncontaining 30% crude protein. Apart from supplementary feed, live feed such as small fish, small chingri etc. will be supplied three days in a week.\r\nFor the study of reproductive biology, live samples comprised of 10 female and 10 male fish of E. vacha will be collected by seine net during January to June, 2012 from the rearing pond. After collection, the live samples will be brought to the laboratory and the gonads of females and males will be taken out through dissection and preserved for further studies.\r\nFollowing methods will be used to determine the reproductive biology:\r\n	Gonado Somatic Index (GSI)\r\n	Diameter of ova\r\n	Histological study\r\n	Fecundity estimation\r\nIV. Growth performances evaluation of native eel (Monopterus cuchia) and chinese eel\r\n(Monopterus albus)\r\nAn experiment will be conducted to evaluate the growth performances of M. cuchia and M albus at cistern and hapa ecology during January to June 2012. There will be two treatments with three replicates. M cuchia and M albus will be considered as treatment-1 and treatment-2, respectively. In both the treatments stocking density will be maintained at 20/m3. Supplementary feed consisting of live/dead fish will be supplied at the 5% of estimated body weight. Fish will be sampled at fortnightly intervals. After six months of rearing, eels will be\r\nharvested and growth will be evaluated.\r\n', '', 'Fish, Seed production, Genetic fish production.', 'GOB', 2100000, 1300000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Seed Production', 'Fishes', '1) Breeding techniques of N. chitala, G. giuris and E. vacha will be developed; and\r\n2) N. chitala, G. guuris and E. vacha fry will be available for aquaculture with a view to conserve endangered species.', 'Endangered species of fishes like N. chitala, G. guuris and E. vacha will be available due to get its breeding technology.', ''),
