(1414, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Depart. of Fisheries Technology', 'Project', 'PCR-Based method  to detect pathogenic microorganism in exportable shrimp and fish product in Bangladesh', 'Faculty of fisheries, BAU, MY-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', 'Development of protocol for detection of pathogenic microorganism in exportable shrimp and fish products using PCR  based techniques.\r\nImprovement of quality assurance programme &nbsp;of exportable shrimp and fish products.', '', '', 'Fish, Microorganism, Fish Production', 'AU-UGC', 120000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(1415, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture, BAU', 'Project', 'Landing centres and availability of fish FAUNA of Mymensingh Town', 'Mymensingh district', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1. Sources and supplying fishs organisms in Mymensingh town\r\n2. Landing/Entering centers\r\n3. Available of fisheries organisms etc.\r\n4. General post harvest condition for these organism.\r\n5. Fish biodiversity of Mymensingh\r\n', '', 'An investigation was carried out on fish landing centres, availability of fish fauna and marketing system during the period from October 2009 to September 2011 in sixteen landing centres and markets of Mymensingh town. Among a total of 122 species of fishes available of which, 113 finfish; 85 freshwater, 14 exotic and 14 marine; 7 were prawn /shrimps and 2 mud crab and tortoise. The most abundant freshwater fish species were Catla catla, Labeo rohita, Calrias batrachus, Cirrhinus cirrhosis, Channa punctatus and Hilsa ilisha. Common marine fishes were Lates calcarifer, Euthynnus affinis and Mugil cephalus and shellfish, Macrobrachium rosenbergii and Penaeus monodon. Carps and other fish, eg. catfish, tilapia, small indigenous fish, prawn and shrimp including marine fish could be seen in the landing centers and fish markets in Mymensingh town. Trains, buses, trucks and pickups were used as transport of fish to the landing centers from outside to Mymensingh. Most of the fish (84.6%) were brought from outside the district like Netrokona, Jamalpurk, Gazipur and Kishoreganj. Main source of the fishes were different ponds, haors, beels and rivers of Mymensingh. \r\nThe market chain from farmers to consumers encompassed mainly primary, secondary and retail markets and a large number of people were involved in fish marketing channel as bepari, aratdar, paiker and retailer. Paiker and  bepari bought fish from producers and sold fish to retailer through aratdar. Ti was extimated that total marketing cost of fish for aratdar was Tk. 1.33, paiker Tk. 6.05 and retailer Tk. 1.83 per kg of fish. The highest marketing costs (Tk.  6.05) were for paiker because they had paid higher aratdari commission and higher transportation cost. Average net profit was Tk. 3.32 for paikers, for aratdars Tk. 1.63 for retailers Tk. 5.23 at peak period per kg of fish. To improve marketing channel physical facilities including unnecessary and unexploited middlemen should be eliminated.  \r\n', 'Fish, Fauna, Fish biodiversity', 'AU-UGC', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fisheries Production', 'Fishes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(1416, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Microbiology and Hygiene, BAU', 'Project', 'Prevalence and characteristics of food poisoning Bactria in poultry and poultry products of selected area in Bangladesh.', '', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '1.	To isolate food borne bacteria such as salmonella, campylobacter and stx producing E. coli from poultry and poultry products.\r\n2.	To determine tin vitro susceptibility of food borne bacteria against commonly used antimicrobial agents. \r\n3.	To investigate the characteristics of these pathogens by PCR', '', 'An attempt was undertaken to determine the prevalence and characteristic of food poisoning bacterial such as Escherichia coli in apparently healthy chickens from poultry farms, live bird markets and a village at Sadar Upazila, Mymensingh. A total of 350 local samples were aseptically collected from layers (n + 150), broilers  (n = 150) and indigenous chackens (n=50). Samples were enriched in nutrient broth and streaked onto Eosine Methylene Blue (EMB) agar, MacConkey (MC) agar, blood agar, Salmonella Shigella (SS) agar and brilliant green agar (BGA) for cultural characterization of E. coli isolates from chickens. Culture positive samples yielded characteristic colonies of E. coli with metallic sheen on EMB agar, bright pink or red colonies on MC agar, hemolysis on blood agar, slight pink smooth colonies on SS agar and green colour colonies on BGA media. E. coli isolates produced acid and gas by fermenting sugars (dextrose, sucrose, lactose, maltose and manitol) and gave positive reaction to indol, methyl red (MR) and catalase tests but negative reaction to voges proskeur (VP) test. Pathogenicity test in 1-4 day old Swiss albino mice indicated that E. coli isolates of chickens were pathogenic. The antibiotic sensitivity pattern demonstrated that E. coli-isolates were moderately sensitive to ciprofloxacin, chloramphenicol, gentamicin and cephalexin, less sensitive to kanamycin and cephradine and resistant to amoxicillin, streptomycin, tetracycline, and nalidixic acid. Out of 350 clocal samples 276 (78.86%) were E. coli positive. Data of this study suggest that intestine of chicken is a major reservoirs of E. coli. ', '', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1417, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetics and Plant Breeding', 'Project', 'Sustainable Rice Seed Production and Delivery system in Southern Bangladesh (Barishal, Rajbari and Faridpur Districts).', 'Barishal, Rajbari and Faridpur Districts', 'High', '', '', '', '', 'December 2011', 'March 2013', '1) Coordinate and support production and distribution of different categories of seeds of high yielding and stress tplerant rice varieties in 22 Upazilas of Barishal, Rajbari and Faridpur districts through a network of partners involving government organizations. One thousand five hundred farmers from each Upazila will be selected and thereby a total of 33,000 farmers will be involved in the project activities.\r\n2) Establish effective systems for targeted dissemination, farmers (380) centered high quality seed multiplication and monitoring, evaluation and impact assessment to ensure maximum impact through sustainable seed production and delivery.\r\n3) Increase farmers awareness of the new high yielding and stress tolerant varieties and improve their knowledge on proper handling, storage of seeds and good management practices.\r\n4) Strengthen the capacity of seed production and distribution systems to ensure sustenance and longer-term impacts by a) enhancing the facilities and increasing the capacity of key partners for systematic production of sufficient seeds b) Training partners involved and providing relevant information on production, handling, storage and delivery. ', '', '', 'Stress tolerant, seed production, quality seed multiplication', '', 11952200, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Seed Production', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
