(1427, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery, BAU, Mymensingh', 'Project', 'Development of Briquetting technology for coconut coir dust ', 'Khulna, Bagherhat, Jessore and Mymensingh districts', 'High', 'Adaptive', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '1.To conduct a field survey to assess the availability of raw materials for coconut coir dust briquette in Bangladesh.\r\n2.To develop a technology for coconut coir dust briquetting.\r\n3.To determine the physical properties, heating value and burning quality of briquette from coconut coir dust.', '', 'This research project was conducted to develop briquetting technology for coconut coir dust to produce briquette and to investigate the physical properties, heating value and burning quality of produced briquette. The study was conducted during the period of July 2010 to June 2011 in the districts of Khulna, Bagerhat, Jessore and Mymensingh. Briquette was not formed only with coconut coir dust even mixing with binding material. Briquettes were formed after mixing coconut coir dust with rice husk at different ratios. At constant moisture content (10.8%)(wb) the density of briquette formed by the mixing of coco coir dust and rice husk at the ration of 1:1 and 1:2 were found 1.48 gm/cc and 1.53 gm/cc respectively. At the same moisture content the crushing strength to briquette formed by the mixing of coco dust and rice husk at the ration of 1:1 and 1:2 were found 83.02 kg/cm2 and 96.25 kg/cm2 respectively. But with the variation of moisture content both density and crushing strength changes if the coconut coir dust and rice husk rations in coconut coir dust briquette is kept constant. Coconut coir dust briquette in the ratio 1:1 and 1:2 took 15.81% and 16.98% more time respectively to burn than that of rice husk briquette in the same Chula. The calorific value of coconut coir dust briquette of ratio 1:1 and 1:2 was 4621 Kcal/kg and 5277 Kcal/kg respectively but for rice husk briquette it was 4345Kcal/kg respectively. But with the variation of moisture content calorific value changes if the coconut coir dust and rice husk rations in coconut coir dust briquette was kept constant. Though Briquettes made from coconut coir dust and rice husk at ration of 1:1 and 1:2 were found more compact and harder than rice husk briquette. So for transportation and storage these will be better than rice husk briquette. ', 'Coconut coir dust, ', 'BAU', 119500, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(1428, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Horticulture', 'Project', 'Carrot and Onion seed production and related post harvest innovations to provide well adapted and nutritious vegetable for Bangladesh.', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1) Identify high-yielding, nutritious onion and carrot cultivars adapted to a major south Asian production area.\r\n2) Establish Bangladesh oriented crop production and post harvest storage guidelines and mannuals, programs and cell phone based information to integrate water, nutrient and pest management practices that optimize inputs, minimize off target impacts, and provide sound post harvest storage practices for seed production.\r\n3) Establish onion and carrot seed production systems to better fulfill local demands with a goal to decrease expensive seed imports, increase crop yield and improve human nutrition.\r\n4) Establish collaboration with AVRDC/WVC on large scale carrot and onion seed production.', '', '', '', 'USDA', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1446, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Formulation of Bio-Pesticides in controlling Phomopsis fruit rot, foot/collar rot and shoot and fruit borer of eggplant.', 'IPM laboratory, Department of Plant Pathology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2010', '1)	To develop effective biologically based materials to control Phomopsis fruit rot, collar/foot rot and shoot and fruit borer in eggplant.\r\n2)	The adoption of biologically based materials as a component of integrated pest management of phomopsis fruit rot, collar/foot rot and shoot and fruit borer of eggplants.\r\n', '', 'Tablets made of garlic (Allium sativum), allamanda (Allamanda cathertica), neem (Azadiracta indica) and there binary mixures were inhibitory to Phomopsis vexans. Garlic and allamanda tablets sprayed at 1:4 w/v concentration effectively reduced leaf infection, and fruit infection and lesion size on fruit. Among the treatments, neem tablet (1:4 w/v) was found effective to reduce shoot and fruit infestation of eggplant. For successful management of fruit rot of eggplant, spray of garlic or allamanda and for shoot and fruit borer of eggplant, spray of neem tablet (1:4 w/v) may be recommended at flowering and fruiting stage. Decomposition of waste by applying Trichoderma harzianum and growth of four different crops in the decomposed municipality waste was studied. Municipality wastes (degradable parts) decomposed by T. harzianum was used for growth of four species BAU Begub-1, tomato (Minto), Chilli (NS1701) and Indian Spinach (BARI-1). Five treatments such as field soil, mixture of 50% decomposed waste and 50% field soil. 100% decomposed waste, mixture of 50% decomposed waste and 50% undecomposed waste and 100% undecomposed waste were employed. The plants of 100% decomposed waste grew vigorously in consideration of all growth parameters like seed germination, plant height, number of branches, number of leaves etc. and the same treatment gave better performance in reducing disease incidence. The plants of 50% decomposed waste and 50% undecomposed and mixture of 50% decomposed waste and 50% field soil gave moderate result. It reveals that treatment was effective when at least half of waste was mixed with Trichoderma suspension. Thus the experimental results open the possibility of using municipality waste for compost preparation. The F5 generations of eggplant crosses were evaluated for their genotypic and phenotypic performances for disease resistance and concerned yield characters under confined field condition. The inoculated F5&not; plants remained free of infection from P. vexans and exhibited differential disease reaction. In random amplified polymorphic DNA (RAPD) technique, 3 decamer primers generated 28 and 31 bands in (Laffa S &times; IPM-31 and Dohazari G &times; IPM-31) from which 16 (57.1%) and 18 (58.1%) were polymorphic, respectively. The F5 progenies showed different gene diversity. Comparatively higher genetic distance and lower genetic identity was observed between the genotype combinations.     \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Bio-pesticide, Phomopsis, Fruit rot, collar rot, fruit borer of eggplant', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Vegetable disease management', 'Eggplant', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
