(1433, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Irrigation and Water Management', 'Project', 'Yield and Water Productivity to deficit irrigation imposed at different growth stages of Hybrid Maize', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-06-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '1.	To investigate the effects of single stress of deficit irrigation on growth and development of maize applied at different growth stages or days after sowing.\r\n2.	To study the effects of deficit irrigation on yield and yield component of maize.\r\n3.	To find out the water productivity of maize.\r\n4.	To identify the moisture sensitive growth stages of maize.\r\n', '', 'This study demonstrated the experimental evidence of the effects of deficit irrigation on yield and water use efficiency (WUE) of maize. The experiment consisted of two factors: irrigation and variety of maize. Irrigation had five treatments/levels  Io: on irrigation (control), I1: irrigation at IW (irrigation water applied)/CPE (cumulative pan evaporation) = 0.4, I2: irrigation at IW/CPE = 0.06, I3: irrigation at IW/CPE = 0.8 and I4: irrigation at IW/CPE = 1.0, and maize variety had three treatments  V1: BARI hybrid maize 5 (BHM-5), V2: BARI hybrid maize 7 (BHM-7) and V3: Pacific 984. Maize was grown with three irrigations applied at 43, 63 and 83 day after sowing (DAS) and recommended s standard fertilizer doses. The experiment was laid out in a split plot design with three replications. The irrigation treatments were employed in the main plots and the varieties were in the sub-plots. Both the irrigation and variety employed different degrees of influence on growth the yield attributes of maize; some attributes differed degrees of influence on growth and yield attributes of maize; some attributes differed significantly while other differed insignificantly. Treatment I4 produced the highest grain yield (9.30 t ha-1) and I0 produced the lowest yield (7.62 t ha-1). Pacific 984 produced the highest grain yield (8.60 t ha-1) and BHM-7 produced the lowest yield (7.31 t ha-1). There was however no significant (p=0.05) effect of irrigation and variety on the grain yield of maize. The interaction effect between irrigation and varieties, on the other hand, exerted significant impact on grain yield. The treatment combination I4V3 produced the highest grain yield (9.31 t ha-1) and I0V2 produced the lowest yield) 6.34 t ha-1). The water use efficiency differed significantly among the irrigation treatments but insignificantly among the varieties. In case of interaction effects, WUE differed significantly.  The maximum stressed treatment (I0) provided the highest VUE and maximum irrigated treatment (I4) provided the lowest WUE.', 'Yield, Water productivity, Irrigation, Hybrid maize', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Irrigation', 'Maize', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
