(1466, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Local and Global implications for use of catfish (Pangasianodon hypophthalmas) pond sediments in fodder grass production in peri urban areas of Mymensingh, Bangladesh.', 'Mymensingh district', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Farmed fish and milk production have grown rapidly in much of Asia in recent decades to meet the needs of rapidly growing and urbanizing populations. Catfish (Pangasianodon hypophthalmus) production in Mymensingh, Bangladesh is intensive, resulting in huge sediment deposit in the pond due to regular supplies of artificial feeds. The removal and disposal of nutrient-rich sediments creates pollution of receiving water bodies both locally and through inefficient use of energy intensive inputs, globally. Regular removal of pond sediment is time consuming and incurs high labour costs. Conversely, Mymensingh is an important region for dairying lacking of quality green fodder linked to the cost of N fertilizer (urea). The use of N fertilizers is cost-intensive; the manufacture and distribution of such oil-based urea is major part of the energy cost of food production and is highly sensitive to volatility in energy prices. In this context, the objective of the present study was to examine the potential for using catfish pond sediments to substitute for conventional N fertilizers used for green fodder grass production to support dairying. An experiment was conducted in Pangasius farm in Dhanikhola village under Trisal Upazila focusing the effects of Pangasius pond sediment on the growth and production of para grass (Brachiaria mutica). According to soil analysis, the major soil nutrients such as nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P) and potassium (K) were very high in Pangasius pond sediment compared to virgin soil. The total nitrogen content of the sediment was 0.30% which was double than that in the sediment of carp polyculture pond, and traditional compost (0.4-0.5%) made of animal waste and crop residues. The organic carbon in Pangasius pond sediment (3.15 &plusmn; 0.04) was more than double than that of virgin soil (1.31 &plusmn; 0.1). The fodder was cultivated with various levels of Pangasius pond sediment in a completely randomized designed on-farm experiment in 6 treatment, each with three replications. The size of each replication plot was 25 m2 (5m x 5m) which was organized in the rice-field closed to the Pangasius farm. The nutrient doses of the treatment 1-6 were of control (only virgin soil), 100% inorganic N, 75% inorganic N + 25% sediment N, 50% inorganic N + 50% sediment N, 25% inorganic N + 75% sediment N, and 100% sediment N, respectively. Following transplantation of cutting (25 cm in length), the fodder was harvested at the pre-flowering stage (45 days after transplantation). The highest average length of para grass was 85.57 cm in T6 at first cutting where 100% N was supplied from pond sediment. After first cutting a mechanized floating irrigation system was developed to irrigate Pangasius pond sediment into the plot that increased the nutrient content of soil and resulting in higher growth (108.49 cm) of grass in T6. Accordingly the yield of fodder grass in an individual cutting was high ranging from 4.52-6.20 t/ha. The yield of fodder grass was almost similar in three cutting stages for the corresponding treatments. The harvested grass was instantly purchased by the local dairy farm owners showing their positive interest to cultivation of fodder grass. ', 'Calfish, Fish, Pond sediments, Fodder grass, ', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fisheries Production', 'Fishes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(1467, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Poultry Science', 'Project', 'Reducing risk from arsenic contamination for poor people to assess the transfer of arsenic from feed and contaminated water to poultry birds and dairy cattle.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'A study was conducted to investigate the effects of naturally occurring Arsenic on the performance of broiler and desi (local) chicken and its transmission to meat and organs. Two trails were conducted with 0, 250, 500, 1000 ppb of Arsenic (As) in drinking water to broiler (Trial-1) and desi chicken (Trial-2). In trial -1 the birds were reared in cage $ the expedient continued for a period of 28 days, were commercial broiler diets were fed ad-libitum. In trial 2, desi birds were reared in cage for a period of 70 days. Starter diet was fed ad-libitum which was prepared by Arsenic contaminated feed ingredients collected from arsenic contaminated area of Faridpur. \r\nBody weight, feed consumption, FCR and dressing (%) were reduced with the increase of arsenic concentration. Mortality was significantly increased with the increase of arsenic concentration. Arsenic was also found in the edible meat, organs and the dropping. Arsenic level in poultry meat and organs was below the level harmful for human consumption. However, we should be concerned about the indiscriminate use of chemical fertilizer, pesticide growth-promoter etc that may affect meat quality for continuous use. \r\n', 'Poultry, Broiler, Arsenic ', '', 323505, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Arsenic', 'Poultry', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
