(1535, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Dept. of Animal Breeding and Genetics', 'Project', 'In situ conservation and improvement of endangered livestock species in Bangladesh: The distribution and phenotypes of Gayal and Aseel in the home tract. ', 'Sarail Upazila of Brahmanbaria district, and Ruma, Roangchhari, Thanchi Upazila of Bandarban district', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '', '', '', '', '1.	To find out the actual number of Aseel Gayal in the home tract in Bangladesh\r\n2.	To study the economically important phenotypes and genotypes of Aseel  and Gayal. \r\n3.	To study behavior of Aseel and Gayal specially their local adaptability \r\n4.	To take in situ conservation for production seed stock and improving their productivity. \r\n', '', 'This study has been planned to conduct in situ conservation program of Aseel in Brahmanbaria district and of Gayal in Bandarban for producing seed stocks and improving their productivity. To achieve this goal, the actual number of Aseel and Gayal in the home tract in Bangladesh are being estimated, awareness are being  grown among the farmers and policy makers about the importance of conservation  of these species. The economically important phenotypes, behavior and local adaptability of Aseel and Gayal are also being studies. \r\n\r\nIn depth survey was conducted in Sarail Upazila of Brahmanbaria district, and Ruma, Roangchhari, Thanchi Upazila of Bandarban district for knowing the actual numbers of Aseel and Gayal. So far 95 farmers have been enlisted in Ruma and Royangchhari Upazila. The average number of Gayal was 4.95. 32 Aseel farmers in the home track i. e. Sarail have been enlishted so far. The average number of Aseel per house hold was 8.12. The coat of adult Gayal was black. White stocking in the lower part of the legs of all adult Gayal was very prominent. Coat colour of new born calf was red or coffee. The height at wither and weight for adult males ranged from 126 to 136 cm and 490 to 577 kg respectively. The PVC and hemoglobin value was found to be 33.5 &plusmn; 5.71% and 13.43 &plusmn; 2.9 g/100ml respectively. Gayal was found to be sold as sacrifice animals during Oros in Chittagong.\r\n\r\nThe plumage colour of Aseel cock was usually white or red in the wing region and black in the breast region. The plumage colour of Aseel hen was usually brown. Pea comb was common in Aseel. Ear lobe colour was red. Shank colour was yellow. Skin colour was white except the breast portion of cock. Breast region of cock was usually featherless and coloru was red. Egg shell colour was white to light brown. Weight of male ranged from 4.0 kg to 2.9 kg whereas that of female ranged from 1.7 to 2.9 kg. Number of egg per clutch ranged from 8 to 20 while pause period within a clutch was only 1 day. Egg weight ranged from 40 gm to 56 gram whereas average egg weight were about 46 gm. The maximum and minimum sizes of egg were (54 x 40) sq. mm and (46 x 34) sq. mm.  \r\n', 'Livestock, Species, Gayal, Aseel, ', 'BAS-USDA', 35400000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Species', 'Livestock', '', '', ''),
(1536, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Surgery and Obstetrics', 'Project', 'Speed up a Genetic improvement of indigenous sheep through multiple Ovulation and Embryo Transfer (MOET) Technique', '', 'High', 'Applied', '', '01-01-2010', '', '', '', '1.Monitoring their reproductive performances \r\n2.Development of technique of vestries, synchronization in ewes and semen preservation in rams.\r\n3.Evaluate and establish the potential for using MOET for speeding up of genetic improvement. \r\n4.Investigate the factors affecting the success of MOET in this species \r\n', '', 'Twenty six (26) indigenous sheep of 3-5 months old (16 ewe lambs and 10 ram lambs) were randomly divided into controlled (traditional management system) and supplemented group. The ewes in supplemented group showed faster growing rate than ewes in controlled group. The age and weight at puberty in local ewes were 6.8&plusmn;0.84 months and 9.6&plusmn;1.0kg respectively under traditional management. However, the supplemented ewes reach puberty at significantly earlier age (4.38&plusmn;0.52) months). The estrus cycle length in local ewes was 17.0&plusmn;1.4 days. The supplemented ewes had the shorter oestrus cycle length compared with traditional management system. The onset of estrus was determined by the behavioral signs. The duration of oestrus was 27.9&plusmn;6.5 hrs. and it was about the same with the supplemented group. The mature body weight was also greater in supplemented ewes. The gestation length was about the same in both groups (142.3&plusmn;1.9 vs 145&plusmn;0 days). The lamb survival rate, birth weight and weaning weight of lambs were 70%, 1.1&plusmn;0.2kg and 4.2&plusmn;0.3kg in controlled and 91%, 1.2&plusmn;0.2 kg and 6.2&plusmn;2.8 kg in supplemented group, respectively. The post-partum onset of estrus was earlier in supplemented ewes compared with controlled ewes. Like the ewes the supplemented fams showed faster growing rate than rams maintained in traditional management system (32.4&plusmn;6.6 vs 21.8&plusmn;5.5 g/day/ram). The scrotal growth rate followed the same pattern as the body growth rate. The age and eight at puberty was about the same in both groups. The adult body eights (kg) and scrotal circumferences (cm) of rams of controlled group and supplemented group were 1.4&plusmn;3 &amp; 15.94&plusmn;2.3 kg, and 20.5&plusmn;3.7 &amp; 21.9&plusmn;1.1 cm, respectively. The semen collection technique was adopted with the rams of both groups. The volume, color density and concentration were same in both system of management. Mass movement of the spermatozoa was higher in supplemented rams than controlled rams. Motility % of spermatozoa was significantly higher in supplemented rams than controlled rams, in fresh and 24 hrs. and 48 hrs. of preservation of semen (86.0&plusmn;6.1, 77.4 &plusmn; 6.2, 66.8 &plusmn; 5.4 vs 80.0 &plusmn; 6.1, 69.44 &plusmn; 6.0, 60.44 &plusmn; 7.3). Similar higher pattern was observed for % live spermatozoa (94.0 &plusmn; 1.5, 91.8 &plusmn; 1.6 and 85.1 &plusmn; 3.4 vs 93.3 &plusmn; 1.5, 90 &plusmn; 2.9 and 83.3 &plusmn; 3.64). % HOST positive spermatozoa were also higher in supplemented rams. ', '', 'BAS-USDA', 7302200, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
