(1665, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pharmacology', 'Project', 'Poverty alleviation of the destitute women and marginal farmers at sadar thana of Mymensingh district through improved goat farming by controlling parasitic diseases by using neem and pine apple leaves.', 'Department of Pharmacology, Marginal farm women of Mymensingh sadar Upazila', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', '  Bangladesh has about 35.5 million populations (FAO, 1999) of goat and play very significant contribution to rural economy, nutrition and employment of rural poor peoples. More than 30% of rural people in Bangladesh do not hold any land for crop or fish cultivation and rearing of small scale livestock (goat) farming would be an important area where these landless people could seek self employment. Traditionally rural women are the owners of the most of the goats. Goat farming would help generating destitute womens income and empower them in the family. Goat is popularly known as poor mans cow. Goat meat contributes a lot in meeting up our animal protein requirements. Goat skin export significantly helps us earning foreign currency. There are ample opportunities for us to export goat meat in the world markets. Thats why we believe that poverty alleviation through modern goat farming is an appropriate approach of time. At present goats are being reared traditionally in a kind of backyard system. However, intensive goat farming is growing in parallel to the traditional goat rearing system. Over the year goats have become an important tool for poverty alleviation and social empowerment of the poor people in both rural and urban situation in the country. In spite of the fact profitable goat rearing in Bangladesh is faced by several problems, like shortage of feed, poor management and housing and prevalence of various infection and non-infection and parasitic diseases, lack of breeding bucks, proper marketing facilities and financial assistance are serious threat to the goat production in Bangladesh. Gastrointestinal nematodiasis is common problem of livestock in Bangladesh. The ecological factors prevailing here are highly conducive for the survival, multiplication and perpetuation of animal parasites, of which gastrointestinal nematodiasis are encountered most among goat and cattle. In the Department of Pharmacology research work was conducted by using herbal medicine for the treatment of livestock diseases, neem and pineapple leaves were found having anthelmintics action. Training program was conducted in the department of Pharmacology, BAU in 4 batches and altogether 50 farmers were trained in a year.', 'Poverty alleviation, Marginal farmers, Goat rearing, Neem, Pineapple', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 50, 'Poverty alleviation of destitutute women', 'Goat rearing', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
