(1914, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'BAU Germplasm Center', 'Project', 'Collection, Conservation, Characterization and Evaluation of under utilized fruit tree germplasm of coastal and hilly areas of Bangladesh.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2011', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2011', '1) To collect and conserve the germplasm resources especially indigenous/underutilized/ethnic/endangered fruit trees of coastal and hilly areas Bangladesh.\r\n2) To screen and develop hish yielding, regular bearing &amp; disease and pest resistant fruit varieties of indigenous/underutilized/endangered through selection.\r\n3) To develop propagation protocols and tree/orchard management and post harvest management of selected fruit trees.\r\n4) To select off-season fruit species/varieties for year round production of fruits in Bangladesh to meet up the nutritional food deficiencies.\r\n5) To identify and document the distinguishing morpho physiolosian and molecular characteristics of the important plants.', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Germplasm Centre (BAU-GPC) is implementing a three years project funded by DAS-USDA since January 2011 to find out suitable round the year producing fruit varieties for coastal and hilly areas of Bangladesh and conserve germpalsm at BAU-GPC. A survey study has been conducted at the coastal and hilly areas through prescribed questionnaire. A number of germplasm has been collected from both the areas. The collected germplasm area Kawphal, Monkey jack, River ebony, Velvet apple, Sapota, Pummelo, Woode apple, Custard apple, Golden apple, Bullocks heart, Wax jambu, Mango, Guava, Elephant apple, Star gooseberry, Burmese grape, Carambola, Jamun, Pomegranate, Karanda, Bael, Indian olive, Roktogota, Pyalagota, Chinaduly, Lotkon, Coagula, Budumchua etc. All these germaplsam were planted at the BAS-USDA plot in BAU-GPC. Research students are conducting their research on Morphological study of collected fruit tree germp;asm, postharvest behavior of selected fruit tree germplasm and standardization of propagation techniques of underutilized and endangered fruit tree germplasm of coastal and hilly regions. Results showed that maximum success was found in air layering (85-95%) on guava, max Jambu and stargooseberry followed by cleft (80-90%) on mango pummelo, sapota, woodapple and custard apple whereas success of stem cutting and root cutting were less (0-62%).', 'Fruits, Coastal and Hilly areas', 'BAS-USDA', 5930000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Porduction', 'Fruits', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
