(1936, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Food Technology and Rural Industries', 'Project', 'Studies on the processing and preservation of jack fruit and utilization of jack fruit by-products.', 'Department of Food Technology and Rural Industries', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To utilize the waste of the jack fruit as by-products.\r\n2) To conduct field demonstration and performance evaluation among consumers of different class and income groups.\r\n3) To prepare manuals on the processing and preservation of jack fruit on the basis of research findings.', '1) Preparation of mixed jam/or jelly with different proportions of jack fruit pulp, guava pulp or juice, mosta juice etc.\r\n2) Preparation of jack fruit pulp jam or jelly with addition of artificial flavour and colour.\r\n3) Preparation of soft drinks or beverage based on jack fruit pulp.\r\n4) Bottling of jack fruit colls in sugar syrup in tin cans.\r\n5) Utilization of jack fruit rind for preparing jam.\r\n6) Utilization of jack fruit seed powder for preparing biscuites.\r\n7) Approximate analysis of jack fruit pulp, rind and seeds for carbohydrate.  ', 'Jack fruit or ''Kathal'' (Articarpus intogrifolia) is a major commercial fruit of Bangladesh which produced 1,98,000 tons of it in 1979. The leading districts are Dhaka, Rangpur, Sylhet, Dinajpur, Khulna, Rajshahi, Kustia and Tangail. This fruit, perhaps world''s largest is indigenous to Bangladesh, India and Srilanka. Some of the specialization of jack fruit, or for that matter the points in favour of promoting its production in a country like Bangladesh is that\r\n1) It has regular bearing habit.\r\n2) High yield per tree\r\n3) It is used at both ripe and unripe stage\r\n4) It''s wastes are excellent cattle feed and\r\n5) It demands very little management.', 'Jack fruit, regular bearing, ripe and unripe, Kathal', 'BAURES', 50000, 0, 0, 'Report', 'Workshops', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
