(1941, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pathology', 'Project', 'Genotyping Salmonella in Poultry in Bangladesh using Polymerase Chain Reaction.', 'Department of pathology', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Salmonellosis is a hyperendemic disease affecting both man and animals. Salmonella infections are important diseases of poultry. Salmonellosis in poultry is caused by Salmonella enterica sub sp., serovars Gallinarum, Pullorum and Enteritis. This disease causes morbidity and mortality in poultry and responsible for significant economic loss in all the phases of poultry from production to marketing. The infection also has zoonotic importance. The situation may come to Bangladesh that eggs and poultry meat may be exported to foreign countries. In that situation our products must be free from Salmonella. For the control and prevention of these infections, early and sensitive methods for diagnosis of diseases are of prime importance. Conventionally, the diseases can be tentatively diagnosed by (a) sign and symptoms (b) clinical history (c) gross lesions (d) histopathological lesions (e) culture, isolation and identification by staining and biochemical tests. However, all the methods are laborious and time consuming. For confirmative, sensitive and rapidly diagnosis, a Polymerase Chain Reaction using some primers (published in other scientific journals) were adapted for diagnostic approach of Salmonella organism in poultry. In this investigation 100 locally isolated Salmonella organism were used. In this investigation 4 sets of primers were used. We tested only 22 isolated samples randomly out of 100 samples for 4 sets of primers and found positive for targeting gene of invA by Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR). The PCR assay was highly specific as the PCR amplicon of 284 base pairs was observed in this investigation for all types of Salmonella identification. A definitive identification of Salmonella organisms was possible in less than 3 hrs. This PCR method is highly specific as well as sensitive and may be an effective molecular tool in the rapid detection of Salmonella organisms in the poultry. ', 'Salmonellae, poultry, Polymerase, Chain reaction', 'UGC', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Animal disease management', 'Poultry', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
