(1951, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry', 'Project', 'Impact of Mining activities on Geology of Barapukuria open coal mine area in Dinajpur, Bangladesh.', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry, BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '1) To get preliminary information about the impact of mining activities on the geology of Barapukuria open coal mine area, Dinajpur, Bangladesh.\r\n2) To determine the metal concentration in soil, water and plants on the study area.\r\n3) To study on mineralogy of the target area.\r\n4) To assess the metalic pollution level and their mobility pattern in the area.\r\n5) To make some recommendations on the basis of the research, so that further contamination can be minimized.', 'a) Preliminary information about the impact of mining activities will be collected by visiting the study area along with a questionnaire.\r\nb) Soil, water and plant samples will be collected from different selected sites and will be processed for subsequent chemical analysis following standard methods.\r\nc) The concentration of different metals (Cd, Cu, Pb, Zn, Cr, As, Ni etc.) with their speciation in soils, water and plants will be determined by Atomic Absorption Spectrophotometer (AAS) on the basis of standard analytical techniques described by Sparks et al. (1996).\r\nd) The mineralogical constituents present in the sample will be determined by the X-ray Diffraction (XRD) analysis at SRDI, Dhaka.\r\ne) Assessment of metalic pollution will be done on the basis of different standard indexes available on literature.\r\nf) Depending on the study results, some recommendations will be made for the appropriate authority of Bangladesh, which will help to take necessary initiatives to minimize the contamination level as well as it will open new dimensions in conserving soil health and environment as a whole.', 'The research work was conducted at the Department of Agriculture Chemistry, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh.\r\n\r\nThe research work was conducted at the Department of Agricultural Chemistry, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh to investigate the status of heavy metal concentration as well as to assess their pollution level in water and soils of Barapukuria open coal mining area. A total of 50 water and 42 soil samples were collected from 4 sides of mining area and in each side up to 1 km distance was maintained. The collected water samples were analyzed for chemical parameters viz., pH EC, GTDS, DO, Ca,  Mg, Na, K, Zn, Cu, Mn, Fe, B, CI, HCO3, PO4 and SO4. The pH of water samples fluctuated between 6.8 to 7.37. The electrical conductivity (EC) of water samples were within the range of 85 to 907 &micro;S cm-1 indicating low to high salinity. The DO of all collected water samples were within the range of 1.5 to 1.8 mg L-1 with an average of 1.7 mg L-1 indicating that aquatic life is in under stress. The cation chemistry showed dominance for Ca, Na and Mg while the dominant anions were HCO3 and SO4. The most dominant metal in water was Mn and 94% water samples were exceeded the maximum acceptable level (0.20 mg L-1) indicating Mn toxicity in water of the study area. The average concentration of CU, Zn, Pb, Cd and Cr in the soil samples were 22.42, 44.36, 19.63, 0.18 and 55.09 &micro;g g-1, respectively. Out of 42 sampling stations, 27, 34, 33, 32 and 12 locations had the values higher for Cu, Zn, Cd, Cr and Pb, respectively than that of the geochemical baseline value of the study area. The deposition of outlet fly ash may responsible to increase heavy metal concentrations in surface soils around the study area. The overall order of soil environment hazard by various metals in the study area was Zn &gt; Cr &gt; CU &gt;Pb &gt; Cd. The calculated PLI values ranged from 0.54-1.69 for soil samples and  the study results revealed that the contamination factor for most of the sampling sites for all studied heavy metals except Pb were higher than 1.0, which indicates that Zn, Cu, Cd and Cr were the major pollutants in the soils of Barapukuria  open coal mine area. Finally, the calculated Igeo values of some  soils of Barapukuria open coal mine area revealed moderate pollution level by CU, Zn, Cd and Cr from anthropogenic sources. \r\n', 'Coal Mine, Geology, ', 'MOSICT', 2200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Pollution', 'Soil and Water', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(1952, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pathology', 'Project', 'Development of Pathologic and nucleic Acid Based Diagnostic Tool for the Diagnosis of Avian mycoplasmosis. ', 'Department of pathology', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-09-2008', '31-07-2009', '01-09-2008', '31-07-2009', '', '', 'For effective control of Mycoplasmosis, proper early diagnosis is the corner-stone. The laboratory method to culture and identify mycoplasma takes 5-20 days, laborious and expensive and needs expertise. Therefore, a sensitive method for identification of mycoplasma species from clinical samples is needed. The objective of the study was to develop a rapid diagnostic tool for the detection and identification of the avian mycoplasmas. A total of 28 samples, lung exudates, swabs from trachea were collected from dead birds of different poultry farms in Mymensingh district during November 2008 to June 2009. Samples were collected in 10% buffered formalin for histopathological study. Swabs were collected in mycoplasma both supplemented with supplement-G. Additionally Kanamycin solution was added to prevent the growth of bacteria and then the organisms were transferred into mycoplasma agar for isolation. Horse serum were used instead of supplement-G for showing the change of growth pattern. Histopathological studies were conducted using routine procedure. Isolated mycoplasmas were subjected to DNA extraction. PCR was done using a commercial PCR kit. The growth of the organisms were found from 3 days of post inoculation in broth and from 7 days in agar but typical fried egg appearance of Mycoplasma colony was found after 3 passages at 18 days. The pathological study revealed the presence of mycoplasmal related tissue changes. DNA was extracted from mycoplasma vaccine and used as positive control during PCR. DNA extracted from mycoplasma vaccine and the extracted DNA from isolated Mycoplasma was amplified and gave amplified product of 900 bp that was between expected product size of 888-938 bp for MG and 497 bp that was between expected product size of 473-497 bp for MS respectively by forward and reverse primer designed by Lauerman et al. 1995. In this study, preliminary results from field samples suggest that culture using Mycoplasma agar and broth supplement with Supplement-G and kanamycin solution could be useful for the isolation of pathogenic avian mycoplasmas. Culture could be comparatively easier by using horse serum instead of supplement-G. PCR technique could be a useful and rapid diagnostic test for detection and identification of pathogenic poultry mycoplasmas. ', 'Pathologic, Avian Mycoplasmosis, PCR, DNA', 'University Grants Commission of Bangladesh', 62800, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Animal Disease management', 'Avian Mycoplasmosis', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
