(1961, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Medicine', 'Project', 'Evaluation of Hyper-immune serum for the treatment of Newcastle disease in commercial layer chickens', 'BAU campus', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', 'a.	To determine the efficacy of hyperimmune serum in the treatment of Newcastle diseases in commercial layer chickens\r\nb.	Project report publication.\r\n', '', '', 'Diseases, Chicken, Poultry, Hyperimmune serum', 'BAU-UGC', 120000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Chickens', '', '', ''),
(1962, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Parasitology', 'Project', 'Effects of parasitism on growth, morbidity and mortality of calves under rural conditions.', '', 'High', 'Applied', '', '01-08-1993', '31-07-1994', '01-08-1993', '31-07-1994', 'The main objective is to identify parasites including load which affects growth of calves and then determine tactical/strategic control to achieve better growth of calves in rural Bangladesh.', 'All households in four villages adjacent to Bangladesh Agricultural University will be included under this study. Livestock holdings and types of livestock including age groups within each family will be recorded. All calves born out of cows during initial three-four months of the study will be recorded including their weight, and general body condition. Around 50 calves will be necessary for collection of useful information and analysis of data.All these new born calves will be weighed using spring balance twice in the morning (before and after suckling).All feed stuff made available to these calves during their growth will also be weighed. Once in a month to record parasitism, calves infected with parasites will be grouped into two (70% as treatment group and 30% as control group); the treatment group will be treated with appropriate anthelminties in the following day of parasite detection. As a prerequisite for obtaining useful information the period of study should continue at least for 360 days for each calf.', '', '', 'BAU-UGC', 70000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(1963, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Science ', 'Project', 'Preparation of organic fertilizer using dairy farm waste and minimize the environmental pollution. ', 'Experimental dairy farm of Khamaree Shahzadpur, Sirajgonj, adjacent two other dairy farms and laboratory, Department of Animal Science, Department of soil science and Department of Microbiology, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1.	Develop of cost effective method of preparation organic fertilizer.\r\n2.	Use as alternative of chemical fertilizer.\r\n3.	To improve the soil health condition.\r\n4.	Maintain a hygienic management of Cattle farm\r\n5.	Find out a convenient and quick composting method. \r\n', '', 'To develop a convenient method for the preparation of organic fertilizer using dairy farm waste (FYW) few experiments were conducted at Experimental dairy farm of Khamaree Shahzadpur, Sirajgonj, adjacent two other dairy farms and laboratory, Department of Animal Science, Department of soil science and Department of Microbiology, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh. In the first experiment, dairy farm yard wastes (dung, leaf over feed, and dry leafs) were depth anaerobically and aerobically for 12 weeks with 2 and 3 of soil layer alon with or without 10% and 20 % biogas slurry. In anaerobic condition FYW were not decomposed during the period of 12 weeks. Foul order was comes as not incubated with bio-gas slurry. Color of the samples were not changes completely. When incubated aerobically, partial decomposition was completed, but with 20% biogas slurry and 3 soil mixture the FYW was decomposed completely within 12 weeks. In all the cases, bad order was absent and soft texture were observed when decomposed with biogas slurry. Another experiment was trialed with vermic ensuring a 4 cm, 3 cm and 4 cm of broken break, course sand and loamy soil layer vermin bed from the bottom, respectively. During the experimental period the vermin culture could not maintained. It might be due to the wild nature and exceptional food habit of the nematodes. An experiment was then conducted with FYW and also with cow dung. These were decomposed for 3 to 4 weeks anaerobically with and without 20% biogas slurry then kept aerobically with and without 20% composed. Cow dung and also FYW were not decomposed completely by 17 weeks while maintained an anaerobic condition but strong foul odor was performed having bad texture and color. When FHYW and also cow dung were incubated anaerobically with biogas slurry and then ensured an aerobic condition with previously prepared compost, and complete decomposition happened and very good quality composed with nice texture and color was produced 13 to 14 weeks. Foul smell was absent over all the process done. Nitrogen, P, K content were higher (2.36, 1.93 and 1.78, respectively) in the compost prepared through anaerobic and aerobic decomposition with biogas slurry and compost prepared through anaerobic and aerobic decomposition with biogas slurry and compost, respectively. The C:N ration (16.6) lower and pH value (7.5) and water holding capacity (160%) were also higher in these composts. So, it might be speculated that a very good quality compost could be prepared if FYW or cow dung were exposed to anaerobic condition with 20% biogas slurry and then in an aerobic decomposition with 20% compost. ', 'Anamils, Dairy farm waste, Fertilizer', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Dairy Farm Waste', 'Fertilizer', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(1964, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Food Technology and Rural Industries', 'Project', 'Effects of chemicals and temperatures on ripening of selected varieties of tomatoes.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-02-1999', '30-01-2000', '01-02-1999', '30-01-2000', 'a) To study the effects of various chemicals and ripening agents on accelerating the ripening of tomatoes.\r\nb) To study the effects of various chemicals and ripening agents on retarding the ripening of tomatoes.\r\nc) To observe the effects of temperature on ripening of tomatoes.\r\nd) To observe the effects of packaging on ripening of tomatoes.\r\ne) To assess the optimum temperature of ripening\r\nf) to observe chilling injury(CI) in tomatoes.\r\ng) To observe the effects of storage temperature on keeping quality.\r\nh) To determine self-life depending on treatments, variety, maturity and storage temperature.\r\ni) To observe the change in firmness, color, chemical composition such as titrable acidity, TSS, sucrose,and ascorbic acid content.\r\nj) To observe the rate of microbial infection with temperature.\r\nk) To observe weight loss/gain with change of storage temperatures and ripening.\r\nl)Compare the products e.g. juice, ketchup, puress etc. made from fresh and stored(treated) products.', 'a) Raw materials: Four varieties of tomatoes, acetaldehyde, ethylene and other ripening agents.\r\nb) design of experiments:\r\n   1. Chemical treatments:\r\n      (i) Short-term exposure of fruit in acetaldehyde vapor.\r\n     (ii) Short-term exposure of fruit in ethylene vapor.\r\n    (iii) Long-term exposure of fruit in acetaldehyde vapor.\r\n     (iv) Long-term exposure of fruit in ethylene vapor.\r\n      (v) Infiltration of acetaldehyde into tomatoes at various doses.\r\n     (vi) Infiltration of ethylene into tomatoes at various doses.\r\n    (vii) Exposure to different storage temperatures.\r\n   (viii) Observation of chilling injuries in ripe and green tomatoes.\r\n   \r\n   2. Proximate analysis of the treated tomatoes.\r\n   3. Preparation of products.\r\n   4. Taste panel evaluation of the products.\r\n   5. Microbiological examination.\r\n   6. Proximate analysis of the products.\r\n   7. Storage studies.', '', '', 'BAU', 175000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
