(2340, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Entomology', 'Project', 'Development and promotion of IPM strategies of cucurbit fruit-fly Bactrocera cucurbitae (coquillett) in bitter ground. ', 'Entomology Lab. BAU.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-10-2009', '30-09-2011', '1.	To development and utilization of IPM technologies for different pests in the national needs.\r\n2.	To development of appropriate management technologies for fruit fly. \r\n3.	To find out the system for controlling the cucurbit fruit-fly trapping which will be easier, more viable, more economic and more popular to the farmer than the existing systems. \r\n', '', 'The Cucurbit fruit fly, Bactrocera cucurbitae (Coquillett) (Diptera: Tephritidae) poses a severe economic threat for the commercial cucurbit growers in Bangladesh. Because of the difficulties associated with the control of this pest by chemical insecticides, farmers experience great losses in cucurbits. Therefore, to develop a better understanding of IPM a detailed observation on the biology were studied at different diet and different constant temperature and humidity regimes throughout cropping seasons that showed that patterns of occurrence which was facilitated in adopting the management steps to be taken. The observations were made on the life history of Cucurbit fruit fly, Bactrocera cucurbitae on artificial diet at four different constant temperatures (20, 25 and 30, 35 degrees C) with three host plants (Bitter gourd, pumpkin, and white gourd). The results led to the conclusion that B. cucurbitae had a faster egg incubation time in s Bitter gourd at 30&deg;C temperature and preimaginal instars developed significantly faster than those of other diets and hosts. B. cucurbitae had more or similar mean preoviposition duration and egg hatching success at other hosts. Fecundity was significantly higher for the bitter gourd, white gourd and lower on pumpkin. Two distinctly different life history patterns were evident: (1) late onset of reproduction, longer oviposition time, longer life span, and lower fecundity (B. cucurbiate) at artificial diet composed of yeast, sugar, antifungal agents (sodium benzoate and nipagen), citric acid, and distilled water (2) early reproduction, lower oviposition time, shorter life span, and higher fecundity at bitter gourd, Larvel rearing of B. cucurbitae on this diet resulted in 20% less pupal production and 10% lighter pupal weight than from the control diet, whereas pupal density, adult emergence, and egg hatch showed on significant discrepancies. Pupal recovery increased with yeast concentrations up to 14.2%. These results are useful for improving laboratory-rearing methods and for building simulation models to predict (B. cucurbitae population dynamics.\r\n\r\nThe results of the laboratory experiments reveal that temperature greatly affects the survival and development of Cucurbit fruit fly. Temperature influenced the survival of the early stage of grubs and settled stages significantly. Early stage of grubs mortality was as high as 91% at 32&deg;C while lowest mortality was observed at 24&deg;C. at mid range of temperature (25 to 30&deg;C) early stage of grub survival ranged form 41.6 to 48.9%. A simple linear regression of the devedlopmental rate with temperature for early stage of grubs provided an excellent fit to data of the intermediate range of temperature (r2 = 0.96) which is a good approximation of the effect of temperature on the rate of development of this Bactrocera cucurbitae. At higher temperatures 35&deg;C it seemed likely that the developmental rate was beginning to exhibit the characteristic downward turn that occurs when the temperatures are too high for the welfare of the bactrocera cucurbitae the experiments were designed using.  Randomized completely Block Design. The data collected was analyzed using the statistical programme in computer (MINITAB &amp; QBASIC). The extent of losses varies between 30 to 100%, depending on the cucurbit species and the season. The peak period of infestation in endemic areas was from mid March to mid May. Its abundance increases when the temperatures fall below 35&deg;C, and the relative humidity ranges between 70 to 90 %. Keeping in view the bio-ecology of the pest and crop for management cucurbit fruit fly 1st year trials was done using the combination of methods a such as (i) soil amendment with neemcake (1 gm/pit) + removal of infested fruits and fallen fruits regularly, (ii) covering of fruits immediately after fruit-st with polythene bag having pin-holes  and (iii) spraying Kiothin 57EC 10 days interval or spraying bait spray made of 1 .0 g Secufuran 80SP or Dipterex 80SP and 10 g molasses per litre of water or (iv) placing the food bait traps per hectare, each trap made of 1001g mashed ripe sweet gourd (MSG) with 0.25g Secufon 85SP or Dipterex 80SP.  v) A cotton wad measuring 2.5x1.5cm and soaked with 15-20 drops of cuelure {4-(P-acetoxyphenyl)-2 butane or 4-(3-oxobutyl-phenylacetate)}.  Cucurbit fruit fly preferred young and immature fruits and resulted in a loss of 9.7% female flowers. Out of total fruits set, more than one-fourth (26%) fruits were drowpped or damaged just after set and 14.04% fruits were damaged during harvesting stage, giving only 38.8% fruits of marketable quality. Application of botanical pesticide Neemcake was found superior in terms of fruit size (895 g), quality and yield (62.8 t/ha), and reduced fruit fly infestation in biter gourd as  compared to other treatments. Although neem cake + removal of pest preparation is easy and its application is effective for the management of cucurbit fruit fly, ti involves more labour cost and frequent application is a tedious process. Future efforts should be made to find the ways to reduce the cost of tis application to make vegetable cultivation more profitable.\r\n', 'Fruit, Bacteria, ', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Vegetables', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
