(2406, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Technology development for allelopathic weed management in rice', 'Seed Laboratory Greenhouse and Agronomy field laboratory, Department of Agronomy, BAU and Farmers fields of Vabhukhali village, Myensingh sadar.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', 'a.To study the allelopathic effects of rice varieties on the seed germination and seedling growth of barnyard grass an important weed of rice.\r\nb.To study the extend of barnyard grass suppression due to root exudates of selected allelopathic rice varieties under greenhouse and field conditions.\r\nc.To study the effects of number of land tillage time of irrigation and application of NPK fertilizers for maximum release of allelochemicals by the selected rice varieties.\r\nd.To estimate the reduction in herbicide spray and dose, and the costs for adequate weed control in the selected allelopathic rice varieties with selected technology.\r\n', '1.First the effects of root exudates of rice cultivars on the seed germination, seedling growth of the test weed will be studied in laboratory following relay seeding technique and varieties with higher allelopathic potential will be screened out.\r\n2.Then the rice cultivars with maximum inhibitory effects will be evaluated under greenhouse and field conditions to confirm laboratory results.\r\n3.Experiments will be conducted in the fields to find out the appropriate number of tillage, time or irrigation and fertilizer application for maximum release of allelochemicals.\r\n4.The effects of different doses and number of sprays of appropriate rice herbicides on the growth of barnyard grass raised in the selected allelopathic rice varieties will be studied.\r\n5.	Percent reduction in weed control cost and benefit-cost ratio due to using allelopatic rice varieties with the selected land tillage, time to irrigation and NPK application will be estimated.\r\n', 'Weeds are claimed to be the greatest yield constraint in rice crop. weed growth in unweeded crops reduces yields by as much as 34% in rice, 454% in direct seeded rainfed rice and 67% in upland rice (De Datta, 1986). Karim et al. (1998) estimated that an amount of US$ 306 million is lost every year due to weed competition in rice in Bangladesh.  ', '', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2405, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Collection conservation and Exploitation of Land-race of Linseed in Bangladesh', 'Laboratory and field laboratory of Crop Botany, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '1.To collect local landraces of linseed genotypes from different parts of Bangladesh, including Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Gazipur.\r\n2.To study their growth and yield performance as a sole and mixed crop.\r\n3.To study impacts of planting time on the fatty acids composition in linseed.\r\n4.To study &amp;#1120;-3 fatty acids levels of the collected genotypes.\r\n5.To conserve &amp;#1120;-3 fatty acids enriched genotypes with others or future uses.\r\n', 'To achieve the objectives stated several experiment will be carried out by appropriate experimental design:\r\nLocal landraces of linseed or flaxseed will be collected from different parts of Bangladesh. It is generally cultivated during winter season at Rajshahi, Dinajpur, Rangpur, Bogra, Pabna, Sherpur and Jessore districts. Seed will also be collected from relevant research organizations like BARI, Bangladesh Agriculrural Research Institute, Gazipur. Collected seeds will be sown as sole crop either broadcast or line sowing or both. Plot size will be 2m x 2m. \r\na.Fatty acids analysis of landraces of linseeds\r\nb.Effects of plan ting time on the fatty acids composition in linseed\r\nc.Data analyses and report writing\r\n', 'Human can make monounsaturated fatty acids from sugar but are unable to synthesize long chain fatty acids such as linoleic acid and a-linolenic acid. the fish or fish oil is beyond the capacity of Bangladesh people. under the circumstances linseed may be an alternative and the cheapest source of w-3 fatty acid. it changes the fat composition of meat milk, and egg when supply as a dietary supplement. It reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease. therefore, students, teachers, researchers, farmers, nutritionist, feed miller and heart diseased patients etc will be benefited for the study.', '', 'University Grants Commission of Bangladesh', 120000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
