(2392, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Alleviation of salt-stress induced damages in rice plants with foliar spray of proline and glycine betaine. ', 'Department of Agronomy', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2013', '30-06-2014', '01-07-2013', '30-06-2014', '	To investigate the salt stress-induced growth and physiological disorders in rice plants under ambient condition\r\n	To measure the oxidative stress under saline environment\r\n	To evaluate the protective role of proline, glycine betaine and their combination\r\n	To recommend an accurate concentration of proline and glycine betaine for salt stress mitigation\r\n', 'Material: 	\r\n\r\nRice (Oryza sativa L.) cv. BRRI dhan34 (salt susceptible) and BRRI dhan54 (salt tolerant) will be used as test plants\r\n\r\n(a)	Design of experiments: Completely randomized design (CRD) containing 3 replications.\r\n(b)	Growing conditions,\r\n(c)	Measurement of plant height\r\n(d)	Measurement of leaf area\r\n(e)	Measurement of H2O2\r\n(f)	Measurement of dry matter of plant\r\n(g)	Measurement of relative water content\r\n(h)	Determination of chlorophyll and carotenoids content\r\n(i)	Determination of proline content\r\n(j)	Measurement of lipid peroxidation\r\n(k)	Extraction and measurement of ascorbate and glutathione \r\n(l)	Determination of protein\r\n(m)	Enzyme extraction and assays\r\n(n)	Statistical analysis\r\n', 'Salinity is one of the most brutal environmental factors limiting the productivity of crop plants because most of the crop plants are sensitive to salinity caused by high concentrations of salts in the soil. A considerable amount of land in the world is affected by salinity which is increasing day by day. More than 45 million hectares (M ha) of irrigated land which account to 20% of total land have been damaged by salt worldwide and 1.5 M ha are taken out of production each year due to high salinity levels in the soil (Munns and Tester 2008). On the other hand, increased salinity of agricultural land is expected to have destructive global effects, resulting in up to 50% loss of cultivable lands by the middle of the 21st century (Mahajan and Tuteja 2005). In most of the cases, the negative effects of salinity have been attributed to increase in Na+ and Cl ions in different plants hence these ions produce the critical conditions for plant survival by intercepting different plant mechanisms. Although both Na+ and Cl are the major ions which produce many physiological disorders in plants, Cl is the most dangerous (Tavakkoli et al. 2010). Salinity at higher levels causes both hyperionic and hyperosmotic stress and can lead to plant demise. \r\n\r\nThe typical first response of all plants to salt stress is osmotic adjustment. Compatible solutes, such as proline and glycine betaine, are known to accumulate under conditions of environmental stresses and play a pivotal role in the process of osmotic adjustment in higher plants (Hasegawa et al., 2000). Salt stress up-regulates the enzymes involved in proline and glycine betaine biosyntheses in several plant species (Sumithra et al., 2006), and elevated levels of proline and glycine betaine accumulated in plant cells correlate with enhanced stress tolerance (Chen et al., 2000; Munns, 2005). In addition to their roles as osmoprotectants, proline and glycine betaine contribute to the protection of membranes, proteins and enzyme from damaging effect of various stresses (Ashraf and Foolad, 2007). The role of exogenous proline and glycine betaine in aspects of antioxidant defense has been reported in different plant species and cultured cells. However, the antioxidant protection mechanisms of proline and glycine betaine in plant responses to oxidative stress are yet to be fully understood. To our knowledge, there is currently no information is available on the possible beneficial effects of exogenous application of proline and glycine betaine in oxidative defense on rice seedlings grown under salinity. Thus, to gain better knowledge of the rice plant in response to salt stress and their antioxidant defense mechanism provided by proline and glycine betaine, the investigation on the effects of exogenous proline and glycine betaine will be carried out.\r\n', 'Salt stress, rice plants, proline, glycine betaine', 'SAURES-UGC', 60000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Plant Stress Physiology', 'Rice Plant', '', 'At the end of this research an insight into the role of exogenous proline and glycine betaine in mitigating salt stress-induced damages will be known which would help both plant physiologists and plant breeder to manipulate the proline or glycine betanine synthesis in plants. \r\n \r\n', ''),
