(2382, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Caryophylliasis in freshwater catfishes, clarias batrachus and Heteropneoustes fossile of Bangladesh', 'Around Mymensingh district', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-08-2010', '31-07-2011', '01-08-2010', '31-07-2011', '', '', 'A study on caryophyllylliasis i.e. the evaluation of the effect of caryophyllaeid cestode parasitism on the length, on the weight and the condition factor of the infested host; and histopathology on the gut of Clarias batrachus was conducted during the period from August 2010 to July 2011. Fish samples were collected from K. R. market BAU campus brought from various water bodies around Mymensingh. Sex, total length (cm), standard length (cm), head length (cm) and weight (g) were recorded. Five different species of caryophyllaeid were identified from the host examined as-= Djombangia penetrans, Lytocestus indicus, L. birmanicus, L. parvulus and Bovienia serialis. Severe infestations of caryophyllaeid cestodes were found in C. batrachus. Changes in the nature of growth and loss of weight as a result of parasitic infestation were noticed. Accordingly length, weight and condition factors were fund greatly affected. Loss of total length was 8.73% and the highest loss of mean head +length was 4.49% found in smaller infested length goup fish. Loss of weight was 1.63% and the highest percentage loss of weight 26.38 was recorded in the small length group while it was 7.44 in large length group fish. The highest condition factor 1.13, was found uninfected fish and lowest, 0.85, in infested fish. Suggestions were made for further investigation on blood composition and gonadal development of infested host. Djombangia penetrants among the caryophyllaeids was very common infesting the host. In the lower level of infection D. penetrants was found predominantly the anterior region of intestine, whereas in higher level the posterior intestine was also found to be infected. In higher level of infestations the infested area enlarged from the original size and the naked eye the infected area appeared enlarged with white cysts of spots. Under microscope in some cases scolices of the worms were seen perforated through the intestine and surrounded by fibrous connective tissue. The intestinial wall completely destroyed at the point of attachment.  The mucosa and submucosa layer became atrophied. \r\n\r\n', '', 'MOSICT', 500000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Fishes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2381, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Extensiion Education', 'Project', 'Adoption of Hybrid Rice in Greater Mymensingh Region and Associated Issues: A Technology Dissemination Analysis.', 'Greater Mymensingh Region', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2009', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2009', '1.	Determining farmers level of adoption of hybrid rice and the extent of adoption in different recommended practices of hybrid rice cultivation.\r\n2.	Determining farmers assessment of hybrid rice as an innovation.\r\n3.	Determining farmers stage of innovation-decision concerning adoption of hybrid rice and the factors responsible for the innovation-decision.\r\n4.	Identifying important characteristics of hybrid rice adoption farmers.\r\n5.	Identifying farmers barriers in adopting hybrid rice\r\n6.	Determining socio-economic and livelihoods impacts of hybrid rice adoption on farmers households and community.\r\n', 'Nature of Study: this is an empirical study and mainly the primary sources of data will be used for it. \r\nLocale: The Study will be carried out in five districts under the greater Mhymensingh region, namely Mymensingh, Kishoreganj, Netrokina, Jamalpur and Sherpur.\r\nPopulation and sample: Approximately 250  300 farmers (50-60 from each upazila).\r\nData Collection and Analysis: Face to face interview focus group discussion and case study will be employed in collecting data from the farmers.\r\nVariables of the study: Extent of adoption of hybrid rice (singh, 1981), stages of innovation-decision (rogers, 1995), Reasons for adoption of hybrid rice.\r\nAssociated issues: attitude towards hybrid rice, problems in adopting hybrid rice, Impact of hybrid rice cultivation of livelihoods and socio-economic status.\r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 100000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2380, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Physics and Chemistry', 'Project', 'Extraction chromatographic isolation and structural characterization of bio-active compounds from piper and their application to plant diseases.', 'Department of Physics and Chemistry, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1.	Extraction, thin layer and column chromatographic separation of compounds present in medicinal plants pepper and neem.\r\n2.	Structural characterization of bioactive compounds and their selection against bacterial and fungal diseases of plants.\r\n3.	Application of the active compound/compounds against the fungus and bacteria responsible for plant diseases.\r\n', 'Black pepper corns are not produced in considerable amount in our country. It is available in local market. Therefore we will collect Black Pepper from local market. Neem leaves are available in all over the country and also in BAU campus. The experimental techniques will be performed with the following way.\r\na.	Solvent extraction; b. Thin layer chromatography; c. column chromatography; d. Spectroscopic identification and estimation; etc.  To identify different separated pure compounds and elucidate their structure by spectroscopic method IR (Infra red). NMR (nuclear magnetic Resonance) and mass spectrometry will be employed. These are available in BCSIR laboratories, Dhaka.\r\n', 'Chemical investigation on black pepper fruits was carried out in the Department of Agricultural Chemistry, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh, during July 2009 to June 2011.\r\n\r\nPiperine was extracted, isolated from Black pepper (piper nigrum) and identified by TLC. Piperine an alkaloid was isolated by column chromatography which may be responsible for the pungency of black pepper. The aim of this study was to extract, isolate and characterize the structure of Piperine by the help of IR, NMR and mass spectrometric analysis. After recrystallization of the isolate with benzene and chloroform (7:1) to give pale yellow crystals of m. p. 128-129&deg;C (reported 130&deg;C).\r\nThe IR, 1H NMR and mass spectra of the pure crystalline compound (A2) were recorded. The mass spectra of the compound (A2) showed molecular ion M + 284.5 which was similar to that of piperine (mol. Wt. 285). \r\n', 'Pipper, Diseases, ', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Pieces', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2379, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Development of storage technology for groundnut seed.', 'Gaforgaon and Sadar Upazila and seed laboratory of Department of Agronomy, BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', 'a.	To evaluate the present status of groundnut seed supply and its marketing channel.\r\nb.	To evaluate the quality status of farmers seed and BADC seed.\r\nc.	To select suitable storage container for groundnut seed.\r\nd.	To study the relationships of storage environment with the longevity and field performance of groundnut seed.\r\n', 'Both field survey and laboratory experiment s will be undertaken in this project for two years (2009-10 abd 2010-11), Field survey at two villages of each to two Upazillas (Sadar and Gaforgaon of Mymensingh district will be conducted to know the present status of groundnut seed supply, its marketing channel and quality in 2009-10 and also in 2010-11. \r\nTwo laboratory experiments (1) effect of storage container and seed moisture content on groundnut seed quality and (b) Effect of storage relative humidity and type of storage container on groundnut seed quality will be conducted in 2009-10. ', 'Inadequate supply of seed is the main barrier to groundnut cultivation in Bangladesh. The field survey at two villages (Algir Char of Gaforgaon and Sener Char, Astadhar of Sadar Upazila) of Mymensingh district revealed that no farmer could store groundnut seed due to loss of seed viability during storage. Two experiments were conducted at the Seed Laboratory of the Department of Agronomy, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during August 2009 to February 2011 with a view to developing technology for storing groundnut seed. The experiment 1 comprised four relative humidity (viz. 50, 60, 70 and 80% RH), two storage container (viz. polythene bag and cloth bag), and two seed types (viz. shelled and unshelled groundnut seed) while experiment 2 consisted of four storage containers (viz. polythene bag, tin container, plastic pot and cloth bag), three initial seed moisture content (viz.8, 10 and 12%) and tow seed types (viz. shelled and nu-shelled). Both experiments were set up in Completely Randomized Design (CRD) with three replications. Data on seed moisture content, laboratory germination (%), vigour index and field emergence (%) were recorded, Experiment 1 revealed that the germination performance of both shelled and unshelled groundnut seeds stored in polythene bag at 8% moisture content were similar and decreased with increase of relative humidity. Experiment 2 also showed that seeds stored in polythene bag at 8% moisture content exhibited higher viability performance than those stored in plastic pot or in tin container. The present study further showed that the groundnut seed could maintain higher germination of 78% up to 160 days of storage when stored in polythene bags at 8% moisture content under ambient room condition. The result concludes that shelled or unshelled groundnut seed could be stored safely with high viability for about 5 to 6 months in ambient room conditions by keeping in polythene bags after drying to 8% initial seed moisture content.', 'Groundnut, Storage Technology,Groundnut Seed.', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Storage Technology', 'Groundnut', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2378, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Physics and Chemistry', 'Project', 'Extraction chromatograpic and spectroscopic analysis of Bio-Food color from Bixa orellana L. for commercial use', 'Department of Physics and chemistry, BAU, Mymensingh and BCSIR lab. Dhaka and Chittatong.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1.Optimum solvent extraction of food colour from vegetative sources like annatto seed (Bixa orellane L.) and its purification.\r\n2.Column and thin layer chromatographic (TLC) isolation followed by spectroscopic estimation of coloured pigments in the source of our country.\r\n3.Formulation for an economic and practical method for extraction, separation and purification of food colour from annatto seeds. \r\n', 'Bixa orellana plants are located both in the Botanical garden and central laboratory compound of BAU, Mymensingh. So capsule of Bixa tree will be harvested following the protocol developed by Sarmin (2008).  Because of abundant of M2 trees in the campus only this morphotype will used in the investigation and will be collected from BAU campus. ', 'Extraction of food colour pigments from Bixa Orellana (annatto) seed by different organic and aqueous solvent and thin layer Chromatography of extracts of three morphotypes of annatto were studied in the department of Agricultural Chemistry, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during July 2009 to June 2011. Purification, concentration, pH adjustment, adoption of different chemical and physical methods for development of an overall economically sustainable, health friendly technology for both oil and water soluble food grade colour of liquid and powder from were studied in the same department of BAU during July 2010 to June 2011. Important organic solvents like n-Hexane, ethyl acetate, acetone, ethyl alcohol and a solvent mixture were employed for extraction of colour pigment but chloroform was selected as the best organic solvent for extraction on the basis of TLC and physical appearance of the extract. From TLC of different extracts of seeds of three morphtypes of annatto revealed that morphotype-3 is the best one for processing of food colour as it contains minimum number and amount of colourless compounds, gum, fat, etc. and has good physical appearance. To develop technologies for producing both liquid and powder form of food grade colour from annatto seed for practical use different chemical and physical methods and their combination were employed and studied. The method are extraction at high pH, repeated precipitation, vacuum filtration, vacuum drying, Degumming and Defatting distillation under reduced pressure, neutralization, grinding etc. Finally economic and simple protocols were developed for four forms of food grade annatto colour which are water soluble liquid annatto colour, water soluble powdered annatto colour, vegetable oil soluble annatto colour, water soluble annatto colour directly from processed seed. The colour content per gm of powder or per ml of liquid were determined by ultra violet spectrophotometer. ', 'Bio food, Annatto, Seed ', 'BAU', 24000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2377, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Extensiion Education', 'Project', 'Suitability of promising selected NINA technology at farmers field', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '', '', '1.	To test the performance in relation to yield to selected technology.\r\n2.	To assess the adaptation of technology at local condition.\r\n3.	To ascertain the sustainability of technology in the prevailing cropping pattern.\r\n4.	To enhance capacity building of the users for adoption of BINA developed technology and \r\n5.	To analyze the cost and return of BINA technology at farmers level.\r\n\r\n', 'To test the suitability of NINA developed some of the selected promising crop varieties, a total of 60 research plots will be conducted at the farmers fields in three different villages of BAUEC area. Under direct supervision of the researchers and local extension agents all the operational activities during crop growth will be managed by the farmers. Out of 60 research plots: 18 will be on Binadhan-5 and Binadhan-7, 18 for NINA developed groundnut varieties such as Binchinabadam-3, and Binchinabadam-4 and 6 for Binapatshak-1\r\nThe extension agents and input dealers will be selected from the study area for conduction of FGD and KII. In addition to the PI and Associate PI, research opportunities for 4 MS students of the department of Agricultural extension education, BAU will be offered. The MS students will be involved in the project as co-researcher of the project. The MS research cost will be borne from the project fund. Appropriate statistical package SPSS will be used for analysis of data. \r\n', '', '', 'MOSICT', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
