(2368, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pharmacology', 'Project', 'Effect of low priced calcium and phosphorus supplements with medicinal plant of the calcium and phosphorus level in pregnant and lactating cows.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-02-2000', '31-01-2001', '01-02-2000', '31-01-2001', '1.To study the normal physiological values for serum calcium and phosphorous level of pregnant and lactating cow.\r\n2.To find out the effects of dietary supplement of calcium and phosphorus in pregnancy and its effects in milk yield and lactating period.\r\n3.To find out the effects of dietary supplement of medicinal plant (Padmagulancha) on pregnancy and lactation.\r\n', 'for this research project 100 indigenous breed of cattle heads will be selected from BAYU dairy farm and surrounding village of BAU campus. Various preparation of Ca, P or Ca, P combination with medicinal plants which are given to the animal will be collected from local market.', '', 'Animal, Cow, Calcium, Phosphorus', 'BAURES', 617900, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Calcium and phosphorus', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(2369, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Food Technology and Rural Industries', 'Project', 'Prospect of commercial utilization of potato beans', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-02-1994', '31-01-1995', '01-02-1994', '31-01-1995', 'a.	To analyze the proximate composition of potato bean.\r\nb.	To develop process for storage of potato beans.\r\nc.	To develop various products from potato bean.\r\nd.	To maximize the utilization of potato beans.\r\ne.	To assess the acceptability of the developed products by subjective evaluation.\r\n', '	Design of experiment:\r\n	To investigate the effect of preservatives.\r\n	To investigate the effect of temperature (C&quot;&deg;&quot; )\r\n	To investigate the effect of TSS.\r\n	Procedure to be followed in achieving stated objectives:\r\n	Extraction of pulp.\r\n	Proximate analysis of pulp.\r\n	Proportion of jam, jellies.\r\n	Preparation of preserves.\r\n	Preparation o candies\r\n	Preparation of chips.\r\n	Storage studies of the products at different conditions.\r\n	Analysis of proximate composition of the products.\r\n	Taste panel evaluation of the developed products.\r\n', 'Potato bean is a perishable root crop. It is a available for a shorter period of the year. If some suitable methods are developed for preserving this crop, it could be made available round the year for consumers as well as processors use. ', 'Vegetables, Potato Bean, Potato storage', 'BAURES', 41600, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Potato Bean', 'Vegetables', '', '', ''),
(2370, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery', 'Project', 'Energy requirement for selected crop production under different technologies.', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery, BAU, ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-12-1998', '30-11-2000', '01-12-1998', '30-11-2000', '1.	Assess the availability, types and sources of energy in producing selected crops in the rabi and kharif seasons in a rice based farming system.\r\n2.	Determine the utilization and consumption level of available energy in different operations.\r\n3.	Find out energy input-output relationships for selected crops under different technologies.\r\n4.	Determine cost and returns of different technological inputs for selected crops.\r\n5.	Estimate optimum energy requirement s for selected crops. \r\n', 'a.	Site Selection:\r\n1.	Easy accessibility\r\n2.	High cropping intensity area\r\n3.	Labour shortage area (Peri-urban or border area)\r\n4.	High technology concentrated area \r\nb.	Farmers Selection:\r\nFarmers will be selected randomly from the study areas covering various economic groups (large, medium, small and marginal) practicing traditional and improved or mechanized systems through RRA. At least 12 farmers from each village will be selected for the study.\r\n', '', '', 'BAURES', 218500, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2371, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry', 'Project', 'Biological nitrification inhibition: A novel plant-soil interaction can mitigate climate change by improving nitrogen use efficiency in cereal production system.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-06-2010', '31-12-2011', '01-06-2010', '31-12-2011', '1.To isolate and characterize the nitrification inhibitory compounds from the root exudates of cereals.\r\n2.Physiological studies on the mechanisms of BNI-compounds release; mode of action of BNI release from roots.\r\n3.To evaluate the ability and stability of the nitrification inhibitory compounds in the soil.\r\n4.To evaluate the effect of BNI-compounds on the efficiency of C and N assimilation in plants.\r\n5.Finally this trait can be introduced to the rice plant through breeding or biotechnological approach.\r\n6.To evaluate the effect of BNI-compounds released for sorghum roots in increasing NUE by rice plants under different culture system and to determine the percentage of saving urea.\r\n', '', '', '', 'MOSICT', 266000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Climage change', 'Environment', '', '', ''),
(2542, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Structure', 'Project', 'Design and development of environment-friendly and income-generating poultry housing systems at farmers'' level.', 'Mymensingh, Dhaka and other places.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '1.	To identify and characterize the safe and environmental factors for confined poultry housing systems.\r\n2.	To design and develop an environmentally controlled and functional low-cost model poultry house for rural area.\r\n3.	To develop hygienic and economically viable compost preparation technique using the poultry litters.\r\n', 'The work will be started with routine visit of some selected commercial and small stakeholders poultry farms for collecting information of materials and equipments currently being used in the farms through pre-tested questionnaire. The effectiveness of the model farms will be estimated considering the safe environmental factors, suitability to establish in the rural areas, social acceptability to adoption of such farms etc. In furthering the work, a hygienic and economically viable compost preparation technique will be attempted using the solid wastes from the poultry farms (Rashid &amp; Abedin, 1991). The effectiveness and utility of using organic fertilizer will be studied. ', 'The study was conducted to identify the safe environmental parameters of confined poultry housing systems at farmers level under four selected districts in Bangladesh. The study also discussed the formulation of guidelines to design and develop environment-friendly and functional poultry housing systems for the rural areas. Both qualitative and quantitative data were collected from 42 selected poultry farms of the districts through pre-tested interview schedules for identifying safe environmental parameters from engineering viewpoint. On the basis of birds, 45.2%, 33.33% and 21.43% of farms were small, medium and large respectively. The sites, insulating materials, lighting, cooling ventilation, water supply, litter disposal and management systems of the categorical farms were not ideal both from economic and environment-friendly poultry production for erected mostly alongside the road dispersedly located around the homestead. In summer the temperature of the sites varied from 28-34&deg;C during day-time and 25-30&deg;C at night, while in winter, the temperatures were 12-20&deg;C during day time. The most efficient temperature of laying house should be 20-24&deg;C. In rains, the humidity was 80-95% but in winter it was 55-68%. High humidity resulted in wet litter and increased disease prevalence. The ideal relative humidity for poultry should be 60-80%. All small farms we reusing natural ventilation system together with ceiling fans and majority of farm-owners used derelict pond for wastewater and dumping for dead body disposal. Poultry litters used as organic fertilizer, fuel and a few were kept in open yard for bio-degradation. Cleaning agents and disinfectants were found to use in small farms. Only few large farms used chemical agent for fly and pest control. About 60% farm owners used tin-shed with bricks at the end walls, 24% tin-shed with tin and 16% concrete roofing with bricks at end walls.  The roof shapes of tin-shed poultry house were mostly gable types with some offset gables. About 50% farm owners used jute and splitted-bamboo mats and 29% jute-mat or sac as ceiling materials and 21% did not use any ceiling materials. The poultry farmers showed their  keen interest for pre-fabricated elements of environmentally safe poultry houses so that they could by the elements from the market, assemble together to build the poultry house in the form of a package deal depending on their demand and budgets. This would allow the farmers to plan for constructing poultry houses shortly without incurring high initial investments for erecting any permanent structure with the proviso that the occupied lands be replaced for other important future usages. A number of guidelines were suggested for enabling the farmers to design and develop low cost, controlled and functional poultry housing system for profitable farming. This would foster the rural people to copy with the opportunity of income-generating sources from poultry enterprise contributing to national economy. ', 'Environment, Poultry, low-cost, Poultry housing, ', 'University Grants Commission of Bangladesh', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Environment', 'Poultry', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2543, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Medicine', 'Project', 'Evaluation of management Practices, Therapy and Colostral Immunity in the Control of Calf Morbidity and Mortality in Bangladesh', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-02-2000', '31-01-2003', '01-02-2000', '31-01-2003', '1.	To determine the risk factors of management practices associated with morbidity and mortality of calves.\r\n2.	To determine the etiology and epidemiology of calf diseases.\r\n3.	To evaluate the comparative effectiveness of certain oral and intravenous rehydration therapy in diarrheic calves.\r\n4.	To determine the effects and therapy of parasitic gastro-enteritis in calves.\r\n5.	To evaluate the effectiveness of blood transfusion in morbid calves.\r\n6.	To evaluate the effectiveness of fresh and storage colostrums on growth and survival of neonatal calves. \r\n', 'a.	This study will be conducted on calves under 6 months  of age in the dairy farms and rural calves of Bangladesh.\r\nb.	The Bangladesh Agricultural University dairy farm, Mymensingh, Central Cattle Breeding Station &amp; dairy farm, Savar; Milk and Cattle Development Farm, Rajshahi; districts Dairy Farm, Sylhet and some private dairy farms in the district of Mymensingh and Dhaka will be considered for this research work. \r\nc.	The BAY extension centers, and BAU Veterinary Clinic will be included for this study.\r\nd.	The final selection of dairy farms, Veterinary hospital and rural areas will be made on the basis of interest and cooperation of the concerned farm authority.\r\ne.	Different ELISA  kits will be purchased for the diagnosis of enteopathogens associated with neonatal diarrhea in calves. \r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 225000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
