(2524, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Growth performance of microalgae in bean seed and cabbage powder media and their use in silver barb and shrimp larvae production. ', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2001', '30-06-2004', '01-07-2001', '30-06-2004', '1.	To study the growth of microalgae in bean seed and cabbage powder media;\r\n2.	To analyze the proximate composition of bean seed and cabbage powder and microalgae;\r\n3.	To feed the microalgae to shrimp and silver barb larvae.\r\n', 'a. Materials b. Design of Experiment c. Procedure: To analyzed of microalgae in bean seed and cabbage powder media, composition of bean seed and cabbage powder and microalgae; and To feed the microalgae to shrimp and silver barb larvae.\r\n', '', 'Bean, seed powder, mass culture, Microalgae', 'BAU', 225000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Bean', 'Spices', '', '', ''),
(2525, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery', 'Project', 'Development of computer vision for efficient nitrogen application in rice for increasing food security. ', '1. FPM Department Laboratory, 2. Agriculture Farm, BAU and 3. Research plot, BINA.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1.	To develop a comprehensive computer model for establishing the relationship with leaf green pixel and Nitrogen.\r\n2.	To develop color-based rice yield model.\r\n3.	To design and develop a ground-based computer vision system capable of obtaining high-resolution crop images.\r\n4.	To determine the crop and soil parameter by newly develop imaging system.\r\n5.	To determine the leaf color pixel with available commercial instrument and compare with new system. \r\n', 'a.	Data related to the soil nutrient, cropping, climate topographic and input application will be collected.\r\nb.	Process the data and indentify the zones based on soil, crop and crop yield status.\r\nc.	New computer model will be developed based on experimental result and others collected data.\r\nd.	The instrument will be design based on available local materials. Special CCD camera, suitable fish eye lanes would be essentially incorporated with the instrument.\r\ne.	Vision sensor conveys the information about the properties of the captured image such as color, shape, position and angle of the leaf.\r\nf.	To research will concentrate on the development of the images processing technique and database for intelligent vision system. \r\n', '', 'Soil, cropping, climate, image, rice, nitrogen application.', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Nitrogen Application', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(2521, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Anatomy and  Histology', 'Project', 'Effect of Vitamin-E, Selenium and their combination''s on the mucosal immune system of broilers and layers chickens During their postnatal stages of growth and development. ', 'Gazipur and Mymensingh district', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-10-2003', '30-09-2006', '01-10-2003', '30-09-2006', '1.Gross changes of the lymphoid organs and mucosa of the gastrointestinal, respiratory and oviduct of different postnatal stages of chickens supplemented with different concentration of selenium and vitamin E in the diet.\r\n2.Studies of the populations of immunocompetent cells in the lymphoid organs and in the different segments of the mucosa of the gastrointestinal respiratory and oviduct of different postnatal stages of chicken supplemented with different concentration of selenium and vitamin E in the diet.\r\n3.Histology and histochemistry of the immunocompetent cells and their associated organs as mentioned in 2 (i) and 2(ii).\r\n', 'a.Materials:  i) Broilers of day-old, 1 week, 2 weeks, 3 weeks and 4 weeks old. ii) Layers (white leghorn) of one-day, 2 weeks, 1 month, 3 months, 6 months and 1 year of ages. iii) Instruments and chemicals.\r\nb.Design of experiments: Day-old broilers and layers will be purchased from different farm of the Bangladesh.\r\nc.Procedure to be followed in achieving stated objectives: The weight, length and gross changes of the lymphoid organs and the mucosa of the gastrointestinal, respiratory and oviduct will compare in between treated and control groups of chicken using scale, weight box and magnifying glass.  The samples will also stained with periodic acid schiffs, Verhoeffs and Vangiesons method for histochemistry.\r\n', '', 'Vitamin E. Poultry, Chicken, Boilers.', 'BAU', 225000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Poultry', '', '', ''),
(2522, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Microbiology and Hygiene', 'Project', 'Studies on the prevalence isolation identification and selection of vaccine virus stain of pest despetits ruminants virus (PPRV).', 'Over all Bangladesh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-11-2002', '31-12-2005', '01-01-2003', '31-12-2005', '1.	Determination of seroprevalence of PPRV infection in sheep and goats.\r\n2.	Isolation, identification and characterization of PPRV prevalent in Bangladesh from filed cases.\r\n3.	Immunological characterization of the PPRV isolates and selection of vaccine strains.\r\n4.	Comparison of PPRV genome sequence with other PPRV isolates\r\n', 'a.	Animals: Sheep and goats reared in semi-extensive and semi-intensive areas will be examined for the seroprevlence of PPRV.\r\nb.	Study areas: Samples will be collected mostly animals which brought to the Thana veterinary Hospital and semi-extensive farming areas.\r\nc.	Samples: Samples will be collected from suspected cases of infection and also from the contact animals. \r\nd.	Tissue culture: Vero cell will be used in this study for primary isolation and propagation of virus.\r\ne.	Competitive: ELISA kits: This will purchase from the world Reference Laboratory, Pirbright, U.K.\r\nf.	Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction:  for the detection PPRV RNA, RT-PCR will be performed. \r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 225000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Anamils', '', '', ''),
(2520, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery', 'Project', 'Adaptive Research on Solar Dryers for Drying Mango, Pineapple and Fish', 'Cox''s Bazar, Bangladesh Agricultural University-Mymensingh, Nasirpur, Dinajpur. ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '30-09-1997', '31-08-2000', '01-01-1998', '31-12-2000', '1.	To determine the effects of different pre-treatment and drying parameters on the quality of dried pineapple, mango, and fish\r\n2.	To develop technico-economically viable drying strategies for drying of pineapple man go, and fish.\r\n3.	To determine the sorption isotherms for pineapple, mango, and fish.\r\n4.	To adapt and optimize the solar tunnel drier suitable for drying of pineapple, mango, and fish for Bangladesh conditions for small/medium scale commercial production.\r\n5.	To develop a computer model to simulate photovoltaic forced convection solar drying of pineapple, Mango, and fish.\r\n6.	To develop safe storage conditions for dried pineapple, mango (cubes), and fish.\r\n', 'Extensive experiments will be conduced in the laboratory to determine the factors affecting the quality of the dried fruits and fish that will meet international standards. In dried fruit production two types of dried products will be considered: the sweetened and the unsweetened. The laboratory experiments will be focused on the determination of the effects of pre-trements and the drying parameters such as drying temperature, relative humidity and air flow rate on the quality of the dried products. \r\n\r\n\r\nPerformance of solar tunnel driers for drying of fidh and mango at field conditions will be conducted at Cox''s Bazar, Nasirpur, Dinajpur respectively. While the performance of the tunnel drier for drying of pineapple will be conducted at Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh.', '', 'Mango, Pineapple, Fish, Fruit, Storage', 'BARC', 459250, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Storage', 'Fruit and Fishes', '', '', ''),
(2519, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery', 'Project', 'Experimental Investigation of the Performance of the Solar Tunnel drier for drying Jackfruit for production of dried Jackfruit and Jackfruit lather.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-04-2001', '31-03-2004', '01-04-2001', '31-03-2004', '1.	To determine the effects of different pretreatment and drying parameters on the quality of dried jackfruit bulbs and lather.\r\n2.	To determine the sorption isotherm of dried jackfruit bulbs and lather.\r\n3.	To assess the performance of the solar tunnel dried jackfruit bulbs and lather.\r\n4.	To develop a computer model to simulate photovoltaic forced convection solar drying of jackfruit bulbs and lather.\r\n5.	To optimize the solar tunnel drier for efficient drying of jackfruit bulbs and lather under Bangladesh conditions.\r\n6.	To develop safe storage conditions for dried jackfruit bulbs and lather.\r\n7.	To identify the most appropriate and economic design best suited to needs of the users in Bangladesh.\r\n', 'Extensive experiments will be conducted in the laboratory to determine the factors affecting the quality of the jackfruit bulbs and lather that will meet international standards. In dried fruit production two types of dried product will be considered- The dried bulbs and the lather. The laboratory experiments will be focused on the determination of the effects of pretreatment and the drying parameters such as drying temperature, relative humidity and air flow rate on the quality products.\r\nFinally an economic analysis will be conducted to evaluate the viability of the system and an appropriate and economic design best suited to the needs of the users will be identified. \r\n', '', 'Jackfruit, Bulbs, Lather, Fruit, Drying jackfruit', 'BAU', 225000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Storage of Jackfruit Bulbs and Lather', 'Fruits', '', '', ''),
(2518, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pharmacology', 'Project', 'Identification, Collection and preservation of toxic plants and establishment of a toxic plant garden and a herbarium. ', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-09-2004', '31-10-2006', '01-09-2004', '31-10-2006', '1.	Identification, collection and preservation of available poisonous plants (at least 50).\r\n2.	Establishment of a toxicological garden besides Pharmacology building and a herbarium in the department of Pharmacology.\r\n3.	Study of adverse effects of most common poisonous plants will be carried out in laboratory animals and in small animals.\r\n4.	Well be helpful to farmers and the livestock men to identify the toxic plants.\r\n', 'a.	Collection of data from BAU campus, Mymensingh district and some selected parts of Bangladesh.\r\nb.	Design of experiments: Identification of toxic plants throughout BAU campus, Pharmacology building, poisonous plants in laboratory animals and small ruminants at Mymensingh district. \r\nc.	Survey and plants identification and collection will be performed by the help of a taxonomist.\r\nd.	A toxicological garden will be established by planting the collected toxic plants and a herbarium will also be established by these plants.\r\ne.	Study of the adverse effects of moist common poisonous plants will be carried out by suing laboratory animals and small ruminants i.e., toxic signs, hemato-biochemical parameters, post-mortem lesion, toxic dose, LD 50 and their treatment. \r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 150000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2517, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pharmacology', 'Project', 'Study of the Active Principle of total Alkaloids from Holarrhena Antidysenterica wall (Beng Kurchi) and its action on Blood Picture Including SGPt of Cattle.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-11-1997', '31-10-1998', '01-11-1997', '31-10-1998', '1. To find out the total alkaloids\r\n2. to determine the efficacy of the alkaloids\r\n3. to know its action on blood picture including SGPT and SGOT', 'a.	Collection of the plat materials extraction of the total alkaloids and their detection- \r\ni.	Collection of the plant materials, \r\nii.	Extraction of the total alkaloids with other chloroform misture.\r\niii.	Extraction of total alkaloids with other by soxlet apparatus.\r\nb.	Detection of alkaloid: Precipitation test- A little amount of the solution of total extract was treated separately with the following reagents: i. Mayers reagent, ii. Marmes reagent, iii. Wagnors reagent, iv. Dragendorffs reagent, v. Scheiblers reagent, vi. Sonnenscheins reagent, vii. Gold chloride solution and viii. Picric acid solution.\r\n', '', 'Vegetables, Alkaloids, Agriculture', 'University Grants Commission of Bangladesh', 45000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Alkaloids', 'Agriculture', '', '', ''),
(2516, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Statistics', 'Project', 'Impact of Appropriate Crop and Livestock Enterprises on Food Security in Vulnerable Regions of Bangladesh', 'The Selected area are charlands, flood prone and river erosion areas of Shirajgonj, Borga and Jamalpur districts.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '1.	To survey different crop and livestock enterprises of the study areas.\r\n2.	To identify the most promising, profitable and labour intensive crop and livestock enterprise mix.\r\n3.	To measure the poverty level of the people.\r\n4.	To measure different food security indicators of the people. \r\n5.	To formulate policies to help the rural poor to get rid of the food insecurity and malnutrition. \r\n', '', 'This study was based on primary data collected from 120 farm households with the pretested questionaries through field survey. With these data collected by trained enumerators, this study aimed at estimating the contribution of livestock sector to earn livelihood by the people living in vulnerable areas of Sirajganj, Borga and Jamalpur districts. The study measured the food security indicators based on descriptive and functional analyses and observed that younger farmers were engaged in livestock enterprises to earn and affordable income. The average age of farm operators was 43.98 years at the aggregated level. Most of the farmers got credit from the government and non-government organizations to rear livestock where  the share of government bank especially Bangladesh Krishi Bank was only 36  percent. Farmers used only 6.54 decimal of land for their livestock enterprises. Labour utilization per farm was about two persons and monthly salary per labour was taka 4031.15. Households income from livestock and poultry sector was 40 percent of total households income and it was the largest contributor to total income. Households income was significantly influenced by livestock income, age of farmer, experience of farmer and region. Farmers of Sirajganj region earned significantly higher income than that of any other region. Farmers of Sirajganj region earned significantly higher income than that of any other region. Farmers had to spend a lot of money for rearing livestock. The principal cost components were feed cost, treatment cost, cost of day old chick and labour cost. Feed cost of poultry was significantly higher than that of cattle. Farmers had to spend their limited income on different cost components such as family food, education, purchase of property, house purchase or repairing, clothing and treatment.  Households food consumption was significantly influenced by family size and regions. Farmers of Sirajganj and Bogra regions consumed significantly higher amount of foods than that of Jamalpur region. The daily per capital protein and calorie intake were respectively 58.26g and 2248 kcal. at the aggregate level. The average absolute and hard core poverty was respectively 29 percent and 13 percent. Poverty prevalence was more in Jamalpur region than in other regions. The study suggested region wise policy options for poultry rearers and dairy farmers and also suggested that market should be developed for its well-functioning in all areas of Bangladesh to make it dynamic and well integrated so that farmers can be benefited from such intervention. ', 'Food Security, Livestock, Crops.', 'University Grants Commission of Bangladesh', 120000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Food Security', 'Agriculture', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.');
