(2515, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Statistics', 'Project', 'Determinants and Constraints of Adoption of Dairy Cattle Technologies', 'The study was carried out in three different agro-ecological zones hilly highlands (Juniata Upazila under Sherpur District), riverside lowlands (Dewangonj Upazila under Jamalpur District) and Semi-urban areas (Sadar Muymensingh)Three Different Locations in Greater Mymensingh distict.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '1.	To investigate into the genetic and phenotypic diversity of the dairy cattle.\r\n2.	To determine the socioeconomic factors those influence the farmers attitudes to increase cow production.\r\n3.	To identify the constraints on the adoption of improved technologies.\r\n4.	To estimate the adoption level of dairy technologies and their impact on milk yield.\r\n', 'A two-stage probability sample design will  be used. The rationale behind selecting two-stage stratified cluster sampling with its principle of simplicity. Low cost and eases of operation. Each of the selected farm households will be interviewed at random through redesigned questionnaire. Three study sites will be selected purposively from Greater Mymensingh. They will be (i) hilly highlands (Sherpur district). (ii) Kishoregonj or  Dewangonj riverside lowlands and (iii) midlands (Mymensingh district). These three regions will be the three strata of the whole sampling technique and one thana from each of the regions will be selected. Three villages form each thana will be selected using random sampling technique. All the native cattle farm holders will be listed form the selected villages. About 80 farmers will be selected from the three selected villages of each thana using second-stage cluster sampling technique. Finally 240 cattle farm households will be selected from three thanas of different categories. ', 'The present study was undertaken to estimate the adoption level of dairy technologies by the small-scale dairy cattle owners, to determine the socioeconomic factors those influence the farmerss attitudes to adopt dairy technologies and to identify the constraints on the adoption of improved technoloties. The study was carried out in three different agro-ecological zones hilly highlands (Juniata Upazila under Sherpur District), riverside lowlands (Dewangonj Upazila under Jamalpur District) and Semi-urban areas (Sadar Muymensingh) and 180 dairy cattle farmers were interviewed. Self-practiced dairy technologies were listed; adoption score for each technology and adoption index for each farmer were studied. A logistic function was unsed to derive coefficients of explanatory variables likely to influence farmers attitudes to technologies adoption.\r\n\r\nOne-fourth farmers used artificial insemination for breeding purpose and two-fifth belonged to medium or high level of technology adoption. Only 35% farmers adopted crossbred cows and some others upgraded indigenous with exotic breeds. About 17.5% rural farmers and 70% semi-urban farmers reared crossbred cows and rural farmers are reluctant to utilize all kinds of improved technologies.  Secondary and higher educated farmers were 9.7 times more likely to be adopting improved technologies compared to illiterate farmers. Lack of time to spare, low literacy rate and lack of training might have attributed to low adoption and maintenance of proper dairy management records by farmers. The level of technology adoption by smallholder dairy farmers is unsatisfactory and is highly dependent on farmers education, farming experiences, financial status and extension services. The socioeconomic circumstances influence adoption of technologies to a great extent, and these factors are the ones that determine the unique adoption process in any adoption study. \r\nIII equipped and poor result of Al and lack of knowledge about time of mating are the most important constraints of breeding practices. High price of inputs specially concentrate; lack of capital and knowledge about proper feeding land balanced ration; and testing of animals were the important managerial constraints perceived by dairy farmers. The constraints encountered in this study were due to the weak economic position of farmers and lesser economic incentives from government to promote dairy farming techniques of clean milk production, value added dairy products which are locally popular so that farmers in the study area may improve their knowledge and try to adopt the recommended dairy farming practices. Extension services should be increased and strengthened and mass media/telecast program for improved technology should be started and strengthened for transfer of improved dairy farming practices to the needy framers in enriching their knowledge.\r\n', 'Cattle, Dairy Technology, Animals', 'University Grants Commission of Bangladesh', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Adoption', 'Animals', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2514, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Population of quality Protein Maize (QPM with conservation tillage under indigenous mulches for food security of char communities. ', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2013', '1.To monitor mulch induced micro-environment under zero tillage conditions ion charlands.\r\n2.To observe mulching effect on physio-chemical properties of zero tillage soils.\r\n3.To assess growth performance of QPM in charlands under water hyacinth and rice straw mulch corers with no-tillage.\r\n4.To popularize QPM production to the char people for better nutrient and food security.\r\n', '', '', 'Food Security, Maize, Crops, Charlands', 'USDA', 4000000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Food Security', 'Crops', '', '', ''),
(2513, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Medicine', 'Project', 'Seroprevalence of feline leukemia virus infection among Cats', 'Mymensingh and Rajshahi district', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '1.	To determine Seroprevalence of Felv antigen among cats in Mymensingh and Rajshahi district.\r\n2.	To identify risk factors for Seropositivity.\r\n3.	To evaluate the diagnostic utility of a simple and rapid diagnostic test for feline leukemia virus infection in Bangladesh. \r\n', '', '', 'Anamils, Diseases, Leukemia virus, Cats', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Anamils', '', '', ''),
(2512, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pharmacology', 'Project', 'Efficacy of Indigenous Medicinal Plants and Establishment of a Medicinal Garden and a herbarium.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-11-2002', '31-10-2005', '01-11-2002', '31-10-2005', 'a. Identification and collection of at least 50 medicinal plants from BAU and Mymensingh district.\r\nb. Efficacy of these medicinal plants will be carried out in laboratory animals.\r\nc. Estabishment of a medicinal garden beside Pharmacology building and a herbarium in Pharmacology department. ', '', '', '', 'BAU', 225000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2511, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Pathology', 'Project', 'Isolation &amp; Identification of Chlamydiae from the caprine abortions and Reproductive tract at Slaughier. ', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-09-2004', '31-08-2006', '01-09-2004', '31-08-2006', '1.	Isolation of chlamydiae from the reproductive tract of infertile goats\r\n2.	Isolation of chlamydiae from the cases of caprine abortions.\r\n3.	Typing of Bangladesh isolates using species specific monoclonal antibodies/PCR.\r\n4.	Histopathology of chlamydial infection.\r\n', 'a. Materials / Samples collection.\r\nb. Design of experiments: Described in materials.\r\nc. Procedures to be followed in achieving objectives.\r\nCytological and microbiological study, ii) Isolation of chlamydaie iii) Histopathology iv) Immunohistochemistry/PCR', '', '', 'BAU', 150000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(2510, 'Sylhet Agricultural University', 'Department of Irrigation and Water Management', 'Project', 'Environmental Impacts of Groundwater abstraction in Barind Area.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-11-1997', '31-08-1998', '01-11-1997', '31-08-1998', '1.	To study aquifer characteristics and hydrogeology of Barind area.\r\n2.	To study groundwater level fluctuations and the rate of depletion of groundwater levels due to pumping.\r\n3.	To study recharge processes and possible safe yield of Barind aquifers.\r\n4.	To make an inventory on ground water abstraction devices and the total utilization of the resource.\r\n5.	To study the nature and magnitude of intervention caused by groundwater utilization using DTWs and STWs on the local surface water bodies, flora and aquatic ecosystem.\r\n', '', '', '', 'BARC', 128160, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2509, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Science', 'Project', 'Effect of different kindling intervals on reproductive performance of does and growth of young rabbits', 'Goat and sheep Farm, Department of Animal Science, BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2012', '30-06-2013', '01--07-2012', '30-06-2013', '1.	Demonstrate the best time of reservicing after parturition of rabbits.\r\n2.	Know  the effect of kindling intervals on reproductive performance of does and growth of kids.\r\n3.	Develop an Oestrus synchronization protocol by doe-litter separation.\r\n', '', '', '', 'AU-UGC', 150000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Production', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(2508, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Incorporating GIS and Remote Sensing techniques to delineate the best places for freshwater prawn (Machobrachiun Rosenburgii) Culture in Fulbaria. ', 'Fulbaria Upazilla of Mymensingh district. ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1. To create a up to date land use map\r\n2. Create a database on physiology, culture technology and social and economic factors affecting the location of prawn farming in ponds and \r\n3. Selection of suitable areas for prawn culture in Fulbaria Upazilla.', 'a. Location of work: Fulbaria Upazilla\r\nb. Research Plan: a) Field based data collection and b) Laboratory based image processing and modeling\r\nc. Data processing in the laboratory\r\nd. GIS software will be used in the study\r\ne. Image Processing and Manipulation\r\nf. Field based operations\r\ng. Reclassifying the database\r\nh. Weighting procedure\r\ni. Modeling: 1. Water quality sub-model, 2. Soil chemistry sub-model 3. Infrastructure sub-model 4. Support sub-model 5. Inputs sub-model 6. Markets sub-model 7. Risk factors sub-model and 8. Constraints  (which is not available for consideration). ', '', 'Prawn Culture, Freshwater, GIS and Remote Sensing', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Prawn Culture', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(2507, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics', 'Project', 'Study of population genetic Structure of the Stinging Catfish (Shing) Heteropneustes fossilis (Bloch)', 'Genetics and Molecular Biology Laboratory, Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', 'The purpose of this study is to reveal the genetic variation within and differentiation among five different populations of the stinging catfish H. Fossilis in Bangladesh by using micro-satellite DNA markers to help develop management plans for the conservation of this popular fish species. The topic has been included in the research priority of BAURES as well as national needs. ', 'a. Collection of Sample\r\nb. Isolation of Genomic DNA\r\nc. quality and quantity assessment\r\nd. PCR Amplification of Micro-satellite DNA markers\r\ne. electrophoresis\r\nf. Scoring and analysis of genetic variations within and among the populations\r\ng. Report writing and publication ', '', 'Fish, Genetic structure, Catfish', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Genetic Structure', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(2506, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Breeding and Genetics', 'Project', 'Study on the threats to Black Bengal goats conservation in the north western region of Bangladesh.', 'Rajshahi, chapai Nabab gonj and Dinajpur urban  and Peri urban area', 'High', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2009', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2009', '1.	To know the breeds of goats (transboundary) entering into Bangladesh from India.\r\n2.	To know the extent to which BB goats are becoming crossbreds.\r\n3.	To know the opinion of the stakeholders regarding the cause and effect of such crossbreeding. \r\n4.	To propose possible suggestion in order to conserve BB goats of north-western region.\r\n', '', '', '', 'BAU', 100000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2505, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Dairy Science', 'Project', 'Replacement of whole milk with soymilk for raising calves.', 'BAU Dairy Farms and Dairy Technology laboratory of Dairy Science, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1. to prepare soymilk form whole soybean seeds\r\n2. To determine the effectiveness of feeding soymilk on feed intake, growth rate &amp; calf mortality.\r\n3. To disseminate the technology to farmers level who are the backbone of the nation.', 'a. Proximate analysis of whole soybean seeds.\r\nb. Composition of prepared soymilk.\r\nc. Feed intake of calves\r\nd. Body weight chances.\r\ne. Increment of heart girths as bearth.\r\nf. Calf mortality (if any)', '', '', 'BAU', 200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Soymilk', 'Soybean', '', '', ''),
(2504, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Dairy Science', 'Project', 'Effect of Concentrate supplementation with straw based diet on the performance of heifer under farm condition', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Dairy Farm, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1.	To estimate dry matter intake of the heifer\r\n2.	To estimate the live weight and heart girth changes\r\n3.	To observe the reproductive response\r\n4.	To check the gain in productive life\r\n', 'Nine heifers will be selected and grouped into three on the basis of body weight namely- A, B and C. The basal diet of the animal will be rice straw ad libitum and green grass @ two-kg/head/day. Required rice straw will be purchased from the local market and green grass (German, Para, Maize, Kalai, Jumboo etc.) Depending upon the requirement and season will be produced in the fodder production plots of BAU dairy farm. \r\nThe group A, B, and C will be supplemented with 500g, 600g, and 700g concentrate mixture, respectively. The concentrate mixture will be made of wheat bran, rice polish and common salt. The dry matter intake, changes in live weight, heart girth, reproductive response and economic return will be recorded daily, fortnightly, as and when occurs and at the end of the study respectively. The data will be analyzed as per repeated measures of analysis of covariance in CRD and some statistical tools may also be used to express the results. \r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Harvest', 'Crops', '', '', ''),
(2503, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Nutrition', 'Project', 'Bio-availability of phosphorus from virus phosphorus sources and its supplemental effect on the performance of growing cattle. ', 'Animal Nutrition field laboratory and analytical laboratory, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1.	To determine the chemical composition and P contents of locally available feedstuffs.\r\n2.	To investigate the bioavailability of P in the natural and synthetic sources.\r\n3.	To increase the phosphorus contents of fodder crops by application of P fertilizer and to investigate its bioavailability in the animal body.\r\n4.	To improve the P status of growing cattle and supplemental effect on the growth performance of cattle.\r\n', 'a.	Materials: Feedstuffs, metabolism crate and growing animal \r\nb.	Phosphorus sources: Natural sources (feedstuffs) and synthetic sources (bone meal, tripe super phosphate etc.)\r\nc.	Design of experiments: Completely Randomized Designed will be followed for growth trial and fodder experiments and Latin Square Design will be followed to investigate the bioavailability P from various sources\r\nd.	Analysis of experimental data: Using MSTAT statistical package.\r\n', '', 'Animals, Cattle, Chemical composition, P fertilizer,', 'BAU-UGC', 200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Nutrition', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(2502, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Science', 'Project', 'Effect of feeding system on formation and development of ovarian follicles in Black Bengal goats.', 'Goat and Sheep farm, Department of Animal Science, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', 'The proposed experiments will be conducted to know the effect of feeding system i. e. , grazing tethering and stall feeding on follicle reserve in neonatal ovaries, follicular development, age of puberty, prolificacy and post partum heat period in Black Bengal goat. ', 'At first, 2 to 3 month old weaned kids (n=18)of Black Bengal goats will be collected form the local markets. they will be housed in the Goat and sheep farm in Bangladesh Agricultural University. They will be raised in 3 feeding systems i.i. grazing, tethering and stall feeding. Kids will beovariectomized/sacrifised to collect the ovaries at 7 days. 1 month, 2 months, 3 months and at puberty. Data will be analyzed with appropriate statistical methods for each parameters. ', '', 'Animals, Feeding system, Black Bengal goats.', '', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Feeding System', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(2501, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Nutrition', 'Project', 'Conservation of forage germplasm, and evaluation of their productivity and nutritive values for feeding livestock.', 'Field laboratory, Department of Animal Nutrition, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '1.	Identification of available fodder species\r\n2.	Conservation of locally available and exotic fodder species\r\n3.	Green biomass yield and nutritional evaluation for feeding animals\r\n4.	Production of root stocks, cuttings and seeds\r\n', 'Biomass yield of individual species will be recorded ad analyzed for proximate components, ADF, NDF, cellulose, hemicellulose and lignin. this will also be evaluated by in-sacco and in-vitro gas production technique for organic matter digestibility, digestible energy, metabolizable energy, net energy lactation and degradability of nutrients. ', '', 'Animal, root stocks, cutting and seeds, fodder species, green biomass yield', 'BAU', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Green Biomass Yield', 'Livestock', '', '', ''),
(2500, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Science', 'Project', 'Meat Preservation by Freezing to Produce Quality Meat for Human Consumption ', 'Laboratory, Goat and Sheep farm, Department of Animal Science, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '1.	Compared the freezing method of meat preservation with or without curing agent at different temperature.\r\n2.	Found the effect of defrosting method on the quality of meat. \r\n', 'Collection of Meat and Sample preparation (Morning meat, evening meat, day old meat).\r\na.	Physical Profile: Color, Flavor, Texture, Marbling, Juiciness, curing agent preparation, \r\nfreezing temperature setting  Refrigerator temperature, Freeziang temperatjure (5&deg;c  10&deg;c). Preservation of meat with or without curing agent. Defrosting method: Air (Using ceiling fan), Soaking in water with wrapping paper, Microwave\r\nb. Chemical Profile: Observation for Refrigerator (1, 3, 7 days), Freezing (3, 45,90,180 day)\r\nProximate composition, fatty acid determination, Ph measurement, Iodine value, Peroxide value\r\na.	Microbiological Profile: Total bacterial count, Yeast, mould count, Coliform count.\r\n', 'The effect of freezing temperature and defrosting method on the quality of beef was investigated in experiment t 1. For this purpose eight meat samples were stored in the freezer for 90 days and analyzed on 3rd, 45th and 90th day. These samples were taken as air defrosted morning beef at -5&deg;C (M1), water defrosted morning beef at -5&deg;C (M2), air defrosted morning beef at -10&deg;C (M3), water defrosted morning beef at -10&deg;C (M4),, air defrosted evening beef at -5&deg;C (M5), water defrosted evening beef at -5&deg;C (M6), air defrosted evening beef at -10&deg;C (M7), and water defrosted evening beef at -10&deg;C (M8). To assess the quality to frozen meat samples chemical and microbial assessment were studied. Statistical analysis indicated that the advance of storage time quality parameters of beef samples degraded significantly (p&lt;0.01). Highly significant difference existed in morning and evening beef when considering microbial count (p&lt;0.01). Beef can be preserved in freezer at -10&deg;C and soaking in water may be the suitable way of deforestation of frozen packed meat considering less nutrient loss and lower microbial presence.\r\n\r\nExperiment 2 was conducted to find out the effect of defrosting method on the fresh and cured beef. For this purpose six meat samples were stored in the freezer for 90 days and analyzed on 10th, 45th and 901th day. The samples were taken as Air fresh (M1), Water fresh (M2), Micro web fresh (m3) and Air cured (M4), Water cured (M5), Micro web cured (M6). To assess the quality of frozen meat samples, chemical and microbial assessment were studied. Statistical analysis indicated that the quality parameters of beef samples varied significantly (P&lt;0.01). Significant difference existed in fresh and cured beef when considering microbial count (P&lt;0.01). Cured beef can be preserved in freezer at -10&deg;C and slow defrosting by micro wave oven may be the suitable way of deforestation of frozen packed meat considering lower microbial presence.\r\n', 'Animal, Meat, Quality of meat', 'University Grants Commission of Bangladesh', 120000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Meat Storage Technique', 'Animals', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2499, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Science', 'Project', 'The miracle multipurpose tree Moringa oleifera have the potentials of modulate rumen fermentation characteristics and conceivably capable to increase protein supply to the ruminants.', 'Goat, sheep and Horse farm, Animal Science and Animal Nutrition Laboratory and Field Laboratory, BAU. ', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1.	Characterization of M. oleifera leaves, pods, bark and seeds.\r\n2.	In vitro incubation to investigate the nutritional quality of M. oleifera leaves pods, bark and seeds.\r\n3.	Investigate rumen fermentation pattern particularly the nature of protein degradation in the rumen using M. oleifera leaves, pods bark and seed meals with high protein diet.\r\n4.	Kinetic study with M. oleifera leaves, pods, bark and seed meals to investigate rumen fermentation pattern particularly protein degradation in the rumen.\r\n5.	Use of monensin, a growth promoting antibiotics with M. oleifera leaves, pods, bark and seeds to compare rumen fermentation parameters.\r\n6.	Study with M. oleifera leaves, pods, bark and seed meals to investigate optimum doses for higher protein availability in the rumen and post ruminally.\r\n', 'a.	Sampling of leaves and seeds\r\nb.	Chemical Characterization\r\nc.	1. Determination of nutritional properties, Analysis of proximate components\r\n2. Determination of tannins- Total phenols, total tannins, hydrolysable and condensed tannins\r\nd. 	In vitro incubations (Hohenheim gas test)- Assessing fermentation pattern and the effect of polyethylene glycol incubation and measurement of gas\r\ne. 	Measurement of short chain fatty acid and ammonia\r\nf. 	Organic matter digestibility and metabolizable energy.\r\n g. 	Assessing protein precipitation capacity- incubation and sampling\r\nh. 	Analysis of soluble and pellet protein\r\ni. 	Evaluation of protein pattern with electrophoresis. \r\n', 'The experiment was conducted to quantify chemical composition, amino acid and fatty acid composition and mineral content of leaves, amount of different forms of tannins, in vitro gas production (GP), organic matter digestibility (OMD) and metabolizable energy (ME) content of Moringa oleifera leaf, seed, pod and bark to assess the quality and the effect of tannin with and without tannin binding agent polyethylene glycol (PEG) to assess tannin activity. This project was also conduced the use of M. oleifera leaf, pod, bark and seed meals with high protein diet to investigate rumen fermentation pattern particularly the nature of protein degradation in the rumen. The CP value of M. oleifera leaves is comparable with other unconventional fodder leaves and higher than the minimum range of NRC for mature beef cattle (70 g/kg) and high producing dairy cows (190 g/kg) and could be a good feed for ruminants when supplemented with low-protein diet as straw or hay. The EE content was comparable or even higher in M. oleifera leaves than other fodder tree leaves. The NDF and ADF were relatively low compared with other foder leaves provide a good indication of the nutritive value as feed. The amino acieds composition of M.l oleifera leaves were compared with soybean. The aromatic amino acid was rich and the values appeared to be higher or comparable with soybean. The sulphur-containing amino acid was higher in M. oleifera than soybean. Threonine, glycine, alanine, valine, leucine and histidine were higher or even comparable with soybean. Therefore, M. oleifera leaves could be the potential source of supplementary protein for the animals. The majority of saturated fatty acid was plamitic and stearic acid and unsaturated fatty acid was oleic, linoleic and linolenic acid, as in soybean acid, black gram and green gram. The composition of fatty acids in M. oleifera leaves is notable in its content of unsaturated fatty acids, particularly, the essential fatty acids, which are needed components in the diet of animals. The minerals Ca, P, Na, K, Mg, Al, Se, Zn, Fe, Cu, S, Mo and Mn were present in Moringa leaves. Total phenol, total tannin, condensed tannin and hydrolysable tanninwere present in Moringa leaves, seeds pods and in bark. In vitro gas production of these samples ranged from 19.09 to 54.39 ml during 24 hours of incubation. Leaf sample produced significantly (P&lt;0.01) higher gas (54.39 ml) compared to other three samples. The OMD in leaf was significantly higher (P&lt;0.01) compared to seed, pod and bark sample. The ME content (MJ/Kg DM) lf leaf, seed, pod and bark were significantly different (P&lt;0.01) and the values was higher in leaf. The different forms of tannin present in M. oleifera leaf, seed, pod and bark were found low and there was no significant effect on in vitro gas production proved that the tannin was not active. High leaves of tannin impaired digestibility and nutrient utilization and could be use upto the recommended level but feeding M. oleifera leaf dont have any adverse effect on nutrient utilization. The result finally suggested that that M. oleifera could be ranked as a good quality feed to ruminants specially when the usual grazing lands are flooded or feed supplies are very restricted. Addition of leaf, pod bark and seed meal protected protein from ruminal fermentation by increasing soluble protein that made protein concentration very high in the soluble state and at  the same time accumulatin of protein in the pellets were found higher compared to the control. M. oleifera leaf was found more active in this regard. The function of M. oleifera leaf to accumulate protein was found similar with the growth promoter monensin. Protein precipitation started from very early hours of incubation Ammonium concentrations were found higher with the addition of leaf meal as in Monensin. Protein patterns of soluble and particle fraction by PAGE electrophoresis confirmed these results. It can be predicted from the present findings that M. oleifera leaf may use as natural source of feed additives to alter rumen fermentation characteristics especially may available protein in the rumen will ensure ruminant productivity. Further in vivo study in needed to ensure the benefits of M. oleifera leaf as an additive in the ruminant diets as of growth promoter Monensin. ', 'Animals, Tree, Leaf', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Protein', 'Animals', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2498, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Nutrition', 'Project', 'Reduction of methane emission and increased production from livestock through improved feeding and manure management. ', 'Animal Nutrition field laboratory and analytical laboratory, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1.Increase digestibility of fibrous feeds through strategic supplementation and reduce enteric methane production.\r\n2.Improve productivity of cattle as well as reducing luminal methane emission through improved feeding.\r\n3.Find out appropriate method of manure management for preserving the nutrient content and reduce ammonia and other nitrogenous gas emission.\r\n4.Application of manure of improved management in the field for crop production.\r\n', 'a.Selection of animals, formulation of ration and feeding trial- 1. Selection of animals chemical analysis of feeds and formulation of ration 2. Feeding trial experiments, measurements and data recording\r\nb.Management of manure of the experimental animals  1. Manure storage and management 2. Manure analysis for gas and nutrient loss\r\nc.Development of feeding systems for livestock  1. Improved feeding system for livestock\r\nd.Identification of improved management of manure and crop production- 1. Soil an d manure analyses; 2. Manure application in the crop field\r\ne.Data analysis and report writing- Statistical and economic analysis of experimental data and report writing\r\n', '', 'Livestock, Manure, Feeds', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Feeding and Manure Management', 'Livestock', '', '', ''),
(2497, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Poultry Science', 'Project', 'Development of meat type Quail in Bangladesh', 'BAU poultry farm and departmental Laboratory of poultry science, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1.	To develop at least one meat ype quail line that will help to reduce the animal protein gap in the country.\r\n2.	To diversify the poultry production of Bangladesh with a new species.\r\n3.	To engage more people in poultry farming including the vulnerable woman, school going boys/girls and hobbyists. \r\n4.	To establish a new quail stock in the country that will be a worth for future. \r\n', '1.	Establishment of the reference flock of Japanese quail with different plumage colors. \r\na.	Wild (W), b. Black (B), c. white (Wh), d. fawn (F), e. white-breasted (Wb).\r\n2.	Upgradation of different color lines towards higher meat yield: each color line will be upgraded up to 6th generations for higher meat yield through close breeding. To produce a generation, 25% heavier quail of both sexes among 100 individual in each color line will be used on the basis of live weight and feed conversion ratio (FCR) at market age of 35 days.\r\n3.	 Testing of the combining ability of different color lines. \r\n', '', 'Birds, Meat, Poultry, Quail stock.', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Development of meat production', 'Poultry', '', '', ''),
(2496, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Management', 'Project', 'Population and reproductive ecology of barred spiny eel Macrognathus pancalus and its Management recommendations in Bangladesh', 'Fish specimens are to be sampled form a particular perennial habit in/near Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1.	Determine age and growth of M. pancalus of a perennial habit;\r\n2.	To estimate the size age and timing of recruitment;\r\n3.	To determine the timing of spawning and its length, frequency of spawning, size at first reproduction and fecundity of the species;\r\n4.	To determine fishing and natural mortality;\r\n5.	To assess the sustainable yield;\r\n6.	To develop a management guide for the sustainable state of M. pancalus stocks in the various inland habitats in Bangladesh. \r\n', '1.	The determination of fish age and growth ins fundamental in fisheries biology and management. Standard length and body weight of 100 randomly sampled fishes will be measured in each sample. Otolith will be collected from al fish in each monthly sample. Gonad will be extracted from all fish to determine sex ratio, gonadosomatic index, fecundity, spawning season spawning frequency. \r\n2.	Sample will produce a time series of length frequency data which may be sufficient to estimate growth by modal progression. \r\n\r\n3.	A selected subsample including a wide range of individuals of guchi population will be used for the assessment of reproductive condition. Each fish in the subsample is to be sexed and measured and its gonad microscopically assessed. It is worthy to mention that year round monthly samples of M. Pancalus which were already collected to a limited extent in the previous year from the river Old Brahmaputra near BAU campus could be used for this project purposes if necessary. \r\n', 'Commonly used models were employed to estimate population parameters of barred spiny eel, Macrognathus pancalus, small indigenous species in the river Old Brahmaputra using 333 individuals consisting of 12 monthly samples each collected from April 2008 to March 2009. Male-female ratio did not deviate from parity (X2 test, p = 0.68). Recruitment occurred at standard length (SL) of 7.75 and 8.12 cm and at age about 0.54 and 0.34 years for male and female respectively.  The direct fitting of growth equation by ELEFANI model estimated 16.68 cm asymptotic SL for male population and 22.9 cm for female population. Female grew faster than male since growth coefficient was 1.15 for male, and 1.20 for female per year. The asymptotic body weight (BW) for male and female were 25.31 and 76.18 g respectively. Male lived 2.61 years, and female 2.50 years at nost. Growth performance index for male was 2.51 and that female was 2.8. The study determined the spawning season of this species from March to December with a peak in April-May. The minimum SL of a spawning female was 11 cm, and the meal SL at first sexual maturity was 14.8 cm. the species is synchronous iteroperous that a mature female spawned all its eggs concurrently during the spawning season. The analyses of SL-fecundity and BW-fecundity relationships revealed strong relationships between them (R2 = 0.531 and 0.641), and they were statistically significant (P&lt;0.05). the fecundity was 2943 eggs at SL at sexual maturity. The natural and fishing mortalities for male were 1.77 and 2.53 per year, and they were 1.84 and 3.56 per year for female. Male were caught at a rate of 0.59 and females 0.66 per year in the river Old Brahmaputra. The maximum yield per recruit obtained for male was 2.34 g at the fishing mortality of 2.2 per year, and that for female was 4.72 g at the fishing mortality of 1.6 per year. The biomass analyses, however suggested that male attained about 3.59 kg at the age of 11 months while female 8.16 kg at the age of 12 months if 1000 individuals for each sex recruited to the adult stock. A management policy guide to the sustainable perpetuity of M. pancalus fishery in the river Old Brahmaputra was prepared incorporating the output parameters obtained in this research project so far. ', 'Fish, Old Brahmaputra river, Determine age and growth, fish mortality, fecundity of  the species', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Fishes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2494, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Indicators of physiological maturity and proximate composition of edible green seeds for use as a vegetable in Dipogon Lignosus. ', 'Department of Crop Botany, BAU Campus, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', 'To identify indexes of PM and quality  nutritional status/proximate', '', 'Lignosus bean is valued for green seeds and young twigs as vegetable, dry split seeds as pulse soup. A study was carried out to determine indexes of physiological maturity (PM), proper harvest time for vegetable seeds and to assesses quality of seeds of two genotypes (G1, G2) to Lignosus bean (Dipogon lignosus (L.) Verdc.). The four ages of pods/seeds (33, 40, 47 and 54 days after flowering, DAF were designated as pre-physiological mature (prePM), physiological mature (PM), post-PM and harvest maturity (HM). The effects of these four seed maturity stages on pod and seed morphology; germination and total soluble solids (TSS) and proximate composition of seeds were investigated. Eight treatments (2 genotypes x 4 harvest stages) were analyzed in RCBD design. Genetic variation for pod and seed sizes existed. Size of pod (6.72cm long and 1.4 cm wide) and seed 1.71 cm long and 1.21 cm wide) was larger in G2 than G1 (6.41 cm and 1.71 cm long for pod and seed; 1.40 cm and 1.21 cm wide for pod and seed, respectively). Average fresh and dry weights of individual pod (4.56 and 1.51 g, respectively) and seed 2.80 g pod-1, respectively) were also greater in G2 Crude protein was greater in G2 genotype (30.27%) than G1 one (21.70%) at PM stage. Of the four seed harvest stages, larger pod and seed sizes with increased fresh and dry weights of pods and seeds were observed at PM. Germination percentage (&gt;80%) and crude protein (25.48%) were also greater at PM. At PM, TSS was greater in G2 (22.23%) than G1 (20.72%). In combined effect at PM stage, size, fresh and dry weight of pods and seeds were significantly greater in G2 than G1. It may be concluded that pods can be identified at PM by observing physical, physiological and growth indicators and future pods may be harvested at PM due to larger size, increased weight and good nutrients of seed for vegetables purposes in the two genotypes of Lignosus bean.', 'Vegetables, Green Seed, Dipogon lignosus', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Green Seed', 'Vegetables', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
