(2477, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Poultry Science', 'Project', 'Development of a cost effective feeding technology for improved productivity of indigenous (Desi) ducks in Noakhali &amp; Lakshmipur district.', 'Noakhali and Lakshmipur District', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-09-2009', '31-08-2011', '01-09-2009', '31-08-2011', '', '', 'The study was carried out in Noakhali and Lakshmipur districts to investigate the responses of scavenging indigenous (desi) ducks to diets of varying nutrient concentrations. A total of 60 farmers from two districts each of 30 who had been rearing six ducks in each house aged 104 to 150 days was considered. There were two upzilas each of 15 farmers in each district. All farmers were females having experience in rearing scavenging ducks. Five treatments were compared in each stage of production (egg production and growth performance of ducklings). In control group, traditional feeding practices and the remaining four groups received supplemental diets, starter ration containing either a mixture of  rice polish and broken rice (35:65), low nutrient density diet (18% CP and 2700 kcal ME/kg), moderate nutrient density diet (20% CP and 2900 kcal ME/kg) or high nutrient density diet (22% CP and 3100 kcal (ME/kg); grower ration containing either a mixture of rice polish and broken rice (35:65) low nutrient density diet (15% CP and 2600 kcal Me/kg), moderate nutrient density 17% CP and 2800 kcal ME/kg) or high nutrient density diet (19% CP and 3000 kcal ME/kg and layer ration containing either a mixture of rice polish and broken rice (50:50), low nutrient density diet (14% CP and 2500 kcal ME/kg), moderate nutrient density diet (16% CP and 2700 kcal ME/kgO or high nutrient density diet (18% CP and 2900 kcal ME/kg). All diets were formulated with locally available feed ingredients and moderate nutrient density diet was formulated following the nutrient specifications of Wiseman (1986) and NRC (1994). The results showed that egg production, egg weight and body weight gain were increase (P&lt;0.01) almost in a linear fashion with increasing nutrient density. Egg production wa highest in Ramgati upazila, intermediate in Subarnachar and Begumgonj and lowest in Raipur upazila. In ducklings, body weight gain and survivability were increase (P&lt;0.01) with an increase in the density of protein and energy and FCR was higher (P&lt;0.01) with a decrease in protein and energy content in the diet. Growth performance was highest in Ramgati upazila than Begumgonj upazila. Among the supplemental feeds high nutrient density diet resulted highest production followed by moderate nutrient density, low nutrient density, a diet containing 50% rice polish and 50% rice polish and 50% broken rice respectively. The control group had the lowest performance in all trials, as would be expected. Moderate nutrient density and high nutrient density diets showed higher production performance. Considering the feed cost and profit margin, it was concluded that moderate nutrient density diet may be recommended for the feeding of indigenous (desi) ducks to explore their production potential but for the poor farmers, the low nutrient density diet may be considered as an alternative to this diet in the interest of maximizing profits with minimum cost.  ', 'Dcuks, Birds, Animals', 'DANIDA', 3274000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Indigenous Ducks', 'Birds (Domesticated)', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
