(2429, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetics and Plant Breeding', 'Project', 'Screening of salt tolerant genotypes in vitro further gene expression analysis in tomato', 'Genetic Engineering Laboratory, SAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '31-07-2012', '01-07-2011', '31-07-2012', '	To optimize the protocol for growing of tomato seedlings under different salt concentrations.\r\n	To identify the genotypes with suitable performance under salt stress for future breeding program.\r\n	To screen the genotypes for identification and isolation of salt inducible genes.\r\n', 'Seed germination and multiplication:\r\nThe seeds of 41 genotypes of tomato (Solanum lycopersicon L) were collected from Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute, Joydevpur, Gazipur and from local market. 14 out of 41 genotypes were selected based on their germination for the experiment. The germination process was performed in the controlled environment of growth chamber with 25oC, 60% relative humidity, and a 16-h photoperiod from white fluorescent lamps (200 &micro;mol photons/m2/s-1 ). The genotypes used in this study for in vitro screening were, BARI-2, BARI-11, BD-7260, BD-7290, BD-7295, BD-7286, BD-7269, BD-7258, BD-7289, BD-7292, BD-7291, BD-7302, BD-7301 and BD-7762 (2 released variety and 12 advanced lines). The seeds of these genotypes were multiplied in the research farm of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University with established production technology of BARI. The viability of the seeds was excellent. The seedlings were raised in rows containing organic matter rich soil as recommended by BARI. Necessary intercultural operations were done as and when required. Day to day observations were carried out and proper care was taken.  The ripen fruits were stored and the seeds were collected, dried and stored at 4oC until use. \r\n\r\nSterilization, inoculation and germination of the seedlings:\r\nThe experiment was being conducted at the Molecular Genetics laboratory of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University, Dhaka-1207. Seeds were surface-sterilized in 1% (v/v) Clorox bleach (Sodium hypochlorite) for 15 minutes and rinsed three times (5 min each) with autoclaved distilled water (Franklin et al., 1993). The sterilized seeds were placed separately in four sterilized Petri dishes containing filter paper (Whatman No.1). Seeds were inoculated in petridishes containing half strength MS medium (1962). Cultures were kept at 25 &plusmn; 1&deg;C under 16 h photoperiod at 50 &micro;mol/ m2/s-1 (supplied by white fluorescent lamp). Germinated seedlings of four days served as experimental materials.\r\n\r\nSalt tolerance assay:\r\nThe salt tolerance assay was performed as described by Zeba et al., 2009. Four days old germinated seedlings were transferred in a liner order on MS medium supplemented with 0, 50, 100 and 200 mM NaCl. The culture environment included, 25oC, 60% relative humidity, and a 16-h photoperiod from white fluorescent lamps (200 &micro;mol photons/m2/s-1 ). After five days, root length and fresh weight of all plants were measured.\r\n', 'Tomato (Solanum lycopersicum L.) is one of the most important solanaceous vegetable crops in the world in terms of both production and harvested area. It is a favorable food crop   for in vitro studies   due   to   its   low   chromosome   no   i.e.,   2n=2x=24   and   due   to comprehensive knowledge of tomato genetics. Plant tissue culture techniques are recognized as useful instruments in tomato improvement. The present study was conducted to explore the bioassay so as to establish a reproducible protocol for in vitro screening of different genotypes of tomato in different concentrations of NaCl. Fourteen out of forty one genotypes of tomato were selected based on their germination ability and were multiplied in the experimental farm of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University, Dhaka. Evaluation of response of these fourteen genotypes to normal and high salt conditions has been carried out in controlled environment with 25oC, 60% relative humidity, and a 16-h photoperiod from white fluorescent lamps (200 &micro;mol photons/m2/s-1 ). Root assay and fresh weight assay were performed to compare the tolerance response of these genotypes. Five genotypes viz., BARI-2, BD-7260, BD-7290, BD-7286, BARI-11 showed excellent performance of tolerance up to 50 mM of NaCl.   BD-7302 showed better performance under high salt concentrations i.e., at 100 mM and 200 mM but not at low salt stress. It indicates the expression of functional gene occurs at high salt stress. To see the gene expression pattern of previously reported genes such as PIP, LTPs, APETALA2 GRP, Arabinogalactan protein, PRP, Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase etc. which played a protective role under stress condition, further experiment by RT-PCR or Northern hybridization is required. For doing these, nucleotide sequence of full Open Reading Frame (ORF) should be obtained using NCBI database gene bank. Functional analysis of candidate genes using either over-expression of endogenous or foreign genes can help to identify functionally relevant genes that determine salt tolerance. The genetics of physiological characters together with other tolerance components related to metabolic defenses against salinity have to be studied in order to advance the breeding of tomato genotypes tolerant to salinity.', 'Tomato (Solanum lycopersicum L.), tomato seedlings under different salt concentrations.', 'SAURES-UGC', 93000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Abiotic stress (salt), tissue culture', 'Tomato', 'This study dealt with the in vitro screening of salt tolerant genotypes in tomato to made the progress of gene expresssion analysis and thereby identify and isolate the genes involved in the process of salt tolerance for future genetic transformation. As salinity in soils is variable and plant tolerance depends on the stage of plant development, in this study, very young tomato seedlings were phenotyped at several salinity concentrations and at the most sensitive plant stage (five days old seedlings). Based on the germination (Fig. 1), 14 genotypes out of 41 were selected. The selected genotypes used in this study were, BARI-2, BARI-11, BD-7260, BD-7290, BD-7295, BD-7286, BD-7269, BD-7258, BD-7289, BD-7292, BD-7291, BD-7302, BD-7301 and BD-7762. According to the established production technology of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), the seeds of these genotypes were multiplied in the research farm of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University (Fig. 2). \r\n         \r\nThe seeds of 14 genotypes were inoculated in half strength MS medium and incubated in the controlled environment of growth chamber. Healthy plantlets were obtained within four days of inoculation (Fig. 3).  To investigate the salt tolerance in 14 genotypes, the root growth assay was performed with the 4 days old plantlets grown on media containing 0 mM-200 mM NaCl. longest root at 50 mM salt indicating their tolerance to salt at 50 mM, whereas BD-7762 showed the smallest root. As the different genotypes showed varying degree of root length under unstressed condition (0 mM), I had to measure the root reduction size at different salt concentrations (Table 1, Fig. 6). BARI-2, BD-7260, BD-7290, BD-7286, BD-7292, BD-7762 and BARI-11 showed negative reduction i.e., they had no effect of 50 mM salt stress on their growth and development . It was also observed that some genotypes showed no tolerance at lower salt concentration i.e., 50 mM but showed tolerance at high salt concentrations such as BD-7358, BD-7289, and BD-7289 at 100 mM salt stress and some of them even at 200 mM salt stress ( BD-7260, BD- 7289, BD-7291, BD-7302 and BARI-11 respectively). This phenomenon indicates that some genes which are responsible for salt tolerance might not be expressed or weakly expressed at low salt stress but might be strongly expressed at high salt \r\nconcentrations and produce functional protein for defense mechanisms. Buchanan et al (2000) showed similar results in case of spinach leaf tolerance to high salt but not at lower salt stress. MIP family genes showed weak expression under low salt and strong expression under high salt stress. Among the cell wall proteins most of them were previously found to play a protective role in plant cells in response to high salinity (Zeba, 2009; Garcia-Gomez et al., 2000; Ueda et al., 2007; Larkindale and Vierling, 2008). Therefore gene expression pattern analysis of previously identified genes involved in protective role under salt stress is yet to be done.\r\n\r\nSalt sensitivity and tolerances were also recorded based on the comparison of fresh weight under 0 mM (unstressed) to 200 mM salt stressed concentrations. BARI-2, BD-7260, BD-7290, BD-7286, BD-7289, BD-7301 and BARI-11 had more fresh weight at 50 mM as compared to the other genotypes (Fig. 7).  They had no effect of salt and even their growth and development is increased at 50 mM of salt stress (Table 2). The fresh weight reduction is negative if observed in Fig. 8. BD-7286 showed tolerance up to 100 mM of salt stress. BD-7302 did not show tolerance response under low salt (50 mM) but showed tolerance at higher concentrations of 100 to 200 mM salt indicates the expression of some genes which have protective roles under high salinity.  Gene expression data should be obtained in the control and stressed plants of the screened genotypes in support of the defense mechanism of these screened genotypes.  \r\nAnalysis of some previously identified genes which showed protective roles in different abiotic stresses is quiet necessary and the presence and expression pattern of those genes in these screened genotypes of tomato will  provide powerful information for over-expression of those genes in transgenic plants those will confer salt tolerances. Some of the previously reported genes which played protective role in defense mechanisms under high salinity are, Plasma membrane intrinsic protein (PIP) (Forrest and Bhave, 2007), Lipid Transfer Proteins (LTPs) (Kirubakaran et al., 2008), APETALA2 (Shukla et al., 2006), Gibberellin-Responsive Protein (GRP) (Jacobsen et al., 1986; Peng et al., 1999), Arabinogalactan protein (Lamport et al., 2005), Prolin Rich Protein (PRP) (Ueda et al., 2007), Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase   ', 'High salinity is one of the major stress factors among the abiotic stresses. In the world, about 400 million hectares of land are affected by high salinity. In Bangladesh about 1 million hectares of land are affected by high salinity in the coastal regions and it is increasing day by day with the expansion of shrimp culture. Salinity affects almost every aspect of the physiology and biochemistry of plants and significantly reduces yield. As saline soils and saline waters are common around the world, great effort has been devoted to understanding physiological aspects of tolerance to salinity in plants, as a basis for plant breeders to develop salinity-tolerant genotypes. In spite of this great effort, only a small number of cultivars, partially tolerant to salinity, have been developed. Further effort is necessary if the exploitation of saline soils and saline waters that are not currently usable is to be achieved. Salinity affects yield quality and quantity, so that yield characters must be taken into account when breeding for salinity tolerance. But not only yield-related characters are important. As salinity affects almost every aspect of the physiology and biochemistry of the plant, the enhancement of crop salt tolerance will require the combination of several to many physiological traits not simply those directly influencing yield. As salinity in soils is variable and plant tolerance depends on the stage of plant development, plants should be phenotyped at several salinity concentrations and at the most sensitive plant stage(s). For in vitro screening, fourty one genotype of tomato was taken for this study. Most of them were collected from Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI). Fourteen out of forty one were selected based on their germination ability and were multiplied in the experimental farm of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University, Dhaka. Seeds were processed and stored at 4oC. Evaluation of response of these fourteen genotypes to normal and high salt conditions has been carried out in controlled environment with 25oC, 60% relative humidity, and a 16-h photoperiod from white fluorescent lamps (200 &micro;mol photons/m2/s-1 ). Root assay and fresh weight assay were performed to compare the tolerance response of these genotypes. Five genotypes viz., BARI-2, BD-7260, BD-7290, BD-7286, BARI-11 showed excellent performance of tolerance up to 50 mM of NaCl.   BD-7302 showed better performance under high salt concentrations i.e., at 100 mM and 200 mM but not at low salt stress. It indicates the expression of functional gene occurs at high salt stress. To see the gene expression pattern of previously reported genes (PIP, LTPs, APETALA2 GRP, Arabinogalactan protein, PRP, Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase etc.) which played a protective role under stress condition, further experiment by RT-PCR or Northern hybridization is required. For doing these, nucleotide sequence of full Open Reading Frame (ORF) should be obtained using NCBI database gene bank. Functional analysis of candidate genes using either over-expression of endogenous or foreign genes can help to identify functionally relevant genes that determine salt tolerance. Genetic transformation is a powerful tool in the breeding of complex characters, such as tolerance to salinity, if progress is made on the identification of genes involved in the process of salt tolerance, the isolation of genes from other sources of variation, the design of vectors which allow the transfer and co-ordinate expression of several genes (as salt tolerance is a multigenic trait), and the identification and use of regulatory elements, which spatially and temporarily modulate the level of expression of the transgenes. Despite the present limitations, it is foreseeable that our ability to design the future breeding programmes based on genetic transformation will be strengthened with the data obtained from ongoing functional genomics projects. ', ''),
