(2417, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Rural Sociology', 'Project', 'A study on size and Pattern of crop diversification programmes in some selected areas of Bangladesh', 'Department of Co-operation and marketing and Rural Sociology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-03-1998', '30-06-2000', '10-03-1998', '30-06-2000', 'a.	To examine the socioeconomic and tenurial status of the crop diversifying farmers in the areas under study.\r\nb.	To find out the size and pattern of crop diversification programmes of the farmers under study including considering the socioeconomic impact of the additional output of the standard of living of the farmers.\r\nc.	To identify the problems such as economic, customary, family and group farming aspects that are related to the crop diversification programmes in the areas under study.\r\nd.	On the basis of these finding to make some suggestions towards the policy makers for sound crop diversification programmes in the country in future.\r\n', '1.	Materials and methods: mainly primary sources of data were used in the study. For the purpose six villages from the six divisions of Bangladesh were conveniently selected. Again, from each village 50 farm households were randomly selected.\r\n2.	Design of experiment: Each division was considered as cluster. So cluster sampling survey method was followed in selecting the respondents. From each cluster 50 farmers were sampled at random for the study.\r\n3.	Procedures followed in achieving the stated objectives.\r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 39660, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2415, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Anatomy and  Histology', 'Project', 'Morphometric studies of the oviduct and sperm-host glands of deshi-chicken.', '', 'High', 'Basic', 'Completed', '01-07-1999', '30-06-2002', '01-07-1999', '30-06-2002', 'a.	Gross morphometrical analysis of the oviduct of deshi chicken.\r\nb.	Age-related development of sperm-host glands of chicken in Bangladesh.\r\nc.	The distribution of sperm-host glands in different segments of the oviduct of these birds.\r\nd.	Histology and histochemistry of these glands in the oviduct of chicken, and \r\ne.	Collection of semen from the cocks and inseminate into the hens or the hens mated naturally to study the viability of the spermatozoa in the sperm-host gland of chickens of various ages.\r\n', '1.	Materials: a. Deshi chickens of various ages; b. Adults cocks for mating purpose and for the collection of semen; c. Instruments and chemicals\r\n2.	Design of experiments: the chickens of one-day old will be reared together with the males and the female birds will be grouped into different age-groups, viz, 1, 4, 8, 12, 15, 19, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90, 100, 110, and 120 weeks along with their advancement of age. Each age group consists of 10 chickens.\r\n3.	Procedure to be followed in achieving stated objectives:\r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 224917, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2414, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Irrigation and Water Management', 'Project', 'Determining the suitable size of the evaporation pan for Irrigation scheduling in BAU farm, Mymensingh.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-02-1993', '31-01-1994', '01-02-1993', '31-01-1994', '1.To find out a suitable size of evaporation pan.\r\n2.To find out the actual evaporation from the field crop (wheat) by comparing the evaporation from the pans and evapotranspiration from the field crop by taking soil moisture from the field.\r\n3.To find out the total requirement of the field crop (Wheat)\r\n4.To analyze the economic impact of applying different doses of irrigation water in different treatments.\r\n', 'Meterials:\r\ni.Nine evaporation pans of heights 40 cm, 50 cm and 60 cm and diameters 30 cm, 45 cm, and 60 cm.\r\nii. wire, which will be used to cover the pans.\r\niii. one auger\r\niv. 48 numbers of soil collecting boxes\r\nv. 4 numbers\r\nvi. seeds\r\nvii. Fertilizer and manure etc.\r\n\r\nDesign of experiments: For the purpose of irrigation scheduling the available soil moisture content will be considered in the respective treatments\r\n', '', '', 'AU-UGC', 63550, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2905, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Food security in Bangladesh: Proximate composition of tubers and removal of toxicity in flower of cassava strains for use are potential human and animal food. ', 'Department of Crop Botany, BAU, Mymensingh.', 'High', 'Applied', '', '', '', '', '', '1.	To investigate the effect of Morphotypes on tuber yield;\r\n2.	To determine HCN and proximate composition of tubers in 5 selected strains. \r\n', 'Following the steps of the Methodology: \r\n1. Cultivation Protocol:\r\n2. HCN and proximate composition:\r\n3. Data to be Recorded:\r\n4. Growing season:', 'Cassava (Manihot esculenta Crantz) roots (tubers) are used as staple food in Africa, Carbbean and Asia. Starch extracted from tubers is also utilized in garment, paper, food, feed and pharmaceutical industries. Its leafs is rich in protein and vitamins and  can be used as vegetables and feed after removing hydrogen cyanide (HCN). Starch was extracted in cortex and peel of seven cassava accessions (A1+, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6, and A8) in 2011-2012. Extraction was carried out by blending chopped tuber following decantation. For four production, freshly harvested tubers were peeled, chopped, cubed and dried at 50&deg;C with around 12-15% moisture. Dried cube Cassava pieces were milled into flour. Tuber starch content varied from 15.04% (fresh wt basis) in A8 to 5.85% in A1. Variation also existed in tuber protein content among the accessions. Crude protein content varied from 1.87% (average of A2, A3 and A8) to 4.53% in A6. Crude fiber content also varied from 1.96% (average of A4 and A1) to 4.27% in A3. Cyanogens present in cassava convert into HCN during harvesting and processing. HCN variation existed and it was 140 mg/Kg fresh tuber (average of A8 and A1) to 546.0 mg/Kg fresh tuber in A6. Lethal dose of HCN for human is &amp;#8804; 50mg HCN/average body weight. There was no detectable HCN in the flour and starch extracted. Flour and starch extracted from cassava tuber is safe for human and animal consumption.', 'Cassave, Food security, toxicity, animal food', 'MOSICT', 400000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Biology', 'Cassava', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2412, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Biocontrol of Okra Mosaic with plant Extracts. ', '', '', '', 'Completed', '01-07-1994', '30-06-1995', '01-07-1994', '30-06-1995', 'a.	Evaluation of some selected plant extracts in comparison with an insecticides to control okra mosaic under field condition and\r\nb.	Estimation of cost benefit ratio in comparison with an insecticide (diazinon).\r\n', 'The experiment will be conducted twice, once in Kharif and another in Rabi seasons.\r\na. Collection and preparation of plant extract,\r\nb. spray schedule of plant extracts and diazinon 60 EC,\r\nc. collection of Data,\r\nd. Analysis of Data', '', '', 'University Grants Commission of Bangladesh', 32000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2413, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Structure', 'Project', 'Determination of cone Index of Agricultural Soil from state parameter concept. ', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-09-1998', '31-08-1999', '01-09-1998', '31-08-1999', 'a.	Collection of the representative soil from BAU agricultural farm and estimation of its mechanical composition. \r\nb.	A programme of triaxial compression tests for the evaluation of the critical state parameters at different moisture content of the remoulded soil.\r\nc.	Develop a computer software for modeling critical state space of the experimental soil from the known set of critical state parameter.\r\nd.	Evaluation of soil-metal properties required for defining cone surface parameters. \r\ne.	Calibration chamber tests to validate the state parameter concept for unsaturated soil. \r\nf.	A penetrometer test in ta soil bin to simulate the field performance of the penetrometer \r\ng.	Test the penetrometer performance into actual field situation\r\nh.	Computer simulation of the results of the penetrometer performance.\r\n', 'a.	Penetration Test in the soil Tank: An approximate field situation will be created by reprocessing the soil in the tank. The depth of penetration and load due to the advancement of cone-penetrometer within the soil mass will be continuously recorded. \r\nb.	Penetration Test in the Actual field: The Penetration test will be conducted into actual field situation. The depth of penetration and load due to the advancement of cone-penetrometer within the soil mass will be continuously recorded. Penetrations at different depths with existing field moisture contents and dry densities will be carried out to observe the penetrometer performance and it will be analyzed. \r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 99, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2411, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Structure', 'Project', 'Determination of cone index of Agricultural soil from state parameter concept', 'Department of Farm Structure, BAU, MY-2202', '', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-1997', '31-12-1997', '01-01-1997', '31-12-1997', 'a.A programme of triaxial compression test for the evaluation of the variation of the critical state parameters with moisture content of remolded soil samples. \r\nb.Evaluation of soil metal properties required for defining cone surface parameters.\r\nc.Estimation of standard moisture-tension curves of the soils used in the experiments together with their mechanical composition. Calibration chamber tests to validate the state parameter concept for a partly saturated loam soil.\r\nd.A penetrometer test in a soil tank to simulate the field performance of the penetrometer.\r\n', 'a.Soil collection and preparation: Soils from different sites of BAU farms will be collected and its required properties will be determined according to BS 1377; 1990. The soil will be prepared with different densities and moisture contents for triaxial and calibration chamber tests.\r\nb.Triaxial Test: The Standard triaxial test apparatus will used to determine the basic soil paramerters. The testing technique for performing the triaxial tests described by Head (1986) will be followed.\r\nc.Penetration test in the Calibration chamber: The sample preparation for this test is similar to that of triaxial tests but with a large sample of 100 mm diameter and 200 mm height.\r\nd.Penetration test in the soil tank: An approximate field situation will be created by reprocessing the soil in the tank. The cones with different dimension and surface roughness will be used in this test.\r\n', '', '', 'BAU', 25000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2409, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Survey on the status of bacterial wilt of some selected vegetables (Brinjal, Potato and Tomato) in Bangladesh, Characterization of its pathogen and its integrated Management.  ', 'Field Laboratories, BAY.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', 'a.To find out the present status of bacterial wilt of brinjal, potato and tomato in terms of its incidence and severity in different growing regions in Bangladesh.\r\nb.To find out the races or biovars (Virulcen or avirulent) of the pathogen, Ralstonia solanacearum existing in Bangladesh.\r\nc.To find out the cultivated varieties of brinjal, potato and tomato shows tolerance or resistant reaction to bacterial wilt pathogen based on the survey report or screening.\r\nd.To find out the components can be integrated to manage the disease effective at field level.\r\n', 'a.Surveying and sampling, b. Assessment of wilt incidence and severity\r\nc. Isolation of R. solanacearum; d. OR from soil samples\r\ne. Identification and purification of R. solanacearum\r\nf. Detection by Immunostrip; g. Preservation of the isolates\r\nh. Pathogenic test\r\ni. Identification of virulent and avirulent isolates\r\nj. Virulent, Avirulent, Identification of race,Identification of Biovars\r\nk. Integrated management\r\nb.	l. Pot experiment- Preparation of soil, Treatments, Raising of seedlings, Transplanting of seedlings, Preparation of inoculums, Inoculation of R solanacearum, Data collection;\r\nc.	Field experiment- Preparation of Experiment plot, Application of the treatments, Transplanting seedlings, Inoculation of R. solanacearum, Data collection etc.', '', '', 'AU-UGC', 120000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
