(2681, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Mitigation of salt stress by enhancement of antioxidant defense systems with proline in rice', 'Soil science net house and laboratory, Department of Soil Science, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '1.	To investigate the protective effect of proline on the growth and yield of rice against salt stress.\r\n2.	To examine the effect of proline on K/Na ratio, chlorophyll content and proline accumulation by rice under salt stress.\r\n3.	\r\n4.	To examine the effect of proline on the activity of Ros-Scavenging antioxidant enzymes under salt stress. \r\n5.	To suggest an approach for the improvement of crop production under salinity.\r\n', '', '', '', 'BAU-UGC', 120000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2682, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetic and Plant Breeding', 'Project', 'Somaclonal variation and molecular characterization for developing strawberry in Bangladesh', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-04-2011', '31-03-2013', '01-047-2011', '30-03-2013', '1.	To develop method of rapid, efficient multiplication of large scale strawberry in Bangladesh.\r\n2.	To select disease tfee with risk yield and quality (vitamin-C and sugar content) potential, stable strawberry somaclones.\r\n3.	Molecular characterization of strawberry for suitable lines in Bangladesh using RAPD markers. \r\n', '', '', '', 'BAU-UGC', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Strawberry Production', 'Fruit', '', '', ''),
(2683, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Effect of leaf clipping on the forage as well as quality seed production of transplant aman rice grown under different agronomic environment. ', 'Agronomy field and seed laboratory, Department of Agronomy, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1) To develop suitable techniques of leaf clipping of transplant aman rice that will give higher forage as well as grain/seed yield from the same crop.\r\n2) To develop agro-techniques suitable for higher forage as well as grain/seed yield from the same crop.\r\n3) To study the effect of leaf clipping and agrotechniques on the performance of transplant aman rice.\r\n4) To evaluate the quality of forage and rice seeds collected from the dual purpose crop.', 'Treatments: Factor A N-fertilization (kg urea per ha)\r\ni) 100\r\nii) 150\r\niii) 200\r\niv) 250\r\nFactor B: Leaf clipping frequency\r\ni) No leaf clipping (Control)\r\nii) Leaf clipping at 25 DAT\r\niii) Leaf clipping at 25 DAT and 45 DAT\r\niv) Leaf clipping at 25 DAT, 45 DAT and 55 DAT\r\nReplication: 3\r\nDesign: Split-plot', 'To overcome the scarcity of green grass for the cattle and to help in solving the food problem of Bangladesh, the present two experiments were undertaken at the Agronomy Field Laboratory, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during July 2008 to June 2009. To develop suitable techniques of leaf clipping of transplant aman rice that will give higher forage as well as grain/seed yield from the same crop, these two experiments were conducted. The idea behind the experiments was to find out if it is possible to grow rice as a dual purpose crop under Bangladesh condition. Experiment number one was conducted in a split-plot design where rice was grown involving two sets of treatments such as (A) four levels of N (100, 150, 200 and 250 kg/ha) and (B) four clipping frequency: (a) No leaf clipping, (b) leaf clipped once at 25 DAT, (c) Leaf clipped twice at 25 DAT and 45 DAT and (d) Leaf clipped thrice at 25 DAT, 45 DAT and 55 DAT were maintained. The result of the experiment showed that nitrogen fertilization at 250 kg urea/ha with one leaf clipping at 25 DAT combination was found to be the best for obtaining maximum yield and quality seed of transplant aman rice cv. BRRI dhan41. From the second experiment, which involved 4 levels of N and leaf clipping time, it was found that it is possible to get moderate forage yield, maximum grain yield with better seed quality of transplant aman rice from leaf clipping at 25 DAT with 250 kg urea/ha.', 'Leaf clipping, forage, quality seed production, agronomic environment', 'BAURES', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Quality Rice Seed Production', 'Aman rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(2684, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetic and Plant Breeding', 'Project', 'In vitro regeneration, mutation and improvement of rice through anther culture. ', 'Biotechnology and genetic engineering laboratory, Department of genetic and plant breeding', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '1.	Development of efficient and stable protocols for another culture of rice.\r\n2.	Use of the techniques doubled haploid production.\r\n3.	Using mutagenic agent at the time of another culture to improve the line. \r\n', '', 'The experiment was conducted to observe the regeneration potential and also to establish a suitable in vitro plantlet regeneration protocol from mature seed derived embryogenic calli of four indica rice varieties viz BRRI dhan-29, BRRI dhan-28, BRRI dhan-47 and BINA dhan-7 after partial desiccation treatment. Different concentrations and combinations of growth regulators was used in MS medium to observe the callus induction ability using mature embryo as explants. The percentage of callus induction frequency was highest (86.00) in BRRI dhan-47 which required 14.90 days and the lowest (56.50) in BINA dhan-7 which required minimum days (1465). Among the culture media the performance of T4 (MS + 500 mgl-1 L-Proline + 2.0 mgl-12, 4-D + 08 mgl-1 BAP) was better than any other media (for callus induction frequency (%), rapid callusing,  size of the callus (mm), texture of callus and color of callus. The experiment again conduced to evaluate morphological variation due to irradiation we used eight plant materials viz. BINA 7, BR 11, BRRI dhan 22, BRRI dhan 23, BRRI dhan28, BRRI dhan 29, BRRI dhan 33, and BRRI dhan 47 and the anthers of those materials were cultured for 0, 10, 20 days and irradiated with 0, 20, 30, 40 and 50 Gamma rays. The experiment also conducted to develop double haploids rice pants and to select the lines on the basis of their performance we used eight plant materials viz. BINA 7, BR 11, BRRI dhan 22, BRRI dhan 23, Brri dhan 28, BRRI dhan 29, BRRI dhan 33 and BRRI dhan 47. Thus utilization of this technique will help to develop purely homozygous varieties. ', 'BRRI, Rice, vitro plant, homozygous varieties', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Environment', 'Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2685, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry', 'Project', 'Integrated use of Vermicompost, Bio-gas slurry and inorganic Fertilizers for sustainable tomato production.', 'Net house and laboratory in the Department of Agricultural Chemistry, BAU.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '1.	To evaluate the impact of vermicompost, biogas slurry and inorganic fertilizers on the growth and yield of summer tomato.\r\n2.	To assess the nutrient content of summer tomato as influenced by vermicompost, biogas slurry and inorganic fertilizer.\r\n3.	To investigate the residual effect of vermicompost and bio-gas slurry as organic fertilizer on the postharvest soils in terms of integrated nutrient supply on soil fertility. \r\n', '', '', '', 'BAU-UGC', 120000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2686, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Entomology', 'Project', 'Bio-efficacy of biopesticide against jute hairy caterpillar, spilarctia obliqua walker. ', 'Laboratory, green house, horticulture farm of BAU.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '1.	To determine the individual and combined efficacy of Bt and neem based bio-pesticide against S. oblique. \r\n2.	To determine the effect on biology and fecundity of S. oblique by Bt and neem based bio-pesticide.\r\n3.	To calculate the median lethal dose of the tested bio-pesticide against S, oblique.\r\n4.	To determine the compatibility of microbial and neem based bio-pesticide against S. oblique. \r\n', '', '', '', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2687, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Entomology', 'Project', 'Development of integrated management of rhizome fly (Mimegralla coeruleifrons), a major cause of rhizome damage of ginger in Bangladesh.', 'Entomology laboratory and field laboratory, BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', 'The production of the spices ginger cultivation has recently been given due importance nationwide. As rhizome fly is a major problem in ginger cultivation in Bangladesh and conventional ways of pesticide application do not provide sufficient control of the pest, the development and utilization of IPM technologies for it is the need of the day. The extent of damage due to this pest infestation is yet to be determined. The IPM technologies for rhizome fly are not available so far. Development of appropriate management technologies for ginger fly is a timely relevant project. This proposed project will investigate different aspects of rhizome fly and its control options to develop an IPM program. The findings will be useful to the sustainable management of the pest.', 'Life cycle parameters will be studied in the laboratory. Population dynamics of rhizome fly will be determined by day degree model using the data of life cycle parameters at different temparature regimes. Extent of rhizome damage due to rhizome fly infestation will be determined in farmer''s field in three ginger growing areas namely Nilphamari, Jamalpur and Khagrachari. Trials with botanicals and pestcides against the pest will be conducted in the laboratory and field. The data will be collected and analyzed.  ', 'Spices are strongly flavoured aromatic substances of plant origin which are commonly used for seasoning, cooking food and preserving other food stuffs. Ginger is one of the most important spice crops in Bangladesh. The country produces only 43000 metric tons of ginger as against the domestic demand of 96000 metric tons per year. Rhizome fly has been reported as a major pest of ginger in Bangladesh. Ginger farmers struggle a lot to overcome the problem. The adoption of environment friendly pest control strategies is of great relevance today. Considering the importance of rhizome fly, life history parameters will be available which will be utilized in managing the pest. Thermal constant and lower threshold will be determined and day degree model could be useful in determining the population dynamics of the pest. Effective control tactics will be developed for integrated management of the pest. ', 'Rhizome fly, Ginger, IPM', '', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Pest Management', 'Rhizome Fly', '', '', ''),
(2688, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Detection of the causal Agent of leaf mosaic of Jute ', 'Department of Plant Pathology, BAU, BJRI, Dhaka, BJRI rield Research Station, Manikgonj and farmers field. ', '', '', 'Completed', '01-03-2011', '29-02-2012', '01-03-2011', '29-02-2012', '1.	To identify the causal agent of leaf mosaic of jute.\r\n2.	To know the mode of transmission of causal agent of leaf mosaic of jute.\r\n3.	To characterize the causal agent of leaf mosaic of jute by molecular techniques\r\n', '', '', '', 'BAU-UGC', 120000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2689, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Science', 'Project', 'Effect of feeding systems on follicular proportion, ovulation rate and 00cyte quality in Black Bengal Goats. ', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '1.	Experiments will be conducted to know the effects of feeding system i. e. grazing tethering and stall feeding on ovarian follicular proportion. Ovulation rate and developmental competence (rate of in vitru maturation) of 00cytes in Black Bengal goat.', '', '', 'Animals, Black Bengal Goats.', 'BAU-UGC', 240000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Feeding system', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(2690, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agroforestry', 'Project', 'Host specificity of ectomycorrizal fungi to common dipterocarps in Bangladesh.', 'Field Laboratory, Department of Agroforestry, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', '', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1) To identify the specificity of available ectomycorrhizal fungi to common dipterocarps.\r\n2) To identify the degree of growth promotion of different ECM fungi to common  dipterocarps.', 'Experiments will be laid out following RCBD with four replication for each dipterocarp spices.\r\nStudy Species: Dipterocarpus turbinatus, Hopea odorata and Shorea robusta\r\nEctomycorrhizae: Available species of Laccaria, Russula, Amanita, Scleroderma, Suillus, Lactarius genus.\r\nProcedure to be followed:\r\n1) Seeds/seedling/coppice collection.\r\n2) Seedling establishment\r\n3) ECM fungal sporocarps collection\r\n4) Spore germination in the agarose media\r\n5) ECM spore inoculation\r\n6) Observation the growth and development of all dipterocarps seedlings.', '', 'Dipterocarp, ectomycorrhizae, ECM', 'BAURES', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Dipterocarps forestration', 'Fungus', '', '', ''),
(2691, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Assessment of seed quality and seed health of HYV rice from formal and informal sectors in relation to management practices.', 'Laboratory, Glass house, net house and field laboratory, Department of Plant Pathology.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1) To determine the quality and health of HYV rice seeds of formal and informal sectors.\r\n2) To find out the impact of storage practices on health and quality of HYV rice seeds.\r\n3) To manage quality and health of HYV rice seeds.', 'Following procedures will be done:\r\n1) Collection of seed samples\r\n2) Seed health analysis:\r\na) Dry inspection\r\nb) Detection of seed borne fungi\r\n3) Seed quality analysis\r\ni) Purity analysis\r\nii) Moisture test\r\niii) Germination test', 'Seed is one of the most important technologies for crop production. For successful rice production there is no other alternative but good seed. The importance of rice in Bangladesh could never be overemphasized. Among the options to increase rice production use of good seed is most important. In Bangladesh only 12% of good quality rice seed is produced and distributed by GO, NGO and private sectors. Therefore, the remaining 88% of the required seed is produced and used by the farmers. Contaminated seeds can often results in poor germination, seedling vigor and resulting unhealthy crops. Seed borne pathogens cause germination failure, rotting of seed, root and coleoptile and weight loss of the seed in addition to spotting and discoloration to the seed. A good quality seed may be seriously damaged if stored under sub-optimal conditions. Storage fungi are mostly responsible to damage seed in storage by reducing seed viability. In Bangladesh, storage loss as high as 15%. Therefore, there is a need critical study on assessment of seed quality and seed health of HYV rice from formal and informal sectors.', 'Seed quality, Seed health, Moisture test, purity test', 'BAURES', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Quality Seed Production', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(2692, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Allelopathic Potential of Cucumber (Cucumis sativus L.) for rice weed management.\r\n', 'Department of Agronomy, BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-01-2013', '31-12-2014', '01-01-2013', '31-12-2014', '1.	The study in to find out the allelopathic potential of cucumber to control paddy weeds and to develop biological method of weed management through cucumber allelopathiy.', '', '', 'Rice, Cucumber', 'BAU', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(2693, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Entomology', 'Project', 'Morphological and chemical factors of brinjal plants and fruits offering resistance to Epilachna spp. and Leucinodes orbonalis.', 'Central laboratory, Entomology department laboratory and field', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1) To determine the damage level caused by BSFB and EB of selected brinjal varieties/lines through field screening.\r\n2) To identify the morphological characters influencing the infestation rate of BSFB and EB.', '', 'Research experiments relating to the resistance of twenty one brinjal varieties/lines to Leucinodes orbonalis and Epilachna spp. Infestation in relation to morphological and chemical factors of brinjal, were carried out in the field, cage and laboratory during July 2008 to June 2009 in rabi season. The infestation varied significantly among the varieties/lines and also with the age of the brinjal plants. On the basis of shoot infestation Amjuri, Kata begun WS were found to be tolerant; BARI begun-4 (Kajla), Deem begun, Dharala, EG 190, ISD 006, Khatkhatia BAU, Morich begun-L, Thamba, Zhumki were moderately tolerant; BARI begun-1 (Uttara), Bijoy, Borka, Eye red, Irribegun, Islampuri, Islampuri (BADC), Laffa BAU, Singnath were susceptible; Dohazari was highly susceptible. While on the basis of fruit infestation Amjuri, Kata begun were also found tolerant; Morich begun-L, Thamba were found as moderately tolerant; BARI begun-1 (Uttara), BARI begun-4 (Kajla), Deem begun, Dharala, Dohazari-G, Eye red, Irri begun, ISD 006, Islampuri, Khatkhatia BAU, Laffa BAU, Singnath (BLO 83) and Zhumki as susceptible; Bijoy, Borka, EG 190 and Islampuri (BADC) were highly susceptible, respectively. The brinjal shoot infestation rate by shoot and fruit borer was found to be positively correlated with the plant height (0.093), stem diameter (0.322), leaf length (0.217), leaf width (0.322), number of leaf per plant (0.131). Whereas, the infestation was negatively correlated with number of branches per plant (-0.192). In case of fruit, the borer infestation rate was found to be positively correlated with fruit length (0.102), fruit diameter (0.234), fruit weight (0.343) and negatively correlated with the total number of fruits per plants (-0.300). Among the varieties/lines, brinjal fruit infestation was found to be positively correlated with fruit moisture (0.033), Ash (0.599), protein (0.528), fat (0.149), ascorbic acid (0.456) and negatively correlated with fibre (-0.151). The intensity of leaf infestation by Epilachna beetle in different varieties/lines was found in the following order. Zhumki&amp;#707; Khatkhatia BAU&amp;#707; Dohazari-G&amp;#707; Amjuri, BARI begun-1 (Uttara), BARI begun-4 (Kajla), Singnath (BLO 83)&amp;#707; Dharala, Islampuri, Laffa BAU, Thamba&amp;#707; Bijoy, Irribegun, Islampuri (BADC), Morich begun-L&amp;#707; Borka, Deem begun, EG 190, Eye red, ISD 006 and Kata begun WS. Brinjal leaf infestation rate by epilachna beetles was found to be negatively correlated with the plant height (-0.097), number of branches (-0.112), stem diameter (-0.177) and number of leaf per plant (-0.268), whereas, the infestation was positively correlated with leaf length (0.201) and leaf width (0.11). Preference of epilachna female beetle for egg deposition on brinjal varieties/lines was studied. Basal portion of dorsal side of leaf was preferred by EB. The number of egg mass deposited by EB was positively correlated with plant height (0.012), leaf length (0.514), leaf width (0.019) and leaf color (0.172) but negatively correlated with number of branches (-0.093), stem diameter (-0.442) and number of leaf (-0.090).    ', 'Brinjal plants, Epilachna, Leucinodes, resistance', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Vegetable Production', 'Brinjal Shoot and Fruit Borer (BSFB)', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
