(2737, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Feasibility of Sesbania rostrata seed production by intercropping with transplant aman rice.', 'Laboratory and field laboratory, Department of Agronomy, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1) To transplant Sesbania rostrata cuttings in the T. aman field to minimize the space and time problem as well as quality seed within 2 to 3 months without disturbing rice yield.\r\n2) To ensure profitability from intercropping of Sesbania rostrata including biomass production for fuel.', 'The experiment was conducted at the Agronomy Field Laboratory during July to December each year. Top portion of 50 day old Sesbania rostrata plant were used as planting material. Planting was done after 15 days of transplanting rice seedling in between two rows of transplant aman rice.', 'Sesbania rostrata known as African Dhaincha is an aquatic legume green manuring crop. Though it is a unique green manure crop, farmers are not growing it for seed production. For seed production, seeding is done during April-May and harvested for seed and stick in the months of October-November. It takes about 7 to 8 months to produce seed for which farmers have to sacrifice a main crop of his limited land area. Therefore, research should be done to solve this problem. Vegetative propagation is an alternative method which can be practiced as intercrop with transplant aman rice. The plant tops of 50 to 60 day old plant may be used for planting in between the two rows of transplant aman rice. The Sesbania top thus planted become rather not so tall and undergo early flowering by receiving the exposure of days shorter than the critical day length of the season.', 'Sesbania rostrata, T. aman rice, seed production', 'BAURES', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Seed production', 'Sesbania rostrata', '', '', ''),
