(2741, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry', 'Project', 'Phytoremediation of arsenic contaminated soil', 'Laboratory and net house, Department of Agricultural Chemistry, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '1) Remediation of arsenic contaminated soil by easily grown as hyper-accumulating plants.\r\n2) Assessment of arsenic accumulating pattern in root and shoot of the plants.\r\n3) Formulation of time schedule for remediation of arsenic contaminated soils.', 'Two pot culture experiments was conducted in the net house of the Department of Agricultural Chemistry, BAU, Mymensingh taking two arsenic accumulating plants (Barnyard grass and water taro) during two cropping seasons i.e. one crop was raised each year. Two arsenic contaminated soil cores was collected from arsenic affected areas of Dhaldi and Majchor Unions of Faridpur district. The soils was filled in pots and arsenic hyper-accumulating plants was grown with normal cultural practices. Yields and other observations was recorded. Plant uptake of arsenic and its distribution in different plant parts was evaluated. Pre and post harvest soil arsenic status was determined and extent of soil arsenic reduction due to arsenic uptake by hyper-accumulating plants was assessed. Comparatively more suitable arsenic accumulating plant was identified and recommended for the remediation of arsenic contaminated soils. ', 'Experiments were conducted to study the remediation of As contaminated soil in the department of Agricultural Chemistry, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh. In experiment-I jute varieties BARC deshi Pat-1, NINA Deshi Pat-2, CVE-3, OM-1 and )-92 were used to find out the germination ability, against As contaminated medium. The treatment were 0, 15, 40, 70, 100 and 150mgL-1 As. In general increased concentrations of As significantly decreased the germination percentage, seedling height and dry weight of five dry weight were observed in BADCDesi Pat-1, BINA Desi Pat-2, but seedling survived up to 100 ppm dose of As. In experiment-11, BINA Deshi Pat-2, BADC Deshi Pat-1 having high germination potentially observed in experiment I were used to observed the as uptake capacity form contaminated soil medium. This experiment was conducted in a series of pots following applications of 40,100 and 150 mgkg-1 As on soil medium in the net house.  Results of experiment-II reflected that as uptake by the different parts of BADC Deshi Pat-1 increased with the increasing with the increasing addition of As in the soil medium. Maxium as concentration (27.21 mgkg-1 As) was found in shoot against 150 mgkg-1 As application in soil, on the other hand maximum As content (19.37 mgkG-1 As application in soil. On the other hand maximum As content (19.37 mgkg-1 As) was detected from the shoot of BINA Deshi pat-2 when 40mgkg-1 As applied in the soil.\r\nIt was evident that there are some jute varieties which have the ability to accumulate As in their bark. Further study will be required for final recommendation to remediate As from the contaminated soil by jute.\r\n', 'Arsenic, Soil, Jute, Rice.', 'BAURES', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Soil polution', 'Arsenic', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2742, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry', 'Project', 'Extraction, Chromatographic analysis and subsequent processing of stevia rebaudiana leaves for the commercial production of food grade sweetener a sucrose substitute. ', 'i) Agril. chemistry laboratory, ii) Central lab, BAU, iii) BCSIR Lab. Dhaka iv) Net house, dept of Agril. Chemistry.', '', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2012', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2012', '30-06-2013', '1.	Development of health friendly and economic methods for extraction of steviol glycosides from leaves of stevia rebaudiana.\r\n2.	Chromatographic analysis of the extract.\r\n3.	Development of simple and health friendly purification procedure fo the extract for removal of fat, oil, gum and other useless compounds.\r\n4.	Development of simple and economic processing technology for  producing food grade aqueous concentrate and powder from of steviol glycosidic sweetrev. \r\n', '', '', '', 'BAU-UGC', 150000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
