(2745, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Horticulture', 'Project', 'Shelf life extension of Papaya', 'Laboratory of Horticulture and Central Lab, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1) To develop a package of low cost technology for extension of shelf life of Papaya.', 'Following experiments were conducted:\r\n1) Effects of pre-cooling and wrapping materials on the extension of shelf life of Papaya without affecting the post harvest quality of fruits.\r\n2) Effects hot water treatment and immersion period on the extension of shelf life of papaya without affecting the post harvest quality of fruits.\r\n3) Effects of stage of maturity and modified atmosphere packaging on the extension of shelf life of papaya without affecting the post harvest quality of fruits.\r\n4) Effects of low temperature storage on the extension of shelf life of papaya without affecting the post harvest quality of fruits.\r\n5) Effects of plant extracts on the extension of shelf life of papaya without affecting the post harvest quality of fruits.\r\n6) Effects of different post harvest treatments on the extension of shelf life of papaya without affecting the quality of fruits', 'Post harvest loss of fresh fruits is one of the important problems in the tropics. Its post harvest losses range up to 40-100%. The high perishibility of the fruit is attributed to adverse physio-chemical changes, namely, weight loss due to respiration and desiccation, softening of flesh, loss due to microbial attack and changes in sugar and acid contents. Papaya is a very fleshy fruit with a soft skin. Papaya fruits are very susceptible to many fungal diseases namely anthracnose, stem end rot and rhizopus fruit rot causing enormous loss in fruit quality. This problem is a major concern in a hot humid country like Bangladesh. Post harvest research in Bangladesh is very limited. Although some reports are available, yet it has not been possible to develop any technology to reduce the post harvest losses of papaya and to extend its shelf life. Therefore, the proposed research proposal has been initiated to reduce the post harvest spoilage and to extend the shelf life of papaya. Hopefully, the findings of the project will be helpful to solve the above mentioned post harvest problems of the papaya growers, traders and the consumers to a great extent and to initiate a basis for post harvest research in Bangladesh.', 'Shelf life of papaya, Quality of fruits, Post harvest loss', 'BAURES', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Shelf life extension', 'Papaya', '', '', ''),
(2746, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry', 'Project', 'Vermicomposting of different wastes and its impact on okra cultivation as organic farming', 'Net house and laboratory, Department of Agricultural Chemistry, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '31-12-2010', '01-07-2009', '31-12-2010', '1) To assess the nutrient status of prepared vermicompost from different wastes.\r\n2) To evaluate the impact of vermicompost on the growth, yield and nutrient content of Okra.\r\n3) To study the influence of vermicompost on disease incidence of Okra.\r\n4) To investigate the residual effect of vermicompost on the post harvest soils.', 'The experiment was conducted in the net house and laboratory of the Department of Agricultural Chemistry, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh and the experimental techniques was performed with the following ways:\r\n1) Different wastes collection\r\n2) Vermicompost preparation\r\n3) Experimental treatments\r\n4) Parameters\r\n5) Vermicompost, plant and soil analysis', 'Vermicomposting is an ecofriendly technology that converts different wastes into high valuable organic fertilizer for sustainable vegetable crop production to reduce the use of chemical fertilizers. This is an appropriate ecobiotechnological process of waste management regarding safe disposal of wastes for preventing environmental pollution and also soil health improvement as organic fertilizer for reducing soil pollution caused by chemical fertilizers. Different wastes such as press mud and municipal solid waste were spiked with cow dung at ratios of 50:50, 70:30 and 90:10 in vermibed and the status of nutrient during mineralization of wastes in the presence of earthworm (Eisenia fetida) was studied. As control treatment, same experimental setup without earthworm was also maintained. Vermicomposting increased the contents of N, P, K, S, and Zn but decreased organic C content as well as C:N ration in different experimental beddings as compared to control treatment after 75 to 90 days of earthworm activity. Considering the nutrient status, vermicompost prepared from press mud and cow dung (70:30) was applied in a pot experiment to study its performance on the growth, yield and nutrient content of okra.  The experiment was laid out in a completely randomized design (CRD) with 3 replicationsand treatments. The experimental treatment were: T1  control, T2  Recommended dose of chemical fertilizers (CF), T3  VC1 (Vermicompost @ 5 t /ha-1), T4  VC2 (Vermicompost @ 10 t/ha-1), T5  VC1 + 50% CF, T6  VC1 + 75% CF, T7  VC2 + 50% CF and T8  VC2 + 75% CF. application of vermicompost @ 10 t/ha along  with 50% chemical fertilizer (T2  treatment) showed the best performance for growth parameters such as plant height, no. of leaves plant-1, days to  flowering and first harvest, no of mature green pods plant-1, length and diameter of green pod followed by the use of vermicompost @ 10 t/ha-1 along with 75% chemical fertilizer (T8 treatment). Vermicompost with different doses of chemical fertilizers had significant influence on the yield and yield contributing characters of okra as compared to control treatment. The contents of N, P, K, S and Zn in okra were significantly influenced by vermicompost treated soils. Vermicompost treated soils conserved more organic C, macro and micro nutrients under consideration over control. These findings revealed that vermicomposting could be an alternative technology for the management of different wastes into useful organic fertilizer and the increase of plant nutrition and soil fertility would help to maintain the long-term soil productivity for sustainable okra cultivation. ', 'Vermicompost, Okra, Organic matter', 'BAURES', 199950, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Organic Farming', 'Okra', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2747, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Study on the prevalence of Strawberry diseases and their control through IDM approaches in Bangladesh', 'Rangpur- Sadar, Lalmonirhat-Kaliganj, Hatibandha;  Memensigh-Sadar and Laboratory, Green house, Horticulture farm, BAU.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1) Recording of incidence and severity of Strawberry diseases of different nurseries.\r\n2) Isolation and identification of severe pathogens related to the prominent diseases of strawberry.\r\n3) Control of those pathogens through IDM approaches both in vitru and in vivu condition.', 'Following activities were done:\r\n1) Disease incidence, diagnosis of strawberry diseases and identification of pathogens.\r\n2) Cultural Practices\r\n3) Preparation of bio-control agents\r\n4) Bio-assay\r\n5) Pot/field experiments\r\n6) Preparation of mixture of bio-control agents and their application', 'An investigation of strawberry (Fragaria ananassa) diseases was performed in several districts (viz. Rangpur- Sadar, Lalmonirhat-Kaliganj, Hatibandha;  Memensigh-Sadar, crown rot was found epidemic in all the above mentioned districts that caused premature recorded in Rangpur Sadar. The highest incidence (&gt;85%) on crown rot disease was recorded in Rangpur Sadar. The other soil borne diseases recorded in the strawberry fields  were Pythium root rot (Pythium sp), Rhizoctonia bud rot (Rhizoctonia sp), Root knot (Meloidogyne sp), Mycosphaerella leaf spot (Mycosphaerella fragariae), and Phomopsis blight (Phomopsis sp). After collection of infected strawberry samples, all the diseases were diagnosed in the plant diseases clinic, BAU, Mymensingh. Grey mold, pestalotia rot, Penicillium rot, Rhizopus rot, Aspergillus rot and anthracnose were also predominantly recorded in the mature stage of the strawberry fruits. From this investigation, it was revealed that soil borne pathogens were epidemic for strawberry diseases. Trichoderma harzianum based biopesticide (64 kg/ha) with cowdung (30 t/ha) treatment was found very much effective to control all the recorded soil borne diseases here that also yielded the highest cost benefit (C:B) ratio in compare to non-treated treatments. On the other hand using of Trichoderma suspension @ 10 ml /L can successfully control leaf spot, Phomopsis blight and other fruit diseases of strawberry. ', 'Strawberry, Disease, IDM, Pathogens', 'BAURES', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Plant Disease', 'Strawberry', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2748, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Screening of salt tolerant land races of rice and crop species', 'Green house and Agronomy field laboratory, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1) To screen out some most important salt tolerant rice cultivars for coastal areas.\r\n2) To find out the morphological properties responsible for salt tolerance.\r\n3) To find out other crop species like sugar beet that would be suitable to grow in the coastal belt of Bangladesh.', 'Seeds of known salt tolerant rice cultivars was collected from the research organizations and farmers of the saline affected region that are commonly grown there. Using appropriate statistical design the performance of all of the rice cultivars were evaluated in pot experiments in the green house of the department of Agronomy, BAU under various salinity levels. Depending on their performance a screening was made and most tolerant five cultivars were chosen for further experiments. Salinity tolerance at various growth stages of the chosen cultivars and their morphological properties contributing salt tolerance such as forming salt gland if any will be further studied.\r\nSeeds of tropical sugar beet, which is a salt tolerant halophytic plant, from Syngenta, Sweeden was collected. Another experiments was conducted to evaluate the salt tolerant level of that crop.', 'Increasing level of salinity in the coastal belt of Bangladesh is posing serious threatening catastrophe for crop production. The viable options for ensuring crop productivity of saline soil are to select salt-tolerant crop species/cultivars and/or to ameliorate salinity stress effects through agronomic management. The objectives of the project were: i) to screen out the most salt-tolerant landraces of rice and other crop species and ii) to ameliorate salinity stress effect in rice through agronomic management practices. Seeds of 25 local landraces of rice were collected from the farmers of coastal area of Bangladesh. Based on the performance in terms of seed germination and seedling growth under various levels of salinity, five most salt-tolerant landraces namely Kajal Lata, Super Miniket, Lal Jamaibabu, Hogla and Nunsa aus were initially screened. The growth and yield performances of these five landraces of rice along with their morphological characterizations were evaluated through a pot trial in the net house of the department of Agronomy, BAU. Based on their survival rate and yielding ability under various levels of salinity used in this study these varieties could be ranked in terms of their salinity tolerance as Lal Jamai babu &gt; Hogla &gt; Kajol lata &gt; Super miniket. Pot trials were also conduced to ameliorate salinity stress effects in salt tolerant high yielding rice variety BRRI dhan47 through agronomic management such as application of gypsum and ash. Application of both gypsum and ash exerted significant positive role in improving the salt tolerance of rice cv. BRRI dhan47.\r\n\r\nTo screen salt tolerant wheat varieties a pot experiment was conducted in the net house of the department of Agronomy,  BAU including ten wheat varieties (nine Bangladeshi varieties viz. Akbar, Sufi, Prodip, BAW-1064, Shotabdi, BAW-1059, Anando, Bijoy, Aghrani and one variety from Egypt). Five salinity levels, viz. control (no salt), 40 mM, 60mM, 80 mM and 100 mM were imposed at 45 days after sowing (DAS). The Egyptian variety survived up to 100 mM salinity level while all the Bangladesh varieties died above 40 mM salinity level except Shatabdi. The highest grain yield (2.51 t ha-1) was found in Egyptian variety followed by Shotabdi (2.41 t ha-1).\r\n\r\nSugarbeet is known as a halophytic plant having high tolerance to salinity stress. To explore the possibility of growing tropical sugarbeet in Bangladesh, an experiment was  conducted in the Agronomy Field Laboratory, BAU including five varieties viz., Shubhra, Cauvery, EB-0616, EB-0626 and EB-0809 sown at four different sowing dates such as 10 November, 20 November, 30 November and 10 December. The results revealed that variety and sowing data exerted significant effects on beet yield of tropical sugarbeet. The results indicate that all the varieties gave their highest yield with 10 November sowing when compared to the other sowing dates used in the study and among the five varieties EB-0809 yielded the highest beet (157.0 t ha-1).\r\n', 'Sugar beet, Salt tolerance, Coastal region', 'BAURES', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
