(2827, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Food Technology and Rural Industries (FT&amp;RI)', 'Project', 'Coordinated project on contaminants and adulterants in food chain and other mitigation: BAU component. ', 'Norshingdi municipalities (industry and super market)', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2013', '01-05-2011', '30-06-2013', '1.	Current issues, status, changes, and constraints of quality control in processed food products summarized.\r\n2.	An exclusive list of harmful chemicals and adulterants used in processed food products prepared.\r\n3.	Resources for detection, identification and mitigation of hazardous contaminates and adulterants in processed food strengthened.\r\n4.	Hazardous adulterants used in selected processed foods assessed. \r\n', '', '', 'Food chain, mitigation', 'NATP-SPGR', 6611200, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Foof Safety, quality, Hazands and Risk', 'Food &amp; Nutrition', '', '', ''),
(2828, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Surgery and Obstetrics', 'Project', 'An integration of Reproduction, Nutrition and Diseases Management for Developing Market-oriented Dairying in Bangladesh. ', 'Mymensingh, Chittagong, Satkhira, Khulna Sadar, and Pabna districts. ', 'High', '', '', '', '', '', '', '\r\n1.	To identify the existing resources in favor of dairying and to be used us future intervention.\r\n2.	To understand the farmers involvement in dairying in contrast to his/her daily workload.\r\n3.	To identity the changing trend of dairy farming .\r\n4.	To understand farmers 0views on the breeds of  dairy cattle.\r\n5.	To record the project status of land use.\r\n6.	To identify the constraints of dairying and to gather farmers views in overcoming the handles.\r\n7.	To identify the services available to the dairy farmer and to understand the farmers expectations of future services.  \r\n', '', '', '', 'International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)', 8000000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(2829, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Breeding and Genetics', 'Project', 'In vitro culture (IVC) of Buffalo embryos', 'Department of Animal breeding and genetics', 'High', 'Applied', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To obtain the efficient culture condition for in vitro fertilization (IVF) of Buffalo oocytes\r\n2) To establish the suitable culture condition for in vitro culture (IVC) of buffalo embryos\r\n3) To test the viability of the in vitro developed blastocysts\r\n4) To build up knowledge base in the in vitro production (IVP) of buffalo embryos', 'Methodology was followed the steps:\r\n1) Experimental site selection\r\n2) Collection and processing of ovaries\r\n3) Collection and grading of cumulus-oocyte-complexes (COCs)\r\n4) In vitro maturation (IVM) of oocytes\r\n5) In vitro fertilization (IVF)\r\n6) Checking the fertilization rate', 'The present research has been undertaken to explore the collection and evaluation of slaughterhouse ovaries, follicles and COCs, maturation of buffalo oocytes by using bovine follicular fluid (BFF) and bovine serum (BSA) as well as subsequent fertilization using buffalo frozen semen. Under this project two MS students successfully completed their research work and still one is going on. The results obtained from the experiment shown that there were no significant (p&lt;0.05) difference in the parameters between left and right ovaries except length, the length (cm) was distinctly higher in case of right ovaries (2.32 &plusmn; 0.06) compared to left ovaries (2.14 &plusmn; 0.085). normal quality COCs (grade A and grade B) were found significantly (p,00.01) higher in type-1 than those of type-II, total number of observed follicles aspirated follicles, total number of cumulus-oocyte-complexes (COCs) and number of normal COCs were significantly (p&lt;0.05) decreased when corpus luteum present. He cumulus oocyte complexes (COCs) were collected by aspiration of slaughterhouse buffalo ovaries. After maturation in TCM 199 supplemented with one of 10% BFF, 5% BSA or without supplementation (control), the COCs were fertilized in Brackett and Oliphant (BO) medium using capacitated frozen buffalo spermatozoa. It was observed that the percentage of COCs reached to M-II stages were 40.78 &plusmn; 3.84, 65.74 &plusmn; 2.39 and 67.52 &plusmn; 0.85; normal fertilization (formation of 2 pronuclei) were 23.28 &plusmn; 3.00, 29.30 &plusmn; 0.73 and 30.52 &plusmn; 1.21 for control 10% BFF and 5% BSA supplementation, respectively. The results indicated that the rate of maturation could be significantly increased (p&lt;0.05) by using 10% BFF or 5% BSA to that of control but the supplements showed similar results (p&lt;0.05). in fertilization, it was observed that buffalo frozen spermatozoa could fertilize the buffalo oocytes and the fertilization rate was 23.28% to 30.52%. The fertilizer rates were significantly increased (p&lt;0.05) when 10% BFF or 5% BSA was supplemented in maturation media. Therefore, we could be concluded that buffalo oocytes might be fertilized by using capacitated buffalo spermatozoa and both 10% BFf and 5% BSA could be supplemented in maturation media to enhance the maturation rate as fertilization of buffalo oocytes and the results suggest that the culture condition for IVC was found optimum and the grade A COCs might be suitable for buffalo embryo production.   ', 'Buffalo, Embryo, oocytes, Artificial insemination, IVP', 'MOSICT', 2100000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Animal Biotechnology', 'Buffalo', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012'),
(2830, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Co-oprative and Marketing', 'Project', 'A study on institutional impact on farm production, investment and income in selected areas of Mymensingh district', 'Department of Cooperation and Marketing, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2002', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2002', '1) To find out the socio-economic status of the selected farmers both member and non-member under proposed study.\r\n2) To determine the institutional impact on farm production, investment and income of the member-farmers in the selected areas\r\n3) To identify the problems of both member as well as non-member farmers and to make some suggestions for formulating sound policy for farm production in future in the country.', 'From Mymensingh district, BRDB credit co-operative based 10 villages are to be selected for the present study. Among them, 150 member-cultivators are to be randomly selected and for corresponding assessment to them, 150 non-member cultivators from the same villages are to be selected following random sampling method. Then with well developed two separate interview schedules, one for member and another for non-member farmers, will be used in collecting necessary information covering last two years boro paddy cultivation by direct survey method. The analysis will be diverted towards the specified objectives. In addition to the tabular representation an endeavor would also be taken to develop some relationships and tests in the proposed study.', 'Food problem is one of the major problems of Bangladesh. Unfortunately, the production in such a vital sector still depends on the varieties of nature and the annual food production target varies widely from year to year. Food deficit on account of increasing pressure of population is widening. One of the long-term to this grave problem, is to boost up farm production at the micro level, i.e. farmwise\r\nIn the above context, it becomes relevant and increasing necessity to investigate the impact of the institutions on farm production, investment and income of the farmers. For the proposed study, only one institution, namely co-operative has been chosen and other institutions like rural banks, etc. have been leftout. The findings of the study may provide some new information to the co-operative students and the concerned authority for policy formulation and be of some help to initiate further studies in this respect.', 'BRDB, Direct survey, Mymensingh', 'BAURES', 150000, 0, 0, 'Report', 'Survey', 0, 'Crop Production', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(2831, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Breeding &amp; Genetics', 'Project', 'Studies on the quantitative trait loci (QTL) of economics traits in Balck Bengal Goat. ', 'Baraigram upazila under Natore dist., Ishurdi upazila under Pabna dist. and Banderban upazila under Banderban district. ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2012', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2012', '1.	Production of pure Black Bengal bucks and back cross does.\r\n2.	Identifying the best Black Bengal bucks and does for production of seed stock.\r\n3.	Identifying the quantitative traits loci.\r\n4.	In Black Bengal Goat for meat quantify and quality and other economic traits.\r\n5.	Comparative studies of Black Bengal and crossbred goat for economic traits.\r\n6.	Enhancing the institutional capacity for education and research.  \r\n', '', '', 'Black goat, Production of Black Bengal goat', 'NATP-SPGR', 12710220, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Genetic Imporvement and Innovative Breeding', 'Livestock', '', '', ''),
(2832, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Management', 'Project', 'Building capacity to manage the coastal zone in a changing climate.', 'Department of Fisheries Management, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '06-10-2009', '31-12-2012', '01-01-2010', '31-12-2012', '1.	The project will enhance cross disciplinary understanding and expertise in adjustment to a changing environment for the coastal zone of Bangladesh. This is expected to improve future management of natural resource in coastal floodplain and ultimately the livelihoods of a large population of poor people vulnerable to climate change and associated hazards.\r\n2.	Research climate change impact and adaptation for livelihood environment and fisheries in the coastal  zone and \r\n3.	Mainstream climate change into existing courses and teaching. \r\n', '', 'Bangladesh is among the countries with large number of people vulnerable to the potential impacts of climate change. The extensive coastal floodplains are important for natural fisheries, shrimp farming, agriculture and other natural resources including the Sundarbans mangrove forest. The livelihoods of over 20 million people are based largely on the biodiversity in the southwest region. However, the inhabitants of this region are prone to foods, cyclones, salinity intrusion and droughts, and the incidence of these hazards is rising. Recently two cyclones (known as Aila and Sidr) hit the southwest region of the country. Considering the above in view, a DFID funded INSPIRE project has been conducted for understanding the impacts and adaptation measures through sustainable coastal resources management in the cyclone affected greater Khulna areas. \r\nThe present study was carried out to understand impacts of climate change on the shrimp farming, hatchery and nursery operations in the selected upazilas (Paikgaccha and Shyamnagar).  In the study areas, about 80-90% people are involved with shrimp farming with 10-15 years experience. 60% shrimp farmers thought that the weather has changed abruptly within the last 5 years. The study showed that the first and foremost factor is high temperature (49.5%). Majority farmers (43.21%) encountered that increased temperature interrupted the farm operation, while lower growth (54%), lower production (19%), loss of crops (13%), less water (4%), mortality (4%), mortality (4%), and diseases (4%) occurred due to less rainfall or drought. From the study, fishermen (80%) reported that shrimps were susceptible to diseases such as deformation, white spots or lesions on skins, while 13.33% mentioned PL susceptible to diseases. After cyclones, besides shrimp farming (85%), people are now doing crab culture (40%), vegetable gardening (25%) and some other small business as their livelihood measures. It was also understood that only 10% and 25% are getting support from govt. and NGOs, respectively after cyclones Aila and Sidr. Now, the shrimp farmers and coastal people have started their living and building up their livelihood assets through developing various other adaptation measures.\r\nAcknowledgements: the authors are grateful to the DFID for funding the INSPIRE climate Change project through the British Council Bangladesh. \r\n', 'Environment, Climate change, fisheries, Coastal areas, Communities. ', 'DFID', 8000000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Livelihood, Environment &amp; Fisheries', 'Climate Change', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(2833, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Horticulture', 'Project', 'Development of sustainable technology for quality seed production of onion', 'Department of Horticulture, Soil Science and Plant Pathology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '01-07-1997', '30-06-2000', '1) To developa sustainable technology for quality seed production of onion\r\n2) To develop technology for maximizing seed yield of onion', 'Following experiments were done:\r\n1) Determination of bulb size, spacing and date of planting bulbs for seed production of onion\r\n2) Determination of optimum fertilizer dose for onion seed production\r\n3) Effects of ploytunnel on yield and quality of onion seed\r\n4) Controlling purple blotch disease of onion seed crop\r\n5) Effects of some major and minor elements in presence of NPK on yield and quality of onion seeds\r\n6) Effect of late N application on growth, yield and quality of onion seed\r\n7) Determination of irrigation frequency and water use efficiency for onion seed crop\r\n8) Effects of low temperature storage of bulbs on yield and quality of onion seeds\r\n9) Effect of growth regulators on crop growth cycle, yield and quality of onion seed', 'Onion production in Bangladesh is declining but its demands is increasing. The average yield of onion in this country is only around 4 tons/ha which is one of the lowest in the world. Most important reason is unavailability of quality seeds. In Bangladesh, the most serious problem for onion seed crop is the high level incidence of purple blotch disease. Another problem is the pre-monsoon early rainfall which causes enormous loss to seed crop. Again, information on irrigation requirement for onion seed crop is very scanty. As a matter of fact no package technology is available to the farmer for production of quality onion seed. Unless proper attention is given to the research and development of onion, its cultivation in near future would be at risk. Therefore, if a sustainable technology for quality seed production of onion could be developed the onion growers would be highly benefited.', 'Quality seed production, Onion, Purple blotch', 'BAURES', 628000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Quality Seed Production', 'Onion', '', '', ''),
(2834, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Management', 'Project', 'Cereal system Initiative for South Asia (CSISA) in Bangladesh.', 'Dinajpur and Sunamganj districts.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-10-2010', '30-11-2012', '01-10-2010', '30-11-2013', '1.	To explore the existing system and practices of production of Mola, Darkina, and Dhela in pond and wetland based system in Bangladesh. \r\n2.	To develop methods on mass production of Mola, Darkina and Dhela in pond and seasonal floodplains under fish culture using semi-intensive and intensive system.\r\n3.	To identify the market linkages of Mola, Darkina and Dhela to understand the uses of Mola, Darkina and Dhela product and supplied from different systems.\r\n4.	To understand about the participation and benefits of households involved in production of Mola, Dharkina and Khela using improved technology.\r\n', '', '', 'Mola, Dhela, Darkina fish, Fish production, ', 'USAID', 900000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Production', 'Fishes', '', '', ''),
(2835, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Technology', 'Project', 'Preparation of fish ball and fish stick from low cost silver carp and quality aspects under different processing, packaging and storage conditions.', 'Faculty of Fisheries, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '1) To formulate and manufacture fish stick and fish ball from silver carp fish for better utilization\r\n2) To observe the effectiveness of some local gel strengthening ingradients such as white potato starch, mashed white potato, mashed red potato, esculent root, etc. on the quality of fish stick and fish ball.\r\n3) To disseminate the technology to the poor farmers through value addition\r\n4) To involve the rural women in income generating activities. ', 'Procedure of the methodology are given below: \r\n1) Raw material collection\r\n2) Preparation of fish stick and fish ball\r\n3) Proximate composition analysis\r\n4) Packaging\r\n5) Gel strength (gm/cm2)\r\n6) Study of shelf life of the products\r\n7) Sensory evaluation\r\n8) Biochemical parameters\r\n9) Microbiological analysis\r\n10) Training of the fish farmers\r\n11) Involvement of rural women', 'Silver carp fish stick and fish ball in household level will generate additional income for commercial fisherman. The socio-economic implications would be favourable such as i) both urban and rural consumer would show interest towards the products. ii) Successful production will raise the price of raw material so that fishermen will get higher return of the catch iii) This will improve the livelihood of poor fishermen iv) People will get better nutrition at cheaper price.', 'Fish Stick, Fish ball, Silver carp, Shelf life', 'BAURES', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish Processing', 'Silver carp', '', '', ''),
(2836, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Management', 'Project', 'Experimental Pond Unit assessment in Bangladesh.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-01-2012', '31-12-2013', '01-01-2012', '31-12-2013', '1.	Evaluate ponds in North central and Southeast region of Bangladesh and Eastern North Carolina for their physical, Chemical and Biological characteristics during a grow out. \r\n2.	Evaluate the ability of BAU to complete all of these measures. \r\n', '', '', 'Fisn, Pond, ', 'USAID', 4500000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Pond Assessment', 'Fish', '', '', ''),
(2837, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department ofFisheries Management', 'Project', 'Potentiality for the development of an integrated prawn farming system in Bangladesh for sustainable livelihoods of the rural poor', 'Phulpur and Gouripur Upazilas of Mymensingh district', 'High', 'Applied', '', '01-09-2005', '31-08-2006', '01-09-2005', '31-08-2006', '1) To understand the socio-economic, environmental and technological aspects of integrated prawn farming.\r\n2) To identify the constraints of integrated prawn farming and how its impact on the livelihoods of the rural poor.\r\n3) To develop a technology package on prawn-fish-rice farming for the recommendation to the poor farmers.', '1) Questionnaire development and conducted survey.\r\n2) Participatory Rural Appraisal (PRA)\r\n3) Cross Check Interviews\r\n4) Participatory research\r\n5) Data analysis', 'Freshwater prawn farming is mostly concentrated in southeast Bangladesh mainly Khulna, Bagerhat and Satkhira districts. Prawn farming is not widespread in other parts of Bangladesh due to lack of research and extension works. Although a new prawn farming system is in the process in Mymensingh area in recent years, farmers could not culture prawn with fish and rice due to lack of technical knowledge. Therefore, to sustaining livelihoods of the poor farmers, it is important to know the socio-economic, environmental and technological aspects of integrated prawn farming. Aside from a better understanding of prawn farming, it is necessary to develop a technology package on prawn-fish-rice farming for the recommendation to the poor farmers. In addition, it is important to identify the factors which may be important in maintaining a favourable condition for vulnerable farmers that enable livelihoods to be sustained through integrated prawn farming.', 'Prawn, PRA, Participatory research', 'BAURES', 75000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Integrated Farming System Development', 'Shrimp, Fish, Rice', '', '', ''),
(2838, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'A Genetic Dissection of Traits Required for Sustainable water use in Rice Using Genome wide Association Studies. ', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-01-2012', '31-12-2015', '01-01-2012', '31-12-2015', 'To identify genes, along with their physiological function and the pathways they operate in, which in hence adaptability to water efficient production for breeding targeted to sustainability, furthermore to provide the research community with a set of genomically characterized rice land-race for south and south-east Asia irrigated environments to be used in future association mapping studies. ', '', '', 'Soil, Rice, ', 'IRRI', 3300000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Rice production, Land-race', 'Soil', '', '', ''),
(2839, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Anatomy &amp; Histology', 'Project', 'Evaluation of Reproductive Performance of Black Bengal Goat in Arsenic paluted area of Mymensingh district. ', 'Mymensingh district, BAU Lab. ', 'High', 'Evaluation /Impact studies ', 'On-going', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2013', 'To investigate the effect of arsenic on the reproductive tract on Black Bengal Goat in arsenic affected area of Mymensingh district. Research work should able to predict either the present status of arsenic in surface water or drinking water in Mymensingh district. Would significant effects on the reproductive performance of Black Bengal goats or not. ', '', '', 'Goat, Animal, Arsenic.', 'BAU', 240000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Production', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(2840, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Biological control of Bacterial wilt of Tomato with strain(s) of Bacillus sp.', 'Department of plant pathology, Seed pathology laboratory, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-10-1998', '30-09-2001', '01-10-1998', '30-09-2001', '1) Determination of antagonistic effect of (Bacillus spp.) on the Pseudomonas solanacearum in vitro and in-vivo.\r\n2) Evaluation of the cultivar reaction of tomato against bacterial wilt (P. solanacearum)\r\n3) Determination of the effect of different inoculation techniques to the development of bacterial wilt of tomato.', '(a) Materials: Different culture media for multiplication of bacteria, seeds of different varieties of tomato, pots, soils, chemicals, glasswares, inoculation device, inoculation chamber, hand globes, incubator of controlled temperature, refrigerator\r\n(b) Design of experiments\r\nVariety = 5\r\nReplication = 4\r\nStatistical Method = RBD and DMRT\r\ni) Collection of inoculum of Bacillus spp.\r\nii) Isolation of Bacteria\r\niii) Preparation of media\r\niv) Preparation of bacterial suspension\r\nv) Interaction of Pseudomonas solanacearum and Bacillus spp. in-vitro\r\nvi) Interaction of P. solanacearum and Bacillus spp. in-vivo\r\nvii) Cultivar reaction to bacterial wilt of tomato\r\nviii) Inoculation technique', 'Several workers made an attempt of chemical and cultural control of bacterial wilt of tomato, but they failed to achieve a remarkable success. Chemical control of plant pathogen is expensive because of their high prize and import from abroad. Some worker have, however, reported varying degrees of success in developing tomato varieties resistant to bacterial wilt. Some possibilities of biological management of bacterial wilt of tomato were studied by antagonistic agents. Use of chemicals are hazardous due to long residual effect and causes environmental pollution. For these and other reasons, researchers in academic institution and private companies have interested their efforts to develop non-chemical approaches to plant disease control. So the control of pathogenic bacteria with antagonistic micro organisms would have been considered.', 'Tomato, P. solanacearum, Bacillus spp., Isolation of Bacteria', 'BAURES', 419000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Crop protection', 'Tomato', '', '', ''),
(2841, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Pathology', 'Project', 'Conventional and Molecular methods for characterization of clostridium perfringens,  the causal agent of necrotic enteritis in chicken with experimental pathological study by local isolate. ', 'Department of Pathology lab. BAU.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-01-2013', '31-12-2014', '01-01-2013', '31-12-2014', '', '', '', 'Chicken, Broiler  birds', 'BAU', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Broiler birds', 'Animals', '', '', ''),
(2842, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Microbiology and Hygiene', 'Project', 'Isolation, characterization and protective efficacy of Bacteriophage against Salmonella pullorum and Salmonella gallinerum. ', 'Microbiological Hygiene Lab. BAU.', 'High', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-01-2013', '30-06-2014', '01-01-2013', '30-06-2014', '1.	Prevalence study, isolate an identification and molecular characterization of salmonella pullorum and salmonella gallinarum.\r\n2.	Isolate and characterization of bacteriophage of salmonella pullorum and salmonella, gallinarum from environmental samples in different areas of Bangladesh.\r\n3.	Therapeutic efficacy of isolated bacteriophage against multitude resistant poultry salmonella in animal model.   \r\n', '', '', 'Animal', 'BAU', 300000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Animals', '', '', '');
