(2862, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Statistics', 'Project', 'Micro-credit Programmes of Different NGOs: A Comparative Study', 'Dhaka, Mymensingh, Sherpur, Netrokona and Kishoreganj districts(BRAC, Grameen Bank, PROSHIKA, ASA and CARE Bangladesh)', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '1.	To identify the structural difference between different micro-credit programmes run by five leading NGOs (BARCk, Grameen Bank, PROSHIKA, ASHA and CARE Bangladesh).\r\n2.	To understand and verify the feasibility of high interest rate and its setting mechanism by the selected NGOs.\r\n3.	To compare the management of default cases by different NGOs.\r\n4.	To evaluate the clients views regarding the credit programmes they are involved with and compare the results between different NGOs.\r\n5.	 To identify the efficient micro-credit programmes through development of selection criterion. \r\n', '', 'This study aims ot evaluate micro-credit programmes of five leading NGOs (BRAC, Grameen Bank, PROSHIKA, ASA and CARE Bangladesh) in terms of their structural differences, interest rate, management of default cases, clients views towards the programmes. The final objective of this project is to develop some selection criteria to identify the efficient programme. The expected sample size of this project is 400 to be collected from the selected NGOs operating micro-credit programmes in Dhaka, Mymensingh, Sherpur, Netrokona and Kishoreganj districts. So far 250 respondents of the selected NGOs were interviewed. The preliminary results suggest that about 14% of the respondents received loan of Tk. 5000 or less and another 42% received loan between Tk. 5001-10000. Seventy five percent of the respondents took loan before. Around 50% of the respondents took the first loan less than five years ago. About 80% of the respondents did not know the actual interest rate. More than 50% of the respondents took loan for business purposes. About 75% of the respondents reported that the NGO field workers were motivated. Sixteen percent of the respondents reported that they needed some ones request to get loan. About 90% of the respondents were satisfied with the NGO activities and 50% thought that the interest rate was right. The project is halfway through the approved duration. It is expected that most of the objectives will be achieved after completion of the project.', 'Micro-credit programmes, NGOs, ', 'BAU', 239280, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Evaluation', 'Micro-credit Programmes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
