(2942, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of pathology', 'Project', 'Epidemiology and modelling of the spread of highly pathogenic avian influenza virus in Bangladesh', 'Department of pathology', 'High', 'Applied', '', '01-06-2003', '31-05-2004', '01-06-2003', '31-05-2004', '1) To develop a thematic risk map using GIS technology\r\n2) To assess spatial and temporal risk factors\r\n3) To investigate wild migratory and domestic water fowls as potential reservoir of HPAI\r\n4) To develop a risk model based on identified risk factors.', '1) Plan of action\r\n2) Data collection\r\n3) Spatial data\r\n4) Temporal data', 'Highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) was first reported in Bangladesh in 2007. Since then the disease has become entrenched in the poultry industry of Bangladesh. There have been five waves of HPAI outbreaks with distinct seasonality. It still remains to be answered which climatic factors lead to seasonal perpetuation of HPAI outbreaks, what risk factors contribute to geographic intensity of HPAI outbreaks and what serves as the reservoir for the persistence of HPAI in Bangladesh. Based on the existing knowledge a set of putative risk factors for incursion and spread of HPAI were defined. These included climatic factors (temperature, rain fall &amp; humidity), poultry density, human population density, growth centre, number of rural markets, number of major roads and highways, abundance of water bodies, and domestic duck population. Fecal/respiratory swabs were collected from migratory birds and ducks. Preliminary analysis of the meteorological data and temporal outbreak data suggest that low ambient temperature, minimum rainfall and low relative humidity favor HPAI outbreak in Bangladesh. The weighted scores of each risk factor will be utilized to develop a risk map model to identify high risk, low risk and no risk areas of the country. Preliminary analysis of the spatial data on other risk factors, which have been collected from the case and control Upazilas were showed that poultry density, population density, growth center and percentage of water bodies have a significant effect on the transmissions of HPAI in Bangladesh. Laboratory analysis of faecal or cloacal swab samples from migratory and domestic waterfowl yielded 16 samples from migratory birds containing haemagglutinating agents and on the other hand, 21 samples from domestic ducks had haemagglutinating agents. Among HA positive samples 4 from migratory birds and 7 from domestic ducks were AI Type-A positive by RT-PCR. Further work is in progress.', 'GIS map, HPAI, Spatial and temporal', 'MOSICT', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Increase Rice Production and Food Security', 'Avian Influenza', '', '', ''),
