(3098, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery', 'Project', 'Appropriate and efficient hand tools for small farming system in Bangladesh.', 'Goneshampur, Muktagachha and  Modhupur under Mymensingh district.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-04-2001', '30-03-2003', '01-04-2001', '30-03-2003', '1.	To review the current status of agricultural hand tools available in the high potential area.\r\n2.	To identify criteria to improve the design and manufacture of hand tools.\r\n3.	To evaluate the hand tools in terms of:\r\na.	Functionality,\r\nb.	Convenience of use,\r\nc.	Energy demand,\r\nd.	Ease of manufacture, and\r\ne.	Cost.\r\n4.	Extension of improved design into the high potential production areas of Bangladesh. \r\n', '1.	A participatory rural appraisal survey will be conducted to select the research sites and hand tools to be included in the field test.\r\n2.	Three sites namely Goneshampur, Muktagachha and  Modhupur area will be selected to conduct the field.\r\n3.	A  workshop will be arranged in the department of farm power and Machinery, BAU, Mymensingh.\r\n4.	One student from postgraduate level will carry out the thesis work under this project program. \r\n', '', 'Hand tools, Farming, production', 'BAURES', 150000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Farming', 'Hand tools', '', '', ''),
(3099, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of parasitology', 'Project', 'Epidemiology and pathology of Trichomonas gallinae a protozoan infection from common pigeon in Mymensingh', 'Laboratories of the Department of Parasitology and Department of pathology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2008', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2008', 'Epidemiological and pathological aspects of T. gallinae infection will be studied', 'About 300 domestic pigeons and squabs will be collected from different local markets of Mymensingh. In the present study the observations will be made on the samples collected from the upper digestive tract of domestic pigeon. For this at first the crop will be rinsed with physiological saline and will be examined with a phase contrast microscope for the presence of those flagellates.\r\nThe following method is also expected to give useful results. A cotton swab will be flufed up a bit and immersed in distilled water. The excess fluid will be removed and the swab will be inserted into the crop. All walls of the crop will be contacted by using a swirling motion with the swab which be then withdrawn and the fluid held in the cotton pressed on to a slide with the help of a spatula or blunt knife. The protozoa can be seen to move about in a some what jerky wobbling motion.\r\nCollected samples from the crop will be preserved and will be stained by the Giemsa''s method according to the procedures as described by Cable (1957) and morphology will be studied by the method of Abraham and Honigberg (1964). All the works will be carried out in the Department of pathology. Simultaneously severely infected pigeons will be slaughtered to find out the lesions produced by protozoa. Gross lesions observed in the slaughtered pigeons will be recorded. The representative tissues will be collected and histopathological studies will be carried out with the help of the department of pathology. The expected findings from the study for a period of 12 months will help to identify the risk factors of the protozoal infection and control strategies will be identified and disseminated to the veterinarians and farmers through extension workers.', '', 'Pigeon, Epidemiological, pathological', '', 100000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Livestock production', 'Pigeon', '', '', ''),
(3100, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Effect of two levels of iso-nitrogenous inputs of cow and poultry manures on plankton production and Fish growth.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-11-1998', '31-10-2001', '01-11-1998', '31-01-2001', '1.	To determine the composition of the manures.\r\n2.	To determine the physical and chemical parameters of water.\r\n3.	To evaluate the effects of two levels of isonitrogenous inputs of cow the poultry manures on quality and quantity of plankton production.\r\n4.	To evaluate the effects of the same on fish growth, stocking at a rate of 8000/ha in the ration of 30 (calta catla); 40 (labeo rohita), 30 (Cyprinus carpio)\r\n5.	To evaluate the effects of three stocking densities using one level of the doses which gave the best results in plankton production and fish growth. \r\n', 'The main Methodology of the research Project have been given below: \r\na.	Material:\r\nb.	Design of Experiments:\r\nc.	Procedure to be followed in achieving stated objectives:\r\nd.	Data collection\r\ne.	Data analysis.\r\n', '', 'Cow, fish, Manure, Poultry', 'BAU-UGC', 335140, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Cow &amp; poultry manures and Fish growth', 'Agriculture', '', '', ''),
(3101, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Microbiology and hygiene', 'Project', 'Establishment of mosquito cell line (C6/36) for the isolation and characterization of arbo-viruses prevalent in Bangladesh.', 'Cell culture laboratory, Department of Microbiology and Hygiene, BAU, Mymensingh ', 'High', 'Applied', '', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '1) Establishment and maintenance of mosquito''s cell line for the isolation of dengue and chikungunya viruses from the acute phase serum samples of the patients of Bangladesh and mosquitoes samples.\r\n2) Identification of the genome of viruses collected from the supernatant of the infected culture fluid by FAT. PA and RT-PCR.', '', 'Dengue is one of the most important mosquitoes borne virus disease of human population of the tropical and sub tropical countries of the world. The disease caused by a single standard positive sense, enveloped RNA virus of the genus flavivirus, family Flaviviridae. There are four ser-types of dengue viruses (DENV-1, DENV-2, DENV-3 and DENV-4). They are antigenically distinct from each other. The disease dengue, is transmitted by biting of the mosquitoes species Aedes aegypti and Aedes albopictus. The disease appeared in the form of epidemic in the year 2000 at Dhaka, Bangladesh. Since then it is appearing as a serious threat every year to the people of Bangladesh. Although the virus infect human population but it is difficult to grow the viruses in the human or other mammalian cell line. Mosquito cell line (C6/36) is the only cell line which is being used all over the world to isolate dengue viruses directly from the sera of dengue infected patients. For sero-types identification and molecular characterization of the virus isolates of Bangladesh large quantity of viruses are required and which is not possible without propagation of the viruses in the C6/36 cell line. Therefore, mosquito cell line has been established and given highest priority for detail study of dengue virus isolation in Bangladesh. A total of 171 serum samples were collected both from the acute and convalescent phase dengue suspected patients of Holy Family Red Cresent Medical College Hospital during the year 2007-2008. Of the 171 samples virus isolation was positive in from eight samples only in C6/36 cell line. The Bangladeshi isolates of dengue viruses revealed characteristic CPE in the C6/36 cell line. Presence of virus', 'Mosquito cell line, Arbo-viruses, Dengue', 'BAURES', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Animal Health Protection', 'Arbo-Viruses', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3102, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Medicine', 'Project', 'Epidemiological investigation of group B rota viruses in Animals and Humans in Bangladesh.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-05-2003', '30-04-2006', '01-05-2003', '30-04-2006', '1.	Study on the RNA electropherotyping of non A rota viruses of animals and humans from diarrheic stool specimens of animals and humans.\r\n2.	Development of molecular methods to characterize and classify antigenically diverse rotaviruses in animals and humans.\r\n', 'Sampling procedures, processing of samples: Faecal samples will be collected on random basis from the calves of the experimental areas. The available diarrhoeic faces will be collected first and followed by the available normal faces from young calves. After collection from rectum with all aseptic precautionary measures, the faecal materials will be kept in sterile, screw caped container. Phosphate buffers (PBS pH 7.4 ) will be mixed with each sample making 1:10 dilution by volume. The samples will be centrifuged at low speed centrifugation at 3000 rpm for 30 minutes. The supernatant will be collected, labelled properly and kept into deep freezer at 20 C until the samples are used for ds RNA extraction and PAGE analysis. ', '', 'Animals, Human, Rota virus', 'BAURES', 225000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Animals and Humans', '', '', ''),
(3103, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of farm power and machinery', 'Project', 'Feasibility of Poverty alleviation through production of Indigo in the small scale farming system in Madhupur areas.', 'Department of farm power and machinery, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-05-2003', '30-04-2006', '01-05-2003', '30-04-2006', '1) Overall literature review\r\n2) PRA on Indigo cultivation\r\n3) Multiplication method: Effect of NPK and Rhizobium inoculants on growth and nodulation in different sp., effect of plant spacing, moisture levels, cutting, fertilizer and irrigation effect, height and cutting intervals on growth and biomass production in Indigofera sp.\r\n4) Indigo processing system - Design and fabrication of the plant.\r\n5) Varietal screening: To study and evaluate the potential of Indigofera sp. for indigo recovery.\r\n6) Development of a physical model for indigo production in Bangladesh.\r\n7) Booklet preparation and training workshop.', '1) Internet searching will be done for overall literature review, journals and books available will be collected.\r\n2) Farmers in the upland areas who will be interested for Indigo plant cultivation will be selected for PRA survey.\r\n3) Leaf plant production trail with different species will be carried out in the farmers field.\r\n4) Indigo extraction process system will be constructed near to the farmers field for efficient indigo extraction\r\n5) Indigo will be extracted from different ages of leaves and plants.\r\n6) Time of harvesting of leaves to dipping into the process tank will be recorded and its influence on the amount of indigo will be determine.\r\n7) Influence of type of water on the amount of indigo yield will be verified.\r\n8) Agitation system in the process tank will be installed.\r\n9) Some trial with heating may be tried to know its influence on the amount of indigo extraction.\r\n10) Further modification of separation process of indigo from the process system will be studied.\r\n11) Physical characteristics such as plant diameter, plant height, growth rate, weight of leaves per cut, disease susceptibility, bulk density of indigo will be determined.\r\n12) Economic analysis will be carried out to forecast the benefit of the cultivation of indigo in comparison to the cultivation of other conventional crops.\r\n13) A workshop will be held to help transfer the knowledge gathered from the research to users, extension workers.', '', 'Poverty alleviation, Small scale farming system', 'BAURES', 225000, 0, 0, 'Report', 'Training', 0, 'Poverty Alleviation', 'Small scale farming', '', '', ''),
