(3199, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Irrigation and Water Management', 'Project', 'Improvement of irrigation system performance and assessment of irrigation water  quality at BAU, farm', 'BAU farm.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '1.	To determine of quantification of irrigation water used for rice and wheat.\r\n2.	To determine of ET for rice and wheat.\r\n3.	To determine of judicious irrigation scheduling.\r\n4.	To determination of crop water productivity for rice and wheat.\r\n5.	To reduction of conveyance loss and field loss.\r\n6.	To study the recharge and depletion characteristics of ground water, and\r\n7.	To determination of irrigation water quality parameters including arsenic.\r\n', 'The main Methodology of the research Project have been given below: \r\na.	Material:\r\nb.	Design of Experiments:\r\nc.	Procedure to be followed in achieving stated objectives:\r\nd.	Data collection\r\ne.	Data analysis.\r\n', '', 'Rice, Wheat, Crops, Irrigation, ground water, arsenic', 'BAURES', 200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Irrigation and Water Management', 'Crops', '', '', ''),
(3200, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery', 'Project', 'Development of power tiller operated zero tillage tools for multi crop seeding.', 'Department of FPM Laboratory and Wheat Research Center, Dinajpur.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1.	To develop power tiller operated zero tillage drill machine.\r\n2.	To make seed and fertilizer distribution arrangement with the toolbar frame.\r\n3.	To test the machine performance for wheat, maize and mung bean establishment.\r\n', 'The main Methodology of the research Project have been given below: \r\na.	Material:\r\nb.	Design of Experiments:\r\nc.	Procedure to be followed in achieving stated objectives:\r\nSearching of rare fruit germplasms and addition of new fruits in the fruit production\r\nsystem of Bangladesh is crucial now a day. Though the collection of fruit germplasm and variety development is very lengthy procedure but it will benefit to the researchers from the beginning. Our target is to the establishment of research area on fruits at SAU which could help us to incorporate new fruit crops in the fruit market of Bangladesh. However, the planned project will be undertaken with the following objectives.\r\nCollection and incorporation of rare, high valued and exotic fruit plants/planting materials in the existing germplasm centre of SAU.\r\nb.	Creation of research environments on fruits at SAU.\r\nc.	Assist to enhance fruit diversity in Bangladesh.\r\nd.	Improvement efforts directed to the development of new superior fruit plants.\r\ne.	Introduction and performance trial of two new fruit varieties (exotic melon) inside the\r\nexisting germplasm centre of SAU.\r\nInitiatives to conduct research and to release new fruit varieties of Bangladesh under the coverage of SAU.\r\ng. Transfer of technology and associated information regarding established germplasm centre to the researchers, breeders and producers of Bangladesh.\r\nd.	Data collection\r\ne.	Data analysis.\r\n', 'Zero tillage is defined as the operation of planting crops in previously unprepared soil by opening a narrow slot or band only of sufficient width and depth to obtain proper seed coverage. The traditional tillage methods have long resulted in exposed field surface, decrease soil fertility, serious water loss and soil erosion and increasingly worse ecological environment. In order to achieve sustainable development in agriculture it is now required to promote the systematized protective tillage techniques and implements for preservation of soil moisture suitable to intensive farming areas. The adoption of reduce tillage methods can offer significant environmental benefits while providing energy savings. No tillage and reduce tillage have been being used since ancient times as indigenous practices. Because farmer had not enough muscle force to prepare the land to a considerable area and depth by hand. When mechanical tillage system appeared farmers started believing that the more tillage you do, the more yields you get. But truth was that the more tillage you do the more erosion and soil degradation you get, especially in warmer area.\r\nLate planting is a major problem in most wheat producing area of Bangladesh. Late planting reduces the yield and efficiency of applied inputs to the crop. A linear decline in yield of 1-1.5% per day is observed when wheat is planted after the end of November irrespective of short or medium duration varieties. In this case increased nitrogen applications can not compensate for the decline in yield from late planting. The estimated total zero tillage in South Asia has been more than 5.6 I lakh ha in 2002-03 and about 1.07 lakh farmers are currently practicing this technologies in Indian sub-continent.\r\nLong turn-around time can be caused by excessive tillage, soil. moisture problems, lack of bullock or mechanical power for ploughing and other farm jobs like threshing and managing rice crop before preparing land for wheat.\r\nTherefore, this program has been undertaken to improve a power tiller operated zero tillage planter in terms of cost saving, eliminate delay planting and moisture conservation, as compared to conventional techniques through machinery application.\r\n', 'Wheat, Maize, Mung bean, fertilizer distribution, zero tillage, machine', 'BAURES', 198500, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Technical Knowledge', 'Crops', 'The zero tillage planting system is considered to bc., simpler and quicker than the present ploughing system without reducing the crop yields. Crops can be established without tillage. Due to less soil disturbance, biological activities of the soil micro organisms will be increased which ultimately improve the soil health. Cost of cultivation to be reduced and farmers will be benefited. Specifically following output will come out from this project:\r\n1)	Zero till toolbar frame fabricated\r\n2)	Seed and fertilizer distributor mechanism developed\r\n3)	Workshop arranged and final report Produced\r\nThis project will potentially contribute in the followingaspects \r\n1)	Improve soil health\r\n2)	Reduce crop establishment cost\r\n3)	Reduce soil erosion\r\n4)	Environmental friendly technology\r\n', 'Zhao-CZ (1989) run a project in Hubei, china and found that the zero tillage was more suitable for paddy soil under rice-wheat cropping system than the traditional tillage system.\r\nAlam et al. (1993) carried out an on-farm experiments at 34 locations in the Punjab. Pakistan, where wheat was direct drilled into rice stubble or sown using conventional methods and reported that the effect of zero tillage vs. conventional tillage was significant in the 2&quot;d and 3''d years and overall zero tillage increased wheat yield by 10%.\r\nGajendra et al. (2000) carried out a research project in a rice-Wheat crop rotation in India and found a promising result. They reported that the zero tillage technology saves cost for land preparation and also increase crop yield by an average of 15%.\r\nPandey et al. (2003) carried out a study among 34 cultivator households to examine the impact of zero tillage in terms of cost structure, retune and resource use efficiency in India. They observed impressive cost saving by 20% under zero tillage in wheat.\r\nTherefore, this program has been undertaken to improve a power tiller operated zero tillage planter in terms of cost saving, eliminate delay planting and moisture conservation, as compared to conventional techniques through machinery application.\r\n', ''),
