(3366, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Technology', 'Project', 'Preparation of quality smoke cured product of some fresh water fish species and the effects of salt concentrations and smoke temperature on their shelf life and quality at ambient, refrigerated and frozen storage temperature.', 'Department of Fisheries Technology Laboratory, BAU', 'Medium', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '1) To develop hot smoke ready to eat quality cured fishery product to be prepared from Oreochromis niloticus, Wallago attu, Mystus aor, Clarias batrachus, Hypophthalmichthys molitrix, Cyprinus carpio to establish its potentiality and utility.\r\n2) To find out the effect of different brine concentrations &amp; smoke temperature and of smoking time on the product development.\r\n3) To study the quality of the products and shelf life of those products at ambient temperature, refrigerated temperature and at frozen storage.\r\n4) To study the nutritive value and bacterial load of the cured products.\r\n5) To study the acceptability of the products by panel test and sensory tests in large scale to be introduced among public.', 'The hot smoke curing of different fish would involve the following major steps of operation:\r\n1) Preparation of raw material or preparation of fish.\r\n2) Brining\r\n3) Drying\r\n4) Smoking\r\n5) Cooling', 'Generally, there are two methods of smoking fish - cold and hot smoking, which give different products. Hot smoking means curing fish by smoking at a temperature of 60 - 70 c at some stage in the process in order to cook the flesh. Hot smoked fish do not require further cooking before consumption. Both fatty fish and white fish can be used for the smoking purpose showing variable shelf life. There are reports of having longer shelf life of about 6 months of hot smoked cured fish and even longer with vacuum packaging. In tropical developing fisheries, smoking is used not only to impart desirable flavour of the products but with an aim to use as a means of fish remaining unsold after retail display and high fish catch during rainy season when drying of fish is impossible. At this stage, fish can be smoked for a short period of few weeks of time to up to few months if the hot smoke cured fish is vacuum sealed and frozen stored for use in lean period. The shelf life and the quality of the smoked fish product depends on different factors such as salt concentration of the brine solution, types of fish, dipping time, temperature of brine, smoke temperature, type of wood/saw dust for smoking etc.', 'Quality cured fishery product, Shelf life, Ambient temperature', 'BAU-UGC', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Preservation technology development', 'Fish', '', '', '');
