(3413, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Technology', 'Project', 'Field application of local herbal pesticides as complete replacement of harmful chemical pesticides in dried fish in sidr affected Dublarchar of the Sunderbans.', 'Fish processing Laboratory, BAU and the dry fish processing zones of the Sunderbans.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1. To determine the efficacy of several local herbs like neem, garlic, Biskatali, hijal, shathi, malkata, kachu, marigold and nishinda and two spices - red chili and turmeric in deterring/repelling pests and insects in dried fish.\r\n2. To determine the individual or combined effects of both the powder (direct application) and extracts of these herbal pesticides.\r\n3. To determine the field dosages of the pesticides for deterring/repelling a blow fly, Diptera sp., a beetle, Dermestes sp. and a mite, Necrobia sp.\r\n4) To develop field application protocol of selected herbal drugs with the involvement of stakeholders of sidr and aila affected Dublarchar of the Sunderbans.\r\n5. To develop the skill of fisher women and socially excluded fishers to prepare herbal pesticides for local use.\r\n6. To detect the impacts of these botanical pesticides on dried fish quality and consumer''s acceptance.\r\n7. To determine the cost profit ratio and realization of profit due to application of herbal drugs in dried fish.', '1. Test plants\r\n2. Test insects\r\na. Blowfly maggot\r\nb. Dermestid beetle\r\nc. Mite\r\n3. Collection and rearing of insect\r\n4. Preparation of plant dust and extaacts\r\na. Collection and processing of plant materials\r\nb. Preparation of plant dust\r\nc. Preparation of plant extracts\r\n5. Preparation of stock solution\r\n6. Disinfestations of dried fish\r\n7. Direct toxicity test by Tropical Application Method\r\n8. Repellency test\r\n9. Participatory determination of dose for field application\r\n10. Participatory study of impact of herbal pesticide on texture and taste of dried fish\r\n11. Cost and profit analysis of pesticide application\r\n12. Statistical analysis.', 'About 20% of the total fish caught in Bangladesh are sun dried and mostly consumed in the domestic market annually. One of the major problems associated with the sun drying of fish is the infestation of the products by the blow fly and beetle larvae. Various harmful chemical pesticides have been used for a long time, but they have serious lethal effects on consumers body. Botanical pesticides are the alternative to synthetic chemical pesticides since these compounds are biodegradable and less persistant in the environment. Plant products are considered to be non toxic to mammals, birds and fish. There are about 2000 plant species seem to possess pest control properties. In Bangladesh, some of the possible herbs are neem, garlic, bishkatali, hijal, kachu, malkata etc. Some spices like turmeric and red chili and citrus extracts can be good preservatives against insect infestation in fish.', 'Herbal pesticides, Repellency test, Disinfestations of dried fish', 'BAU-UGC', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Effect of herbal pesticides in fish drying', 'Fish', '', '', ''),
(3414, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Technology', 'Project', 'Studies on the quality problem of Shrimp at different stages in value chain', 'Khulna area and Faculty of Fisheries, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2010', '31-12-2011', '01-01-2010', '31-12-2011', '1) To identify causes of quality losses at different stages in value chain.\r\n2) To evaluate the quality loss of shrimp due to injecting of foreign materials through push and use of STP and other chemicals.\r\n3) To evaluate the quality loss of shrimp products due to repeated freezing and thawing\r\n4) To investigate the shelf life of different shrimp products.', '1) Survey on qualitative and quantitative spoilage of shrimp at various stages of handling and transportation.\r\n2) Investigation on inserting foreign material through pushing and quality assessment.\r\n3) Investigation on the use STP and chemicals and quality assessment.\r\n4) Investigation on the repeated freezing and thawing.\r\n5) Shelf life of the value added shrimp products. ', 'Shrimp is a highly perishable commodity. The importing countries particularly, the EU countries, USA and Japan are highly conscious about food hygiene and safety. These countries will not accept any food item with doubtful quality in respect of its freshness, hygiene and safety for human health. In Bangladesh, the shrimp export volume is very low and stagnated around 73000 MT in 2007-2008. The processing industries are producing and exporting a number of value added products such as head on shell on shrimp with claws. There is common phenomenon in all processing industries that the processors buy shrimp abundantly in cheaper season when the price of the raw materials is low. During the lean period, the processors buy shrimp and make block frozen for certain period. As soon as when the buyers place order for different value added products, at that time the frozen blocks are thawed and produce different types of value added products. There is no report available on Bangladeshi shrimp about quality loss during repeated freezing and thawing. The present state of the art makes room for wastages of the valuable shrimp resource at each point of the supply chain. It is suspected that the loss, both in quality and in quantity, must be substantial leading to a significant economic loss also. In the face of extremely low production, any loss of this very valuable exportable resource is most undesirable. However, dependable information to quantify such losses at various points of shrimp handling is lacking. ', 'quality loss of shrimp products, shelf life of different shrimp products.', 'BAU-UGC', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish production and quality management', 'Shrimp', '', '', ''),
