(3427, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics', 'Project', 'Production of sex reversed female shing (Heteropneustes fossilis)', 'Mini hatchery cum breeding complex and wet laboratory, BAU', 'Medium', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '1) Optimizing the dose of feminizing hormone for producing sex reversed female individual of shing.\r\n2) Optimizing the duration of administering the feminizing hormone.', '1) Collection, maintenance and induction breeding in H. fossilis\r\n2) Experiment to optimize the dose of feminizing hormones.\r\n3) Experiment to optimize the treatment duration of feminizing hormones', 'In natural condition, shing attains sexual maturity at the end of first year of its life. The females are considerably larger weighing more than two times of the males of same age and male-female ratio is also not 50:50 in a population, the number of male being much less compared to the female. Both the natural and laboratory reared population of H. fossilis have been reported to be female biased (2 female: 1 male). Reasonably higher growth rate, very high market price and demand make female an appropriate candidate for aquaculture. So, availability of sex reversed female shing seed will enhance its production and fulfill the animal protein demand at least to some extent.', 'sex reversed female shing, feminizing hormones.', 'BAU-UGC', 239840, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish production', 'Shing fish', '', '', ''),
(3428, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Culture and production of house fly larvae and spirulina using poultry waste and their use as food for catfish post larvae.', 'Live food culture laboratory, Nutrition laboratory, Department of Aquaculture, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-09-2005', '31-08-2007', '01-09-2005', '31-08-2007', '1) To analyze the physio chemical properties of poultry waste.\r\n2) To produce maggot using poultry waste.\r\n3) To produce spirulina in tanks and polythene bags using residue after producing maggot\r\n4) To determine the chemical composition as proximate composition of cultured maggot and spirulina\r\n5) To feed maggot and spirulina through feed and or as live feed to Clarias batrachus post larvae.\r\n6) To ensure continuous supply of spirulina to the farmers through mass culture.\r\n7) To remove aquatic pollution surrounding the target poultry farms\r\n8) To improve the environmental and socio economic condition of the rural people living in and around the farm areas\r\n9) To improve the fish culture status in the study area. ', 'Fly larvae will be grown in poultry waste in tray. The organic nutrients in the form of carbon and nitrogen will be used by them, nutrient loads will be at least 40% reduced. Then spirulina will be grown in the residue of PW in the laboratory. Spirulina platensis will be checked during culture to maintain purity under microscope following the keys of Edmondson (1959), Bold and Wynne (1978). Mass production of spirulina will be done in tanks of 500 L capacity. It will be collected by a plankton net and dried in oven or spray dried, and will be stored in the freeze for future use. In the lab condition, 30% fish meal protein will be partially replaced by spirulina in the feed of catfish post larvae and maggot will be fed directly. Fish meal protein will be replaced upto 100% by spirulina and maggot using six different treatments i.e. treatment 1 (control), treatment 2 (20% spirulina+ 75% fish protein), treatment 3 (50% spirulina + 50% fish protein), treatment 4 (75% spirulina + 25% fish protein), treatment 5 (100% spirulina), treatment 6 (50% maggot + 50% feed with spirulina and fish meat) and treatment 7 (10% maggot). Other ingredients will be added following the procedure of Habib et al. (2001). The proximate composition of maggot, spirulina, prepared feeds and cultured fish will be done.', 'At present, there are about 90,000-100,00,000 poultry farms producing approximately 120 million birds every year in Bangladesh. These birds are releasing a huge amount of dropings as poultry waste. It contains high organic nutrients and chemical oxygen demand (COD) causing environmental degradation and pollution around the farm area. This waste is not waste, it is our national health if we use it properly. It may be used to grow maggot and the residue may be used to grow spirulina platensis. The fly larvae maggot contains high protein, lipid, minerals, amino acid, polyunsaturated fatty acids and vitamins. The research work will also bring a long term benefit in at least two ways 1) by producing maggot and spirulina and 2) by creating pollution free environment for the nation. For microalgae culture, the inorganic standard media is very expensive. The proposed research will be helpful to establish inexpensive/low cost medium for maggot and spirulina as well as other important microalgae production in aquaculture systems in Bangladesh. This type of development is very essential to bioremediate the waste.', 'House fly larvae, Catfish food, Spirulina, maggot', 'BAURES', 150000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Catfish food management', 'House fly larvae', '', '', ''),
(3429, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Technology', 'Project', 'Production of fish sauce from low cost small fresh water fish and their qualitative evaluation', 'Fish Processing laboratory, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '1) To identify the suitable low cost fresh water fish species and other aquatic animals including crustaceans and molluscs for fermentation.\r\n2) To optimize a fermentation method best suited under Bangladesh condition by monitoring the bacteriological and biochemical changes during fermentation process.\r\n3) To characterize the fermented fish product on the basis of organoleptic, bacteriological and biochemical parameters.\r\n4) To investigate shelf life of fermentation fish product by determining organoleptic and biochemical aspects of quality changes and microflora in the fermented product.\r\n5) To investigate the consumer acceptability of fermented fish product by test panel procedure.', '1) Collection of fish samples\r\n2) Proximate analysis of fish samples\r\n3) Production of fish sauce\r\n4) Qualitative analysis of fermented fish sauce\r\ni) Organoleptic characteristics\r\nii) Biochemical characteristics\r\nBacteriological characteristics\r\n5) Consumer acceptability test\r\n6) Shelf life study of fermented fish sauce', 'In Bangladesh volume of fermented fish product is very insignificant except that of semi-fermented fish product &quot;Chepa shutki&quot; or &quot;shidol shutki&quot; but the product like fish sauce is not produced at all. Whereas, fish sauce is part and parcel of preparation of many oriental foods. It can be added with vegetables to enhance the food value of the dishes. All the fish sauces being sold in Bangladesh are imported. But there is great scope for the production of fermented fish sauce locally. Many small fish species from both fresh water and marine water are underutilized or not utilized economically, that can be used for the production of fish sauce. Advantages of preparing fish sauce are its simple technology and very low capital investment. Currently, more attention has been given to improving traditional fermented fish products in order to increase the availability of low cost protein food for local consumption in many developing countries. Therefore, it would be worthwhile to conduct an investigation on the feasibility of producing fermented fish sauce in Bangladesh.', 'fish sauce, microflora , organoleptic, fermentation method', 'BAU-UGC', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish processing', 'Fresh water fish', '', '', ''),
