(3433, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries', 'Project', 'Physico-Chemical Condition and Plankton Population of three Fish Ponds in Gazipur.', '', 'High', 'Applied', '', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3434, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Planting Time Effects on Growth Productivity and Seed Quality of Slender Grain Rice', '', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', 'To examine the effect of planting time on growth, yield and seed quality of newly released slender grain rice variety. ', 'Field study was conducted during the rainy season (Aman) of 2008 at Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University. The experiment was designed as a randomized complete block with three replications treatments were consisting of seven planting time of newly released slender grain rice variety BU dhan 1. The planting times of the variety were 1 July, 1 August, 15 August, 1 September, 15 September and 1 October. Finally, growth, yield and seed quality were recorded for analysis of variance (ANOVA) and the means were compared according to Duncans Multiple Range Test (Gomez and Gomez, 1985).', 'The now variety BUdhan 1 is most productive when it is planned on August 15. Other date of plantings before and after that date reduced the yield of the variety. The variety seems to be susceptible to produce a large number of sterile spikelets which needs be minimized to enhance the grain yield. Further, the variety has lodging tendency which also restrict to explore the yield potential. Therefore, other crop management practices should be developed so that the variety can resist to a certain degree to lodging under adverse climatic conditions. ', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3435, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Agricultural use of Household Waste in Tomato Cultivation', '', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', 'The study was proposed with the overall objective of recycling of embedded nutrients of household waste, chicken manure and cow dung in agriculture using tomato as a test crop. The specific objectives were: (i) to determine the effect of household waste on the yield of tomato, (ii) to assess the potential of household waste to supply N, P and K to tomato, and (iii) to quantify their effects for the improvement of soil properties.', 'Household waste collection and composting: Household wastes from BSMRAU campus was collected, sorted and composted and then used for tomato cultivation and the performance was compared with chicken manure (CM) and cow dung (CD). Background nutrient concentrations of household waste compost (HWC), CM, CD and field soils (FS) were estimated.\r\nExperimentation: Two experiments (one pot and one field) were conducted using 11 treatments with 3 replications. The treatments of pot experiment were:  (1) control; (2) Recommended doses of  N, P and  K; (3) HWC: Fs (10:90); (4) HWC: FS (20:80); (5) HWC: FS (30:70); (6) CM: FS (10:90); (7) CM: FS (20:80); (8) CM: FS (30:70); (9) CD: FS (10:90); (10) CD: FS (20:80); and (11) CD: FS (30:70).\r\nStatistical analysis: SPSS version 10.0 statistical software was used to analyze the data. One-way-ANOVA and Univariate analysis were performed. Means were separated by LSD. 95% confidence level was used to get the significant difference. \r\n', 'Two experiment were conducted using 11 treatments with 3 replications during February to May 2009 to quantify the potential of household waste compost, chicken manure and cow dung to produce tomato yield, to supply nutrients especially P to tomato (BARI hybrid tomato 4) and their effects on the improvement of soil properties.\r\n\r\nTreatments containing different levels of organic wastes significantly improved the pH and OM status of residual soils as well as enhanced the fertility i.e. treatments significantly increased N, P and K contents in soils. The study revealed that application of different organic wastes in combination with inorganic fertilizer yield and nutrient uptake of tomato can be improved. It means soil fertility and crop productivity can be improved which in turns ensure the sustainability of production systems. \r\n', 'Tomato, Household Waste, N, P and K, Soil properties. ', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3436, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of fisheries management', 'Project', 'Artificial Propagation and rearing of an indigenous fish species, Rani, Botia Dario', 'Fisheries Field Complex, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2010', '1) To determine the effective dose of carp pituitary gland and HCG as the inducing agents to breed Botia dario;\r\n2) To study the fertility rate, hatching rate and embryonic development process of this species;\r\n3) To study the effects of different natural and artificial feeds on the growth and survival of larvae for rearing them up to the stockable size.', 'The brood fish of Botia dario will be collected from different places of Mymensingh district for breeding purpose. As soon as the fish reaches the ripe stage, they will be brought to the hatchery and injected with HCG and carp pituitary extract at different doses to find out the appropriate hormone dose for inducing ovulation. The eggs will be fertilized with milt from male rani and placed to the hatching jar for incubation. The hatching jar will be supplied with aeration to ensure sufficient oxygen to the developing embryos. Different methods and techniques will be applied to increase the hatching success of the fertilized eggs on trial and error basis. Time and temperature will be recorded. Embryonic developmental progress will be studied as per method followed by Binoy Chakraborty, 2004. The spawn will be transferred to the well prepared nursery pond to observe their survival and growth rate with different ingredients rich supplemental diet. After a period of two months, the fingerlings will be released in grow out ponds. Monthly growth rate, length weight relationship, fecundity, average daily weight gain, specific growth rate, water quality parameters etc. will also to be studied. ', 'According to IUCN (2000), out of total 266 number of living fish species in Bangladesh, 12 are critically endangered, 28 endangered and 12 are vulnerable and more are under increasing threat for sustainability. Rani is one of the endangerted species. I believe that it will be possible to develop an appropriate potential mechanism for artificial propagation of Rani through hormonal manipulation and use of various hatchery devices. Well planned research activities may lead to resolve the complicated reproductive process of Rani fish.', 'Rani, Botia Dario, Binoy Chakraborty, HCG', 'BAU-UGC', 200000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish Production', 'Rani and Botia Dario', '', '', ''),
(3437, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries', 'Project', 'Dietary Mineral Requirement of Mrigel Fish (Cirrhinus Cirrhosus)', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '1.	To know optimum dietary mineral requirement of mrigel fish.\r\n2.	To evaluate growth performances of mrigel fish feeding diets with various mineral levels.\r\n3.	To evaluate the effect of dietary minerals on chemical composition of flesh and bone of mrigel fish.\r\n', 'The experiment was conducted in cages, placed in a pond of aboujt 80 dec size. The cages were made of bamboo stick, covered with a net and the size of the cage was I m3. Four experimental diets containing about 30% protein has been formulated with different ingredients. Diet I was without Ca and P supplements. Diets 2-4 were supplied with only Ca (0.5%), only P (0.5%) and both Ca and P, respectively. The fry of mrigel fish (Cirrhinus cirrhosis) of average weight 2.2 g were stocked at a rate of 40 fry/cage and each of the experimental diets was supplied to 3 replicate groups of fish.\r\nThe proximate composition of experimental diets and fish were analyzed according to the methods given in association of official analytical chemists (AOAC, 1980). The mineral composition of experimental fish was analyzed according to the method described by Hossain and Furuichi (2000a). Data were analyzed statistically.\r\n', 'The result of this study showed that mean final weight gain (%) of mrigel fed diet 1 (without Ca and P supplement) were significantly lower than the fish fed diet 4 with Ca and P supplement. A dietary Ca supplementation in Diet 2 could not increase the growth, however, a dietary P supplementation in diet 3 improved the growth of mrigel, which was similar to that of the fish fed diet 4. The FCR values were lower, i.e. better, in fish feed diet 3 and 4. The highest survival (%) was observed in mrigel fed diet 3 and lowest in diet 2.\r\n\r\nIn the present study the growth of mrigel was significantly lower in fish fed diet I and diet 2, respectively, which indicate that a deletion of Ca and P from practical diets impair poor growth in mrigel and only dietary Ca supplement cannot improve the growth.  These results indicated that dietary P also necessary for better feed performance in mrigel. Variation in dietary treatment did not affect the whole body chemical composition of fish. Therefore, from the growth and fed utilization data it is evident that dietary P is necessary for mrigel, however, Ca may be dispensable. \r\n', 'Mrigel fish, Mineral, Fish', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3438, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy and Environment.', 'Project', 'Influence of Tree Leaves as Green Manure on Crop Productivity and Soil Properties at Different Nitrogen Levels.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '1.	To investigate the effect of incorporation of different tree leaves on yield of maize.\r\n2.	To determine the optimum nitrogen dose in combination with the different tree leaves added condition, and\r\n3.	To examine the soil properties changes due to the application of leaves of different tree species.\r\n', 'The experiment was conducted at the research farm of BSMRAU during October 2008 to June 2009. The design of the experiment was split-plot where leaves of eight different tree species namely cassia seamia, gliricidia sepium, swietenia macrophylla, Leucanea leucocephala, Artocarpus heterophyllus, Dallbergia sissoo, Azadirachata indica and Eucalyptus camalduloecies were arranged in main plots and tree different  doses of N (o, 50 and 100% of recommendation) were distributed to sub-plots. There was also a control treatment where well decomposed cowdung instead of tree leaves was applied along with full N dose. Maize growth, yield and yield contributing characters were recorded. Top soil pH, organic carbon (%), total nitrogen (%), available P (ppm), S (ppm) and caption exchangeable capacity (meq/100g) were determine3d following standard methods.', 'The soil properties were changed in a positive direction, where the values for all the measured parameters were higher in tree leaves applied treatment s  than those of initial soils. The highest soil organic C (0.93%), available P (19.12 ppm) and CEC (18.87 meq) and were recorded in G. Sepium, while maximum total N (0.093%) was found in L. Leucocephala. The findings indicate that tree leaves cou7ld be potentially used as  green manure to improve soil fertility and to increase crop production. Fast growing tree species may be used as fertilizer tree to sustain crop production and to save inorganic N fertilizer use.\r\n\r\nTree leaves could be used as green manure and application of tree leaves along with N fertilizer would be more efficient in not only to increase crop productivity but also to improve soil fertility and to save chemical N fertilizer.\r\n', 'Tree leaves, Green manure, crop productivity,  soil properties, Nitrogen levels, ', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3439, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Effect of Organic Manure and Crop Residue Management on soil Properties and Crop Performance under Wheat-Mungbean-T. aman Cropping Pattern', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', 'To find the impact of cow dung, poultry manure and crop residues incorporation on soil properties and performance of different crops of wheat-mung bean- t. aman cropping pattern.', 'The experiment was conducted in factorial randomized completely block design with two factors and three replications. Treatments for factor A were: c0- crop residue not incorporated and C1- crop residue incorporated and for factor B (Fertilizer management). Recommended dose of N, P, K, S, Mg, Zn and B, T1- Cow dung at 10 t/ha + recommended dose of chemical fertilizer minus nutrient content of organic manure at 40 % Mineralization (R-M), T2- Cow dung at 5 t/ha + (R-M), T3- poultry manure at 5 t/ha + at 2.5 t/ha + (R-M). Recommended fertilizer dose for wheat was: N-140, P-35, K-75, S-18, Zn2, Mo-0.5 kg/ha. For mungbean recommended fertilizer dose for rice was: N-70+P-15+K-40 + S-8 + Zn-1.25 kg/ha.', 'Highest grain yield of wheat was found in T1 which was statistically similar to T2 and T3 and the lowest was found in T0. The result suggested that the integrated nutrient management as superior compared to recommended inorganic nutrient dose. Total uptake on N by wheat was the highest in T4 which was at par the T2 and T3. The total P uptake was the highest in T5 and it was similar to T4 and T1 the lowest P uptake was in the T2. The total K uptake was statistically similar among the treatment. However, the highest K uptake was in T2.', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3440, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Evaluation of some Indigenous Rhizobium Isolates of Chickpea against Exotic Strains and Screening of Rhizobium Isolates under Acid Stressed Condition.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', 'a.	To evaluate the performance of Rhizobium isolates which have high nitrogen fixing ability in chickpea.\r\nb.	To evaluate the performances of locally isolated Rhizobium strains against the exotic strains.\r\nc.	To select Rhizobium strains which are highly tolerant to soil acidity.\r\nd.	To obtain maximum yield in chickpea using biological nitrogen fixation technology.\r\n', 'Field Experiment: Seven Rhizobium isolates and two exotic strains were used as different treatment. A control treatment was also considered. The experiment was laid out in a Randomized Complete Block Design (RCBD) with 3 replications. Fertilizer doses (P, K, S and other micronutrients) were calculated on the basis of soil test values. Data on different parameters like number of nodules/plant, nodule dry weight, shoot length root length, dry wt. of plants, shoot N% total N in plant, seed yield etc. were collected accordingly. Analysis of soil and plant samples was done in the laboratory.\r\nLab experiment: The strains were screened for nitrogen fixation potential under acid stressed condition by conducting lab experiment.\r\n', 'a.	The present research work had two major objectives: To evaluate the performance of Rhizobium isolates which have high nitrogen fixing ability in chickpea.\r\nb.	To evaluate the performances of locally isolated Rhizobium strains against the exotic strains.\r\nTo conduct research, seven rhizobium isolates viz. CA-R1, CA-R2, CA-R3, CA-R4, CA-R5, CA-\r\nR6, CA-R7 and CA-R8 of chickpea were collected from soil from ICRISAT and another strain (BINA-15) from BINA. It is recommended that isolate CA-R7 and isolate CA-R6 can be used for the production of chickpea. However, before making any recommendation, field trials in different AEZ should be carried out for further verification.\r\n', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3441, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Medicine', 'Project', 'Control of Clostridial enterotoxaemia of ruminants with experimentally prepared vaccine/toxoid', 'Department of Medicine, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-06-1999', '31-12-2000', '01-06-1999', '31-12-2000', '1) Isolation and production of toxins from Clostridium perfringens.\r\n2) Characterization of toxins of Clostridium perfringens.\r\n3) Preparation of toxoid/vaccine.\r\n4) Efficacy of toxoids/vaccines in the lab animals and ruminants hosts.\r\n5) Laboratory and field trial of toxoids/vaccines in ruminant hosts and lab. animals.', '1) Isolation of bacteria and production of toxins from C. perfringens.\r\n2) Purification and characterization of toxin of C. perfringens.\r\n3) Preparation of toxoid/vaccine.\r\n4) Efficacy of toxoid/vaccine in laboratory animals and ruminal hosts.\r\n5) Laboratory and Field trial of toxoid/vaccine in ruminant hosts &amp; Lab. animals.\r\nA. Factors in study\r\ni. Characterization of toxin and determination the type of organism using standard antisera of type A, B, C, D &amp; E.\r\nii. Detoxification of toxin for preparation of toxoid/vaccine assessment by dermonecrotic and or toxicity test in laboratory and ruminant animals.\r\niii. Efficacy test of toxoid/vaccine in laboratory and ruminant animals. Protective efficacy will be determined through challenge doses of toxin &amp; bacteria.\r\niv. Field trial of vaccine/toxoid to determine the duration of immunity and protectivity against the microbe will be done.\r\nB. Treatments to be used and their arrangements\r\nC. Procedures\r\nC.1. Experimental design\r\na. Dermonecrotic test in guineapigs\r\nb. Toxicity test in mice\r\nc. Efficacy test of toxoid/vaccine\r\nD. Statistical analysis.', 'Clostridium perfringens is the cause of cattle mortality. Disease usually occurs during winter months commencing from September till April. During this period of the year pasture is usually dry and devoid of succulent grasses. Animals eat down to the grass roots naturally exposing to soil borne clostridial organism - Clostridium perfringens. Although this microbe is an usual inhabitant of gastrointestinal tract yet the disease occurs when cattle have impacted rumen thereby helping the organism to multiply and produce exotoxin to the extent to cause enterotoxaemia and sudden death. Both young and adult cattle irrespective of sex are affected but young healthy cattle upto the age of 4-5 years were found more susceptible. In all cases of deathanimals had abdominal distention and ruminal stasis. Diarrhoea with blood started subsequently and animal died within 24-48 hours. Hardly time is available for treatment. The present project is designed to control the clostridium enterotoxaemia due to Clostridium perfringens with locally prepared toxoid/vaccine. Toxoid/vaccine thus produced locally will be used in the field for extensive use of cattle, sheep, goat &amp; buffaloes in order to save farmers from great economic loss. Cost analysis of the toxoid/vaccine will be done for hand of field use.', 'Clostridial enterotoxaemia of ruminants, Dermonecrotic test in guineapigs, ruminant animals.', 'BARC', 917000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Disease management of Livestock', 'Clostridial enterotoxaemia', '', '', ''),
(3442, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Screening of Rice Genotypes for Genetic Improvement of Drought Tolerance in Upland Rice', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '1.	To identify lines or varieties which can emerge when seeded deep in the soil.\r\n2.	To identify lines or varieties which have fast seedling growth.\r\n3.	To know about the performance of advance line and check varieties.\r\n', 'Plant Materials: 30 advance breeding lines and 3 check varieties.\r\nSeeds of 30 advance breeding lines and 3 check varieties were sown in 6 trays containing 40% soil with 60% sand at plant physiology green house in Bangladesh rice \r\nResearch Institute (BRRI). Each entry was sown at April 17, 2009 in a line and 20 seeds in each line were maintained at two sowing depth 2cm and 6 cm. No. of emergence, plant height for fast growth was measured at every alternate day. Coleoptile length, mesocotyle length, seminal root length, nodal root length, endosperm weight, seedling weight and root weight were also measured.\r\n', 'For drought tolerance of rice not only the CRL but also the number of thick roots at deeper soil zone is considered as one of the important characters. Amount the tested entries eleven lines produced the thick roots below 40cm. \r\nRooting ability is a ration of root and shoot and it expresses the amount of root (mg) produced below 40 cm soil depth per gram of shoot. The highest amount of root produced below 40 cm soil depth by the BR 7178-2B-2-3 followed by BR 7187-2B-2-3.\r\nWhen 2-3 characters are considered for selection of a line or variety t is difficult for selection. From the scoring systems the BRRI dhan 43, BR 6976-2B-11-1 was scored 1.6.\r\n', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3443, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Investigation of Diseases of Juvenile Thai Koi, Anabas testudineus from Farming System of Mymensingh region, Bangladesh.', 'Ponds around the Faculty of Fisheries, BAU and Fish farms (6 nos.) from Bailor, Trishal and Bhaluka, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '1) To carry out control research on growth and health condition of juvenile Thai Koi in ponds around Fisheries Faculty, BAU.\r\n2) To know the water quality parameters of investigated farms and ponds.\r\n3) To determine diseases in juvenile Thai Koi through clinical and histopathological procedures.\r\n4) To know monthly variation of diseases in juvenile Thai Koi.\r\n5) To treat the affected fish by various chemotherapeutants.\r\n6) To sort out possible preventive measures.', 'The proposed research will be designed for a period of two years starting from July 2009. A preliminary survey will be carried for the selection of six fish farms from Trishal, Bailor and Bhaluka where Thai Koi culture is going on. Through such survey previous history of disease occurrence on fishes will be recorded. Following farm condition, a control culture of Thai Koi will be carried out at BAU fish ponds near Fisheries Faculty Building. Water quality parameters like temperature, D.O., PH, hardness will be determined monthly from the investigated ponds.\r\nAffected Thai Koi collected from different farms and BAU culture ponds will be treated by various recommended chemotherapeutants to observe possible disease recovery measures. Almost similar procedure will be repeated in the second year with other three new farms in order to make the result more authentic. ', 'A study was conducted to investigation of diseases and culture of Thai koi Anabas testudineus over a period of 165 days from 29 September 2010 to 13 March 2011 in nine earthen ponds located in the northern side of the Faculty of Fisheries, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh. Three stocking densities such as 500/decimal (T1), 750/decimal (T2) and 1000/decimal (T3) were tested with the three replications. The water quality parameters were monitored at fortnightly interval. The mean value of water temperature in T1, T2 and T3 was 23.25 &plusmn; 1.95&deg;C , dissolved oxygen content were 5.0  &plusmn; 1.33 ng/Lm 4.95  &plusmn; 1.32 mg/L and 5.05  &plusmn; 1.11, pH were 7.50  &plusmn; 0.20, 7.62  &plusmn; 0.28 and 7.70  &plusmn; 0.336 and alkalinity were 171.00  &plusmn; 19.12, 168.00  &plusmn; 18.14 and 164.00  &plusmn; 25.47 respectively. At the end of the study the mean specific growth rates of Thai koi were 0.89%, 0.85% and 0.84% the average weight gain (g) were 43.69 &plusmn; 0.11, 36.69  &plusmn; 1.90 and 36.36 &plusmn; 0.29 in T1, T2 and T3 respectively. The survival rates were 95.08%, 95.49% and 88.00% in T1, T2 and T3 respectively. Fish productions were 5557.50 kg/ha, 7043.62 kg/ha and 8558.55 kg/ha in T1, T2 and T3 respectively. The result demonstrated significantly higher mean production and net benefit in T3 than in T1 and T2 (P&lt;0.05). The experiment was also carried out to investigate the health and diseases status of Thai koi for seven months during the September 2010 to March 2011. Clinically, it was observed that fish were affected with scale loss, rough skin discoloration and dermal ulcer during the winter season. Histopathologically, in the months of December and January, necrosis and vacuums were observed in skin and muscle. Gill of the Thai koi were affected with loss of primary and secondary gill lamellae, necrosis and hemorrhage in the months of December and January. In case of liver and kidney necrosis, pyknosis, vacuums and hemorrhages were observe d in the months of December and January. However, increased clinical and pathological signs were observed in T2 and T3 in December and January. During the FGD, farmers also mentioned that diseases like EUS and tail and fin rot were the dominant diseases especially in the months of December and January.', 'Diseases of Juvenile Thai Koi, Trishal, Bailor and Bhaluka, chemotherapeutants ', 'BAURES', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish disease management', 'Thai Koi', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
