(3477, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Intercropping system of wheat along with grasspea and lentil under different sowing pattern\r\n', '\r\nDepartment of Agronomy', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2011', '30-06-2012', 'to determine the sowing pattern and total yield of wheat + grasspea / lentil under intercropping systems.\r\nii) 	to assess the compatibility between wheat and grasspea / lentil as intercropping combination.\r\niii)	to study the grasspea / lentil as companion crop with wheat cultivation regarding the use of economic level of nitrogen fertilizer in main crop. \r\niv)	to assess the economic validity of wheat &amp; grasspea / lentil inter-cropping system.\r\n\r\n', 'Two years intercropping experiments were conducted at the agronomy research field of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University (SAU), Dhaka during the period from November 2008 to March 2009 and November 2009 to March 2010. The experimental field was located at 90o 22/ E longitude and 230 41/ N latitude at an altitude of 8.6 meters above the sea level. The land was located at 28 Agro ecological zone (AEZ 28) of Madhupur Tract (Appendix I). It was deep red brown terrace soil and belongs to Nodda cultivated series. The soil was clay loam in texture having pH ranges from 5.47 to 5.63. Organic matter content was very low (0.82%). The climate is subtropical with low temperature and minimum rainfall during December to March was the main feature of the rabi season. The weather data of the experimental site for the two years have been presented in Appendix II. Three types of crops have been used in this experiment. The crops were wheat (Triticum aestivum) cv. BARI gom-19 (Shourav), grasspea (Lathyrus sativus) cv. BARI khesari-2 and lentil (Lens culinaris) cv. BARI masur-4. In this experiment wheat was grown as main crop and grasspea, lentil were grown as companion pulse crop. The land was ploughed thoroughly with a power tiller and then laddering was done to obtain a desirable tilth. Weeds, stubbles and crop residues were cleaned from the land. The final ploughing and land preparation was done on 12 November 2008 for first year and 16 November 2009 for second year. The soil of the experimental field was collected and tested the chemical status before initiating the second year sowing and the results have been presented in Appendix III. For sole wheat and intercropping plots, fertilizers were applied at the rate of 100, 80, 30 and 20 kg ha-1 of N, P2O5, K2O and S, respectively (BARI recommendation) in first year and nitrogen level was varied according to the nitrogen treatments keeping other fertilizers as recommendation in the second year. 2/3 urea and whole amount of TSP, MoP &amp; gypsum were applied as basal dose and rest 1/3 urea was applied at crown root initiation stage (21 DAS) followed by irrigation. In case of sole grasspea and lentil fertilizers were applied at the rate of 20, 40, 20 and 7 kg ha-1 of N, P2O5, K2O and S, respectively and whole amount of urea, TSP, MoP &amp; gypsum were applied as basal. In case of wheat and grasspea / lentil intercrop fertilizers were applied for wheat and no additional fertilizers were applied for grasspea / lentil. The seeds of wheat (cv. Shourav) and grasspea (BARI khesari-2) were collected from Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. The lentil seeds (BARI masur-4) were collected from Bangladesh Agricultural Development Corporation (BADC). Seeds were treated with Vitavax 200 @ the rate of 3 g kg-1 of seeds and sown in line on 12 November  2008 and 16 November 2009 as per treatments. The recommended seed rate of wheat, grasspea and lentil were 125, 50 and 40 kg ha-1, respectively. The seeds were placed in lines as per treatments. After that the seeds were covered with loose friable soil. The treatments were in the first year as T1 = sole wheat, T2 = sole grasspea, T3 = sole lentil, T4 = wheat paired row (WPR), T5 = WPR+ one row grasspea, T6 = WPR+ two rows grasspea, T7 = WPR+ one row lentil, T8 = WPR+ two rows lentil, T9 = 1:1 row ratio of wheat and grasspea, T10 = 3:1 row ratio of wheat and grasspea, T11 = 1:1 row ratio of wheat and lentil and T12 = 3:1 row ratio of wheat and lentil. The second year experiment comprised of following treatments. T1 = wheat normal row + 100kg N  ha-1 (recommended nitrogen dose), T2 = wheat paired row (WPR) + 100kg N ha-1, T3 = sole grasspea + 20kg N ha-1, T4 = sole lentil + 20kg N ha-1, T5 = WPR + 1 row grasspea + 80kg N ha-1, T6 = WPR + 1 row grasspea + 100kg N ha-1, T7 = WPR + 1 row grasspea + 120kg N ha-1, T8 = WPR + 1 row lentil + 80kg N ha-1, T9 = WPR + 1 row lentil + 100kg N ha-1, T10 = WPR +1 row lentil + 120kg N   ha-1, T11 = wheat + lentil (3:1) + 80kg N ha-1 and T12 = wheat + lentil (3:1) + 100kg N ha-1, T13 = wheat + lentil (3:1) + 120kg N ha-1, T14 = wheat + grasspea (3:1) + 100kg N ha-1. Both the experiments were laid out in Randomized Complete Block Design (RCBD) with three replications. The experimental unit was divided into three blocks each of which represents a replication. Each block was divided into small plots in which treatments were applied at random. The distance maintained between two plots was 0.75 m and between blocks was 1.5 m. The plot size was 4 m x 2 .5 m.  It is mentioned here that the sole wheat was sown maintaining row spacing as 20 cm. The wheat seeds were sown as continuous in each line following the seed rate. Grasspea and lentil as sole and intercrop were sown maintaining line and plant spacing as 30 cm x 10 cm, respectively. The wheat paired row was created as two wheat line brought close together with 10 cm line spacing. Thus 40 cm free space was obtained between two wheat paired rows (WPR) to place one/two row grasspea / lentil. In case of 1: 1 row ratio of wheat and grasspea / lentil alternate wheat and grasspea / lentil was sown in line and in case of 3: 1 row ratio of wheat and grasspea / lentil, one row grasspea / lentil was fitted after three rows of wheat. Germination of seeds was ensured by light irrigation. Two Irrigations were given at crown root initiation and heading stages (22 and 53 DAS) of wheat. During irrigation care was taken so that water could not flow from one plot to another or overflow the boundary of the plots. Two hand weeding were given at each experiment to control weeds. After germination 10 plants were randomly collected from each plot at an interval of 15/20 days after sowing (DAS) to record different growth parameters. At full maturity, the wheat, grasspea and lentil crops were harvested plot wise on 9 March 2009 and 10 March 2010. Before harvesting 10 plants of wheat, grasspea and lentil from each plot was selected randomly and uprooted. Those were marked with tags, brought to the threshing floor where seeds and stover were separated, cleaned and dried under sun for 4 consecutive days. Crop of each plot was harvested from 3.75 m2 separately then those were weighted to record the seed yield which was converted into t ha-1. Data were collected for different parameters compiled and tabulated in proper form. Appropriate statistical analysis was made by MSTAT C computer package program and the treatment means were compared by least significance difference (LSD) at 5% level of significance. ', 'A two years project was initiated during November, 2008 at the research field of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University, Sher-e-Bangla Nagar, Dhaka with the financial assistance of University Grand Commission (UGC) through Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University Research System (SAURES). The project involved with two years rabi seasonal experiments, one conducted in 2008-2009 and another in 2009-2010 with the objective to assess the intercropping system of wheat with grasspea and lentil under different spatial arrangement and nitrogen level. The variety BARI gom-19 (Shourav), BARI khesari-2 and BARI masur-4 were taken for wheat, grasspea and lentil, respectively. The treatments were in the first year as T1 = sole wheat, T2 = sole grasspea, T3 = sole lentil, T4 = wheat paired row (WPR), T5 = WPR+ one row grasspea, T6 = WPR+ two rows grasspea, T7 = WPR+ one row lentil, T8 = WPR+ two rows lentil, T9 = 1:1 row ratio of wheat and grasspea, T10 = 3:1 row ratio of wheat and grasspea, T11 = 1:1 row ratio of wheat and lentil and T12 = 3:1 row ratio of wheat and lentil. The second year experiment comprised with following treatments. T1 = wheat normal row + 100kg N ha-1, T2 = wheat paired row (WPR) + 100kg N ha-1, T3 = sole grasspea + 20kg N ha-1, T4 = sole lentil + 20kg N ha-1, T5 = WPR + 1 row grasspea + 80kg N ha-1, T6 = WPR + 1 row grasspea + 100kg N ha-1, T7 = WPR + 1 rows grasspea + 120kg N ha-1, T8 = WPR + 1 row lentil + 80kg N ha-1, T9 = WPR + 1 row lentil + 100kg N ha-1, T10 = WPR +1 row lentil + 120kg N   ha-1, T11 = Wheat + lentil (3:1) + 80kg N ha-1 and T12 = Wheat + lentil (3:1) + 100kg N ha-1, T13 = Wheat + lentil (3:1) + 120kg N ha-1, T14 = Wheat + grasspea (3:1) + 100kg N    ha-1. Both the experiments were laid out in a Randomized Complete Block Design (RCBD) with three replications. Results indicated from two years experiments that paired row system of wheat was dominating normal wheat cultivation in respect of  increased yield (3.30 t ha-1, 3.12% more and 3.41 t ha-1, 5.90% more), BCR (1.62, Tk. 0.22 more and 1.62, Tk. 0.05 more) and net income (Tk.18309 ha-1, 12.05% more and Tk.29797 ha-1, 12.1% more). This paired row system did not get any additional cost for planting but offered a space between two paired rows of wheat for intercropping with one row grasspea/lentil keeping optimum plant population of wheat with recommended fertilizers dose. This spatial arrangement showed the maximum LER (1.38 and 1.23, ie. 38 and 23% more land advantage), net return (Tk. 30,126 ha-1 and 40,047 ha-1), monetary advantages (Tk. 13,423.91 ha-1 and 16,621.70 ha-1) and BCR (1.71 and 1.82) in two years experimentation which ultimately compensated the reduction of wheat yields under intercropping system. The second important spatial arrangement came out from the experiments as wheat and grasspea/lentil together cultivation in 3:1 row ratio with normal dose of fertilizers as they showed increased LER, net return and BCR than sole wheat cropping.', 'Wheat, Lentil, inter-crop, grasspea, ', 'SAURES-UGC', 102000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Total Production per unit land', 'Wheat and lentil increment', 'The results of the first year experiment revealed that at maturity, the highest plant height (91.08 cm) of wheat was obtained from 3:1 row ratio of wheat &amp; lentil treatment and the lowest (80.62 cm) was obtained from WPR+ one row grasspea treatment. The highest dry matter (11.92 g) of wheat was obtained from WPR+ two rows grasspea treatment and the lowest dry matter (6.15 g) was obtained from WPR+ two rows lentil treatment. The highest number of tillers plant-1 (4.2) of wheat was shown in WPR+ two rows grasspea treatment while the lowest number (2.41) from WPR+ two rows lentil treatment. The highest length of spike of wheat (15.56 cm) was obtained from WPR+ one row grasspea   treatment. The lowest length of spike of wheat was obtained from WPR+ two rows lentil   treatment (13.85 cm). The highest spikelet spike-1 (16.64) was obtained from sole wheat treatment and the lowest (14.93) was obtained from 3:1 row ratio of wheat &amp; lentil treatment. Maximum thousand grain weight (40.24 g) of wheat was recorded in 3:1 row ratio of wheat &amp; lentil treatment. The lowest grain weight (36.89 g) was found with sole wheat treatment. The highest grain yield (3.30 t ha-1) of wheat obtained from WPR. Among the intercropping system the highest grain yield (3.11 t ha-1) obtained from 3:1 row ratio of wheat &amp; grasspea and the lowest grain yield (1.94 t ha-1) was obtained from 1:1 row ratio of wheat &amp; lentil treatments. The yield of wheat as sole reduced by 2.84 % to 39.39 % when the crop shared growing condition with grasspea / lentil. Maximum harvest index of wheat (42.59%) was obtained from WPR+ one row lentil treatment and the lowest (33.96%) was obtained from 1:1 row ratio of wheat &amp; lentil treatment.\r\nIn the second year, in case of wheat at final harvest, the tallest plant (81.85 cm) was observed in wheat + lentil (3:1) + 120kg N ha-1   treatment and shortest plant (75.09 cm) was observed in WPR + 1 row grasspea + 80kg N ha-1  treatment. The highest dry matter was obtained from wheat + grasspea (3:1) +100kg N ha-1 treatment (10.09 g) and the lowest dry matter (7.87 g) was obtained from WPR + 1 row grasspea + 80kg N ha-1  and wheat + lentil (3:1) + 80kg N ha-1   treatments. The highest (75.22) tillers m-2 was shown in wheat normal row + 100kg N ha-1 treatment while the lowest number (52.87) from wheat + lentil (3:1) + 120kg N ha-1 treatment. The highest length of spike (15.67 cm and 15.65 cm) was obtained from WPR + 1 row lentil + 100kg N ha-1 and wheat + lentil (3:1) + 120kg N ha-1 treatments. The lowest length of spike was obtained from WPR + 100kg N ha-1 treatment (13.55 cm). It was WPR + 1 row lentil + 100kg N ha-1 that gave the highest spikelet spike-1 (20.19) and WPR + 1 rows grasspea + 120kg N ha-1 showed the lower spikelet spike-1. Maximum thousand grain weight (42.40 g) was recorded in wheat + lentil (3:1) + 80kg N ha-1 treatment. The lowest grain weight (39.50 g) was found with WPR + 1 row lentil + 100kg N ha-1 treatment. The highest grain yield (3.41 t ha-1) was obtained from WPR + 100kg N ha-1 treatment and the lowest grain yield (2.31 t ha-1) was obtained from wheat + lentil (3:1) + 80kg N ha-1 treatment. Treatment WPR + 100kg N ha-1 provided 5.90% increased yield over sole wheat. The yield of wheat as sole reduced by 8.38 % to 28.26 % when the crop grown along with grasspea / lentil. The highest (42.40%) harvest index was obtained from wheat + lentil (3:1) + 120kg N ha-1 treatment and the lowest (38.35%) harvest index were obtained from WPR + 1 row lentil + 80kg N ha-1 treatment. ', 'The first year and second year experiments that the planting pattern of wheat paired row could be practiced in lieu of normal sowing and one row grasspea fitted in between two paired rows of wheat with BARI recommended fertilizers which eventually gave an increase of gross return, net return, monetary advantage, BCR and LER over normal planting of wheat that compensated losses in wheat yield under intercropping system. The second important spatial arrangement of wheat and grasspea cultivation may be in 3:1 row ratio.', ''),
