(3487, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Department of Genetics and Plant Breeding', 'Project', 'Improvement of Oleiferous Brassica crops', '', '', '', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'SAURES-UGC', 45900, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3488, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Cultivation of rice suing different planting techniques.', 'Agronomy Field, SAU', '', '', 'Completed', '01-06-2005', '31-12-2006', '01-06-2005', '30-11-2006', '1.	to find out the effect of planting methods for optimum growth and yield of rice.\r\n2.	to compare the performance of inbred and hybrid rice varieties.\r\n3.	to predict the perfect planting method for optimum growth and yield of rice.', 'Four experiments were conducted at the Agronomy field at Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University, Dhaka during the period from June 2005 to November 2006. The farm belongs to the general soil type, Shallow Red Brown Terrace Soils under Tejgaon Series. The land was above flood level and sufficient sunshine was available during the experimental period. Soil samples from 0-15 cm depths were collected from experimental field. The analyses were done by Soil Resources and Development Institute (SRDI), Dhaka. The physicochemical properties of the soil along with weather data is presented in Appendix i &amp; Appendix ii. A hybrid rice variety Sonar Bangla-1 was used for all the experiments along with a modern inbred variety BR 11 (Mukta) in the first experiment, BRRI dhan 29 in the second experiment and BRRI dhan 32 in the third and fourth experiment as a test crop. Seeds of BR 11, BRRI dhan 29 and BRRI dhan 32 were collected from BRRI, Joydebpur, Gazipur, Bangladesh and the Sonar Bangla-1 were colleted from the Mollika Seed Company, Dhaka which they imported from China. A common procedure was followed in raising of seedlings in the seedbed except SRI seedlings. The nursery bed was prepared by puddling with repeated ploughing followed by laddering. The sprouted seeds were sown as uniformly as possible. Irrigation was gently provided to the bed as and when needed. No fertilizer was used in the nursery bed. For SRI, sprouted seeds were sown as broadcast in two portable trays containing soil and cowdung each for BRRI dhan 29 and Sonarbangla-1. Thin plastic sheets were placed at the base of the trays to protect water loss. The moisture of the trays was controlled accurately by applying water everyday, which ensured proper growth of all the seedlings in the trays. These trays were kept inside a room at night to protect the seedlings from\r\nfreezing temperature of the season and kept in sunlight at daytime for proper development of seedlings. The experimental fields were prepared by ploughings and cross-ploughings followed\r\nby laddering to have a good puddled field. All kinds of weeds and residues of previous crop were removed from the field. At the time of first ploughing, cowdung @ 10 t haTi was applied for all experiments. The experimental area of first and second experiments were fertilized by 120, 80, 80, 20 and 5 kg ha-1 N, P205, K20, S and Zn, third and fourth experiments by 120, 80, 120, 55 and 10 kg ha-1 N, P205, K20, S and Zn in the form of urea, triple super phosphate (TSP), muriate of potash (MP), gypsum and zinc sulphate respectively. The entire amounts of triple super phosphate, muriate of potash, gypsum and zinc sulphate were applied at final land preparation as a basal dose. Urea was applied as three equal installments in Aman season and four equal installments in Boro season. The first installment of urea was top dressed after seedling recovery and the last before panicle initiation. Three sets of treatments included in the first experiment that assigned in a split-split plot design where three planting materials as (i) Sprouted seeds (M1), (ii) Nursery seedlings (M2) and (iii) Clonal tillers (M3) were assigned in the main plot; two variety as (i) BR11 (inbreed variety)-Vi and (ii) Sonar Bangla-1 (hybrid variety)-V2 in the sub-plot and two planting methods as (i) Broadcast (T1) and (ii) Line sowing (T2) in the sub sub-plot. Two sets of treatments were included in the second experiment in a Split-plot design where two varieties viz. (i) BRRI dhan 29 (inbred) and (ii) Sonarbangla-1 (hybrid) assigned in the main plot and five cultivation methods viz. (i) Sprouted seeds in line (P1), (ii) Sprouted seeds broadcast (P2), (iii) Nursery seedlings (P3), (iv) SRI (P4) and (v) Clonal tillers (P5) in the sub plot. In the third experiment, two varieties (i) BRRI dhan 32 (Inbred) and (ii) Sonarbangla-1 (Hybrid) assigned in the main plot and five tiller separation days viz. (i) 20 days (ii) 25 days (iii) 30 days (iv) 35 days and (v) 40 days assigned in the sub-plot. The treatments of fourth experiment was as per third experiment only the variation of sub plot treatments having clonal tillers age instead of tiller separation days. The size of unit plot was 4 m x 3 m in all experiment. The distances between plot to plot and replication to replication were lm. In the first experiment, the sprouted seeds were sown directly in the main field on June 22, 2005 and at the same time as seed bed for raising nursery seedlings. A 25 days old seedlings were uprooted carefully and transplanted as per experimental treatment on the well puddled plots on July 18, 2005 having two seedlings hill-1. The clonal tillers were collected at 30 days after transplanting from a nearby plot and planted on August 18, 2005. In the second experiment, nursery seedlings (40 days old) were transplanted on January 15, 2006 maintaining 25 cm x 15 cm spacing. In case of SRI treatment, 14 days old seedlings were uprooted from the trays and transplanted on January 15, 2006. Sprouted seeds were sown on January 15, 2006 continuously in line with 25 cm rows and broadcast haphazardly. On February 14, 2006 clonal tillers were collected and separated (30 days after transplanting) from the mother crop and transplanted on the same field. In the third experiment, 25 days old seedlings were transplanted on July 19, 2006 maintaining the spacing of 25 cm x 15 cm with two seedlings hill-1. Four clonal tillers hill-1 were separated from each plot following the procedure of Biswas (2001) on August 8, August 13, August 18, August 23 and August 28 as per treatment. The clonal tillers of different ages were transplanted in the fourth experiment on August 21. Two hand weedings were done for all the experiments where first weeding was done at 20 days after sowing/planting followed by second weeding at 15 days after first weeding. Irrigation water was added to each plot according to the needs. Plant protection measures were taken as and when necessary. Field trap and zinc bait were used to control the rat. For controlling the birds watching was done properly, especially during morning and afternoon. Maturity of crop was determined when 90% of the grains become golden yellow in color. The harvesting of first experiment was done on October 25, 2005, October 30, 2005 and November 7, 2005 for sprouted seeds, clonal tillers and nursery seedlings respectively. In the second experiment the harvesting of Sonarbangla-1 was done on April, 23; April 26; May 02; May 06 and May 08, 2006 for nursery seedlings; clonal tillers; SRI; Sprouted seeds in line and sprouted seeds broadcast, respectively and BRRI dhan 29 was done on May 10; May 14; May 19; May 21 and May 28, 2006 for nursery seedlings; clonal tillers; Sprouted seeds in line; sprouted seeds broadcast and SRI, respectively. Harvesting of third experiment was done on October 19 and November 03, 2006 for hybrid variety and inbred variety respectively. The fourth experiment was harvested on November 8 and November 27, 2006 for hybrid and inbred variety respectively. In all the experiments, ten hills per plot were randomly selected from which different data were collected and 6 m2 areas from middle portion of each plot was separately harvested and bundled, properly tagged and then brought to the threshing floor for recording grain and straw yield. Threshing was done using pedal thresher. The grains were cleaned and sun dried to moisture content of 14 %. Straw was also sun dried properly. Finally grain and straw yields plot-1 were recorded and converted to ton ha1.\r\n', 'Rice (Oryza sativa L) is the most important crop of tropical world and in Bangladesh. There are different methods of planting rice such as direct seedings (haphazard and line sowing), transplanting of seedlings (haphazard and line), transplanting of clonal tillers, SRI (System of Rice Intensification) etc. The effectiveness of these methods are reported by many researchers (Biswas, 2001; Biswas and Salokhe, 2001; Roy et al., 1990; Biswas and Salokhe, 2002; Sharma, 1992; Alauddin, 2004; Laulanie, 1993; Roknuzzaman, 1997; Varughese et al., 1993). A 2-years project was started during 2005 with the financial support of SAURES of which two experiments were conducted in Aman season, 2005 and Boro season, 2005-2006 and other two experiments in Aman season, 2006. The objective of the project was to compare the performance of hybrid and inbred variety under different cultivation methods along with the performance of clonal tillers. The rice varieties included in these studies were Sonarbangla -1 as a hybrid variety, BR!! (Mukta) in first year Aman season, BRRI dhan 32 for the second year Aman season and BRRI dhan 29 in Boro season. Three planting materials viz, sprouted seeds, nursery seedlings and clonal tillers were used in first experiment along with two planting methods viz, line and haphazard planting. Five cultivation methods viz, sprouted seeds broadcasted, sprouted seeds in line, nursery seedlings, SRI and clonal tillers were included in the second experiment. Five tiller separation days viz, tiller separation at 20, 25, 30, 35 and 40 days after transplantation were included in the third experiment and five different ages of clonal tillers viz. 20, 25, 30, 35 and 40 days were tested in the fourth experiment. Results showed that hybrid variety performed better in all the experiments compared to inbred variety. Clonal tillers performed better in Aman season but nursery seedlings in Boro season. Planting in line showed better performance with highest grain yield (4.81 t ha-1) than haphazard method (4.32 t ha-1). The combined effect of planting materials, varieties and planting method resulted in the highest grain yield from clonal tillers of hybrid variety with line sowing method in the first experiment (Fig. 1). Nursery seedlings of the inbred variety resulted the highest grain yield (8.88 t ha-1) and sprouted seeds broadcast of the inbred variety gave the lowest grain yield (6.35 t ha-1) in second experiment (Fig. 2). Earlier tiller separation (20-25 DAT) resulted higher grain yield in hybrid variety but no such variations was observed in inbred variety (Fig. 3). The inbred variety with 25 days of clonal tillers resulted the superior performance in grain yield (4.37 t ha-1) that similar (5.21 t ha1) with hybrid variety of 40 days old (Fig. 4)\r\n', '', 'SAURES', 100000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Crop food', 'Rice', 'A 2-years project was started during 2005 with the financial support of SAURES of which two experiments were conducted in Aman season, 2005 and Boro season, 2005-2006 and other two experiments in Aman season, 2006. The objective of the project was to compare the performance of hybrid and inbred variety under different cultivation methods along with the performance of clonal tillers. The rice varieties included in these studies were Sonarbangla -1 as a hybrid variety, BR!! (Mukta) in first year Aman season, BRRI dhan 32 for the second year Aman season and BRRI dhan 29 in Boro season. Three planting materials viz, sprouted seeds, nursery seedlings and clonal tillers were used in first experiment along with two planting methods viz, line and haphazard planting. Five cultivation methods viz, sprouted seeds broadcasted, sprouted seeds in line, nursery seedlings, SRI and clonal tillers were included in the second experiment. Five tiller separation days viz, tiller separation at 20, 25, 30, 35 and 40 days after transplantation were included in the third experiment and five different ages of clonal tillers viz. 20, 25, 30, 35 and 40 days were tested in the fourth experiment. ', 'Results showed that hybrid variety performed better in all the experiments compared to inbred variety. Clonal tillers performed better in Aman season but nursery seedlings in Boro season. Planting in line showed better performance with highest grain yield (4.81 t ha-1) than haphazard method (4.32 t ha-1). The combined effect of planting materials, varieties and planting method resulted in the highest grain yield from clonal tillers of hybrid variety with line sowing method in the first experiment. Nursery seedlings of the inbred variety resulted the highest grain yield (8.88 t ha-1) and sprouted seeds broadcast of the inbred variety gave the lowest grain yield (6.35 t ha-1) in second experiment. Earlier tiller separation (20-25 DAT) resulted higher grain yield in hybrid variety but no such variations was observed in inbred variety. The inbred variety with 25 days of clonal tillers resulted the superior performance in grain yield (4.37 t ha-1) that similar (5.21 t ha1) with hybrid variety of 40 days old.', ''),
