(3510, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Entomology', 'Project', 'Diversity, abundance and impacts of insect visitors on mango based agroforestry system', '', '', 'Applied', 'On-going', '01-07-2012', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2012', '30-06-2013', 'i.	To identify the insect species available in the mango based agroforst; \r\nii.	To figure out the significant of pollinator species and fruit setting;\r\niii.	To know the pest population and their infestation level\r\n', 'Study site and conditions: The study will be conducted in the Agroforestry Field Laboratory of Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University, Gazipur in the surroundings of the Sal Forest (25&deg;25&amp;#8242; North latitude and 89&deg;5&amp;#8242; East longitude), and approximately 40 km north from Dhaka, the capital city of Bangladesh. The land use in this area is small scale and dominated by natural and disturbed tropical forests. Mango based agroforestry system is interrupted by different management intensity, grasslands, paddy and vegetable fields. As no honey bees are managed in this region and crop pollination is completely rely on diverse native pollinator community.\r\n\r\nSelection of mango trees and estimation of light intensity: Twenty mango trees in the field will be selected, which will cover a range of environmental conditions because of agroforestry practices. Light intensity will be measured with a lux meter.\r\nCollection and identification of insects: Collection of insects on mango trees in the agroforestry system will be continued from October 2012 to September 2013. Each collection will be made for 60 minute between 09.00 and 13.00. The starting time will be depended on the distance to the chosen site. Collected insects will be carried to the Entomology Laboratory for identification.  \r\n\r\nObservation of behavioral characteristics of pollinator insects: For observation of behavioral characteristics, peak foraging period of the insects and landing duration of an insect on each flower will be measured. For determination of peak foraging period, insects will be collected with sweeping net five times (between 07:00 - 08:00, 09.00 - 10.00, 11.00 - 12.00, 01.00 - 02.00 and 03.00 - 04.00 h of the day) in a day at the full bloom of the trees. Then species diversity and abundance per catch will be counted. Landing duration (length of remaining time) of the pollinator species will be observed on mango flowers between 09:00 and 13:00 at the full bloom of the trees. \r\n\r\nEffect of pollinators on fruit setting: Effect of insect pollinators on fruit setting will be investigated according to Willmer and Stone (1989). Five flower clusters at five branches of each tree will be labeled and kept open to insect pollination. On the other hand, another five branches of each tree will be labeled and covered with very fine nylon mesh gauze (10 &amp;#956;m) to exclude insect pollination. Bags will be fixed around the branches about one week before flowering. The bags will be removed after five weeks of major flowering and the total number of green swollen ovules will be counted.\r\n\r\nObservation of insect infestation: Five mango trees in the field will be selected from different amount of shade. The observations will to be made from four directions viz., East, South, West and North. The crop will be observed at fortnight interval throughout the year for the incidence of various insect pests. The observations will be recorded during early morning hours (07.00 - 09.00) to take the advantage of sedentary nature of insect at that time. Systematic recording of the data will be made to quantify the pest level. Four branches of each tree will be tagged, and from each branch, five twigs or panicles will be observed for recording data on leaf eating caterpillar and adult weevils. The scale insect, and gall midge number will be counted from the per square inch area of five affected leaf. The mealy bug will be counted per five affected leaf and twig or panicle. Number of nymphs and adults of mango hopper in a single panicle/ inflorescence from each direction of selected tree will be visually counted during season. On maturity, all fruits of each plant will be harvested and percent fruit infestation by fruit fly will be calculated.\r\n\r\nStatistical analysis: Descriptive and parametric statistical methods will be employed for analyzing data using IBM SPSS 19.0.\r\n', 'A major ecosystem function in agricultural landscapes is the pollination of crops, which has recently been related to declining pollinator diversity (Klein et al., 2003). Free and Williams (1976) stated that mango flowers are inadequate as pollen resources, and honeybees are attracted to other flowers nearby. Many other authors have, however, considered several hymenopteran species to be suitable for pollination of mangos (Manning, 1995; Gibbs and Muirhead, 1998). Farjado et al. (2008) found that introduction of bee colonies in mango orchard significantly increase fruit setting.\r\n The diversity of insects in agroforest is strongly affected by the type of agroforest and by subsequent changes in management. Fruit-feeding butterfly species in agroforest is related to food resources provided by shade trees (Schulze et al., 2004; Waltert et al., 2004). Philpott (2005) stated that ant communities are affected by shade tree removal. To increase knowledge on pest and pollinator interactions with agroforestry techniques, more systematic observations on pest and pollinator in ongoing agroforestry research is necessary.\r\n', '', 'BSMRAU', 60000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
