(3530, 'Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University', 'Department of Horticulture', 'Project', 'SEED AND NUTRITIONAL QUALITY ASSESSMENT FOR IMPROVEMENT OF BLACK CUMIN UNDER ENVIRONMENTAL STRESS CONDITION', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'To improve the indigenous and exotic cultivars of Black cumin on basis of yield and nutritional quality.\r\nTo determine medicinal value of Black cumin cultivars.\r\nStudy of various factors relating to seed quality deterioration.\r\nTo find out the yield potentiality of black cumin under different agro-ecological zones in Bangladesh.\r\n', 'The study was conducted at the Horticulture Research Field, Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University, Gazipur during the rabi season of 2012-13. Laboratory analysis was done at the Seed Science and Technology laboratory, Seed Science and Technology unit, Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University (BSMRAU). The details of the materials and methods employed during the course of this investigation are described in below.\r\n1.2.1 Site and Soil\r\nThe experimental site is situated at 24.090N latitude and 90.260 E longitude with an elevation of 8.4 m from the sea level. Soil of the experimental field was silty clay loam belonging to the Salna series of Shallow Red Brown Terrace Soil (FAO, 1988). The area represents the Madhupur Tract under Agro Ecological Zone (AEZ) 28. The soil is characterized by heavy clays within 50 cm from the surface and is acidic in nature. The soil has poor physical and chemical properties. At the time of initiation of the experiment the soil was silty clay in texture in the surface layer and silty clay loam in subsurface soil. The detailed information of the basic soil properties are presented in table 1.1a and 1.1b.\r\n1.2.2. Climate and weather condition\r\nBlack cumin was grown in rabi season of 2012-13. The mean maximum and minimum temperatures during the growing season of  2012-13 were 32.79oC and 10.23oC, respectively. The total rainfall during that time was 101.60 mm and the day length was 10-12 hours.  The  mean relative humidity maximum and minimum were 71.25 to 84.52 %, respectively. The weather related data were recorded during the study period and collected from the Meteorological Station of BSMRAU and has been presented in Appendix 1.\r\n1.2.3 Planting materials\r\nFour cultivars were used in this experiment as exotic, Iran (V1), BARI kalojeera-1(V2), Local, Faridpur (V3) and Local, Nature (V4). Imported exotic (Iran)  cultivars was collected from Laltir Seed company, Gazipur; BARI kalojeera-1 from Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute, Gazipur; Local ( Faridpur ) and Local ( Natore ) were collected directly from farmers of Faridpur and Natore respectively.\r\n1.2.4 Seed treatment\r\nThe seeds were soaked in water for 24 hours in order to facilate germination. They were dried and treated by Bavistin @ 2 g/kg of seed to minimize the primary seed-borne diseases.\r\n1.2.5 Land preparation\r\nThe land was well prepared by deep and cross ploughing with a tractor disk harrow followed by laddering. Weeds and stubbles of the previous crops were collected and removed from the field during land preparation. Soil clods were broken and plots were prepared as 10 cm raised so that irrigation and rain water easily could drain out and seeds could easily be germinated.\r\n1.2.6 Manuring and fertilization\r\nThe experiment plots were manuered and fertilized with cowdung, urea, TSP and MP at the rate of 10 t, 125, 95 and 75 kg/ha respectively (BARI, 2007). The total amount of cow dung, half of urea and all of TSP and MP were applied in the form of Urea, TSP, MoP  respectively at the time of final land preparation. The remaining urea was applied at 40 days after sowing (DAS) of seeds as top dress followed by irrigation.\r\n1.2.7 Experimental design and layout\r\nThe experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with three replications. The treatments were randomly allotted in each block. Each block consisted of 4 plots and the dimension of each plot was 1.2 m x 1.2 m (1.44 m2) having a plot to plot and block to block distances of 0.5 m and 1.0 m, respectively.\r\n1.2.8 Sowing method\r\nThe seeds were mixed with some loose soil to allow uniform sowing in rows. Then, seeds were sown in rows 15 cm apart continuously by hand @ 10 kg/ha ( BARI, 2007), maintaining a depth of one cm. Continuous line sowing was done to facilate to main plant to plant distance 10 cm by rouging later on ( BARI, 2007). The seeds were covered with loose soil properly just after sowing and gently pressed by hands. The sowing was done on November 1, 2010 with slight watering just to supply sufficient moisture for proper germination. \r\n1.2.9. Weeding and thinning\r\nThe field was kept free by hand weeding. Weeding cum thinning was done in installments at 25 and 40 and 60 days after sowing (DAS). To keep spacing 10x 15 cm2, properly thinning was done at 25 days after sowing.\r\n1.2.10. Crop protection\r\nFungicide Bavistin @ 2 g/L was sprayed to control damping off. The spray was done 2 times at an interval of 10 days from 25 days after sowing. There was no insect attack to the crop. \r\n1.2.11. Harvesting\r\nThe crop was harvested when 50% of the capsules color changed from green to straw color. The seed plants were cut at the base by sickle early in the morning to avoid shattering of capsules during harvest. Then the stalks with capsule were dried in the sun. Seeds from capsule were separated by beating with sticks and cleaned by winnowing and dried properly (10% moisture of seed).\r\n\r\n1.2.12 Collection of data\r\nData were collected from the inner rows of each plot to avoid the border effect. In each unit plot, 10 plants were selected randomly for recording data.  The following seed yield and yield contributing characters were recorded.\r\n1.	Days to 1st emergence \r\n2.	Days to 50% emergence\r\n3.	Days to 1st flower bud initiation\r\n4.	Days to flower bud initiation in 50% plants\r\n5.	Days to 1st flower blooming\r\n6.	Days to flower blooming in 50% plants\r\n7.	Days to 1st capsule setting\r\n8.	Days to capsule setting in 50% plants\r\n9.	Days to first capsule ripening\r\n10.	Days to capsule ripening in 50% plants\r\n11.	Plant height\r\n12.	Number of primary branches per plant\r\n13.	Number of secondary branches per plant\r\n14.	Number of tertiary branches per plant\r\n15.	Length of leaf\r\n16.	Breath of leaf\r\n17.	Length of capsule\r\n18.	Capsule diameter\r\n19.	Length of pedicle\r\n20.	Fresh weight per plant\r\n21.	Number of seeds per capsule \r\n22.	Number of capsule per plant\r\n23.	Fresh seed weight per capsule\r\n24.	Fresh seed yield per plant\r\n25.	Dry weight per plant\r\n26.	Dry seed weight per capsule\r\n27.	Dry seed yield per plant\r\n28.	1000 seed weight\r\n29.	Seed yield (t/ha)\r\n30.	Stover yield (t/haHarvest index (%)\r\n\r\n', 'Seed production of black cumin was investigated at Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University, Gazipur during winter 2012-13. Two experiments were carried out to fulfill the objectives of the study. Among the genotypes, variations  were observed in respect of  days to emergence, flower bud initiation, fruit setting, fruit ripening, plant height, number of branches, leaf and capsule size, pedicle length, biological yield and seed yield. Exotic genotype gave the highest seed yield (2.36 t/ha) followed by BARI Kalojera-1(2.05 t/ha), Faridpur local (1.96 t/ha) and Natore local (1.82 t/ha). Oil content was higher in BARI Kalojera-1 and Natore local was found superior in almost all mineral nutrients content. Among the genotypes, Natore local had the highest amount of potasium (1.18%) and calcium (0.66%) content in the seeds of black cumin. In conclusion, exotic genotype had the highest yield potential where as genotypes Natore local content the highest nutrients content.', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
