(3637, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Optimization of supplementary feeding practices in semi-intensive carp farming system in Bangladesh', 'Department of Aquaculture, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-1999', '30-06-2002', '01-07-1999', '30-06-2002', '1) To find out an optimum feeding rate using only rice bran and rice bran + mustard oilcake as supplemental feed for carp polyculture.\r\n2) To find out the best form and method of feed presentation for an economic supplemental feeding system.\r\n3) To find out the effect of supplemental feed on the primary productivity of pond as well as on fish growth.', 'The supplemental feed to be used in the experiments such as rice bran and mustard oilcake will be procured from Mymensingh local market. The experimental fish to be used in different experiments will include catla (Catla catla), Rohu (Labeo rohita), mrigel (Cirrhinus mrigala), mirror carp (Cyprinus carpio) and Thai sharpunti (Puntius gonionotus). The fish will be obtained from fresh water station, Fisheries Research Institute, Mymensingh.\r\nAll the experiments will be conducted in 12 earthen miniponds of size 30 m2 each situated near the Fisheries Faculty Buildings. All the pond has access to a deep tube well water supply so that the desired water level in each pond could easily be maintained. During heavy rainfall or to prevent overflow, the ponds are connected to a drainage system. Alternately, the experiments may be conducted in the conducted in the experimental ponds of the Fisheries Faculty Field Laboratory Pond Complex.', '', 'optimum feeding, rice bran + mustard oilcake as supplemental feed, economic supplemental feeding system', 'BAURES', 388400, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish Production', 'Supplementary fish feed', '', '', ''),
(3638, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics', 'Project', 'Studies on biology and culture potentiality of dhela (Osteobrama cotio cotio)', 'Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-04-2000', '30-09-2000', '01-04-2000', '30-09-2000', '1) To assess the interactions of dhela and carps and their influence on the overall fish production in a given ecosystem;\r\n2) To determine the food and feeding habits of dhela; and\r\n3) To estimate the fecundity and Gonado somatic index (GSI) of dhela.', 'Following experiments were conducted:\r\n1) Effect of dhela (Osteobrama cotio cotio)on the growth and production of carps in polyculture.\r\n2) Food and feeding habits of fresh water cyprinid, Dhela (Osteobrama cotio cotio)\r\n3) The fecundity of dhela (Osteobrama cotio cotio) and the relationship of fecundity with length, weight and gonad weight.\r\n4) Estimation of Gonado somatic index of dhela (Osteobrama cotio cotio) ', '', 'dhela, fecundity and Gonado somatic index, food and feeding habits of dhela', 'ICLARM', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish Production', 'Dhela (Osteobrama cotio cotio)', '', '', ''),
(3639, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Technology', 'Project', 'Studies on the Improvement of Food Qualities and Shelf Life of Traditionally produced Fermented Product (NGA-PI) by Rakhaing Community at Cox''s Bazar and Bandarban Region under different storage condition.', 'Cox''s Bazar, Bandarban, Faculty of Fisheries, BAU Campus, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '1) To collect information on the socio-economic condition of the producer''s and consumers of the fermented fishery product (NGA_PI) in the Rakhaing villages of Cox''s Bazar (Chawfalldandi and Nazirartek Upazilas) and Bandarban (Bandarban sadar Upazila) region of Bangladesh.\r\n2) To investigate the present status of fermented fishery product (NGA-Pi) produced at Cox''s Bazar and Bandarban region.\r\n3) To detect the steps of processing which are responsible for high level of quality degradation of fermented fishery product (Nga-Pi).\r\n4) To establish an improved model for preparing fermented fishery product Nga-Pi.\r\n5) To assess the nutritional and food quality of traditional and improved products.\r\n6) To study the shelf life of Nga-Pi produced traditionally and in laboratory under different storage and packaging conditions.\r\n7) To conduct training to the Nga-Pi producer community for incorporation of hygienic and improved quality product.', 'a) Survey and data collection from survey area\r\ni) Questionnaire\r\nii) Tap Recorder\r\nb) Collection of Traditional Nga-Pi and the raw materials for Nga-Pi production\r\n1) Insulating box\r\n2) Ice\r\nc) Nga-pi production:\r\ni) Ceramic tub and mortar\r\nii) Use of clean and white salt\r\niii) Screening drying yard\r\niv) Collection of raw materials\r\nv) Washing and sorting\r\nvi) Dewatering\r\nvii) Drying and pounding\r\nviii) Wrapped with leaves\r\nix) Aging\r\nx) Storage ', '', 'fermented fishery product, Rakhaing villages of Cox''s Bazar, NGA-Pi ', 'BAU-UGC', 240000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fish processing', 'Food Quality', '', '', ''),
(3640, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Parasitology', 'Project', 'Studies on the effects of Bonostomum trigonocephatum infection on the cellular components of blood and haemoglobin in local goats of Bangladesh.', 'Department of parasitology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', '', '', '', '', '', '1) To find out R.B.C values of female goats as affected by different levels of intestinal worms of B. spp.\r\n2) To find out W.B.C values of female goats as affected by different levels of intestinal worms of B. spp.\r\n3) To observe the Haemoglobin (HB) levels of blood of different groups.\r\n4) To find out the faecal eggs per grams of faeces of female goats as affected  by different levels of Bonostomum worms.\r\n', 'A uniform group of 12 worm free local female goats aged between 2 to 3 years will be randomly allocated into treatment groups, T1, T2 and T3. They will be housed in individual pens with concrete floors. Strict cleanlines and hygienic measures will be adopted to ensure that adventitious infections with nematode parasites did not occur. All animals will be fed uniform concentrate mixture at equivalent to 1% of their live weight. The concentrated feed will be compounded using copra-meal (50%), tricalcium phosphate (1.7%), rice bran (2.9%, and other essential vitamins and minerals. Grsasses will be offered at libitum to satisfy the dry matter requirement of the animals.\r\nBonostomum spp. infective larvae will be obtained by culturing the faeces of kids harbouring the non-specific infections of the parasites. Each animals in the treated T1, T2 and T3 will be fed orally with a single dose of 0, 15,000 and 30,000 Bonostomum spp. infective larvae in 10 ml physiologicalsaline solution respectively.\r\nAbout 5 ml blood will be collected from the jugular vein of each animal at fort-nightly intervals. Blood samples will be treated with exolates anticoagulant to prevent blood clotting. Total R.B.C and W.B.C will be determined by hemocyto metric method. At fortnightly intervals faecal samples will be collected directly from the rectum of each animals and the number of eggs per gram of faeces will be determined following a modified method. A split-plot in time analysis of variance will be used to test for differences between different levels of larval infections by period interaction. Comparison based on the least significant difference at p=0.05 will be made between the means of T1, T2 and T3 at each time period. ', '', 'Bonostomum trigonocephatum, faeces of female goats, intestinal worms of B. spp', 'BAU-UGC', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Goat disease management', 'Goat', '', '', ''),
