(3659, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Potentiality of using allelopathy (an eco-friendly concept) to control weeds in rice field', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2010', '1.	To compare the effectiveness of rice straw and water hyacinth in controlling weeds in rice field. \r\n2.	To determine the suitability of using rice straw and water hyacinth in improving soil health. \r\n3.	To find out the optimum concentration of rice straw and water hyacinth to control weeds in rice field. \r\n4.	To determine the performance of rice straw and water hyacinth to increase yield of rice.\r\n', 'The experiment was conducted at the Agronomy field of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University, Dhaka during the period from November 2009 to June 2010. The farm belongs to the general soil type, Shallow Red Brown Terrace Soils under Tejgaon Series. The land was above flood level and sufficient sunshine was available during the experimental period. Soil sample from 15 cm depth were collected from experimental field before start of the experiment as well as after harvest of the crop. The analyses were done by Soil Resources and Development Institute (SRD1), Dhaka. The physicochemical properties of the soil of the experimentatal soil was presented in Appendix I. The seeds of two rice varieties namely BRRI dhan29 and BRRI hybriddhan2 were collected from Bangladesh Rice Research Institute (BRRI), Joydebpur, Gazipur on 09 December, 2009. \r\nThe collected seeds were soaked in water for 48 hours and then tied in two separate bags those covered with jute sacks for sprouting. The tied bags were frequently monitored and moistened when dried to ensure better and uniform sprouting of the seeds. A small land in a sunny place, free from waterlogging was selected as a seedbed that ploughed and cross ploughed, watered and finally prepared as a standard wet seedbed. The sprouted seeds were spread in two separate beds those optimally prepared for better germination of seeds. The beds were watered and watched for few days to save the seeds from bird attacked and other hazards. The seedbed was carefully monitored to ensure water and other intercultural operations were done as and when needed. Fertilization and other plant protection measures were taken as per necessity for getting healthy seedlings. As per the findings of Naguchi and Salam (2008), the rice straw of variety BRRI dhan38 having Allelochemical properties was collected and prepared as a planting material for the experiment. The collected rice straw was cut into small pieces for easy incorporation in the main field. As a part of experimental material the fresh materials of Water hyacinth (Eichhornia crassipes) was collected, cut into small pieces for easy application and incorporation in the main field. An area of 35m x 30m was marked as a main experimental plot. The plot was ploughed and cross ploughed with the help of disc plough and harrow. The land was watered and finally leveled with leveler to ensure uniform application of water. The lay-out of the experiment was done by maintaining 4m x 3m plot having 1m gap between two main plot, sub-plot as well as sub sub-plot and 1.5m gap between two replications (Appendix II). The ails of the entire marked sub sub&not;plot, sub-plot, main plot and replications were bunded by making ridge with the help of soil collected from the gaps. The plots were then ready to accept different treatment materials, fertilizers, seedlings etc. The whole plot was manured with cowdung @ 10 t/ha that spread 15 days before ploughing. The chemical fertilizers were used @ 120-40-45- 10-5 kg NPKSZn/ha respectively. The whole amount of all fertilizers except urea was applied as a basal dose on 23rd January, 2010. The urea fertilizer was top dressed in three equal installments on 7 days after transplanting (28/01/2010) after seedlings recovery.\r\n', 'The project was initiated during 2009 with the financial support of Ministry of Science and Information (S''z, Communication Technology (MSICT) of which the experiment entitled &quot;Potentiality of using Allelopathy (an eco-friendly concept) to Control Weeds in Rice Field&quot; was conducted in Bora season, 2009 -2010. The objectives of the project was to compare the performance of Water hyacinth and Rice straw to control weeds of two rice varieties as well as to improve soil health and crop yield having different concentrations. Two rice varieties included in the study were BRRI dhan29 and BRRI hybriddhan2 that assigned to the main plot. Two Allelopathic materials viz. Rice straw and Water hyacinth were in the sub-plot and three concentrations of Allelopathic materials viz. no Allelopathic material (control), 0.50 kg/m2 and 1.00 kg/m2 in the sub sub-plot. The 40 days old seedlings were transplanted on January 23, 2010 maintaining 25cm x I5cm spacing with two seedlings/hill. Results showed that hybrid variety with 0.50 to 1.00 kg/m2 Rice straw showed the lowest number of weeds/m2 at 30 days after transplantation but at 50 days after transplantation the lowest number of weeds/m2 was found in the control treatment. The highest number of effective tillers/hill (19.67) was given by the variety BRRI dhan29 with 1.00 kg/m2 of Water hyacinth application. In respect of grain yield, the highest yield (7.50 t/ha) was found in the hybrid variety with 1.0 kg/m2 of Water hyacinth application and the lowest yield (5.36 t/ha) was given by the control treatment of BRRI dhan29. It may be concluded from the study that Rice straw had Allelochemical that control weeds in the initial stage of the crop but at 50 days after transplantation it has no effects on it. On the other hand Water hyacinth has the potentiality to add nutrients to the soil that reflected on the growth of the crop as well as higher yield.', '', 'MOST', 500000, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Weeds', 'Rice', '', '', ''),
(3660, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Conrol of weeds in rice field using allelopathy (an eco-friendly concept)', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-11-2010', '31-10-2011', '01-11-2010', '31-10-2011', '1. to evaluate the allelopathic potential of different naturally grown plants.\r\n2. to find  out farmer''s friendly method for controlling weeds.\r\n3. to identify the promising and potential plant residues/extracts for increasing rice production.', 'The research project was completed in the Agronomy department of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University, Dhaka during the period from July 2010 to June 2011. The experimental farm belongs to the general soil type, Shallow Red Brown Terrace Soils under Tejgaon Series. The land was above flood level and sufficient sunshine was available during the experimental period. Soil sample from 15 cm depth were collected from experimental field before start of the experiment as well as after harvest of the crop. The seeds of three rice varieties namely BRRI dhan46, Guti Swarna and Ranjit were collected from Bangladesh Rice Research Institute (BRRI), Joydebpur, Gazipur and local area of Rangpur on June, 2010. The collected seeds were soaked in water for 24 hours and then tied in three separate bags those covered with jute\r\nsacks for sprouting. The tied bags were frequently monitored and moistened when dried to ensure better and uniform sprouting of the seeds. A small land in a sunny place, free from waterlogging was selected as a seedbed that ploughed and cross ploughed, watered and finally prepared as a standard wet seedbed. The sprouted seeds were spread in three separate beds those optimally prepared for better germination of seeds. The beds were watered and watched for few days to save the seeds from bird attacked and other hazards. The seedbed was carefully monitored and other intercultural operations were done as and when needed. Fertilization and other plant protection measures were taken as per necessity for getting healthy seedlings. The allelopathic materials of Lantena camera, Goose weed, Bon sarisha and Araich were collected from nearby fields and roadside those prepared as a planting material for the experiment. The collected materials were dried and cut into small pieces for easy incorporation in the main field. An area of 37m x 26m was marked as a main experimental plot. The plot was ploughed and cross ploughed with the help of disc plough and harrow. The land was watered and finally leveled with leveler to ensure uniform application of water. The lay-out of the experiment was done by maintaining 4m x 3m plot having 1 m gap between two main plot, sub-plot as well as between two replications. The ails of all the marked sub-plot, main plot and replications were bunded by raising soil above. The plots were then ready to accept different treatment materials, fertilizers, seedlings etc. The whole plot was manured with cowdung @ 10 t/ha that spread 15 days before ploughing. The chemical fertilizers were used @ 100-70-45-10-5 kg NPKSZn/ha respectively. The whole amount of all fertilizers except urea was applied as a basal dose on 2nd August, 2010. The urea fertilizer was top dressed in three equal installments on 7 days after transplanting (09/08/2010) after seedlings recovery, 25/08/2010 and 11/09/2010. The prepared Lantena camara, goose weed, bon sarisha and araich were weighed and transferred to the plot, spread uniformly to the plot as per treatment and incorporate well to the soil on 02/08/2010. The seedlings of three rice varieties were uprooted carefully, transferred to the main field and transplanted on August 02, 2010. The spacing was maintained as 25 cm x 15 cm having 2 seedlings/hill. All the three replications were transplanted on the same day as per layout.\r\nThe experiment was laid out in a split-plot design with three replications. The three varieties namely BRRI dhan46 (V1), Guti Swarna (V2) and Ranjit (V3) were assigned in the main plot and five allelopathic materials namely Control (Mo), Lantena camera (Mi), Goose weed (M2), Bon sarisha (M3), and Araich (M4) in the sub sub-plot. The gap filling was done on August 15, 2010 as per necessity by retransplanting of seedlings to the missed/damaged hills. Water was ensured to the field in such a way that there should not have any scarcity of water that affects the experiment. Two hand weedings were done on August 25, 2010 and September 18, 2010 when weeding data were taken using a quadrat. The collected weeds from different treatments were separated, identified and recorded as per their number as well as dry weight. The field was infested by different insects and diseases those controlled by applying appropriate ways in time. The Guti Swarna variety was matured earlier than the other two varieties. The Guti Swarna variety was harvested on November 25, 2010 and the BRRI dhan46 and Ranjit on December 03, 2010. Ten hills per plot was randomly selected from very beginning for collecting plant height, yield contributing and other relevant data like number of effective and ineffective tillers per hill, length of panicle, number of filled and unfilled grains per panicle, grain weight and straw weight. The weed density and dry weight were measured at 20 DAT and 40 DAT. The grain yield and straw yield were recorded by harvesting the inner six lines from each plot to avoid boarder effects. The harvested plants were threshed &amp; dried to a constant moisture level. Statistical analyses were done by using the IRRISTAT computer package developed by IRRI and the mean differences among the treatments were compared by least significant difference test at 5 % level of significance following Gomez and Gomez (1984).\r\n', 'The project was initiated during 2010 with the financial support of Ministry of Science and Information &amp; Communication Technology (MSICT) of which the experiment entitled &quot;Control of weeds in rice field using Allelopathy (an eco-friendly concept)&quot; was conducted in Aman season, 2010. The objectives of the project was to evaluate the allelopathic potential of different naturally grown plants for controlling weeds and increasing rice production. Three rice varieties included in the study were BRRI dhan46, Guti Swarna and Ranjit that assigned to the main plot. Five Allelopathic treatments viz. Control (no allelopathic material), Lantena camera, Goose weed, Bon sarisha and Araich were in the sub-plots. The concentration of allelopathic materials was 0.50 kgm-2. The 30 days old seedlings were transplanted on August 02, 2010 maintaining 25cm x 15cm spacing with two seedlings/hill. Results showed that hybrid variety with 0.50 to 1.00 kg/m2 Rice straw showed the lowest number of weeds/m2 at 30 days after transplantation but at 50 days after transplantation the lowest number of weeds/m2 was found in the control treatment. The highest number of effective tillers/hill (19.67) was given by the variety BRRI dhan29 with 1.00 kg/m2 of Water hyacinth application. In respect of grain yield, the highest yield (7.50 t/ha) was found in the hybrid variety with 1.0 kg/m2 of Water hyacinth application and the lowest yield (5.36 t/ha) was given by the control treatment of BRRI dhan29. It may be concluded from the study that Rice straw had Allelochemical that control weeds in the initial stage of the crop but at 50 days after transplantation it has no effects on it. On the other hand Water hyacinth has the potentiality to add nutrients to the soil that reflected on the growth of the crop as well as higher yield.', 'Rice, Weeds', 'MOSICT', 200000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Weeds', 'Rice', '', '', '');
