(3661, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Disease Diagnostic and Fish Health Management', 'Project', 'Investigation and identification of Causative Agent into the Emerging Disease of Fish and Development of their control strategies.', 'Fresh water station, Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institution (BFRI), Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2012', '1) Investigation and identification of dosease producing organism in farm fishes.\r\n2) Histological changes in different organs of diseased fish.\r\n3) Improvement of the fish farm bio-security through responsible use of chemotherapeutics \r\n4) Determination of relationship within climatic factor change, water quality parameter change and disease occurence\r\n5) Development of control strategies against emerging disease.', 'Investigation and Identification of disease producing organism in farm fish: Field observation and collection of disease fish:\r\nAffected farms will be visited to collect diseased fish. Local people, farm owner and fishermen will be interviewed through questionnaire to collect information regarding diseases. Possible recommendations will be made immediately accordingly the farm owners. Moribun disease fish will be transported to the laboratory for necessary study.\r\nLaboratory examination will be done on:\r\na)	Clinical study\r\nb)	Parasitological study\r\nc)	Bacteriology study\r\nd)	Mycological study\r\ne)	Water quality (pH, DO, hardness, alkalinity and ammonia) ii Histological changes in different organs of diseased fish :\r\nDifferent organs of diseased fish will be investigated through histological study &amp; interpretation will be made\r\niii.	Improvement of the fish farm bio-security throught responsible use of chemotherapeutics\r\nFor the purpose of fish farm bio-security with responsible use of antibiotics, growth promoter, Aqua drugs,\r\niv.	Determination of relationship within Climatic factor change, Water quality parameter change and Disease occurrence:\r\nDiseases causing severe mortality in P. hypopthalmus, H fossilis and A. testudineus and Oreochromis niloticus. Therefore, in order to identify the causative agents(s) such as parasites, bacteria, and fungus epidemiological data will be collected on P. hypopthalmus, H. fossilis and A. testudineus. Oreochromis niloticus. Suitable diagnostic techniques will be applied to diagnose the diseases. Water quality parameters responsible for causing diseases in fish will also be tested on the spot for better understanding of the occurrence of diseases. For\r\nthe determination of relationship within climatic factor change, water quality parameter change and disease occurrence will be studied.\r\n-	Study will be carried out on pond and beds once in a month\r\n-	Water parameters(depth, pH, DO, hardness, alkalinity and ammonia) will be tested on spot\r\n-	Spread pattern of disease and seasonal changes related to disease outbreak will be observed\r\n-	Species specificity will be observed\r\n-	The relationship within climatic factors change, water quality parameters change and disease occurrence will be determined.\r\n\r\nDevelopment of control strategies against emerging diseases of fish following trials will be conducted:\r\n- The pathogen will be collected and stored in lab.\r\n- Suitable medicinal materials (chemotherapeutics, antibiotics will be selected\r\n - Treatment trial in aquarium and mini pond\r\nControl strategies will be developed by applying better health management practices and commercially available, low cost, eco-friendly and safe drugs, both at aquarium and pond level.\r\n', '', 'Histological changes, climatic factor change, water quality parameter change, emerging disease', 'GOB', 800000, 800000, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Disease management', 'Fish', '1) Targeted fish production will be achieved if preventive measures are taken in time.\r\n2) Effective control strategies will be developed to minimize mortality due to disease\r\n3) Relationship will be determined between climatic factor changes with disease occurrences\r\n4) Better management practices will be developed if fish health management at the farm level is addressed', 'Better health management, preventive measures and disease control will minimize fish mortality and overall will increase fish production at the farm level.', ''),
(3662, 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University Research Facilities Improvement ', 'Sher-e-Bangladesh', 'High', 'Applied', '', '01-01-2011', '31-12-2013', '01-01-2011', '31-12-2013', '1. to enrich existing research facilities of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University.\r\n2. to facilitate the faculoties and student''s of Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University for conducting quality research.\r\n3. to strengthen the technology/knowledge bank of the University', '', '', '', 'HEQEP-UGC', 17368000, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Improvement', 'Agriculture (Crops)', '', '', ''),
(3663, 'Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute', 'Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Optimization of Stocking Density (Tilapia, Thai Pangas and common carp) and Impact Analysis of Cage Culture in the River Brahamputra, Mymensingh', 'Brahmaputra River, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2012', '1) To optimize the suitable stocking density of common carp (Cyprinus carpio) in net cages.\r\n2) To develop improved cage management and feeding techniques; and\r\n3) To analyze the cost-benefit ratio.', '', '', 'Tilapia, Thai Pangas and common carp, Cage culture, Brahmaputra River, ', 'GOB', 1800000, 1200000, 600000, 'Report', '', 0, 'Cage Culture', 'Tilapia, Thai Pangas and common carp', 'Suitable stocking density and improved cage management technique will be expanded', 'Fish production will be increased in the Brahmaputra river areas of Mymensingh through cage culture.', ''),
(3664, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated nutrient management for Cauliflower', 'BARI Central Farm, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '(i) to find out the contribution of macro and micronutrients along with cowdung on the yield of cauliflower and (ii) to update balanced fertilizer recommendation for target yield', 'Full dose of PKSZnBMo and 1/3 N were applied at the time of final land preparation and the remaining N was top dressed in two equal installments at 21 and 42 days after planting. Well decomposed cowdung was applied in the individual pits prior to planting as per treatments imposed. One month aged healthy seedlings of Snowball variety was transplanted maintaining a spacing of 40 cm in 60 cm apart rows. Intercultural operations and plant protection measures were done to ensure luxuriant growth of the crop. Harvesting was done when the heads attained proper size and were at the right stage of maturity (heads were remained compact but had not brocken into segments). The harvesting was lasted for 18 days. Ten plants from each plot were tagged at random to keep records on plant height, number of leaves plant-1, curd weight and curd circumference. Yield of the curd (t ha-1) was determined on the basis of per plot yield. A total of 24 post harvest soil samples were collected and analyzed in the laboratory to see the fertility status of the soil. Cowdung sample was also analyzed to know its nutrient composition. Finally data was statistically analyzed using IRRISTAT Package.', 'A field experiment on cauliflower (Brassica oleracia) was carried out during the rabi season of 1997 and 1998 in Chhiata series of the grey Terrace soil (Albaquepts) under AEZ-28 of BARI Central Farm, Gazipur. The objectives were (i) to find out the contribution of macro and micronutrients along with cowdung on the yield of cauliflower and (ii) to update balanced fertilizer recommendation for target yield. The experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with 6 treatments viz. T1 = N150 P45 K80 S20 Zn5 B2 Mo1 kg-1 (RD): T2 = 50% of RD + cowdung @ 10 t ha-1; T3 = 50% RD of NPK + cowdung @ 10 t ha-1; T4 = 50% RD of S Zn B Mo + cowdung @ 10 t ha-1; T5 = Cowdung @ 10 t ha-1 and T6 = Absolute control. The mean highest yield (36.53 t ha-1) was obtained from the treatment T1 which was statistically significant over all other treatments. The second highest yield (30.37 t ha-1) was derived from T2 which was statistically inferior to T1 but significant over rest of the treatments. However, T2 produced 219% higher yield over control whereas the sole and higher rates of chemical fertilizer (T1) contributed 284%. Moderate yield (24.69 t ha-1) was obtained from T3 indicating that a package of NPK fertilizer along with cowdung may be suitable for the marginal farmers. Cowdung alone (T5) or in combination with micronutrient fertilizer (T4)  produced significantly higher yield over absolute control (T6). The yield components like plant height, no. of leaves per plant did not differ significantly where comparison were made between T1 and T2 but in other cases, this parameters varied significantly. The fertility status of the soil was tended to improve where both cowdung and chemical fertilizers were applied in an integrated approach. From economic analysis, treatment T1 appeared at the best producing the maximum marginal rate of return (3689%) along with the highest gross margin of Tk. 2,74,638 ha-1 yr-1 followed by T3. However, integrated approach of nutrient management was found beneficial in respect of yield sustainability and to maintain soil fertility.', 'Macro and micronutrients, Soil fertility, Target yield, Gross margin, Cauliflower', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Cauliflower', 'Highest doses of chemical fertilizers produced the highest yield with better economic return but integrated management of nutrients from both organic manure and inorganic fertilizers even with the reduced dose was found beneficial in respect of yield sustainability and improved soil fertility.', 'Integrated nutrient management like both the chemical fertilizers and organic fertilizers together keep the soil healthy and improve soil fertility.', ''),
(3665, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Integrated use of organic and inorganic fertilizer on the production of tomato', 'Horticulture farm,  BAU, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-10-2003', '31-03-2004', '01-10-2003', '31-03-2004', ' i) to study the effect of cow dung, poultry manure and mustard oil cake on the growth and yield of tomato; ii) to identify the suitable organic manure which would be better for tomato cultivation, and iii) to compare the growth and yield of tomato raised through use of organic and inorganic fertilizer.\r\n', 'The experiment was carried out at the Horticulture Farm of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh, during the period from October 2003 to March 2004. The soil of the experimental field was silty loam with the pH of 6.7. The analytical data of the soil have been presented in Table 1. The tomato cultivar used in the experiment was BARI Tomato-2 (Ratan). The experiment consisted of five treatments viz: 11= Cow dung (15 t ha-1), T2 = Poultry manure (10 t ha 1), T3 = Mustard oil cake (5 t ha-1), T4 = Inorganic fertilizer (550 kg urea ha-1 + 450 kg TSP ha-1 + 250 kg MoP ha-1) and T5 = Inorganic + organic fertilizer (550 kg urea ha-1 + 450 kg TSP ha-1 + 250 kg MoP ha-1 + 15 t cow dung ha-'').The experiment was laid out in Randomized Complete Block Design (RCBD) with three replications. Thirty day old seedlings were transplanted on 20 November during the Rabi season of 2003. Intercultural operations such as gap filling, weeding, staking, pruning, irrigation, and plant protection measures were taken as and when necessary. The collected data were analyzed and the differences between the means were evaluated by the least significant difference (LSD) test at 5% level of probability. ', 'An experiment was conducted at the Horticulture Farm of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during the period from October 2003 to March 2004 to evaluate the effect of organic and inorganic fertilizers on the production of tomato. The experiment consisted of five different treatments viz, cow dung, poultry manure, mustard oil cake, inorganic fertilizer, and inorganic + organic fertilizer. Different treatments showed significant variations on yield components and yield of tomato. Poultry manure treatment gave the best results on all the parameters except, fruit length, fruit diameter and weight of individual fruit. The highest number of leaves, number of flower clusters, total number of flowers and fruits plant-1, number of flowers cluster-'' and yield of tomato (89.6 t ha-1) were obtained from poultry manure treatment. On the contrary, the lowest values of all these parameters and yield (68.8 t ha-1) were recoded from cow dung treatment. The highest fruit length (5.44 cm), fruit diameter (5.56 cm) and individual fruit weight (90.7 g) were recorded from the inorganic treatments. The highest gross income (Tk. 716640 ha-1), net return (Tk. 658837 ha-1) and benefit cost ratio -(12.4) were recorded from the poultry manure treatment. The performance of organic and inorganic fertilizers on tomato production followed the pattern as poultry manure &gt; mustard oil cake &gt; inorganic fertilizer &gt; inorganic + organic fertilizer &gt; cow dung.', 'Tomato, Integrated nugtrient management, Organic manure, Inorganic fertilizer.', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Tomatoes', 'The findings of the experiment indicated that the best yield and the highest financial benefit could be obtained from poultry manure treatment. So, it may be concluded that comparatively better tomato production in possible by using poultry manure rather than using other organic and inorganic fertilizers. ', 'Peoples will be Inspiration to use poultry manure for better and more tomato production.', ''),
(3666, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Tomato Okra-Indian Spinach Cropping Pattern', 'Farmer''s homestead of Elenga (AEZ-8), Tangail.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '1. to minimizing the use of chemical fertilizers through the use of organic manure; and\r\n2. to find out the suitable combination of chemical fertilizers and organic manure for sustainable crop yield.  ', 'Field experiments on Tomato-Okra-Indian Spinach cropping pattern were conducted under irrigated condition at farmer''s homestead of FSRD site, Elenga, Tangail during 2007-08 and 2008-09. The experimental site was medium high land which belongs to Young Brahmaputra and Jamuna Floodplain (AEZ-8). The initial soil test values of the experimental field are presented in Table 1. Nutrient contents of the organic manure used in the experiment are shown in Table 2. Each ton of poultry manure may supply 4.82 kg N, 7.74 kg P, 4.94 kg K, and 2.58 kg S while the contribution of cowdung estimated to be 3.48 kg N, 4.80 kg P. 3.0 kg K and 1.8 kg S. The heavy metal content in poultry manure was found to be at minimum level. Organic matter (OM) content of the initial soil was very low. The soil was also deficient in total N, exchangeable K, available S and Zn to a great extent. There were 5 treatment combinations taking 100%, 75% and 50% recommended dose of chemical fertilizers (RCF) with or without manure. The manure dose for tomato was 5 t ha-1 cowdung or poultry manure in combination with both 75% and 50% RCF. For olcia, the manure dose was 2.5 t ha-1 in combination with 75% RCF and 5 t ha-1 in combination with 50% RCF. Following crop, Indian spinach was treated with 100%, 75% and 50% recommended urea-N only (table 3). \r\nTable 1. Initial nutrient status of the experimental field.\r\nLocation	pH	OM\r\n0,\r\n''	Ca	Mg	K	Total N%	P	S	B	Cu j	Fe	Mn	Zn\r\n			meq100 9-1			J9 9\r\nElenga,\r\nTangail	5.9	0.75	5.6	1.5	0.12	0.08	17	15	0.34	6	228	25	1.3\r\nCritical level	-	-	2.0	0.8	0.20	-	14	14	0.20	1	10	5	2.0\r\n\r\nTable 2. Nutrient status of the organic manure used in the experimental field.\r\nName of the manure	Moisture\r\n%	\r\npH	OM	Ca	Mg	K	N	P	S	B	Zn	Pb	Cd	As\r\n			%	&micro;G G-1\r\nPoultry\r\nmanure	57	7.4	20.1	5.50	2.60	1.15	1.12	1.8	0.6	0.012	0.11	10.0	Tr.	3.13\r\nCowdung	40	7.0	8.32	1.12	0.32	0.50	0.58	0.8	0.3	0.013	0.15	-	-	-\r\n\r\n\r\nBARI Tomato-8, BARI Derosh-1, BARI Puishak-1 were tested varieties for Tomato, Okra and Indian Spinach, respectively. The experiment was laid out in a Randomized Complete Block Design with four replications. The unit plot size was 2.4m x 2.2m. The experiment was initiated in the Rabi season with Tomato (October- February) as the first crop followed by Okra (March - Mid July) and Indian spinach (Late July - September). The spacing for both Tomato and Okra were 60 cm x 40 cm and for Indian spinach was 30cm x 10cm. The sources of N, P, K, S, Zn and B were urea, TSP, MP, gypsum, zinc sulphate (monohydrate) and boric acid, receptively. In case of tomato, recommended chemical fertilizers dose was N150 P40  K80 S20 Zri2 B1 kg ha-1 while it was Ni201335K70S15 Z112Bi kg ha-1 and N120 kg ha-1 for okra and Indian spinach, respectively (FRG, 2005). In case of tomato the whole amount of P, K, S, Zn, B, cow dung and poultry manure were applied during final land preparation and 1/3 N was applied before transplanting. The remaining 2/3N was applied in two equal installments at 25 and 40 days after transplanting. In case of okra, the whole amount of P, K, S, Zn, B, cowdung and poultry manure were applied during final land preparation and N was applied in three equal installments at 20, 40 and 60 days after sowing. In case of Indian spinach, the entire amount of N was applied in two equal installments at 15 and 30 days after sowing. After harvesting of the first crop (tomato), the plots were prepared for sowing the next crop, okra. Again, after harvesting of the second crop, the plots were prepared for sowing Indian spinach. All intercultural operations such weeding, mulching, irrigation and pest management were done as and when required. The crops were harvested on whole plot basis. Data were analyzed by computer using MSTAT-C Package while mean separation was done by LSD.Methods of chemical analysis.\r\nMethods of chemical analysis:\r\nSoil pH was measured by a combined glass calomel electrode pH meter using soil: water ratio of 1:2.5 (Jakson, 1958). Organic carbon was determined by wet oxidation method as described by Walkley and Black (1935). Total N was determined by micro Kjeldahl method (Bremner and Mulvency, 1982). Ca and Mg were measured extracting with 1N KC1 following ASI method (Hunter, 1984). P, K, Cu, Fe, Mn and Zn were extracted by a single solution (0.25 N NaHCO3, 0.01 M disodium EDTA and 0.01 N NH4) as described by Hunter, 1984. Sulphur was extracted by calcium phosphate and the concentration of available S was determined by turbidimetrically with BaCl2. Boron was determined by hot water extraction method. The total nutrient and heavy metal contents in manure samples were determined digesting with concentrated nitric and perchloric acid mixture (Yoshida et al, 1976).\r\n ', 'Field experiment on Tomato-Okra- Indian spinach cropping pattern was conducted at a farmer''s homestead of Tangail (AEZ 8) during 2007-08 and 2008-09 to find out a suitable combination of chemical fertilizers and organic manure for sustainable crop yield. There were 5 treatments comprising different percentages of the recommended chemical fertilizers (RCF) with two levels (0 and 5 t ha-1) for tomato and three levels (0, 2.5 and 5 t ha-1) for okra each of poultry manure and cowdung. No organic manure was used for the third crop Indian Spinach. The treatments were arranged in Randomized Complete Block Design with four replications. An amount of 75% dose of RCF (NisoP 401(soS2oZn2Bikg ha-1) along with poultry manure @ 5 t ha-1 appeared as the best suited combination providing tomato yield 95.3 t ha-1 and 88.2 t ha-1 for the first year and second year, respectively. Again, an amount of 75% doe of RCF (Ni20P35k70S15Zn2B1 kg ha-1) along with poultry manure @ 2.5 t ha-1 appeared as the best package providing the highest okra yield (15.03 t ha-1 and 12.98 t ha-1). The highest yield (36.3 t ha-1 and 33.7 t ha-1 for the first and second year, respectively) of Indian spinach was recorded from (75% recommended N + PM residue), which was statistically identical with (100 % recommended N) but significantly higher over rest of the treatments. Poultry manure performed better over cow dung. A package of 75% recommended chemical fertilizer along with 5 t PM ha-1 appeared as the best suited combination providing higher yield and economic return.', 'Soil fertility, Integrated nutrient management, Blanced Fertilization, Tomato, Okra, Indian spinach, Sustainable yield. ', 'MOSICT', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Nutrition', 'Tomatoes', 'The yield of the pattern Tomato-Okra-Indian Spinach increased significantly due to integrated use of chemical fertilizer and organic manure in the homestead under AEZ-8. Use of poultry manure may reduce the use of chemical fertilizer up to 25% from the conventional recommendation. A package of 75% recommended chemical fertilizer along with 5 t PM ha-1 appeared as the best suited combination providing higher yield and economic return.', 'Farmer will be use of poultry manure in the field and they get more tomato production significantly.', ''),
(3667, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Effects of Cowdung, Poultry Manure and Fertilizers on the growth and Yield of Wheat', 'Soil Science Field Laboratory, Bangladesh Agricultural University (BAU), Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '03-12-2000', '31-03-2001', '03-12-2000', '31-03-2001', '1) to study the effect of cowdung and poultry manure on growth and yield of wheat\r\n2) to study the effect of fertilizers on the growth, yield and quality of wheat.\r\n3) to study the combined effect of organic manure and fertilizers on the growth and yield of wheat\r\n4) to study the effect of cowdung, poultry manure and fertilizers on the nutrient content and uptake by wheat\r\n5) to study some characteristics of the post harvest soil.', 'The experiment was conducted at the field laboratory of the department of soil science, Bangladesh Agricultural University (BAU), Mymensingh, during the period from 3rd December 2000 to 25th March 2001 to examine the effects of cowdung, poultry manure and fertilizers (N, P, K, S, Zn and B) on the growth and yield of wheat cv. Kanchan. There were twelve treatments: T0 (control), T1 (Cowdung), T2 (Poultry manure), T3 (NPK), T4 (NPK + Cowdung), T5 (NPK + Poultry manure), T6 (NPKS), T7 (NPKSZn), T8 (NPKSZnB), T9 (NPKS + Poultry manure), T10 (NPKSZn + Poultry manure), T11 (NPKSZnB + Poultry manure). The experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with three replications. The rates of different organic manures and fertilizers were 5 t ha-1, Poultry manure 5 t ha-1, 90 kg N ha-1 from urea, 40 kg P2O5 from TSP, 60 kg K2O ha-1 from MP, 20 kg S ha-1 from Gypsum, 3 kg Zn ha-1 from ZnO and 1 kg B ha-1 from Borax. There were 36 (12 &times; 3) unit plots, each plot measuring 4.0 &times; 2.5 m2 , plots were separated from each other by a space of 20 cm and block distance 1m. During growing period of wheat, all necessary cares were done for ensuring and maintaining the normal growth and development of the crop. The physical and chemical properties of the soils were reported to be sand 22.84%, silt 70.0%, clay 7.16%, textural class silt loam, pH 7.22, organic matter 1.71%, total N 0.063%, available P 9.44 &micro;g gm-1, available S 13.34 &micro;g gm-1, exchangeable K 0.139 me 100g-1 soil and CEC 10.35 me 100g-1 soil.', 'A field experiment was conducted at the Soil Science Field Laboratory of Bangladesh Agricultural University (BAU), Mymensingh during the winter season of 2000-2001 with a view to study the effects of cowdung, poultry manure and fertilizers on the growth and yield of wheat (cv. Kanchan). There were twelve treatments T0 (control), T1 (CD), T2 (PM), T3 (NPK), T4 (NPK + CD), T5 (NPK + PM), T6 (NPKS), T7 (NPKSZn), T8 (NPKSZnB), T9 (NPKS + PM), T10 (NPKSZn + PM), T11 (NPKSZnB + PM). The experiment was set up in a randomized complete block design with three replications for each treatment. The rates of different fertilizers were 90 kg N from urea, 40 kg P2O5 from TSP, 60 kg K2O from MP, 20 kg S from gypsum, 3 kg Zn from ZnO and 1 kg B from borax per hectare. The result showed that the different treatments significantly influenced grain and straw yields of wheat. All treatments exerted positive effect on the growth parameters (plant height, tillers hill-1, spike length, spikelets spike-1, grains spike-1 and 1000-grain weight) and yield of wheat and the treatment T11 (NPKSZnB + PM) produced the highest grain and straw yield. The percent increase of grain and straw yields varied from 22.81 to 131.49 and 33.40 to 79.59 respectively, over control. The overall results indicate that for efficient wheat production in the area under study, application of poultry manure with NPKS, NPKSZn and NPKSZnB showed better result in all aspects of the experimental study.', 'Cowdung, Poultry manure, Fertilizers, Growth, Yield and Wheat', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Effect of organic and chemical fertilizers in crop production', 'Wheat', 'The application of NPKSZnB fertilizers with poultry manure increased the grain and straw yield of wheat cv. Kanchan. The combined application of organic manure and fertilizers were more beneficial for wheat production.', 'Organic manure and chemical fertilizers combined increase wheat production and keep soil fertility. ', ''),
(3668, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Evaluation of some Organic Manure on the yield of Cabbage under integrated nutrient management system', 'BARI Central Farm, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2002', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2002', '1) To find out the relative requirement of cowdung, poultry manure, oil cake and chemical fertilizer for maximizing the yield of cabbage and \r\n2) To evaluate the contribution of organic manures (cowdung, poultry manures and oil cake) in reducing the chemical fertilizer from the present recommendation. ', 'A field experiment with cabbage was carried out in the experimental field of Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute, Joydebpur, Gazipur during rabi season of 2000-2001 and 2001-2002. The soil belongs to the Chhiata series of the Grey Terrace Soils (Aeric Albaquept). Results on some physical and chemical properties of initial soil samples collected from 0-20 cm depth from the experimental field are presented in Table-1.\r\nTable 1. Texture and fertility status if initial soil sample at central farm, BARI, Gazipur\r\nTexture	p-H	OM	Ca	Mg	K	Total N%	P	S	B	Cu	Fe	Mn	Zn\r\n			Meq 100-1 g		                                      &micro;g g-1\r\nSilty clay	6.2	1.5	12	4.1	0.17	0.08	15	17	0.24	5.67	120	13	2.7\r\nCritical level	2.0	0.8	0.2	-	14	14	0.2	1	10	5	2\r\n\r\nThe soil was silty clay in texture having pH 6.2 and low in organic matter, total-N, available P, B and exchangeable K. The experiment was set up in randomized complete block design with 3 replications. There were 27 plots having an area of 3.0 m &times; 2.4 m each. Healthy cabbage (Atlas-70) seedlings of equal size (25 days old) were transplanted in rabi season with a spacing of 60 cm from row to row and 60 cm from plant to plant. There were nine treatments viz. T1 : 250-35-80-40-2-1 kg ha-1 (RD) of N-P-K-S-B-Mo, T2: 70% of RD, T3: 70% RD + 5 t CD ha-1, T4: 70% RD + 10 t CD ha-1, T5: 70% of RD + 5 t PM ha-1, T6: 70% RD + 10 t PM ha-1, T7: 70% RD + 2.5 t OC ha-1, T8: 70% RD + 5 t OC ha-1 and T9: absolute control. Urea, TSP, MP, gypsum, boric acid and sodium molybdate were used as source of N, P, K, S, B and Mo, respectively. All P, K, S, B, Mo, cowdung, poultry manure, oil cake and 1/3 N were applied at the time of final land preparation and the remaining 2/3 N was applied in two equal installments at 21 and 42 days after planting. Cowdung, poultry manure and oil cake used in the study were also analyzed and data are presented in Table 2.\r\nTable 2. Nutrient status of the oil cake, poultry manure and cowdung used in the experimental field\r\nOrganic manure	N	P	K	Ca	Mg	S	Mn	Zn\r\n	                                                     %	          &micro;g g-1\r\nOil Cake	4.9	0.8	1.48	4.4	1.6	2.4	0.42	1.2\r\nPoultry manure	1.8	1.6	1.64	8.5	6.2	1.6	0.92	1.5\r\nCowdung	0.8	0.5	0.9	0.6	0.31	0.3	0.89	1.0\r\n\r\nOil cake was very rich in nutrient content followed by poultry manure while cowdung contained much lower amount of plant nutrients. All intercultural operations such as weeding, irrigation etc. were done as and when necessary to raise healthy crop. Harvesting was done when the head attained proper size and at the right stage of maturity. As all the heads did not develop uniformly, the harvesting lasted for 17 days. Ten plants from each plot were tagged at random to take records on number of unfold leaves, head circumference and yield. The yield and yield attributes data were analyzed statistically and the mean differences were tested by Duncans Multiple Range Test (Steel and Torrie, 1960). Particle size distribution was done by hydrometer method, the textural class was ascertained using Marshalss traiangular co-ordinates and soil pH was measured with a combined glass calomel electrode (Jackson, 1958). Exchangeable K and available P, S, Cu, Fe, Mn, Zn and B were analyzed following standard laboratory procedures (Hunter, 1984).\r\n\r\n', 'Field experiment were conducted to estimate the relative requirement of cowdung (CD), poultry manure (PM), oil cake (OC) and chemical fertilizer on the yield of cabbage and to evaluate the contribution of organic manures in reducing the chemical fertilizers during the rabi seasons of 2000-2001 and 2001-2002 in Chhiata series of the grey Terrace Soil at BARI Central Farm, Gazipur. A total of 9 treatments comprising 3 levels each of cowdung and poultry manure (0, 5 and 10 t ha-1) as well as oil cake (0, 2.5 and 5.0 t ha-1) along with 70% of the recommended dose (RD) of chemical fertilizer (N250 P36 K80 S40 B2 Mo1 kg ha-1) were used in the study. The experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with 3 replications. The highest mean yield (87.10 t ha-1) was obtained from T8 (70% RD + 5 t OC ha-1), which was significantly higher over all other treatments except T6 (70% RD + 10 t PM ha-1) and T7 (70% RD + 2.5 OC ha-1). The second highest mean yield (84.75 t ha-1) was obtained from T7 followed by T6, which was statistically identical with T8 but significantly greater over rest of the treatments. The treatment package T5 (70% RD + 5 t PM ha-1) may be recommended for the marginal farmers whereas resource rich farmers may use either T7 (70 RD + 2.5 t OC ha-1) or T6 (70% Rd + 10 t PM ha-1) for maximum gross margin.', 'Organic manure, Chemical fertilizers, Recommended dose, Cabbage yield, Terrace Soil, Gross margin', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Cabbage', 'A package of 70% recommended dose of chemical fertilizer (N175 P25 K56 S28 B1.4 Mo0.7 kg ha-1) along with 5 t ha-1 poultry manure may be recommended for the cultivation of cabbage in Grey Terrace Soil of Joydebpur for yield sustainability and economic profitability. However, rich farmers may use either 10 t PM or 2.5 t OC ha-1 instead of 5 t PM ha-1 along with 70% RD for highest gross margin. Use of 10 t PM or 2.5 OC is sufficient enough to reduce 30% chemical fertilizers from the present conventional recommendation. ', 'Organic fertilizers use normally reduce the use of chemical fertilizers and provide a profitable return.', ''),
(3669, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Efficacy of organic manures on the yield of Tomato grown under integrated nutrient management approach', 'BARI Central Farm, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2002', '30-06-2005', '01-07-2002', '30-06-2005', '1) To find out the response of tomato to chemical fertilizer and organic manure\r\n2) To find out the efficient organic manure in reducing the amount of chemical fertilizer from the conventional recommendation\r\n3) To determine the optimum rates of chemical fertilizer and organic manure for maximizing the yield of tomato.', 'Field experiments on tomato were carried out at BARI Central Farm, Gazipur during the rabi seasons of 2002-2003, 2003-2004 and 2004-2005.The soil belongs to the Chhiata series of the Grey Terrace Soil under AEZ-28. The fertility status of the initial soil was poor showing N, P, S and Zn below the critical level where as K was just at par. However, B status was medium and Mn, Fe and Cu level was higher. The  Cowdung and poultry manure were analyzed in the laboratory and the nutrient contents have been presented in Table 1. There were 12 treatment combinations (Table 2) having 3 replications, which was arranged in randomized complete block design. The unit plot size was 3.0 m &times; 2.4 m. The tested variety was BARI Tomato-9 (Lalima). Tomato seedlings (25 days old) were transplanted in rabi season with a spacing of line to line 60 cm and plant to plant 45 cm. Urea, TSP, MP, Gypsum, Zinc oxide and Boric acid were used as the source of N, P, K, S, Zn and B, respectively. All P, K, S, Zn, B, CD, PM and 1/3 N were applied at the time of final land preparation and the remaining 2/3 N was applied in two equal installment each at 3rd and 5th weeks after transplanting. Irrigation and other intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. The harvesting was done by picking the matured fruits and subsequent harvesting were tagged at random to take records on plant height, no. of fruits per plant and fruit weight per plant. Data on yield and yield contributing characters was recorded and statistically analyzed following IRRISTAT package. Particle size distribution of soil was done by hydrometer method, the textural class was ascettained using Marshalss triangular co-ordinate and soil pH was measured with a combined glass calomel electrode pH meter. Exchangeable K and  available P, S, Cu, Fe, Mn, Zn and B were analyzed following standard laboratory procedures. ', 'Field experiments on tomato (cv. BARI Tomato Lalima) were conducted in Chhiata series of the Grey Terrace Soil (Aeric Albaquept) under AEZ 28 at BARI Central Farm, Gazipur during the rabi seasons of 2002-2003, 2003-2004 and 2004-2005. The objectives were to find out the efficient organic manure in reducing the amount of chemical fertilizer from the conventional recommendation and to determine the optimum rates of chemical fertilizer and organic manure for maximizing the yield of tomato. Twelve treatments comprising different portions of the recommended dose (RD) of chemical fertilizers (N150 P45 K80 S25 Zn2 B1 kg ha-1) in combination with 4 levels of poultry manure (PM) (0, 2.5, 5 and 10 t ha-1) and 3 levels of cowdung (CD) (0, 2.5 and 10 t ha-1) were used in the study. Experiments were laid out in randomized complete block design with 3 replications. Poultry manure appeared as more efficient over cowdung in reducing the chemical fertilizer and also for maximizing the yield. Addition of 5 t PM ha-1 was found good enough to reduce 50% RD of chemical fertilizers. The highest mean yield (71.80 t ha-1) was obtained from T1 (100% RD + 2.5 t PM ha-1), which was statistically identical with T6 (50% RD + 10 t PM ha-1) and T5 (50% RD + 5 t PM ha-1) but significantly higher over rest of the treatments. Slight improvement in fertility status of soil was observed where poultry manure and chemical fertilizer were applied in integrated approach. The highest marginal rate of return (15285%) was obtained from T5 treatment. Considering the yield, economic benefit and soil fertility management aspects, the treatment T5 (50% RD + 5 t PM ha-1) may be recommended for the cultivation of Tomato in the study area. ', 'Organic manures, Chemical fertilizers, Recommended dose, Tomato yield, Terrace soil and gross margin', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Tomato', 'Poultry manure @ 5-10 t ha-1 along with 50% recommended dose of chemical fertilizers (N75, P23, K40, S13, Zn1, B0.5 kg ha-1) appeared as the best suited combination in respect of yield sustainability and to maintain soil fertility in the study area in order to fertility management by enriching the soil with organic matter and turning the vegetable cultivation towards organic farming.', 'Chemical fertilizers added with organic manures make the soil nutrient enrich and provide good production performance by keeping soil health.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque. Integrated Nutrient Management for Sustainable Crop Yield &amp; Soil Fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute. Publication No. 14, 2012'),
(3670, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy and Histology', 'Project', 'Mobilization of immunoglobulin (lg)- containing plasma cells in harderian gland, cecal tonsil and trachea of broilers vaccinated with Newcastle disease vaccine', '', '', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '', '', 'The present research was undertaken to study the histology and postnatal development of harderian gland, cecal tonsil and trachea of various groups of broilers and the response of baby chick ranikhet disease vaccines (BCRDV) on the mobilization of lgs cells during development of organs. Both histological and immunohistochemical studies were carried out on a twelve chickens, the chickens were grouped into vaccinated broilers (D14 and d28) and non-vaccinated broilers (D1). For histological study routine hematoxylin and eosin (H &amp; E) stain were used to study the capsule, lobule and acini of harderian gland, four histological layers of cecal tonsil, villi of cecal tonsil and four histological layers of trachea, tracheal cartilage. Indirect immunoperoxidase method was done to study the frequency and distribution of lgs- positive cels in the Harderian gland, cecal tonsil and trachea at various groups of chickens. In the present study, the harderian gland in all groups of chickens was a branched compound tubuloacinar gland surrounded by a capsule. The harderian gland surrounded by a thin, connective tissue capsule which was gradually thickened at a D28 group of chickens. The connective tissue septa from the capsule penetrate the gland, dividing the gland into unequal-sized numerous lobes and lobules. The length and breadth of the lobules of the Harderian gland at D28 group of chickens were significantly higher than D\r\n14 and D1 groups of chickens. The lumen of the lobule was irregular or sometimes regular in various groups of chickens. The lumen of the lobule was irregular or sometimes regular in various groups of chickens. The lumens of the acini were spherical, however, few of them were elongated, and the cell boundaries were distinctly visible. At D28 groups of chickens the frequency and distribution of lgM, IgG and lgA- positive cells were higher than the D14 and D1 groups of chickens. Among the Igs the IgG- containing positive cells were significantly higher at D28 and D14 groups of chickens followed by IgM and IgA- containing positive cells but the frequency of IgM-positive cells were higher than the lgG and positive cells at D1 group of chickens.\r\nIn cecal tonsil, abundant lymphocytes, lymphatic nodules and numerous plasma cells were found to be  observed in the villi, in the base of the villi and in the lamina propia and more seen at D28 group of chickens that D14 and D1. The size of  the villi of cecal tonsil was gradually higher in D28 group of chickens than D14 and D1 groups of chickens. At D28 group of chickens the frequency and distribution of IgG-positive cells were higher followed by IgA- positive cells were higher followed by IgM and IgA- positive cells. At D1 group of chickens the frequency and distribution of IgA- positive cells were higher followed by IgM and IgG- positive cells.\r\n\r\nIncrease of trachea, few plasma cells were distributed in the sub-epithelial layer. The size of tracheal cartilage was varied among the groups. At D28 group of chickens the length and breadth of tracheal cartilage were higher followed by D14 and D1 groups of chickens. At D28 group of  chickens IgM- containing positive cells ere higher followed by IgG and IgA- positive cells. Whereas, IgM- positive cells were higher followed by IgG and IgA- positive cells at D14 group of chickens. At day-old chickens IgG- containing plasma cells were more than IgA and IgM- positive cells. \r\n\r\nIn conclusion, the proesengt study suggested that, harderian gland, cecal tonsil and trachea act as lymphoid organs. Data compared for harderian gland, cecal tonsil and trachea, it was found that in the non- vaccinated broilers, Igs positive cells were more found in cecal tonsil. Cecal tonsil plays the major role in immunity followed by trachea and then Harderian gland. In the vaccinated broilers and with the advancement of age, Igs- positive cells were more found in Harderian gland. Harderian gland uptake the function of cecal tonsil and plays the major role in immunity followed by cecal tonsil and then gtrachea. This variation may be due to dysfunction of the cecal tonsil with the advancement of age. \r\n', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3671, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Radish-Tomato-Red Amaranth-Indian Spinach cropping pattern in a Homestead area', 'Homestead area of Joydebpur, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2002', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2002', 'To find out the optimum dose of chemical fertilizers and organic manure for the homestead vegetable cropping pattern.', 'Field trails on homestead cropping pattern were conducted in the Chhiata series of the Grey Terrace Soil under AEZ-28 at Joydebpur during 2000-2001 and 2001-2002. The experiments were carried out at the green house premise of soil science division, BARI, which was high land having silty clay soil and may be regarded as  homestead area. The soil was slightly acidic (pH) and low in organic matter (1.6%), total N (o.11%), available P (13 &micro;g g-1) and exchangeable K (0.18 c mol kg-1) contents. Soil Zn content was at par with critical level, while sulphur and boron contents were slightly above the critical level. Poultry manure contained 1.8% N, 1.0% P, 1.64% K, 1.6% S and 1.5 &micro;g g-1) Zn, while the nutrient composition in cowdung was 0.8%, 0.5%, 0.9%, 0.3% and 1ppm for N, P, K, s and Zn, respectively. Standard laboratory procedures were followed for the chemical analysis of soil and manures sample. A vegetable cropping pattern viz. Radish (early September-early November)-Tomato (mid November-mid March)-Red amaranth (early April-early may) and Indian Spinach (mid May-mid July) were grown in the same plots in succession. The first two crops were fertilized with 3 levels (0, 5 and 10 t ha-1) each of poultry manure (PM) and cowdung (CD) along with different percentages of the recommended dose of fertilizers (RDF). In addition, the second two crops were fertilized with 3 levels (0, 2.5 and 5 t ha-1) each of PM and CD in combination with different percentages of the RD of nitrogenous fertilizer only. Thus, 10 treatments were formulated.\r\nThe experiments were conducted in a randomized complete block design (RCBD) with 3 replications. The unit plot size was 3.0 m &times; 2.4 m and the experimental plots were kept fixed during the entire periods of the experiments. The seeds of the first crop radish were sown in line maintaining a spacing of 45 cm &times; 30 cm on 12 and 17 September 2000 and 2001, respectively. The crop was harvested on 9 November 2000 and 15 November 2001. The harvesting of tomato fruit was started on 13 and 15 February 2001 and 2002, respectively, by picking the matured fruits and subsequent harvesting was done until leaves were dried up. The harvesting of the edible vegetable was done on 2 and 7 May 2001 and 2002, respectively.  The recommended dose of fertilizers for radish and tomato were N150, P35, K80, S20, kh ha-1 and  N150, P35, K80, S20, B1 kg ha-1, respectively. \r\nThe radish attained maturity for edible vegetable at 40-50 days after sowing when the root crop remained succulent without any hollow in the heart. Red amaranth attained maturity at 25-30 days after sowing having 12-18 leaves plant-1 and when plants were succulent and fibreless. Tomato fruits started ripening at 70-80 days after transplanting. Indian spinach attained maturity at 30-35 days after transplanting with 11-18 leaves shoot-1. The yield and yield attributing data were recorded and analyzed statistically following IRRISTAT package.	\r\n', 'An experiment was conducted with Radish-Tomato-Red Amaranth-Indian Spinach cropping pattern in a homestead area of Joydebpur (AEZ-28) during 2000-2001 and 2001-2002. The objectives was to find out the optimum dose of chemical fertilizers and organic manure for obtaining higher yield of the crops. The first two crops were fertilized with 3 levels (0, 5 and 10 t ha-1) each of poultry manure (PM) and cowdung (CD) in combination with different percentages of the recommended dose of fertilizers (RDF). The second two crops were fertilized with 3 reduced doses (0, 2.5 and 5 t ha-1) each of PM and CD along with varied percentages of the RD of nitrogen fertilizer (urea). There were 10 treatment combinations having three replications, which were arranged in the randomized complete block design. The result indicated that an amount of 75% RDF along with 5 t ha-1 of PM (T5) appeared to be the best combination providing a mean yield of 62.30 and 90.20 t ha-1 for radish and tomato, respectively, which was statistically at par with T6 (75% RDF + 10 t PM ha-1) , but significantly higher over rest of the treatments. Again, an amount of 75% RD of N along with 2.50 t ha-1 of PM showed overall best results providing the mean yield of 16.10 and 47.70 t ha-1 for red amaranth and indian spinach, respectively, which was statistically identical with the yield obtained from PM @ 5 t ha-1 in combination with same dose of N fertilizer, but significantly higher over rest of the combinations. Performance of poultry manure was better than that of cowdung. Sole application of either organic manure or chemical fertilizers yielded inferior results over their integrated use. The same treatment T5 (75% RDF + 5 t ha-1 PM; 75% RD of N + 2.5 t PM ha-1) was also economically profitable as it gave higher marginal rate of return (5000%). ', 'Nutrient management, Homestead, Cropping pattern', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Radish-Tomato-Red Amaranth-Indian Spinach Pattern', 'The best source of organic manure over cowdung. An amount of 25% chemical fertilizers might ba saved or reduced from the present recommendation if the fertilizers are integrated with poultry manure @ 5 t ha-1. A package of 75% chemical fertilizers are integrated with poultry manure @ 5 t ha-1. A package of 75% chemical fertilizers along with 5 t ha-1 of poultry manure for the first two crops and 75% nitrogen fertilizer in combination with 2.5 t ha-1 of poultry manure for the next two crops may be recommended for maximizing the yield of Radish-Tomato-Red amaranth-Indian spinach cropping pattern at the homestead area representing Grey Terrace Soil under AEZ-28 of Gazipur District.', 'Organic fertilizer use reduced use of chemical fertilizers with increasing the crop yield potentiality.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop Yield &amp; Soil Fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agril. Res. Ins., Publication no. 14 ');
