(3672, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Microbiology and Hygine', 'Project', 'Epidemiology and bacterial pneumonia of goat and its prevention and control measures', 'Mymensingh and Sirajganj districts. ', '', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '', '', 'The study was undertaken for epidemiological investigation and characterization of bacterial pathogens responsible for goat pneumonia. Nasal swabs (n = 47) and lungs (n=3) were collected from the black Bengal goats in Mymensingh and Sirajganj districts. Samples were inoculated onto Nutrient agar, Eosin Methylene Blue agar, MacConkey agar and Blood agar for the isolation of bacteria. Indentificatikon was performed by Germs staining method, motility and biochemical tests. Antibiotic sensitivity profile of goat bacterial isolates was performed against 11 antimicrobial agents. Pasteurella spp were isolate from 25 cases and staphylococcus spp from 13 cases.  Mixed infection caused by Pasteurella spp and staphylococcus spp. was recorded in 12 cases. Pasteurella spp. were highly sensitive to ciprofloxacin. On the contrary, Staphylococcus spp. were found to be highly sensitive to erythromycin, tetracycline, enrofloxacin, and norfloxacin and less sensitive to amoxicillin. Prevalence of pneumonia was higher in winter season as compared to summer (27.14% and 1090%, respectively) and young goats were more affected than older (33% and 11.33%). Higher rate of pneumonia was recorded in female (22.95%) in comparison to male (11.94). ', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3673, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Microbiology and Hygine', 'Project', 'Prevalence, Characteristics and antibiogram profiles of Salmonella recovered from chickens', '', '', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '', '', 'Salmonella spp. are the most frequently reported causes of food-borne illness worldwide that area closely associated with the consumption of contaminated poultry and egg products. This study was designed to isolate and identify Salmonella spp from cloacal samples of apparently healthy chickens available in the live bird markets and poultry farms in and around Bangladesh Agricultural University Campus, Mymensisngh, Bangladesh. Salmonella was characterized culturally, biochemically, serologically and by antibiotic sensitivity analysis. This study showed the differences in prevalence of Salmonella spp in different seasons, chicken lines, chicken ages and locations. A total of 200 (90 in summer and 110 in Rainy season) samples were collected from chickens of different lines and ages, of them, 104 samples were found to be positive (52%) for Salmonella spp.  The prevalence of Salmonella spp in summer (67.78%) was statistically significant (p &lt; 0.01 ) as compared to the prevalence in Rainy season (39.09). Antibiogram study was performed by disc diffusion method against 10 commonly used antibiotics which revealed multi-durg resistance in most of the isolates tested. The highest resistance was found with Tetracycline (75%) followed by Erythromycin (65%) and Nalidaxic acid (65%), Kanamycin (55%), Chloramphenicol (45%) and sulphamethoxazole (45%). Furthermore, the isolates were intermediately sensitive to Ampicillin (80%) followed by Gentamicin (70%) and Ciprofloxacin (50%). To conclude, the prevalence and drug resistance indicated the possible significance of chicken as a reservoir of multiple antimicrobial-resistant Salmonella  and suggest the need for detailed epidemiological study and judicious use of antibiotics. ', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3674, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Microbiology and Hygiene', 'Project', 'Sero-Prevalence of human, bovine and avian tuberculosis and Molecular Characterization of the isolated Mycobacteria ', '', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '', '', 'In this study the selected government and private dairy, sheep and goat farms for comparison of bovine tuberculosis were considered. A total of 527 cows, 228 calves, 63 buffaloes, 273 sheep and 155 goats of different breeds, sexes and ages were selected for tuberculin tests in the Central Cattle Breeding and Dairy Farm, Savar, Dhaka, Bangladesh Agricultural University Dairy Farm, Mymensingh, Crown Dairy Farm, Savar, MIBM Dairy Farm, Savar, BLRI, Savar and Lal Teer LBF, Kalihati, Tangail. The results of the univariate descriptive analysis of various variables were studied. It was revealed that 21.31% of cows belong to Central Cattle Breeding and dairy farm (government farm) and 1.33% of cows belong to Crown Dairy Farm, MBM Dairy Farm (private farm) and 26.82% of cows belongs to Lal Teer LBF, Kalihati, Tangail were found as reactors in tuberculin test. The results of tuberculin test on the calves revealed that the 10.92% and 11.77% of calves belongs to the Central Cattle Breeding and Dairy Farm and BAUl, Dairy Farm were reactors respectively. The results also revealed that the 7.69% and 0.00% of calves belongs to the MBM Dairy Farm and Crown Dairy Farm were reactors respectively. IN BLRI sheep and goat farms 25 (9.15%) sheep and 2 (1.29%) goats were responded to CFT using bovine type tuberculin, on the other hand in Lal Teer LBF, Kalihati, Tangail 18 (28.58%) buffaloes were to be responded to bovine type tuberculin.', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
