(3705, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Yield Maximization of Chilli', 'Central farm of the Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', 'To find out an optimal combination of chemical fertilizers and organic manure (cowdung) for higher and sustainable yield of Chilli.', 'The experiment was conducted at the Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jamalpur during the rabi seasons of 2006-2007 and 2007-2008 to find out a suitable combination of organic and inorganic fertilizers for the cultivation of chilli. There were two factors viz. varieties of chilli and fertilizer combinations in the experiment. Chilli varieties were BARI Morich-1 and Jamalpur local (Balijuri). Organic and inorganic fertilizer combinations were: F1= Soil test base (STB) fertilizer dose for high yield goal, F2= STB + Cowdung 5 t ha-1, F3= 50% of STB + Cowdung 5 t ha-1, F4= FRG 2005 based fertilizer dose for high yield goal, F5= Farmers practice (FP) and F6= Native fertility (Control).  The experiment was laid out in factorial RCB design with four replications. Thirty five days old seedlings were transplanted on November 10, 2006 and November 12, 2007 maintaining a spacing of 40 cm between row to row and 30 cm plant to plant. Unit plot size was 3 m &times; 2.4 m. \r\nZn, B, CD and &frac14; K were applied at final land preparation and the remaining &frac34; of K and whole amount of N were applied in three equal installments at 25, 50 and 70 DAT. Matured fruits of chilli were harvested four times and sun dried. Crop performance data on plant height, fruits plant-1, fruit length, fruit diameter and fruit yield were recorded and statistically analyzed by using MSTATC program. Mean separation was done by DMRT at 5% level of significance.\r\n', 'A field experiment on nutrient management for chilli was conducted at the Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jamalpur in two consecutive years 2006-2007 and 2007-2008 to find out suitable combination of organic and inorganic fertilizer for yield maximization of chilli.  There were two varieties viz. BARI Morich-1 and Jamalpur local (Balijuri) and six fertilizer combinations viz. F1= Soil test base (STB) fertilizer dose for high yield goal, F2= STB + Cowdung 5 t ha-1, F3= 50% of STB + Cowdung 5 t ha-1, F4= FRG 2005 based fertilizer dose for high yield goal, F5= Farmers practice (FP) and F6= Native fertility (Control) as treatments in the experiment. The experiment was laid out in factorial RCB design with four replications. Results showed that integrated use of fertilizers and manure (cowdung) in combination was found to be the best for maximizing yield of chilli. The highest yield (2.31 t ha-1) of dry chilli showing 261% higher over control was obtained in F2 treatment that received N120, P60, K120, S18, Zn2, B0.5 kg ha-1 +cowdung 5 t ha-1. Between two varieties BARI Morich-1 showed better performance and yielded higher (1.78 t ha-1) than Balijuri.', 'Chilli, Fertilizer, Manure, Yield', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Chilli', 'Application of N120, P60, K120, S18, Zn2, B0.5 + cowdung 5 t ha-1 appeared as the best suitable combination of fertilizer and manure for the higher and economically profitable yield of chilli. Between two varieties BARI morich-1 performed better giving higher yield. Thus, a package of  N120, P60, K120, S18, Zn2, B0.5 + cowdung 5 t ha-1  and BARI morich-1 may be recommended for the cultivation of chilli in Brahmaputra Flood Plian soil of Jamalpur region. ', 'Organic fertilizer in combination with chemical fertilizer provide higher yield potentiality and keep the soil healthy.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14'),
