(3708, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Pathology', '', 'Epidemiology of Lieshmaniasis in domestic animals and its molecular diagnosis in selective villages of Fulbaria Upazila in Mymensingh district', 'Fulbaria upazila of Mymensingh district', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '', '', 'Visceral leishmaniasis (VL), also known as kala-azar, is a fatal vector-borne parasitic disease.  Worldwide incidence is 500000 cases per year. The true incidence of kala-azar in Bangladesh is close to 40000  45000 per year. In this present study attempt were taken to identify the factors associated with kala-azar and Post kala-azar Dermal Leishmaniasis (PKDL) in human in Fulbaria upazila of Mymensingh district. A total of 359 cases were recorded from the rural area by door to door survey and the data from the upazila health Complex, Fulbaria. The incidence of kala-azar is higher in male (58.22%) than female (41.78%). Children less than 10 years of age were affected most frequently (40.11%). The incidence was found to decrease with the increase of age (11-20 years = 19.50 % cases, 21-30 hyears = 19.22%, 31-40 years = 10.58%, 41-50 years = 6.40% and above 50 years = 4.17% cases). Among the Kala-azar infected patients, only 14.48% cases developed PKDL. Incidence of PKDL also decreased with age. The rural area of Fulbaria is well known for mud house for living. Forty seven (47) percent of kala-azar infected patient were found to lining in a mud house and rest 53% have tin shed house but with earthen floor in most of the cases. Among the kala-arzr infected patients 66% people have been found rearing domestic animal either cattle, goats or dogs. These animal sheds were made by clay with cracked wall &amp; wet either cattle, goats or dogs. These animal sheds were made by clay with cracked wall &amp; wet area, which are favorable for sand fly. However the relationship of domestic animals with spreading of the kala-azar is not established. Most of the people (72%) were found having no idea about sand fly. Only 28 % people knew about the sand fly. Vegetations around the house, lining in proximity to prior case, cracked mud house walls with humid area, poor economic condition, nutritional deprivation, illiterate people, lack of  proper treatment and diagnostic facilities, incomplete treatment, lack of awareness and proper knowledge about the diseases were other risk factors found behind to increasing incidence of kala-azar in Fulbaria. Attentions need to be paid considering the severity and effects of kala-arar in Bangladesh. ', '', '', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3709, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Pathology', 'Project', 'Molecular Genetic analysis of Fasciola gigantica occurring in goats in Mymensingh', 'Mymensingh district', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '', '', 'Understanding genetic structure and status of genetic variation of the Fasciola gigantica isolates form different hosts, has important implications for epidemiology and effective control of fascioliasis. The aim of the present work was to study the molecular genetic analysis of fasciola gigantica isolates collected from liver of goats, using the random amplified polymorphic DNA fragments polymerase chain reaction (RAPDs-PCR). Three out of ten decamer random primers were used to amplify genomic DNA and the primers yielded a total of 14 RAPD markers of which 14 were considered as polymorphic. The percentage of polymorphic loci is 100%. Genetic variation statistics for all loci, average number of allele is 20000 and average number of gene diversity is 0.42347 and their standard deviation is 0.0000 and 0.05858, respectively. The co-efficient of gene differentiation (Gst) and gene flow (Nm) values across all loci were 1.0000 and 0.0000, respectively indicating genetic divergence among populations. The UPGAM dendrogram based on Neis (1972) genetic distance, indicated segregation of 16 F. gigantica isolates into two main groups: Group-1 contains isolate-1, isolate-12, isolate-6, isolae-2, isolate-7, isolate-9, isolate-3, isolate-4, isolate-10, isolate-13, isolate-11, isolate-12, isolate-5, while isolate-8 isolate-15, isolate-6, isolate-14 are grouped in group-II. The Group-1 was further separated into different clusters, sub-clusters, units and sub-units. Comparative examination of the results obtained by RAPD analysis and the information about the isolates source give evidence that a predominant clone of F. gigantica isolates is circulating in Bangladesh and there is sufficient genetic diversity persists among the isolates as well. Thus, RAPD offers a potentially simple, rapid and reliable method to evaluate genetic variation and relatedness among 16 F. gigantica isolate. This assay is also useful for both diagnosis and epidemiological surveys in endemic regions. ', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '');
