(3710, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Project', 'Comparative performance of cowdung, poultry manure and their slurry on the growth and yield  of Cabbage', 'Central farm, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', 'To evaluate the effect of slurry in combination with chemical fertilizers on the yield of cabbage.', 'The experiment was carried out during 2006-2007 and 2007-2008 in Grey Terrace Soils at BARI, Joydebpur. The initial soil analysis of the experimental field was done. The soil is acidic in nature. Ca and Mg contents were above the critical limit. Potassium (K) content is below the critical limit. The P, S, B and Zn contents were close to critical limit. The experiment was set up in a randomized complete block design with three replications. There were 36 unit plots having an area of 3.0 m &times; 2.4 m. Equal sized, healthy 25 days old seedlings (Var. Atlas-70) were transplanted on 20 Novemver 2006 and 26 November 2007. The seedlings were transplanted with a spacing of 60 cm from line to line and 45 cm from plant to plant. The treatments used in this experiments were : T1= 100% RDF, T2= 75% RDF, T3= 50% RDF, T4= 75% RDF + cowdung @ 5 t ha-1, T5= 50% RDF + Cowdung @ 10 t ha-1, T6= 75% RDF + Cowdung slurry @ 5 t ha-1, T7= 50% RDF + Cowdung slurry @ 10 t ha-1, T8= 75% RDF + poultry manure @ 5 t ha-1, T9= 50% RDF + poultry manure @ 10 t ha-1, T10= 75% RDF + poultry slurry @ 5 t ha-1, T11= 50% RD + poultry slurry @ 10 t ha-1 and T12= Absolute control. Recommended dose of fertilizers (RDF) for cabbage was N250, P36, K65, S20, B2 kg ha-1 (BARC, 2005). \r\nHarvesting was done from 10 February to 24 February 2007 and 18 February to 2 March 2008. Data on the number of unfolded leaves, circumference, individual head weight and head yield were recorded. The yield and yield attributes data were analyzed statistically and the mean differences were tested bu Duncans Multiple Range Test.\r\n', 'An experiment was conducted to evaluate the effect of cowdung, poultry manure and their slurry on the yield of cabbage during 2006-2007 and 2007-2008 at Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute, Gazipur. The treatment T10 having 75% recommended dose of chemical fertilizers along with 5 t ha-1 of poultry slurry was found to produce the highest yield of cabbage in both years, which was identical to that obtained with 75% fertilizers + 5 t ha-1 cowdung slurry (T6) and poultry manure (T8). Treatments 100% fertilizers (T1) and 75% fertilizers + 5 t ha-1 cowdung (T4), 50% fertilizers + 10 t ha-1 poultry slurry (T11) and 75% fertilizers + 5 t ha-1 poultry slurry (T10) produced identical cabbage yield in 2006-2007. The average highest gross margin (Tk. 4,12,972 ha-1) was observed with T10, which was closely followed followed by T6 (Tk. 4,10,972 ha-1), T8 (Tk. 4,10,472 ha-1) and T1 (Tk. 4,03,630 ha-1). These treatments were also found cost undominated. Performance of slurry form of manure was better than that of aerobically decomposed form of manure, and between cowdung and poultry manure, performance of poultry manure was better. Use of this bioslurry at the rate of 5 t ha-1 can reduce the chemical fertilizers use by 25%.', 'Cowdung, poultry manure, Cabbage', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Cabbage', 'Profitable production of cabbage (cv. Atlas-70) 5 t ha-1 each of poultry slurry or cowdung slurry along with 75% recommended dose of chemical fertilizer may be applied in Grey Terrace Soil (AEZ_28) of Gazipur. By using bioslurry at the rate of 5 t ha-1 , the dose of chemical fertilizers can be reduced by 25%. Both slurry of cowdung or poultry manure were found better than decomposed cowdung or poultry manure.', 'Poultry manure or Cowdung in combination with chemical fertilizers reduced the use of chemical fertilizers by 25% as well as provide better yield performance.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3711, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Effect of poultry manure in combination with chemical fertilizers on the yield and nutrient uptake by chilli in the hilly region', 'Hill valley of HARS, Khagrachari', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', 'To determine the effect of poultry manure in combination with chemical fertilizers on the yield and nutrient uptake by chilli in the hilly region.', 'Field experiment was conducted to determine poultry manure in combination with chemical fertilizers on the yield and nutrient uptake by chilli in the hill valley.There were six treatments: T1= 100% STB (Soil test base) chemical fertilizer dose N100, P65, K100, S20, Zn4 kg ha-1, T2= 100% STB + 2.5 t PM ha-1, T3= 75% STB + 2.5 t PM ha-1, T4= 75% STB + 5 t PM ha-1, T5= Farmers practice, T6= Native fertility. The experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design replicated 3 times.  The unit plot size was 5 m &times; 3 m with spacing of 40 cm &times; 30 cm. Thirty days old seedlings were transplanted. All the intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. The crop was harvested eight times after fruit maturity. The field data on important parameters were recorded from 10 randomly selected plants for analysis. The data were collected on plant height, fruit length, fruit diameter, weight of fruit, fruit weight per plant and yield. Data on different yield contributing parameters and yield were recorded and analyzed statistically and adjusted with least significant difference (LSD) at 5% level of significance.', 'Field experiment was conducted to determine poultry manure in combination with chemical fertilizers on the yield and nutrient uptake by chilli in the hill valley. There were six treatments: T1= 100% STB (Soil test base) chemical fertilizer dose N100, P65, K100, S20, Zn4 kg ha-1, T2= 100% STB + 2.5 t PM ha-1, T3= 75% STB + 2.5 t PM ha-1, T4= 75% STB + 5 t PM ha-1, T5= Farmers practice, T6= Native fertility. The experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design replicated 3 times. Average result revealed that the T4 (75% STB + 5 t PM ha-1) produced the highest fruit yield 6.25 t ha-1 and lowest 3.67 t ha-1 in control treatment. An inclusion of 5 t PM ha-1 can reduce 25% of chemical fertilizer. Integrated use of PM at the rate of 5 t ha-1 with 75% STB dose (N75, P50, K75, S15, Zn3 kg ha-1) were found to be the best combination in respect of dry chilli yield and fertility management by enriching the soil with organic matter.', 'Nutrient uptake, poultry manure, chemical fertilizers, yield of chilli', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Chilli', '100% STB based fertilizer with 2.5 t ha-1 poultry manure gave highest yield. But poultry manure 5.0 t ha-1 along with 75% recommended dose of chemical fertilizer (N75, P50, K75, S15, Zn3 kg ha-1) may be recommended for chilli cultivation in the hilly region.', 'Poultry manure in combination with chemical fertilizers increase crop yield and reduce the use of chemical fertilizers.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3712, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Pathology', 'Project', 'Intra-dermal tuberculin, cultural and polymerase chain reaction (PCR) tests for the detection of Tuberculosis in dairy cattle of selected areas in Bangladesh. ', 'Mymensingh, Sirajganj, Dhaka, Bogra, Chittagong, Tangail and Sylhet districts ', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '', '', 'Bovine tuberculosis (BTB) is a chronic debilitating infectious disease that infects animal and humans. Tuberculosis (TB) in animal is caused by Mycobacterium bovis, Mycobacterium tuberculosis and Mycobacterium avium sub.sp Paratuberculosis called Mycobacterium tuberculosis (NTB) complex. This investigation was designed to determine the occurrence of bovine, human and avian TB in dairy cattle in selected areas of Bangladesh. Dairy cattle in the farms of Mymensingh, Sirajganj, Dhaka, Bogra, Chittagong, Tangail and Sylhet districts were tested using single intra-dermal (Bovine purified protein derivates) and comparative intra-dermal (Bovine and avian purified protein derivates) Tuberculin tests. Out of 656 cattle tested for bovine and avian TB using Tuberculin test, 21 (3.20%) appeared reactive to bovine TB.  A dairy cow in Mymensingh dairy farm appeared reactive to both bovine and avian TB.  In this study, 10 suspected animals were sacrificed and used on culture for Mycobacterium isolation and characterization. Bacteria were grown on Lowenstein-Jensen (LJ) media. Out of 10 samples 7 were grown in culture and appeared positive to M. bovis in PCR setting. The tuberculin test reactive cattle (N=10) were sacrificed, DNA was extracted from Lymphonode, lung and bonemarrow at necropsy. PCR amplification from the genomic DNA of extracted animal tissue showed MPB83 gene (600bp) of M. bovis in seven cases and H37 R&amp;#7525;  gene (337bp) of M. tuberculosis in one case. One animal showed only bone form of tuberculosis and MPB83 gene was amplified (600bp) from the DNA extracted from bonemarrow. It is concluded that cattle of organized dairy farms at Mymensingh, Dhaka, Sirajgong, Chittagong, Tangail and Sylhet districts were infected with bovine and human TB and the PCR tests we adopt can be used to detect those diseases at early onset', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3713, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Sustainable yield of major vegetable crops in relation to climate change and land degradation.', 'Central farm, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', 'To find out the effect of integrated nutrient management on yield of vegetable crops in relation to climate change and soil degradation.', '', 'The crop based agriculture of Bangladesh is under threat of vulnerability due to climate change. The countrys limited land resource is under the process of much degradation due to salinization, acidification, erosion, inundation, pollution and desertification. Maintenance of soil fertility with  production sustainability is the prime factor in achieving food security under the threat of global climate change. Raising the production of vegetables is a great task become land resource is shrinking gradually. Integrated nutrient management (INM) approach may play a vital role in increasing yield and quality of vegetables and improving the soil health. Numerous research had shown that application of 5-10 t PM ha-1 may reduce the use of chemical fertilizers up to 50% from the present recommendation. In addition, the said amount of manure when integrated with chemical fertilizers (50-75%) of the conventional recommendations) may bring yield sustainability of cabbage, cauliflower, broccoli, tomato, carrot and also year round vegetable production in farmers homestead. The nutrient balance, soil fertility and cost and return factors also gave positive trend of improvement for INM approach. Tomato, brinjal, potato, watermelon can be grown successfully in saline soil of coastal regions following drip irrigation in raised bed with mulch technique and thus could be a better option of cultivation under changing climate. Studies on the build up of soil organic matter, reclamation of soil acidity, adaptation under water logging situation, maximum use efficiency of fertilizers, water and other inputs should be strengthened. Development of sustainable soil management technologies matching with long spell drought, short winter, uneven rainfall, floods and salinity hazards is an urgent need in achieving food security under climate change. ', 'Integrated nutrient management, Climate change, Vegetable, Soil fertility', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Vegetable crops', '1) Yield of different vegetables increased substantially due to integrated use of both organic manure and chemical fertilizers.\r\n2) Poultry manure appeared as the best source of organic manure over cowdung.\r\n3) Integrated use of both chemical fertilizer and poultry manure may reduce the use of chemical fertilizer from the present conventional recommendation.\r\n4) Further depletion of soil fertility may be checked with positive trend of improvement if INM related technologies are followed.\r\n5) Moderate dose of poultry manure along with chemical fertilizer appeared as cost un-dominated providing higher marginal rate of return.\r\n6) The benefit of INM technology should be demonstrated and disseminated to the farmers through extension personnel.\r\n7) More motivation and subsidy are required for the adoption of such technology by the farmers.\r\n8) Agricultural policy measures should be strengthened so that farmers may get proper support, encouragement and guidance to switch over conventional agriculture towards technology oriented agriculture.\r\n9) Appropriate measures must be taken to sustain soil fertility and crop productivity under changing climate.', 'Organic manures may be a alternate option to increase the productivity in combination with chemical fertilizer.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3714, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for cabbage-Red amaranth-Bitter Gourd-Red amaranth cropping pattern in Grey Terrace soil under homestead of Gazipur region.', 'Dhirashram village of Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2007', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2007', '1) To minimize the use of chemical fertilizer through the use of organic manure adopting integrated nutrient management approach.\r\n2) To find out the suitable combination of chemical fertilizer and organic manure for sustainable yield of the pattern.', 'Field trials on homestead based cabbage-red amaranth-bitter gourd-red amaranth cropping pattern were conducted in the Chhiata series of the Grey Terrace Soil under AEZ-28 at Gazipur during 2005-2006 and 2006-2007. The experimental site was a high land under farmers homestead. The soil of the experimental site was silty clay in texture having pH 6.4, organic matter content 1.5%, total N 0.08%, available P 13 g g-1, exchangeable K 0.14 meq 100 g-1, available S 15 g g-1 and available Zn 3.6 g g-1 which showed the initial fertility status of the soil. A vegetable cropping pattern viz. cabbage (November-February), red amaranth (mid February-late March), bitter gourd (early April-early August) and red amaranth (mid August-mid October) was grown in the same plot in succession. The first and 3rd crops were fertilized with three levels (0, 2.5 and 10 t ha-1) each of poultry manure (PM) and cowdung (CD) along with different portions (%) of the recommended chemical fertilizers (RCF). In addition, the second and 4th crops were fertilized with different portions of recommended dose of nitrogen fertilizer (RNF) only. The experiments were conducted in a randomized complete block design with 3 replications. The RCF considered for cabbage (cv. Atlas-70) and bitter gourd (cv. Gaz Korolla) were N250, P35, K65, S40, B2 kg ha-1 and N80, P80, K40, S8, B1 kg ha-1, respectively. The RNF for red amaranth (cv. BARI Lalshak-1) was considered as N60 kg ha-1. Urea, TSP, MP, gypsum and boric acid were used as the source of N, P, K, S and B, respectively. Entire quantity of P, K, S, B, CD and PM and 1/3rd N were applied as per treatment at the time of final land preparation and the remaining 2/3rd N was applied in two equal installments each at 3rd and 5th weeks after sowing/transplanting for cabbage and bitter gourd. On the other hand, for red amaranth, the whole amount of N fertilizer was applied at seven days after emergence. After the harvest of the first crop (cabbage), the individual plots were prepared for sowing the next crop, red amaranth. Again after the harvest of the second crop (red amaranth), the seedlings of the 3rd crop (bitter gourd) were transplant in pits maintaining a spacing of line to line 1.5 m and pit to pit 1 m, having six pits per plot. An amount 50% organic manure and chemical fertilizers (except N) were broadcasted during the final land preparation and rest 50% fertilizer (except N) and manure were used in the pits prior to seed sowing. Entire amount of nitrogen as urea was used in equal splits as ring method at 2, 4 and 6 weeks after germination followed by light irrigation. The seeds of the 4th crop (red amaranth) were sown after the harvest of 3rd crop. The experimental plots were unaltered over the year. Harvesting was done at the right stage of maturity as per the nature of the particular crops. The yield and yield attributing data were recorded and analyzed statistically following MSTAT-C package while the mean separation was done by Duncans Multiple Range Test.', 'Field experiments on cabbage-red amaranth-bitter gourd-red amaranth cropping pattern was conducted for homestead area in Chhiata series of Grey Terrace Soil under AEZ-28 at Dhirashram, Gazipur during 2005-2006 and 2006-2007 to evaluate the contribution of chemical fertilizers and organic manure alone and in combination on the yield of the pattern. The crops were fertilized with different portions (%) of the recommended chemical fertilizers (RCF) in combination with three levels (0, 2.5 and 10 t ha-1) each of poultry manure (PM) and Cowdung (CD). The experiment was set up in RCB design having eight treatments and three replications. An amount of 100% recommended chemical fertilizers (RCF) along with 2.5 t ha-1 of PM (T1) showed the best result providing a mean yield of cabbage (77.82 t ha-1), which was identically followed by T4 (50% RCF + 10 t ha-1PM). The highest mean yield of bitter gourd (31.22 t ha-1) was also obtained from T1, which was at par with T4 (28.28 t ha-1). Again, an amount of 100% RNF (T1) alone showed overall best results providing the mean yield of 12.07 and 12.83 t ha-1 for red amaranth (mean of 2nd and 4th crop), which was identical with T4 (50% RNF + residue of PM). Cowdung showed significantly lower results than poultry manure. Sole application of either organic manure or chemical fertilizers yielded inferior results to their integrated use. The highest MBCR (28.71) was obtained with T1, which was closely followed by T4 as such both the treatments appeared as economically profitable.', 'Terrace Soil, Poultry Manure, Cowdung, Chemical fertilizer, Homestead', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Cabbage-red amaranth-bitter gourd-red amaranth pattern', 'Integrated use of chemical fertilizers and organic manure appeared as the Best over sole use of either chemical fertilizers or organic manure in respect of yield sustainability of the cropping pattern. An amount of 100% RCF along with 2.5 t ha-1 PM gave the highest yield providing with greater MBCR. The second highest yield with economic benefit was obtained from T4 package (50% RCF + 10 t ha-1 PM) which was only 10% lower than the best treatment (100% RCF + 2.5 t PM ha-1). As such 50% recommended dose of chemical fertilizers may be reduced with the addition of 7.5 t ha-1 PM. Depending on the availability of poultry manure, farmers of the Gazipur region may use 50% chemical fertilizers from the conventional recommendation along with 10 t ha-1 PM for homestead vegetable cultivation in achieving yield sustainability, regeneration of soil fertility and minimization of environmental pollution due to over use of chemical fertilizers.', 'Poultry manure use for vegetable cultivation can reduce upto 50% chemical fertilizers with providing more vegetable yield and improve soil fertility.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3715, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Pharmacology', 'Project', 'Comparative efficacy of ivermection and medicinal plants against gastrointestinal nematodiasis and ectoparasites in meat producing pulls.', 'Mymensingh district.', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2012', '', '', 'To determine the prevalence of endo and ectoparasitic infestation of bulls in and around the BAU area in Mymensingh district in Bangladesh an epidemiological investigation was carried out during the period from July 2010 to September 2010. Beef cattle is popularly reared in this area for fattening purpose and to sell at the time of Eid ul Azha. A total of 100 beef cattle of age 1.5 to 2 years were examined, 70% of animals were positive to mixed infection (endo and ecto) 60 (60%) were found to be infested with several species of ticks and lice. Prevalence of ectoparasitic infestation was significantly (p&lt;0.005) higher in animal reared under free range system than that of semi-intensive system and cattle with malnourished and poor health status were found to be significantly more vulnerable to such parasitic infestation than normal healthy cattle. Seasonal prevalence showed that, significantly (p&lt;0.001) higher prevalence occurred in summer season, followed by winter and rainy season. A total of 15 bulls of mixed infections were selected in this experiment. The effect of patent drugs ivermectin and one indigenous medicinal plant namely Neem (Azadirachta indica) leaves on body weight was observed on day 7th, 14th and 21st respectively. Body weight of each group of calves prior to treatment was taken and live weight gain of each group of bulls on 7th, 14th and 21st days was calculated in kg. the increased values of body weight in bulls of the treated groups were not significant on day 7 and day 14 but that were highly significant (p&lt;0.01) on day 21 compared to control. Ivermectin was 100% effective against endo and ecto parasites of bulls, when compared with control group at 7th day of post treatment, no ectoparasiktes were detected on body surface and no ove as present at fecal examination. Neem leaves powder 100 gm/kg b. wt was administered orally on 1st and 4th day of experiment and epg count reduced 42% on 7th day and 53% on 14th day. Neem leaves posder 15% (water extract) was sprayed on body surface daily once and continued for 7 days and on 14th day 60% ectoparasites wdre eliminated from the body.', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3716, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Effects of Fertilizers, Poultry manure and lime on soil fertility and Maize (Zea mays L.) Yield', 'Agricultural Research station, Burirhat, Rangpur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', '1) To observe the nutrient availability in presence of lime and organic amendments.\r\n2) To evaluate the effect of integrated use of chemical fertilizer, organic manure and lime on the yield of maize in acid soil.', 'A field experiment was conducted in non-calcareous floodplain soils under AEZ-3 at Agricultural Research Station, Burirhat, Rangpur during rabi seasons of 2006-2007 and 2007-2008. The hybrid maize (cv. BARI hybrid Maize-5) was taken as a test crop. The soil was highly acidic (pH-4.6) having low organic matter content (1.24%). The content of total N was very low (0.08%). Exchangeable Mg (0.72 meq 100 g-1) . Sulphur and phosphorus contents (12.0 and 12.5 &micro;g g-1, respectively) were below the critical level. Boron and Zinc contents were also low. Therefore, the initial fertility status of the soil was reasonably poor.\r\nThere were 7 treatment combinations comprising two levels (0 and 2 t ha-1) of lime, three levels (0, 3 and 6 t ha-1) of poultry manure and one absolute control. A , blanket dose of N250, P55, K100, S40, Zn5, B2 kg ha-1 was used in the study. The treatments were formulated as follows: T1= control; T2= N250 P55 K100 S40 B2 Zn5 kg ha-1 and PM0 lime0 t ha-1; T3 = N250 P55 K100 S40 B2 Zn5 kg ha-1 and PM0 lime2 t ha-1; T4= N250 P55 K100 S40 B2 Zn5 kg ha-1 and PM3 lime0 t ha-1; T5= N250 P55 K100 S40 B2 Zn5 kg ha-1 and PM3 lime2 t ha-1; T6= N250 P55 K100 S40 B2 Zn5 kg ha-1 and PM6 lime0 t ha-1; T7= N250 P55 K100 S40 B2 Zn5 kg ha-1 and PM6 lime2 t ha-1. The experiments were laid out in a randomized complete block design with three replications. The poultry manure used in this study was analyzed and found that the heavy metal content was low but the content of essential nutrients was much higher than many of the conventional organic manure.\r\nThe unit plot size was 4 m &times; 5 m. Maize seeds were sown providing a spacing of row to row 75 cm and seed to seed 25 cm. The seed rate was 25 kg ha-1. Urea, TSP, MP, gypsum, Zinc sulphate and boric acid were used as sources of N, P, K, S, Zn and B, respectively. All P, K, S, Zn, B, poultry manure and 1/3rd N were applied at the time of final land preparation and the remaining 2/3rd N was top dressed in two equal installments at 30 and 60 days after sowing. Lime was applied once in the first year (2006-2007), one month before final land preparation. Irrigation, insect control and other intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. Data on yield and yield contributing characters were recorded and analyzed statistically following IRRISTAT.\r\n', 'A field experiment on Maize (cv. BARI Hybrid maize-5) was conducted in non-calcareous Grey Floodplain Soil under AEZ-3 at Agricultural Research  Station, Burirhat, Rangpur during rabi seasons of 2006-2007 and 2007-2008. The objective of this experiment was to find out the effect of fertilizer, lime and poultry manure on nutrient availability and their contribution to the yield of maize. There were seven treatments comprising two levels of lime (0, and 2 t ha-1), three level of poultry manure (0, 3 and 6 t ha-1) and one absolute control. Besides these, a blanket dose of N250, P55, K100, S40, Zn5, B2 kg ha-1 was used. The treatments were arranged in a randomized complete block design with three replications. The highest mean yield (10.0 t ha-1) was obtained from T7 (2 t lime + 6 t PM ha-1) followed by T5 (2 t lime + 3 t PM ha-1)  and T3 (2 t lime ha-1). Treatment T7 showed statistically similar result with T5 and T3 but significantly higher than the rest of the treatments. The second and 3rd highest yield was obtained from T5 and T3, respectively, which was statistically similar with T6 (100% RD + 6 t PM ha-1) and T4 (100% RD + 3 t PM ha-1) treatments. The lowest mean yield (4.27 t ha-1) was found with control (T1). Lime and poultry manure amended plots showed an improvement in soil fertility. Negative apparent balances of N and K due to their lower efficiency deserve further replenishments for the subsequent crops. Slightly lower MBCRin lime and poultry manure treated plots over RD of chemical fertilizer may be accepted considering their overall benefits in achieving sustainability. Based on the economic return, benefits of liming in reclaiming soil acidity with greater nutrient availability and poultry manuring for the improvement of soil physical, chemical and biological environment, the treatment package T5 (3 t PM + 2 t lime ha-1) along with N250, P55, K100, S40, Zn5, B2 kg ha-1 may be recommended for optimization of the yield of hybrid maize in the greater Rangpur Region (AEZ-3).,', 'Maize, Poultry manure, Lime, Nutrient availability', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Maize', 'Two years study revealed that lime plays a major role in augmenting the yield. Therefore, soil of Rangpur region should be amended with lime @ 2 t ha-1 at least one month before cultivation. Considering the over all benefits, the treatment package T5 (lime 2 t ha-1 and poultry manure 3 t ha-1) along with blanket dose of N250, P55, K100, S40, Zn5, B2 kg ha-1 may be recommended for the cultivation of hybrid maize in the greater Rangpur region (AEZ-3).', 'Maize production will be increased if poultry manure is added with chemical fertilizer.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3717, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated nutrient management for the brinjal(red amaranth-red amaranth)-kangkong cropping pattern', 'Farmer''s homestead under AEZ-8 at Elenga, Tangail', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2010', '1) To minimize the use of chemical fertilizer through the use of organic manure following integrated approach.\r\n2) To find out the suitable combination of chemical fertilizer and organic manure for sustainable yield\r\n3) To improve soil fertility for better soil health.', 'Field trials were conducted in farmers homestead at FSRD site, Elenga, Tangail during the period of 2008-2009 and 2009-2010 on brinjal (red amaranth-red amaranth)-Kangkong cropping pattern. The experiment was laid out in a RCB design with five treatments and four replications. The unit plot size was 2.4 m &times; 2.2 m. Two organic manures such as cowdung and poultry manure were added at different combinations in addition to recommended dose of chemical fertilizers. BARI Begun-7, BARI Lalshak-1 and BARI Gimakalmi-1 were tested varieties for brinjal, red amaranth and Kangkong, respectively. Spacing  for brinjal was 60 cm &times; 40 cm. Red amaranth was cultivated twice as an intercrop with brinjal. Spacing for kangkong was 30 cm &times; 10 cm. After harvesting of brinjal, the individual plots were prepared for sowing of kangkong. For brinjal (Brinjal + Red amaranth as intercrop), the whole amount of TSP, MP, gypsum, Zinc sulphate, Boric acid, cowdung, poultry manure and 1/3rd N were applied at the time of final land preparation and the remaining 2/3rd N were applied in two equal installments at 3rd and 5th weeks after transplanting. For red amaranth as intercrop, &frac12; N was applied at sowing and rest &frac12; N at 10 days after germination. Total amount of chemical fertilizers except N and entire amount of organic manure were applied for kangkong during final land preparation. Urea was applied in three equal installments at 30, 45 and 60 days after sowing.\r\nBrinjal seedlings (30 days old) were transplanted in the 2nd week of November and harvest was completed in the last week of April. Red  amaranth as a first intercrop with brinjal was sown in the 2nd week of November and harvest was completed in the 3rd week of December. The 2nd phase of red amaranth was sown in the 3rd week of December and harvest was completed in the last week of January. Kangkong was sown in the 2nd week of April and harvest was completed in the 1st week of September. The yield and yield attributing data were recorded and analyzed statistically following MSTAT-C program while the mean separation was done by LSD.\r\n', 'Trials on Brinjal (red amaranth-red amaranth)-Kangkong cropping pattern were conducted in Grey floodplain soil at farmers homestead under AEZ-8 at Elenga, Tangail during 2008-2009 and 2009-2010. The main objective was to find out the suitable combination of chemical fertilizers and organic manure for sustainable yield and to reduce the use of chemical fertilizer through the use of organic manure. First crop (Brinjal) was fertilized with two levels (0 and 5 t ha-1) each of poultry manure and cowdung and the last crop Kangkong was also fertilized with 2 levels (0 and 2.5 t ha-1) each of poultry manure and cowdung. Red amaranth was fertilized with 50 or 75% of the recommended dose of nitrogen only. Five treatment packages with 4 replications were arranged in a randomized complete block design. An amount of 75% of recommended chemical fertilizer (N150, P35 K100 S20 Zn2 B1 kg ha-1) along with 5 t PM ha-1 (T2) produced the highest yield (35.72 t ha-1 in 2008-2009 and 34.75 t ha-1 in 2009-2010) of brinjal, which was statistically identical with T1 (100% RCF) and was significantly higher over rest of the treatments. The yield of red amaranth as an intercrop varied significantly from 7.31 to 11.43 t ha-1 and 8.41 to 12.95 t ha-1 for the first and second companion crops with main crop (Brinjal) where the highest result was observed with T2 and the lowest in T5. Performance of poultry manure was better than that of cowdung. The highest yield of 39.14 t ha-1 in 2008-2009 and 38.80 t ha-1 in 2009-2010 of kangkong was recorded from T2 (75% RCF + 2.5 t PM ha-1) which was closely followed by T1 (100% RCF) but significantly higher over rest of the treatments. Poultry manure along with reduced dose of chemical fertilizer appeared as economically profitable giving higher marginal rate of return.', 'Integrated nutrient management, Intercropping, Brinjal, Red amaranth, Kangkong', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Brinjal (red amaranth-red amaranth)-Kangkong pattern', 'An amount of 75% recommended dose of chemical fertilizer (RCF) along with 5 t PM ha-1 for the first crop (Brinjal) and 75% recommended N for red amaranth as intercrop and 75% RCF with 2.5 t PM ha-1 for the third crop (Kangkong) appeared as the best suited combination in respect of yield and economic return. Thus the said treatment package may be recommended for sustainable yield of the pattern in the study area.', 'Poultry manure in combination with chemical fertilizer increase crop yield potentially as well as improve soil fertility.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3718, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Effects of application of MSW compost on rice and maize production.', 'Agronomy Field Laboratory, BAU Mymensingh and village- Sutiakhali, district- Mymensingh.', 'High', '', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2011', '', '', 'Four field experiments were conducted at the agronomy field laboratory of BAU to examine the effects of integrated use of composted MSW obtained from the INSPIRE project on the performance of Boro rice (2009-11), maize (2009-10) and T. aman rice (2009-10) and one super-imposed trail (2010-11) was given at the Farmers fields of village Sutiakhali, Mymensingh. The results showed that lone application of composed MSW did not perform well for enhancing grain and straw yields of all the 3 tested crops but integrated use of compost and fertilizer gave highly significant increases in both grain and straw yields. In 2009-10 Boro rice, 100% recommended fertilizer (RF) use in combination with 5t-10 t/ha of compost generated the most acceptable figures of grain yield of Boro rice while the optimal compost and fertilizer combination was 100%RF and 12.0 t/ha of compost, producing the highest grain yield (8.8t/ha = 150% increase over  control). The 2010-11 Boro rice gave the optimal integration of 10.50t/ha compost together with 100% FR, producing 6.7t/ha of rice grains. The integrated use of compost and fertilizer in maize also realized highly significant influences showing the combination of 100 RF + 10t compost yielding over 10t grain/ha. In T. aman rice, lone compost application was found inferior to RF use by high level interaction was found when optimal grain yield over 5.0t/ha was achieved from 13.0t/ha compost+50% RF. In super-imposed trail, grain yield of T. aman rice increased by 38.5% and 42.7%, respectively in the HYV cvs. NINA7 and BR11 rice with combined application of 10T compost + 10%RF compared to the farmers practice. The corresponding increase was 80.0% in case of local rice cv. Kalizira. It can, therefore, be concluded that integrated use of fertilizer and composted MSW has synergic effect in obtaining higher grain yield of Boro rice. Maize and T.aman rice with the commended fertilizer rate (FR) in together with around 10t/ha of the compost application. Super-imposed trail also demonstrates the yield advantages by up to 42.7% in HYV T. aman rice at farmers fields and up to 80.0% in local variety from the integrated use of 10t compost + RF than the farmers practice and therefore, the latter technology could be recommended to farmers    for large-scale cultivation.', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(3719, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Effect of tillage depth and IPNS on soil physical properties and yield of hybrid maize.', 'Central Research Farm, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2011', 'To study the effect of tillage and organic-inorganic fertilizer on soil physical properties and yield of hybrid maize.', 'A field experiment was conducted to observe the effect of tillage and IPNS on soil physical properties and yield of hybrid maize in Joydebpur, during rabi season of 2008-2009, 2009-2010 and 2010-2011. Eighteen treatment combinations comprising 3 tillage practices (T0: minimum tillage, T1: tillage up to 10-12 cm and T2: tillage up to 20-25 cm depth) and 6 levels of fertilizer i.e. F1: control, F2: 5 t cowdung + *(R-M) ha-1, F3: 10  t cowdung +*(R-M) ha-1, F4: 2.5 t poultry manure + *(R-M) ha-1, F5: 5 t poultry manure + *(R-M) ha-1 and F6: recommended dose (RD): N255 P55 K100 S40 B1 kg ha-1 was tested in a split-plot design with three replications. Tillage was assigned in the main plot and fertilizer in the sub plot. The unit plot size was 4.5 m &times; 3.0 m and maize was planted with spacing 75 cm &times; 25 cm. One third nitrogen and other fertilizers were applied at the time of final land preparation and remaining nitrogen was applied in two equal splits at 30 and 55 days after sowing. The experiment was sown with variety BARI Hybrid Maize-5 on 20 December, 2010 and harvested on 18 May, 2011. Data on physical and chemical properties of soils were collected from 0-25 cm depth.', 'A field experiment was conducted to observe the effect of tillage and IPNS on soil physical properties and yield of hybrid maize in Joydebpur, during rabi season of 2008-2009, 2009-2010 and 2010-2011. Eighteen treatment combinations comprising 3 tillage practices (T0: minimum tillage, T1: tillage up to 10-12 cm and T2: tillage up to 20-25 cm depth) and 6 levels of fertilizer i.e. F1: control, F2: 5 t cowdung + *(R-M) ha-1, F3: 10  t cowdung +*(R-M) ha-1, F4: 2.5 t poultry manure + *(R-M) ha-1, F5: 5 t poultry manure + *(R-M) ha-1 and F6: recommended dose (RD): N255 P55 K100 S40 B1 kg ha-1 was tested in a split-plot design with three replications. Bulk density, particle density, porosity and field capacity were slightly affected by tillage and IPNS but the effect was non-significant. Yield and yield contributing characters of hybrid maize were significantly influenced by both tillage and IPNS. The F3 (10 t cowdung + *(R-M) ha-1) treatment gave the highest grain yield 9.72 t ha-1 followed by F5 (5 t poultry manure + *(R-M) ha-1) treatment (9.40 t ha-1). Interaction effect of tillage and fertilizer on yield and yield contributing characters was non-significant.', 'Tillage, IPNS, Hybrid Maize, Yield', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Tillage depth and soil physical properties', 'Maize', 'From three year''s result of the study, it can be concluded that there was no significant difference among the tillage practices on soil physical properties but maize yield and yield attributes were significantly influenced by tillage practices in the second and third year. The F3 treatment (10 t cowdung + *(R-M) ha-1 performed better in respect of soil physical parameters and yield of maize which was statistically identical with F5 (5 t poultry manure + *(R-M) ha-1 treatment.', '', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3720, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Potato with Maize Intercropping system', 'Agricultural Research Station, Burirhat, Rangpur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2007', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2007', '1) To find out the suitable and economic fertilizer dose for maximizing the yield of the said intercropping system.\r\n2) To know the nutrient uptake by the crops and apparent nutrient balance.', 'The experiment on potato with maize intercropping system was conducted in non-calcareous Grey floodplain soil under AEZ-3 at ARS, Burirhat, Rangpur during rabi season 2005-2006 and 2006-2007. The initial fertility status of soil was poor and based on the soil test values the following treatment combinations were formulated and used in the study. The experiment was conducted in RCB design with 4 replications. Potato tuber (cv. Cardinal) was planted on late November maintaining the spacing of 60 cm &times; 30 cm. On the same day, maize seeds (cv. BARI Maize-5) were sown in line every after 3 and 5 potato tubers (Hills) for 15 and 25% maize population, respectively. All intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. The crops were harvested at the right stage of maturity. The relevant data and samples were collected and analyzed.', 'An experiment on potato with maize intercropping system was conducted in non-calcareous Grey floodplain soil under AEZ-3 at ARS, Burirhat, Rangpur during rabi season 2005-2006 and 2006-2007. The objectives were to find out the suitable and economic fertilizer dose for maximizing the yield and to know the nutrient uptake by the crops and apparent nutrient balance. There were eight treatments comprising 2 sets of planting geometry (PG1 &amp; PG2) and 4 doses (NM1, NM2, NM3 and NM4) of nutrient management package. The experiment was conducted in RCB design with 4 replications. The tested variety was cardinal and BARI maize-5 for potato and maize respectively. The highest tuber yield (31.61 and 30.52 t ha-1) of potato was obtained from NM1, which was statistically at par with NM2 &amp; NM3 and all of them were significantly higher over control (NM4). Incase of companion crop (Maize), the highest grain yield (2.45 and 2.32 t ha-1) was obtained from NM2 which was significantly higher over all other treatments.  The intercrop plant population up to 25% did not affect the yield of the main crop significantly although PG2 gave higher yield over PG1 for companion crop. The interaction between planting geometry and nutrient management was non significant for the main crop. Incase of companion crop, the highest yield (2.77 and 2.68 t ha-1) was obtained from NM2 &times; PG2 which was significantly higher over all other combinations. Nitrogen and potassium balances were appeared as negative for all the nutrient management packages except control. The P balance was positive for NM2 and NM3 packages and negative for NM1. Sulphur balance was marginally negative while Zn balance was positive for all the packages except control. The highest potato equivalent yield (33.83 t ha-1) along with highest gross margin (Tk. 260096 ha-1) and MBCR (14.24) were obtained from NM1 &times; PG1 and appeared as economically profitable.', 'Integrated Nutrient Management, Potato, Maize, Intercropping', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Potato and Maize intercropping', 'Accommodation of intercropped population up to 25% may be suitably adjusted with 100% main crop. The nutrient management packages (NM1, NM2, and NM3) produced reasonably higher yield and appeared as promising where the potato equivalent yield was higher in NM1 package (crop removal based dose) appeared to be economic as it provided higher gross margin and MBCR. Nitrogen and potassium balances were negative for all the nutrient management packages, which needs to be properly addressed. Phosphorus and sulphur were apparently balanced with slightly negative trend. Zinc balance was positive.', '', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3721, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Effect of Inter-cropping of Sesbania rostrata with transplant aman rice and their economic performance.', 'Agronomy Field Laboratory, BAU, Mymensingh.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '31-12-2010', '01-07-2010', '31-12-2010', '', '', 'An experiment was conducted at the Agronomy field laboratory, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh, from July to December 2010 to determine the effect of intercropping of Sesbania rostrata with transplant aman rive cv. BR11 (Mukta) and their economic performance. The experiment consisted of eleven treatments viz. i) T1 = Sole rice (25cm x 15 cm), ii)  T2 Sole Sesbania (25 cm x 15  cm), iii) T3 = rice + Sesbania (25 cm x 15 cm), iv) T4 = Rice + Sesbania (25 cm x 20 cm), v) T5 = Rice + Sesbania (25 cm x 25 cm), vi) T6 = rice + Sesbania (50 cm x 15 cm), vii) T7 + Rice + Sesbania (50 cm x 20 cm), viii) T = Tice + Sesbania (50 cm x 25 cm), ix) T9 = rice + Sesbania (75 cm x 15 cm), x) T10 = rice + Sesbania (75 cm x 20 cm), and xi T11&not; =Rice + Sesbania (75 cm x 25  cm). The experiment was laid out in a Randomized complete Block Design with three replications. Results showed that plant height (cm), number of total tillers hill-1, number of effective tillers hill -1, number of non-effective tillers hill -1, length of panicle (cm), number of grians panicle-1, number of sterile spiketlets pancicle-1, 1000 grain weight (g) grain yield (t ha-1) and straw yield (t ha-1) were significantly influenced due to intercropping of Sesbania under different spacing of Sesbania planting. The highest-grain (5.11 t ha-1) and straw (6.17 t ha-1) yields of rice were obtained from sole rice. Spacing arrangement of Sesbania planting significantly affected the most of the yield and yield attributing characters of Sesbania rostrata. The highest seed yield (901.88 kg t ha-1) and stick yield (1201.25 kg t ha-1) were obtained from sole Sesbania cropping. Rice equivalent yield (7.01 t ha-1), gross return (Tk. 144758 t ha-1), net return (Tk. 110478 t ha-1 ) and benefit cost ration 93.23) were the highest in the treatment T11 = Rice + Sesbania (75 cm x 25 cm).', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.');
INSERT INTO `research_info` (`research_id`, `org_name`, `ddcr_name`, `ppe_type`, `r_title`, `r_location`, `r_priority`, `r_type`, `r_status`, `plan_sd`, `plan_ed`, `actual_sd`, `actual_ed`, `r_objective`, `r_method`, `r_abstruct`, `r_keywords`, `fund_source`, `total_budget`, `total_expenditure`, `total_refund`, `d_technology`, `p_organize`, `p_trained`, `r_programarea`, `commodity`, `outcome`, `impact`, `reference`) VALUES
(3722, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Study on the feasibility of crop diversification in rice based cropping systems in haor ecosystem', 'Dingaputa haor Purba Tetulia Village, Mohangonj Upazila in Netrakona district', '', '', '', '20-07-2010', '15-05-2011', '20-07-2010', '15-05-2011', '', '', 'An experiment was conducted in five farmers field in Dingaputa haor Purba Tetulia Village, Mohangonj Upazila in Netrakona district during the period from 20 July 2010 to 15 May 2011. The objective of the study was to determine the feasibility of growing short duration vegetable and oil crops in seasonal fallow of Boro rice-fallow cropping patterns in terms of both combined yields and economic performance. Six short duration vegetable such as potato, red amaranth, stem amaranth, spinach, radish and mustard were the first crops and Boro rice (var. BRRI dhan28) was the second crop. Thus there were six types of cropping patterns Potato-Boro rice-Fallow, Red amaranth-Boro rice-fallow. Stem amaranth-Boro rice-Fallow, spinach-Boro rice-Fallow, Radish-Boro rice-Fallow and Mustard-Boro rice-fallow here. The experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with five replications. The results indicate that there were no significant reductions regarding growth and yield of rice due to vegetable production before Boro rice crop. Boro rice in all the cropping patterns gave statistically similar grain yields, straw yields, plant heights, number of effective tillers hill-1, number of non-effective tillers hill-1, total number of tillers hill-1, panicle length, number of grains panicle-1 and 1000 grain weights. The agronomic productivity (rice equivalent yield t ha-1) of the cropping patterns Potato-Boro rice-Fallow, Red amananth_Boro rice-Fallow, Stem amaranth_Boro rice-Fallow, Spinach_Boro rice-Fallow, Radish_Boro rice-Fallow and Mustard-Boro rice-Fallow were 22.42, 15.48, 17.04, 17.79, 22.11 and 11.56 t ha-1, respectively with economic productivity (gross return Tk ha-1) of 364162.50, 251712.50, 276900.00, 292012.50, 359125.00 and 187850.00 respectively and the benefit cost ratio of 1.88, 1.52, 1.65, 1.69, 1.75 and 1.12, respectively. From diversification practices in Dingaputa haor ecosystem potato-Boro rice-Fallow and Radhsh-Boro rice-fallow cropping patterns were found to be the most suitable cropping patterns', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3723, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Sustaining soil fertility and production of Wheat-Mungbean-T. aman cropping Pattern', 'Regional Agricultural Research Station (RARS), Jessore', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2000', '30-06-2010', '1) To update the balanced fertilizer recommendation for sustaining the production of wheat-mungbean-T. aman cropping pattern.\r\n2) To monitor soil health after each cropping pattern\r\n3) To estimate uptake of different nutrients and to make a balance sheet for each nutrient.', 'This field trial was conducted in High Ganges Floodplain Soils (AEZ-11) of RARS, Jessore during the period of 2000-2010. The experiment was laid out in a RCB design with six treatments replicated three times. The unit plot size was 5 m &times; 6 m. The treatment combinations were T1= 125% recommended dose (RD), T2= 100% RD, T3= 75% RD, T4= 50% RD, T5= Farmers practice and T6= native nutrient. The farmers practice treatment was 60-40-30 kg ha-1 of NPK respectively. The tested wheat variety was Saurav. All PKS Zn and half of N were applied at the time of final land preparation and the remaining half of N was applied before booting stage. The seeds were sown in 3rd week of November and were harvested in 3rd week of March. Only nitrogen was applied @ 20 kg N ha-1 in all the plots except the native nutrient treatment for the 2nd crop mungbean (cv. BARI Mung-6). The seeds were sown in the 4th week of March and first picking was on the first week of June and continued up to 3rd week of June. Then the total biomass was incorporated in the soil. Initial soil analysis was done following standard soil test protocol. Soil pH was measured by glass electrode pH meter, organic carbon by wet oxidation method, total N by micro-Kjeldahl method, available P by Olsen method, exchangeable K &amp; Mg by IN NH4OAc, pH 7.0 extraction, available S by 0.15% CaCl2 extraction, available Zn, Fe, Mn &amp; Cu by DTPA extraction and available B by MCP extraction followed by determination by azomethine-H.\r\nThe same sequence was maintained in T. aman (BRRI dhan-33) for fertilizer treatments. The seedlings were transplanted in the 1st week of July and harvested in the 1st week of October. LSD test was used to determine the significant differences in the response of different treatment combinations. Fertilizer rates for the pattern are given below: RD for wheat = 120-35-75-20-5 kg of N P K S Zn ha-1, respectively, FP = 60-18-30 kg of N P K ha-1, respectively + 5 t ha-1 CD for mungbean = 20 kg N per ha RD for T. aman = 100-40-60 kg of NPK/ha, FP = 60-18-30 kg of NPK kh ha-1.\r\n', 'A long term field experiment on wheat-mungbean-T. aman cropping pattern was carried out in high Ganges Floodplain Soils (AEZ-11) of RARS, Jessore during 2000-2010. The objectives were to find out sustainable fertilizer recommendations, monitor soil health, estimate uptake of different nutrient for the cropping pattern &amp; to make a balance sheet for each of the nutrient. There were six treatments (125% recommended dose (RD), 100% RD, 75% RD, 50% RD, farmers practice and native nutrient). The design was RCBD with three replications. Result showed consistently highest yield from each of the crops of the pattern with 125% RD treatment and which were statistically similar to 100% RD treatment. As the grain yield and biomass production were higher in 125% RD treatment, the total nutrient uptake was also higher in this treatment. The nutrient balance sheet indicated a negative balance of N and S in all treatments but there were positive balances of P and Zn in all the treatments except for the native fertility treatment. In case of K, a large amount was removed form the soil, which may lead to K depletion in the long run.', 'Soil fertility, Sustaining, Wheat, T. aman, Cropping pattern, Green biomass', 'Others (Please specify):', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, '', '', 'Initially there was a declining trend in grain yield of T. aman, the cropping pattern showed fairly sustainable yield. Although farmers dose showed higher economic return but it appears to be unsustainable regarding the yield and soil health. To bring production sustainability at least 100% RD dose should be adopted but resource rich farmers may use 125% dose to get higher gross margin. However, mungbean biomass should be incorporated in to the soil with proper care to sustain the organic matter level. It is obvious from the nutrient balance calculation that nitrogen and potassium mining occurs from soil so nutrient management should be carefully planned to maintain soil fertility and crop production.', 'Mungbean biomass increase soil health and increase total productivity of wheat-mungbean-T. aman cropping pattern.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3724, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Effect of municipal solid waste compost, fertilizers, rhizobial inoculation and flora on the growth and yield of wheat', 'Soil Science Field Laboratory of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-12-2010', '30-04-2011', '01-12-2010', '30-04-2011', '', '', 'The effects of municipal solid waste (MSW) compost, fertilizers, rhizobial inoculation and flora on the growth and yield of wheat was studied through a field experiment at the Soil Science Field Laboratory of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh, during December, 2010 to April, 2011. The soil belongs to the Sonatata soil series under the AEZ-9 (Old Brahmaputra Floodplain soil). The soil was silty loam in texture having pH 6.94, organic matter 1.62%, total nitrogen 0.067%, available phosphorus 10.45 ppm, exchangeable K 0.08 me/100g soil, available sulphur 12.00 ppm and caution exchange capacity 15.0 me/100g soil. There were seven treatments such as To = control, T1 100% recommended dose N P K S Zn and B fertilizers (RDF)O, T2 = 100% RDF + compost @ 3.5 t ha-1, T3 = 100% RDF + compost @ 3.5 t ha-1, + Rhizobium, T4 = 75% RDF + 25% N based compost, T5 = 75% RDF + 25% N based compost + Rhizobium, T6 = 100% RDF + Flora. The experiment was laid out in a Randomized complete Block Design with three replications. Nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, sulphur, zinc and boron were applied as basal dose from TSP, MOP, gypsum, zinc oxide and boric acid @ 100 kg N, 30 kg P, 80 kg K, 15 kg S, 2 kg Zn and 1 kg B, respectively as the recommended dose. Compost was applied @ 3.5 t ha-1 and N-based as per the treatments. Flora was sprayed 3 times days after sowing. The seeds were inoculated with rhizobial strains immediately before sowing. Intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. Data were collected on plant height, spike length, spikelets spike-1, filled grains spike-1, grain and straw yields. The NPKS contents in grain and straw were determined and the total NPKS uptake was calculated. Inoculation of seeds with rhizobial strains and application of MSW compost and fertilizers significantly influenced all the parameters studied. All the treatments increased the grain and straw yields of wheat significangtly over control due to different treatments and the yields ranged from 866.7 kg to 5333 kg ha-1, and 1000 kg to 3833 3.5 ha-1, respectively. The NPKS content in wheat grain and total uptake by wheat grain due to different treatments ranged from 1.310 to 1.870%, 0.265 to 0.358%,  0.308 to 0.358%, 0.308 to 0.388%, 0.157 to 0.220% and 12.88 to 108.45 kg, 3.61 to 18.63 kg, 11.77 to 63.19 kg, 1963 to 13.78 kg 3.5 ha-1, respectively. Application of fertilizer (N P K S Zn B) increased the wheat yield significantly over control. Again of MSW compost application with fertilizers increased wheat yield significantly over fertilizer application. Rhizobial inoculation in combination with MSW compost and fertilizer application further increased wheat yield considerably. Application of growth regulator flora did not show any beneficial effect on wheat production. Rhizobial inoculation in combination with compost application can reduce the use of fertilizers for wheat production. Application of 75% recommended dose of NPKS Zn and B fertilizers with 25% N-based compost.', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3725, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Efficacy of Vermicompost in improving the soil health and sustaining the yield of cabbage.', 'Central farm, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2010', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2010', 'To study the efficacy of Vermicompost to improve soil health, yield and nutrient uptake of cabbage in grey terrace soil of Bangladesh', 'A field trial was conducted with cabbage (cv. Atlas-70) during the rabi season 2009-2010 in Grey Terrace Soil of Bangladesh,  AEZ-28. Joydebpur soil belongs to the Chhiata series of Grey Terrace Soil (AEZ-28). The tested crop was cabbage (cv. Atlas-70). There were 12 treatments: T1= 100% RCF, T2= 80% RCF, T3= 60% RCF, T4 = VC (1.5 t ha-1) + 100% RCF, T5= VC (3 t ha-1) + 80% RCF, T6= VC (6 t ha-1) + 60% RCF, T7= VC (6.0 t ha-1), T8= CC (1.5 t ha-1) + 100% RCF, T9= CC (3.0 t ha-1) + 80% RCF, T10 = CC (6.0 t ha-1) + 60% RCF, T11 = CC (6.0 t ha-1) and T12 = control. The experiment was laid out in 8.1 m2 plots in a randomized complete block design with 3 replications. Equal sized healthy twenty five days old seedlings of cabbage were transplanted on 23th November 2009 with a spacing of 60 cm from row to row and 45 cm from plant to plant. Fertilizers were applied as per treatment based on BARC fertilizer recommendation guide 2005. The 100% recommended dose of N-P-K-S-B was 250-35-65-40-2 kg ha-1, respectively and these were used in the form of urea, TSP, MP, gypsum, and Boric acid, respectively. The entire amount of P, K, S, B, VC and CC and 1/3rd N were broadcasted and incorporated in the soil at the time of final land preparation and the remaining 2/3rd N was applied in two equal installments at 25 and 45 days after transplanting. 25 days old seedlings were transplanted in the 3rd week of November 2009. Harvesting of cabbage was done when the head attained proper size and at full maturity. Ten plants from each plot were tagged at random to take records on different agronomic parameters of cabbage. Data on growth, yield and yield contributing parameters were recorded and statistically analyzed with the help of statistical package MSTAT-C and mean separation was tested at 1% for significance by DMRT. Post harvest soil and plant samples were also collected and analyzed.', 'A field trial was conducted with cabbage (cv. Atlas-70) during the rabi season 2009-2010 in Grey Terrace Soil of Bangladesh,  AEZ-28 to observe the ability of vermicompost to increase the growth, yield and nutrient uptake of cabbage and to improve soil health. The experiment was laid out in RCB design with twelve treatments replicated three times.  The sources of VC were cowdung and kitchen wastes (3:1) processed by epigeic earthworm Eisenia fetida. Different nutrient packages significantly influenced the yield and yield components of cabbage. It was observed that 100% RCF + 1.5 t ha-1 VC produced the highest head yield (99.3 t ha-1) of cabbage. This yield was statistically identical with 100% RCF + 1.5 t ha-1 CC (94.0 t ha-1) and 80% RCF + 3.0 t ha-1 VC (89.1 t ha-1). Vermicompost exhibited better performance than CC alone or in combination with chemical fertilizer. The enhanced yield of cabbage in this study can be partially explained by the elevated levels of NPKSB contents in the VC. It is suggested that VC (1.5 t ha-1) + NPKSB (100%) is more favourable for higher head yield of cabbage but VC (3 t ha-1) + NPKSB (80%) can be economically and environmentally suitable. In this fertilizer package, 20% chemical fertilizer is reduced in presence of VC. Use of VC can play a vital role in minimizing the fertilizer crisis. All the treatments showed a negative balance for N and K and those for P and S was positive balance except the control treatment at Joydebpur. Residual effect of VC showed increased plant available nutrients in post harvest soil; to improve and sustain soil health as well as to improve crop production, chemical fertilizer rate needs to be reduced. Vermicompost @ 3 t ha-1 along with 80% RCF (N240 P35 K60 S30 B1 kg ha-1) appeared as the best suited combination for maximizing the yield of cabbage in Grey Terrace Soil of Bangladesh (AEZ-28).', 'Vermicompost, Cabbage, Conventional compost', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Please select a program area', 'Cabbage', 'Vermicompost is more efficient than conventional compost for cabbage cultivation. The treatment package consists of 3 t VC ha-1 with 80% RCF (N240 P35 K60 S30 B1 kg ha-1) appeared as the best suited combination for maximizing the yield of cabbage in the study area (AEZ-28). As such, 20% amount of chemical fertilizer may be reduced from the present recommendation with the addition of 3 t ha-1 of vermicompost. This integrated package of nutrients may left a considerable amount of plant nutrients in soil, which might be helpful in sustaining the soil health as well as would be beneficial for the next crop. Apparently N and K balances were found negative, which need to be taken into account.', 'Soil health will be improved through using organic manures and yield of crop also be increased.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3726, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Long term Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining soil fertility and yield of Maize-mungbean-T. aman cropping pattern.', 'Central farm, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2011', '1) To find out judicious fertilizer recommendation for Maize-Mungbean-T. aman cropping pattern for sustainable yield.\r\n2) To monitor soil health after each cropping cycle\r\n3) To estimate uptake of different plant nutrients and make a balance sheet for each of the nutrients.', 'The long-term field experiment was initiated in the Chhiata series at Joydebpur (AEZ-28) during 2007-2008. The initial soil samples, collected from a depth of 0-15 cm were analyzed in the laboratory following standard methods. Soil pH was measured by glass electrode pH meter, organic carbon by wet oxidation method, total N by micro-Kjeldahl method, available P by Olsen method, exchangeable K &amp; Mg by N NH4OAc, pH 7.0 extraction, available S by 0.15% CaCl2 extraction, available Zn, Fe, Mn &amp; Cu by DTPA extraction and available B by MCP extraction followed by azomethine-H determination.\r\nThe collected main produce (grain, pod, curd) and by-product from each plot was dried in an oven at 65oC for about 24 hours and ground by a grinding mill. Later the ground samples were then chemically analyzed for P, K, S and micronutrients following di-acid digestion procedure. Nitrogen was determined following on the conventional sulphuric acid digest.\r\nThe experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with four replications. Five different treatments viz. T1: Native nutrient, T2: HYG (FRG) from chemical fertilizers, T3: HYG (STB) from chemical fertilizer, T4: HYG (STB) from chemical fertilizer + 5 t ha-1 CD and T5: HYG (STB) from chemical fertilizer + 3 t ha-1 PM were selected for different plots randomly. The unit plot size was 5m &times; 6m. The tested crop for maize was BARI hybrid maize-5. Maize seeds were sown in line with 75 cm row to row and 25 cm seed to seed spacing. \r\nFertilizer N-P-K-S-Mg and B were supplied from urea, TSP, MP, gypsum, Magnesium sulphate and boric acid respectively. All PKSMgB and 1/3 of N were applied at the time of final land preparation. The remaining two third of N were applied as top dress at 30 and 60 days after sowing. The maize was harvested in the end of April each year. Plant samples and post harvest soil samples were collected from each plot for chemical analysis.\r\nFor T. aman rice, the variety BRRI dhan39 was used in the experiment. Transplanting was done during the middle of July with a row to row spacing of 20 cm and plant to plant spacing of 15 cm. All fertilizers including 1/3rd  of N were applied before transplanting. Rest of N was applied in two installments at 15 and 45 days after transplanting. T. aman rice was harvested in the third week of October. Data on yield and yield contributing characters were recorded and statistically analyzed.\r\n', 'A long-term field experiment on maize-mungbean-T. aman cropping pattern was conducted in the Grey Terrace Soil (AEZ-28) of Gazipur during the year of 2007-2011 with the objective of finding out suitable fertilizer combination for sustainable yield of the pattern, monitoring soil health as affected by chemical fertilizers and organic manures and to make a balanced sheet of each nutrients. There were five treatments viz. T1= Native nutrient, T2 = HYG (FRG) from chemical fertilizers, T3 = HYG (STB) from chemical fertilizer, T4 = HYG (STB) from chemical fertilizer + 5 t ha-1 CD, T5 = HYG (STB) from chemical fertilizer + 3 t ha-1 PM. The experiment was laid out in RCBD design with four replications. Data revealed that the T5 produced the highest yield of maize grain consistently in four maize crops. The legume component (mungbean) produced about 1.2 t ha-1 grain and added over 7 t ha-1 green biomass. The third crop (T. aman) also produced the highest yield with the T5 treatment. The yield of maize and rice were statistically similar to all other fertilizer treatments. The native nutrient treatment produced the lowest yield. This trend of influence was consistent for almost all the yield contributing characters of maize and rice. The nutrient removal by maize and rice was standard and needs presentation of a balance sheet for the nutrients.', 'Long-term, Sustaining, Soil fertility, Maize, T. aman, Cropping pattern, Poultry manure', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Maize-Mungbean-T aman pattern', '1) Although CD and PM produced higher yields over the FRG rates but increase was not substantial\r\n2) The yield and growth was substantially affected where organic manures were not added.\r\n3) The FRG treatment treatment could be modified as MYG (STB) + 5 t CD.', 'Organic manures improve soil fertility and increase crop yield.', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3727, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Lentil with Mustard mixed cropping systems', 'Regional Agricultural Research Station (RARS), Jessore', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2007', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2007', '1) To find out the suitable and economic fertilizer dose for maximizing the yield of the said mixed cropping system.\r\n2) To know the nutrient uptake by the crops and apparent nutrient balance.\r\n', 'The experiment was conducted at Regional Agricultural Research Station, Jessore under AEZ-11 during rabi 2005-2006 and 2006-2007. Organic matter content of the soil was low (1.16%). Potassium, sulphur, and Zinc status of the soil were found to be at par or below the critical level. On the basis of soil test value, the following treatments were formulated and used in the study. The treatments were arranged in RCB design with 4 replications. Lentil variety BARI Masur-4 and mustard variety BARI Sharisha-9 were used @ 36 and 8 kg ha-1 respectively. The seeds were sown broadcast on first week of November. The experiment was conducted under rainfed condition. Plant protection measures and other intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. Crops were harvested at their right stage of maturity. Plant samples were collected and chemical analysis were done and nutrient uptake and balance were calculated. Yield data was recorded and analyzed statistically.', 'An experiment on lentil with mustard mixed cropping system was conducted in calcareous dark grey floodplain soil under AEZ-11 at RARS, Jessore during rabi 2005-2006 and repeated for 2006-2007. The objectives were to find out the suitable and economic fertilizer dose for maximizing the yield and to know the apparent nutrient balance. There were 8 treatments comprising 2 sets of planting geometry (PG1 &amp; PG2) and 4 doses (NM1, NM2, NM3 and NM4) of nutrient management. The experiment was conducted in RCB design with four replications. The tested variety was BARI Masur-4 for lentil and BARI Sarisha-9 for mustard. The crops were grown under rainfed condition. The nutrient package NM2 (based on FRG05) produced the highest yield (1402 and 1394 kg ha-1) for lentil, which was statistically identical with NM3 (IPNS based dose) but significantly higher over NM1 (crop removal based dose). Almost similar trend of response was found in mustard (companion crop) where the highest seed yield (261 and 334 kg ha-1) was obtained in NM2 during first and second year, respectively. Higher plant population (up to 30%) of mustard did not affect the yield of the main crop (lentil) significantly. The interaction effect between planting geometry and nutrient management was statistically non-significant. However, the highest gross margin (Tk. 59548 ha-1) along with highest MBCR (8.12) was obtained from NM2 &times; PG1 package. Nitrogen and K balances were positive for all the treatments while P and Zn balances were positive for NM2 and NM3 packages.', 'Lentil, Mustard, Mixed cropping, Integrated nutrient management, Cost and return', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated nutrient management', 'Lentil and Mustard', 'The PG2 (100% lentil + 30% mustard) appeared to be the suitable crop combination under lentil with mustard mixed cropping system.\r\nBoth NM2 (FRG05 based dose) NM3 (IPNS based dose) appeared to be promising for optimizing the yield of the said mixed cropping system.\r\nNitrogen and potassium balances were highly negative for all treatments because recorded yield was higher than the target; as such, higher rates of nutrients should be applied for yield sustainability and restoration of soil fertility.\r\nHighest gross margin and MBCR were recorded from NM2 and thus appeared as economically profitable.\r\n', '', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3728, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Horticulture', 'Project', 'BAU-Germplasm Center, fruit tree improvement program (FTIP).', 'BAU-Germplasm Centre, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '1991', '1991', '', '', '', '', 'BAU-GERMPLASM CENTER (BAU-GPC)-The largest fruit bio-diversity center in Bangladesh-one stop service for fruit conservation, diversity, research, development, extension, education and recreation. Initially the project was established on 1 acre of land in 1991 funded by Swiss Agency for develo9pemnt and Cooperation (SDC) whose mission was established of a seed bank and extension of technologies among the farmers. About 8500 thousand plants of 161 species have been planted and being maintained in this Germplasm Centre. Over the past 20 years FTIP has developed a vast array of improved and conserve resources and science based appropriate technology for fruit tree propagation. Last year extended about 10 acres of land with the objectives i) to maintain the germplasm centre (GPC) as a facility for education, research and training ii) to conserve the germplasm resources (fruit free, medicinal plants and associated agro forestry sp.) iii) to supply quality planting materials to various organization. BAU-GPC at present conserves 220 varieties of mango, 57 varieties of guava, 25 varieties of litchi and 48 varieties of citrus. 94 accession of jackfruit, 67 species of minor fruits and 52 species of exotic fruits collected from 47 countries including 97 species of medicinal plants. BAU-GPC-FTIP has been released total 70 varieties of fruits. Different systematic approach like sapling distribution, exchange visit, motivational tour, and demonstrations was performed for implementation of the project. In total 104 MS students are doing research here from different discipline on conservation, bio-diversity, integrated crop management, post-harvest technologies and processing.', 'Fruit, Germplasm, Horticulture. bio-diversity, medicinal plants.', 'Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC)', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Germplasm', 'Fruit', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3729, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Horticulture', 'Project', 'Adaptive research on BAU developed high value, nutritive rich fruit varieties in different region  with special emphasis on extreme saline tolerant and sandy areas of Bangladesh.', 'Fifteen Uapzillas under 9 district (Palashbari and Sadar upazilla Gaibandha, Pirganj upazilla under Rangpur, Nageswari and Bhurungamari upazilla under Kurigram, Aditmari and Patgram Upazilla under Lalmonirhat, Tarash and Ullapara Upazilla under Sirajganj, Lalpur under Natore, Iswardi and Sadar Upazilla under Pabna, Mongla and Morelganj upazilla under bagerhat and Agoiljhara upazilla under Barisal district) were selected for Research Location/Site. ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Fifteen Uapzillas under 9 district (Palashbari and Sadar upazilla Gaibandha, Pirganj upazilla under Rangpur, Nageswari and Bhurungamari upazilla under Kurigram, Aditmari and Patgram Upazilla under Lalmonirhat, Tarash and Ullapara Upazilla under Sirajganj, Lalpur under Natore, Iswardi and Sadar Upazilla under Pabna, Mongla and Morelganj upazilla under bagerhat and Agoiljhara upazilla under Barisal district) were selected.  The adaptive research is expected to identify the most suitable BAU developed high value fruit varieties in three (extreme north, north-western, and saline) selected regions. Unit now, BAU-GPC developed released 39 different varieties of mango, guava, jujube, citrus and other fruits. Both on-field and household demonstrations has been conducted with some of the selected fruit varieties in all 15 selected upazilas. There were four on-field demonstration has been  conducted in a land of 22-50 decimal and 60-140 saplings of different fruit varieties has been planted. The planning of the demonstration has been carefully conducted with consultation of the demonstration farmer and considering appropriateness of the varieties. Each of the 25 selected households was provided with saplings of 4-5 high value fruit varieties. Household women were responsible for the homestead plantation and the varieties have been provided as per their choice and needs. For all plants, support has also been provided for planting care and intercultural operations. Beneficiaries have been provided with four-days training programme on propagation and management of fruit trees orchard and eight in-situ training programme has been provided in the farmers field. The result may disseminate to the ASPS II farmer groups through training, result demonstration, and field days. In particular, a number of field days have been organized in some selected upazillas. The grassroots level extension organizers of DAE, who has played a vital role in communication the obtained information to the farming community. Results have been informed though supplying of leaflets and other extension materials. DAE officials were involved in communicating and dissemination of technology to the ASPS II farmers (ICM-FFS groups), while the participating NGOs (AFIP, world Vision, BRAC, PROSHIKA, RDRS etc.) are carry out the technologies to their groups of rural poor.', 'Fruit, Nutritent, Salinity, Sandy areas', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Nutrient', 'Fruits', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
