(3765, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for the production of Garlic in old brahmaputra flood plain soil', 'BARI Regional Station, Jamalpur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-11-2007', '30-03-2008', '01-11-2007', '30-03-2008', '1) To determine an optimal combination of fertilizer and manure for yield maximization of garlic.\r\n2) To evaluate the integrated use of organic manures viz. cowdung, poultry manure and mustard oilcake with chemical fertilizers on the yield of garlic.\r\n', 'The experiment was carried out from November 2007 to March 2008 in Old Brahmaputra Flood Plain soil (AEZ-9) of BARI Regional Station, Jamalpur. Two garlic varieties BARI Rasun-1 (V1) and Jamalpur local (V2) were used as test crop. There were ten treatment combinations of fertilizer and manures as T1:  100% optimum fertilizer dose (OFD) viz. N152.5 P60.6 K126.5 S44 Mg11.5 Zn4.08 B1.36, T2: 50% of the OFD (N76 P30 K79 S22 Mg5, Zn2, B0.68), T3: T2 + 10 t CD ha-1, T4: T2 + 15 t CD ha-1, T5: T2 + 2 t PM ha-1, T6: T2 + 3 t PM ha-1, T7: T2 + 1 t MOC ha-1, T8: T2 + 2 t MOC ha-1, T9: Farmers practice (FP) (N75 P0 K52 S15 DAP300 kg ha-1 + cowdung 12 t ha-1), T10: Control treatment (No fertilizer and manure). The treatments were arranged in randomized complete block design with three replications. Cowdung, poultry manure and mustard oilcake were used as organic manure. Two levels for each of the manure were : cowdung (10 and 15 t ha-1), poultry manure (2 and 3 t ha-1) and mustard oilcake (1 and 2 t ha-1). There were 60 unit plots each measuring 2m &times; 1.5 m. Well decomposed cowdung, poultry manure (PM), and mustard oilcake (MOC) were applied to the plots 15 days before planting cloves. Fertilizers such as urea, TSP, MP, gypsum, MgO, ZnO and boric acid were used as sources of N, P, K, S, Mg, Zn and B, respectively. Full amount of TSP, gypsum, Zinc oxide, magnesium oxide and boric acid and 50% each of urea, MP and DAP were applied at planting. The rest of the 50% urea, MP and DAP were applied as top dressed in two equal installments at 30 and 50 days after planting.\r\nData on plant height, leaf number, length and diameter of bulb, single weight and bulb yield were recorded. Plant height and leaf number per plant were recorded at 20 days interval starting from 30 days after emergence of seedling and it was continued up to 110 days. Bulbs were harvested on 30 March 2008. Both initial and post harvest soil as well as plant sample were analyzed following standard methods. The collected data were statistically analyzed using MSTAT-C program.  \r\n', 'An experiment was conducted from November 2007 to December 2008 to determine the suitable combination of chemical fertilizer and organic manure for yield maximization of garlic. There were 10 combinations of fertilizer and manure as T1:  100% optimum fertilizer dose (OFD) viz. N152.5 P60.6 K126.5 S44 Mg11.5 Zn4.08 B1.36, T2: 50% of the OFD (N76 P30 K79 S22 Mg5, Zn2, B0.68), T3: T2 + 10 t CD ha-1, T4: T2 + 15 t CD ha-1, T5: T2 + 2 t PM ha-1, T6: T2 + 3 t PM ha-1, T7: T2 + 1 t MOC ha-1, T8: T2 + 2 t MOC ha-1, T9: Farmers practice (FP) (N75 P0 K52 S15 DAP300 kg ha-1 + cowdung 12 t ha-1), T10: Control treatment (No fertilizer and manure). Yield potentiality of two garlic varieties BARI Rasun-1 and Jamalpur local were evaluated with these fertilizer treatments. Treatments were distributed in factorial RCB design with three replications. BARI Rasun-1 (7.04 t ha-1) gave significantly higher yield than Jamalpur local (6.27 t ha-1). The highest bulb yield (7.83 t ha-1) was obtained with T6 treatment over control and 100% OFD (T1) were 48.5 and 8.56%, respectively. Bulb yield of 8.54 t ha-1 was obtained from T6 treatment with BARI Rasun-1 and the lowest yield (3.94 t ha-1) was found in the control treatment with Jamalpur local variety. Maximum marginal benefit cost ratio, MBCR (10.6), the highest gross return (Tk. 2,74,050) and gross margin (Tk. 2,61,529) were obtained in T6 treatment.', 'Garlic, Nutrient, Growth and Yield', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Garlic', 'Depending on the yield, gross margin and MBCR values, the fertilizer package N76 P30 K63 S22 Mg5.75 Zn4, B0.68 kg ha-1 along with 3 t poultry manure ha-1 may be recommended for the production of garlic in old Brahmaputra flood plain soil under Jamalpur region, in Bangladesh and similar environment else where.', '', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
