(3768, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Effect of Integrated Nutrient Management at Farmers Homestead on the yield of Cabbage', 'Farmers homestead in Dhirashram village of Gazipur sadar, Gazipur ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2007', '01-07-2005', '30-06-2007', '1) To evaluate the proper nutrient management packages and\r\n2) To determine the economic dose of fertilizer for cabbage\r\n', ' The experiment was conducted at MLT site Dhirashram, Gazipur sadar (AEZ-28) during the rabi seasons of 2005-2006 and 2006-2007. The design of the experiment was RCBD with five dispersed replications. The plot size was 4m &times; 5m. Autumn Queen was used as a variety which was transplanted from 1-7 November. Fertilizers were applied as per treatment based on soil analysis and BARC fertilizer recommendation guide 1997. Initial soil analysis was done following standard soil test protocol. Soil pH was determined by glass calomel electrode pH meter, OC was determines following Walkley and Black (1934) method, available P following modified Olsen method, S by CaCl2 extraction following turbidity method, Zn by DTPA extraction and B by MCP extraction method. Five different fertilizer packages were tested and the treatments were T1 = IPNS based fertilizer management for high yield goal (HYG) with PM, T2= IPNS with CD for HYG, T3= Soil test basis inorganic for HYG, T4= Farmers dose and T5= control.\r\nThe entire amount of CD, PM, P, S, B and one half of K were applied during final land preparation. Total amount of urea and remaining one half of K were applied as top dress in three equal splits at 7-10, 25-30 DAT to heading stage. Thirty five days old seedlings of cabbage were transplanted at a spacing of 60cm &times; 60cm. Intercultural operations such as weeding, irrigation and pest control measures were done in order to maintain the normal crop growth. Irrigations were given six times. The crops were harvested on 11-18 January. Data on yield and yield attributes along with other parameters were collected properly and subjected to statistical analysis.\r\n', 'The experiment was conducted at MLT site Dhirashram, Gazipur sadar (AEZ-28) during the rabi seasons of 2005-2006 and 2006-2007 to evaluate the proper nutrient management packages and to determine the economic dose of fertilizer for cabbage. The cabbage variety Autumn Queen was tested. Soil test based (STB) inorganic fertilizer doses for HYG and IPNS treatment with poultry manure (PM) and cowdung (CD) along with farmers practice and control (No fertilizer) treatment were verified.  Average of two years data showed that higher head yield of cabbage (110.6 t ha-1) was obtained from IPNS based fertilizer for HYG with PM. Regarding cost and return analysis higher gross margin for organic fertilizer reduced the BCR in IPNS treatment.', 'Homestead, Cabbage, Integrated Nutrient Management, Poultry manure, Cowdung', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Cabbage', 'From the two years result, it was found that, higher yield and return was obtained from integrated nutrient management with poultry manure (T1) and soil test based inorganic fertilizer dose for high yield goal (T3) in cabbage. Considering the yield, cost and return as well as soil fertility concern the fertilizer packages based on IPNS (T1 and T2) for HYG were found superior for cabbage production in Gazipur sadar under AEZ-28.', '', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
