(3784, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Horticulture', 'Project', 'Collection, conservation, characterization of garlic and onion', 'BAU Germplasm Centre, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '13-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '13-05-2009', '31-07-2011', '', '', 'The project was carried out to collect, conserve and characterize of garlic &amp; onion germplasm and developed suitable onion seed production technologies at BAU-germplasm Center, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Maymensingh during period from 13 May 2009 to 31 July 2011. Physio-morphological Characterization of 25 Garlic Genotypes has been completed. Sixteen (16) promising garlic germplasm out of 25 have been from better in respect to their growth and yield performance (6-9.6 t/ha). Among these the highest yield (9.6 t/ha) was observed from garlic germplasm G 49 ( Vietnam-2009) and it has been registered from National Seed Board of Bangladesh BAU Garlic-3 (Reg, No. 05(14)-05/2011). Morpho physiological characterization of 11 onion germplasm has also been completed. Six (6) promising onion germplasm out of 11 have selected on their growth and yield performance (10-60 t/ha). Among these, the highest yield (15.60 t/ha) was observed from onion germplasm 0-8. Allicin content of 26 local accessions and 12 USDA accessions was estimated in last year (2009-2010). Ti was observed that allicin was found in both clove and leaves of all local garlic genotypes. USDA clove contains higher allicin than local genotypes. Among the local germplasm G13 clove contained higher allicin (2.4 mg/ml) and G15 leaves contained higher allicin (1.9 mg/ml). An experiment which was conducted to know the performance of selecgted garlic germplasm under zero tillage (under chalan beel) condition. Among the selected 8 garlic germplasm BAU garlic-1 showed highest vield (7.2 t/ha &amp; 6.3 t/ha) in both dry land and zero tillage condition followed by BAU garlic -2 (7.0 t/ha to 6.2 t/ha). The lowest yield (5.53 t/ha and 5.10 t/ha) in both dry land and zero tillage condition was observed in Garlic-33, respectively. Under field validation with different organic practices were also conducted to know the suitable organic manure and date of planting on the yield and quality of onion seed under this project. The results are poultry manure (paragon and quality of onion seed under this project. The results are poultry manure (paragon compost) and 31 October (planting time) is the best for yield and quality of onion seed production.', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Collection, Conservation and Characterizations', 'Spiece Crops', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3785, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Bitter Gourd', 'Field of Horticulture Research Centre, BARI, Joydebpur, Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-03-2011', '30-06-2011', '01-03-2011', '30-06-2011', 'To study the effect of N, P, K, and S fertilizer on yield attributes and yield of bitter gourd (cv. BARI Karola-1).', 'The experiment was carried out at the research field of Horticulture Research Centre, BARI, Joydebpur, Gazipur during the period from March to June 2011 on a grey terrace soil. The initial soil samples were collected from a depth of 0-20 cm prior to fertilizer application and analyzed in the laboratory.\r\nThe soil test values showed that the experimental soil was deficient in nutrients especially N, P, K and S. The soil is slightly acidic. There were fourteen treatments comprising four levels each of N (0, 90, 120 and 150 kg ha 1), P (0, 20, 40 and 60 kg ha-1), K (0, 40, 80 and 120 kg ha-1) and S (0, 20, 30  and 40 kg ha-1).The field experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with three replications. The unit plot size was 2m &times; 2m. BARI Korola-1 was used in this trial. The whole amount of PSBZn, CD and &frac12; K was applied and mixed up with the soil during final pit preparation. Twenty five days old seedlings were transplanted on March 5, 2011. Only one plant was planted on a pit. Nitrogen was applied around the plants after 15 days of transplanting. Half of K and 2nd installment of N were top dressed at flower initiation stage by ring placement method. The remaining 1/3 N was applied to the plants at fruiting stage. Irrigation and other intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. Plants were supported by bamboo stick before flowering. Young bitter gourd fruits were harvested time to time starting from first week of May to last week of June 2011. Yield data were collected, analyzed statistically and the mean differences among the treatments were compared by DMRT.\r\n', 'A field experiment was carried out at the research field of Horticulture Research Centre, BARI, Joydebpur, Gazipur during the period from March to June, 2011 to study the effect of N, P, K, and S fertilizer on yield attributes and yield of bitter gourd (cv. BARI Karola-1). There were fourteen treatment combinations comprising four levels each of N (0, 90, 120 and 150 kg ha-1), P (0, 20, 40 and 60 kg ha 1)), K (0, 40, 80 and 120 kg -1) and S (0, 20, 30 and 40 kg ha-1) along with a blanket dose of 2 kg B, 4 kg Zn ha-1 and 5 t cowdung ha-1. The combined effect of NPKS significantly increased yield attributes and yield of bitter gourd. The highest yield and yield attributes of bitter gourd was achieved by the treatment N120 P40 K80 S30 kg ha-1 (T12). Response of N and P was distinct in comparison to K and S. A significant quadratic response was observed between yield to added N and P levels. Similar response was also found in case of K and S.', 'Bitter gourd, INM, Kharif', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Bitter Gourd', 'The present result indicates that judicious nutrient management in bitter gourd can ensure high yield. Application of N120 P40 K80 S30 kg ha-1 along with a blanket dose of 2kg B, 4 kg Zn ha-1 and 5 ton cowdung ha-1 appeared as the best combination for maximizing the yield of bitter gourd in the study area (AEZ-28).', '', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
