(3787, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated nutrient management for tomato in high barind tract', 'FSRD site Kadamshahar, Godagari, Rajshahi ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', 'To find out an optimum and economic fertilizer dose for tomato production in high barind tract.', 'A study was undertaken at the FSRD site Kadamshahar, Godagari, Rajshahi during 2006-2007 and 2007-2008 to find out an optimum and economic fertilizer dose for tomato production in high barind tract. Before conducting the experiment, soil of the experimental field was analyzed in the SRDI laboratory. The soil of the experimental plots belongs to Amnura series under AEZ-26.\r\nFertilizer recommendations for high yield goal (HYG) were determined from soil test values according to Fertilizer Recommendations Guide 2005. The fertilizer levels used by the farmers were considered as farmers practice (FP). This was the average of the fertilizer doses used by the farmers of the village Kadamshahar during 2005-2006. The sources of nutrients were urea for N, TSP for P, MP for K, gypsum for S and Zinc oxide for Zn. Cowdung had 0.96% N, 0.27% P, 0.82% K. Full doses of cowdung, one fourth of urea and all other inorganic fertilizers were applied according to individual plotand mixed with soil at the time of final land preparation. The rest urea was top dressed at 21, 35 and 45 days after transplanting. The unit plot size was 3m &times; 2m. Thirty days old seedlings of tomato (cv. Surrokha) were transplanted on 16 September 2006 and 27 September 2007 with the spacing of 60 cm &times; 50 cm. Tomato was harvested on 1st December 2006 to 15 January 2007 and 8 December 2007 to 2 February 2008. Intercultural operations viz. weeding, irrigation, fungicide and insecticide spray were done in order to support normal plant growth. Data on yield and yield contributing characters were recorded. Observations were made on yield components from 10 randomly selected plants per plot. The data were analyzed statistically and the mean differences were adjusted by LSD. The economic analysis was done for gross return, marginal benefit cost ratio and marginal rate of return for different nutrient management packages following the method suggested by Perrin et al. (1979).\r\n', 'A study was undertaken at the FSRD site Kadamshahar, Godagari, Rajshahi during 2006-2007 and 2007-2008 to find out an optimum and economic fertilizer dose for tomato production in high barind tract. The treatment combinations were T1= N140 P40 K90 S30 Zn4 kg ha-1 (Based on soil test for HYG), T2= T1 + cowdung 5 t ha-1, T3 = N124 P33 K74 S30 Zn4 kg ha-1+ cowdung 5 t ha-1 (IPNS for high yield goal), T4 = N135 P37 K50 S8 Zn1.5 kg ha-1, T6 = N80 P30 K55 S20 kg ha-1 (Farmers practice) and T7 = Native fertility (Control). The yield and yield components of tomato were significantly influenced by the different nutrient management packages in both the years. The IPNS treatment (T3) produced the maximum fruit yield of tomato (43.05 t ha-1 in 2006-07 and 58.36 t ha-1 in 2007-08) which was 155% and 217% higher over control in 2006-07 and 2007-08, respectively. The highest gross margin Tk. 290020 ha-1 was obtained in T3 treatment followed by Tk. 260760 ha-1 in T2 treatment. So, the fertilizer dose N124 P33 K74 S30 Zn4 kg ha-1+ cowdung 5 t ha-1 was optimum for maximizing the yield as well as economically profitable and viable for tomato production in the high barind tract soil.', 'High Barind Tract, Integrated Nutrient Management, Tomato, IPNS', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Tomato', 'The present result indicates that judicious nutrient management in bitter gourd can ensure high yield. Application of N120 P40 K80 S30 kg ha-1 along with a blanket dose of 2kg B, 4 kg Zn ha-1 and 5 ton cowdung ha-1 appeared as the best combination for maximizing the yield of bitter gourd in the study area (AEZ-28).', '', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3788, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Horticulture', 'Project', 'Collection, characterization and conservation of vegetable and fruit plant genetic resources of Bangladesh.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '', '', 'Three experiments were conducted during July, 2010 to June, 2011. In experiments 1 &amp; 2, field performance and genetic variability of 8 red amaranth (Amaranthus tricolor L.) and 12 stem amaranth (Amaranthus oleraceus L.) accessions using RAPD were investigated. In experiment 1, red amaranth accession AT-08 gave the highest yield (20.53 t/ha) and AT-05 gave the lowest yield (16.91 t/ha). In experiment-2, the stem amaranth accession A0-09 gave the highest (52.78 t/ha) yield and A0-12 gave the lowest (36.67 t/ha) yield. Molecular characterization and diversity study of red and stem amaranth accessions were conducted using RAPD markers. DNA amplification of 8 red amaranth accessions with four decamer primaers produced 13 distinc bands of which 0 (73.34%) were considered as polymorphic and 3 bands (26.66%) were monomorphic. In stem amaranth, selected four decamer primers generated 12 distinct bands of which 11 (94.45%) were considered as polymorphic and 1 band (5.55%) was monomorphic. Among 8 red amaranth accessions, the highest (0.955) genetic distance was observed between AT-02 vs. AT-07 while lowest (0.080) genetic distance was observed between AT-07 and AT-08. The highest genetic distance was observed between AO-05 vs. Ao-12 while lowest genetic distance was observed between A0-10 and AT-11 among the 12 stem amaranth accessions. In experiment 3, field performance of 13 F1 liens of lemon (Citrus limon) was studied. Significant variations were recorded among the F1 lines in respect of different morphological characters, growth and yield. F1 lines (2x33) and (18x33) and (18x33) were tallest (214 cm) and smallest (105 cm), respectively. Among 13 F1 lines ((7x33) and (18x33) showed the highest (78.20%) and lowest (37.11%) fruit set, respectively. Highest (13.67) number of fruit was produced by F1 lines (3x33) and (7x33), lowest (1.67) was shown by F1 line (2x24). Highest fruit weight (102.33 g) was found in line (33x34) and lowest (51.33g) in F1 line (3x2). In case of plant height, plant spread, male: hermaphrodite flowers ratio, percent fruit set and yield per plant; F1 liens (7x2), (7x33), (7x2), (7x33) and (33x34) showed highest significant positive heterosis (129.41, 315.22, 77.25, 141.96 and 72.43, respectively) over mid parent.   ', 'Vegetable, Fruit, Plant, Plant genetic ', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Genetics', 'Fruit and Vegetables', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3789, 'Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute', 'Soil Science Division', 'Experiment', 'Integrated Nutrient Management for Cucumber', 'Horticulture Research Centre, BARI, Gazipur ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', '01-07-2006', '30-06-2008', 'To determine the optimum fertilizer dose for maximizing the yield of cucumber', 'An experiment was conducted at the research field of Horticulture Research Centre, BARI, Gazipur during Kharif season of 2006-2007 and 2007-2008. The soil test values showed that the experimental plots were deficient in nutrients especially N, P, K and S. The field experiment was set up in a randomized complete block design with three replications. The variety Shila was used as a test crop. The unit plot size and plant spacing were 2m &times; 2m and 1.5m &times; 1.5 m respectively. There were fourteen treatments comprising four levels each of N (0, 40, 80 and 120 kg ha-1), P (0, 20, 40 and 60 kg ha-1), K (0, 30, 60 and 90 kg ha-1) and S (0, 10, 20 and 30 kg ha-1) along with blanket dose of B2.0 Zn3.0 kg ha-1 and cowdung 10 t ha-1. The whole amount of P, S, B, Zn, CD and &frac12; K were applied and mixed up with the soil during final pit preparation. Nitrogen was applied around the plants after 15 days of transplanting. Half of K and 2nd installment of N was top dressed at flower initiation stage by ring placement method. The remaining 1/3 N was applied to the plants at fruiting stage. Transplanting was done on the 2nd April 2007 and 20th March 2008. The intercultural operations were done as and when necessary. Young cucumber fruits were harvested from 13th May to 16th July, 2007 and 28th April to 21st May, 2008. The necessary field data were recorded from two selected plants at each treatment. The optimum and economic dose of fertilizer nutrients were calculated using the formula: Y = -b/2c and Y = 1/2c (pf/py  b) respectively.', 'An experiment was conducted at the research field of Horticulture Research Centre, BARI, Gazipur during Kharif season of 2006-2007 and 2007-2008. The objective was to determine the optimum fertilizer dose for maximizing the yield of cucumber. Treatments comprising four different levels of N, P, K and S along with blanket dose of Zn3.0 B2.0 kg ha-1 and cowdung 10 t ha-1. The treatments were arranged in a randomized complete block design with three replications. The combined effect of NPKS significantly increased yield and yield attributes of cucumber. Significant synergistic effect on yield and yield attributes of cucumber was achieved from the treatment of N80 P40 K60 S20 kg ha-1. However, the response of N and P was more distinct in comparison to K and S. From regression analysis it was found that the relationship was quadratic in nature. An optimum economic dose of N84 P50 K64 S24 kg ha-1 was obtained from polynomial regression equations. The said dose along with the blanket dose of B2.0 Zn3.0 kg ha 1 and cowdung @ 10 t ha-1 may be recommended for cucumber production in grey terrace soil of Joydebpur under AEZ-28.', 'Nutrient management, Cucumber', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Publication', '', 0, 'Integrated Nutrient Management', 'Cucumber', 'From two years study it is evident that judicious nutrient management in cucumber can ensure high profit. However, it can be concluded from this findings that application of 84-50-64-24-kg NPKS ha-1 along with the blanket dose of B2.0 Zn3.0 kg ha-1 and cowdung @ 10 t ha-1 was appeared to be the optimum economic dose for cucumber cultivation in grey terrace soil of Joydebpur under AEZ-28.', '', 'S. Noor, N.C. Shil, M.A. Haque, 2012. Integrated Nutrient Management for sustaining Crop yield &amp; Soil fertility. Soil Science Division, Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI), Joydebpur, Gazipur. Publication no.-14  '),
(3790, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of  Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Nursery diseases of some selected fruit species in Bangladesh.', 'Mymensingh, Dinajpur, Rajshahik, Jhenaidah, Moulovibazar, Jessore, Bogra, Rangpur, Modhupur (Tangail), Faridpur, Ramgorh, Khagrachari, Sharupkathi, Savar and Gazipur', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Nursery diseases of nine different selected fruit species viz. Mango, Lithchi, Jujube, Jackfruit, Guava, Lemon, Banana, Papaya and Coconut were investigated in the 14 different locations viz. Mymensingh, Dinajpur, Rajshahik, Jhenaidah, Moulovibazar, Jessore, Bogra, Rangpur, Modhupur (Tangail), Faridpur, Ramgorh, Khagrachari, Sharupkathi, Savar and Gazipur. Altogether 94 nurseries were investigated. Diseases of fruit species in the nurseries were recorded and surveillance of nursery diseases of fruit species were investigated. In  mango 8 different diseases (anthracnose, bacterial leaf spot, red rust, powdery mildew, scab, bacterial leaf blight, malformation and die-back), in litchi 4 diseases (leaf spot, leaf blight, die-back and red rust), in jujube 2 diseases (leaf spot and leaf blight), in jackfruit 2 diseases (leaf spot and lead blight), in guava 4 diseases (leaf spot, leaf blight, red rest and anthracnose), in lemon 4 diseases (leaf spot, die-back, scab and canker), in coconut 2 diseases (leaf spot and bud rot), in papaya 3 diseases (damping off, leaf spot and leaf curl) and in banana 3 diseases nurseries of fruit species leaf blight of mango and leaf blight of litchi were first time recorded in Bangladesh, where the diseases causal organism was identified as Pseudomonas syringae pv. Syringae by challenge test as well as by biochemical tests. The diseased plant parts of different fruit species were collected from different selected locations of Bangladesh. Isolation and preservation of pathogens were carried out. The weather data of different locations were also collected. Relationship of weather data on incidence and severity of different diseases of fruit species. Viz. anthracnose of mango, red rust of mango, bacterial leaf blight of mango and malformation of mango; leaf blight of litchi, and die-back of litchi; leaf spot of jujube and bacterial leaf blight of jujube; leaf spot of jackfruit; anthracnose of guava; die-back of lemon and canker of lemon; damping off papaya, leaf curl of papaya and papaya, mosaic; leaf spot of coconut and bud rot of coconut and sigatoka of banana, were studied. Molecular characterization as well as pathogenic variability of the isolated pathogens will be studied shortly. Pot experiment as well as field experiment has been started for developing eco-friendly management model of nursery diseases of selected fruit species in Bangladesh.', 'Fruit, Nursery, Species, Diseases, Bacterial leaf spot, red rust, ', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Fruits', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3791, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Genetic improvement of teasle gourd', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '', '', 'Bangladesh is a densely populated country and about 30% of the people are suffering from malnutrition. Vegetables are one of the important source of nutrients for human. In summer, vegetables are scantly. Among the summer vegetables teasle gourd (Momordica dioeca Roxb.) is  one of the important source of nutrients, it  has high food value. Germination of seeds is very difficult or impossible for its hard seed coat. As a dioecious plant, the propagation entirely depends on underground tuberous roots. Maintenance of tuberous roots in the field or in storage is difficult. Fruit quality of kakrol deteriorates due to presence of large number of hand seeds. Micro-propagation and use of mutagens may help to overcome these problems to a great extent by producing new variants. Seedless or less seeded teasle gourd may be obtained by applying mutagens during biotechnological studies.\r\n\r\nStudy in 2010-2011 comprised two experiments. I. comparative study of normal and regenerated plants on the basis of morphological characters. II. Effect of gamma ray (physical mutagen) in teasle gourd.\r\n\r\nI.	Normal and regenerated tease gourd plants were evaluated. The morpho-physiological variations were much prominent between normal and regenerated plants. Regenerated plant is a good yielder in respect of fruit number, individual fruit weight and lesser number of seeds fruit-1. \r\nII.	Gamma radiated in lower doses (5 Gray), callus obtained from cotyledon explants had higher number of shoots compared to control. The radiated callus was grown on solidified MS medium containing 1 mg L-1 BA &amp; 0.3 mg L-1 IBA. Decrease in the number of shoots and shoot bud formation was observed in higher doses (15 &amp; 20 Gray) of gamma radiation.\r\n', 'Gourd, Genetic, Malnutrition, Teasle gourd', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Vegetables', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
