(3857, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of parasitology', 'Project', 'Epidemiology and pathology of Onchocerca spp. infection in cattle', 'Department of parasitology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-08-2008', '31-07-2009', '01-08-2008', '31-07-2009', '', '', 'Epidemiology and pathology of Onchocercosis was studied during August, 2008 to July, 2009 through slaughter houses examination. Out of 190 samples examined from cattle. 104 (54.73%) samples were found positive for two species of Onchocerca. Onchocerca amillata was detected only from aorta whereas Onchocerca gutturosa from the ligamentum nuchae. The prevalence of Onchocerca amillata (56.84%) was higher than Onchocerca gutturosa (52.63%). Over all parasitic burden was (2.84&plusmn;0.37), but mean parasitic burden of Onchocerca gutturosa (3.24&plusmn;0.54) was higher than Onchocerca amillata (2.44&plusmn;0.74). In case of Onchocerca gutturosa, prevalence was significantly (p&amp;#706;0.05) higher (61.29%) in older cattle aged &amp;#707;4 years than young aged between &amp;#707;2-4 years (50.00%) and calf (37.5%) aged 1-2 years. In case of Onchocerca amilliata, the prevalence was significantly (p&amp;#706;0.01) higher (65.78%) in older cattle aged &amp;#707;4 years than young aged between &amp;#707;2-4 years (57.14%) and calf (25.00%) aged 1-2 year. Prevalence of Onchocerca gutturosa was significantly (p&amp;#706;0.01) higher in female (58.00%) than the male (46.67%) for Onchocerca gutturosa and 54.24% for Onchocerca amillata. In case of Oncerca gutturosa, the prevalence was significantly (p&amp;#706;0.01) higher in May (80.00%) and lower in November (30.00). In case of Onchocerca amillata the prevalence was significantly (p&amp;#706;0.01) higher in March (77.77%) and lower in September (37.50%). In case of Onchocerca gutturosa, the prevalence was significantly (p&amp;#706;0.01) higher in summer season (67.85%) followed by Rainy (50.00%) and winter (42.85%) seasons. In case of Onchocerca amillata the prevalence was significantly (p&amp;#706;0.01) higher in summer season (70.83%) followed by winter (54.28%) and rainy (50.00%) seasons. Gross examination of the affected aorta showed thickened, dilated and elevated. Histological examination revealed the parasitic granuloma with infiltration of eosinophils and numerous section of parasites (Onchocerca amillata) in the wall of aorta. So, it is concluded that onchocercosis is a threat to cattle irrespective of age, sex of the host and seasons of the year.  ', 'Epidemiology, Onchocerca, Infection, Cattle', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Disease management', 'Cattle', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3858, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of parasitology', 'Project', 'The effect of herbal and commercially available antiprotozoal drugs on pigeon trichomoniasis due to Trichomonas gallinae', 'Department of parasitology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Efficacy of four herbal and five commercially available antiprotozoal drugs was evaluated in vitro and in vivo on pigeon trichomonasis due to Trichomonas gallinae. Experimental groups were given with these medicines at different concentrations (%) and doses and control groups were not given any drugs. Among the herbal drugs (Thankuni, Neem, Bishkatali and Guava). Thankuni 20% conc. Showed the highest efficacy (80% and 75% in vitro and in vivo condition, respectively) where as Guava (10% conc.) had the lowest efficacy (38.46% and 33.33% in in vitro and in vivo condition, respectively). Among the commercial drugs (metronidazole, tinidazole, ornidazole, secnidazole, nitazoxanide), metronidazole &amp; ornidazole (30mg/kg bwt.) had the highest efficacy (100%) in both in vitro and in vivo condition where as nitazoxanide (30mg/kg bwt.) had the lowest efficacy (84.61% and 83.33% in in vitro and in vivo condition, respectively). In each cases efficacy was highest when higher concentration and doses was used. No exception was recorded. The present study suggests that metronidazole is the most effective drugs tested against pigeon trichomonasis and also proved cost effective. ', 'Antiprotozoal drugs, Trichomonas, Pigeon, Gallinae', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Effect of herbal drugs on livestock', 'Pigeon', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3859, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of parasitology', 'Project', 'Epidemiology of schistosomiasis in Ruminants (Cattle, Goat) and identify their risk factors with pathological effects.', 'Department of parasitology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Epidemiology of schistosomiasis and its risk factors with pathological effects were studied from 278 fecal samples and 169 visceral samples from naturally infected cattle and goat of Bangladesh. Eleven hundred different snails were also examined. By fecal examination and intestinal scrapings examination showed two species of schistosomes, namely, S. indicum and S spindale were found in Bangladesh. Overall prevalence of schistosomiosis was 60.63%. The prevalence was higher in cattle (67.40%) than goat (46.29%). Prevalence was higher (83.83%) in adult cattle than young (56.37%) and calf (21%). Sex wise prevalence showed higher in male (75.29%) than female (41.15%) and breed wise prevalence showed that local breeds were more susceptible than cross breed animals. The study also revealed that Schistosoma was more positive in visceral sample than fecal sample. Among the 1100snail examined, 3.09% were found positive with furcocercus cercaria. The relative distribution of eggs within the intestinal wall showed striking changes as the infection progressed. Histopathology of intestines showed that presence of immature schistosomes in the lamina propria and eggs in the cystic area of lamina propria with infiltration of lymphocytes, neutrophils and macrophages. It was concluded that the prevalence of visceral schistosomiasis in cattle and goat is underdiagnosed and the carrier status of these animals in the sub clinical state is potentially high. Therefore, it is suggested to design an appropriate sustainable control strategy of the parasite.  ', 'Schistosomiasis, Epidemiology, Ruminants, Pathological effects', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Disease management of Livestock', 'Cattle and Goat', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3860, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology', 'Project', 'Organoleptic attributes and biochemical evaluation of jackfruit pulp as affected by cryopreservation', 'Departement of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology, BAU, Myemnsingh ', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Organoleptic attributes and biochemical characteristics of three types of jackfruit pulp stored at low temperature were analyzed to make prediction whether the pulp could be made available year round by means of cryopreservation. The samples were stored at about 20&deg;C and the analysis was carried out at 0 day, 90 day, 180 day and 270 day of storage period. The results show that there are significant changes in the chemical properties and organoleptic attributes of jackfruit pulp during storage. Carotene and vitamin C content decreased gradually for all the varieties up to 270 days of storage period. TSS content increased slightly during storage. Total, reducing and non-reducing sugars content were almost stable throughout the storage period. Titrable acidity for all the varieties slightly increased and pH values decreased. Organoleptic attributes also decreased slowly.\r\n\r\nTow nutritionally important compounds, vitamin C and carotene decreased considerably during storage. These two important antioxidant need some attention so that they can be preserved during storage. This result of the study provides important information to the processing industry to produce products with a better nutritional quality and investigate whether the jackfruit pulp has a potential market for commercial cultivation. \r\n', 'Jackfruit, biochemical, Organoleptic. ', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Viramin', 'Fruits', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3861, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of pathology', 'Project', 'Cholesterol lowering effects of Lupinus angustifolius (Sweet lupin) in rats', 'Department of pathology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'To assess the minimum level of incorporation of L. angustifolius in the diet (as the lone protein source) and its effects on concentrations of tri-glycerides, total cholesterol, low density-lipoproteins (LDL) and blood urea nitrogen (BUN) in plasma, weaned rats were fed fat-free milk protein based diet (LACT: 330g/kg) and diets containing either lupin protein as raw meal supplemented with methionine (LMM: 266g/kg). Lupin meal extracted with 70% cold ethanol, supplemented with methionine (LME: 266g/kg) and non protein control (NPC) for 21 days. Diet based on raw sweet lupin and solvent extraction induced substantial decrease in both total plasma cholesterol and low-density lipoprotein (LDL) as compared to those of lactalbumin protein. There was about 2.5 times reduction in LDL level in rats fed LMM and LME than the corresponding LACT rats. However, triglyceride level in rats fed on LMM and LME showed a substantial increase as compared to those of LACT. Although, LMM and LME consumed less protein than those of LACT however, lupin seed meal supported the growth and well being of the animals. Histo-pathologic studies have revealed that solvent extraction has almost eliminated the toxic effects that was exerted by the raw lupin seed meal and so did decrease the BUN level. These results suggest that solvent extraction may take sweet lupin seed safer and makes it as one of the stronger natural hypo-cholesterolemic agents when results of total plasma cholesterol and LDL levels were studied from LLM and LME compared with the LACT. The hypocholesterollaemic action of lupin seed meal is attributable possibly to impaired intestinal cholesterol absorption, probably involving strange chelating effect of lupin protein that has reduced the micellar solubilization of cholesterol. Furthermore, according to the present investigations, the contribution of the up-regulation of genes involved in tri-acyl-glycerol hydrolysis in lupin feeding needs to be explained.  ', 'Cholesterol, rats, Lupin, LDL', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Cholesterol lowering effects', 'rats', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3862, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Breeding &amp; Genetics', 'Project', 'Community driven livelihood program with red Chittagong cattle', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The research project is aimed to conserve and improve the red Chittagong Cattle through enhancing the livelihood of community farmer. From the inception of the project up to date the details information regarding progeny, productive and reproductive performance and farmers benefits from milk and animal sale are being recorded with close monitoring. The mean birth weight, 205 day weaning weight, weaning age of male, female and pooled values were 14.21 &plusmn; 0.27 (34), 14.79 &plusmn; 0.37 (35) and 14.50 &plusmn; 0.23 (69) kg, 41.54 &plusmn; 2.05 (20), 47.85 &plusmn; 3.03 (20) and 44.69 &plusmn; 1.87 (40) kg, 191.68 &plusmn; 3.26 (20), 185.60 &plusmn; 3.30 (20) and 188.56 &plusmn; 2.34 (40) days respectively. The mean lactation length, lactation milk yield, daily milk yield and dry period were 228.13 &plusmn; 6.61 (52), 466.66 &plusmn; 27.38 (41) kg and 260.97 &plusmn; 24.77 (32) days, respectively. The mean postpartum estrous period, service period, conception rate and calving interval were 160.05 &plusmn; 15.89 (37) days, 215.52 &plusmn; 17.33 (42) days 73.30 &plusmn; 3.15 (80)% and 509.89 &plusmn; 15.37 (65) days, respectively the average herd mortality was 9% from which calf mortality was 16.5%. the monetary benefits are being realized by RCC farmers through milk sale growing bull sale, culled cow sale etc. The findings of the study indicate that farmers are making money out of RCC genetic resource being ensured. Further, biological data being generated on animals of new generations and parties / stages are creating research opportunity for the graduates and would be useful to standardize performance and animal recording system in rural household level. ', 'Red Chittagong cattle, livelihood,', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, '', '', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3863, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Breeding &amp; Genetics', 'Project', 'Development and application of decision-support tools to conserve and sustainably use genetic deversity in indigenous livestock and wild relatives', 'Department of Animal Breeding &amp; Genetics, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'It was evident from the study that 37.26% households reared goat and 75.57% reared chicken. About 9.25% households kept Dwarf Deshi, Long Leg, 3.39% Naked Neck and 88.29% unidentified indigenous breed. About 67.27% households reared 2.00 Black Bengal, 14.73% reared 1.41 Brown Bengal, 1.66% reared 2.00 White Bengal, 31.46% reared 1.93 Boiragi and 5.69% reared 0.78 Black and White Bengal goats. Evidence showed that 97.85% households reared chicken in free range system at the day and 62.44% households kept chicken in confined condition at night. The results also showed that 92.27% households kept goat at free range system at day and 60.88% households kept goat at night in confined house. On an average, 21.74% households purchased feed for chicken. About 99.5% chicken owners and 80.5% Black Bengal goat owners practiced natural uncontrolled methods for breeding. New Castle was identified main disease for chicken and 45% households were affected by this disease. Dysentery was the main problem for goat keeping families. Only 20.15% chicken and 30.22 goat keeping households used vaccines as preventive measures. Age at 1st laying was 6.48 &plusmn; 0.123 months, average number of days per clutch was 18.04 &plusmn; 0.398, the number of eggs per clutch was 15.72 &plusmn; 0.413 and the number of clutch per year was 3.37 &plusmn; 0.105. The male weight at maturity of chicken was 1.14 &plusmn; 0.04 kg while female weight at maturity was 1.02 &plusmn; 0.02 kg. Age at 1st kidding of goat was 10.59 &plusmn; 0.52 months, number of kids/kidding was 2.04 &plusmn; 0.8, kidding interval was 155.14 &plusmn; 9.31 days, dry period was 82.26 &plusmn; 5.83 days, lactating period was 72.88 &plusmn; 3.77 days, male weight at maturity was 8.98 &plusmn; 0.62 kg, female weight at maturity was 12.36 &plusmn; 0.99 kg. The results of the study indicate that the indigenous chicken and goats represent valuable assets for the rural households.', 'Livestock, wild relatives, Goat, Black Bengal, ', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Livestock', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3864, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of pathology', 'Project', 'Molecular genetic analysis of Fasciola gigantica occuring in cattle in Mymensingh', 'Department of Pathology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Random amplified polymorphic DNA (RAPD) was conducted for molecular genetic analysis of 16 Fasciola gigantica isolates to observe genetic variability and relatedness among them. Three out of 10 decamer random primers were used to amplify genomic DNA and the primers yielded a total of 15 RAPD markers of which 11 were considered as polymorphic. The percentage of polymorphic loci is 73.33%. Genetic variation statistics for all loci, average number of allele is 1.7333 and average number of gene diversity is 0.2396 and their standard deviation is 0.4577 and 0.1847, respectively. The co-efficient of gene differentiation (Gst) and gene flow (Nm) values across all loci were 1,0000 and 0.0000, respectively indicating genetic divergence among populations. Dendrogram based on Neis (1972) genetic distance using Unweighted Pair Group Method of Arithmetic Means (UPGAM) indicated segregation of 16 F. gigantica isolates into two main groups: Group-1 contains isolate-1, isolate-8, isolate-10, isolate-5, isolate-6, isolate-9, isolate-13, isolate-15, isolate-14, isolate-2, isolate-7, isolate-3, isolate-11, isolate-16, isolate-4; while isolate-12 alone is grouped in Group-II. Isolate-12 belonged to group-II. This isolate is separated from other 15 F. gigantica isolates. Genetic distance is higher between isolate-12 vs. other F. isolates. Genetic variation refers to the differences in the hereditary constitutions of the individuals of a species and it is important in maintaining the pathogenic stability and biological potential of a species of the parasite. Highest genetic variability within populations and significant genetic differentiation between populations indicates stable genetic resources of a species. This study indicates that isolate-12, isolate-9 and isolate-16 contains the highest genetic variation and they are in the separate cluster. Again isolate-1, isolate-8, isolate-10, isolate-13 and isolate-15 have the lowest genetic variation and they are in the same cluster. Comparative examination of the results obtained by RAPD analysis and the information about the isolates sources give evidence that a predominant clone of F. gigantica isolates is circulating in Bangladesh and there is sufficient genetic diversity persists among them. Thus, RAPD offer a potentially simple, rapid and reliable method to evaluate genetic variation and relatedness among 16 F. gigantica isolates. ', 'Genetic analysis, Fasciola gigantica, cattle, isolates', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Molecular genetic analysis', 'Fasciola gigantica', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3865, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Breeding &amp; Genetics', '', 'Genetic Variation on the control of Resistance to Nematodes in the small Ruminant in Bangladesh: Artificial Challenge of Haemonchus contortus. ', 'Bandarbah and Natore districts', 'High', 'Applied', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The activities of the project are running as per schedule of the project. This research is being conducted as part of studies on QTL of economic traits of Black Bengal goat in Bangladesh. This project is founded by Bangladesh Agricultural Research Council. The QTL study requires accurate recording of phenotypes of experimental animals. Animal recording for production, reproduction and health traits (parasite infestation) has already been introduced for experimental animals of this program. The farmers of shits program are now aware of animal recording. Ear tag with identification has been set to each and every animal of this program and phenotypic performance of animal is being recorded regularly. The animal identification and recording will also continue in next year and subsequent years also.\r\n\r\nTo quantify relative resistance to gastrointestinal parasites of different populations of goat, measures have been taken to use an artificial challenge protocol followed by a natural field challenge for BBH (Black Bengal goat of Hilly region) and BBW (Black Bengal goat of western region). BBH is assumed to have resistant to gastrointestinal parasites specially Haemonchus contortus and BBW is assumed to be susceptible to gastrointestinal parasites specially Haemonchus contortus. 20 BBW goats of 4-5 month old were collected from Bandarban (Hill district) and transferred to Natore, a district in the western part in the 1st week of March, 2011. 20 goats of BBW of same age were also selected form Natore. There are 8 male and 12 female goats in each group. These 40 animals were subjected to artificial challenge. In 3rd week of March, 2011 all the goats were treated with lvermectin @ 1 ml/10kg body weight for deworming. Faces were collected every week to check the presence of parasite as well as for total egg count. In the middle of May, 2011, a blood sample for DNA extraction were collected and animals were challenged with 5000 infective L3 larvae. Body weight, fecal egg counts (FEC), packed cell volume (PCV), and FAMACHA scores were taken at 0, 28, 38, and 42 days after artificial infection. Haemonchus contortus was absent in the BBH population but present in BBW population. The PCV of goats was 7.06 &plusmn; 5.72% on an average with a range of 40% to 20% in Bandarban district. The same was 22.36 &plusmn; 4.13 on an average with a range of 15 % to 35% in Natore. In artificial challenge, fecal egg counts (FEC) was almost 0 at 0, 28, 35, and 42 days after artificial infection in BBH population whereas FEC ranged from 500 to 1300 in BBW population or the same period. Such variation was also observed for PCV and Hb value in BBH and BBW population.\r\n', 'Goat, BBW, BBH, Ruminant, Genetic variation', 'BARC', 0, 0, 0, '', '', 0, 'Economical Production', 'Animals', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3866, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of pathology', 'Project', 'Epidemiology, pathology and sensitive tools for the diagnosis of Peste des petits ruminants in Bangladesh.', 'Department of pathology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The present study was aimed to investigate the descriptive epidemiology. Sero-prevalence, efficacy of local PPR vaccine, pathology of PPR in Bangladesh and to adopt RT-PCR for quick detection of PPR using filter paper. Peste des petits ruminant (PPR) is an acute viral disease of small ruminants caused by a Morbillivirus and characterized by fever, oculonasal discharges, stomatitis, diarrhea and pneumonia. The disease causes severe losses to small ruminant production and is presently considered as one of the major threats to about 22 million small ruminant population of Bangladesh. Epidemiological information was collected with a disease report form. For sero-prevalence 600 sera were collected randomly from 30 herds of different areas of Bangladesh and for vaccine efficacy 100 healthy unvaccinated goats were selected. Sera were collected before, 21 days and 180 days of vaccination. Both sera samples were analyzed using competitive ELISA. A filter paper method of PPRV RT-PCR was developed using blood, nasal swabs and tissue suspensions, filter papers placed directly into the PCR tube. Mortality was recorded higher in the young goat (&amp;#706;1 year). Introduction of newly purchased animals from the market played an important role in transmission of the virus in the flock. Religious festival also played an important role in dissemination of the virus throughout the country. An overall sero-prevalence of 21% has been found in the country. It was observed that after 21 days of vaccination 62% of the goats were sero-positive and after 180 days post vaccination it declined to 34.72%. Grossly, emaciated and dehydrated carcarsses, severe hemorrhagic enteritis, consolidated lungs and hemorrhagic lymphnodes were observed. Microscopically, enteritis with large mononuclear infiltration, tracheaitis, broncho-intestitial pneumonia consistent with large mono nuclear infiltration in the interestial space and fibrin were found. RT PCR using smeared filter paper with blood and nasal swab was successfully standardized. Nasal swab yielded positive detection in both febrile and non febrile state, while blood yielded positive detection only in febrile state. Filter paper method of RT-PCR using nasal swab could be sensitive tools for the diagnosis of PPR in infected herd.  ', 'Epidemiology, pathology, Peste des petits, Ruminants', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Animal disease management', 'Ruminants animal', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3867, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Animal Breeding &amp; Genetics', '', 'Studies on the Quantitative Trait Loci (QTL) of economic traits in Black Bengal Goat: Phenotypic of G0 and G1 populations.', 'Bandarban and Natore district', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'This experiment is being carried out in the department of Animal Breeding and Genetics, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh to produce seed stock of Black Bengal goat and to detect Quantitative Traits in Black Bengal goats. Two flocks of goats are being reared through contact farmers in Natore and Bandarban district respectively. Carcass yield, litter size and kidding interval are the traits of interest for QTL study and selection criteria. Ear tags have been set to all the selected goats for proper identification and record keeping. The recording of productive traits is being carried out using standard record sheets. Farmers volunteers in cooperation of contact farmers maintain the records on productive traits. Birth weight of 326 kids (for G0 and G1 does for 1st and 2nd parities) in Natore as recorded so far was 1.25 &plusmn; 0.01 kg and the growth rate was 49.77 gm per day for 90 days. The birth weight of 56 kids of selected does in Bandarban district ranged from 0.80 to 2.0 kg with an average weight of 1.37 &plusmn; 0.26 kg. The litter size in Natore and Bandarban area was 2.00 and 1.91 respectively (considering 1st and 2nd parity together). Kidding interval of G0 does in Natore was 213.20 &plusmn; 3.71 days. Grade and standard have developed to evaluate meat yield and meat quality. The dressing% ranged from 36.16 to 52.32% for the control group in Natore. That ranged from 50.00 to 55.00% for the control group in Bandarban. Genotyping of bucks, does and kids used in this experiment has started. Husbandry of goat rearing of contract farmers has been improved resulted increase in number of goat per family. In conclusion, it may be said that field units with experimental animals are running to a positive direction to fulfill the desire goal.', 'Black Bengal Goat, Animal Breeding, Animals', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Economical Production', 'Animals', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3868, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of pathology', 'Project', 'Genetic Characterization of peste des petits ruminants virus of Goats', 'Six selected areas namely Dhaka, Jessore (South west), Rajshahi (North west), Sylhet (North east), Chittagong (South east) and Mymensingh (South)', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The aim of the present study was molecular characterization of the peste des petits ruminants (PPR) virus circulated throughout the country and has been making havoc around the year to our 22 million small ruminants. This study was conducted over a period of 12 months at six selected areas namely Dhaka, Jessore (South west), Rajshahi (North west), Sylhet (North east), Chittagong (South east) and Mymensingh (South). Different outbreaks were investigated and samples (Lymphnodes Lung tissue etc.) were collected for RT-PCR and sequencing. RT-PCR was initially standardized using vaccine virus as a positive control and a PPRV-F specific primer set. RT-PCR was performed with Qiagen One step RT-PCR kit. Several isolates were collected from the collected samples of the different out breaks. F gene of representative isolates were sequenced aligned and phylogenic tree was constructed with some other available similar gene sequence. It was found that our isolates belong to the lineage 4 with other Avian isolates.', 'Peste des petits, ruminants, Goat, Genetic', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Disease management of ruminants', 'Goat', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3869, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Poultry Science', 'Project', 'Effect of Arsenic on Chicken performance and its contamination to chicken meat', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'A study was conducted to investigate the effects of naturally occurring Arsenic on the performance of broiler and desi (local) chicken, and its transmission to meat and organs. Two trails were conducted with 0, 250, 500, 1000 ppb of Arsenic (As) in drinking water to broiler (Trial-1) and desi chicken (Trial-2). In Trial-1 the birds were reared in cage &amp; the experiment continued for a period of 28 days. Where commercial broiler diets were fed ad-libitum. In trial 2, desi birds were reared in cage for a period of 70 days. Starter diet was fed ad-libitum which was prepared by Arsenic contaminated feed ingredients collected from arsenic contaminated area of Faridpur.\r\n\r\nBody weight, feed consumption, FCR and dressing (%) were reduced with the increase of arsenic concentration. Mortality was significantly increased with the increase of arsenic concentration. Arsenic was found in the edible meat, organs and the dropping. Arsenic level is poultry meat and organs was below the level harmful for human consumption. However, we should be concerned about the indiscriminate use of chemical fertilizer, pesticide, growth promoter etc that may affect meat quality for continuous use. \r\n', 'Poutrly, Broiler, Arsenic', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Arsenic', 'Poultry', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3870, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Effect of weeding and foliar application of urea fertilizer on the yield and yield components of boro rice', 'Department of Agronomy, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-02-2009', '31-07-2010', '01-02-2009', '31-07-2010', '', '', 'The experiment was conducted at the Agronomy Field Laboratory, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during boro season starting from February 2009 to July 2010. Four weeding regimes viz. no weeding (W0), one weeding (W1), two weeding (w2), three weeding (W3) and urea doses i.e. no urea application (N0), 60 kg N ha-1 (N1), 80 kg N ha-1 (N2), 100 kg N ha-1 (N3), 120 kg N ha-1 (N4) and 220 kg N ha-1 (N5) were included in the study as experimental treatments. The treatments N1 to N4 were practiced by spraying of urea fertilizer through solution in 3 installments at 15 days interval starting from after 15 days of transplanting. Incase of N5, urea top dressed in three equal splits following the same procedure. Weedings were done before the application of urea as per experimental design. The experiment was laid out in a split plot design with three replications. The unit plot size was 4 m &times; 2.5 m i. e. 10 m2. BRRI dhan29 was used as experimental crop. Triple Super Phosphate (TSP), Muriate of Potash (MP), gypsum and Zinc sulphate were applied at per BRRI recommendation at final land preparation. Fifty day old 2 seedlings hill-1 were transplanted on 11 February 2009 at 25 cm &times; 15 cm spacings. Weeding exerted significant influence on yield and yield components of boro rice. Two weeding produced the highest grain, straw and biological yields. The highest yield might be contribution of highest number of effective tillers, more number of grains panicle-1. Spraying of urea solution did not show any remarkable contribution in grain yield. Highest grain yield was obtained with highest dose when applied in split. This indicates that spraying of urea solution in rice is not as effective as was observed in split application.', 'Weeding, Foliar application, Urea, Boro Rice', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'N fertilizer management', 'Boro rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.');
