(3871, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Maximizing Profitability from off-season Jute seed production by intercropping and mixed cropping with Partially Shade tolerant crop species.', 'Agronomy field laboratory, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2007', '30-06-2009', '', '', 'Six field experiments were conducted during the period from July 2007 to June 2009 at the Agronomy Field Laboratory, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh to examine the effect of maximizing profitability from off-season jute seed crop of both the Olitorius and Capsularis species. There were several treatment combinations of mixed cropping with seeding ratio of the tall and dwarf crops, row-rations for intercropping and paired row system and a number of arrangements of the crops in the raised bed system. The results in Experiment 1 revealed that the paired row intercropping (10 cm soybean-15 cm soybean-30 cm jute-20 cm jute-15 cm soybean-15 cm soybean-30 cm jute-15 cm soybean-10 cm soybean i.e. 6 soybean rows and 4 jute rows take 180 cm out of the allotted 30cm&times;6=180cm) produced the highest capsularis jute seed equivalent yield (615.05 kg/ha) amongst the treatments. In experiment 2 where 14 mixed and inter-cropping treatments were trialed, it was noted that paired row intercropping emerged as the best treatment producing the highest Olitorius jute seed equivalent yield (1610.6 kg/ha) and here mungbean as a shade tolerant crop showed a good yield performance. The results of experiment 3 involving 10 treatments revealed that paired row intercropping produced the highest equivalent yield of 1437.38 kg/ha of Capsularis jute seed. Here, sweet potato was cultivated as shade tolerant crop species but its tuber yield production was not high in the intercropping system. The experiment 4 comprising 10 treatments of mixed and intercrops with capsularis jute seed showed that paired row intercropping produced the highest yield of 915.37 kg/ha jute seed equivalent yield and this treatment was the best among all the treatments under trial. However, cabbage as a shade tolerant crop did not perform well in this combination. Experiment 5 involving 13 treatments in year II revealed that paired row intercropping system was the best treatment on the basis of Capsularis jute seed equivalent yield (1406.17 kg/ha). Mungbean as a legume crop can easily sustain with jute as dwarf crop and its yield performance was higher than sweet potato. Crop combination of Capsularis jute and sweet potato was not profitable, because when sweet potato was cultivated as dwarf crop within Capsularis jute, the rate of tuber formation along with its yield was very low. In experiment 6 where 13 mixed and inter-cropping treatments were trialed, it was observed that paired row intercropping emerged as  the best treatment producing the highest Olitorius jute seed equivalent yield (1577.18 kg/ha) and here mungbean as a dwarf crop showed a good yield performance. Therefore, on the basis of the results of all the experiments, it may be concluded that the paired row intercropping system of intercropping (10cm dwarf crop-15cm dwarf crop-30 cm jute-20 cm jute-15 cm dwarf crop-15 cm dwarf crop-30 cm jute-20 cm jute-15 cm dwarf crop-10 cm dwarf crop i.e. 6 dwarf crop rows and 4 jute rows take 180 cm out of the allotted 30 cm &times; 6 = 180 cm) is the best for off-season jute seed production. This system is more profitable than the sole jute seed cropping. As a dwarf crop, mungbean is more sustainable and profitable crop than sweet potato for intercropping/mixed cropping with Olitorius jute. Olitorius jute is more profitable than Capsularis jute for off-season seed production.', 'Off-season Jute Seed, Intercropping, Mixed cropping, shade tolerant crop', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Maximum profitability from intercropping or mixed cropping', 'Jute seed', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
