(3902, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agronomy', 'Project', 'Effect of poultry manure, prilled urea and urea supergranules on the growth, yield and quality of transplant aman and boro rice', 'Agronomy field laboratory, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', 'To study the effect of urea supergranules, poultry manure and spacing of transplanting on the yield of boro rice cv. BRRI dhan28', '', 'An experiment was carried out at the Agronomy Field Laboratory, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh, during the period from December 2008 to May 2009 to study the effect of urea supergranules, poultry manure and spacing of transplanting on the yield of boro rice cv. BRRI dhan28. The experimental treatments comprised ten fertilizer doses viz. (i) T1 = control (No Urea supergranules and poultry manure), (ii) T2 = 1.8g USG per 4 hill, (iii) T3 = 2.7g USG per 4 hill, (iv) T4 = PM at 5 t ha-1, (v) T5 = PM 7.5 t ha-1, (vi) T6 = 1.8g USG per 4 hill + PM 5 t ha-1, (vii) T7 = 2.7g USG per 4 hill + PM 7.5 t ha-1, (viii) T8 = 1.8g USG per 4 hill + PM at 2.5 t ha-1, (ix) T9 = 2.7g USG per 4 hill + PM 3.75 t ha-1 and (x) T10 = Recommended dose of prilled urea (240 kg ha-1) and two spacings viz. (i) S1 = 25 cm &times; 15 cm and (ii) S2 = 25 cm &times; 20 cm. The experiment was conducted in a randomized complete block design with three replications. Urea supergranules and poultry manure showed significant effect on all the yield contributing characters and yield except panicle length, weight of 1000 grains and harvest index. Results revealed that the highest grain yield (6.16 t ha-1) was obtained from T9 (2.7g USG per 4 hill + PM 3.75 t ha-1) and the lowest grain yield (3.89 t ha-1) was obtained from T1 (Control (No urea supergranules and poultry manure). All the yield contributing characters and yield were significantly affected by spacing except the number of non- effective tillers hill-1 and harvest index. Higher grain yield (5.19 t ha-1) was obtained from S1 (25 cm &times; 15 cm) and lower grain yield (5 t ha-1) was obtained from S2 (25 cm &times; 20 cm). Interaction of Urea supergranules, poultry manure and spacing of transplanting showed significant effect on all the yield contributing characters and yield except plant height, number of total tillers hill-1, panicle length, total number of grains panicle-1, weight of 1000 grains and harvest index. The highest grain yield (6.28 t ha-1) was obtained from T9 &times;S1 (2.7g USG per 4 hill + PM at 3.75 t ha-1) with the spacing of 25 cm &times; 15 cm and the lowest grain yield (3.59 t ha-1) was obtained from T1&times; S2 (control (No Urea supergranules and poultry manure) with the spacing of 25 cm &times; 20 cm. BRRI dhan28 in the treatment T9 &times;S1 (2.7g USG per 4 hill + PM at 3.75 t ha-1  with the spacing 25 cm &times; 15 cm was found to be most promising practice in boro rice cultivation. Treatment T9&times;S2 with the spacing of 25 cm &times; 20 cm and T10 &times;S1 exhibited similar behavior as that of T9&times;S1. Farmers, therefore, can choose any one of these three practices based on profitability.', 'Poultry manure, prilled urea, Urea supergranules, aman and boro rice', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fertilizer management on crop production', 'Aman and Boro Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3903, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery', 'Project', 'A manually operated rice  seedling transplanter', 'Department of Farm Power and Machinery of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Self-propelled rice transplanter mode in Korea and Japan are costly in one hand and highly sophisticated on the other hand. Furthermore, seedlings have to be grown on small tray that is contrary to seedling growing and handling culture in Bangladesh. Such technology cannot be suitable in Bangladesh as the farmers are very conservative and reluctant to change traditional attitude. On the other hand farmers are demanding a machine to replace the manual rice transplanting activities because of drudgery. Therefore, an attempt was made to design and construct a manually operated mechanical device suitable for transplantation of paddy seedlings. A push type mechanical rice seedlings transplanter were designed and constructed in the workshop of the Department of Farm Power and Machinery of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh. It was constructed with constructed with two skidders, one star wheel, two seedling conveyor belt and its associated delivery tray. Seedling could be fed manually on the conveyor belt by an operator while pulling the device forward. A crank mechanism linked with star wheel could push the seedling from the bottom of the seedling delivery tray into the soil. An optional tray attachment could hold bunch of seedlings on the handle of the transplanter. The design of the machine were done in such a way the existing culture of seedling production and handling method were not disturbed. This project was proposed for two years for successful completion. It was approved initially for one year and the proposed work completed exactly on schedule. Within year two purpose have been achieved i.e. a manually operated rice seedling transplanter has been designed and fabricated. The project needed one more year to test the machine in the laboratory as well as in the field. In split of very good progress  of the work, the project could not be completed because of lack of support for remaining portion of activities in the 2nd year. ', 'Rice, Seedling Transplanter', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Seedling Transplanter', 'Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3904, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Arsenic shoot-grain relationships in boro rice varieties grown at arsenic contaminated sites of Sonargaon and Faridpur.', 'Sonargaon and Faridpur areas', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The concentration of arsenic (As) in rice grains has been identified as a risk to human health. The high proportion of inorganic species of As is of particular concern as it is a non- threshold, class 1 human carcinogen. In this study grain arsenic was measured in 76 boro rice cultivars consisting of Bangladesh landraces, local improved (BRRI) cultivars, and parents of permanent mapping populations grown in two field sites in Bangladesh, Faridpur and Sonargaon. Grain and shoot samples of all rice varieties were analyzed for total as well as for different forms of As, P and Si to establish the relationship with arsenic content in rice cultivars. No correlations were observed between shoot and grain speciation, with the inorganic form comprising 93.0-97% of As in the shoot and 63.0-83.7% in the grains. The percentage of dimelthylarsinic acid was between 1.4 and 6.6 in the shoot and 16.1 and 37.0% in the grains. A positive correlation was observed between shoot As and shoot Si, however, no correlation was observed between shoot Si and grain As. The strong negative correlation between shoot P and grain As indicate that As utilizes the P transport mechanisms in rice for transport into the grain, that is, P is out compeling As. The concentration of P in the cultivars during the vegetative stage had less than a 2-fold range, whereas at harvest the range was greater than 6-fold. This suggests that there is a large variation between the cultivars in P remobilization from the shoots to the grain. These results suggest that the translocation of As into the grain from the shoots is potentially using P rather than Si transport mechanisms. The translocation of inorganic As and DMA from the shoot to the grain differs considerably among the rice cultivars. ', 'Arsenic, Boro Rice, Arsenic contaminated, Sonargaon, Faridpur', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Arsenic contamination', 'Boro Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3905, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Effect of poultry manure, soil and foliar application of nitrogen on yield performance and nitrogen recovery of boro rice (cv. Minikit)', 'BAU research farm, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'A study was conducted at the soil science field laboratory of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during boro season of 2009 with a view to evaluating yield performance and nitrogen recovery of Minikit rice grown with foliar spray of urea, soil applied urea and poultry manure. The experiment was laid out in a randomized complete block design with three replications. There were nine treatment combinations as: T1 = (control), T2 = (PM), T3 = (PM + 1.25% urea spray), T4 = (PM + 2.5% urea solution spray), T5 = (PM+ 30 kg N ha-1 + 1.25% urea solution spray), T6 = (PM + 60 kg N ha-1 + 1.25% urea solution spray), T7 = (30 kg N ha-1 + 1.25% urea solution sparay, T8 = (60 kg N ha-1 + 1.25% urea solution spray) and T9 = (90 kg N ha-1). Poultry manure was applied @ 5 t ha-1. Foliar application of urea was done for eight times during the crop growth starting at 10 days after transplantation at seven days interval, the volume of urea solution in each spray was 400 L ha-1. The amount of N added in different treatments through foliar, soil applied urea and poultry manure were 0, 80, 98, 116, 128, 158, 48, 78 and 90 kg ha-1 in T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, and T9 treatments, respectively. The application of 5 t ha-1 resulted in an increase of 0.42 t ha-1 yield of rice. The application of 1.25 and 2.50% urea solution to rice in presence of poultry manure showed the yield increase of 0.42 and 0.53 t ha-1, respectively. The highest grain yield of 5.04 t ha-1 was recorded in T6 and was statistically identical to T3, T4, and T7 treatments in recording the grain yield. Foliar application of urea increased the N recovery percentage by rice. Overall results from the two experiments at BAU farm showed that foliar application of urea fertilizer can increase the yield of rice but such increase is not sufficient enough to get a satisfactory yield of rice.  ', 'poultry manure, foliar application, nitrogen recovery, urea solution spray', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Fertilizer management for crop production', 'Boro Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3906, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Comparative study on the effects of Bradyrhizobium inoculant and urea-N on the growth and yield of Soybean: Improvement, Testing and Production of Bacterial fertilizers.', 'BAU Farm, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '30-04-2009', '01-01-2009', '30-04-2009', 'to study the comparative effectiveness of Rhizobium inoculants and urea-N on the growth and yield of soybean.', '', 'A field experiment was conducted in the Soil Science Field Laboratory of Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during the period from January to April, 2009 to study the comparative effectiveness of Rhizobium inoculants and urea-N on the growth and yield of soybean. The experiment was laid out in the randomized complete block design having 3 replications. There were 7 treatments such as T0 = control, T1 = BAU-107, T2 = BAU-151, T3 = TAL-102, T4 = Mixed culture, T5 = Urea-N and T6 = Mixed culture + Mg. The inoculants used in the experiment were previously collected, selected and preserved in the Department of Soil Science, BAU, Mymensingh. There were 21 unit plots for the experiment. Phosphorus @ 10 kg ha-1 from TSP, potassium @ 25 kg ha-1 from muriate of potash and sulphur @ 10 kg ha-1 from gypsum were applied as basal dose before sowing the seeds. Nitrogen was applied @ 10 kg ha-1 from urea to the treatment T5. Half dose of urea was applied before sowing seeds and rest half was applied in two equal splits at 20 and 40 days after sowing. Magnesium @ 10 kg ha-1 was applied from MgO in the experiment T6 before sowing the seeds. Data were collected at 45 and 80 days after sowing. Soybean yield and yield contributing characters were recorded at maturity. Inoculation with Rhizobium strains significantly increased the nodule number, nodule dry weight, root weight, shoot weight, N content and N uptake of soybean at all observations over uninoculated control. The performance of all the inoculants were promising in growing soybean crop in the Bangladesh Agricultural University Farm. All the inoculants performed better as compared to urea-N application @ 10 kg ha-1 and the strain TAL 102 was found as the best. Application of Mg along with the inoculants was found beneficial and increased the biomass production, nodulation and protein content of soybean. ', 'Rhizobium, Soybean, Urea-N', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Impact of bio-fertilizer and inorganic fertilizer', 'Soybean', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3907, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Leaching loss of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium and sulphur in the Old Brahmaputra Floodplain soils.', 'Department of Soil Science, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-02-2009', '30-06-2009', '01-02-2009', '30-06-2009', 'to study the leaching loss of N, P, K and S in the Old Brahmaputra Floodplain soils', '', 'Four pot experiments were carried out in the net house of the Department of Soil Science, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during February to June (Boro season) of 2009 to study the leaching loss of N, P, K and S in the Old Brahmaputra Floodplain soils. The soil having pH 6.8, total N 0.15, available P 12.8 ppm, exchangeable K 0.11 me/100g soil 0.07me/100g soil and available S 11.5 ppm and the sandy loam soil having pH 6.6, total N 0.08%, available P 7.00 ppm, exchangeable K 0.07me/100g soil and available S 7.50 ppm were used in the experiment. There were six treatments such as T0 (control), T1 (N120 P25 K60 S20, recommended dose), T2 (N180 P37 K90 S30 of recommended dose), T3 (75% of T1 from fertilizer and 25% N from cowdung), T4 (as T1 but N from goote urea) and T5 (as T1 but N applied as foliar spray). The nutrients P, K and S were applied as basal dose in the pots while urea was applied in three equal splits except T4 and T5. One goote urea pot-1 was placed after 7 days of transplanting in T4. In T5, urea was applied as foliar spray at 10 days interval. Leachates from individual pots were collected at 15 days intervals to determine the amount of loss of NPKS. In silt soil, the total leaching loss of N, P, K and S due to different treatments during the growing season under saturated condition ranged from 7.11 to 33.09, 0.061 to 0.205, 2.70 to 4.61 and 3.98 to 23.37 kg/ha while the values under alternate wetting and drying condition ranged from 15.51 to 39.42, 0.076 to 0.192, 1.90 to 3.00 and 1.51 to 5.60 kg/ha, respectively. The leaching loss of N, P, K and S in sandy loam soil due to different treatments under saturated condition ranged from 22.23 to 91.21, 0.281 to 1.947, 34.68 to 42.01 and 6.89 to 43.80 kg/ha and  the values under alternate wetting and drying condition ranged from 16.00 to 90.21, 0.072 to 0.293, 9.60 to 11.20 and 3.75 to 17.81 kg/ha respectively. Leaching loss of N, P, K and S varied with soil type, moisture level and rate of fertilizer application over time. The loss of nutrients increases with the increase of fertilizer application. The integrated use of fertilizers reduced nutrient leaching loss. The use of goote urea reduced the leaching loss of nitrogen. ', 'Leaching loss, nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, sulphur, Old Brahmaputra Floodplain', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Estimation leaching loss of fertilizer', 'N, P, K and S', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3908, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Soil Science', 'Project', 'Selection of wheat varieties for tolerance to boron deficiency', 'Department of Soil Science, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', 'to select wheat varieties can tolerant Boron deficiency.', '', 'Boron deficiency is a major cause of low yield of wheat in Bangladesh. This element deficiency causes grain sterility in wheat. Boron deficiency can be overcome by two ways: one is application of boron fertilizer and other is use of wheat varieties tolerant to boron deficiency. Considering grain set and grain yield response as an indicator of B efficiency or inefficiency, the commonly grown Bangladeshi wheat varieties such as Sourav and Prodip, as observed in the previous two years, appeared as moderately B efficient varieties (B deficiency tolerant) and Shatabdi as B inefficient (B deficiency sensitive). Similarly Cranbrook (Australian variety) and Bobwhite (Mexican variety) were found to be moderately B efficient and Condor and Halberd (both Australian varieties) be B inefficient wheat varieties. The grain yield showed a significant positive correlation with the number of grains spike-1 indicating that boron supplement had a positive influence on grain set. Boron application also positively impacted physiological parameters, viz. chlorophyll a &amp; b and sugar contents. There was no significant interaction of Boron &times; sowing date in wheat indicating that all three factors functioned independently. The 4th week of November, as recorded in the previous year too, was found to be the best sowing time for wheat cultivation in Mymemsingh area. This finding has special implication that sowing of wheat in this country is often delayed as because this crop is grown after transplant aman rice harvest. The hydrophonics isotope experiment (conducted at UC, Davis, USA) showed that plant (wheat) root B concentration increased with time up to 3 hours and cell sap B concentration up to 6 hours and then declined. The 10 day old plants did not show positive response to B addition since boron supply from seed reserve and deionized water was adequate to support young plants.   ', 'Wheat, Boron, boron deficiency', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Crop Production', 'Wheat', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3909, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Irrigation and Water Management', 'Program', 'Utilization and management of sugar mills effluent water for irrigatin purposes to increase crop production.', '', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Well planned use of sugar mills effluent (hereafter called wastewater) may not only conserve valuable water resource and alleviate surface water pollution problems, but also take advantage of tis nutrient c9ontents. In order to judge suitability of this wastewater for irrigation, major properties of wastewater of North Bengal Sugar Mill ((NBSM) and its impact on some important soil properties were evaluated by laboratory experiments. The properties of three wastewater samples from different locations of the disposal canal and one freshwater sample from a hand tube well at the NBSM complex were determined. The major physical, chemical and hydraulic properties, and solute-transport parameters through disturbed and undisturbed samples of wastewater-affected and wastewater-unaffected soils were determined. The electrical conductivity (EC) and pH of wastewater varied from 0.78 to 1.05 dS/m and 606 to 9.95, respectively. The wastewater was rich in terms of nitrogen (15.8-24.7 mg/I) and phosphorus (5.2-6.0 mg/I) concentrations were higher in wastewater than in freshwater. Biological oxygen demand (BOD) and chemical oxygen demand (COD) of the wastewater ranged from 183 to 309 mg/I and 196 to 685 mg/L, respectively. Temperature of wastewater at the head end of the disposal canal was 39.5&deg;C. The EC, BOD, COD, temperature and manganese contents of wastewater exceeded the threshold values for irrigation and, therefore, the wastewater was not suitable for irrigation without treatment. Wastewater raised soil EC but reduce its pH. It improved soil fertility by increasing phosphorous, potassium, sulphur and organic matter. Wastewater also caused an increase in porosity and decrease in bulk density. Soil-water content at field capacity and saturated hydraulic conductivity increased due to the effect of wastewater. Velocity of pore-water in wastewater-affected soil decreased from 0.96 to 0.45 cm/h. Consequently, the mean travel time of an inert solute (CaC12) increased from 31.45 to 43.51 in indicating that wastewater-affected soil hindered movement of chemical pollutants through it.    ', 'Sugar, Sugar Mills, Irrigation, Increase production, Water.', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Production', 'Sugarcane', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3910, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Horticulture', 'Project', 'DNA finger printing and conservation of the germplasm of important vegetables and fruits of Bangladesh', 'Department of Horticulture, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Two experiments were conducted along with conservation of more than 2000 germplasm of different vegetables and fruits in the field and laboratory. In experiment-1, DNA finger printing of 35 mango (Mangifere indica L.) germplasm was carried out using 6 SSR primers and a total of 50 alletes were detected. The number of alleles per locus ranged from 5 to 12, with an average of 8.3. Polymorphism information content value ranged from 0.5999 (primer MICA231-1) to 0.8531 (primer MITG436-1) and average was 0.7670. The gene diversity ranged from 0.6449-0.8669 and average diversity was 0.6706. Positive correlations were found between gene diversity, number of allele and the allele size range. All the cluster analysis (NJ tree, UPGMA &amp; PCO) used in the study revealed wide variation among 35 mango germplasm. The UPGMA dendrogram, based on genetic distance segregrated 35 mango germplasm into 2 main clusters. The values of pair wise comparisons of Neis (1972) genetic distance (D) between varieties ranged from 0.2643 to 1,0000. Comparatively higher genetic distance (1,000) was observed between a numbers of germplasm pair. Among them, Fazli vs Langra, Anurata vs Gopalbhog, Aruna vs Golapbash, Baromashi vs Horidoshi, Beguntoli vs Meghnath, Benison vs Golpita, Carabao vs Kalua, Ratna vs Amrapali, Gopalbhog vs Kathalibhog, Gutu vs Sulkhur, Subornalekha vs Meghnath and Hybrid 13 vs Surma Fazli are important. The lowest genetic distance (0.2643) was found in Beguntoli vs Subornarekha. UPGMA cluster analysis showed that all 35 mango germplasm could be easily distinguished based on the information generated by the 6 SSR markers except Baromashi and Subornarekha. In experiment-2, field performance and variability of 12 selected germplasm of brinjal (Solanum melongena L.) using morphological traits and DNA finger printing were studied. All characters under study showed significant variations among the germplasm for different yield and yield attributes. The highest number of fruits per plant was recorded in SM29 (60.67). The highest average weight of individual fruit was recorded in SM11 (164.17 g) and the lowest individual fruit weight was observed in SM35 (17.83 g). DNA finger printing was conducted using RAPD markers. Amplification with 5 decamer primers produced 54 RAPD markers of which 49 (89.56%) were polymorphic and 5 (10.44%) were monomorphic. The highest genetic distance (0.9445) and the lowest genetic similarity (0.3889) were observed between SM59 vs SM11. The lowest genetic distance (0.1388) was observed between SM22 vs SM29. UPGMA dendogram based on genetic distance segregrated 12 brinjal germplasm into five clusters. The result of the present study revealed that wide variation exist among the mango and brinjal germplasm and SSR and RAPD markers can be for DNA finger printing of mango and brinjal germplasm, respectively for DNA finger printing of these important fruit and vegetable crops.   ', 'DNA, finger printing, germplasm, vegetables, Fruits', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Vegetables and Fruits', 'Mango and brinjal', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3911, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics', '', 'Morphological variation in three populations of Glossogobius giuris (Hamilton, 1822) Perciformes: Gobiidae)', 'Mymensingh, Mithamoin haor of Knhisoreganj and estuary of Tetulia river of Barisal.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Landmark-based morphometric and meristic analysis of pond, haor and estuary populations of Glossogobius giuris (Hamilton, 1822) (Perciformes: Gobiidae) were studied to find out variations among the three stocks. Samples were collected from three different regions such as pond of Mymensingh, Mithamoin haor of Knhisoreganj and estuary of Tetulia river of Barisal. Significant difference ((*P,0.01) were observed in 13 general morphometric and 23 size adjusted landmark-based morphometric measurements among three stocks. Among three stocks. Among the 11 meristic counts the first dorsal fin rays (D1FR), transverse scale above lateral line (TSALL), branchiostegal rays and number of vertebrae were same among fishes from these stocks. In case of pectoral fin rays (PcFR) and transverse scale on lateral line (TSOLL) haor stock was significantly higher than other stocks. In discriminant space, pond stock was isolated from other two stocks. On the other hand, haor and estuary stocks showed very close relationship. \r\n\r\nA dendrogram based on the hierarchial cluster analysis using size adjusted general morphometric and landmark measurements for G. giuris formed two main clusters- pond stock in one cluster and other two stocks (haor and estuary) remained in another cluster. It indicates that pond stock was separated. The 2nd cluster of dendrogram explained that haor and estuary stocks had very close relationship.\r\n\r\nThis result that pond stock of Mymensingh was morphologically dissimilar to other stocks of G. giuris and haor stock of Kishoreganj and estuary stock of Barisal showed very close relationship. This resulted that these three populations were morphologically separated from each other.\r\n', 'Fishes, Genetics, Biology, Morphological variation', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Morphological Variation', 'Fishes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3912, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Horticulture', 'Project', 'Studies of postharvest management of mango and banana to reduce loss extend shelf life and maintain quality', 'Department of Horticulture, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'A number of experiments were conducted at the laboratories of the Departments of Horticulture, Plant Pathology and Biochemistry, Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh. The first experiment attempted to screen commercially important banana varieties of Bangladesh in relation to their nutritional composition, storage behavior and levels of natural tolerance to postharvest diseases. Mature green bananas of 10 different varieties, namely Agniswas, Champa, Safa, Tulapait, Baisha, Jat, Gera Sundari, Shabri, Amritasagar and Mehersagar were the experimental materials. The single factor experiment was laid out in a completely randomized design with three replications. Among the physio chemical parameter studied, color, firmness, total weight loss, pulp to peel ratio, percent moisture content, total sugar content, total soluble solids, titratable acidity, disease incidence and disease severity increased, whereas percent dry matter content, vitamin C and pH of banana pulp decreased with the progress of storage duration. At the 16th day of storage the highest levels of weight loss (44.91%), disease severity (100%) and disease incidence (100%) were observed in variety Jat, whereas the lowest rate in physiological weight loss (23.94%) and disease severity (2.07%) were observed in variety Safa and the latter variety also had the longest shelf life (17.9 days) when held at ambient condition for ripening. Another experiment was carried out to evaluate the effects of different non-chemical treatments to reduce postharvest loss and prolong shelf life of babnana. Banana fruits of variety Shabri at commercial maturity were used as experimental materials. The postharvest treatments were control, hot water treatment at 500C for 5 minutes, pre-cooling at 5 and 100C for 30 minutes, banana storage at low temperature (15 and 200C) and bananas dipped in neem extracts (1:1 and 1:2). The single factor experiment was laid out in completely randomized design with three replications. Low temperature storage at 15 and 200C extended shelf lives of bananas by 9 and 8 days, respectively over control fruits. The present study also screened the commercial mango varieties of Bangladesh in relation to nutritional composition, storage behavior and levels of natural tolerance to postharvest diseases. Results showed that the variety Bombai had the highest TSS content both at mature hard and eating ripe conditions. Vitamin C contents varied significantly among the varieties and ranged from 32-118 mg/100 g at mature green stage to 24-85 mg/100 g at eating ripe stage. The variety Langra contained the highest amount of vitamin C. In all the banana varieties examined, vitamin C content sharply declined with the duration of storage. The levels of disease severity varied significantly among the varieties. The severity level gradually increased with the progress of storage duration. It was found that the mango variety Bombai was quite susceptible to postharvest rots followed by Gopalbhog. In contrast, the variety Langra was relatively tolerant followed by Fazli. In relation to shelf life, the variety Fazli had the longest shelf life (14 days), whereas the variety Bombai had the shortest shelf life (9 days). The fourth experiment evaluated the effects of low temperature and non-chemical postharvest treatments to extend shelf life and maintain quality of mango fruits of variety Langra. The experiment consisted of two factors, namely storage temperature (ambient condition and 130C) and postharvest treatments (control, fruits dipped in neem extract, fruits wrapped in plastic film and fruits dipped in hot water at 500C for 5 minutes). The factorial experiment was laid out in completely randomized design with 3 replications. The combined effects of temperature and postharvest treatments were significant to influence disease severity of mango fruits during storage and ripening. At the 6th day of storage, no diseases symptoms were found in those fruits held at 130C, whereas the fruits stored at ambient condition had different levels of diseases. Neem extracts was found to be promising in reducing the levels of disease severity as compared to other treatments. At the 12th day of storage, the fruits treated with neem extract and held at 130C had only 1% disease severity. By contrast, the untreated fruits held at ambient condition had 86.33% disease severity. This result was possibly due to the suppressed fungal growth at low temperature and the inhibitory effects of the active ingredient of neem extract, a recognized botanical pesticide. The shelf lives of mango fruits held at ambient condition and 130C were 7.5 and 15.1 days, respectively and which results suggested that low temperature doubled the storage of life of mango. The longest shelf life (16.6 days) was found in fruits treated with hot water and held at 130C (15.6 days) followed wrapping fruits with plastic film and storing at the same temperature (14.5 days).   ', 'Postharvest management, Mango, Banana, Shelf life, Quality', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Postharvest management of fruits', 'Mango and Banana', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.');
