(3913, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Horticulture', 'Project', 'Reduction of postharvest spoilage and extension of shelf life of Litchi (Litchi chinensis Sonn.) varieties of Bangladesh.', 'Department of Horticulture and farm, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Litchi (Litchi chinensis Sonn.) is tropical and subtropical fruit of high commercial value throughout the world for its white translucent aril, attractive red color and high nutritive value. Litchi is a popular but expensive fruit item of Bangladesh. Presently, 44000 metric tones of litchi are produced from 1619 hectares of land with an average yield of 4.5 metric tones/hectare (BBS, 2008). Huge postharvest loss (30-50%, Wills et al. 2004) occurs for most tropical fruits due mainly to the postharvest physiological changes and decay (mainly due to infections caused by Aspergillus, Penicillium, Rhizopus, Colletotrichum and Botryodiplodia). So, scientists believe that increased return to litchi growers might come from conservation after harvest. In addition, the per capita fruit consumption is less (38 g/day) compared to the minimum requirement (100 g/day). The economic storage life of litchi could be extended dramatically if the rates of the postharvest physiological changes were slowed down, microbial decay eliminated, pericarp browning due to rapid desiccation of water was reduced and faulty postharvest handling techniques addressed. In Bangladesh, research works on the reduction of huge postharvest spoilage of litchi are unnoticeable despite its great importance. A number of litchi varieties (China-3, Bombay, Mongolbaria, Mojaffarpuri, Bedana, BARI Litchi-1, BARI Litchi-2 and BARI Litchi-3) are grown in Bangladesh. However, reports regarding the levels of tolerance of these varieties to postharvest decay and pericarp browning are absent, and therefore, a detailed investigation on the levels of varietal tolerance is of utmost importance. Postharvest pericarp browning is the most serious and unique problem of litchi during storage and ripening. After harvest, litchi fruits become brown within 2-3 days which ultimately render the fruits unmarketable. Presently, the most critical area of examination is how to reduce the postharvest losses of litchi possibly by growing relatively tolerant varieties in relation to microbial decay and pericarp browning, by manipulating normal physiological behavior, and by keeping postharvest disease levels under control. In this connection, many physical (high temperatures, controlled humidity, ionizing radiation, heat treatment, modified atmosphere and controlled atmosphere) and chemical (synthetic fungicide and growth regulators) treatments were tested to control postharvest wastages of fruits. Chemical control is the most widely used practice throughout the world for many tropical fruits. However, consumers are reluctant to buy chemically treated fruits due to widespread public concern about the hazardous impacts of pesticide residues. Therefore, exploring natural alternatives to chemicals also merit investigation. This is an on-going project. However, some important results are summarized here. The present study mainly focuses on reduction of pericarp browning and extension shelf life of litchi. Even though the data have not been analyzed completely, but the results of the experiments seem very useful, especially in minimizing browning severity, the most serious postharvest problem of litchi. Preliminary results suggest that the low cost and natural techniques like plastic box and plastic bag with or without litchi leaves would be useful in reducing browning and extending shelf life of litchi. The longest shelf life was obtained in those fruits that were held in plastic box and plastic bag with litchi leaves and stored at 100C (9 days). By contrast, the unwrapped fruits when held at ambient conditions had shelf life of only 1 day. Vitamin C content sharply declined with the progress of storage duration. It declined from 20-33 mg/100 g (day 1) to 5-9 mg/100 g (day 4).    ', 'Postharvest spoilage, Litchi, Shelf life', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Reduction postharvest loss of fruits', 'Litchi', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3914, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics', '', 'Livelihood improvement of prawn farmers, nurserers and hatchery operators of Noakhali region under DANIDA project ensuring seed quality', 'Upakul Freshwater Prawn Hatchery, Sonapur, Noakhali.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2010', '30-06-2011', '01-07-2010', '30-06-20101', '', '', 'To develop a protocol for the production of quality brood stocks of freshwater prawn in captivity, experiment was carried out since September 2009 with financial support of DANIDA in Noakhali. Several experiments were conducted during 2010-11 fiscal year to assess the performance of F1 PL of three broodstocks-i) Halda, ii) own developed and iii) gher origin were reared for two months in six earthen ponds (15 decimal each) at Subarnachar, Noakhali through supplemental feeding (CP Company). F1 juveniles of three broodstocks were stocked at the rate of 40 individuals per decimal in six earthen ponds (15 decimal each). They were reared for 9 months with own formulated feed (protein 32%). F1 berried females of each source were bread in the Upakul Freshwater Prawn Hatchery, Sonapur, Noakhali. Fecundity, hatching rate and PL conversion rate of each source of F1 broods were determined. Conversion rate of F1 PL to juveniles of Halda origin (64.94%) and own reared origin (60.88%) were significantly (P&lt;0.05) higher than those of gher origin (35.27%)). F1 brood stocks of won developed origin showed highest hatching rate (53.59%) and PL conversion rate (42%). \r\nGenetic variation of three different broodstocks and their F1 progenies was studied with muscle tissues through starch gel electrophoresis using seven enzymes (LDH, MDH, PGM, GPI, G#PDH, IDH and EST) in CA 6.1 buffer system. Nine presumptive loci were encoded and among them four loci (Mdh-1*, Est-1*, G3pdh* and Idh-1*) were found to be polymorphic (P95). The mean proportion of polymorphic loci were 44.44%, 55.56%, 55.56%, 22.22%, 33.33% and 22.22% in Halda, own developed and gher brood stocks and their progenies respectively. Highest genetic variability was observed in won developed broods. Among the brood stocks, the lowest pair-wise population differentiation (Fst) (0.03 and highest gene flow (Nm) (9.13) were found in Halda and own developed broodstocks indicating close relationship among them as both were originated from river. Based on Neis (1972) UPGMA dendrogram, six populations were divided into two major clusters separated from earch other by the highest genetic distance of D = 0.08. Cluster-1 consisted of Halda and own developed broodstocks and F1 progeny of own developed broods while cluster-2 contained gher broodstocks and F1 progeny of Halda and own developed broods. As both Halda and own developed broodstocks originated from river, genetic distance between these two populations was low (D=0.01) compared to genetic distance between gher and either of Halda (D=0.04) or own developed broodstocks (D=0.07). \r\n', 'Prawn production, Fish, Hatchery, Prawn farmers', 'DANIDA', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Prawn production', 'Fishes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3915, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics', '', 'Refinement of cryopreservation techniques and setting up cryogenic bank of two indigenous catfishes, Heteropneustes fossilis and Clarias batrachus for quality seed production', 'Department of Fisheries Biology and Genetics, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Experiments were conducted to develop and standardize the protocols for cryopreservation of sperm of catfish, Heteropneustes fossilis and Clarias batrachus and to establish cryogenic gene bank. The activation of sperm of H. fossilis and C. batrachus suspended in four extenders such as Alsevers solution, egg-yolk citrate, urea egg-yolk and Ginzburg fish ringer was tested using different concentration of NaCI solution and the motility of Sperm decreased as the NaCI concentration increased and was completely inhibited at 1% NaCI solution. Toxicity of cryoprotectant to sperm was investigated using 5, 10 15 and 20% cryprotectant (DMSO, methanol and ethanol) with the incubation time of 5 to 45 min. sperm motility decreased with the increase of the cryprotectant concentration (5, 10, 15 and 20%) and incubation time (5-45) min). Motility of sperm was &gt;60% at 5 and 10% of cryoprotectants at 10 min incubation and above 40% at 15% concentration. Alsevers solution, egg-yolk citrate, ufrea-egg-yolk and Ginzburg fish ringer and three cryropectants, DMSO, methanol and ethanol were used to preserve sperm. Alsevers solution with 10% DMSO showed best performance producing post-thaw motility of 86.25 &plusmn;2.04% for H. fossilis and 80 &plusmn; 2.18% for C. batrachus. Urea egg-yolk and eg-yolk citrate with 10% DMSO produced 64.29  &plusmn; 1.71% and  57.86  &plusmn; 2.4% post-thaw motility for C. batrachus respectively. For H. fossilis egg-yolk cigtrate produced 82.50  &plusmn; 2.04% post-thaw motility while 80  &plusmn; 3.22% post-thaw motility as obtained from Ginzburg fish ringer. Sperm preserved with alsevers solution plus DMSO produced best hatching that was 37.97  &plusmn; 2.39% for H. fossilis and 50.29  &plusmn; 1.22% for C batrachus. Alsevers solution with 10% methanol produced satisfactory results (32.65 &plusmn; 2.70% and 41.54  &plusmn; 5.54% hatching for H. fossilis and C. batrachus respectively). In cryogenic storage the motility of sperm gradually reduced with the progress of storage time and 75% and 82% motility reduction were recorded from Alsever solution plus DMSO and Alsevers solution plus methanol for H. fossilis, and those of 70% and 75% for C. batrachus respectively. The efficacy of cryogenic stored sperm for fertilization was tested and satisfactory level of fertilization and hatching were obtained from one month and two month-old cryopreserved sperm. ', 'Fish, Seed producgtion, Cat fish', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Seed Production', 'Seed; Trees', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3916, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of pathology', 'Project', 'Assessment of seed quality and seed health of TLS of rice from formal, semiformal and informal sectors in Bangladesh.', 'Department of plant pathology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Quality of rice seed is of crying need of the farmers of Bangladesh. In Bangladesh rice seeds are available from farmers, BADC, NGOs and private sectors consisting of formal, semiformal and informal sources. Certified rice seeds are not available as per need of the country. But TLS (Truthfully Labeled Seed) is relatively more available in the market than the certified seed though the quality of TLS is not controlled fully by the SCA. Therefore, the quality of TLS of rice available in the market needs to be studied. Considering the above points, the present study has been designed to investigate the quality of TLS of rice available from different sources in the market. Seed samples of different varieties of TLS of rice were collected from different sources like formal, informal and semiformal sources (BADC, farmer, NGO and Private seed companies). Altogether 94 seed samples were collected from the different seed sectors. Purity, moisture, germination, vigour and seed health tests were carried out in Boro and T. aman season. HYV seeds of BADC and hybrid seeds of different sources were found to have lower moisture content, higher purity percentage, germination and vigour index. Farmers seed was found as of poor quality. Seed health tests was done for all the collected samples. Different seed borne fungi viz. Aspergillus flavus, Alternaria padwickii, Bipolaris oryzae, Curvularia lunata, Fusarium oxysporum, Fusarium moniliforme, Serocladium oryzae, and Penicillium sp. Were recorded. Higher percentage of seed borne infection was found in farmers seed then BADC and hybrid seed samples. Dry inspection test revealed apparently healthy seeds in higher number in BADC hybrid seed samples. The association of bacteria with the seed samples and other seed quality attributes is under investigation.    ', 'Assessment, Seed quality, TLS, Seed health', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Seed quality assessment', 'Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3917, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Plant Pathology', 'Project', 'Status of Tikka disease of groundnut in Bangladesh and effect of BAU-Biofungicide on improving seed quality', 'Department of Plant Pathology, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '', '', 'Groundnut (Arachis hypogaea L) is an annual legume oil crop produced all over the country. Leaf spot or Tikka (Cercospora arachidicola and Cercospora personata) of groundnut is an economically important foliar disease and major yield reducing factor all over Bangladesh. A wide spectrum of survey on the incidence and prevalence of leaf spot or tikka disease of groundnut in major groundnut growing areas in Bangladesh was carried out during 2008-09. This survey was done at farmers field as well as research plots of different research organizations viz. Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI) and Bangladesh Institute of Nuclear Agriculture (BINA) in addition from different regional agricultural research stations of BARI. A total number of 262 germplasms/lines/varieties were evaluated using the grading score (0-9) of the disease. None of the surveyed materials were found free from the disease. The disease incidence and severity were found to vary from location to location, variety to variety and growth stage of plants where leaf damage, disease severity and grading score ranged from 9-80%, 20-90% and 4-9, respectively. The highest leaf damage, disease severity and disease score were recorded from research field of BARI, Hathazari, Chittagong followed by experimental farm, Department of plant pathology, Bangladesh Agricultural University (BAU), Mymensingh, but lowest count was made in research field of Bangladesh Institute of Nuclear Agriculture (BINA), Ishwardi, Pabna where BINA used mutant variety. Considering variety the highest leaf damage, disease severity and disease score were recorded in Dhaka-1 and DG-2 and lowest in BARI chinabadam-7 and BARI chinabadam-8. The diseased leaf samples from different groundnut growing areas of Bangladesh were collected and the disease causal organisms, Cercospora arachidicola and Cercospora personata were isolated, purified and identified. Phyologic race as well as growth character of  Cercospora arachidicola and Cercospora personata were studied. The conidial length and breadth of Cercospora personata were found to range from 19.31-38.80&micro;m and 5.86-10.60 &micro;m, respectively and septation of the conidia ranged from 2-6. The conidial length and breadth of Cercospora arachidicola were found to range from 36.2-168.95&micro;m and 2.59-10.30 &micro;m, respectively having septation 4-12. Effect of different plant extracts (fresh leaves of tomato, marigold, safata, neemleaf, datura, lemon grass, debdaru, bulb of garlic and onion), BAU-biofungicide and Bavistin were evaluated for their effect on vigour and germination of groundnut following tray method, where maximum vigour was recorded by treating seeds with BAU-biofungicide followed by tomato leaf extracts. BAU-biofungicide treatment showed 46.07% higher vigour over the control. 100% germination was obtained by applying BAU-biofungicide followed by tomato leaf extracts as seed treatment which was 20% higher over the control.     ', 'tikka disease, Groundnut, BAU-Biofungicide, Seed quality', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Crop disease management', 'Groundnut', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3918, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'The influence of carbohydrate and organic extract as energy sources in medium on germination and seedlings growth of spathoglottis plicata orchid in vitro.', 'Department of Crop Botany, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-08-2008', '31-05-2009', '01-08-2008', '31-05-2009', 'to investigate the effects of carbohydrate and organic extracts supplemented as energy source in medium on seeds germination and seedlings growth of Spathogiottis plicata orchid in vitro', '', 'An experiment was conducted in Tissue Culture Laboratory of the Department of crop botany BAU from August 2008 to May 2009 to investigate the effects of carbohydrate and organic extracts supplemented as energy source in medium on seeds germination and seedlings growth of Spathogiottis plicata orchid in vitro. The Hyponex medium of 20 ml and 30 ml with pH 5.8 was taken in 100 ml conical flask for seeds germination and seedling growth respectively. The culture was maintained at 250 &plusmn;10C room temperature under 16 hours lighting of 30 &micro; mol m2 S-1 provided by florescent tubes. Among carbohydrates sucrose at 30 g L-1 was the best as energy source for seeds germination and seedling growth in vitro. Organic extracts of corn, potato and tomato were supplemented into Hyponex medium at 25, 50, 100 and 200 ml L-1 with a control where no extract was added. Corn extract (25 ml L-1) supplemented into medium enhanced seed germination percentage and seedling growth significantly in vitro. Potato extract was inhibitory both for seed germination and seedling growth. Tomato extract (25 ml L-1) also supported seeds germination but not seedlings growth.     ', 'Organic extract, germination, seedlings growth, Spathoglottis plicata orchid', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Influence of carbohydrate and organic extract as energy sources in medium on germination and seedling growth', 'Spathoglottis plicata orchid', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3919, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Establishment of disease free taro cultivar development protocol through in vitro regenerated somaclone selection', 'Tissue culture laboratory, Department of Crop Botany, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', 'to establish the disease free plantlet regeneration protocol in taro (Colocasia esculenta L.). Axilary buds meristems from seed corm of cultivar MK029, Maharchandi and Bilashi were used as plant material', '', 'An experiment was carried out in the tissue culture laboratory of Department of Crop Botany during the period July 2008 to June 2009 to establish the disease free plantlet regeneration protocol in taro (Colocasia esculenta L.). Axilary buds meristems from seed corm of cultivar MK029, Maharchandi and Bilashi were used as plant material. The culture condition was maintained at 25&plusmn;10C for 16 hours light provided by florescent tube in a growth room. Half Muraghige and Skoog (HMS) medium supplemented with NAA 2.0 mg L1 and 2.4-D 2.0 mg L-1 wa, the best for direct plantlet production when tip of bud explants remained intact (Without damaging apical meristem), but produced callus under damaged tip. Among the different treatments, the highest callus induction was found in HMS medium supplemented with 2.0 mg L-1 2,4-D + 0.5 mg L-1 NAA. Among cultivars MKO29 was found most suitable for callus induction followed by Maharchandi and Bilashi. Plantlets regeneration from callus and thin section (from in vitro grown mini corm) was enhanced with complex organic extracts of tomato and taro. Multiple shoot initiation from thin section explant and their growth in vitro  was the best on medium supplemented with 2.0 mg L-1 NAA + 2.0 mg L-1 2,4-D. MK029 produced higher number of shoot with highest growth parameters at 2.0 mg L-1 NAA + 2.0 mg L-1 2,4-D. Thus present research established a protocol for in vitro disease free plant regeneration in Bangladeshi Taro suitable for the production of numerous plantlets within a short duration which may substitute corm plantation in farmers level, reduce disease  infestation and will save 10% of seed corm which has long been using as seed corm by the farmers. It also paves the way of salt, drought or stress tolerant plantlet production through callus derived somaclones selection in vitro.     ', 'Taro, Development protocol, Somaclone, Maharchandi, Bilashi', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Vegetable crop production', 'Taro', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3920, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'In vitro regeneration of Taro somaclone for the selection of salt tolerant cultivar', 'Department of Crop Botany, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2009', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2009', 'to select salt tolerant taro cultivar', '', 'An experiment was conducted in the Department of Crop Botany, from January to December of 2009 for in vitro somaclones regeneration in Taro (Colocasia esculenta L.) to select salt tolerant cultivar. Bud explants from seed corm was sterilized with 0.1 g L-1 HgCl2 for 20 minutes and cultured on half strength Murashige and Skoogs Medium (HMS). The culture was maintained at 25&plusmn;10C under 16 h photoperiod of 30 &micro;mol m-2s-1 provided by florescent tubes. The highest callus induction was found in medium supplemented with 2.0 mgL-1 2,4-D + 2.0 mgL-1 BA. Multiple somaclones were developed from callus in course of culture on 0.5 mgL-1 BAP and 0.5 mgL-1 NAA. To select salt tolerant somaclone, mini somaclones were cultured in medium with 100, 200 and 400 mgL-1 NaCl and survived somaclones were selected. Among the treatments, the growth performance of plantlets in 100 mgL-1 NaCl was similar to that of control and higher concentration (200-400 mgL-1) retarded growth and survival percent of somaclones. Plantlets selected tolerant in vitro at 400 mgL-1 NaCl. The growth of acclimatized plantlets was normal and the survival rate of the plantlets was 100% in soil. Detailed study is going on to select salt tolerant improved cultivar in taro.     ', 'Taro somaclone, Salt tolerant, in vitro', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Salt tolerant Vegetable crop production', 'Taro', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3921, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Soil moisture conservation using mulching practices at farmer''s level', 'Char Nilakkhia, Mymensingh sadar, Mymensingh', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', '01-07-2008', '30-06-2009', 'to evaluate the effect of some indigenous mulch on the soil moisture, temperature and nutrient status as well as growth of some important crops in the winter', '', 'Experiments were conducted at different locations each representing a farmers field in Char Nilakkhia under Mymensingh sadar Upazila to evaluate the effect of some indigenous mulch on the soil moisture, temperature and nutrient status as well as growth of some important crops in the winter of 2008-2009. The experimental fields were prepared by ploughing followed by laddering, and recommended doses of fertilizers were applied before the final land preparation. Tomato, onion, chilli and potato seeds/seedlings were sown/transplanted maintaining proper spacing. Different mulch materials viz. black polythene (BP), transparent polythene (TP), water hyacinth (WH), saw dust (SD) and rice straw (RS) along with no mulch (NoM) as control were used for the treatments. The mulches were applied at the time of or within a week of sowing or transplanting. Data were collected on soil moisture and temperature, major nutrient contents and on the yield and yield attributes of the crops. Results reveal that soil moisture varied significantly for the mulching but the corresponding mulches gave similar results in all locations. Polythene mulches conserve maximum soil moisture (23%) compared to the control (15 to 17%) or other mulch materials (20 to 22%) in the tomato field. Soil temperature recorded at 5 cm soil depth varied significantly and it became maximum at 2 pm in all the mulched/non-mulched plots. TP mulch retained maximum soil temperature (340C) followed by BP (320C) and minimum soil temperature was recorded under WH (250C) mulch at 2 pm. Mulched plants produced higher number of fruits plant-1, and BP and WH mulched plots produced maximum number of fruits plant-1. Bulb diameter and size of onion were larger in mulched plots particularly for BP and WH mulches. The higher number of fruits plant-1 resulted higher yield which might commensurate with the conservation more soil moisture and temperature and soil nutrients than non-mulched one (control) for the mulching. BP and/or WH mulches may be recommended for crop production in the winter of Mymensingh.     ', 'Soil moisture, Mulching, Tomato, Onion, Potato', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Crop production by using mulching practices', 'Tomato, onion, potato', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3922, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Invitro regeneration of teasle gourd', 'Department of Crop Botany, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Among the summer vegetables, teasle gourd is an important source of nutrients for human body.  As dioecious nature of the plant, the propagation entirely depends on underground tuberous roots. Maintenance of quality of tuberous roots in the field as well as storage condition is difficult. Micropropagation may help to overcome these problems to a great extent by producing new variants. With a view to increase commercial production of teasle gourd, an attempt was made to generate a complete reproducible protocol for large scale propagation and in vitro regeneration from different organs of teasle gourd. Segments from different organs of teasle gourd were used as plant materials. The explants were cultured on MS medium supplemented with NAA (0.0, 0.1 &amp; 0.2 mgL-1) and BAP (0.0, 0.5, 1.0, 1.5 and 2.0 mgL-1) for callus initiation. The culture medium supplemented with 0.1 mg L-1 NAA and 1.0 mgL-1 BAP resulted highest percentage of callus formation from internode explants with better morphological features. Proliferated calli were cultured on MS medium for shoot initiation. The node explants had produced highest shoot regeneration in minimum days (15) on MS medium containing 0.1 mgL-1 NAA and 1.0 mg L-1 BAP. The shoots were subcultured on MS medium supplemented with IBA and IAA for rooting. Sufficient roots were induced on half MS medium containing only 0.3 mg L-1 IBA. A protocol of regeneration of teasle gourd has been developed via callus formation using nodal explants.      ', 'Regeneration, Teasle Gourd, callus, Propagation', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Invitro regeneration of crop', 'Teasle gourd', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3923, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Biotechnological approaches for the improvement of teasle gourd', 'Department of Crop Botany, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Kakrol (Momordica dioeca Roxb.) is a popular summer vegetable in Bangladesh. Recently it has become a major vegetable in Bangladesh because of its high nutritional value and exporting potentiality as well. Fruit quality of kakrol deteriorates due to the presence of large number of hard seeds. Seedless or less seeded teasle gourd may be obtained by applying radiations or chemical mutagenes during tissue culture. Induction of somaclonal variation through callus culture may lead to achieve seedless or less seeded fruit. To establish and develop a reproducible protocol for rapid propagation of teasle gourd from internode, node, leaf, leaf petiole and shoot tip explants were cultured on MS medium supplemented with naphthalene acetic acid (NAA), 6-benzyl amino purine (BAP), indole butyric acid (IBA) and indole acetic acid (IAA). Sterilized explants were cultured on the medium supplemented with different concentrations and combinations of NAA (0.0, 0.1 mg L-1) and BAP (0, 0.5, 1.0, 1.5, 2.0 mg L-1). The combination of growth regulators for callus and shoot induction NAA at 0.1 mgL-1 and BAP at 1.0 mgL-1, and for root induction was IBA at 0.3 mgL-1. Aiming to mutagenetic effects, 100 mgL-1 and 200 mgL-1 colchicine was used in MS medium for callus initiation. A good number of calli were induced on the medium containing 100 mgL-1 colchicine. Calli were subcultured on the same MS medium for shoot induction. Sufficient number of shoots with 2.7 cm shoot height was achieved after 42 days. Healthy shoots were separated from the callus by a sharp blade and place on half MS medium supplemented with 0.3 mgL-1 IBA for rooting. A good number of roots were produced from each shoot. Afterwards the regenerated plantlets were acclimatized.       ', 'Teasle gourd, vegetable, Biotechnological approaches', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Vegetable crop production through biotechnological approaches', 'Teasle gourd', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3924, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Study on impact of Aqua drugs and chemicals on fish health and productivity', 'Department of Aquaculture, BAU, Myemnsingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The present study was conducted in farmer ponds at field level and experimental ponds at BAU to find out the impact of aqua drugs and chemicals on health and production of fish. In aqua drug shop of investigated areas, 50 different kinds of aqua drugs and chemicals were recorded. Among those, 15 kinds are widely used by the farmers such as Renamycin, Amoxifish, Ossi-C, Timsen, Aquamysine, Aquamycine, Virex, Aquakleen, Geolite gold, Oxy Dox F, Polgard plus, charger gel, Seaweed, Bactisal and Deletix. Production of Thai Pangus (81001 kg/acre in chemical treated ponds whereas 4800 kg/acre in non-treated ponds) and Thai koi (14000 kg/acre in chemical treated ponds whereas 10000 kg/acre in non treated ponds) in Gouripur and Muktagacha Upazillas, respectively, were almost double in the chemical treated ponds compared with non treated ponds. In experimental ponds, it was found that food conversion ratio ( FCR) was 1.27 and 1.13 in the treatment I and treatment II in c ase of Pangus. However, in case of Thai koi, FCR in the T1 was significantly reduced that of TII.  Production of Pangus in the non treated ponds was higher which was 7328.16 kg per acre than in the treated ponds, where it was 6400.08 kg per acre. Whereas, production of koi in the treated ponds was higher (1471.92 kg/acre) than that of non-treated ponds (1296.00 kg/acre).\r\nIn upazillas like Fulpur, Muktagacha and Fulbaria EUS, dropsy, Edwardsiellosis diseases were recorded with pangus and tilapia. Shing had 90-100% mortalities within very short period from unknown diseases with no obvious symptoms (except swollen abdomen and spots) provided 30-100% recovery after application of drugs. In EUS affected tilapia in Fulpur (20%) and Muktagacha (30%) and farmers used Renamycin, Polgard plus and Ossi-C with a result 80-95% recovery. In Edwardsiellosis affected pangus in Fulpur (80%) and Fulbaria (50%), farmers used Renamycin, Timsen, Polgard pous and Ossi-C in Fulpur and Geolite and Ossi-C against dropsy in Fulpur with a result of 95% recovery. Zoothamnium and various s;pots on skin, scale loss in koi, where farmers used Renamycin, Aquamycine, Ossi-C and Polgard plus drugs as treatments and achieved 70-80% recovery. It was thus observed that aqua drugs played excellent role in recovery of fish diseases and maintenance of health. \r\nClinically all the fishes of various regions did not show any remarkable changes. Histopathology in the control ponds, skin-muscle, liver, kidney nad gill of fish had almost normal structure. However, in the chemical treated ponds, the above mentioned investigated organs of fishes had remarkable pathological changes like necrosis, hemorrhage, vacuum, melanocytes and partial loss of organs. \r\n', 'Fishes, Fish production, Aqua drugs, Chemicals on fish health', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Aqua drugs', 'Fishes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3925, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Food security in Bangladesh: A study of Cassava (Manihot esculenta) through selection against hydrocyanic acid toxicity', 'Comilla and Khagrachari', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Cassava (Manihot esculenta Crantz. Euphorbiaceae) is an important tropical starchy root (around 30% starch) crop and is the important source of staple for about 500 million people especially in Africa. The carbohydrates from tuberous root of Cassava plant are also used for starch in garment industry, raw materials in bakery, food and pharmaceuticals company, and as an animal feed. Cassava is a drought tolerant plants that thrives on poor soils where other crops can not be grown successfully. Perhaps, the most important aspect is the realization of highest root yield of Cassava (35-50 t/ha, average 25-30 t/ha) compared to yield of rice and other cereals (2-10 t/ha). At harvest of Cassava roots, the amount of HCN acids varies from harmless to lethal. Five Cassava morphotypes were collected from different Cassava growing regions of Bangladesh. Leaf and tuber were analyzed for hydrozen cyanide (HCN) toxicity and nutrient composition. The results revealed that leaf HCN varied between 147.96 mg/kg fresh wt in Comilla and 284.68 mg/kg fresh wt in Ornamental morphotypes. The edible tuber was tested for HCN at fresh and boiled (10000C for 1 hour in water) conditions. Two morphotypes, Comilla and Khagrachari, had safer level of HCN (&amp;#706;50 mg HCN/kg fresh wt.) and other two morphotypes, Sagordege and white had higher HCN level (&amp;#707; 50 mg HCN/kg fresh wt.) unsuitable for consumption. Comilla porphotypes also had better tuber protein content. We apparently recommend Comilla and Khagrachari morphotypes for human consumption. However, for validity repeated analysis is needed for final recommendation. ', 'Food security, Cassava, Hydrocyanic acid, Tuber, Africa', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Alternate starch food production', 'Cassava', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3926, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Crop Botany', 'Project', 'Physiological adaptation against salt stress in rice: Osmoregulation is the primary target', 'Laboratory of the Department of Crop Botany, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'A series of experiments were conducted with 12 rice genotypes and two salinity levels (0 &amp; 100 mM NaCl). On the basis of salinity tolerance (ST), the 12 rice genotypes were grouped into 4: tolerant (Pokkali, Ashfal, Benapole &amp; Jamainaru), moderately tolerant (Gunshi &amp; Hoglapata), relatively sensitive (Mohini, Kaliboro, Boilam &amp; Chinikanai) and sensitive (Jamaibabu &amp; BRRI dhan29). All the tolerant and a representative from each group were used for successive experiments. The relative water content (RWC) was 92% in the tolerant group and 80% in the sensitive rice, BRRI dhan29. This trait is related to biomass yield. All the genotypes that grouped with Pokkali had the lower Na+/K+ in shoot (0.81-1.03) while that of Pokkali was 1.03. The popular landraces (Ashfal, Benapole &amp; Jamainaru) of our coastal zone had lower Na+ /K+ in shoot than that of Pokkali, the benchmark tolerant genotype. In the contrast, the Na+ : K+ ratio in shoot of the sensitive check, BRRI dhan29 was 3.41. As an indicator of ST, Na+ : K+ ratio in shoot of relatively sensitive landraces, Mohini (2.25), which was greater than the moderately tolerant Gunshi (1.35). In case of organic osmolyte, proline accumulation was the greatest in the sensitive and gradually decreases towards the tolerant. The results revealed that organic osmotyle, proline functions as energy sink in sensitive rice, whereas accumulation of inorganic osmolyte, K+ functions to maintain turgor pressure in tolerant rice genotypes. Taken all together, it may be concluded that our local landraces are more potential for accumulating inorganic osmolyte (K+) during salinity stress and we have to conserve those genotypes for the development of osmo tolerant rice through genetic manipulation (Biotechnology) in future.  ', 'Physiological adaptation, salt stress, Rice, Osmoregulation', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Crop production in saline conditions', 'Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3927, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Extension Education', 'Project', 'Adoption of hybrid rice in greater Mymensingh region and associated issues: A technology dissemination analysis', 'Mymensingh, Netrokona and Kishorganj districts.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '(i) determine farmers extent of adoption of hybrid rice cultivation, (ii) determine farmers assessment of hybrid rice as an innovation, (iii) determine farmers stage of innovation decision concerning adoption of hybrid rice, (iv) identify important characteristics of hybrid rice adopters, (v) identify farmers in adopting hybrid rice, and (vi) exploring relationship between farmers adoption of hybrid rice and their selected characteristics', '', 'The research has been undertaken to have an understanding on farmers adoption behavior of hybrid rice and associated issues in greater Mymensingh region. Though hybrid rice is gaining popularity day by day, there is a dearth of research based information on its various aspects of adoption. Therefore the specific objectives of the study were to (i) determine farmers extent of adoption of hybrid rice cultivation, (ii) determine farmers assessment of hybrid rice as an innovation, (iii) determine farmers stage of innovation decision concerning adoption of hybrid rice, (iv) identify important characteristics of hybrid rice adopters, (v) identify farmers in adopting hybrid rice, and (vi) exploring relationship between farmers adoption of hybrid rice and their selected characteristics. The study was to be carried out in three selected Upazilas of under the greater Mymensingh region. The primarily selected Upazilas were Phulpur of Mymensingh district. Madan of Netrokona district and Itna of Kishorganj district. In the first stage of data collection, randomly selected 100 farmers were interviewed in Phulpur Upazila. The analysis of so far collected data revealed that 38 percent hybrid rice farmers had medium adoption (33-67% of the farm, boro rice area) followed by 37 percent and 25 percent having low (up to 33% of farm area) and high (more than 67% farm area) adoption, respectively. As for the assessment of hybrid rice as an innovation, majority of the farmers evaluated it as a suitable rice variety considering its relative advantage, compatibility , complexcity, trialability and observability. It was found that 54 percent farmers perceived hybrid rice having medium benefit, while 43 percent and 3 percent perceived it as having high and low benefits, respectively. The highest (79 percent) farmers faced moderate problems, while 15 percent and 6 percent faced respectively low and high problems in cultivating hybrid rice.  ', 'Hybrid Rice, Greater Mymensingh region, Hybrid rice adopters', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Hybrid Crop production', 'Hybrid Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3928, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Aquaculture', 'Project', 'Investigation into the Disease condition of indigenous koi Anabas testudineus and its control.', 'Mymensingh, Sherpur, Netrokona, Kishoregonj, Tangail, Jamalpur and Gazipur district.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'With intensive aquaculture practices, disease problem is becoming a limiting factor for sustainable aquaculture. The indigenous koi Anabas testudineus was found to suffer from a reddish lateral lesion that devolved into shallow ulcerative disease condition. Investigation into the above disease condition of the koi was undertaken and Aeromonas hydrophila could be detected firm the naturally diseased koi of Mymensingh, Sherpur, Netrokona, Kishoregonj, Tangail, Jamalpur and Gazipur district. In total 27 isolates were collected from the intestine liver and kidney by Aeromonas isolation medium (AIM) and subsequent morphological, physiological and biochemical characteristics. They hydrolysed esculin and were resistant of vibriostatic agent 0129. Quantitative studies of bacterial flora on TSA plates showed that the minimum bacterial load was 1.6 z 102 cfu/g in blood and maxium, 4.9 x 109 cfu/g in intestine, of the fish collected from Tangail and Sherpur respectively. So the disease was successful with all representative isolates in apparently healthy koi that developed haemorrhage and ulcerative lesions over the body, especially near the mouth, head and caudal regin, internally, kidney, liver, and spleen were swollen and enlarged. Histopathological observation revealed the development of diffused necrosis and glomerular atrophy in kidney. Liver showed focal necrosis and massive vacuolations.   Treatment trial I with four chemotherapeutics, oxytetracycline, potassium permanganate, copper sulphate, and  malachite green showed best result (100% cure) by oxytetracycline and good (80% cure) by CuSO4. Treatment trial II with Oxysentin 20% (oxytetracycline HCI BP), Acimox (amoxicillin) tri hydrate BP) and oxy-D Vet (oxytetracycline 20% and doxycycline 10%) showed best result with Oxy-D Vet (100% cure). An antiserum was raised against a reference strain, AQK809*, in local rabbit and agglutination titration of the antiserum with the heat killed cells (HKC) and formalin killed cells (FKC) of the above 27 isolates showed that all the isolates were of similar serotypes. The titer against the protein somatic HKC was within 320 to 640 and that of FKC, 640 to 1280. Vaccination by the HKC at a dose of 0.1 ml/fish, 15 days prior to experimental infection, developed resistance against MAS in 60% of the experimentally infected koi. Serotyping of the A. hydrophila strains from all over Bangladesh, protein purification and more vaccination in field level are future research interests', 'Koi, Disease, Fish', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Diseases', 'Fish', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3929, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Environmental Science', 'Project', 'Increasing sink strength to reduce greenhouse gas emission from rice fields to minimize global warming', 'BAU farm, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Daytime CO2 fluxes observed over new rice sink (regrowth/ratoon) of Boro rice in some selected days were all negative indicating the absorption of CO2 by the new sink of rice in presence of light. Positive flux values at night indicated respiratory release of CO2 by the ecosystem. Balance of daytime and nighttime fluxes showed all negative values indicating that the absorption of CO2 by the ratoon was larger than the release of CO2 to atmosphere by the ecosystem. It means it is always better to allow rice ratoon to grow to minimize greenhouse gas emission from rice ecosystem ignoring ploughing  immediate after harvest. During the rice growing seasons, it has become evident that the CO2 flux is variable in relation to plant growth and canopy coverage. Here, the early growth stage of rice shows the commencement of CO2 uptake but relatively low. It is also observed that respiratory release of CO2 is higher during the early stage. In full vegetative growth stage, rice plants vigorously increase the LAI and canopy coverage resulting increase of CO2 uptake during daytime. Later at maturation, when the leaves reach senescence, diurnal uptake of CO2 show decreasing trend. After harvesting rice, the CO2 release increases though it sometimes shows a minimal CO2 uptake by rationing of rice plant with other weedy plants. To increase rice sink strength of post boro fallow, we applied irrigation and urea fertilizer including other cultural practices. Standing water at the field augmented the growth of ratoon and other weedy plants which in turn helped in more CO2 sequestration. Diurnal variation of CO2 absorption over ratoon of boro rice in a clear day indicated that maximum fixation was observed more that 10 umole CO2 m-2 s-1 (DOY 117). Net ecosystem exchange (NEE), gross primary production (GPP) and ecosystem respiration (Reco) observed in 2008 indicated that after aman harvest (after DOY 333) GPP and NEE became almost zero, but Reco was positive, though small due to absence of rice/new sink. Net Ecosystem Exchange (NEE), gross primary production (GPP) and ecosystem respiration (Reco) observed in 2009 indicated that after boro harvest (after DOY 151) GPP and NEE tended to be near zero, but Reco was positive, though small due to absence of rice/new sink. Soon GPP showed positive values as in normal rice growth period and NEE started to be negative indicating absorption of CO2 by the development of new sinks after proper management practices.    ', 'Sink strength, greenhouse gas emission, Rice, Global warming', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Green house gas emission', 'Rice', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.');
