(3930, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry', 'Project', 'Assessment of toxic metalic contamination in different fish species of the polluted rivers', 'The rivers namely Buriganga, Turag, Shitalakhaya, Brahmaputra and Jamuna.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The contamination of river water with toxic metals has increased due to the uncontrolled disposal of untreated industrial and municipal wastes as anthropogenic activities. Fish bioaccumulates some toxic metals from the polluted river as one of the most indicative factors for assessing metal pollution and risk potential of human consumption. Considering this fact, an attempt was made to evaluate metal ionic toxicity levels of water and fish in the polluted rivers viz. Buriganga, Turag and Shitalakhaya as well as the unpolluted rivers viz. Brahmaputra and Jamuna. River water samples collected from non-point sources was assessed their quality for aquaculture usage during dry and wet seasons. Colour, odour and turbidity of water samples in the polluted rivers were observed. The chemical analysis of river waters included pH, EC, TDS, Ca, Mg, K, Na, Zn, Cu, Mn, Cd, Cr and Pb. Fish samples collected from different polluted and unpolluted rivers were analyzed for the levels of metals such as Zn, Cu, Mn, Cd, Cr and Pb in order to elucidate the status of these contaminants in fish meant for human consumption. In both seasons, the polluted river water samples were slightly acidic to alkaline (pH = 6.9-7.9) and the unpolluted river water samples were alkaline (pH = 7.3-8.0) in nature. As per TDS, all the river water were rated as fresh water (TDS&amp;#706;1,000 mgL-1) in quality. EC and SAR values indicated that water samples were under low salinity (C1), medium salinity (C2) and low alkalinity (S1) hazard classes expressed as C1S1 and C2S1. In the polluted rivers namely Buriganga and Turag, Cr level was marginally higher than the legal limit but Cd and Pb levels exceeded the acceptable limit indicating toxicity for aquaculture and might pose threat in aquatic ecosystem. The measured contents of other metal ions such as Zn, Cu and Mn in the polluted river water samples were above the safe limits for aquaculture. The levels of metallic ions were higher in dry season as compared to wet season. The intensity of river water pollution was established in ranking of Buriganga&amp;#707; Turag&amp;#707; Shitalakhaya. The detected concentrations of Zn, Cu, Mn, Cd, Cr and Pb ions in the unpolluted river water samples and fishes collected from these rivers were far below the toxic levels and did not appear to pose a threat. Among the analyzed metals, Cd and Pb ions were detected above the permissible levels in liver and muscle tissues of both stinging catfish and spotted snakehead collected from the polluted rivers viz. Buriganga and Turag causing toxicity for human consumption. Stinging catfish was the species found to highly bioaccumulate these metals. Fish species bioconcentrated appreciable amounts of Cd and Pb as toxic metals in the liver as compared to the muscle.    ', 'Toxic metalic contamination, Fish, Buriganga, Turag, Shitalakhaya, Jamuna, Brahmaputra', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Assessment of toxic metals contamination', 'Fish', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3931, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Management', '', 'Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) for Energy Cost and Food Safety Issues in Seafood Value-chain in Bangladesh', 'Department of Fisheries Management, BAU, Myemnsingh-2202.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2013', '01-07-2009', '30-06-2013', '', '', 'Seafood farming particularly of shrimp (Penaeus monodon) and prown (Macrobrachium rosenbergii) together is currently recognized as the second most important export sector contributing to the national economy of Bangladesh, because of its continuous growth over last two decades. In order to sustain current export market demand, there are various requirements of the consumers countries through value chain stakeholders to standardize seafood production and post-harvest processing activities in compliance with international trade norms related to environmental, food safety, and social issues. The present study was carried out based on direct observation in the field, key informant interviews and questionnaire surveys focusing of energy costs in terms of wider environmental impacts and possible risks of food contamination. \r\nUsing the life cycle assessment (LCA) tools, it was observed that the main energy requiring segments are brood collection, hatchery, nursery, feed ingredients collection and processing, fish feed mill, grow-out farm, processing plants, and transportation at all stages. Globally, most of the LCA studies on aquaculture showed fish feed processing as hot spot for costing major proportion of energy. However, per unit freshwater prawn farming in Bangladesh tends to require lower level of energy, compared to other prawn countries. Moreover, shrimp farming is carried out in an extensive system without any dependence on external feed supply. Along with energy consuming stages of seafood product life cycle, there are various likelihood of food contaminations and safely hazards. The pathogenic contamination due to use of natural shrimp brood in hatcheries can cause disease outbreaks in grow-out farms and subsequently results in product contamination. The use of probiotics, antibiotic and disinfectants in seafood farm tends to increase the risks of food safety hazards. Particularly, the presence of nitrofuran (a residual product  of antibiotic drugs) due to use of antibiotic mixed poultry feed in prawn farms cause seafood safety hazards and often become responsible for ban on export of seafood. The hygiene management in the ice factories, use of water for ice production, its transportation, ice crushing, methods of seafood transportation from local chatal/depots to the processing plants are found to exert considerable risks in food safety. \r\nThe recently growing chatal (local landing centre for auction) have inadequate physical facilities in terms of hygienic floor, instant supply of quality ice, personal hygiene of the workers, water supply, toilet facilities etc. This study showed tow critical dimensions of seafood production in Bangladesh the first one is positive and encouraging due to farming of seafood with low energy cost, and the second one is negative, that is the risk of product contamination. The follow-on research will quantify such strengths and weaknesses of value chain to develop a comparative standard of Bangladesh seafood with that of other producing countries. This research being carried out with different work packages with Sustaining Ethical Aquaculture trade (SEAT) Project (2009-2013) funded by EU under FP7 framework programme. The results of the study along with other follow-on researches will contribute to sustainability of seafood value-chain independently.\r\n', 'Energy cost, Food safety, Seafood, Agriculture', 'EU', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Seafood', 'Agriculture', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012.'),
(3932, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry', 'Project', 'Biodynamics of microbial biomass in soil', 'Department of Agricultural Chemistry, BAU', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', '    Microbial biomass C, N and S were determined in seven different soil types of Bangladesh. Across the soil, biomass C ranged from 71.7 to 1054, mean 470.10 &micro;g g-1, biomass N from 10.09 to 157.46, mean 92.85 &micro;g g-1, and biomass S from 1.92 to 13.44, mean 6.3 &micro;g g-1 soil. The proportion of soil organic C, total N and total S contained in the microbial biomass range from 1.51 to 3.77 (Mean, 2.51), 3.40 to 5.66 (4.65) and 1.09 to 3.01% (2.10), respectively. The biomass C:N, C:S and N:S ratios varied considerably across the soil and ranged from 4.1 to 7.2 (Mean, 5.37), 37.5 to 87.5 (71.77) and 5.3 to 18.8 (14.34), respectively. Microbial biomass S in 7 different soil types was linearly related with biomass C and biomass N. The regression accounted for 93.3% for biomass C and 86.3% for biomass N of the variance in the data. Most of the soil properties significantly correlated with each other. Biomass C, N and S were positively correlated with a number of soil properties particularly with organic C, total N, K2SO4 extractable SO4-S and electrical conductivity and among themselves. The soil properties, in various linear combinations showed 84-98% of the variability in the biomass nutrients. Mean biomass S and N were 45 and 129% higher than available S and N pool across the soil. Stepwise multiple regression showed that biomass C, N and S were also dependent on SO4-S as a second factor of significance which could limit microbial growth under the environmental conditions prevailing in the study sites.', 'Biodynamics, Microbial, Biomass, Soil', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Soil organic matter content', 'Microbial biomass', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3933, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Agroforestry', 'Project', 'Management practices for sustainable multistrata production systems in institutional fallow and wastelands', 'BAU Campus', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Selected agroforestry and agricultural management technologies for sustainable multistrata production systems (SMPS) were followed in a developing garden at Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh. The selected land remained as fallow and waste for long time near the University stadium gate. Therefore, it was selected for the development of a multistrata plant gallery, in a similar fashion to that of stadium gallery, with mixed diversified plant species for beautification, HVT production and environmental improvements in the locality. These were done along with the development of systems for regular income generation. So, that the systems became sustainable and could be adapted in the farmers land, such as in their homestead and other fallow and wastelands as well as in other institutional places. Initially, the land was uneven with ditches, gravels, large brick parts, buried brick walls of ruined houses and covered with grasses and bushes that turned some areas into wastelands. Therefore, no plantation could be successful previously. The initial development of the land was carried out by removing all the unwanted materials from soil followed by soil working and leveling. The land was then laid out comprising the systems with beautification, long term output as an insurance with HVT, regular income generation with fruits, lemons, forages, organic manures etc. both for economic output and environmental benefits. Proper drainage system and internal pathways have been developed in accordance with the design of the multistrata gallery systems. The trees, shrubs and other plants have been grown as either understoried or intercropping systems so that intensive crop cultivation could be done that generated regular output from the system. This encouraged the trees and shrubs with faster growth compared to control ones. The system has been enriched with the intervals of pruned and pollarded Neem and Bakphul trees to develop natural insect repellent and soil fertility development systems respectively that could make the whole system sustainable. In order to keep the systems properly managed, initial vacant places were cultivated with onion, chilli, bittergourd, sweet gourd, potato, tomato, Okra, mustard, Indian Spinach, stem amaranth etc. following agronomic and horticultural practices along with multiplication of Neem, Jatropha and lemon through seeding and cutting techniques. These cropping systems were gradually being replaced by shade tolerant Kakrol and other green vines, chilli, papaya etc. as required along with maximum accommodation of endangered herbaceous crops and other species to develop an ideal institutional model of multistarta production systems. The SMPS were managed through regular cleaning of drainage systems, spading and mulching of weedy areas, pruning of leader and unwanted branches, hedges etc. The roughages and green leaves thus collected were kept in heaps for production of manures naturally. Following decomposition, the manures were separated from the heaps and distributed throughout the garden followed by spading and soil mulching during April and October of each year. The undecomposed stuff were again dumped into the ditches which were simultaneously buried by subsequent addition of roughages, grasses, crop residues and the cycle were repeated . In addition, the regular liter falls from all the crops and MPTS especially from Bokulphul plants increased soil fertility resulting good crop and other plant growth. The standing neem trees and the harvested neem leaves distributed in crop zones also developed insect repellent system thus requiring application of no insecticide. At the time of vine crop regeneration, the Jatropha plants were pollarded to hedge levels to develop vine support system following severe root pruning of the plants. These reduced the higher cost of production against bamboo stick support. Weeding, watering and soil mulching were done as an when found necessary. The under storied cropping systems throughout the year were as follows: a) Only on summer/winter crop. b) one summer and one winter crop, c) Three or more overlapping/mixed crops and d) Control MPTS with no crop along with soil management in all the systems. The sustainability and economic outputs are being studied following for identification of the best possible management system.', 'Agroforestry, Sustainable multistrata production systems, MPTS', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Agro-forestry development', 'Sustainable multistrata production systems', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.'),
(3934, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', 'Department of Fisheries Management', '', 'Development of polyculture technology for giant freshwater prawns (Macrobrachium  rosenbergii) and mola (Amplypharyngodon mola)', 'Department of Fisheries Management, BAU, Mymensingh-2202', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The project evaluated potential developments in prawn polyculture by testing a variety of culture systems of evaluation of growth and yield. In experiment 1, the potential of additional of the nutrient-dense, small fish mola into polycultue with freshwater giant prawn was evaluated at the fishers Field Laboratory. Bangladesh Agricultural University, Mymensingh during August to December 2010. The effects of mola at different densities in polyculture with freshwater prawn, and the production performance between all-male and all-female freshwater prawn in monoculture were evaluated. The experiment had five treatments: all male prawn + 1 mola m-2, all male prawn + 1.5 mola m-2, all male prawn + 2 mola m-2, only male prawn and only female prawn (T1, T2, T3, T4, and T5, respectively) with three replications each. Prawn stocking densities were the same (3 juvenile m-2) in all treatments. Feeds were supplied twice daily for prown in all ponds at appropriate feeding rates. Plankton, macro-benthos abundance and water quality parameters (except transparency and chlorophyll-a) did not vary significantly (p&gt;0.05) among the treatments. Survival of prawn in monoculture irrespective of gender was lower than in polyculture with mola. Mean harvest weight, weight gain, specific growth rate, net and gross production of all female prawn was significantly (P&lt;0.05) lower than all male and those of other treatments with different densities of mola. Addition of mola at different densities had no effect on survival, gain in weight, or production performance of freshwater prawn. Therefore, mola may be stocked as an additional species with freshwater prawn that would give higher total production, provide family nutrition as well as generate additional income. \r\nIn experiment 2, the effects of adding silver carp and catla to mola and freshwater giant prawn in polyculture systems were evaluated. The experiment had five treatments: T1 (prawn and mola), T2 (prawn, mola and catla), T3 (prawn, mola and silver carp),  T4 (prawn, mola, catla, and  silver carp), and T5 (only mola), each with three replications. Stocking density of mola varied to produce approximately the same total fish biomass in all the treatments. Prawn stocking densities were 120 juvenile dm-1 (dm=decimal=40m2) and 6 carp dm-1. Feeds were supplied twice daily for prawn at appropriate feeding rates. Water quality parameters (except transparency) did not vary significantly among treatments. Survival of freshwater prawn in prawn-mola-carp and catla, and with silver carp, respectively than with only mola or with mola and catla. Net and gross production of prawn were significantly higher with silver carp and with silver carp-catla but not with only mola or mola-catla. Average weight gains, SGR, net and gross production were significantly lower for silver carp than in catla or in catla silver carp treatments. The balanced stocking densities of prawn-mola with catla- silver carp developed a synergistic interaction resulting higher net and gross productions. Not and gross productions were significantly higher in treatment T5, where only mola was stocked at higher densities. Therefore, carps can be added with prawn and mola to enhance total production, which would play a significant role in providing family nutrition as well as generating additional incomes.  \r\n', 'Polyculture, Freshwater prawns', '', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Freshwater Prawn Production', 'Fishes', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, Volume-22, 2011.  Proceedings of the workshop of BAU Research Progress, 02-03 April 2012. '),
(3935, 'Bangladesh Agricultural University', '', 'Project', 'A study on the threats to Black Bengal goat conservation in the north western region of Bangladesh', 'Rajshahi, Chapai Nwabganj and Dinajpur Districts.', 'High', 'Applied', 'Completed', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2009', '01-01-2009', '31-12-2009', '', '', 'The study was conducted to investigate the extent to which BB goat has become crossbreds, breed or types of goat entering into our population and to find out the consequences of such crossbreeding in Rajshahi, Chapai Nwabganj and Dinajpur region during January  December, 2009. For gathering information farm families were surveyed randomly, animals were directly counted and weighed, and opinions on the conservation and related issues were obtained from the farmers and extension personnel through interview schedule. It was revealed that percentage of crossbreeds were 64.20, 44.42 and 24.43 in Rajshahi, Chapai Nwabganj and Dinajpur regions and the bucks identified that entered into our BB population were of Sirohi, Beetal, Jamunapari, so called Pakistani and few unknown breeds. Although live weight and milk production were found to increase linearly and significantly (p&amp;#706;0.05) with the increase of exotic inheritance in BB goat but reproductive potential like litter size, kidding interval, age at first heat and post partum heat period were adversely affected. Live weight at one year of age in whether with 0, 50 and 75% exotic blood irrespective of region were observed to be 15.10, 16.45 and 20.58 kg respectively. Lactation adjusted milk yield (3rd lactation)/day for the same groups were found to be 554.36, 637.00 and 724.13 ml respectively. Liter size (adjusted) and age at first heat (month) figured 2.33, 1.98 and 1.95 and 7.04, 8.08 and 8.59 respectively for the above mentioned groups. It appeared that performances of the crossbreeds were not so much encouraging but buck rearers showed their interest to introduce bucks from West Bengal and market them at extra ordinary higher price (Tk. 50-80 thousand/buck) to the hindu community during puja occasion. In the absence of any breeding policy in force, BB goats in the north western part of Bangladesh have been loosing their purity. Hundred percent extension people were of the opinion that indiscriminate crossbreeding of BB goat with Indian long eared bigger sized bucks has become the main threat against BB goat conservation. If an immediate measure for conservation of BB goat is not undertaken it is likely that we may loose our only goat breed within a short period of time in the north western region of Bangladesh.', 'Threats, Black Bengal goat, Conservation, Western region', 'BAURES', 0, 0, 0, 'Report', '', 0, 'Livestock Development', 'Black Bengal Goat', '', '', 'Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress, 07-08 March, 2010. Bangladesh Agricultural Bangladesh Agricultural University Research Progress. Volume 20. Proceedings of the Workshop of University Research System (BAURES), BAU, Mymensingh.');
