(164, 'Rearing of crossbreed Hens in Rural Bangladesh.', 'In the economy of rural poultry plays a very important role. Poultry keeping is one of the most appropriate income generating activities for the rural women, youth, landless and marginal farmers. It provides cash income, generate employment opportunities and at the same time increase production of very valuable protein food-meat and eggs. Out of total animal protein food consumed in the country 28% comes from the poultry meat and eggs alone; The village women with short-term poultry training under this project on modern management including the prevention of diseases by learning vaccination techniques against prevalent rural poultry diseases can earn a respectable income to improve their living by raising poultry by scavenging, semi-scavenging or expended poultry operation with larger number of broiler and layers. These trained women will act as local trainers to other village women poultry raises in their and act as model poultry growers for others in the neighbourhood; In keeping livestock including poultry in the rural farming household, the role played by women, from the initial investment to the consumption and marketing of livestock is an essential part of the family involvement in agricultural production process and in the earning of family livelihood; For women who stay home livestock raring is often their only way of earning some income. Women irrespective of class differences feel the need of having a separate income of their own and livestock including poultry is one of the major sources of some income; a)To help the family in time of need;b)To save money for future investments in land etc.c)To buy things for herself and her children like daily necessities, good food and books etc. d)To eat more eggs and meat to supplement protein intake for the family to avoid malnutrition of women folks and children particularly, the most vulnerable groups.e)To enhance their status in the family.f)To empower them in the decision making process. Commercial private poultry farmers have already initiated a program called Contract Growing System. Under this contract system, the entrepreneurs supply high producing quality baby chicks, feed, vaccines, medicines and supervision to the flocks the village growers provide housing and labor only. At appropriate age, the contracting farms buy back the grown-up broilers/pullets from the growers at market rate. This program gives a handsome income for the growers. Trained women under this project can very well take part in the contract growing system to increase their income and thereby better livelihood;', 'Winrock International', 'Livestock', 'Hen rearing.', 'Dr. M A Mannan', 'Co-ordinator', '2000-07-01', '2001-06-30', '', '300000', 'USAID'),
(165, 'Feeding of Urea Molasses treated straw for cattle fattening (9).', 'Use of resources (Straw & Molasses ) as quality cattle feed;To develop the skill and capacity of the poor women for adoption and dissemination of the technology Urea Molasses Straw as feed for cattle fattening;To increase the income and employment opportunity for the poor women;', 'Winrock International', 'Livestock', 'Beef fattening.', 'Dr. M A Mannan', 'Co-ordinator', '2000-07-01', '2001-06-30', '', '300000', 'USAID'),
(166, 'Integrated Fish-chicken farming.', 'To select and lease 4 ponds having total 280 decimals in size from the project area of Bangappara under Austagram Thana of Kishoreganj district;To selected 80 organized disadvantaged women interested in fish-chicken farming unitedly under technology transfer project;To impart 5 days training to  organize women under the technology transfer program on fish-chicken farming for improving their knowledge and skills in the allied field and changes of attitude, beliefs and perception; To impart 5 days orientation training to 3 technology transfer program staff for efficient program implementation by enhancing their knowledge and skills in the light of technology transfer and enable to generate social mobilisation in favour of integrated fish-chicken farming in the area;To conduct baseline survey of 80 beneficiaries to identify their problems and needs on technology transfer of integrated fish-chicken farming; To use phostoxin tables in technology transfer ponds 4 tables per decimal for destroying Rakhush fish; To provide 6101 fingerlings of 8-10 cm size/ha Ruhi 25%, Siver carp - 30%, Catla 10%, Mrigal 20%, Common carp 5%. In addition Rajpunthi 2000 per hectare for fish rearing in accordance with the technology transfer of Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute;To rear total 565 layer chicken (500 chicken per hectare) in 4 technology transfer ponds through 16 chicken sheds (4 sheds in each pond) as per procedure of technology transfer project; To provide prepared chicken feed as per technology transfer to 565 chickens for 36 weeks during project period as per recommendation of technology transfer project; To impart intensive motivation to fish-chicken farming organized women to ensure their participation in technology transfer for getting higher animal protein for family consumption as well as supplementary income out of sale of suplus production in the form of fish, meat,  egg and others;To take appropriate care about health and hygiene of chicken for prevention and curative measures of diseases;To rear fish without fish feed by adopting other modern technology as proposed by Bangladesh Fisheries Research Institute for bumper fish production;To ensure regular supervision, follow-up monitoring and reporting for popularising the programme socially accepted and significant achievement; To ensure audit and evaluation of program for significant achievement;', 'Winrock International', 'Fisheries', 'Integrated farming.', 'Dr. M A Mannan', 'Co-ordinator', '2000-07-01', '2001-06-30', '', '300000', 'USAID'),
